<SLUG> BC-WARHERO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING VET HAD A SECRET: HE'S A WORLD WAR II ERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENX _ Edward Sherlock doesn't have much time left.
</P>
<P>
   A stomach problem, which has plagued him since being released as
a prisoner of war during World War II, has slowly deteriorated his
body.
</P>
<P>
   For now, most of what he sees is in room 526, bed B, at a
hospital in Sun City West, near Phoenix. And some days, his family
feared, there wasn't much more for the 75-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But as Sherlock's wife, Anna, and son, J.W., searched through
his old Army records, trying to find something that might increase
his veteran's benefits and help pay his bills, they discovered a
secret of his past.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlock is a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   They already knew he had spent 27 months as a prisoner of war.
But what they didn't know was that his efforts fighting in three
battles in North Africa during World War II had earned him a Bronze
Star, a Purple Heart and several other ribbons for his service.
</P>
<P>
   So, quietly, they collected paperwork, finding old records about
Sherlock and calling government offices to learn the rest. With
help from staffers from the office of Senator John McCain, also a
former POW, they were able to learn more about Sherlock's service.
</P>
<P>
   And on Saturday, the family had a special ceremony, complete
with the posting of the colors, at the Disabled American Veteran's
post in Glendale. But as Sherlock's health declined, they couldn't
take him to the ceremony. Instead, J.W. picked up the award and
then his wife and two of his three sons gathered in a small waiting
room to present him the medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got something for you, Dad,'' said his son, J.W.
Sherlock. ``Your stars and all the ribbons you're due. Now everyone
knows you're a hero, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Taylor, director of the Governor's community policy office,
handed him a special certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very touching,'' said Taylor. ``It's been (more then 50
years) since he was in the military. This just kind of fell through
the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherlock, a quiet man, looked down into his lap. He smiled and
said thanks. ``It's a real surprise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To know Sherlock helps to understand his underwhelming response.
</P>
<P>
   He's a modest man.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up one of 13 children in Uniontown, Penn., he joined the
Army at age 16. He lied about his age, figuring it was the right
thing to do, his family recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He fought three battles in North Africa before the Germans
captured him. Then he spent two years and three months as a
prisoner of war. During that time, he slept on wooden planks and
straw. He was malnourished and told his wife that once he had to
march 25 miles, and watched some of his friends collapse and die.
</P>
<P>
   When he was released from the camp, he weighed just 78 pounds,
45 pounds less than his usual weight.
</P>
<P>
   And when he returned to his hometown in 1945, he just wanted to
get on with his life. His mom had died when he was 12. His dad had
died when he was a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   For his injuries - mostly a severe stomach problem developed
while in one of the prison camps - he got $45 a month from the
government. That eventually increased to $275 he now receives.
</P>
<P>
   So he moved to New York where a few of his sisters lived. He met
Anna and got married. He found a career as an office manager. They
later had three boys.
</P>
<P>
   And when any of them would ask about his service, Sherlock would
brush off the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask as a kid, he'd change the subject,'' remembers J.W.,
now 45. ``He'd move on to something else. `What's the score of the
Yankees' game' or something.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way he is, says Anna, his wife of 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look for glory,'' says Anna, 70. ``He wasn't raised
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The last few years, since they retired to Sun City West, he has
spent his days tinkering about the house. ``That's still his
prisoner of war stuff. He likes to be alone,'' she said. ``He's
fixed everything in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, he started growing sicker and weaker, she said.
His body no longer was absorbing food. Now, he's on oxygen and IVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he doesn't want a fuss made about him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So it didn't surprise her if he seemed even a little bit
embarrassed by Saturday's celebration.
</P>
<P>
   She says that other veterans also may be due awards, but just
don't know it. Now, she says, the family is waiting to see if the
increased medical benefits come through.
</P>
<P>
   And they're trying to celebrate Sherlock's accomplishments more
than 50 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, they'd be thrilled. But I think he wonders what
he needs it for,'' she says. ``But I think in his own little way,
he was thrilled. He would never let you know. But I think in the
days to come, I think he may think, `Well, they appreciated me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And when his son, J.W. tried to ask his father about the award,
a ``What do you think, Dad,'' type of question, Sherlock just
looked down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we had turkey for lunch,'' he said. ``Maybe I should
head back to my room.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
