<SLUG> BC-ALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOU GEHRIG'S DISEASE PATIENTS WAIT FOR BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The hard part about having a fatal disease in 1999 is
that the promises of miracle cures, genetic antidotes and
biococktails twinkle all around like lights of distant rescue ships
_ too far off to be of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very maddening,'' said Kevin Spicer, afflicted with Lou
Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish those breakthroughs would be available right now,
before the disease takes over more of my body.'' Lacking the muscle
control to speak, the Tucson man communicates these thoughts
through his computer e-mail system. (would not give his age)
</P>
<P>
   Spicer's disease, named for the baseball legend who died of it
in 1941, is scientifically known as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis,
or ALS.
</P>
<P>
   ALS gradually destroys the motor nerves, causing muscles to
atrophy, leading to paralysis. Arizona's 250 to 300 victims of Lou
Gehrig's disease know that three to five more years of life is the
most they can expect after diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Though the disease has no cure, many of its victims do not sit
and wait. An estimated 20 percent of Arizonans with ALS, including
Spicer, are enrolled in research projects.
</P>
<P>
   They explore, looking for something that works, something that
will extend their time and give them a fighting chance. And even
those who have given up on their own chances often want to do
something that will help others, turning their personal tragedies
into something of value to medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the best ALS antidote is a drug called Riluzole. But
it lengthens life by only three to five months.
</P>
<P>
   So nationally, a flood of medical experiments is now probing
ALS, giving sufferers an opportunity to be involved in the search
for answers.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, at least four major studies are under way at Mayo
Clinic Scottsdale and at the University of Arizona. Barrow
Neurological Institute in Phoenix also is nationally known for its
research on ALS, though it doesn't have a study under way
presently.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is easy about ALS; it's even difficult to diagnose.
Doctors usually identify it only by observing how the person walks
or speaks, and by eliminating all other possible diseases. The one
left is ALS.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way to spot the disease earlier is a priority research
project at UA. Dr. Valerie Cwik is using magnetic resonance imaging
technology to track the chemical indications of neuron loss in the
brain, a research path she hopes will lead to earlier diagnosis and
to better tracking of the disease's course.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Bosch of the Mayo Clinic Scottsdale, meanwhile, is
experimenting with implanted pumps that deliver a potent drug
directly into the cerebrospinal fluid canal. He is hoping that it
will increase survival time. The medication slowed the progress of
the disease in laboratory rats, but a later human trial was not
successful. Better delivery of the drug, through use of the pump,
might make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Bosch is also testing new pills that might slow the progression
of the disease and increase survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biology of ALS is better understood now, and we are
finding ways to slow down the disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In all the ongoing Arizona research projects, doctors comment
that ALS patients volunteer readily and are unusually brave, almost
cheerful, in the face of their fate. It may help that ALS is
usually not physically painful.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the experience of being alive seems more clear and
interesting when the end of life comes suddenly into view. One of
Bosch's late patients told him that this was the luckiest time of
her life because it made her appreciate every moment.
</P>
<P>
   To make that experience last as long as possible, some ALS
patients are willing to try anything.
</P>
<P>
   George Pittman, 61, of Tucson, recently brought his wife, Sally,
and his 11-year-old grandson with him to his appointment at the
Mayo Clinic. His implanted medicine pump was due for a checkup and
refill. He reported some sleeplessness and tingling sensations
throughout his body _ potential side effects of the medication.
</P>
<P>
   Bosch asked him if he wanted to reduce the dosage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, no!'' said Pittman emphatically, adding that he could
live with the side effects if the drug gave him any chance of a
longer life. He looked at his wife and grandchild. Not long ago he
was playing golf in the top of health.
</P>
<P>
   It all started in January 1998, when he fell a few times while
jogging. There was no apparent reason for it. After a seemingly
endless battery of tests with no answers from his Tucson doctor, he
came to Mayo and was given the bad news by Bosch.
</P>
<P>
   His implanted pump, the size of a computer mouse, contains, he
hopes, a new drug considered by the Mayo Clinic to be a big
improvement. There is a one-third chance that Pittman is part of
the study's control group and his pump contains only a waterlike
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an amazing group of patients,'' said Cwik. ``There is a
saying among ALS doctors that they have the nicest patients in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not easy doctoring. ALS doctors at Mayo, Barrow and UA
have learned how to deal with the difficulty of telling people they
are going to die, then watching them lose body functions over just
a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have cried a lot with patients and families,'' Cwik said.
</P>
<P>
   Roxanne McLaughlin, research coordinator for the Mayo ALS
studies, agrees that it is tough duty: ``When I think I can't do
this anymore, I look at the letters, poems and cards I keep above
my desk from patients and families we have helped.''
</P>
<P>
   The bestselling book ``Tuesdays with Morrie'' is about the
wisdom of a thoughtful ALS patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get life lessons five or six times a day like those in that
book,'' McLaughlin said. ``So many of the patients are so
accommodating. I wonder if I would be that generous if someone was
always asking for blocks of my time and my remaining time was so
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   The disease may be toughest on patients who would like to
participate in the Scottsdale and Tucson experiments but do not
qualify, are too sick or live too far away.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Beck (NO AGE GIVEN) lives 4{ hours from Phoenix in Ganado
on the Navajo Reservation _ too far for him to travel. His family
is relying on traditional Native American healing ceremonies to
ease his suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Though his decline continues _ he has lost his voice and most of
his movement _ they believe the ceremonies give him a psychological
boost and the hope that a cure might be found for him.
</P>
<P>
   A few ALS patients, including two Phoenix-area residents, have
turned to Jack Kevorkian to end their suffering. But most say they
would not consider that.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rule, my patients want to live _ sometimes desperately,''
Cwik said.
</P>
<P>
   The national ALS Association neither condones nor disapproves of
assisted suicide for patients, unusual for a mainstream medical
group.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizonans who went to Kevorkian were Nicholas Loving, 27, in
1995, and Shahla Semino, 46. Semino was one of Bosch's patients,
and the first of his patients to take her life that way. He had no
indication that she was going to do it, except that, on her last
appointment, she hugged him and said goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   He later watched a farewell video she left behind, and, with her
family, accepted her decision. ``I don't want to reach the point
when I would not be able to wipe away my own tears,'' she said in
the video.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he shakes his head, saying, ``She had at least two years
to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that those two years can be expensive, sometimes costing
as much as $200,000, Bosch has written letters to Congress urging
changes in Social Security disability and Medicare coverage rules.
The way the law is now written, many ALS patients die before the
eligibility requirements for treatment and benefits are fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to hang on for as long as they can, there
are, in fact, glimmers of hope on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   New promising gene research, for instance, may lead to a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Bosch has been involved in eight studies since 1993, seven
involving experimental drugs. Another test is being planned for
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Next on Cwik's agenda is a study using a drug that may control
emotions that sometimes are magnified by ALS _ laughing and crying
can be uncontrollable in some patients. Maybe there is a clue
there, she hopes.
</P>
<P>
   In another study, she will measure the effect of exercise on ALS
patients. ``You lose the nerves going to the muscle. We don't know
if more exercise is good, indifferent or damaging.''
</P>
<P>
   ALS patient George Pittman has volunteered to help her find out.
</P>
<P>
   He was recently in an exercise video that ALS patients who also
participate will see. He jokes that he is the Jane Fonda of ALS
exercise tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I volunteer for everything they have,'' he said. ``Bring them
all on. This at least gives you hope.'' &QL; 
Maureen West can be reached at (602) 444-8167 or at
maureen.west(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
