<HEADER>
A3158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-LEDE-HNS &LR;      06-21 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PINEHURST, N.C. _ Payne Stewart didn't want to spend another summer
hearing about what a great effort he made and what a terrific
competitor he is.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's for losers. He knows that from experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at the U.S. Open, everybody told me what a great try
it was,'' Stewart said Sunday. ``Well, I didn't want to hear that
again. I didn't want to hear that when I got back home and all my
friends came up and said, `Boy, you sure tried. It was a great
effort. But bad luck.' I didn't want to hear that. And it motivated
me.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the man who has been renowned more for his fashion
statements and penchant for near misses than for his golf game got
it right.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made sure the 99th U.S. Open would have one of the most
breathtaking finishes in the tournament's history when he dunked a
15-foot putt into the cup on the 72nd hole for a par that gave him
a one-stroke victory over Phil Mickelson at Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to the 18th, Stewart had made a 25-footer on the 16th
for par and a three-footer after a sensational 7-iron for birdie on
the par-3 17th.
</P>
<P>
   He needed every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted my little derriere off today,'' Stewart said. ``I
never gave up. I kept playing and kept plugging. I got the job
done. And that means a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Mickelson staged a brilliant battle through the
misty, coolish afternoon and evening at Pinehurst. They were the
only players to get under par for the tournament at any point
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's even-par 70 for the final round was matched by
Mickelson. Others _ Tiger Woods and Vijay Singh, in particular _
tried to stay with them. But in the end, it was the final twosome
battling it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``With three holes to go, I felt like I was in control of the
tournament,'' said Mickelson, who had a one-stroke lead as the pair
stepped to the 16th tee. ``I was leading, and it was a difficult
course to make birdies on. It was a little disappointing that the
only bogey came at such an inopportune time.''
</P>
<P>
   If consistency won the award, Mickelson would have been a
runaway champ. His lone bogey of the day came at the 16th. Right
after Stewart had dropped in his par-saving putt, Mickelson could
not get an eight-footer to drop.
</P>
<P>
   When both hit terrific shots to the ticklish 17th, where Woods'
earlier bogey had ended his chances, it came down to a putting
contest. And nobody could beat Stewart at that part of the game
Sunday. His 24 putts were fewer than all but one player (Dudley
Hart with 23) took in the final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that shot where he knocked it in there close on 17
where the realization that he could beat me entered my mind,''
Mickelson said. ``Until then, I thought I was in control, making
pars and playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the last three holes, I just didn't have that little extra
that Payne showed. He came through with that little extra on a
couple of his putts, and I ended up missing mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made his three-footer at the 17th after Mickelson's
six-footer missed. In two holes, Stewart had made up two shots. But
as was the case all week at Pinehurst, making pars when you needed
them was no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th hole was an adventure for Stewart. He hit what he
thought was a good drive, but it ended up in the right rough. With
the ball buried in wet grass, Stewart knew he had only one option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought that drive was in the fairway,'' he said.
``But I got up there and had no chance to even think about (going
for) the green. So I took my medicine. I didn't compound the
situation by making two mistakes in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart chopped out of the rough with a 9-iron and was left with
75 yards to the pin. Mickelson, sensing that par might be enough to
get him into a Monday playoff, hit a safe shot to the front half of
the green and was left with a 25-foot putt for birdie. Stewart's
lob wedge ended up 15 feet right and slightly short of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I saw Phil hit his shot, I didn't feel that he was going
to make that putt,'' Stewart said. ``So I played my wedge shot
there, and I wanted to be underneath the hole putting back up. I
would have liked it to be a little closer, but I had practiced my
putt earlier in the week. I knew what the line would be, and so I
just went through my routine and told myself to believe that it
needed to be hit just inside-left of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked up, it was about two feet from the hole and it
was breaking right in the center and I couldn't believe it. I
couldn't believe I'd accomplished another dream of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   This now makes three major championships for Stewart, including
his second Open after having won in a playoff over Scott Simpson in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's victory capped a week of many subplots. He won it on
Father's Day while Mickelson's wife was on the verge of going into
labor with their first child. Stewart scattered the ghosts of
previous Opens. He lost a four-shot lead last year when Lee Janzen
shot a closing 68, and faltered in '93, also to Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was Stewart's tournament to win. He had started
with a one-stroke lead and protected it for most of the day until
things got hairy at the end.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the challengers faltered.
</P>
<P>
   First, Tim Herron couldn't capitalize on a rare birdie on the
par-4 fifth, one of only four birdies on that hole Sunday. On the
par-3 sixth, he dumped his tee shot in the left bunker, had his
escape roll back into deep rough and ended up with double bogey to
go 3-over for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Next was David Duval, who put Stewart on alert when he started
the day with birdies at the first two holes. But Duval missed the
green on the sixth and couldn't get up and down, then bogeyed the
eighth and fell to pieces on the 179-yard ninth. He bunkered his
tee shot, hit the blast over the green, had his chip do a U-turn,
put the next shot eight feet past but saved his double bogey.
Nevertheless, he was 4 over par for the tournament and out of the
running. He would shoot 7 over par on his last 13 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson was Mr. Consistency. He parred around until making a
gutsy birdie putt on the seventh to get to 1-under and cut
Stewart's lead in half.
</P>
<P>
   Singh made a 20-footer on No. 8 for birdie and then sank a
five-footer on the par-5 10th to get to even-par for the
tournament. But Singh made a fatal bogey on the 16th when he
couldn't get to the 489-yard par-4 in two and then couldn't get up
and down.
</P>
<P>
   Woods played the front nine in even-par to stay in the chase.
But with Mickelson, Stewart and Singh all covering the first nine
holes in 1 under par, Woods was beginning to run out of holes. When
he three-putted from 10 feet on No. 11, including a miss from 30
inches, Woods had fallen to 2 over par and seemed like a goner. He
fought back. But a missed five-footer at the 17th spelled the end
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Mickelson were left standing. And when Stewart's
putt put a lid on it, he leaped for joy and then spent a moment to
console Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said he's really happy for me that Amy (Mickelson's
wife) and I are expecting our first child and that he's really
excited for us,'' Mickelson said. ``He said being a parent is a
special thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would have made for a cool story for our daughter
to read about as she gets older. But this is still something
special. Becoming a father will be a bigger change in my life than
if I'd won this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   To which most parents, including Stewart, would say: He doesn't
know the half of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
