<SLUG> BC-STATUES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CAPITOL STATUES HONOR MANY KNOWN TO FEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Robert E. Lee looks mighty good in bronze, chin up,
sword by his side, standing tall in National Statuary Hall of the
U.S Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   And there's President Andrew Jackson, humorist Will Rogers,
Mormon leader Brigham Young and Sen. Daniel Webster. Tourists
recognize their names, if not their images, easily.
</P>
<P>
   But who is Ephraim McDowell?
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer in abdominal surgery, the Capitol guide will tell you.
This Kentucky physician made a name for himself removing a
gallstone from President James K. Polk in the early 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the two Kansas contributions _ Sen. John James Ingalls
and Gov. George Glick _ are not unique in their obscurity. Many of
the 96 statues from the 50 states are of people who cut a much
bigger figure in the Capitol than they ever did in the history
books.
</P>
<P>
   But Ingalls and Glick may be about to make fresh history. They
are on the verge of eviction, possibly the first to be sent home
from these halls.
</P>
<P>
   A committee of Congress is considering a request by the state of
Kansas to replace them with two better-known Kansans: former
President Dwight D. Eisenhower and aviator Amelia Earhart.
</P>
<P>
   Every state is entitled to two statues at the Capitol, and it is
believed that not one has been replaced in the 129 years since the
first statue went up.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Legislature, with some dissension, asked for the
change this spring, and now the flap will be taken up in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nobody who is going to block this,'' insisted U.S.
Rep. Todd Tiahrt, a Wichita Republican who helped lead the push for
a switch.
</P>
<P>
   But the Capitol architect, who oversees the statuary scattered
around the Capitol, believes a switch may take an act of Congress.
On its Web site, the architect's office says a statue becomes
federal property once unveiled and can't be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that a state cannot unilaterally come in and
reclaim its statue without some kind of authority from Congress,''
architect spokesman Herb Franklin said. ``This is a view that is,
shall I say, academic.''
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate committee to whom Capitol Architect Alan Hantman
reports warned him recently not to meddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please do not take any action that prevents the Congress from
properly determining guidelines'' for moving the statues, wrote
Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska and Rep. Bill Thomas of California of
the Joint Committee on the Library in a letter to Hantman.
</P>
<P>
   The committee plans a hearing this summer to talk about Kansas'
request and whether the full Congress must approve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inevitable that states might wish to re-examine the
individuals whose statues represent them,'' Stevens and Young
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Amen, says Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sort of like term limits,'' Ashcroft mused. ``When you
are there long enough, maybe it's time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   If statues start moving, Ashcroft said, he would like to see one
of Harry Truman installed for Missouri, although he has no plans to
initiate a change. Missouri has Thomas Hart Benton and Francis
Preston Blair Jr., who, among other things, were U.S. senators.
</P>
<P>
   Benton, one of Missouri's first two senators, was well known for
his support of western expansion. Blair, a strong ally of Abraham
Lincoln, was key in keeping Missouri, a slave state, in the Union
during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas wanted to change its statues back in the early 1970s but
was ignored in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a precedent many House members didn't want to tackle,''
said Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas, who served in the House at the
time. ``I wish the Kansas delegation well. If they can do it, fine.
If not, I understand the precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiahrt said he doesn't think Kansas will set off a stampede of
statue switching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some states will consider it, but those statues are
there for a reason,'' Tiahrt said.
</P>
<P>
   Take John Gorrie. Pursued a patent to make an ice machine, went
broke and died in seclusion, his story goes. But while trying to
figure out how to keep fever patients cool, he accidentally
invented air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   His statue was sent from Florida, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, in approving the statue collection in 1864, said
states should decide who is deserving, based on ``distinguished
civic or military'' service. The only stipulation was that the
person be dead.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nationally known figures in the collection include
Jefferson Davis, George Washington, U.S. Grant and James Garfield.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition is from Colorado, astronaut Jack Swigert of
Apollo 13 fame. North Dakota, Wyoming, New Mexico and Nevada have
sent only one statue to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The average statue has been in the hall for 77 years and are
mostly people who made history in the 1800s, explaining their
relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls, standing rather smartly, hand on his hip, in a long
dress coat, has been in Washington since 1905.
</P>
<P>
   Glick was installed in 1914, downstairs in the Hall of Columns.
This first Democrat to be elected to statewide office in Kansas
seems best remembered for helping curb an outbreak of
hoof-and-mouth disease. He is depicted with an open hand by his
side, a pose that seems now to say ``Why me?''
</P>
<P>
   Tiahrt said the statues of Ingalls and Glick would be returned
to the state Capitol in Topeka. Under the current plan, Eisenhower
would replace Glick first, with Earhart replacing Ingalls later.
</P>
<P>
   A committee is being formed in Abilene, Kan., to raise $250,000
to commission an Eisenhower statue, ship it to Washington and
return Glick to Kansas. No efforts have started to raise money for
an Earhart statue.
</P>
<P>
   Updating statues is a public service, Ashcroft thinks. ``The
Capitol of the United States becomes a teaching tool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the folks over there aren't worth learning
about,'' he said. ``But I've been in that hall and we (should not)
say those people are the only ones worthy of recognition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
