<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-PHONES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT TO OFFER DIGITAL-AGE PHONE SERVICE FIRST TO KC RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Residential consumers in Kansas City will get
first shot at Sprint Corp.'s ballyhooed Integrated on Demand
Network, a digital-age phone service that will deliver local and
long distance service, and high-speed Internet access through a
single connection to the home, with a single bill.
</P>
<P>
   Today, for the first time, Sprint will offer concrete details on
ION's deployment and announce its plans to roll out the service to
consumers in Denver, Seattle and Kansas City by December.
</P>
<P>
   ``These first three cities are the beginning of a nationwide
rollout,'' said Terri Morrow, a vice president in Sprint's consumer
services group. ``From that point forward, we'll be announcing new
markets every quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic ION package will include four voice lines _ each
equipped with caller ID and voice mail _ two high-speed data
connections, and virtually unlimited domestic long-distance
service.
</P>
<P>
   Family members in different rooms will be able to use all those
connections simultaneously. And with a simple point-and-click
interface on their computer, consumers can control their own
service, adding lines or forwarding calls to their wireless phone
while they are out of the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they deliver, this looks compelling,'' said Jonathan
Haller, an analyst with Current Analysis Inc.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how many customers will be attracted by a
service that will cost between $100 and $150 monthly, plus hardware
and installation costs of $400 to $450.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming they've done their market research,'' said Tony
Ferrugia, an analyst with A.G. Edwards in St. Louis. ``If it
doesn't generate the kind of demand they're looking for, they'll
lower the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence vision embodied in ION is one that every
telecommunications provider is chasing. But most carriers have
concentrated their efforts on the more lucrative business market.
Even those with plans to serve residential customers will be
hard-pressed to bring a comparable service in the same time frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Sprint gets this out in December, they'll be ahead of any
timetable I've seen at AT&AMP;T,'' Ferrugia said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint faces physical limitations on where it can provide the
service. It plans to deliver ION by souping up the copper phone
lines that run into most homes. That technology is only capable of
reaching customers who live within three miles of a central office
where Sprint has installed its equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Customers interested in the service can sign up to get more
information at www.sprint.com/ioninfo
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3162 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-HNS &LR;      06-21 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Lindy Ruff knew something wasn't quite right, and
mute confirmation of the terrible truth wasn't long in coming.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Buffalo Sabres coach wanted to know why the sort of goal he
had seen waved off so many times before in this controversy-filled
NHL season suddenly had been good enough to decide the last game of
the Stanley Cup Finals. Since commissioner Gary Bettman happened to
be standing nearby, Ruff figured he would go right to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to answer the question: Why is that not
reviewed?'' Ruff said after Brett Hull's shot off a rebound 14
minutes, 51 seconds into the third overtime early Sunday morning
gave the Dallas Stars a 2-1 win in Game 6 and a 4-2 victory in the
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's question was prompted by the fact Hull had a skate in the
crease when he got his decisive shot past Sabres goalie Dominik
Hasek. The response from Bettman?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, he just turned his back on me,'' Ruff said. ``He
almost looked to me as though he knew this might be a tainted goal
and there was no answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's wee hours, well after the final shot was fired in a
game that did not end until about 1:35 a.m. in the East, the NHL
scrambled to explain how this could be.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, supervisor of officials Bryan Lewis attempted to
provide an answer. Essentially, Hull could be in the crease because
he had control of the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there reasons why a guy can have a foot in the crease and
score a goal?'' Lewis said. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about all the goals disallowed this season when an
offensive player had so much as a toe in the crease?
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate here seems to be, Did he or did he not have
possession and control?'' Lewis said. ``Our words from upstairs and
our view was that yes, he did. He played the puck from his foot to
his stick, he shot and scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Hull shot twice. Hasek blocked the first effort, but
Hull lifted the second into the net.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, Lewis insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other component of the debate is, Does the puck change as
a result of hitting the goalie on the glove?'' he said. ``A puck
that rebounds off the goalie, the goal post or an opposing player
is not deemed to be a change of possession. Therefore Hull would be
deemed to be in possession and allowed to shoot and score a goal,
even though the one foot would be in the crease in advance of the
puck.''
</P>
<P>
   In answer to Ruff's request for a review, Lewis said there had
been one, though it wasn't announced. It had been determined,
without fanfare, that the goal was good. And no, the fact the Stars
already were celebrating and the Stanley Cup was in the process of
being presented didn't affect the thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Lewis insisted.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect, this explanation did little to mollify the
Sabres, who were understandably unhappy with both the process and
the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he was in the crease at first, and then I saw
the replay,'' Hasek said. ``I was about to go back on the ice
because I couldn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame. For two months, we've been playing hard, and to
lose like that ''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who joined his father, Bobby (Chicago, 1961), as
father-son Stanley Cup winners, wasn't about to let the controversy
ruin his morning, preferring to lay blame at the heart of the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad rule, and they're going to have to work on it this
summer,'' he said. ``If I've got control of it the whole time, it's
my puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going back out there, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the second-longest game in Stanley Cup Finals history _
Edmonton's 3-2 win over Boston in Game 1 of the 1990 Finals lasted
an additional 22 seconds _ hardly anyone was in the mood to go back
out on the ice, least of all Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock revealed that Hull had been bothered
by more than the sore groin the club had announced when the $17
million offseason addition missed most of Game 3 and all of Game 4
of the Finals. In addition to a torn groin, Hull also has a torn
medial collateral ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hid a lot of things,'' Hitchcock said. ``What this man did
to go on the ice, what we did between periods to get him back on
the ice I mean, he might be rehabbed enough to start the (next)
season.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this one, Hull was an extreme case when it came to
playing hurt, but most everyone involved was a little worse for
wear.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' Benoit Hogue played with a torn anterior cruciate
ligament. Mike Modano persevered with a fractured left wrist. The
second-oldest team ever to win a Stanley Cup basically played a
doubleheader to seal the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Buffalo is the same way,'' Hitchcock said, ``but I
don't know where this group would have been if we would have had to
play a Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't have to do so now, but Hitchcock's group _ and
certainly Ruff's _ deserved a better way to ring down the curtain
at the conclusion of a long, tense series and a final act that
covered more than five hours and featured 104 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   When it was done, Dallas' Joe Nieuwendyk was awarded the Conn
Smythe Trophy as Most Valuable Player of the postseason, another
decision (by a small group of veteran hockey writers) that raised a
few eyebrows. Stars goalie Ed Belfour turned back 53 of 54 shots in
the final game and yielded just one goal in the final 208:14 of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   The slight, however, didn't seem to be weighing heavily on
Belfour's mind as he celebrated his first Stanley Cup title. Amid
the champagne, beer and bonhomie of the winning locker room, the
much-maligned 34-year-old was all smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest moment of my life,'' he said. ``To be a
part of a great team like this is the best thing that's ever
happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Also high on the list of Stars finding redemption on this night
and early morning was Modano, the center who assisted on Hull's
winning goal. After years of fighting the image of a
one-dimensional player, an emotional Modano was ``our best player
the last two games of this series,'' according to Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike always carries the weight of the world on his
shoulders,'' the coach said. ``Sometimes it's unnecessary, but I
think he's in a position that he feels he's carrying the torch for
the hockey club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here a long time. He made some significant
adjustments to his game that had to be made for us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would suggest Dallas isn't a worthy winner. The Stars are
two-time President's Trophy winners for best regular-season record
in the league. This year, they added the Jennings Trophy for fewest
goals allowed.
</P>
<P>
   They beat Edmonton, St. Louis and Colorado to advance to the
Finals. Belfour got the best of Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy, a
three-time Stanley Cup champion, in the Western finals, then
outlasted Hasek _ generally considered the best goalie in the world
_ in a memorable Finals showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres graciously conceded those points. In the end, all
they wanted was the courtesy of an explanation. Instead, they were
shown the commissioner's back and the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' Buffalo center Mike Peca said. ``It's over,
and it'll be a story for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
