<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS &LR;      06-21 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Chris Holt walked the first batter he faced Sunday and had already
given up a run before his first teammate stepped into the batter's
box.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think you know how this story ends, you're probably
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was no snowball effect, no buzzard's luck. In
other words, it wasn't your typical Holt ending. His
bend-but-don't-break pitching performance, coupled with Carl
Everett's monster day at the plate, highlighted the Astros' 11-3
victory over the Montreal Expos at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who has a 2.27 ERA over his last five starts, won for the
first time since Aug. 21, 1997, and Everett drove in a career-high
six runs, including four on his fourth career grand slam. It was
his second home run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   What made the day even more meaningful for Holt (1-6) was the
fact his parents, Richard and Nancy, made the trip from Dallas to
attend the game on Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dedicated this game to my dad,'' Holt said. ``I told him
before the game that I was going to get him a win, and I battled
through and was able to do it. I didn't have my best stuff, but it
was good enough to finally get the monkey off my back. The offense
scored a lot of runs, and Carl Everett was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of Everett's home runs were to straightaway center field,
unquestionably the toughest place to hit a home run in the
Astrodome. Not only is it the deepest part of the ballpark, but fly
balls tend to die when they head toward the big wagon gate 400 feet
from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are two of the longest home runs you're going to see hit
to center field at this ballpark,'' Astros interim manager Matt
Galante said of Everett's blasts.
</P>
<P>
   But when you hit them as well as Everett did Sunday, they have a
good chance to leave any yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one was probably the hardest ball I've hit all
year,'' said Everett, whose seven home runs tie Derek Bell for
third on the team. ``They shut me down in the first two series (of
the homestand against San Diego and Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   ``My only theory today was to try to hit the ball hard, and I
did. But this was Chris Holt's day. Everyone embraced him after the
game. There's more to come for him. If he keeps pitching the way
he's been pitching, he's going to win a lot of games, because we're
going to score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up Sunday's offensive explosion to back pay. The 11 runs
the Astros scored equaled their total in Holt's last four losses
combined.
</P>
<P>
   After losing three of four games to the Braves, the Astros took
all three from Montreal for their fourth series sweep of the
season. They open a brief three-game road trip tonight at St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero's fielder's-choice grounder scored a run for
the Expos in the first, and it appeared Holt might be headed for
another one of his infamous opening innings. But third baseman Bill
Spiers helped keep the damage to a minimum with a diving stab of
Jose Vidro's liner down the third-base line with two out. Moments
later, Spiers' first-inning single tied the score at 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's had an outstanding couple of days at third base,''
Holt said. ``He's been unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio, who was 3-for-4 and scored three runs, had an RBI
single in the second, and the first of Everett's two bombs gave the
Astros a 3-1 lead after three innings. Tim Bogar's third home run
of the season _ all coming in the last 12 days _ upped the Astros'
lead in the sixth inning, and a rare two-run infield single by Alex
Diaz keyed a three-run rally in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos put runners on base against Holt in each of the seven
innings he pitched except the fifth, and they put the leadoff
runner on three times. But the resilient righthander didn't allow
another run until the seventh when Manny Martinez scored on Orlando
Cabrera's two-out double to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few times I made bad pitches, but I was lucky enough
that it didn't end up hurting me too much,'' said Holt, who has
allowed two or fewer earned runs in each of his past five starts.
``I got mad at myself a couple of times, because I know I can make
better pitches. But the bottom line is we got a win, and I'll take
a win any way I can get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt left the game with two out and runners on second and third
with the Astros grasping a 4-2 lead. Trever Miller coaxed a crucial
inning-ending grounder from pinch hitter James Mouton to end the
Expos' threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to get out of that situation,'' said Miller, who
did allow an eighth-inning run, only his fourth in 17 appearances.
``We (the bullpen) have let Chris down a couple of times before,
and it felt nice to be the guy to get him rolling. It also feels
nice that they (the coaches) are getting more confidence in me and
are willing to put me in those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact they were on the wrong end of a rout, the Expos
wanted to get closer Ugueth Urbina some work in the eighth inning.
Everett's eyes must have lit up. Two of Everett's three career hits
against Urbina have been grand slams, including his last one before
Sunday, which came in 1997 when Everett played for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urbina is basically a slider/changeup pitcher,'' said Everett,
who has six multihomer games in his career. ``He throws a fastball
in the upper 90s, but he really doesn't use it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
