<HEADER>
A3166 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LAD     06-21 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARZAN'S SWING TOPS AUSTIN'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A new swinger topped a record-setting slate at the
nation's multiplexes as ``Tarzan'' edged ``Austin Powers: The Spy
Who Shagged Me'' with an estimated $34.1 million at 3,005 theaters
during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan,'' Disney's 37th animated feature, beat the goofy
sequel by slightly more than $2 million as the musical comedy
posted the second-best opening ever for an animated film after
1994's debut of ``The Lion King.'' Strong reviews and a massive
marketing push led to ``Tarzan'' performing well above industry
forecasts, which had been in the $26 million to $28 million range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marketing department did a spectacular job in being able
to convince the public to see a film they already knew,'' said
Disney marketing executive Chuck Viane. ``We had never thought we'd
be able to beat `Austin Powers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Multiplex business was spectacular with ``Tarzan'' and ``The Spy
Who Shagged Me'' at well more than $30 million each, a solid
opening for ``The General's Daughter'' with $22.3 million and an
impressive $17.8 million for ``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom
Menace.'' Estimates showed an overall total of $129 million, a
record for a nonholiday weekend and well above the previous $124
million mark set over July 24-26 when ``Saving Private Ryan''
opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' tapped the family market effectively with that group
composing 65 percent of audiences, with more than 80 percent of
viewers saying they would ``definitely recommend'' the film, Viane
said. ``We saw lots of large families, with grandparents and young
children, going into theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie analyst Arthur Rockwell said ``Tarzan'' is on its way to
becoming another powerful franchise for Disney. ``It was a bold
move by Disney to lock up the rights to the character, which they
can exploit better than anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service, said ``Tarzan'' benefited from drawing young teens and
could do as much as $200 million domestically. That would rank it
as the third-largest Disney animated film ever after ``The Lion
King'' at $313 million and ``Aladdin'' at $217 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word of mouth on `Tarzan' is amazing, and it doesn't have
any real competition for families until Disney opens `Inspector
Gadget' on July 23,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   The strong opening underscores the ongoing strength of Disney's
core business of animated films at a time when rivals such as
DreamWorks and Paramount have been encroaching on its turf. Disney
traditionally releases a mid-June animated film, but its last four
_ ``Pocahontas,'' ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' ``Hercules,''
``Mulan'' _ have been viewed as slightly disappointing with each
grossing well under $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   New Line's second weekend of ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' with
Mike Myers as the swinging British secret agent, lost 42 percent
from its massive opening but still drew impressively with $31.9
million at 3,314 theaters. That brought its total to a stunning
$116.7 million after 11 days, making it the 127th highest-grosser
of all time and giving it a shot at joining the club of 26 films
that have topped $200 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   Also posting solid numbers were Paramount's opening of ``The
General's Daughter'' with $22.3 million at 2,856 theaters as the
John Travolta thriller performed in line with expectations. Studio
executives reported the audience for ``Daughter,'' with Travolta as
a military investigator, was predominantly over 25 as its strategy
of counter-programming toward adults paid off.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The General's Daughter' did very respectable business that
was brought in mostly by Travolta,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth weekend of ``Star Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace''
finished a strong fourth at 3,019 theaters to push its 33-day take
to $327 million, $2.5 million short of ``Forrest Gump'' at the No.
5 spot on the all-time list and $274 million behind ``Titanic'' at
No. 1. The prequel's decline from its fourth weekend amounted to
only 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said most customers seeing ``Phantom Menace'' now are
repeaters and noted that creator George Lucas and distributor 20th
Century Fox made back their investment long ago. ``Everything now
is just gravy for them,'' he added. ``Even though it won't beat
`Titanic,' the numbers are still mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a distant but decent fifth place was Universal's
fourth weekend of ``Notting Hill'' with $7 million at 2,786 sites
to push its total to nearly $80 million. Disney's third weekend of
``Instinct'' continued its fast fade with $3.1 million at 2,129
theaters, edging Universal's seventh weekend of ``The Mummy'' with
$3 million at 2,332 to push its overall take to nearly $142
million.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were a trio of holdovers led by Warner
Bros.' 12th weekend of ``The Matrix'' with $1.4 million at 1,365
screens to push its total past $163 million to 50th place, topping
``The Sound of Music.'' Fox's eighth weekend of ``Entrapment''
followed with $1.2 million at 1,465 theaters and MGM's sixth
weekend of ``Tea With Mussolini'' finished 10th with $625,000 at
273 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's limited opening of romantic comedy ``An Ideal
Husband'' generated strong returns with $195,000 at 10 theaters and
will be expanded in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful box office performance should continue for several
more weeks with a trio of high-profile openings due shortly. Sony's
Adam Sandler comedy ``Big Daddy'' opens Friday, while Warner's Will
Smith vehicle ``Wild Wild West'' and Paramount's ``South Park''
both debut June 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
