<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-21 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ It was five years ago when the Rockets and Knicks
engaged in a lurching, brutish, disjointed, offense-starved affair
in the NBA Finals, and the TV-viewing eyes of the nation grew heavy
with disinterest.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in Houston we either barely noticed or hardly minded
that what we were watching was less than an artistic masterpiece.
To finally put a grip on the long-suffering city's first major
professional sports title, we'd have been content to watch a pair
of bull elephants dance in tutus.
</P>
<P>
   Beauty, after all, is in the eye of the beholder of the
championship trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why there is no complaining these days in San Antonio,
a town that is at long last ready to put aside its reputation as a
place that honors glorious defeat and usher in a new era with the
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Alamo City is filled with tooting car horns and
the music of a basketball fiesta, the sounds of the NBA in just
about every place else from coast to coast are these: Clank! And
Click!
</P>
<P>
   That's Clank! as in all of the missed shots by both teams in
this year's Finals, most notably the 1-for-20 stretch by the Knicks
in the first half of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   That's Click! as in all of those channels changing on all of
those TVs. Nash Bridges on CBS and 20/20 on ABC never had it this
good in the ratings game on Friday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was no real reason to expect the 1999 Finals to
produce gripping drama in the first place. Consider that the level
of play in the league this year had already plummeted like a
watermelon heaved down an empty elevator shaft thanks to the labor
lockout, the compressed schedule and the first year post-Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Add on the fact that this is a meeting between the No. 1 seed in
all of the league, the absolutely sizzling Spurs, winners of 44 of
their past 50 games, and the No. 8 seed from the Eastern
Conference, the Knicks, a half-lucky, half-gritty Cinderella with
cornrows that is now being exposed for what it truly is:
overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   The result to date has been a pair of San Antonio wins that have
produced the largest 2-0 lead since the Enola Gay flew over
Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is more than merely one championship series and one
set of TV ratings that is taking a hit here. It is the
entertainment value of the NBA game itself, which has been
declining for most of the '90s as a result of physical play on the
inside, a decline in fundamental skills from the increasingly young
players who enter the league and _ perhaps most important of all _
the suffocating effect of micromanaging and overcoaching that has
taken away the free-form jazz style of an improvisational sport.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why NBA commissioner David Stern _ years after he first
so cavalierly waved off warnings of impending trouble _ is
gathering a select committee of coaches and assorted executives
here in New York on Tuesday in an attempt to inject offense back
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk of both increasing and decreasing the time
on the shot clock and of moving the 3-point line either closer or
farther away from the basket. There is speculation about changing
the shape of the lane, making it wider at the base to clear out
more room in the middle and open up the game again to the drivers
and slashers who are most creative with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   This is how serious the Joint Chiefs of Points are: They're even
considering sending out a memo that would order referees to call a
foul when a defender is using his forearm like an ax against the
trunk of an oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   It says here that the most effective rule change would be to
eliminate the 3-point line altogether. It has become a cancer
growing wildly and unchecked throughout the body of the sport,
warping the game and giving us the yawning spectacle of players
spotted up along the arc watching one or two teammates work an
isolation play.
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA eliminated the 3-point line _ and the bonus for
long-range heaving _ it would bring motion back into the game. It
would also force players to rediscover the lost art of the 16- to
18-foot jumper that used to be automatic.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Knicks are struggling badly on the championship
stage, having failed to score 20 points in five of the eight
quarters played to date. The Spurs easily won a game when they
scored just 80 points, part of the second-lowest combined offensive
output (147 points) in Finals history.
</P>
<P>
   This is an ugly, sloppy and dull brand of basketball, as it was
five years ago when it was the Rockets and the Knicks. It's just
that from outside the emotional investment, it hits you right
between the eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
