u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WENATCHEE-SEX-CASE-SP     06-21 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENATCHEE-SEX-CASE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WILL ALLOW WOMAN'S SUIT AGAINST STATE, CITY OF WENATCHEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sarah Doggett, one of 60 Wenatchee children the state
insists were sexually abused in the mid-1990s, has won the right to
sue authorities for allegedly kidnapping her and forcing her into
an Idaho mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In an unexpected move Friday, King County Superior Court Judge
Richard Eadie ruled that justice would not be served if procedural
problems prevent Doggett from pursuing her lawsuit against the
state Department of Social and Health Services, former Wenatchee
police Detective Bob Perez and the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   Also named in the suit are Child Protective Service workers Dean
Reiman and Pat Boggess.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett, now 20 and living in California, is the eldest Mark and
Carol Doggett's five children. Her parents were swept up in the
1994-95 Wenatchee child sex abuse cases where 43 adults were
accused of nearly 30,000 counts of rape and molestation involving
60 children.
</P>
<P>
   Perez accused the Doggetts of 1,000 counts each of child sexual
abuse. They were convicted of one count each of child rape and were
sentenced to nearly 11 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The couple was released from prison in June 1998, after an
appellate court ruled the state failed to introduce evidence
showing the reliability of accusations made by one of their
children.
</P>
<P>
   While allowing Chelan County to refile the charges, the court
ruled any new trial may come only after a hearing on whether the
child's statements against her parents were tainted by coercive or
suggestive interview techniques used by police and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Chelan County Prosecutor Gary Reisen has not said if he will
seek another trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Doggett's suit centers on her claims that her civil rights
were violated when she was ``forcibly removed'' from a foster home
in California on Jan. 4, 1995, by Perez and Boggess, a CPS social
worker. Five days later, the suit contends, she was forced to
accept treatment at Pine Crest, a psychiatric hospital in Coeur
d'Alene, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of Jan. 10, 1995, CPS officials in Wenatchee
invited Doggett in for a talk but almost immediately called a
LifeLine Ambulance to pick up the then-16-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing voluntary about it. They had an ambulance
(crew) come to the DSHS office in Wenatchee, tie me to the gurney
and drive me off to Idaho,'' Doggett told the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer. ``They put me in Pine Crest. The paperwork says
I went there voluntarily, which is not true, not true at all. Since
when does `voluntary' mean handcuffs, restraints and shackles
around my waist to the gurney?'''
</P>
<P>
   Doggett and other teenagers say they were forced into Pine
Crest, even though Washington state law forbids involuntary
commitment of those older than 13 unless they are a proven threat
to themselves or to others.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts on behalf of Doggett and several other Wenatchee
children to sue Pine Crest and its parent company were thwarted
when the hospital's corporation went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The state claims Doggett agreed to treatment, was suicidal and
had an eating disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those were their concerns,'' she asks, ``why did almost all
my treatment at Pine Crest deal with me having to remember sexual
abuse that never happened? They insisted that I'd stay at Pine
Crest until I admitted that my parents had raped and molested us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That never happened, never,'' she said. ``My parents never
touched us like that and I wasn't going to say that they did.''
</P>
<P>
   She was held at Pine Crest for a month. She never accused her
parents of any charge.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett's suit was filed in February 1997. In September of that
year, Doggett's Spokane lawyer quit, leaving the 19-year-old
without counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mailbox was filled with legal papers but none of them made
any sense to me at all,'' Doggett said. ``I was trying to find
another lawyer, but I was in California, by myself, with only the
money I was making as a cashier in a sports store. No one seemed to
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no way of knowing that if I didn't respond to the
papers, my case would be thrown out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Eadie, having received no response from
Doggett, dropped all charges except one against Chelan County.
</P>
<P>
   However, two weeks after the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
published ``The Power To Harm,'' a series of articles about
misconduct in the Wenatchee investigations and prosecutions,
Seattle lawyers Ronald Meltzer, Mike Rosen and Lynne Wilson agreed
to take Doggett's case and fought to have it reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's ruling, Eadie acknowledged Doggett should have
responded to the court papers. However, the judge said justice
would be better served if he reinstated most of the suits.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the facts at the time Doggett received the 1998 motions
to dismiss: she was young, confused, without counsel and suffering
from depression.''
</P>
<P>
   Eadie did not allow the reinstatement of claims against Cindy
Andrews, a state-hired mental health therapist, and Tim Abby, a
supervisor in the CPS Wenatchee office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
