<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KOREA-NIGERIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA BEATS NORTH KOREA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Marvelous Mercy Akide told anyone who would
listen that Nigeria was more than just a song-and-dance sideshow.
She was right, giving Cinderella a whole new look _ one with more
multicolored hair than Dennis Rodman and a goalkeeper (Ann
Chiejine) with more flair than Jorge Campos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the chosen one did all the talking. Akide, who said
earlier in the week that her team was not afraid of anyone, not
only walked it, she talked it, personally making sure Nigeria's
third Women's World Cup showing was a good one.
</P>
<P>
   Akide scored, then notched the game-winning assist as Nigeria
defeated North Korea 2-1 in their opening game of Group A action
Sunday at the Rose Bowl in front of 17,102.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of you know my name by now,'' Akide said. ``You
have to give a lot of glory to God and by the grace of God we will
be victorious again against the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the U.S. and Nigeria opened Group A with victories. They
meet Thursday in Chicago, with the winner assured a spot in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I don't care if we meet the Brazilian men's
team or the U.S.'s men's team, I believe in attacking football and
that's what we will continue to do,'' said Nigerian coach Ismalia
Mabo, whose team showed typical African speed and touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in football you have to take risks, especially in a
tournament of this magnitude and we will continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Falcons came into the tournament almost unknown
despite their easy road through African qualifying, outscoring
opponents 25-0. Because they rarely travel outside of Africa and
because they were winless in six previous games in Women's World
Cup action since 1991, few experts gave them any chances of winning
a game.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when they arrived in Los Angeles, sending shock
waves throughout the tournament after a 4-3 friendly victory over
China, one of the pretournament favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that victory psyched our girls,'' Mabo said. ``It
was a morale booster. We told the people back home what we had done
and we promised them we wouldn't be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, they're certainly not afraid of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they (U.S.) are the favorites,'' Mabo said. ``But I
think we sent a message tonight that this team is going to fight to
the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be intimidated, we are going to attack
them and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria scored first as Akide muscled her way past a North
Korean defender along the end line in the 50th minute. She was
looking to thread a cross in front of the goal area, but with no
strikers cutting toward the net, she rifled a right-footed shot to
the near post.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean goalkeeper Jong Hui Ri had the post covered, but
Akides' shot was too strong, bouncing off Ri's arm to the near
netting for a 1-0 lead in the 50th minute.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea tied the match on a beautiful timing pass in the
74th minute. Along the left side, Jong Ran Jo sent a through pass
to a cutting Song Ok Jo, who was able to one-touch from five yards
out to tie the match.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't last long as Akide once again found herself free
down the right side after a pass from Patience Avre. With Ri coming
out to challenge, Akide slipped a pass in front of the net,
allowing Rita Nwadike to finish an easy tap-in to earn the victory
in the 79th minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
