<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-21 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTMARE OF A COURSE REALLY A DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ One of the questions here has been whether
they'll get another one. After what we just saw, a better question
might be, why can't they get every one?
</P>
<P>
   This was a United States Open for the ages, a tense and dramatic
battle of man vs. man that was almost always dwarfed by the even
more intriguing matchup of man vs. course. It is not very often
that the pampered golfers of the PGA Tour covet the same role all
those vanquished Dream Team opponents did seven years ago. That is
to say, the basic players' mantra here was ``Beat me, whip me,
invite me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament started, people said it would prove to be
a tribute to Donald Ross, the man who laid out this course 92 years
ago. As it unfolded, people said it was a tribute to Donald Ross.
And now that it's over, people can reiterate that it was a tribute
to Donald Ross. Never have so many been so humbled so happily.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a competition in which four men had a very reasonable
chance to win with three holes to play, and this quite obviously
has to go down as one of the great Opens of all time. Winning an
Open at any time is a thrill and great achievement. Being the only
man to break par over four days at this particular US Open gives
Payne Stewart an inordinate measure of satisfaction, all the more
so because in order to win his second Open title he needed to sink
a 15-foot putt on the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to pretend I was Jack Nicklaus sinking a putt to win
the US Open,'' he confided. ``It's exciting to think someone might
now be out there pretending to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   The final nine holes of this tournament Sunday provided
extraordinary theater. First Tiger Woods, having squandered some
very good birdie opportunities by failing to make putts (turning,
for example, a very good birdie chance into a three-putt), injected
himself back into the hunt with birdies on Nos. 14 and 16. He was
very much in it until he failed to take advantage of a superb sand
shot by blowing a 4-foot putt on 17. As he marched to the 18th tee,
he was heard to take his Maker's name in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking in the bulrushes for the entire tournament was the
mysterious Fiji-born golfing machine known as Vijay Singh. He began
the day three strokes behind the leader, Stewart. By the 10th he
was 2 under for the day, and by the 13th he was only one stroke
behind Stewart and Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Singh was sailing along until the 16th. The golfing machine
began to break down with a drive into the left rough. His second
shot was flat, landing on an embankment about 100 yards from the
green. He got to within 15 feet, but he couldn't nail the putt,
settling for a bogey 5.
</P>
<P>
   The greens at Pinehurst No. 2 are often very close to the next
tee. We are talking verrry close. As Singh was addressing his tee
shot on the par-3, 191-yard 17th, a ball plopped onto the 16th
green and a tremendous roar went up. It was Tiger's second shot.
Vijay responded by nailing his tee shot to within 6 or 7 feet. He
wasn't dead yet. But after waiting for Tiger to putt out on the
hole behind him, Singh missed the putt. Now he really was out of
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Picture stuff was unfolding all the time. As Tiger's
playing partner, Tim Herron, was lining up his putt on 17, there
was a huge groan from the gallery back at 16. That was Mickelson
missing a putt for his only bogey of the day. Seconds later a great
cheer went up from the same people as Tiger was lining up his putt.
That was Stewart ramming home a 25-footer for a critical par.
</P>
<P>
   People would later ask Stewart and Mickelson if either ever felt
in control of the tournament. What nonsense. No one is ever in
control of a tournament at No. 2. The course is in charge. Getting
a birdie here is not cause for celebration. It is a warning. What
it usually means is that retribution is just ahead. There is no
such thing as momentum when you play No. 2. It is as if you're
taking it to the hoop and there is a shot-blocker on every hole.
</P>
<P>
   That's why what Stewart and Mickelson did over the final two
holes will go down in golf history. Tied for the lead after 16
holes of competition, each man hit his tee shot to within 6 or 7
feet on 17. Mickelson missed his putt. Stewart sank his to go one
up with a hole to play.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson drove safely on 18. Stewart caught the left rough. He
took no chances getting out with a 9-iron, and then he delivered a
lob wedge about 15 feet below the hole, even as Mickelson was on in
two with a 20-footer, but a typically diabolical Pinehurst
20-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The rangy lefty had to settle for par. Stewart stood over his
putt, determined it was ``inside left,'' made sure he kept his head
still (a handy tip from his wife), and dropped it in.
</P>
<P>
   Winning this tournament was work. ``I'm fatigued,'' said
Stewart. ``I'm tired. I know I should be hungry, but I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   To win at Pinehurst requires a special combination of skill and
resolve. That's why the good players love playing here. So what if
there were only four subpar rounds in the final three days? This is
a course that, without being tricked up, puts a little hair on your
chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the course,'' saluted Mickelson. ``I'm sure everyone
would tell you this. It's a course that tests all of your shots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the USGA is very pleased with what happened this
week,'' declared Payne Stewart, the new US Open champion. ``The
golf course stood the test.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, Payne. You stood the test. The golf course just
invited you to give it your best shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
