<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ITALY-GERMANY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY TIES GERMANY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 Staff Writer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Italy coach Carlo Facchin pondered the
question for a moment and was quick and straightforward with his
response. Was Italy pleased with getting a point out of Sunday's
1-1 tie with Germany in a Group B Women's World Cup match in front
of 17,102 at the Rose Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we were,'' Facchin said. ``This was not Mexico (we
played), it was Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Had the opponent been Mexico _ a 7-1 loser to Brazil in the
other Group B match, Saturday at Giants Stadium _ Facchin might
have been a bit more disenchanted with the result. But against one
of the tournament's top four seeds, getting a point after the
team's first match was pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Germany is a good team,'' Italy midfielder Antonella
Carta said. ``I would say they probably have the best players in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so a few American women might beg to differ, but the point
is clear. A tie leaves this group wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every game, we want to win,'' said Germany coach Tina
Theune-Meyer. ``But today I can live with a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which will play Brazil on Thursday in Chicago prior to
the United States-Nigeria match, scored its goal in the first half
on a header by diminutive striker Patrizia Panico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the Germans didn't really consider me because I am not
as tall,'' said a smiling Panico, who stands 5-foot-4 and was wide
open just 10 feet from the goal when she headed Carta's chip past
German goalkeeper Silke Rottenberg. ``I just waited for the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rottenberg and Theune-Mayer said defender Doris Fitschen was out
of position on the play, leaving Panico unmarked for the
36th-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then the ball deflected off (Fitschen's) leg and I didn't
have a chance,'' Rottenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, Italy's counterattack kept Germany on its heels,
drawing numerous fouls and creating several quality chances in its
bid for the upset. The second half, however, was a different story
as Germany began to play the type of game it has shown in the past
to rank it among the best teams in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the first 15 minutes of the second half would be
hell,'' Carta said.
</P>
<P>
   That it was as Germany peppered Italy goalkeeper Giorgia Brenzan
with shot after shot, including one by Maren Meinert on a volley
that hit the crossbar two minutes into the final 45. Carta
countered for Italy on a direct kick just above the arc with her
own crossbar-rattling blast just five minutes later, but the score
remained tied.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans finally cracked Italy in the 61st minute when Birgit
Prinz drew a hard tackle from Roberta Stefanelli on the left wing,
resulting in a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   Bettina Wiegmann scored the equalizer, sending a low shot into
the right corner of the net. Brenzan guessed correctly but didn't
have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team really threatened down the stretch, although
Germany averted a near-disaster when Panico's cross deflected off
defender Kerstin Stegemann, trickling past Rottenberg just by the
left post for a corner kick.
</P>
<P>
   Wiegmann, who with her teammates will play Mexico on Thursday in
Portland, remembers the last time Italy and Germany played to a 1-1
tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the European Championships in 1997 and it was one of
the first games,'' Wiegmann said. ``But in the end, we ended up
champions. If the same result happens here, we'll be happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
