<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REIGN OF PAYNE 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Payne Stewart, who tasted the sting of defeat
a year ago in the US Open at San Francisco's Olympic Club, said on
the eve of Sunday's final round of the 99th championship over the
storied No. 2 course at Pinehurst Resort and Country Club that
whoever won would do it around and on the greens. He proceeded to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   This may have been the most gutsy performance seen in the
nation's major tournament, culminating when Stewart sank a 15-foot
putt on the 18th hole to win the championship. After all, Stewart
missed the first four greens on the back side in regulation, but he
made perhaps the two biggest putts of his career on the 16th to
save par and on the 18th to save the par that won him the Open for
the second time.
</P>
<P>
   That brought him home in 68-69-72-70_279, 1 under par, to finish
one shot in front of playing partner Phil Mickelson (70_280), who
missed a birdie putt from 25 feet on the 72d hole that would have
forced a playoff Monday. Tiger Woods (70_281) missed a rash of
short putts that cost him his second major championship, and PGA
Championship winner Vijay Singh (69_281) saw his chances dashed on
the 16th, when he endured his only bogey of the round out of the
heavy left rough.
</P>
<P>
   As defender Lee Janzen said Saturday, ``I've been asked many
times what the hardest golf course is I've ever played. Now I have
the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Steve Stricker (73_285) broke par in the third round with a
1-under 69. Singh and Dudley Hart (69_291, tied for 17th) were in
subpar numbers Sunday. The course was applauded, but the USGA's
set-up drew considerable criticism.
</P>
<P>
   It still stood the test and produced a rousingly competitive
show that brought out the best in Stewart, who won a title to go
with the one he won at Hazeltine eight years ago in a playoff with
Scott Simpson. Just a year ago, Stewart shot a closing 74 to
Janzen's 68 to lose by a shot. This was all forgotten Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This championship essentially came down to the final three
holes. Stewart's chip on the 16th, where ``for some reason I felt I
needed to make it,'' went 25 feet past the hole. He made the
par-saving putt. Mickelson pulled a 3-iron into the rough, chopped
it out, hit a 3-iron to 8 feet, and missed for his lone bogey.
Stewart's 6-iron on the par-3 17th settled in within 3 feet of the
pin. Mickelson missed his birdie attempt.
</P>
<P>
   There was the constant presence of Woods, who made a twisting
putt on the 14th for his third birdie of the day but pulled his tee
shot on 17 and ended up missing a putt to save par that he said was
8 feet but seemed a lot closer. When he missed a curling putt for
birdie on the 18th, all he could do was sit and watch. ``I did
everything I possibly could do to hang in there,'' said Woods, who
missed a par putt from inside 3 feet on 11.
</P>
<P>
   So it came down to Stewart, who said his first victory, in 1982
at Quad Cities, will also be his fondest because his father was
able to see it before he died of cancer, and Mickelson, whose wife
Amy is expecting their first child before the end of the month.
Mickelson struck a gorgeous second shot into the 18th hole after
Stewart's tee ball strayed into the right rough. He pitched short
of the trap to the front right of the green.
</P>
<P>
   This is where it seemed there might be an 18-hole playoff. After
Mickelson missed his birdie putt, Stewart stood over his par-saver
from 15 feet and looked up just in time to see it go into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the putting green last night,'' he said, ``and my
wife (Tracey) told me I was moving my head when I putted. I didn't
move it once today. I read the putt. I just knew it was going to go
to the right. I looked up when it was 2 feet from the hole, and
couldn't believe it was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt with three holes to go, I was in control of the
tournament,'' said Mickelson ``I was leading, and it's a very
difficult course to make birdies on. It's unfortunate that the only
bogey came on the 16th hole. I felt I still had a very good chance,
even until the last putt. Payne made two exceptional putts on 16
and 18, and I think those putts showed a lot of character. I putted
well, but I pulled the two on 17 and 18 and missed by an inch or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was give myself a chance,'' said Stewart,
who hit only seven greens in regulation. ``I never gave up. I
didn't hit that many great shots, but I got the job done. I said
yesterday if I won again I was going to enjoy it. If I told you my
emotions, I'd choke up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
