<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ MASTERFUL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's becoming a hitter's nightmare, the kind that
figures to be repeated a lot this season. It begins with Pedro
Martinez and his 90 mile-per-hour fastball, and it ends with Tim
Wakefield and his dancing knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it went Sunday at Fenway Park, where the Red Sox
defeated the Texas Rangers, 5-2, before 31,501. Martinez scattered
six hits and struck out 10 while allowing just one run before
departing after eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   After two Red Sox relievers got one out, Wakefield came into the
game to retire the last two batters, striking out one, as he
notched his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory and a Yankees loss to Anaheim, the Red Sox
pulled to within half a game of first-place New York in the AL
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing _ again _ is how Pedro pitched,'' said Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams. ``He sets the tone. He really competed out
there. He kept us in the game early when we didn't capitalize on
some situations. He just kept pitching and getting outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the same in every game and every start. To say the
least, he's kept us in every game. He must be pitching pretty darn
good. And we've got some relievers who have picked him up and done
a nice job. When he does pitch, we play good defense behind him.
The pitches that he has and the heart to compete makes him pretty
special.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would have blamed Martinez if he had viewed Sunday's
start with some concern. Texas has a power-packed lineup, but the
Rangers couldn't dent Martinez until the fourth, when Rafael
Palmeiro drove in a run with a sacrifice fly. Boston rallied for
three runs in the bottom of the inning off rookie Ryan Glynn (0-2),
who allowed three runs on eight hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ninth, Texas wouldn't score again. Maybe part of the
reason is because since Martinez lost, 13-1, to Montreal June 9,
he's viewing each opponent with equal respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to fall into that trap,'' he said. ``There is no
one weak team in this league. Everybody here is a big leaguer, and
that's how I take them all. I pitch with the same intensity that I
do with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Rangers? One of the best, you might say. But they're all
good. Montreal knocked me out and stopped my roll after nine (wins)
in a row. They were supposed to be the underdog. (Sunday) I went
out and competed and felt comfortable after the third inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Martinez felt much better after the fourth-inning
rally by his teammates. The inning began as Damon Buford reached on
an error by shortstop Royce Clayton. Trot Nixon brought him home
with the second of his three hits, a triple to the triangle in deep
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to drive the ball up the middle or to the left
side,'' said Nixon. ``It's something I have to work on more and
more. It felt good. I got a pitch where I wanted it and I didn't
try to do much with it. I thought (Roberto) Kelly had a bead on it.
I didn't think I hit it that good. When I saw him stop short of the
wall, I knew that I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to help the team out. I haven't done that much
this year. I just tell myself to keep working, keep battling.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon scored on a single by Jose Offerman, who scored from first
on a double by John Valentin. In the eighth, the Sox scored two
more runs after a leadoff double by Jason Varitek and consecutive
singles by Nixon, Offerman, and Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield seemed perfectly at ease with his new role as closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer I do it the more comfortable I feel doing the job
I'm asked to do,'' said Wakefield. ``I handle it the same way as if
I'd been a starter. I'm not going to get beat with my second or
third pitch. I'm going to go out and do what I know best, which is
to throw knuckleballs to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the performance of the Red Sox starter that was on
the minds of the Rangers afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martinez is very, very good,'' said Mark McLemore. ``He was
outstanding. The scary part about it is that he's better than that.
He didn't have his A game. He had his A-minus game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said his potent team, which has
played 13 of the last 16 games on the road, has been battling
top-notch pitching along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not swinging the bats real well,'' he said. ``You put a
Pedro on the mound and that's not a good mixture for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been struggling for three weeks to get our offense going
the way we know we can. But in the last three weeks, we've faced
the likes of Roger Clemens, David Cone, Randy Johnson, Andy Benes,
and Kevin Brown. That's a pretty good bunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
