<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD'S CREDENTIALS NOT OVERWHELMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Quick. Who's the best fighter Felix Trinidad has
beaten?
</P>
<P>
   Thought so. No one comes to mind, which raises this question: Is
the jury still out on the fighter who is expected to give Oscar De
La Hoya the toughest fight of his career on Sept. 18 in Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad's most significant victory might be his eighth-round
knockout of Oba Carr in 1994. Beyond that, he beat capable but
forgettable Maurice Blocker to win the IBF welterweight title in
1993 and outpointed fading, 35-year-old Pernell Whitaker in
February.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the kind of credentials one might expect from a
fighter with Trinidad's reputation. At least that's how Robert
Alcazar, De La Hoya's trainer, sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who has he fought? Give me one good fighter,'' said Alcazar,
speaking at a news conference on Saturday at Universal Studios to
promote the fight. ``... People think this is the best fighter
Oscar is going to face. I don't see it that way. I think Trinidad
is a good fighter but not the best. Ike Quartey is one of a few
that are better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I see the difference is Trinidad is too weak for De La
Hoya, and De La Hoya is smarter _ smarter and stronger. And I see a
weakness. Trinidad is quick, he hits hard with both hands, he's a
good technician, but that's from the waist up. From the waist down,
he doesn't know how to walk around the ring. No balance, no
nothing. It's much the same as (Rafael) Ruelas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be a big advantage for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, De La Hoya has faced better competition.
</P>
<P>
   He outpointed Quartey, a bona fide star, in February and has
beaten Genaro Hernandez, Miguel Angel Gonzalez, Carr and a younger,
better Whitaker, all of whom were credible opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trinidad believes De La Hoya is more hype than substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar has done very well marketing himself, but he's not the
boxer people think he is,'' he said through an interpreter. ``I
won't tell you what I think his weaknesses are. On Sept. 18, you'll
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Don King, Trinidad's promoter, admits his fighter has yet to
become one of history's most-revered champions. However, a
convincing victory over the Golden Boy could change that radically.
</P>
<P>
   He compared the fight to the first Roberto Duran-Sugar Ray
Leonard matchup in 1980, in which King promoted Duran, and Bob Arum
(De La Hoya's promoter) handled Leonard. Duran captured the
attention of the world when he won a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly like that fight,'' King said. ``Leonard was the
darling of America, Duran was mine, and Duran took him. It's the
same situation with this fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``... (Trinidad's) a superstar with all of us who recognize his
talents. However, this fight, in one fell swoop, could do more than
reams of stories (about Trinidad) could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight says it all. If he knocks out Oscar as I predict he
will, he'll capture everything De La Hoya has in addition to what
he has.''
</P>
<P>
   What does De La Hoya have to say?
</P>
<P>
   Not much. Of course, he predicts a victory but prefers to let
Trinidad do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``May the best man win,'' he said _ smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Odd couple: The De La Hoya-Trinidad matchup has created strange
bedfellows: arch rivals King and Arum, who have worked side-by-side
only a handful of times over their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Arum was livid that King, Trinidad and Co. were an hour and a
half late for the outdoor news conference, which left hundreds of
De La Hoya fans and members of the media wilting under the hot
afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   However, he didn't complain after the eighth of nine conferences
on the promotional tour. Believe it or not, both Arum and King were
complimentary of one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This conduct today was inexcusable,'' Arum said. ``But I must
say it's the first time it's happened on the tour. He has really
worked hard trying to sell the event. Sometimes he gets long-winded
and carried away with himself, but I suppose that's the price you
pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a professional. We don't have many professionals as
promoters in this sport these days.''
</P>
<P>
   King was equally magnanimous.
</P>
<P>
   He publicly congratulated Arum on his induction into the
International Boxing Hall of Fame, to which King already belongs,
and said he harbors no grudges in spite of years of bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have had our differences, but the man is a
professional,'' King said. ``He was just inducted into the Hall of
Fame. He deserves it. I have no difficulties with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, this fight is of historic proportions. I think, on
Bob's part and my part, we dare not jeopardize history because of
personal idiosyncrasies.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling groovy: De La Hoya seems to be in fine spirits these
days.
</P>
<P>
   He recently fired longtime adviser Mike Hernandez, among others,
and feels he has gained more control over his own destiny, which
gives him what has eluded him for years: peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   That and the excitement of his biggest fight have inspired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time I've noticed myself really focusing even
before training,'' he said. ``I have my game face on already. I
really feel it, it feels different. Since I made my changes outside
the ring, I feel much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge load I was carrying. I dumped the excess baggage.
It's a smooth ride from now on. It's time to take it to another
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand injury: De La Hoya said the hand he injured in his last
fight, against Carr last month, is healed.
</P>
<P>
   He strained tendons in his left hand early in the bout and was
in pain the rest of the way. He wore a cast for about week but is
now able to spar, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez-De La Hoya vs. Vargas: Raul Marquez, who is scheduled to
challenge IBF junior welterweight champion Fernando Vargas on July
17 in Lake Tahoe, has a secret weapon in his corner: De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who befriended Marquez when both fought for the
United States in the 1992 Olympics, has allowed Marquez to train in
his Big Bear camp and has helped with training expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've supplied sparring partners and helped any way we can,''
De La Hoya said. ``He didn't have training expenses, so we helped
out there, too. He was at every disadvantage. We wanted to make
sure everything was even.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my buddy.... When everyone was losing and going their own
way (in the Olympics), Marquez was right behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad De La Hoya can't get into the ring with Vargas. That's
the help Marquez really needs.
</P>
<P>
   Breath taking?: P.J. Goossen of North Hollywood, who lost a
monumentally one-sided decision to Hector ``Macho'' Camacho on
Friday in Struthers, Ohio, said Sunday that a third-round punch
broke three of his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   That left him gasping for air and unable to fight to his ability
the remainder of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even get quarter breaths,'' said Goossen, who had
X-rays taken in Ohio. ``I looked (lousy) for that reason alone. I
couldn't breath. I basically went into survival mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``... He's a great fighter. I take nothing away from him. But
things would've been a lot different if I could've breathed, if I
could've defended myself and thrown power punches back.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen has had his share of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Among his setbacks, hand injuries have disrupted his career; he
was stabbed at a party, which kept him out of the ring for months;
and he broke his foot four days before he was scheduled to fight
Roberto Duran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't keep saying it's bad luck,'' said Goossen, still
devastated on Sunday afternoon. ``Too many things happen to me in
boxing. I don't know. It's just very upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, 29, also perforated an eardrum early in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Michael Grant's unanimous victory over Lou
Savarese on Saturday was convincing but not particularly
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Many expected a dominating performance, particularly against
such a mediocre opponent, as he tries to bolster his image as the
best young heavyweight in the world. Instead, the 6-foot-7,
256-pounder looked ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that he has a lot to learn.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, Jeremy Williams was outpointed by journeyman
Maurice Harris in a heavyweight bout....
</P>
<P>
   Cuban defector Joel Casamayor easily outpointed Mexico's Antonio
Hernandez on Saturday night. He is now in line for a title bid
against the WBA's reigning junior lightweight world champion,
Japan's Takanory Hatakeyama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
