<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-GRANT-SAVARESE-BO     06-21 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GRANT-SAVARESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPORTUNITY KNOCKED, BUT NO ONE ANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many opportunities were missed Saturday night at The
Theatre at Madison Square Garden and not all by the people throwing
punches.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Michael Grant missed an opportunity to separate
himself from the pack of young heavyweight contenders who are the
short-term future of the division when he easily won a 10-round
decision from former contender Lou Savarese but was unimpressive _
though damaging to Savarese's good looks _ while doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Savarese missed an opportunity to reestablish himself as
a contender rather than confirm he is the fast fading pretender
most observers long ago concluded he was. All he got out of
Saturday night's tiff was a $1.05 million purse and another mugging
by his latest and possibly last opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Without question Jeremy Williams missed an opportunity to make a
case for himself as a legitimate heavyweight, losing a lopsided
decision to a last-second replacement named Maurice Harris, who
seemed to hurt Williams every time he landed flush on his chin,
which was often.
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis, the World Boxing Council titleholder, was at
ringside and missed the chance to come away with a viable option to
a rematch with Evander Holyfield. Lewis had flown to New York at
midday to discuss his future and the possibility of substituting
the winner of the Grant-Savarese fight for either Holyfield or
mandatory challenger John Ruiz of Chelsea, but by the time the
fights were over there was nothing more to say on that subject.
Grant was the favorite to assume that role and he did his part by
winning, but he did not do anywhere near enough to make a case for
himself as a replacement for either.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the biggest loser of the night, Ike
Ibeabuchi. The African heavyweight sat at ringside, trying to get
close enough to Lewis to yell at him about a fight. Security kept
him out of ear shot and his own miscalculation kept him out of the
ring and hence out of sight of a chance to make a strong case that
he is ready for both Lewis and Grant.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons only Ibeabuchi and his manager could fathom, he
rejected a $400,000 offer to fight Williams in the semi-main event
Saturday night, which, as it turned out, would have likely resulted
in another smashing victory for him and a chance to increase his
leverage with the top heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasted with Grant's unimpressive victory, the exposure
Ibeabuchi would have received might even have elevated him to the
level he already thinks he's at _ the level where you get paid
seven figures to fight even questionable opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Cedric Kushner was so convinced this would be the
result of a Williams fight on HBO that he agreed to kick in his end
of the purse as well, which meant Ibeabuchi turned down $700,000 to
fight a guy who was slapped silly by a replacement who had four
days to get ready for him. After the fight, Ibeabuchi and his
manager, Texas attorney Steve Munisteri, tried to make their case
but it was weaker than Williams's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should Ike fight someone he feels is clearly inferior to
him?'' Munisteri said. ``You guys should be giving him credit for
that. He wants to fight the best and if Michael Grant is the best
he wants to fight him.''
</P>
<P>
   That is until someone began to pester Munisteri about the price
he would set for such a fight. At first Munisteri refused to
answer, his lawyerly instincts kicking in.
</P>
<P>
   He kept saying, ``We don't want to negotiate in the press,''
even though he was the one who brought Ibeabuchi to press row as
soon as Grant's victory was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the guy who chose not to fight,'' HBO analyst Larry
Merchant finally said to Ibeabuchi in exasperation, which led the
fighter to glare at him but say nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a frustrated Munisteri ignored his own advice and did
negotiate in the press, saying ``We'd fight for $3 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that was like saying he'd fight for $30 million
because Grant, who has a multifight deal with HBO, wants $3.5
million for such a fight and such a match is barely worth that, let
alone nearly double it.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, there were more losers than winners Saturday
night. In fact, on this night at least, they were all losers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
