<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SAMPRAS     06-21 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SAMPRAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN, GREEN GRASS IS SAMPRAS'S HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's the big homecoming game for Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   No, there won't be cheerleaders, screaming and building pyramids
Monday afternoon at 2. Nor a band playing the fight song and ``Hail
the Conquering Hero!'' No homecoming queen or even the Queen of
England will blow kisses, although the Duchess of Kent usually
smiles fetchingly as Pete bows dutifully toward the Royal Box.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter. This address _ Centre Court, Wimbledon _ is as
much home as itinerant Pete Sampras has ever wanted. And opening
day of the 122-year-old tennis bash is a homecoming he's
increasingly yearned for as the arid weeks rolled by since July 5,
1998, when he won the last set of the tournament from Goran
Ivanisevic.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Frost wrote that home is the place where they have to
take you in. Although life hasn't gotten that bad yet for Pete, he
has seemed a man overboard and enveloped in a fog since leaving
London. Sure, he's No. 1 again, but only because his challengers
cringe at the thought of life at such an altitude. However, not an
impressive No. 1, winning only one insignificant tournament during
the 50 weeks since his fifth Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
   But Centre Court shines through the fog like a lighthouse. It's
Pete's sanctuary. Grass underfoot once more feels like a life raft.
He's through gasping and treading water _ ``I'll be tough to beat
here. The place brings out something special in me; it's sweet. I
feel more at home here than anyplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   You can see why. Having won 39 of his last 40 matches at the Big
W, Pete begins his quest for a 20th century record sixth
championship in the champion's traditional role: raising the
curtain to reveal himself and the spear carrier, a canny but
erratic Australian lefty, No. 35 Scotty Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always feels good to walk out there for the first match,''
says Pete, smiling wide. Pete knows the route better than a cop
knows his beat, and always cuffs his man. Sitting and sunning
beside an outside court now, he contemplates his and Draper's
entry, side by side, into the open-ceilinged green room where
applause from all 13,120 seats will echo throughout the world. The
two will pause, turn and bow slightly at the Royal Box _ an archaic
custom, but part of the Wimbledon time warp _ and then go about
their first-round business.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pressure on me here.'' Pete is loose, congenial, more
relaxed than he's been all year. ``I know how to win on grass. I've
been through it, I've got the game. And if I don't, well, having
five titles is something I never even dreamed of as a kid. Catching
Bjorn Borg? (the Swede whose five spanned 1976-80) I never gave it
a thought. It was too far out of reach. But . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   This is a far cry from the testy Sampras who had bristled at
reporters about the lack of American coverage of the year-end ATP
Championships in Germany where, with a respectable showing, he
confirmed No. 1 for a sixth year running. That incredible stretch
of constancy, a singular feat at singles, eclipsed Jimmy Connors's
professional record (1974-78). It also tied a musty mark of the
illustrious Big Bill Tilden in the pre-open era (1920-25).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking a new look at everything,'' Pete says, conceding
that he'd been ``selfish, self-centered in not playing Davis Cup.''
He has reversed that stance by volunteering to join the team in
Boston for the July 16-18 clash with Australia. ``But I knew I
couldn't stay No. 1 and play the Cup, too. I would've burned out.''
</P>
<P>
   His fear of overextending himself may have something to do with
repeated physical crumbles in long matches _ matches that, mostly,
he grittily won anyway. Because of his Greek heritage, he may be
something of a prisoner of a genetic dysfunction causing anemia
called thalassemia. ``Remarkable he's done so well,'' says a
specialist. Pete doesn't want to discuss it, but won't deny it
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been consumed by No. 1.'' Consumed? This is a word I'd
not heard from Sampras. ``Yeah, consumed. I think you have to be to
stay up there that long. It was my first priority _ me and No. 1.
Everything else was secondary. Personal relationships suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Love life? ``Yeah, everything. It was about me. I was a one-man
show. No teammates to take up the slack if I wasn't playing well.
The people around me had to understand that _ when I needed to eat,
to sleep . . . that's when it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all I cared about, every waking minute _ winning matches.
That takes a lot out of you. It's hard to be the man to beat in any
sport year after year. That's what I'm most proud of, that I
handled that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the others who get close, or do get to No. 1
briefly _ (Marcelo) Rios last year, (Carlos) Moya and (Yevgeny)
Kafelnikov this year _ haven't done.''
</P>
<P>
   They've had their swallow of first cabin fame _ and gagged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Pete nods, ``because it sort of explodes on them, and
they find out it's not just forehands and backhands. It's more than
tennis. It's a lot of things, handling the media and the
expectations, the demands on your time, day in and day out. It's
mental, getting up for every match. It's a whole new ball game when
you get there. Connors and (Ivan) Lendl, (John) McEnroe, Borg could
handle it. I got comfortable with it. I think it's a true test, a
sign of character to stay there. I'm proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers being ridiculed by Connors at the 1991 US Open. The
year before, at 19, Sampras had materialized astonishingly at
Flushing Meadow as the tournament's greenest champion ever.
Defending was heavy lifting that seemed to induce brain hernia.
Pete appeared relieved to be defeated in the quarters and go home _
``It's like a monkey off my back'' _ while Connors, at 39, was
grinding his way to the semis.
</P>
<P>
   To the feisty, flamboyant Connors, whose record of stratospheric
longevity Pete would snap seven years up the road, the Sampras
attitude was inconceivably wimpish. ``You have to die out there
defending your title. You can't be happy with that, with winning
once.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete recalls, ``I found I wasn't happy a year after that, the
1992 Open final I lost to (Stefan) Edberg. Up till then I was a
young guy with talent, happy to be one of the guys. Winning some
tournaments, making a lot of money, content to be No. 5. When
Edberg beat me, after I'd got off to a lead, it hurt. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one match changed my career. I wasn't sure I hated to
lose, wasn't sure what I wanted. But that loss stayed with me a
long time. I did hate to lose. I did want to win major titles (10
since) and be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much to hate after that _ except his woeful busts
at the French _ and in six months he had signed the long-term lease
on the game's penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   But there was the feeling here that, in being consumed, Pete was
taking himself overly seriously, complaining unbecomingly. In a
Dangerfieldian manner that didn't fit an essentially unassuming,
good-natured kid, he whined about not getting enough notice when he
did win the Davis Cup for the US in Moscow in 1995, and for his
extraordinary stay on the pinnacle. Though he had a bully pulpit as
No. 1, he wasn't using it, reaching out enough to help a sport with
problems in his country.
</P>
<P>
   He may be acknowledging that, saying, ``Taking the early part of
the year off I had time to reflect. I thought about (Michael)
Jordan, (Wayne) Gretzky, and (John) Elway retiring after great
careers, really helping their games get more popular, and I
realized I want to do that. I've done No. 1, and if I can win here
or the US Open, maybe I'll stay. But I don't have to. I've got some
years left to play well and do other things, like Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean as much in the US as Ryder Cup, but maybe I
can help change that. I may even,'' he laughs, ``become an
ambassador for the game, become more accessible. Davis Cup had
never done much for me, but when I watched Jim (Courier) and Todd
(Martin) on TV in that wonderful win over Great Britain, I was
inspired. I wanted to be part of it if they'd have me. Play
doubles, do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier, the backbone, wasn't too keen. Pete's earlier refusals
probably cost the US the 1998 Cup, and seemed to doom the team
against Britain. ``Todd and I are the team, the guys who wanted to
play,'' Courier had said after the stunning 3-2 victory at
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim has softened. ``Everybody had practically begged Pete,
and he said no. But later he did call Gully (US captain Tom
Gullikson), and asked if he could help out. I liked that, and the
fact that he didn't expect a singles job, and would be glad to play
doubles. No doubt we're stronger with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been to Boston,'' Pete says. ``They tell me
Longwood's small, and it'll be a madhouse. Sounds great.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a homecoming, but maybe a coming to terms with the
responsibilities of a great champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
