<HEADLINE>
FAST NIGERIANS WIN OVER WWC FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Nigerians might fast-talk a good game,
but the group obviously possesses speedy limbs to keep pace with
those jaw muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet-footed Mercy Akide and the rest of the charismatic
Nigerian cast quickly won over support from Sunday's crowd at the
Rose Bowl, emerging as an early crowd favorite in Women's World Cup
'99.
</P>
<P>
   As advertised, speed was the difference. The Nigerians
repeatedly broke free in the attacking third to create pressure
around North Korea's net.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, only the rhythmic fervor exhibited by the dancing
Nigerian faithful in the stands required as much energy.
</P>
<P>
   Days before, Akide served notice the Nigerians would ``shock the
world'' in the coming weeks. Maybe their stunning 4-3 victory over
global-power China in a recent, closed-door matchup was an early
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, they're a force to be reckoned with,'' Team USA
assistant coach Lauren Gregg said. ``I think they're playing with
confidence off their result with China. They're clearly here to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nigeria, which flashed periodic weakness on its back line,
could have that liability severely exposed against the 4-3-3
formation the Americans will employ in Thursday's Group A matchup.
</P>
<P>
   So who's favored now?
</P>
<P>
   USA dazzled in its opening game to keep the inside track,
overcoming early jitters to thwart Denmark's resolve in a 3-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But upstart Brazil's explosive offense (it hammered Mexico 7-1)
joined Nigeria in boasting the tournament's most creative offenses
thus far. Both are obviously aiming to outlast opponents in
wide-open affairs.
</P>
<P>
   China, Norway and Sweden have also fared well, with Italy's
speedy defense making it the early surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico and Germany are on the other end of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans, because of their six-goal loss margin to Brazil,
are staring at an early exit. They must now play a defensive-minded
style in winning group games against Germany (Thursday) and Italy
(next Sunday) since goal differential is a key tie-breaking
criterion in group-play advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Germany lost the majority of 50/50 balls and sometimes seemed
disorganized in the back, although solid play in the middle often
offset its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sunday's sparse Rose Bowl turnout (17,102) was
disappointing, it was hardly unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the day we were worried about,'' said WWC '99
president and CEO Marla Messing, ``because the U.S. had already
played, the Father's Day holiday and the non-local matchups would
keep people away.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, WWC '99 has sold more than 485,000 tickets, easily
ranking as the best-selling women's sporting event in history.
</P>
<P>
   WWC memorabilia was clearly the hottest commodity on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't keep up, we were obliterated,'' vendor Sam Sheikh
said. ``We usually bring $3 per (fan) in inventory for something
like this. Today we tripled that to $9 per head and still almost
sold out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
