<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THREE-HIT DAY, NIXON'S THE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-NIXON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Trot Nixon's first full season in the big leagues
hasn't been working out the way he had hoped. Mired under .200 for
the early part of the year, Nixon has worked his way toward a more
respectable average, but still the hits haven't fallen in as often
as he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday that changed. In a 5-2 Red Sox victory over the
Rangers, Nixon came through with three hits and two runs batted in,
including his first triple.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who raised his average to .242, has been working hard
throughout the season, taking plenty of pregame batting practice
with hitting coach Jim Rice, who has been tinkering with his
stance. Nixon's most recent change involved taking the bat off his
shoulder as he awaits the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep my swing in place, around the shoulder, at the
chest area, and I just go from there,'' said Nixon. ``It's good to
have a game like this, helping the ball club out, helping the team
win. And it's good for me, too. It keeps my confidence back up
there. It's a battle every day for me, and I'm just going to keep
battling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get out there in the cage, with Ricey and (manager)
Jimy Williams, everything starts to feel a lot better. I can get
frustrated but I just keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start struggling like you are, like I've been, you
keep working every day, keeping that swing that you want, and
that's what I've had to do and that's what I'll continue to do
until playoff time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon drove in the Sox' first run in the three-run fourth
inning, as his drive to center went over Roberto Kelly's head for a
triple to score Damon Buford, who had reached on an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to drive the ball and it felt good,'' said Nixon. ``I
got a pitch where I wanted it and I didn't try to do too much with
it. I thought Kelly had a bead on it. I didn't think I hit it that
good. I saw him stop and I realized that I hit it pretty good. It
was a fastball in the inner half. The Rangers may have thought I
was going to bunt. That was a fun situation.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no one tougher on himself than Nixon. He wants to keep
improving his average, perhaps up to the .310 level, his average
last season with Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're struggling, you're going to be tough on
yourself,'' Nixon said. ``I'm a competitor. I want to do well and
help the team. I want to do it all. At times, it gets overbearing
with myself. Sometimes it may hurt me and also it drives me to make
myself better.
</P>
<P>
   ``You battle the first time up and you get that hit and it kind
of relaxes you the rest of the way. I want to make contact, do what
you can to help the team, maybe bunt the guy over and make a hit
here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can hit. It's taken a little bit longer this year
than I expected, but I'm working every day, trying to make myself a
better ballplayer. The hits haven't come around but I know it
will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
