<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FINALLY ACQUIRE PALFFY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the boldest move of his two-year stint as
general manager, Dave Taylor on Sunday afternoon completed a
long-in-the-works trade with the New York Islanders involving two
draft choices and six players, the most significant of whom is
27-year-old right wing Zigmund Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Kings also acquired center Bryan Smolinski, 27;
journeyman goalie Marcel Cousineau, 26; and the Islanders'
fourth-round selection in Saturday's NHL draft. Smolinski will be a
restricted free agent on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders receive 20-year-old center Olli Jokinen, one of
the NHL's top prospects; 1998 first-round draft choice Mathieu
Biron, a 19-year-old defenseman; 1996 second-round selection Josh
Green, a 21-year-old right wing; and the Kings' first selection
Saturday, the eighth pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a marquee player,'' Taylor said of Palffy, a three-time
40-goal scorer. ``He's one of the most exciting players in the
game. Every time he touches the puck, he does something clever with
it, especially from the blue line in.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the trade should instantly improve the Kings, it
continues a path for the franchise that Taylor had vowed to avoid
since becoming general manager in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's draft will be the 33rd for the Kings since they
entered the NHL in 1967, and the Kings have traded their
first-round selection before using it 22 times. Additionally,
Jokinen and Biron join a long list of first-round selections traded
by the Kings either early in their careers or before their NHL
careers had begun .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've given up a significant package of young
assets,'' Taylor said. ``But (with) the opportunity to acquire
Palffy and Smolinski and the offense they can bring to the club, we
were happy to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy held out for the first two months of last season, but
still led the Islanders with 50 points in 50 games. The Kings
inherit the five-year, $26-million contract Palffy signed in
December with the fiscally challenged Islanders. The contract also
holds a club option for a sixth season at a reported $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy's addition gives the Kings greater offensive depth and
firepower than they've enjoyed since the early years of the decade,
with such players as Palffy, Smolinski, Luc Robitaille, Jozef
Stumpel, Donald Audette, Glen Murray populating the top two lines.
Smolinski had 40 points in 82 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, Audette and Murray all are right wings, but Taylor said
Palffy and Audette can play on either side of the ice. Palffy and
Stumpel, his Slovakian countryman, played together with Nitra in
the Czech League in 1990-91, and also have been linemates in
international competition.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult aspect of the deal for Taylor was parting
with Jokinen, the third player chosen in the 1997 draft. Jokinen
had 21 points in 66 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL was determined that any trade of Palffy not be perceived
as an effort by the Islanders to dump hefty salaries. Nonetheless,
the trade probably will increase the Kings' payroll by $6 million
once Smolinski signs.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a 2 p.m. Sunday freeze on transactions, Taylor and
Islanders general manager Mike Milbury beat the deadline. The trade
then was reviewed by the NHL, which granted approval late Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an organizational decision,'' Taylor said. ``Without
question, the fact that we were moving into the Staples Center had
an impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
