<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS COME OUT SWINGING 
</HEADLINE>
 MEETING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ The Olympics are meant to promote peace, mutual
understanding, athletic excellence, and good sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   But those ideals were nowhere to be found Sunday at the closing
of the 109th session of the International Olympic Committee, the
first IOC assembly open to the press under new rules to promote
transparency. What could have been a time of gracious
congratulations to the winners of a bid to host the 2006 Winter
Games _ and a chance to reflect on how to improve the Olympic
movement _ instead degenerated into a day of name-calling,
accusations, and veiled threats.
</P>
<P>
   The committee bidding to host the Games in Sion, Switzerland,
had been mum about the Salt Lake City payoff scandal dogging the
IOC for the last half-year _ until its front-running bid went up in
smoke Saturday to rival Turin, Italy. With no fear now of offending
judges or burning bridges, the Swiss took out their disappointment
on an Olympic committee they accused of a vendetta vote against
Switzerland. It was a Swiss IOC member, Marc Hodler, who pulled
back the curtain on a pattern of influence peddling and excess.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of the Swiss bodes ill for the difficult task ahead
of rebuilding the Olympics' reputation and integrity, a job that
will require Olympic states to unite and cooperate to promote
reform.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-36 vote for Turin also could make life difficult for the
IOC itself, which is headquartered in Lausanne, a mere 60 miles
from Sion. Already that proximity has taken its toll; on Saturday,
angry supporters of Sion's bid reportedly vandalized a statue at
the IOC offices and spraypainted the letters of the word ``Mafia''
into the five Olympic rings _ an apparent insinuation that Italy
bought the vote for Turin. Anti-IOC banners were strewn around the
garden, and protests were expected.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Swiss government voiced discontent, saying it believed
third-time bidder Sion ``had a very good chance of winning.'' The
Swiss Federal Council also announced, somewhat ominously, that it
should ``carry out an in-depth analysis at all political levels of
the reasons for the failure of Switzerland's candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, regardless of whether certain IOC members voted for
Turin as a backlash against the Swiss for Hodler's whistleblowing,
it could be payback time in the other direction. If the Swiss
government wants to be vindictive, it could wield legal and
monetary weapons against the IOC, which has enjoyed tax-exempt
status there for years.
</P>
<P>
   D'Bernard Comby, a Swiss parliamentarian and member of Sion's
committee, said that as the home of IOC headquarters, his country
has a duty to force the IOC to get its house in order. He cited a
recent decision by the Swiss government not to waive the
value-added tax for the otherwise tax-exempt IOC, and said other
laws may need to be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the IOC released a statement saying it
``understands the disappointment'' of the Swiss, but stressed that
the IOC chose ``freely and democratically between the two
finalists, both of whose bids were excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also chided ``the excessive reactions of certain
people,'' but hoped ``the traditional Swiss sense of calm will soon
prevail once more.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, who lives in a luxury
hotel in Lausanne, said he has no plans to move himself or the
headquarters out of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch also defended the revamped temporary selection
process, under which IOC members could not visit bid cities, and
said he would object to reinstating site visits. It was during such
trips that wining, dining, and bribing of IOC members by bid cities
reportedly took place.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who himself has faced criticism of his lavish
lifestyle _ which this week was centered around a highly discounted
$5,460 presidential suite and a police-escorted Mercedes _ bristled
at suggestions from a reporter that he could exercise some
austerity to set an example for the entire IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a bedroom, I need an office, I need a car. That's
all,'' he retorted, adding that the reporter might suggest
appropriate cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC passed a new rule Sunday that members would be allowed
to accept gifts of ``nominal value'' only, down from a previous
$200 limit that was widely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, the IOC warned members traveling to the United
States that they could face questioning by the FBI or subpoenas in
connection with an estimated $1 million in illegal payoffs by Salt
Lake City to get the 2002 Winter Games. IOC director-general
Francois Carrard said the organization will provide members with
legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said the IOC would not resist questioning. ``We will
respect the FBI . . . (and) the Justice Department. We want this
problem to be finished as soon as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
