<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     06-21 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ HAS ALL THE RIGHT MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pedro Martinez breezed through one of the top hitting
lineups in baseball Sunday at Fenway Park. He yielded just six hits
and one earned run in eight innings as he fashioned another
Renoir-like masterpiece, brushing away the Rangers with a palette
full of fastballs, curves, and changeups in assorted hues.
</P>
<P>
   While Jin Ho Cho dedicated his first major league victory to his
late father Saturday, Martinez happily dedicated Sunday's victory
to the man who first handed him a baseball, his father Paullino,
who is in town from Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic
visiting his sons. ``I think every game I win is dedicated to
him,'' said Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   He made Sunday's 5-2 victory against the American League West
leaders seem so easy. ``I was very comfortable on the mound,'' said
Martinez. He threw 108 pitches, 71 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez shows no signs of slowing down as spring becomes
summer. He struck out 10, marking the 10th time the AL strikeout
leader has reached double figures this season, the 48th time in his
career. He is on a pace to reach his career high of 18 games, set
in 1997 when he was with the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted to talk to Martinez and manager Jimy Williams
about next month's All-Star Game at Fenway, and whether Martinez
would be starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to (Joe Torre),'' Martinez said. ``I thought I could
have been the starter last year and the year before and I wasn't.
One guy gave me an excuse that he was being respectful to the other
guy (Greg Maddux). The other guy told me that a guy who had pitched
a perfect game gave the team a better chance to win. I have no
defense for that. I expect that. This year I just figure I'm going
to be there. I don't know what the excuse might be this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long way off. What is it? Three weeks? I'm not going
to worry about it now. What happens happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If what happened on the mound Sunday continues to happen, there
is no way in the name of Smoky Joe Wood that anyone can deny
Martinez the starting assignment after he took the major league
lead in victories with his 13th.
</P>
<P>
   He was near the top of his game, only yielding a few bloop hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as good as he always is,'' said Texas third baseman
Todd Zeile, who had a rough afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, who had hit safely in six of his last seven games, struck
out his first two at-bats, then grounded out to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had that sneaky 90 mile-an-hour fastball, a great curve,
and a heck of a changeup. There is not a lot to report,'' said
Zeile. ``He's a great pitcher. It's not just that he has good
stuff, either. He's a tough competitor. He's a smart pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek had the best view of Martinez.
``He had great stuff. He only made one mistake. Pedro did a
phenomenal job against one of the hardest-hitting teams in
baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What impresses me about Pedro is that when he gets in a tough
situation, he turns his game up a notch and takes it to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Red Sox wrap up their four-game series against the
Rangers Monday night, Martinez has other games on his mind. He is
interested in watching his older brother, Ramon, pitch Monday night
in Lowell on his first rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go and watch him,'' admitted Martinez. ``But the
Red Sox haven't given me permission yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team is getting excited about Ramon's game. Jimy had
a smile that you rarely see. I can't wait to see that happen and
the reaction we're going to have if he's able to come back here
soon. I know him. His mechanics. I think it will be a great idea if
I can be there.''
</P>
<P>
   You can bet his father, Paullino, will be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's having a great time here,'' said Martinez. ``It's hot at
home now and it's much cooler here. He's having a lot of fun
shopping and just hanging around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Martinez brothers take after their father. ``He was a
pitcher, too,'' said the proud son. ``He was a pretty good amateur.
Felipe (Alou) and Manny Mota told me so. They used to play with
him. Unfortunately, I never saw him play. But he loves the game,
even now. Sometimes he'll drive by a field and a game will be going
on. He'll stop and watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   And right now, he's enjoying watching his sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
