</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN CONCURS WITH CUP CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden said he
didn't watch the entire third overtime of Saturday night's Game 6
of the Stanley Cup finals, but after looking at the video of Brett
Hull's controversial winning goal, Sinden said he believes the
right call was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I saw, and I didn't really see it like I would look
at it in my office, I thought it was an allowable goal,'' said
Sinden. ``You can't blame Buffalo for being upset. They probably
see it one way and the league sees it another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many goals this year decided by fractions for or
against. That standard should be maintained even though the players
are celebrating the Stanley Cup at the time you're trying to
decide. I can't comment properly on whether it was a good goal or
not. I know for sure they would review it pretty closely. It looked
to me as if he had control.''
</P>
<P>
   The man-in-the-crease rule has been a hot button-issue around
the league and not just for the Bruins (remember Tim Taylor's big
toe nullifying P.J. Axelsson's potential winning goal during
Boston's first-round playoff loss to Washington last year?). The
rule will be on the agenda for Monday's Board of Governors meeting,
which Sinden will attend in New York. Commissioner Gary Bettman
said the NHL braintrust is going to decide whether the rule is
worth keeping or needs modification.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started already,'' said Sinden, referring to the
discussions that have taken place on the subject. ``It should have
some meat to it now. The point of controversy here, as I see it, is
whether or not the player who scored the goal had control while his
foot was in the crease. If in fact the video goal judge deemed he
did have control even though one foot was in the crease, then the
goal should count. It's going to be a very interesting session.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the dilemma of such a rule is restoring the
spontaneity of goal scoring while keeping players out of the
crease. It's difficult to do without the aid of video replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it hurts the game if there were no fans in the
stands, but I don't think they like having these reviews all the
time,'' said Sinden. ``What I see happening is that they're going
to ask a committee to find a way to keep a deterrent that will work
to keep players from interfering with the goaltender but at the
same time, allow goals to be scored if there's absolutely no harm,
like in the Taylor example. This was their biggest fear, that a
Stanley Cup would be decided by the in-the-crease rule one way or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the league is looking at changing the rule to a no-harm,
no-foul concept. Sinden said that promises to open a Pandora's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you one thing, you now open up a discussion as to
what you mean by `No harm.' '' he said. ``What I think is no harm,
you may not. This rule works really good except in my opinion, it
cheats the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euphoria of a goal, especially for the home team, is
removed so often. You have to review these things, I think the
average time is a minute and 30 seconds; it just takes away from
the flow of the game. It may not be necessary to have it even
though 99 percent of the time and the incident (in Saturday's Game
6) might be in the one percent, but 99 percent of the time it's
very, very accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the accuracy more important than the spontaneity? And if
it isn't, is the league prepared to have players push the envelope
at every opportunity?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have a rule with zero tolerance, this is
the way to do it,'' said Sinden. ``But it spoils so many other
things. If we can find a way to deter the players from going in the
crease, that is what the rule was set up to do, if we can find a
way other than the fear of the video camera exposing them, then we
should look for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
