<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HIT STRIDE ON ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A year ago, France '98 World Cup was going
strong, and the Revolution were halfway into their annual nine-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Revolution have been able to maintain their
confidence and overcome the problems that plagued them last season.
Much of the credit goes to the goalkeeping of player-coach Walter
Zenga. But the Revolution also appear to be developing an
intangible quality of resourcefulness. They continue to display
some self-destructive habits, but they have been able to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are forming an identity as a team that travels
well _ 10 of their 15 points have been earned away from home as
they prepare to visit Dallas next Saturday. And judging by the
productive stretches of midfield play in a 3-2 win at Tampa Bay
Saturday, they have enough depth and versatility to be a viable
playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   There was a quiet confidence about the Revolution after the
match. They seem to be galvanizing at a crucial point in the
season, though there is some latent dissension, especially
regarding the situation of Edwin Gorter, who has been benched after
providing key contributions in victories over Chicago and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution also appear too willing to live dangerously,
squandering advantages through fundamental mistakes. The first two
goals of the game resulted from amateur defensive mistakes,
allowing Joe-Max Moore a simple chance in the fourth minute and the
Mutiny's Musa Shannon a half-field, uncontested run half an hour
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did enough to get the three points,'' midfielder John
Harkes said after the Mutiny game. ``But we make work for
ourselves. We were balanced and we forced an error and it was 1-nil
and we were playing well. But we can't let them back in the game
like we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an important game for both teams. We want to put some
wins together and get away from the bottom two teams. And it was
important that we kept our level high.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, team morale is the Revolution's top priority. There seem
to be enough leaders to prevent the dissension and doubt that have
hampered the team the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga and assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi were bold and
pragmatic enough to use three different starting lineups as the
Revolution earned four points in three games over seven days. The
team showed the effects of the scheduling, appearing tired toward
the end of the game. But the Revolution remained poised enough to
compensate for errors and exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great sign,'' defender Dan Calichman said. ``If we can
play them in Tampa after we have just played a midweek game and get
a result, we should be able to take them next time, when we have
fresh legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
