<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3229 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-BOS &LR;      06-21 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR-CROSSED HULL NEW DALLAS HERO 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ A millionaire many times over, his tongue often as
deadly as his stick, Brett Hull showed up at fame's front door
Sunday morning wearing unfamiliar clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Once the NHL's most feared shooter, known for avoiding contact,
drifting effortlessly to open ice, and driving home booming slap
shots, Hull wore the suit of a soldier in the closing moments of
the Stanley Cup finals. Limping and riddled with the pain of a
mangled knee and torn groin muscles, hockey's version of the Spirit
of '76, Hull popped the winning goal over a sprawled Dominik Hasek
to bring the Dallas Stars their first Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the whole world has left me,'' said a somewhat
subdued Hull, sitting beside teammate Guy Carbonneau on top of a
row of lockers amid the mayhem in the Dallas locker room after the
2-1 victory. ``It's done. I did it. And I don't have to answer to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the National Hockey League, no stranger to controversy in
the playoffs, that was left with some explaining to do.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's goal, a two-shot followup off a Jere Lehtinen chance with
5:09 remaining in the third overtime, came with the front half of
the Golden Brett's left skate blade clearly in the crease. By the
league's working standard of the last two seasons, with goals
routinely disallowed under such foot-in-the-crease circumstances,
it appeared the perfect case of a goal that would be wiped from the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   As the Stars rejoiced on the ice, an incensed Lindy Ruff, the
Sabres head coach, bolted from the Buffalo dressing room after
spotting Hull's encroaching skate on video replay.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had some 'splainin' to do, and Ruff was headed to the
top man, NHL commissioner Gary Bettman, who stood at ice level for
the ceremonial presentation of the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted Bettman to answer the question,'' said Ruff, his club
rubbed out in what was the second longest game in the history of
the Cup finals _ behind only the Boston Garden marathon that ended
when Edmonton's Petr Klima drove home the winner in Game 1 of the
'90 championship. ``Why is that not reviewed?''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ruff, the commissioner turned his back on him and
said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He almost looked to me like he knew this might be a tainted
goal and there was no answer for it,'' said Ruff. ``I just wanted
an explanation. Just tell me. Listen, is it a good goal, not a good
goal? There was no answer. No review.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Lewis, the league's supervisor of officials, eventually
was the one left with the final interpretation, which he provided
in a brief news conference at approximately 2:15 a.m., some 45
minutes after the goal.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lewis, Hull's foot indeed was in the crease, but
the goal stood because off-ice officials deemed Hull never lost
possession of the puck _ despite it bouncing off Hasek and leaving
the tinted blue crease before he reached out of the restricted area
to gather it in and lift it by a sprawled Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Cup came down to one word: possession.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Lewis and no fewer than three other off-ice
officials, sequestered in a video replay booth at the end of the
press box, Hull never lost control of the puck. As if some
invisible fishing line remained tethered to the end of his stick
and the black rubber disc, Hull followed up the carom off Hasek and
remained one in whole with the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that interpretation, which had Lewis sounding as if he
were trying to explain the mystery of the Immaculate Conception,
the Dallas Stars were the 1999 Stanley Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there reasons that a guy can have his foot in the crease
and score a goal?'' said Lewis, setting up his detailed explanation
of Hull's winner with a rhetorical question. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the street, stunned Buffalo fans quietly streamed to
their cars. Many had tears in their eyes. In a city where their
beloved Bills lost in four straight Super Bowl appearances, this
was one more crushing defeat for Western New York sports fans. The
vast percentage of those who left the building wouldn't learn of
the controversy surrounding the goal until they heard it on their
car radio on the drive home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the drill,'' said one disconsolate fan as she headed
into the night, a sleeping young child cradled in her arms. ``No
one has to tell us when it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   An angry Hasek, who just missed getting a glove on Hull's
forehand lift, wasn't as resolute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me very mad,'' said Hasek, who in the first period
uncharacteristically let in a very soft goal, a Jere Lehtinen
lollipop that squeezed in at the left post. ``It could happen any
time during the season, but if it happens in a Stanley Cup final .
. . I still cannot believe it. I don't understand what the video
judge is doing. Maybe he was in the bathroom. Maybe he was
sleeping. Maybe he doesn't know the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules, said Lewis, are posted for every video replay judge
in all 27 NHL rinks. He added that a clarification of the rules was
sent from his office to all NHL clubs as recently as March 25. The
clarification, stressed Lewis, in part underscored instances when a
player can be in the crease and a goal can be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gutless move,'' was how Sabres forward Joe Juneau, a former
Bruin, summed up the whole affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to put my jersey on and go back out,'' said Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's return-to-action comment was eerily reminiscent of the
first round of last year's playoffs when what appeared to be a
winning goal by Boston's P.J. Axelsson was taken away in a
first-round series with Washington. Capitals netminder Olaf Kolzig,
not for one second believing that it was anything but a goal, took
off for the Washington dressing room at the FleetCenter. He was at
the Caps bench, ready to leave the ice, when a teammate told him to
stop, the goal was under review. Kolzig said following the game,
after the Caps won in OT, that he never noticed that Tim Taylor's
toe was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the game, Bruins president/general manager
Harry Sinden accused the league of a ``coverup'' in regard to its
inconsistency in determining the man-in-the-crease violations. Days
later, NHL headquarters decided to fine Sinden for his comments _ a
league employee went so far as to provide the Globe with a copy of
the league bylaws Sinden violated with his comments _ but the fine
never was levied.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres forced the overtime in Game 6 here when Stu Barnes
drilled home a Wayne Primeau feed with 1:39 to go in the second
period. It was the 26th shot taken on Eddie Belfour and the only
one to beat him of the 54 Buffalo landed on net.
</P>
<P>
   As the third period and three overtimes played out, referees
Terry Gregson and Bill McCreary put their whistles in their
pockets. By and large, play was clean, checking tight, quality
scoring chances few. Counting Hull's winner, Dallas held a 24-22
shot advantage in the overtime after being outshot, 32-26, in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The battered Hull, torn apart by an Alexei Zhitnik hit in Game
3, when he played only three shifts, said after the triumph that he
needed pain-killing shots to his left knee and extensive taping to
the knee and his groin area between every period to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could have played a Game 7,'' said Hull. He
expected to have an MRI on his knee no later than Monday _ either
before or after the Stanley Cup parade in Dallas. According to
coach Ken Hitchcock, Hull is not a good bet to begin the 1999-2000
regular season, due to the severity of his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story on Brett Hull when the dust settles is going to be
an incredible story,'' said Hitchcock, who repeatedly referred to
his squad as a ``magical team.''
</P>
<P>
   Just prior to popping in the winner, the somewhat frail-looking
Hull told his linemate, Jere Lehtinen, that his leg and groin were
blown out and that Lehtinen would have to cover for him on defense.
He could get to the front of the net and take a shot, but he might
have nothing left, he said to Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Lehtinen unloaded an attempt on Hasek from the
left circle. Hull was in front to pick up the loose puck and
responded with his first shot on Hasek, simultaneously avoiding a
hit by a charging Brian Holzinger. With Mike Modano off to his
side, and his foot in the crease, Hull then reached out to his
right, picked up the rebound beyond the blue paint, and lifted home
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stops all the naysayers,'' said Hull. ``I don't have to
answer to anyone. I don't. Joe (Nieuwendyk) doesn't. Mike (Modano)
doesn't. Eddie (Belfour) doesn't. We won it.''
</P>
<P>
   With one little lift, nothing resembling the countless bombs he
has unloaded in his 12-year career, Hull shook off the seemingly
ceaseless criticisms of his play. The goal put his name on the Cup
and validated his game, and, to an extent, his place in NHL
history. Some six weeks shy of his 35th birthday, he proved himself
a gamer in the biggest game of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream about it,'' mused Hull, thinking what it meant to
win the Cup. ``I dream about it _ it's just unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
