<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NORWAY-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY KICKS OFF DEFENSE ON RIGHT FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Leaving no doubt that their theme song is
``We Are the Champions,'' the Norwegian national soccer team
dominated Russia Sunday, 2-1, in their first Women's World Cup
match. Though the final score seemed close, it did not reflect just
how overpowering the defending World Cup champions looked to the
14,143 fans at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians, who lost to the US in the World Cup finals in
1991, got the title back in 1995 and have made it clear that they
intend to keep it. So they had no mercy for Russia, which had never
before been to the World Cup. Norway struck early and often; its
players were quick to attack and shadowed the Russians as soon as
they got the ball. Eleven minutes went by, in fact, before the
Russians could get the ball out of their half of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm very pleased with the 19 good chances we had and
the good technical play we had,'' said Norwegian coach Per-Mathias
Hogmo. ``But it was a little more exciting than I like.''
</P>
<P>
   The excitement came from forward Marianne Pettersen, who scored
a goal and had an assist, but also had many more opportunities. In
fact, she had 11 shots for the entire game; Russia's whole team
only got off six.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did have a lot of chances, but I hope to score more in
the next games,'' Pettersen said. ``But I'm happy with the goal I
scored. It's comforting to see we had so many chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway's first goal in the 28th minute was textbook soccer, as
the red jerseys swarmed the Russian goal. Pettersen, at the top of
the box, took a pass from a teammate and headed the ball to Brit
Sandaune, who drilled it in past Russian goalkeeper Svetlana Petco.
Russia would finish the first half with no shots on goal, compared
to six by Norway. Russia's corner kicks were also a virtual
no-show: The team had just one shot, while Norway had 10.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was more of the same, as Russia couldn't put a
play together. Pettersen and Sandaune, meanwhile, paired up again
in the 68th minute. Sandaune lofted the ball in front of the goal,
and though Russian defender Natalia Karasseva tried to clear it
with a header, it landed at Pettersen's feet, and the forward drove
it in from the left side of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 minutes later, Russia finally came alive. Natalia
Barbachina, who was in front of the Norway goal, passed the ball
out to Galina Komarova, who was more than 20 yards out. But
Komarova fired and put it in the back of the net over the hands of
Norwegian goalkeeper Bente Nordby.
</P>
<P>
   That was all Russia would manage in its first World Cup
appearance. The team was held to two shots on goal for the game;
Norway had 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the match was close,'' Hogmo said. ``We played a
lot better than Russia, but we know they are hard to beat and that
it was going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian team insisted on looking at the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I am relatively happy,'' said Russian coach Yuri
Bystritski ``Although we lost the game, we're still students of it,
and we want to focus on the next couple games so that we're second
in our group.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway next faces Canada Wednesday, while Russia will play
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Hogmo said he's not thinking too far ahead, so he's not worried
about the US team or defending the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't beat the United States now, because we meet Canada,''
he said with an exasperated laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, let him take one game at a time. That, so far,
is working quite well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 0220EDT &QL; 
