<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-ANALYS     06-21 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL'S FOOT NOT RELEVANT TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ OK, fine, let's have a do-over.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the city that always weeps, the only way to assuage the
broken souls of Sabres fans would be to summon the Stars back from
Dallas, drop the puck, and keep the Cup clock running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' said former Bruin Joe Juneau, after his Sabres
saw the Dallas Stars capture the Stanley Cup here Sunday morning
with Brett Hull's controversial goal, ``everybody will remember
this as the Stanley Cup that was never won.''
</P>
<P>
   The masses that line the parade route in Dallas Monday won't see
it that way. There will be no asterisk next to the long list of
Stars that will be added to the hallowed Stanley Cup in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When Hull's shot popped over a sprawled Dominik Hasek with 5:09
to go in the third overtime, Dallas was the Cup champion, and
forever should be remembered as a proud bunch of aging stars and
role players, festooned around some very talented younger legs, who
won with grit and determination. They shouldn't be remembered for
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   If they are, then shame on the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Hull's foot was in the crease, in truth, had no
bearing on his winning shot going in the net. If there is any
solace here for Sabres fans, it should be that. Up until the league
fell in love with its replay gadgetry, no one ever looked twice at
the kind of goal the Golden Brett scored. Hull also has blue eyes.
In this case, the color of his eyes and the placement of his foot
had the same influence on whether Hasek could stop the shot: none.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Lewis, ex-referee and the NHL's supervisor of officials,
went to great lengths to explain (he doth explain too much) in his
postgame news conference that Hull, in effect, never lost the
handle on the puck. What else could Lewis say? By then, the Cup
already had been handed to the Stars, the building was all but
empty, and hockey-mad Big D was in full gallop over the best little
dang Cup the West ever won.
</P>
<P>
   It stretches credulity beyond all reasonable limits to say that
a player is in control of his shot when it bounces off the
netminder. By that standard, Mike Torrez's right hand must have
sailed over The Wall on Bucky Dent's homer. If that's where
technology has brought us, then the vote here is to bring back
silent movies and the Stanley Steamer.
</P>
<P>
   Far better for the NHL to have told the world that the goal
counted, the Stars were the champions, and that it was dismissing
the niggling technicality that a couple of inches of Hull's skate
blade made it into the badlands. In other words, the truth would
have gone a long way.
</P>
<P>
   The league heavies, either commissioner Gary Bettman or Lewis,
also could have added that the whole mess only proved once more
that the man-in-the-crease rule, though well-intentioned, is
dysfunctional and undermines a lot of the game's great qualities _
speed, spontanaeity, competitiveness, just to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   A good number of fans enter NHL buildings, even in the Original
Six cities, unsure of the game's basic rules. Even those who know
the intricacies of a two-line offside pass can't untangle the
mystery of the man-in-the-crease violation. There is nothing more
mummifying for a crowd of 17,000 to sit and wait while a referee
grabs a telephone along the sideboards and talks goal with the
gods. Bettman is among those who wants those wait-and-see sessions
to come to an end. It can't happen too soon.
</P>
<P>
   The league has seen bad calls before, perhaps none so blatant as
in the deciding game of the 1980 finals, Flyers vs. Islanders.
Early in the action, linesman Leon Stickle didn't whistle an
offside call when a Clark Gillies pass left the attacking zone for
a trailing Butch Goring. Some 2 feet into the neutral zone, Goring
picked up the pass and dished off a relay that Duane Sutter then
knocked by Pete Peeters. The goal stood. It wasn't the Cup-winning
goal, but the Islanders carried on for a 5-4 victory, Bob Nystrom
banging home the winner in OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I blew it,'' said a chagrined Stickle, one of the
league's best on-ice officials. ``Maybe there was tape on the stick
and it confused me. Maybe I was too close to the play.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, then Flyers coach Pat Quinn said, ``Nothing
should taint their victory. They worked hard for the victory.
What's done is done. It can't be changed, but it should be an
embarrassment to that official.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? We all got over it. A good guy made a bad mistake.
Things were different then, of course, because the world before the
proliferation of cameras, the Internet, and everyone being given a
phone number at birth accepted that no system is foolproof. The
constant bollixing of the man-in-the-crease calls shows that only
fools keep relying on foolproof systems.
</P>
<P>
   There's an easy answer to all this. It's not a perfect,
foolproof answer, but it gets the job done. Leave the
crease-interference infractions up to the referees' discretion, but
keep the replay cameras rolling. If the on-ice ref doesn't like the
look of a goal, thinks a player might have hindered a goalie from
making a stop, he can go to the tape if he feels it's necessary.
The tape then is a backup, not some machine that governs the game
like some Wizard of Oz behind the curtain. A toe in the crease
won't stop a goal from going on the board. That's all anyone should
ask of the whole process.
</P>
<P>
   No one with an ounce of sympathy can like what happened to the
Sabres. Based on where the league is today with its messed-up rule
_ the fact that it remains on the books _ Buffalo should have had
another kick at the can.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a good goal. Hull wasn't cheating. He made a gutsy
play to get to the net and provided a nifty touch to bury it for
the winner. It was a page torn from old-time hockey, and even the
most irate Sabre should be able to appreciate a finishing touch
from a time of old. The old game is fine. It's the new rules that
stink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
