<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY DALY RIPS USGA 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-DALY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Just three days after captivating the crowd
with his flamboyant game and candor, John Daly reemerged Sunday as
the troubled person he is.
</P>
<P>
   Daly was penalized two strokes for hitting a moving ball, scored
an 11 at the 485-yard, par-4 eighth hole, closed with an 83 for a
29-over 309 total, then tore into the United States Golf
Association before storming out of the village of Pinehurst. His
participation in the US Open, he said, is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now know why Bruce Lietzke doesn't play the US Open,'' said
Daly to an impromptu press gathering in front of the Pinehurst
clubhouse. ``What the USGA wants to do is embarrass the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my penalty and pay my fine, but I'm standing up for
the players. I don't consider the US Open a major anymore. My
majors are the Masters, the British Open, the PGA, and the Tour
Championship.''
</P>
<P>
   At the root of his anger was an annual criticism _ tough pins on
treacherous greens that result in high scores. But what left
observers shaking their heads was the turnaround in Daly's
disposition from Thursday, when he opened with a 2-under 68. After
that round, Daly said, ``I think it's a fun golf course. I think
everybody that's playing in it this week, all 156 say it's a lot of
fun to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many were actually saying Pinehurst No. 2 was ``fun,'' but
neither were they ready to say that Daly's later comments, as he
claimed, were on their behalf. Tom Kite, for instance, managed a
slight smile when asked if Daly's penalty at No. 8 served as a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't interpret it that way,'' said Kite, who was paired
with Daly. ``The only thing I heard from the players was that the
pin placements were exceedingly difficult. Basically, the players
like the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett was also penalized for hitting a moving ball at
last year's Open at the Olympic Club in San Francisco, but that
came in the second round at the 18th hole, and the USGA assumed the
blame for setting a bad pin. In this case, few were rushing to
support Daly's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pins didn't have to be as tough as they are,'' said Lee
Janzen, last year's winner, ``but the course isn't unfair. All
anybody has to do is look at the leaderboard and see the good
golfers who are there. Marginal golf shouldn't win the US Open.
Outstanding golf should.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly played anything but outstanding golf after starting the
tournament with three straight birdies. He made only three birdies
after that and scored three double bogeys, a triple, and whatever a
7 over par is for the disastrous eighth. He said he hit a lot of
good shots but was not rewarded because of the penalizing pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not play at Pebble Beach next year,'' he said in
reference to the site of the US Open. ``I don't want to see them
ruin another great golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly has a five-year exemption into the US Open for his 1995
British Open triumph, so Pebble Beach would be the end of that
window, unless he were to meet some other criteria. But those who
have been around Daly are more troubled by yet another entry on a
disturbing list of incidents. Three recent examples:
</P>
<P>
   --Two weeks ago in the first round of the Memorial Tournament,
Daly six-putted from 8 feet to conclude a round of 82. He promptly
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   --At the British Open last summer, Daly was going to miss the
cut at Royal Birkdale when he drove into a fairway bunker at the
18th hole in Round 2. He took several swipes at it and hacked it a
few more times around the green. It took several minutes to figure
out his score, which went into the books as a 10.
</P>
<P>
   --Last year at the Bay Hill Invitational in Orlando, Fla., Daly
drove it into the water at the par-5 sixth, went to the drop area,
and proceeded to hit five more into the water. He scored an 18 on
the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's battles with alcoholism were recounted following
Thursday's round, and he also told reporters he was in serious
financial trouble, having lost millions gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is with me, I don't know who's showing up tomorrow .
. . I can honestly say that,'' he said. ``And it's a little
scary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
