<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART-S TIMING COULDN'T BE BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-STEWART-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ The scene at the 11th hole Sunday at Pinehurst
No. 2 was beyond deja vu. It was virtually identical to the
scenario that may have cost Payne Stewart the 1998 US Open at the
Olympic Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Meeks, the director of rules and competition for the United
States Golf Association, once again was following the final twosome
at the US Open, and once again Payne Stewart was in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had noticed the play was slow for several holes,'' said
Meeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks was in a golf cart trailing the final twosome, stopwatch
in hand, timing the play of Stewart and his partner, this year Phil
Mickelson and last year Tom Lehman. And by the 11th hole, Meeks
sprung into action, telling Dr. Trey Holland of Indianapolis, a
vice president of the USGA, to notify Stewart and Mickelson they
would be ``on the clock'' as of the 12th hole.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th hole. Same as last year. The same hole in the same
major _ the Open _ where Stewart was told his play was dawdling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, you're concentrating so hard on your golf that you're
not paying attention to where the group is in front of you,'' said
Stewart. ``What I'd like to see them do is work a little harder to
speed up the first two days here. The last two days . . . darn . .
. you're trying to win a prestigious golf tournament. You'd hate to
have a penalty affect whether or not you win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on the clock from 12 through 14,'' said Holland, the
rules official assigned to the twosome. Indeed, when Holland
approached Stewart and Mickelson as they left the 11th tee, Stewart
got out the first words before Holland could speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me you're putting us on the clock,'' said Stewart,
and then Stewart strode away piqued when Holland told him that,
indeed, they were. Mickelson took the news more calmly. ``I've been
on the clock all four days here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of deja vu was even more eerie as Stewart approached
the 11th green. Last year Stewart lost his composure when his ball
landed in a sand-filled divot on the 12th hole and he asked for a
ruling on whether he could get relief. Stewart was denied and then
told, for good measure, that he and Lehman were on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Stewart asked for a ruling when his second shot
landed between a bunker and the green, this time on the 11th. Sand
from previous bunker shots was splayed across the grass ``and I
just wanted to know if I could remove the sand or not,'' he said.
But, just as last year, Stewart was on the clock as of the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Being on the clock means a golfer has a certain time to strike
the ball, depending on various circumstances such as whether the
ball is on the tee, on the fairway, or on the green, and whether he
is the first or second player hitting. Golfers rarely are
penalized, but some become upset when told they are being timed.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Tiger Woods and Tim Herron, the twosome in front of
Mickelson and Stewart, were already gone from the faraway green of
the 454-yard, par-4 11th hole by the time Stewart and Mickelson
reached the 11th tee, ``that wasn't why we put them on the clock,''
said Meeks.
</P>
<P>
   Being out of touch with the twosome in front of you can
automatically incur the hands of the ticking clock, but not so this
time. Stewart and Mickelson were dallying too much, ``some five
minutes and eight seconds'' behind the pace they should have been
playing, Meeks explained.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at Olympic, on the hole after being put on the clock,
Stewart made bogey. Sunday, he made bogey again. ``I drove in the
rough and took my medicine; I just made some bad swings,'' said
Stewart, refusing to blame Holland's notification.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Stewart reacted differently when he struggled at
the 18th hole. ``I wasn't doubting myself out there at all,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he understands the USGA's ``idea of having to play
at a pace, and I think it's all right to come up and inform us that
we're being put on the clock instead of coming up and telling you
you have a bad time because you never realized in the first place
you're on the clock. Still, you're concentrating so hard on your
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 14th hole, Woods and Herron again were visible in the
distance ``and we took them off the clock after the 14th hole,''
said Meeks. ``They were on the clock for three holes.'' So
Stewart's mind now was off the clock and again totally on golf.
</P>
<P>
   And what golf it was. The deja vu ended abruptly on the 16th
hole because, unlike last year, when Stewart lost the Open to Lee
Janzen by a stroke, this time his mental toughness rescued him. At
16, when Stewart's second shot landed short of the green, ``for
some reason I felt like I had to chip it in, and I hit a very poor
chip,'' he said. ``And as it went 25 feet past the hole, I said,
`You didn't need to do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart absolutely needed to do what he did next. ``I stood
up there on that green, I got my line, and went through my
(putting) routine and I made my stroke.'' The absolute snake of a
downhill 25-footer ``went in,'' said Stewart, ``and off I went.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed were two immense scenes of tension and potential
rarely seen except in these finishing holes of major golf
tournaments. On both the 17th and 18th greens, Stewart and
Mickelson stood with a so-small putting stick in their hands, a
little white ball at their feet, and where that white ball went
after being struck would determine the joy of their round, their
day, their year.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Stewart dropped his putts and twice Mickelson couldn't.
If he tried to express his emotions, said Stewart when it was all
done, ``I couldn't speak.''
</P>
<P>
   But speak he would to Meeks before he left Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell Tom Meeks, `I thought this was a golf
tournament, and not a track meet.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 0225EDT &QL; 
