<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOUDON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANDLER DRINKS IT IN 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Doug Chandler's drought began, of all places,
after a victory two years ago in an American Motorcyclist
Association-sanctioned Superbike event at a venue called Laguna
Seca in Monterey, Calif. Laguna Seca, Spanish for dry lagoon. How
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   After a dry spell that lasted 28 races, Chandler thirsts for
victory no more.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in the featured Superbike event of the 76th Loudon
Classic at New Hampshire International Speedway, the 33-year-old
native of Salinas, Calif., earned the right to stand atop the
podium and quaff a bottle of champagne after riding his Team Muzzy
Kawasaki to victory before an announced crowd of 30,000. Chandler
finished ahead of Vance &AMP; Hines Ducati riders Ben Bostrom,
runner-up for the fourth race in a row and fifth time this season,
and Anthony Gobert, who won the pole and led the first 13 laps
around the 12-turn circuit but had his streak of four consecutive
victories snapped with a third-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's tough, you know, when you have such a long dry
spell,'' said Chandler, who gave a glimpse of his Kawasaki's
strength when he posted the fastest lap (81.433 miles per hour)
during a practice session Sunday morning. ``You kind of get
frustrated. Last year, I didn't mind it really, because of the way
the points were going, so I wasn't too bothered (after finishing
second in the Superbike points race). This year, we struggled with
the bike (with a 13th at Phoenix and an 11th at Rosamond, Calif.),
which put us out of the championship, but the victory is a morale
booster for me but more for the mechanics who work long and hard on
the bikes. They don't give up. This is a reward for that hard
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's triumph boosted Chandler, a three-time Superbike
champion, from sixth to fourth in the points standings with 214.
</P>
<P>
   With four races remaining, Chandler trails leader Matt Mladin by
55 points, while Bostrom and Gobert are tied for second with 264,
five behind Mladin.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the season, that's all I can do; just go for
the wins,'' Chandler said. ``But this really feels great. The guys
gave me a perfect bike all weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident on Lap 14 when Chandler ran down Gobert on
the front stretch and executed a perfect pass on the inside of Turn
1 to take the lead for good. Gobert then fell to third when Bostrom
overtook him in Turn 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to set the quickest pace I could,'' said Gobert,
a 24-year-old Australian. ``At the same time I was trying to save
the tires. But Doug went past me pretty easy in Turn 1 and gapped
me pretty much (on the) straightaway, so I knew he had more than
what I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom came to that realization midway through the race when he
bore down on Chandler on the winding backstretch but was unable to
execute a move without endangering himself or other riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was setting a really good pace and I ran really hard trying
to catch up,'' said Bostrom, 25, of Redondo Beach, Calif. ``Then he
caught up to a couple of lappers and carved his way around them
pretty well. But there just comes a point when you say, `I'm not
going to win this one; the other guy's outriding me.' So we'll take
second and go on to the next one and see how we do. But one day
we'll win one of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Hayden of Owensboro, Ky., finished ahead of Aaron Yates
and Tommy Hayden, Nicky's older brother, to win the 600cc
Supersport race . . . Derek King of Charleston, S.C., recorded his
first career victory in the 250cc Grand Prix event, finishing ahead
of Chris Ulrich of Lake Elsinore, Calif., and Jeff Wood of
Mansfield, Mass., who made a spectacular Turn 1 move on Quenni King
to earn his first career podium finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
