</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S SEND MIESKE TO ASTROS FOR CLASS AAA RIGHT-HANDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Over the last few days, Matt Mieske had thought
about talking with manager Lou Piniella about his playing time.
Mieske had just seven at-bats in June.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he did talk with Piniella, and learned he'd been traded
to the Houston Astros for Class AAA right-hander Kevin Hodges.
Piniella told Mieske something the outfielder was pleased to hear:
``If we can get you back in the future when we need an outfielder,
I'd like to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 2{ months with the Mariners, Mieske did what Piniella
asked him to do. In his first at-bat for Seattle, he cracked a
pinch-hit home run, something no Mariner had done in all of '98. He
batted .366 in 41 at-bats, and had a .417 average off left-handed
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   In going to Houston, which has the best record in the National
League, Mieske has a strong chance of returning to the playoffs. He
was a reserve for the wild card-winning Chicago Cubs last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be a winning team,'' Mieske said, ``you've
got to have all the pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Mieske was one of those pieces in his brief Mariners tenure. The
problem was the M's had one piece too many. Counting the injured
Jay Buhner, the Mariners had seven outfielders, which was one too
many for a roster that needs 11 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Astros general manager) Gerry Hunsicker and told
him he's getting himself a good player,'' Piniella said. ``Matt can
swing the bat, plays a very representative outfield and is a good
guy on the ballclub. We didn't get a chance to use him much, but we
were very happy with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mieske learned of the move about three hours before the
Mariners' game in Cleveland last night. He paged through an Astros
media guide, learning his new teammates as he said goodbye to his
old ones. He watched the game from the press box and will meet with
the Astros Tuesday in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The move ``shocked'' Mieske, who said he knew something had to
happen within the crowded outfield but didn't think he'd be the
player to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed a two-year contract, and you expect to be somewhere
for a while,'' Mieske said. ``We signed a year lease on our
apartment in Seattle. It's part of the game, and when it happens
you've got to roll with it and make adjustments. You've got to be
able to change directions in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mieske figures to get more at-bats on a National League team,
where pinch-hitting opportunities are greater and his skills
against left-handers can be put to use. In his career, Mieske is a
.319 hitter with 31 homers in 540 at-bats against left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like every time I was called upon, I did my job,''
Mieske said. ``That's rewarding and it makes you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, 26, is in his ninth minor league season, and made it to
Class AAA for the first time this year. He was 1-4 with a 2.94
earned-run average in eight starts for Class AA Jackson, earning a
promotion to Class AAA New Orleans, where he went 1-3 with a 7.24
ERA in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good-sized guy, 6-foot-4 and 200 pounds,'' said Roger
Jongewaard, the Mariners' vice president for scouting and player
development. ``Our report was from double-A, and it said that he
has four average pitches and looks like he's starting to figure it
out. He's not a premium guy, but he's a usable guy who has a
chance. He's an average prospect, and he can come up and be an
average pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges will be sent to Class AAA Tacoma, where he will pitch in
the Rainiers' starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   SETBACK FOR BUHNER: Buhner had hoped to be activated Monday from
his hamstring strain, but Charles Gipson is likely to be recalled
from Tacoma to take Mieske's place. Trainers wanted Buhner to run
the bases successfully for two days, but Sunday's running session
did not go as well as hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to put Jay on the roster until we're absolutely
sure,'' Piniella said. ``He struggled a little bit out there today;
he was still a little sore. I would think he's about 85-90
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Buhner returns, Piniella said, he won't be able to
play every day, which should give Butch Huskey a chance to play
semi-regularly. Huskey, who has hit well in Buhner's absence, can
play first, left and right field and will see time when Piniella
rests players at those positions.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: The Mariners will meet with No. 1 pick Ryan
Christenson Monday. The club's first offer to the Riverside
(Calif.) high school catcher was $1.1 million, but given what
players near Christenson's draft position signed for last year and
this year, he can command about $1.7-$1.8 million. Once Christenson
signs, his probable destination is Class A Everett. ...
Right-hander Paul Abbott worked seven innings for the second start
in a row at Tacoma last night, and is likely to start the finale of
the Mariners' three-game series with Anaheim on Thursday. ...
Indians right fielder Manny Ramirez suffered a bruised knuckle on
his left index finger when hit by a Frankie Rodriguez fastball in
the first inning last night. The majors' leader in RBIs was taken
to a nearby hospital for X-rays, which found no broken bone.
</P>
</TEXT>
