<SLUG> BC-BAPTISM-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERGY STRIVE TO MAINTAIN SPIRITUAL MEANING OF BAPTISM
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a minister baptizing a baby 
 By DEBRA LESTER AND MARY LOFTUS 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baptism is one of the most significant rites of the Christian
church, whether recited as part of a formal church ceremony where a
baby is welcomed into the fold or outside by a pond as a minister
lowers an adult believer into the symbolic waters.
</P>
<P>
   But some clergy and religious scholars are afraid that baptism
is becoming trivialized, a social ritual detached from its deeper
spiritual meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Curtis, a Presbyterian minister and professor of biblical
studies at Geneva College in Beaver Falls, Pa., and an Old
Testament specialist, says the sacrament of baptism is much more
than just a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people decide, 'Let's get the kid done, here's $25 for
the priest.' That's a great abuse. We're fighting to restore
baptism as a distinctive honor within the believing community of
Christians, to reclaim this sign so that it's truly distinctive,
not just a cultural accouterment,'' Curtis says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when Elle Macpherson's year-old son, Arpad Flynn
Alexander Busson, was baptized in Italy this year, what the
supermodel wore _ a tight, mink-trimmed beige suit designed by
Valentino _ garnered more attention than the ceremony itself.
</P>
<P>
   While Macpherson's motives may have been pure, the paparazzi
surrounding the church didn't allow the ceremony much sanctity.
</P>
<P>
   Baptism today is sometimes misunderstood, agrees Gayle Felton, a
Duke Divinity School assistant professor who took part in a study
that produced: ''By Water and the Spirit: A United Methodist
Understanding of Baptism.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our confusion has resulted in a feeble appreciation of
baptism, which often reduces it to a sentimental service of
thanksgiving for a child or a ceremony of 'joining the church' on
the part of an adult,'' Felton says.
 &UR; WITHIN THE CHURCH &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, in his role as a minister, has baptized infants. ''But
not any infant,'' he says. ''If a person is a member within the
visible church, attempting to live a life of faith within the grace
of God, this person's children I will happily baptize. If a person
comes without a commitment to the church of Jesus, I ask them to
become committed. I routinely do a fair amount of instruction about
it. There is a general sense that the sacrament is important, a
blessing from God, but often people didn't understand the
theological details.''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion is understandable, since the ritual and its meaning
can vary by denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the use of water is common to almost all
baptisms. Water is a powerful religious symbol that expresses
cleansing, washing away of sin, immorality or impurity, and also
death and rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Baptist, charismatic and Pentecostal denominations usually
practice believer's baptism or immersion, while Presbyterian,
Episcopal, Catholic and United Methodist churches practice infant
baptism or sprinkling.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Orthodox Church combines both rites, baptizing infants
by immersion. The priest holds the nose and keeps the mouth sealed
as he immerses the baby three times, in the name of the Father, Son
and Holy Ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Barrett, religion professor at Wofford College in
Spartanburg, S.C., notes that the Greek word for ''baptism'' means
immersion. But as Christianity moved into the Middle East and other
arid climates, water in amounts large enough for immersion was not
always available. Pouring water over the person being baptized gave
way to sprinkling.
 &UR; COMPETING THEOLOGIES &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the contemporary church, the two styles of baptism _ baptism
by immersion, or ''believer's baptism,'' and baptism by sprinkling,
or infant baptism _ represent differing theologies. Believer's
baptism is done in response to salvation already obtained, while
infant baptism is a declaration of God's grace.
</P>
<P>
   ''Infant baptism is based on the idea that God loves us before
we can love him,'' said Barrett. ''It's the supreme example of
grace _ God's acting to save us before we can save ourselves.''
Infant baptism is a primary sacrament in many churches.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't do anything that's more important than the baptism of
our children,'' said the Rev. Mickey Fisher, pastor of Trinity
United Methodist Church in Spartanburg. One family in his
congregation, just after baptizing their infant son, described the
ceremony as a vital first step in providing their children with a
firm foundation of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very important to have our children grow up in church,''
Rena Fowler, the mother of the baptized baby, said. ''A baptism
ceremony is just as important as a wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gregory D. Goolsby, a priest at the Catholic Church of
St. Monica in Duluth, Ga., says the Catholic church also performs
infant baptisms, the key to becoming an ''adopted child of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a pitcher of water that I dump over the infant's head
three times. I tend to use a gracious amount of flowing water. In
some Catholic churches, the baby will be set down in a bowl of
water, and water will be poured over his head,'' Goolsby says.
</P>
<P>
   Most children are baptized in the Catholic church between two to
three weeks to six months after birth.
</P>
<P>
   ''The deacon prepares parents for the sacrament, and sometimes
the godparents as well,'' according to Goolsby. ''It's a good time
to re-evangelize. Often, this is the time families will return to
the church.''
 &UR; REBORN IN WATER &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Believer's baptism, on the other hand, is performed on older
children or adults, usually through full immersion. In the Baptist
tradition, the ritual is a confirmation of salvation, which is
something that can happen only when the person can understand what
it means.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing wrong with sprinkling,'' says the Rev. Hub
Blankenship Jr., of Spartanburg Community Church. ''But as a baby,
it's not a conscious decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, 21 people were baptized by Blankenship in a lake near
the church. All were considered by the Southern Baptist
congregation to be old enough to already have experienced
salvation. The youngest to be immersed in the warm waters was 6
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Some churches that baptize by immersion have baptistery pools
(usually behind the altar) that resemble huge bathtubs, complete
with spigots. Other churches use ponds, lakes or rivers, or even
swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   Sacraments such as baptism, says Curtis, ''do not in themselves
save. But they do encourage and help a life of salvation. Baptism
is how Jesus places his mark of blessing upon all those who are
included in the visible church _ the community who does believe,
striving for the justice of God in the midst of a fallen world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Debra Lester writes for the Herald-Journal in Spartanburg,
S.C. Mary Loftus writes for the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
