<HEADER>
A3491 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2KCOLUMN22-CO     06-21 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2KCOLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doom may not follow Greenspan's gloom
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan peers through
his thick glasses, he sees a bright and blossoming economy. Because
of new technologies, such as computers, scanners, satellites and
more, ``something special has happened to the American economy in
recent years,'' the central banker told the Joint Economic
Committee of Congress last week.
</P>
<P>
   But when Greenspan looks into the next century, his view seems
to darken. ``The rate of growth of productivity can't increase
indefinitely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the nation's central bank during the 1990s, Greenspan
has gotten a great deal of the credit for the eight-year economic
expansion. But his place in history is not yet firmly set. Someday,
economic historians may look back at his comments about
productivity and put him in the same class as poor Henry Ellsworth,
the nation's commissioner of patents more than 150 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before Congress in 1843, Ellsworth remarked: ``The
advancement of the (industrial) arts, from year to year, taxes our
credulity and seems to presage the arrival of that period when
human improvement must end.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, his comment about human improvement ending has
been wildly embellished. Twisted versions of his quote, sometimes
attributed to other patent commissioners, typically turn up in
business speeches about shortsighted thinking.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how Ellsworth's words get mangled, the point is
the same: The patent commissioner was a dunderhead for not seeing
that inventors were about to unleash a torrent of new goods from
light bulbs to tractors to airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Now Greenspan has set himself up to provide the punchline for
untold numbers of Rotary Club speeches in the next century.
Business leaders may find themselves chuckling again and again over
the silly notion that 1999's rate of productivity growth could not
be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity is a measure of the amount of goods and services
workers turn out per hour. When productivity rises, factories can
make more cars, refrigerators or other goods with the same number
of employees. That holds down costs and boost profits so that
bosses can afford to give workers raises. A rising productivity
rate suggests an improving standard of living for both workers and
employers.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, productivity, outside of agriculture,
has grown at an annual rate of about 2 percent, roughly double what
it was in the 1970s and 1980s. Most economists think this boost is
the byproduct of new equipment such as bar-code scanners, cellular
phones, hand-held computers that transmit package-tracking
information and other sophisticated tools.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to productivity in the next century, the bulls on
Wall Street believe we ain't seen nothin' yet. As the Internet
pulls together more information and speeds up transactions,
productivity gains could be enormous. Just as the Industrial Age
took a few decades to pick up steam and broadly boost living
standards, so too will the Information Age need a little more time
to get its traction.
</P>
<P>
   But once the typical home has a high-speed Internet connection
and businesses are tapping the information resources created by the
Internet, productivity will skyrocket, pushing average Americans to
previously unimaginable levels of affluence, at least according to
believers in the ``new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out they are right, Greenspan, who today is known as
a brilliant economist, may someday take his place alongside
Ellsworth in the pantheon of very smart men who never saw it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   This is a weekly report by Atlanta Constitution editorial writer
Marilyn Geewax on issues raised by the coming of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
