</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lightning's power finally hits home
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lightning in cartoons and children's drawings always looks like
a jagged dagger, issuing in a single point from burnt-marshmallow
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way I imagined it when as a kid I first heard the
story about a great-uncle who was hit by lightning. He was bent
over the engine of a stalled pickup truck at the edge of a field. I
thought of lightning as a deadly finger tapping him on the shoulder
as he cursed Ford Motor Company.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else, though, reality turns out to be more
complicated. Lightening forks and dances about. Half the bolts hit
the ground at more than one place.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that after spending a week staring into trees and
trying to figure the path of the lightning bolt that struck my
house. I gave this up as an idle exercise. It seemed to have been
everywhere, all at once.
</P>
<P>
   It hit the place like a bomb. Instead of experiencing the
familiar, reassuring gap between hearing thunder and seeing light,
I heard an explosion and saw instantaneous light, as though stadium
lights were being switched on and off by pranksters outside of the
window. The house smelled liked barbecued robot.
</P>
<P>
   I am no lightning wimp. I cannot be. I live in central Florida,
The Thunderstorm Capital of the Nation.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, this designation is on no license plate,
T-shirt or bumper sticker. Nowhere on I-4 is a sign saying:
``Welcome to Central Florida -- The USA's Thunderstorm Capital!''
We could have lightning death-count signs the way New Hampshire has
injury signs with moose-related accident numbers on them.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why we try to hide our awesome, busy skies. Our
thunderstorms constitute a natural wonder. Not only in intensity
but in number. We experience 70-100 thunderstorm days a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to Central Florida and watch the lightning strikes!''
would be a dandy slogan bidding to the more adventuresome traveler.
Eco-tourists from places with tame, white-bread, boring old weather
could come here to experience the full-bore natural drama of a
ground-shaking, wind-making, Book of Revelations-style,
day-turns-to-night-and-the-seas-boil-and-rage variety of
thunderstorm. People ashamed of their lightning fears could come
here to face them down.
</P>
<P>
   These storms take my breath away every summer. Even when they
aren't trying to burn my house down.
</P>
<P>
   I eventually found the place where the lightning bolt struck. It
hit a high-up limb of a large oak tree and left a narrow, blackened
path of ripped bark as it sought the ground. Some of the leaves
were withering.
</P>
<P>
   How the lightning moved from tree to downspout is unclear to me.
It baked and discolored the metal spout, popped its rivets and tore
it halfway off the house. Nearby, it took two shallow scoops out of
the driveway for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Was this the same bolt that burned the air conditioner, charred
phone lines and escaped out the television cable, bursting
insulation and popping connectors? That seems like a lot of places
for a rogue electrical charge to be. Was it more than one hit?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could say. ``Lightning's funny,'' summed up one repair
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the mystery purely electrical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is God punishing you,'' suggested my eighth-grade
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is God telling you to get off the phone once in a
while,'' I suggested right back. Angry-deity theology is a game two
can always play. And angry deities with lightning predate
Christianity and the written word. We were engaged in speculation
of an most ancient kind.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of your theology, there is something awe-inspiring
and enlarging about having a billion volts of electricity visit
one's home. Nature turbulent and random is no respecter of persons.
We think we can make summer go away because we have air
conditioning. Even though a single summer lightning storm can
dispatch any air-conditioning unit in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   And sitting in the home without the telephone ringing and the
televisions disabled, I figured this was just as well. For the
first time of the summer, I listened to tree frogs outside
celebrating the damp.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
