</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student/teacher protests aren't what they used to be
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Since my days on the ``outside'' are
assuredly numbered, I've
</P>
<P>
   decided to confess and throw myself on the mercy of public
opinion before ``they'' come to take me away. It's not a pretty
story, but it needs to be told.
</P>
<P>
   It all began on a fine spring day at a small, private school set
down in the gently rolling hills of west central Georgia. As the
bona-fide soccer moms went about their benign business of
fingernail transplants and making sure they had shoes to match all
of their outfits, I, with knowledge and aforethought (I'm not sure
that fits here, but I've always wanted to write it) did willfully
promote civil disorder and incite an entire student body to revolt.
On that grim day an anarchist was born.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, don't blame me. I told you it wasn't a pretty story. Blame
it on the passion of youth _ I was only 45. And I only did it once.
</P>
<P>
   My desk was in the high school's central hall. I was a
volunteer. My recognized job included answering the phone, ordering
lunch, and convincing visiting parents that the escalating dialogue
they heard coming from the Latin room was not student unrest, but
rather the Platonic method of teaching employed by this particular
instructor.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, due to the location, my desk was the unofficial
student center. During a free period, Billy would stop by, write
the morning announcements (frequently in dialect), and share his
dreams for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ace the SATs and become a brain surgeon.'' (He
did both.) Suzy would often stop to share her latest hat _ usually
a '50s model she'd liberated from her grandmother's cedar chest.
April wanted to talk about Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, I was the complaint department: ``Our bus driver
passes gas. Gross!'' or, ``Somebody's gotta tell Danny to get some
odor-eaters for his Docksiders.''
</P>
<P>
   But on this particular spring morning, we began playing with the
big boys. No time for piddling complaints about Tommy throwing
Ginny's shoes on the roof (after he'd forcibly removed them from
her feet), or the 'possum who'd been raiding the student lounge. In
the blink of an eye, the situation became grave and my unofficial
occupation switched from oracle to activist.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation approached from the west hall. Billy was the
spokesperson. ``Mrs.
</P>
<P>
   Wofford is leaving at the end of the year, and we don't want her
to go. Everything we know about history we've learned from her.
Besides, she lets us sit on the floor if we want to. What can we do
to make her stay?''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what happened, folks. That's how I came to organize
my first (and only) foray into civil disobedience. By lunchtime, at
my instigation, 40 kids circled the high school carrying
hand-lettered protest signs and chanting, ``No go, Mrs. Wo!'' Sadly
for all of us, the beloved teacher (and my personal friend) left at
the end of the year anyway, to join her husband who'd been
transferred out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, I've felt no remorse over the years, nor have I been
troubled by urges to turn myself in and confess to heretical
behavior. Truth is, I thought I was home free, what with the
statute of limitations and all. But now I'm not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Have you read about the 15-year-old kid in Oregon who spent a
night in jail and is now under house arrest for his alleged role in
a protest outside a Nike store? Police investigators with drawn
guns and brandishing a battering ram, swarmed onto his family's
front porch with a search warrant that turned up over 350
potentially subversive items including a cereal box and an Emma
Goldman (radical and feminist; early advocate of free speech, birth
control, and the eight-hour work day) poster.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, I'm not too impressed with either the kid's attitude
(shooting birds at traffic cops) or his hairstyle (somewhere
between dreadlocks and early Mixmaster), but arrest? Confinement?
</P>
<P>
   And if the constabulary can do this to a 15-year-old kid, just
imagine what they might dream up for a grown woman who should have
known better.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431; email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
