<SLUG> BC-COKE-EUROPE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crisis embroils soft drink giant Coca-Cola in European politics
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The European health scare over tainted Coca-Cola Co.
soft drinks has thrust the Atlanta-based beverage company into a
politically charged thicket over who's in charge of food safety
regulations on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke stepped right into the middle of it,'' said Joseph
Greenwald, a Washington-based trade consultant who was U.S.
representative to the European Union from 1972-75.
</P>
<P>
   First, the issue of food safety is politically sensitive, dating
to the 1996 scandal over Britain's ``mad cow disease'' that split
the 15-nation European Union and still lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Health Minister Van den Bossche, who ordered Coke
products off the shelves last week, had just replaced a minister
who resigned in the ``chicken-gate'' scandal over the tainting of
animal feed, chicken breasts and eggs with cancer-causing dioxin.
The main infraction was failure to report the findings to the
15-nation European Union. Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene
was voted out of office the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem faced by Coke as it tries to repair the damage
is the fact that regulations appear to be a moving target. While
one country bans some Coke products, another issues a warning and
yet another allows sales of some products but not others.
</P>
<P>
   Despite much attention to the emergence of a single European
economy with a common currency, food safety regulations are still
largely left to the member states.
</P>
<P>
   No single authority
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, no single entity has the authority within the
community to restrict drinks or food with safety problems,'' said
Greenwald. ``The European Community does not have the equivalent of
the FDA (the U.S. Food and Drug Administration), and that's one of
the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   William Long, a professor at the Sam Nunn School of
International Affairs at Georgia Tech, compared the European system
to federal-state jurisdictions over some matters in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission in Brussels will adopt health and
sanitation directives, but it's up to each country to put them into
effect by enacting national laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's confusing,'' Long said. ``You're operating in one market,
but 15 countries. You're subject to directives coming out of
Brussels, but each national authority will carry out the
implementation. So it could amount to a pulling off the shelves in
Belgium, but a warning from Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Weintraub, a political economist at the Washington-based
Center for Strategic and International Studies, added: ``You have a
mixture of national responsibility, but commission authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with President Clinton on Thursday, French President
Jacques Chirac said a ``worldwide high scientific council for food
safety'' was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are increasingly concerned, worried,'' he said. But
Clinton urged Chirac to press for a European FDA, a course
considered likely by many European-based experts.
</P>
<P>
   However, such a body might not be able to resolve what Greenwald
called ``fundamental differences'' between Americans and Europeans
on food safety issues that could be figuring in the Coke dispute.
</P>
<P>
   He cited continuing trade disputes between the United States and
European Union over U.S. exports of hormone-treated beef and
genetically modified American crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans want 100 percent risk-free,'' he said. ``But
most Americans are willing to accept some risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
