<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A world of ways to goof off _ only a mouse click away
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you ignore the horoscopes and advice columns when you read
the newspaper? Do you rush right past the comics to get to the
heavy news?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. And it's much the same on the World Wide Web.
While there is enough practical information to suit the most dour
Web surfer, there also are plenty of light features that are just
plain fun.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with horoscopes. While it would probably be foolish
to plan your company's next public stock offering based on the fact
that next Thursday looks good for your Libra sign, most of us give
our horoscopes an occasional glance. One of the best horoscopes on
the Web comes from an astrologer in the United Kingdom called
Jonathan Cainer. You'll get both daily and weekly forecasts there,
along with a look at the entire year. Just follow the stars to
stars.metawire.com.
</P>
<P>
   Advice columns abound on the Web. You don't have to rely on Dr.
Laura when there's a chance to visit a page called Ask Great Granny
at www.mbnet.mb.ca/crm/granny/granny.htmltoc. You'll be able to
browse the answers or post your own question. You'll find things
organized according to categories, including areas for advice about
children, parents, your love life or even your mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, while the idea is amusing, the advice is far from a
joke. You'll find plenty of lighthearted questions and answers but
also some like this one:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a 47-year-old man looking after an 82-year-old mother in
fragile health. I really have no support from anyone else. I have a
brother, but even after repeated attempts to get him to help, he
sloughs it off and leaves it on my shoulders. I'm not sure where to
go from here. I love my mother and she is still reasonably mobile
and alert, although she has chronic and limiting problems. I want
to care for her at home and will continue to do so, but my own
health seems to be suffering. I'm not sure what lies ahead nor
which way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The next site offers you a chance to win money playing games
online. It's called the Free Games Gallery, and you'll find it at
www.nukingdom.com
</P>
<P>
   /games.htm. You'll find a number of games listed on this page _
just click on one and you are on your way. For instance, there's
WinDough, where you can win $15,000 or so just for playing. No
skill is involved here: This game works much like the lottery. You
leave a tiny window open as you go about your business, maybe even
do some work. Winners are notified if their lucky number comes up.
Then, perhaps, you can quit your job and start cruising the Web on
your own time.
</P>
<P>
   Web cameras are a creation of the Internet. Here's how they
work. Someone _ or some institution _ will install a video camera
and transmit the live video, or still photos that are freshened on
a regular basis, on the Web for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Web camera sites aren't for family viewing. All kind
of folks use them. But some of the cameras are G-rated. There is,
for instance, the camera at Sunrise Beach in Hawaii. You'll see the
surf there without leaving your desk. Just go to
www.satlab.hawaii.edu/satlab/sunset.html.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best time-waster of all is to simply enter your own
name in one of the search engines such as AltaVista or Yahoo! and
then click through the list. You may find that your 15 minutes of
fame have already arrived somewhere on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
