<HEADER>
A3502 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-THEATER22-COX     06-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-THEATER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home theater can be created on modest budget
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is it the startling appeal of new theaters with
stadium seating and razzle-dazzle surround sound _ or maybe the
never-ending quest for affordable popcorn? For whatever reason, the
idea of creating a little theater of your own, in your house,
continues to grow and build.
</P>
<P>
   The urge to employ big-screen video to fight your own Star Wars,
right there in the family room, or plant yourself in the backfield,
ready for a handoff, has become the order of the day. Plenty of TV
and stereo dealers will be happy to accommodate you with systems _
for $10,000 to $25,000 or more, or even as little as $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly people are looking for the excitement they now find in
new theaters, with the high-quality sound that is common,'' said
Don Burns, a video and audio salesman in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Doing a home theater on a budget is a practical idea, said Burns
and others, provided you are willing to forgo one of the fancy
high-definition televisions that retail for $5,500 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, most people already have one or more of the
components of a decent home theater system,'' said Buck Brown,
audio video sales manager at a Circuit City in Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The main parts of a home theater include a good TV set, a stereo
VCR, a Dolby digital receiver/amplifier and a six-speaker
surround-sound system. As a source of programming, most experts say
a DVD player is needed. That's the machine that plays movies,
together with superb sound.
</P>
<P>
   The fun of home theater starts with a program source. That could
be a quality videotape, a DVD movie that is deciphered by a DVD
player, a satellite broadcast or, increasingly, a digital broadcast
or programs from digital cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people already have a TV that could be usable,'' said
Brown. ``And that could be any set from 27 inches and up, depending
on the size of the room. Lots of people already have stereo VCRs
that could work in a system.''
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists like Rawland Simmons, video department
supervisor at an Atlanta Best Buys store, say the budget-minded
buyer might even consider skipping the DVD player for now and
starting with a satellite system instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're brand new to DVD,'' said Simmons, ``it means you
need to buy the player and start to build a library. It might be
just as well to spend $300 for a DirecTV or other satellite setup
and get immediate access to a variety of programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, especially purists, point out that DVD is about
the clearest and most attractive picture, and has the flexibility
of interactivity, meaning the viewer can browse the movie easily,
picking out favorite scenes and gathering information about the
movie's background.
</P>
<P>
   It is a unique new way to enjoy movies _ even better than the
commercial theater, because of the flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   DVD, short for digital video disc, has been on the streets only
since mid-1997, but got a burst of sales during the past holiday
season and seems well on the way to denting the videotape sales
market. DVDs were practically launched with the movie ``Twister,''
where the furious tornado pictures and sounds highlighted the new
medium's power to convey excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Starting totally from scratch, the home theater builder would
need to pick up the following:
</P>
<P>
   1. Television set, with cost ranging from nothing, if you have
one you like, to a range of $500 to about $2,200 for a full-blown
60-inch set.
</P>
<P>
   2. A DVD player, from $250 to $500, depending on the extra
features preferred.
</P>
<P>
   3. A Dolby digital receiver, from $300 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   4. A speaker system, from $1,000 to $1,500, including three
front speakers, two rear speakers and a self-powered sub-woofer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another component, often overlooked, is high-quality cables to
connect the system while still maintaining good audio,'' said
Circuit City's Brown. ``If you don't already have the cables and a
good surge protector, it could set you back anywhere from $200 to
$300.''
</P>
<P>
   The sources of good digital programming are considerable, and
eventually will be numerous. In addition to the DVD sources, which
include a library of movies that grows virtually every day, as well
as growing rental collections, don't forget satellite programming.
Eventually, many of us will be able to tap into suitable
programming from upgraded cable service and ``wireless cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people already have laser disc players and a collection of
movies that could be a good program source for home theater. But
the laser disc technology, which was always superior in quality to
videotapes, has been overtaken by DVD. Whether you prefer laser
discs or DVD, the fact is that the library of programming will grow
faster for DVD, video specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest sales in home theater equipment are from October
to January, during the holiday season,'' said Burns. But he and
others say there is a steady flow of sales through the summer, too,
when youngsters are home from college.
</P>
<P>
   The main importance of the home theater is that it's the heart
of a family entertainment center with something for everybody. The
components allow video viewing beyond compare, as well as
facilities for playing music with excellent reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Because the system is divided into components, it allows for
continuous upgrading for new technologies or to accommodate
changing tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
