<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nisus Writer stacks up well with Microsoft Word, at a bargain
price
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Need a word processor but don't want to pay $300 for Microsoft
Word, the industry standard? Check out Nisus Writer, which you can
now buy online for $42.
</P>
<P>
   That's a heck of a deal when you consider that Nisus Writer can
do nearly anything Word can. Nisus also has some features not yet
included in Word.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say Word 98, the latest version, is a bad
program. It's probably the best word processor for the Mac that
Microsoft has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Word remains the only Mac word processor that lets you
create an outline and then turn it into a finished book, study or
thesis.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Word is that it demands a steep price in terms
of internal memory and disk space. The latest version runs
sluggishly on anything but Power Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to Nisus Writer, developed by a small software
company in Solana Beach, Calif. Nisus Writer will run on just about
any Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The program is fast and responsive. Its working motif is clean
and easy to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Like Word, Nisus will let you write anything from letters to
books. You can also design newsletters and Web pages, and include
graphics, pictures and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Nisus also has a few useful features not yet included in Word.
For one, Nisus has a great built-in thesaurus. Just highlight a
word and hit the command key and the letter _ up pops the
thesaurus, which includes both a short definition of the word and a
list of suggested alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Another novel Nisus feature is multiple clipboards, which let
you save up to 10 different things at once.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a feature that lets you select and edit various
parts of a document at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Nisus is easy to program for power users. For non-power users,
it comes with a vast library of macros. For example, the library
includes macros that will automatically find and remove empty
spaces and paragraphs in a document.
</P>
<P>
   Where Nisus falls short is in outlining and the making of
tables. You can format Nisus to outline, but it's a royal pain.
Don't even try to use the program's table feature. It's that bad.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find Nisus Writer in stores, and the program is hard
to find in catalogs as well. The best place to order and learn more
about Nisus Writer is at the company's excellent Web site. You'll
find it at www.nisus.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
