<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Britannica a great reason to upgrade to DVD drive
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If any single piece of software can make it mandatory to include
a DVD drive in every computer, it is the DVD version of the
Encyclopaedia Britannica.
</P>
<P>
   Warts and all _ and it has enough of them to need the services
of a good dermatologist _ the DVD version of the best print
encyclopedia now takes its rightful place as the best electronic
encyclopedia for adults.
</P>
<P>
   I say adult not because of any particularly racy content, but
because the siren song of multimedia has still not totally
convinced the publishers. No erupting volcanos, no roaring tigers
here. Just more and better information than any other electronic
encyclopedia offers.
</P>
<P>
   It was good to see that the 1999 version of the EB no longer
uses Netscape as its search engine, but this was quickly allayed by
seeing that it simply dropped Netscape and picked up Microsoft
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   However, the change was greater than that. The user no longer
feels as though the computer is constantly online, and the
interface is really just as slick as anyone else's. Not quite as
gadgety as Encarta's, but attractive and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is quite a lot of video included on this
wonderful disc. The videos tend to be of satisfying length and
range from views of a herd of elephants going about its daily
business to extremely technical clips depicting the procedure for
making DNA comparisons. Most of it is soundless except for
occasional narration and the insertion of generic bird sounds into
some of the nature films.
</P>
<P>
   Audio clips are limited to the national anthems of the world's
nations and the sounds of individual musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, while you won't get a few bars of Haydn's
``Surprise'' symphony, you get a long, comprehensive biography and
appreciation of his work written by H.C. Robbins Landon, the
foremost Haydn scholar.
</P>
<P>
   The article on flamenco is by far the most intelligent and
detailed I have seen in any encyclopedia; unfortunately, the author
is not listed.
</P>
<P>
   There are brief biographies on many of my favorite folks who are
ignored by every other encyclopedia. The Dalton brothers and Bill
Doolin are here, although the little article on the latter contains
an error _ the deputy U.S. marshal who killed him was Heck Thomas,
not Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Linkage from a subject to related items is splendid, drawing the
casual browser deeper and deeper into the study of a specific area.
I didn't see a single article that didn't have at least one
Internet link.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the other encyclopedias, EB now includes ``features'' _
specially organized areas.
</P>
<P>
   The only one comparable to its peers is the timeline, and this
is very well-done, allowing the user to pick any two of a number of
general subjects for a timeline study.
</P>
<P>
   Most amazing is the Analyst, which allows a student to compare
general statistics of two countries. You can get these comparisons
as written reports or in table form. How else could you learn that
Australia has 20,300 percent more sheep than Canada?
</P>
<P>
   For younger folks, there is a splendid feature called full-text
search, which allows one to ask a question.
</P>
<P>
   I typed in ``Why does a cow chew a cud?'' and got a long list of
responses, the first and most immediately relevant of which was a
definition of ruminant mammals.
</P>
<P>
   The Spectrum feature presents 10 general areas which,
altogether, cover virtually every aspect of human knowledge. These
are basically outlines, and clicking on anything not only provides
a discussion of that topic but offers many related topics, drawing
you deeper and deeper. It's almost addictive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about the warts. The worst of them will bother only users
of Peter Norton's CleanSweep utility.
</P>
<P>
   With CleanSweep running in the background, every time you click
the mouse the program thinks you are about to install a program and
asks if you want it monitored. Annoying, but for EB I can live with
it.
</P>
<P>
   If you are running Windows 98, some of the features won't work
unless you make a change to your computer's file structure. Making
the change is quite simple; the ramifications of it, however, are
not yet clear.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD version of Encyclopaedia Britannica 1999 carries a list
price of $129. If you have a DVD drive, I have to urge you to get
the encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't, then I'll urge you to get the DVD drive and then
get the encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
