<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-TECH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mix schoolwork into summer fun
 &HT;    By Jennifer Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA Summer at my house is the season for a camp or two, the
pool, car trips and leisure. And, most importantly, no school.
</P>
<P>
   But as the boys have gotten older, I've come to realize that
complete withdrawal from all schoolwork is not good.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, come fall, we all pay as they struggle initially with
subjects they knew prior to summer's hot, lazy interlude. So this
year, we're mixing some schoolwork with our leisure, and we're
using technology to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Both boys have been using the Internet increasingly to help with
schoolwork, so it won't seem unusual when we go there for some
summer tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, tutoring is one of the things computers do well. As an
impassive, unemotionally involved machine, it has endless patience
with monotonous drill work such as multiplication and division.
</P>
<P>
   Yahooligans, Yahoo!'s kid-oriented search engine, has an
excellent homework page (www.yahooligans.com/SchoolBell) that links
to several good math sites
(www.yahooligans.com/SchoolBell/Math/HomeworkHelp/).
</P>
<P>
   At MegaKids, www.meganova.com/megakids/flash.htm, you do drills
in multiplication, addition, subtraction and division. At the end
of the drill, you're told your completion time and the number of
errors. In the course of the drill, you are retested on problems
you answer incorrectly. When you're done, you are presented with a
printable certificate stating the results.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, Edu4kids (www.edu4kids.com/math/) allows you to
set the number of problems, the level of difficulty, as in ``Easy,
no negatives; Complex, up to 10 numbers,'' as well as the size of
numbers (0-9), (0-99).
</P>
<P>
   Both sites tell you immediately if your answer is right or
wrong. However, Edu4kids only says if it is incorrect, while
MegaKids gives you the correct answer. I found this feature to be
more helpful.
</P>
<P>
   The other area of schoolwork for which I was able to find useful
sites was grammar. Guide to Grammar and Writing
(cctc.commnet.edu/HP/pages/darling/original.htmlogs) has a long
address, but it's worth it. You also can use its name with a search
engine to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Everything you ever wanted to know about grammar is here, from
sentence and word parts to clauses and phrases and punctuation and
more.
</P>
<P>
   There are explanations for each rule of grammar:
</P>
<P>
   Use a comma and a little conjunction (and, but, for, nor, yet,
or, so) to connect two independent clauses, as in ``He hit the ball
well, but he ran toward third base.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules include hyperlinks for further instruction. In the
example above, the phrase ``independent clauses'' is hyperlinked to
its definition.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each section is an interactive quiz. In the quiz
on ``that, which and who,'' you're asked to fill in blanks in
sentences with the correct answer. For example:
</P>
<P>
   ``1. People live in glass houses shouldn't throw stones.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you do, you find out immediately if your answer is correct.
You also can get the explanation for the correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   These sites are just the tip of the iceberg when it comes to
online tutorial help. Use the keywords Family Education Network to
find help on America Online as well as the kids channel.
</P>
<P>
   But remember, keep the summer schoolwork in proportion, which
would be a ratio of 3:7, or is that 0.3 of 100 percent ... ?
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Hill writes about issues relating to families and
technology for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. E-mail:
jhill(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
