</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't kiss off idea of online dating
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once upon a time, in a galaxy far, far away, I
ventured into the world of online matchmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't all those stories of people who found love online
fascinating? Don't you single folks wonder if it could happen to
you? Think about it: People who, in the normal course of human
events would never, ever find each other, yet were perfect for each
other, were connecting on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   I shared my idea with the editor of the newspaper I was writing
for at the time. She asked me just one thing in that cold, clipped,
impatient voice that has made her something of a legend in that New
York media whirl that keeps Brill's Content and New York magazine
columnist Michael Wolff in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``So have you tried this dating thing for yourself?'' she asked
in her typical, icy tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, well, no,'' I stammered. The idea was for happy couples to
talk about their happy experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``First person or nothing,'' she commanded into the phone. Then,
as her way, she hung up, probably to take calls from Princess
Diana, Gywnneth Paltrow, Oprah Winfrey or whoever it is she talked
to when she wasn't wasting her time with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   So this was the deal: Go out on dates with guys I met on the
Internet, or seriously consider a part-time job selling pretzels on
a street corner. I had no choice. I had to tell an online community
of desperate single men that I was a desperate single woman, then
tell the whole world about it in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   So I ventured on to a Web site called Match.com, although there
are a million sites that offer similar ``dating, mating and
relating'' services. I chose Match, because it gave me a two-week
trial period (they're down to just one week now) and after that if
your online social life is hopping, you can pay about $14 a month
to join the service and browse potential boyfriend or girlfriend
material indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these online romance sites ask you to fill out a
questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   A very cynical girlfriend of mine refers to personal ads as
``lowest common denominator dating.'' Let me tell you, the online
personals are no different. You fill out questionnaires asking you
to describe your height, weight, hair color, religion and so forth.
There's a little room to talk a little about yourself, but here's
where writer's block of epic proportions sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Guys love to talk about how outdoorsy they are. The online
gentleman writes about hiking, basketball, working out at the gym
and the ever-popular ``cuddling up on a cold night with a special
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   We women aren't much better. We invariably describe ourselves as
``petite, smart, beautiful, educated and professional.'' We like
movies, going out to dinner and ``taking in the best the city _
whatever city that might be _ has to offer.'' When it comes to
personals, even Shakespeare would probably be reduced to writing
about long walks on the beach and candlelit dinners. Something
about a personal ad makes you focus less on who you really are and
more on who you think you ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   From my two weeks with Match.com, I learned a couple of things:
There are all kinds of men out there, which is nice to know. I also
learned that men like fresh meat. I posted my profile on a
Wednesday, and before the week was out I was flooded with requests
from an amazing array of men all dying to meet me. However, this
avalanche slowed to a trickle by the second week. I was a leftover
by then.
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite note was from the married French
businessman who comes to the States only once a month and is always
looking for a ``good time.'' I could practically hear his smooth
French accent seeping through his message. Candace Bushnell's
infamous ``Sex in the City'' gals would have jumped at this one,
but I decided to pass on the idea of Internet dating in the fast
lane.
</P>
<P>
   I did meet some nice guys through Match.com. I met a very funny
advertising executive who took me to swank restaurants and hip
parties. However, when the repartee ran down, so did our
relationship. I also met a sweet, shy real estate lawyer who sent
me flowers and took me to sci-fi book festivals. Then I met
possibly the nicest guy of all, a nice homebody who still lived in
his parents' neighborhood, organized community events, and loved
sushi and going fishing with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I couldn't possibly consider him because he seemed
too normal. This may be one of the bigger mistakes in my brief
online dating career. We're all looking for Prince Charming, when
sometimes the Duke of York can make you just as happy. Now I know
that the happy couples who met online saw through all the purple
prose and looked for the real people behind the profiles. I also
learned you have to do the same thing in the offline world, too,
with almost everyone you know.
</P>
<P>
   In the end what I learned from my online dating experience was
the comforting knowledge that women pushing 30 can still meet nice
guys. I also found out that women pushing 30 can meet enough online
jerks, wise guys, philanderers and weirdos to make Ally McBeal's
social life look normal.
</P>
<P>
   Online dating, if you know what you're getting into, can be an
interesting week, if not a lifelong commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
