<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft Office 2000 evaluated in depth
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The inside scoop on the latest version of Microsoft Office,
released last week, is available in the July issue of PC World. An
article examines Office 2000's strengths and weaknesses. One major
weakness the magazine found is that complex Web pages made with
Office 2000 often can't be viewed by other browser applications,
such as Netscape Navigator. The good news, according to the
magazine, is that Office 2000 will recognize documents and
spreadsheets made in earlier versions.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue of PC World, there's a buyer's guide that
lists recommendations for everything from computers to printers to
software. Among the magazine's recommendations are the Dell
OptiPlex GX1p 500 as the best desktop computer; the Quantex M400 C
as the best budget desktop; the Dell Latitude CPi A366XT as the
best laptop; and the MaxTech XPV56P NetPacer as the best modem.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   With the PalmPilot becoming increasingly commonplace, there are
scores of new software packages for this hand-held computer. You
can now use the PalmPilot to organize your thoughts, write outlines
and track travel expenses. Most of the Palm applications are
available online directly from developers. Here's a look at three
popular programs:
</P>
<P>
   _ Quicksheet, which retails for $50, lets you create
spreadsheets on a PalmPilot and export them to Excel. You can also
export Excel spreadsheets to the PalmPilot through Quicksheet.
</P>
<P>
   _ ThoughtMill, which retails for $18, lets you organize projects
that involve multiple tasks over time.
</P>
<P>
   _ BrainForest is an outliner. Retailing for about $50, this
program lets you create and export to your desktop sophisticated
outlines.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that, if you have the right plug-in, the Web is a
great way to listen to the radio? Dozens of sites now stream live
radio broadcasts. One of the recent additions to this genre is
Webradio.com. Through a Java-based technology, the site offers
access to 27 radio stations that are broadcast via the Internet.
The great thing about Webradio.com is that you don't need a plug-in
such as RealPlayer to listen to the site's stations. You'll find
Webradio.com at www.webradio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
