</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWFLASH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FOR KIDS: Evidence of brutality
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peacekeepers in Kosovo believe that large numbers of Kosovar
Albanians were brutally treated by Serbs. Officials estimate that
at least 10,000 people were killed in Serb attacks on the province
in Yugoslavia during the last three months. Troops found torture
equipment and graves with many bodies buried together. They also
heard violent stories from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Now the peacekeepers are afraid that the Kosovars will take
revenge by hurting Serb residents and Serb holy sites. The
peacekeepers will try to protect the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Kosovo, a part of Yugoslavia, are ethnically and
religiously different from the Serbs. The Kosovar Albanians want
their independence from the government of Yugoslavia, which is run
by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Koreas plan to meet
</P>
<P>
   Talks between rival countries North Korea and South Korea are
scheduled to begin today in Beijing, China. Wealthy South Korea has
promised 200,000 tons of fertilizer to poorer North Korea. In
exchange, North Korea must let families who were separated by war
nearly 50 years ago return to the South. Floods and drought have
devastated North Korea's farms since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the talks would actually happen. The two
countries fired on each other in the Yellow Sea last week over
fishing rights. Two North Korean warships were sunk.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean Peninsula was divided into Communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea in 1945. Their border is the world's most
heavily armed, with nearly 2 million troops on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Respect your teacher
</P>
<P>
   If you live in Louisiana and your parents don't make you say
``yes, sir'' and ``yes, ma'am'' to adults, the state will. A bill
is about to be signed into law that will require public school
students to answer their teachers with those respectful phrases.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the ``sir'' and ``ma'am'' bill requires only elementary
school students to use the terms. Higher grades will be phased in
one year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier versions, the bill was even stricter. It would have
forced students to stand every time a principal entered the room,
and teachers would have addressed students as ``Mr.'' and ``Ms.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
