<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ While in our nation's capital, I
made it a point to visit the Smithsonian Aeronautics and Space
Museum to pay my respects to the inventor of the artificial heart.
That's where you can view his airplane hanging from the ceiling,
the Spirit of St. Louis. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. This week: Alan Greenspan
suggested productivity gains from computers may be coming to an
end. In the next century, will he be remembered as we now recall
Henry Ellsworth, commissioner of patents, who in 1843 spoke of the
``arrival of that period when human improvement must end''?
(Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Since my days on the outside
are assuredly numbered, I've decided to confess and throw myself on
the mercy of public opinion before they come to take me away. It's
not a pretty story, but it needs to be told. (Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ Vicki Marsh Kabat is on vacation for several
weeks. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ Half of all lightning bolts hit the ground at more
than one place. I learned that after spending a week staring into
trees and trying to figure the path of the lightning bolt that
struck my house. I gave this up as an idle exercise. It seemed to
have been everywhere, all at once. It hit the place like a bomb.
(Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
