r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A22-COX     06-21 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: As recent transplants to Texas, we have two questions. A
friend who lives in Colorado recently had a baby. Her husband is a
University of Texas graduate. Where can I go in Austin to buy
infant/toddler clothes with UT logos _ hats, T-shirts, sweatshirts,
jackets, etc.? What is the rhyme or reason (if any) to the numbers
and letters used on Texas license plates? _ D.R.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: License plate numbers are allocated to Texas counties in
blocks. There is no discernible pattern to the allocation, although
the Texas Department of Transportation keeps records of where the
plates are. The current system (as of fall 1998) is letter, number,
number, letter, letter, letter; the previous, letter, letter
letter, number, number, letter. No vowels are assigned on these
regular issue plates, so about 12 million combinations are
possible, says Texas DOT's Mike Viesca. These numbers should keep
Texans in license plates until 2004 or 2006. Another difference on
the new plates? The Texas flag is on the right, not the left of the
sequence. For your friend's little Longhorn, pick up all things UT
at Bevo's Bookstore in Dobie Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find out how to purchase Thurber bricks. They
were used in a piece of the flooring at the new airport. My wife's
maiden name is Thurber and we visited Thurber earlier this year. We
would like to obtain a brick for each grandkid. _ J. Sturm
</P>
<P>
   A: Wish I could unearth one or more for you. These pavers were
taken up when Congress Avenue was refurbished years ago. At the
time the City sold some bricks ($5 a pop as I recall) and stored
others. None are for sale currently. The bricks are called Thurber
because they were manufactured in Thurber in the northwest corner
of Erath County (west of Fort Worth). Named for New Yorker H.K.
Thurber, it began as a company coal mining town. The brick plant
opened in 1897 and closed in 1930. An interesting Thurber-ism? It
was one of the first cities with electricity _ in 1895. The
remaining pavers will show up in various city projects like the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a little weather watch radio that picks up continuous
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration weather reports,
and we can get the same thing on cable TV with graphics. Why isn't
the same thing broadcast over one (or several) radio stations with
the same call letters all over the country? Driving through
Oklahoma years ago we were warned of an approaching tornado on our
weather radio. But car radios are more powerful, so using
conventional radio for continuous weather information seems to make
safety sense. _ John N.
</P>
<P>
   A: The National Weather Service has investigated using AM bands
as well as parts of FM bands for NOAA radio, but ``there is not
enough space on these bands to send all the information out
specific to each area and ensure none of the broadcasts interfered
with each other,'' says Larry Eblen, NWS warning and coordination
meteorologist. Now, when you pick up weather information on weather
radio, it is applicable to your area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend recently sent an article about the Joan of Arc TV
special with a note asking if I knew that Joan was really not from
``Arc.'' He said that in fact there is no ``Arc'' in France, and
that her name was actually Jeanne Darc, which in time became Jeanne
d'Arc and eventually Jeanne of Arc. _ John N.
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a town called Arc in France (just east of Dijon) so
the appellation may be based on the place, hometown to father
Jacques d'Arc. However, says Mary Lou Gibson, columnist for
``Catholic Spirit,'' names were also based on occupation. Jeanne's
father, a peasant farmer, could have been a good archer (arc means
bow in French). The saint is also known as ``la Pucelle,'' the
virgin or maid.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My VCR malfunctioned and did not tape the final leg of the
Triple Crown. Is there any place to purchase a copy of the
television broadcast? Is there a viewer who has a copy I can copy?
Help! _ K. Gray
</P>
<P>
   A: A viewer may pop up, but if not, contact Belmont Park to
purchase a copy _ $25 per race for any at the 430-acre site. Lemon
Drop Kid pulled off an exciting victory. Owned and operated by the
New York Racing Commission, Belmont Park racetrack is the largest
in the country. The track is 1.5 miles long and the grandstand, at
1,266 feet, is longer than the Empire State building is tall. Races
are often held in front of capacity crowds (85,000 fans).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have cotton baby dresses (circa 1938) and woolen sweaters
ready for storage. Where can I find acid free tissue paper and
boxes? Also, is there something (not moth balls) that I can include
in the packaging that will help keep down the musty odor? _ J.
Harris
</P>
<P>
   A: Pick up acid-free boxes and paper at The Container Store.
Consider also purchasing zippered storage containers. Clean clothes
can be free of insect larvae if placed in strong sunlight for one
to two hours, spun in a dryer for approximately 45 minutes or
popped in the freezer for a few days . You be the judge of which is
correct for the item and the fabric. Place the clothes in the paper
and then the zippered storage bag to protect from moths and
silverfish. Keeping fresh air out is important. Many people find
the repellent cedar an acceptable odor. Oil of cedar is available
at many hardware stores. Other herbal treatments that do not
wrinkle noses? Lavender, rosemary or lemon grass.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreigstatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
