<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Posting Ten Commandments is a cynical non-solution
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even God can be absent-minded. God forgot _ just flat forgot _
to clue Moses to the 11th Commandment: Thou shalt not bow down to
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Because the deity was woolgathering way back then, the House of
Representatives could vote the other day to have public schools
post the Ten Commandments as a way to cool youth murder while
giving firearms a bye. And never mind that the one thing the eight
boy shooters had in common in the schoolhouse bloodbaths of the
last two years was that it was no trick for them to get guns.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the NRA has tutored us, guns don't cause massacres, boys
do.
</P>
<P>
   Surely only a cynic would suspect any relationship between the
vote and the fact that, as Public Campaign reports, the NRA spent
$15.5 million funding federal candidates, parties and politics
since 1991. Or that, as Common Cause points out, $8.4 million of
that went just to congressional candidates _ and 78 percent of that
to Republicans, who provided the bulk of the bipartisan votes to
substitute pseudo gun controls for the real ones the Senate had
adopted and then to scrap new controls altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt would be even more cynical to note that most members
who piously voted to install the Ten Commandments in public schools
know perfectly well the proposal violates church-state separation.
The Supreme Court has said so clearly.
</P>
<P>
   This is the old political trick of tossing a bone to a confused
public and then blaming an arrogant judiciary when judges, as they
will have no conscionable alternative to doing in this case, snatch
it away.
</P>
<P>
   The House neatly dodged the question of which Ten Commandments.
The versions held sacred by Jews, Catholics and most Protestants
have large areas of overlap but are subtly different in
particulars. Some of the differences have serious theological
implications that may strike the superficially religious as
unimportant but are precisely the specifics by which, cumulatively,
real faith is defined.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, many religious Americans do not subscribe to the
Ten Commandments. The commandments' principles, for instance, are
imbedded in the Koran but are not separately listed as in Torah or
the Christian bibles. There are 8 million Muslim Americans, and
their numbers are growing rapidly. Posting any version of the Ten
Commandments in public schools would, at best, distance Muslim kids
from their Christian and Jewish classmates. It's just that sort of
sectarian pestering that the Constitution's First Amendment tells
us to forgo.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution's Second Amendment, however, does not tell us
we can buy any gun any time anyone wants to. It does not bar the
kind of good-sense measures President Clinton has pressed for. None
of those would confiscate a single firearm or forbid a single
lawful citizen from owning firearms.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how many more school kids must be shot before
Congress wakes up and smells the gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
