<HEADER>
A3544 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWISTERS-CHASERS-COX     06-21 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWISTERS-CHASERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storm chasers rely on speed, high-tech gear
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boiling black and gray clouds have a sinister spin as they
slide east, hanging low over the lonesome West Texas outback.
Surface winds from the south feed the storm, kicking up dust as
they rush to the dark belly of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   A khaki-colored column of dust rises toward the cloud, slowly at
first, then with a great rush as if being sucked up with a
celestial Shop-Vac.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' shouts an excited Matt Crowther. ``This is it. A
tornado is imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bits of the Permian Basin soar skyward for 20 seconds or so.
Then as suddenly as it formed, the column begins to fall apart. The
updraft dies without ever demonstrating the rotation Crowther
expected. This will not be a tornado after all. That chance lost,
Crowther and his partners jump into an idling Honda CRV and speed
southeast, blasting down empty roads to again get ahead of the
strengthening storm, to again get a chance to witness the birth of
a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Crowther and his wife, Betsy Abrams, are storm chasers, driving
hundreds of miles a day to get beneath storms that send most folks
to their basements. Each May, they take time off from their jobs as
meteorologists at the Marietta-based Weather Channel and drive west
to the Plains. For two or three weeks they zigzag across the
flatlands between the Ozarks and the Rockies, grabbing meals at
convenience stores in places like Elida, N.M., and Alva, Okla. Well
after dark, they stop at budget motels in Lubbock, Texas, or Dodge
City, Kan., where, more often than not, they will find the rigs of
fellow storm chasers Nick Nicholson of Lilburn and Mike Phelps of
Paulding County.
</P>
<P>
   They all endure days of seat-numbing driving and the
frustrations of the uncertain pursuit of moments when skill and
luck collide like two weather fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Moments like a June afternoon in northwestern Kansas, where
Phelps watches a tornado three-quarters of a mile wide tear up the
rolling ranchland for half an hour. Or the night Nicholson is
driving north of Alva and sees a tornado moving through the
darkness, illuminated by lightning flashes. Or historic May 3, when
Abrams and Crowther spot nine tornadoes near Oklahoma City during
the outbreak that killed more than 40 people in Oklahoma and
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Christmas morning,'' says Phelps, who has seen 103
twisters in a decade of storm chasing. ``The heart is pounding, the
adrenalin is rushing.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling of victory, Phelps says, knowing that your
work in the past 24 hours has put you in the right place and the
right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also fear, wonder, excitement,'' Phelps says.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia storm chasers are members of a growing fraternity.
Every spring, longtime chasers say, a few more people are running
the back roads, some chasing a lifelong dream, many others inspired
by the the 1996 movie ``Twister.'' It is a trend that concerns
Crowther and other longtime storm chasers. More people chasing the
same storms increases the risks of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 way to get killed storm chasing is in an auto
accident,'' says Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, chasers say, it is common to see scores of cars
chasing the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon,'' says Crowther, ``you'll have to take a number
to get on a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no such troublesome crowds outside Portales, N.M., in
late May as hail rattles the vehicles making up a small caravan of
chasers. The line of vehicles includes the Honda hauling Abrams,
Crowther and friend Jim Williams; a battered 1986 Ford Taurus wagon
driven by Phelps; and Nicholson's 1992 Ford Explorer topped with
four antennas and an anemometer to measure wind speed.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's red four-door is the most elaborately outfitted of
the bunch. A custom-crafted console contains a citizens band radio
used to talk with other chasers, a short-wave radio and a scanner
to pick up police and weather reports. Like all chasers, Nicholson
also has a cell phone. There is a monitor on the dash linked to
instruments on the roof that give the temperature, wind speed and
wind direction. There is a dash mount for a camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   A laptop computer on a special mount in the back seat is linked
to the global positioning satellite system, allowing navigator Rick
Davis of Dalton to track the vehicle's position on a series of
detailed computer maps. Davis can also use the computer's DVD drive
to watch movies, including ``Twister,'' while traveling.
</P>
<P>
   While not everyone uses them to watch movies, every chaser totes
a laptop computer. Storm chaser science is done online in motel
rooms. Every night after checking in and every morning before
checking out, Crowther spends hours online collecting weather data
and running through forecasting models. Many others are doing the
same. The switchboard of the Super 8 motel in Lubbock was jammed
one May morning because so many chasers were logged on.
</P>
<P>
   A good forecast is critical to defining the playing field, and
Crowther ``is one of the best forecasters out there,'' says
Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Storm chasers use the morning to figure out where
tornado-producing supercell thunderstorms are likely to pop up by
late afternoon, and the rest of the day driving to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Once a storm chaser arrives in the area determined by the
forecast, science takes a back seat to experience and instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of art to chasing as well as science,'' says
Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   While Crowther may use his cell phone to call buddies at the
Weather Channel for radar information, most decisions are based on
what he sees in the skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do the driving when we're in chase mode,'' Abrams says.
``There is a reason for that. Matt is looking up out the window
instead of looking at the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowther and other chasers are able to pick out all sorts of
details in clouds that may be 50 to 75 miles away. Where most folks
just see the big picture, they see the brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been chasing since 1990,'' Crowther says, ``and I've
only learned storm structure in the last three years. You just have
to see storm after storm after storm after storm after storm after
storm. And in all different situations.''
</P>
<P>
   But all situations depend on the formation of big thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to get a supercell every day,'' says Crowther.
``If you get a supercell every day, you're going to get your share
of tornadoes.''
</P>
<P>
   While Crowther likes to gather data until checkout time and
beyond, Phelps gets an earlier start driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to get to the target area early,'' says Phelps, who
is also a meteorologist at the Weather Channel. ``Then you have
time to get more data and move out if the target area changes. The
key is to be right there when the storms go up.''
</P>
<P>
   But staking out a supercell doesn't guarantee you'll see a
tornado. Only 10 percent to 20 percent of supercells produce a
tornado, Crowther says.
</P>
<P>
   When looking for thunderstorms, forecasters seek what is called
the triple point: the collision of warm moist air, cooler dry air
and a destabilizing low pressure system that mixes it all up.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for tornadoes, however, requires additional
ingredients, and the most important is called wind shear.
</P>
<P>
   To get a storm turning, the winds need to be blowing in
different directions, and at progressively higher speeds, at
various levels of the atmosphere. Imagine a wind sock as the minute
hand on a clock. Ideally, the wind sock is on the four on the
surface, the eight at 10,000 feet and the 10 at 30,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Once a storm is rotating, it still needs another element to
spawn a twister: strong updrafts and downdrafts. And brisk surface
winds must be blowing into the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Many storms have all that, chasers say, but don't produce
tornadoes. The identification of the magic ingredient is the focus
of intense research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one of those great puzzles of nature that will
never be solved,'' says Phelps. ``And, frankly, that would suit me
just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   If science develops pinpoint forecasts for tornadoes, Phelps
says, ``storm chasing wouldn't be fun anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Storm chasers and their home pages:
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)www.earth.vol.com/(tilde)ngsc/jos.htm (homepage of
Dalton, Ga. stormchaser Rick Davis)
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)www.stormfury.com (homepage of Lilburn, Ga.
stormchaser Nick Nicholson)
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)www.storm-track.com/ (overview of storm chasing)
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)www.tornadoproject.com/ (overview of tornadoes)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
