<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, June 21, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FORENSIC-KOSOVO (San Francisco) _ Forensic science has always
had a ghoulish glamour, epitomized by TV's ``Quincy'' and ``Picket
Fences,'' as well as L.A.'s ``coroner to the stars,'' Dr. Thomas
Noguchi, who autopsied Marilyn Monroe, Janis Joplin and Robert
Kennedy. Now the world's forensic scientists are uniting to
investigate the grisliest crime scene of 1999: Kosovo. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ Frank Jordan has moved a step closer
to declaring his candidacy for mayor, hoping to unseat Willie
Brown, who trounced him in a run- off election 31/2 years ago.
Jordan, who served as mayor of San Francisco from 1992 to 1996, has
taken steps that allow him to solicit or accept campaign
contributions. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-KRON (San Francisco) _ What if one day you turned on your TV
and went to KRON Ch. 4, searching for the news of the day, and you
got stories about wacky strippers or fluffy lifestyle stories
instead of anchor Pete Wilson talking about Mayor Willie Brown?
Tabloidization is just one of many possible scenarios being spun
since the owners of KRON-TV and the San Francisco Chronicle last
week authorized the sale of ``all or some of'' Chronicle
Publishing. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-JUNETEENTH (Undated) _ The Random House publication
of Ralph Ellison's ``Juneteenth'' is Ellison's vision according to
John Callahan, an Ellison scholar, his literary executor and
friend. Callahan has carefully pared Ellison's unfinished
1,500-page manuscript into a trim, neatly structured 354-page
novel. And, he chose the title. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DAVINCI-HORSE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Art and history will collide in
two weeks when an exact replica of a 24-foot bronze horse
envisioned by Leonardo da Vinci is donated to Italians from America
and shipped from J.F.K. International Airport to Malpenso Airport
outside of Milan. By DENNIS YUSKO.
</P>
<P>
   SHANIA-TWAIN (Saint Regis Falls, N.Y.) _ The Pepsi Arena in
Albany _ 185 miles to the south _ may be the closest country-pop
music superstar Shania Twain gets to her vast Adirondack estate
here. Twain, who was in town for a sold-out concert at the Pepsi
Saturday, and her husband-producer Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange have
vacated the North Country estate after an environmental controversy
and put it up for sale for $7.5 million. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-PROFILE-AUTHOR (Undated) _ Author Helen Fielding hates
having to keep answering the same dumb question: Is she Bridget
Jones, her most popular creation? It's just so obvious she's not _
though she is funny, sexy, single, British and over 30 (well, 40).
She's the author of the surprise bestseller, ``Bridget Jones's
Diary.'' By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-CAMP (Becket, Mass.) _ Dancers from many nations will be
converging on the bucolic grounds of Jacob's Pillow in Becket,
Mass., this summer. As they share the diversity of their cultures
and traditions through performances, workshops, lectures and
demonstrations, they will also be celebrating the universality of
the creative force. By TRESCA WEINSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS (Undated) _ No battery, no electricity? No problem, at
least not if you have the Freeplay brand of radio. The device,
seemingly designed to appeal to Y2K phobics and boaters, operates
without the need for external AC power or a disposable battery.
Instead, it runs on solar energy or via wind-up power. By STEVE
BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-CHINA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Blue willow ware employs a
chinoiserie design in the decoration of ceramics, by transfer
printing in a blue underglaze. English potter Thomas Minton is the
reputed inventor of the blue and white willow porcelain dating to
around 1780. It's believed to be the oldest blue and white pattern
made and is probably the most famous. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-DIAMOND-CREEK (Albany, N.Y.) _ In 1966, at age 46, Al
Brounstein he bought an 80-acre mountain plot in Napa Valley,
Calif., to pursue his dream of creating a vineyard of superior
quality. Three decades and three years later, Brounstein is the
proud owner of one of the most highly regarded wineries in the
world, Diamond Creek. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   X-GAMES (Undated) _ Here come the X Games, fashioned by ESPN,
the all-sports network that spawned the idea in 1993 to create an
Olympics-modeled competition for alternative sports and then gave
birth to the event in 1995. But beneath all of the
anti-establishment aura emitted by the X Games lies a traditional
reality: money. By MARK FAINARU-WADA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RATTO-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ The group of NFL
coach/emperors is a small one, and a well-aged one at that. After
all, the twin skills of wisdom and leverage take time to nurture
and muscle. Kind of makes you wonder how Jon Gruden did it so
quickly, especially where he does it, and for whom. Gruden just
finished his fifth or sixth or seventh minicamp (hey, who counts?)
as the head coach of the Oakland Raiders this past weekend. By RAY
RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I was 11 years old, back when
I thought I could think a fish on the hook, and we were fishing in
a small boat in the shallows of Monterey Bay, just off Capitola,
Calif. I lost my rod to the bottom of the ocean and cringed when I
pointed out this sad state of affairs to my Dad. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Peering at a photo of my father
and me that was taken last autumn, a good friend said, ``God, you
look so much like your dad, it's scary.'' knew what she meant. The
resemblance isn't scary-frightening, like ``Silence of the Lambs,''
it's scary-breathtaking, like the first plunge in a roller coaster.
By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The bulk of political
operatives and commentators complained about George W. Bush's
vagueness on national issues as he opened his campaign for the
Republican nomination for president last week. The governor was
taken to task even though conventional political wisdom prescribes
that a front-running candidate keep policy options open so as not
to antagonize committed backers or close the door to attracting
other supporters. By BY HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-COLLEGE (Albany, N.Y.) _ It took a real tussle for
women to get into The Citadel, and initially their presence on
campus caused what a country boy might call hell among the
yearlings. The first one, Shannon Faulkner, bowed out quickly. I
felt for Shannon when she decided she'd had enough, but I also
realized she'd exercised a lot more sense than I had. I actually
finished my first year of college as one of the worst specimens
ever to disgrace a corps of cadets. By MIKE JARBOE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
