<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-CO     06-21 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The injustice of selective enforcement
 &HT;    (For release June 6, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One of society's great problems is selective
enforcement. Rules that were meant for everyone often are applied
only to certain people.
</P>
<P>
   When first I saw in the crime report of my Sunday newspaper that
four people in a Miami district, within five hours of each other on
a Wednesday afternoon, had been arrested for drinking from cans of
beer in public, I chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   What made it amusing was that the brand of beer each was
drinking curiously was reported in the newspaper story: one with a
can of Mickey's malt liquor and three with cans of Old Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to that huge market share of Budweiser, I
asked myself in a jesting moment. Doesn't anyone get busted for
slurping a Bud in public?
</P>
<P>
   As the day went on, I kept coming back to that crime report. The
humor I first saw in it was waning. Some things about it were
beginning to bother me.
</P>
<P>
   The area of crime-weary Miami where all this took place is
Coconut Grove, a trendy section of the city that always has
positioned itself as being on a page different from the rest of the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Its central section is awash with watering holes, many of them
outdoors, or with outdoor patios. The streets of the central
section are lined with sidewalk cafes. Yuppie-types eat dinner in
these places, as well as down beer and wine at the least. It's sold
as a fun place to be, to party _ but apparently only in designated
areas and, perhaps, only with certain brands or, this is where I
worry, with certain people.
</P>
<P>
   No insult intended, but Old Milwaukee is not exactly a
premium-priced beer; folks who need to watch their pennies more
closely are most likely to be buying it rather than, say, Michelob
or Heineken.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut Grove's central section stirs at mid-morning and goes on
well into the night, in fact into the early morning _ loud, brash
and often drunk. So why were four people, all on the nearest
fringes of the party neighborhood, singled out for drinking beer in
public on a Wednesday afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   It's not difficult to figure out. These were suspicious types,
eh? All were over 40. They likely were not dressed well; in fact,
their clothes probably were a bit grubby. And they were drinking
Old Milwaukee, not the premium stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for society, Miami newspapers some two decades ago
stopped indentifying most arrests by race so I have no idea of
whether the arrested were black or white, but I can guess. Or, if
they were white, they conceivably were drifter-types.
</P>
<P>
   A guy with a coat and tie sipping a Bud in a 7-Eleven parking
lot is less likely to get busted than a disheveled guy guzzling an
Old Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Selective enforcement has been a disease of police work
everywhere. I don't know how we're ever going to overcome it, but
it continues to be a huge irritant to resident minorities and
indigents, as well it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Until these four balmy beer busts came along, a most vivid
equivalent is a still-held belief that until recent decades, blacks
had to have a special identification to be on the streets of Miami
Beach after dusk, there being a law that said so.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it was a nasty example of selective enforcement.
Indeed, there was a law but it required all persons involved in any
tourism business (that includes cleaning slop out of hotel
kitchens) to have an official identification card with photo and
fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the selective enforcement came in. While whites
rarely were stopped by police and asked to produce their ID, blacks
were _ so much so that it has been passed down to this very day as
a law written solely against blacks.
</P>
<P>
   There probably is a similar one in Miami about drinking in
public, but it obviously depends on what you're drinking and who
you are.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
