<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-COLLEGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE CADET'S LOSING BATTLE WITH MILITARY SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE JARBOE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nancy Ruth Mace recently became the first woman
to graduate from The Citadel, the military college in South
Carolina that prides itself on being where the tough-as-nails go to
get a little bit tougher.
</P>
<P>
   It took a real tussle several years ago for women to get into
The Citadel, and initially their presence on campus caused what a
country boy might call hell among the yearlings. The first one,
Shannon Faulkner, had a shelf life as a ``knob'' (a Citadel
freshman) of just a matter of days before she bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   I felt for Shannon when she decided she'd had enough. But I also
realized she'd exercised a lot more sense than I had. I actually
finished my first year of college as one of the worst specimens
ever to disgrace a corps of cadets.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons far too complicated to explain _ reasons that
included a war, financial aid, a war, heavy recruiting, a sweet
deal involving ``only'' six years of reserves duty, a war and a war
_ I began my post-high school academic career at Pennsylvania
Military College (PMC). People who know me have a hard time
believing this, but it's a fact.
</P>
<P>
   PMC was a dying school in the hard-knocks town of Chester, Pa.,
that prided itself on nearly 150 years of turning out young
warriors. Many of them had died on battlefields, from Gettysburg to
the Argonne to the Mekong Delta.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more were dying while I was there. We had muffled-drum
formations in the morning every time a grad lost his life in
Vietnam, and listened to stories from the professors and
upperclassmen who had known him.
</P>
<P>
   I can't speak for how things are in military colleges these
days. But I can safely assume that it's no picnic, just as it was
no picnic when I went to one.
</P>
<P>
   There was suffering aplenty at PMC, at least on my part.
Push-ups were the penalty for most transgressions against this odd
society. There was an entire book of ridiculous factoids about the
college to memorize, and there was the devil to pay if you drew a
blank when asked to recite any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the bells in Old Main dedicated to? Albie Filoreto
(whoever the heck he was).
</P>
<P>
   How's the cow? Sir, she walks, she talks, she's full of chalk,
sir; the lacteal fluid extracted from the female of the bovine
species is highly prolific to the Nth degree, sir.
</P>
<P>
   What's the unloaded weight of an M-14 rifle? Sir, 9.5 pounds,
sir.
</P>
<P>
   So my nights were spent filling my head with claptrap like that
while my books gathered dust, and I slept off all the push-ups
during my professors' lectures.
</P>
<P>
   There were punishments for every infraction imaginable; I was
issued demerits for having too many books on my shelves, and once
was forced to squat endlessly, holding a fire extinguisher in my
outstretched arms, for the crime of having cut across a corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally the punishment was the officially banned practice
of ``bracing,'' which basically involved pushing your shoulder
blades together, pulling your chin in as far as possible, and in
effect turning yourself into a twitching, sweating human ramrod.
Quite painful _ especially bad on a simmering day, standing in the
latrine, with hot water turned on in all the showers.
</P>
<P>
   The coup de grace to my sad-sack career came in June, when
during a particularly giddy moment (due to, no doubt, a few too
many push-ups) I dropped a water balloon on the head of a yahoo who
was serving on some sort of pointless guard detail. Push-ups were
not punishment enough in this case; I had to put on a nice, tight
West Point-type heavy wool jacket and slacks and march for hours
(15, over the course of several days) up and down a sidewalk in the
stifling, smelly Chester air carrying a rifle (M-14, unloaded, 9.5
pounds, sir).
</P>
<P>
   I emerged, somehow, from my freshman year strong as hell
(push-ups), tough as hell (push-ups), mad as hell (push-ups) and
with a grade point average that didn't even average out to 1 (more
push-ups). And colleges tend to frown on GPAs that begin with zero
before the decimal point. But I could put one heck of a shine on a
pair of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   So I left Pennsylvania Military College, complete with an
honorable discharge from the Army Reserve. And off I went on the
Grateful Dead tour for a few years, where it took me a lot fewer
push-ups to learn one heck of a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Hoo-ah.
</P>
<P>
   As for PMC, despite the jillion years of ``proud tradition,'' it
folded up like a waterlogged tent as soon as I fled the front gates
and was renamed Widener College (now Widener University). If in
some small part I was responsible for its demise, I have indeed
done a wee bit of good in this world.
</P>
<P>
   And congratulations on your Citadel diploma, Nancy Ruth. Too bad
you missed the Grateful Dead tours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Jarboe is a copy editor at the Albany Times Union, P.O.
Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
