<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GHOST OF REPUBLICANS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The bulk of political operatives and commentators
complained about George W. Bush's vagueness on national issues as
he opened his campaign for the Republican nomination for president
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was taken to task even though conventional
political wisdom prescribes that a front-running candidate keep
policy options open so as not to antagonize committed backers or
close the door to attracting other supporters. That's where Bush
finds himself as he scans the field of actual and potential
contenders for the nomination, who, apart from himself, are several
but unimpressive. His critics and observers think that Bush is
simply pushing the tactic too far for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   I disagree. For my part, the man who is the Republicans' great
hope for recapturing the White House has already said too much. And
it is scary.
</P>
<P>
   There was the New York Times report that Bush, in a campaign
swing through New Hampshire, which holds the first presidential
primary, made what every alert citizen should regard as a most
telling political commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Bush said that if elected,'' the Times wrote, ``his first
two priorities would be pushing through a tax cut and increasing
military spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Now some might wish to consider these priorities as no more than
conventional oratory intended to assure people that they could eat
their cake and have it. Another famous promise was to ``put a
chicken in every pot.'' It was made during the hard times of the
Great Depression in the '30s, when chickens were scarce, and so
were pots.
</P>
<P>
   Soberly assessed, raising defense spending while cutting taxes
is a prescription for national misfortune. If Bush meant what he
said, it would undo the unprecedented economic prosperity the
American people have the good luck to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   You only have to look back to the election in which Ronald
Reagan was campaigning for the same job. When he advanced that same
notion, his then primary opponent, George Herbert Walker Bush,
described it as ``voodoo economics.''
</P>
<P>
   George the Elder later abandoned that acute description in his
successful effort to become Reagan's running mate, going on to
serve as vice president for eight years, and president for four.
</P>
<P>
   George the Younger, however, should attend to what his father at
first said, rather than to what he later did on behalf of political
ambition. Those early words were entirely on the mark, as
subsequent facts and figures conclusively showed.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the madness of raising spending while reducing
revenue, the Reagan presidency's legacy was huge deficits in the
budget and trade, not to mention a weakened dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The chief economist for Merrill Lynch and Co., Donald
Straszheim, was prophetic in 1988 when he said the immediate impact
on the president who came after Reagan would be ``a one-term
presidency. ... On the budget, all the easy cuts have been made. On
the tax side, the public has had hammered home to them over the
last few years the message that tax rates always go down, they
never go up.''
</P>
<P>
   When, as Reagan's successor, George the Elder subsequently felt
compelled to contradict his pledge not to raise taxes (the famous
``read my lips'' statement) he, indeed, wound up serving only one
term.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the act that probably cost him his second term, also began
the process that enabled the nation from then on and through the
Clinton presidency, to go from enormous budget deficits to
surpluses. From that has flowed the present long-lived prosperity
that also has shaped the country's improved circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, it is highly cavalier for Bush W. Bush to even
trifle with the notion of reviving the Reagan policy, all in a bid
for votes. He should remember that Reagan managed in seven years to
almost triple the national debt that he inherited from the 39 chief
executives who had served before him. Now that was history-making.
</P>
<P>
   Another consequence of implementing two basically contradictory
policies was to turn the United States, which had been the world's
biggest creditor nation, into the biggest debtor.
</P>
<P>
   George the Younger needs to reflect on the ghosts of the
not-so-distant past. He is halfway right in his policy: Kosovo
revealed serious deficiencies in the U.S. defense capacities. Dicey
relations with Russia and China call for reassuring the country
that it remains an effective deterrent power.
</P>
<P>
   Recent history should have educated George W. Bush, as well as
the public, to recognize that platitudes about tax cuts, always
popular, are tempting but false illusions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should do his candidacy a great favor by revisiting his
priorities, and explain to the people how these policies would work
today when they failed so miserably a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
