A3662 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHIP OFF THE OLD BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Peering at a photo of my father and me that was
taken last autumn, a good friend said, ``God, you look so much like
your dad, it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew what she meant. The resemblance isn't scary-frightening,
like ``Silence of the Lambs,'' it's scary-breathtaking, like the
first plunge in a roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   After all, boys are supposed to be a chip off the old male
block; girls are supposed to look like their moms. As Billy Bigelow
sang in ``Carousel,'' a daughter should be ``a kind of neat and
petite little tintype of her mother _ what a pair!''
</P>
<P>
   If my dad sang, it would be about how his daughter looks like
him in drag.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, I tend to forget the physical similarity because I
think and behave so much like my mom that it often feels as if she
is standing right behind me instead of in Indiana, 2,000 miles
away. Every cell and nerve ending in my body tells me I am her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   What, besides my face, tells me I am my father's daughter?
</P>
<P>
   Products of our Eisenhower-Kennedy times, Dad and I were never
free to be best pals. We didn't go fishing or shoot hoops or build
dog houses together because dads and daughters just didn't do
things like that back then.
</P>
<P>
   Gender roles were clearly delineated, especially in the cookie
cutter suburbs. There was little cross-pollination.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I think about how lonely my dad had to be all those
years in a house of females (my mom, my sister and me). Although he
often joked about ``living in a nylon jungle,'' he never complained
or sulked or gave the slightest hint that _ once in awhile _ he
wished he'd had a son.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was a little easier for him because he never knew that
sort of fathers-playing-catch-with-sons companionship in his own
childhood. My Grandpa Salter went to work in the coal mines of
southern Indiana when he was 9 years old and pretty much stayed in
them until black lung disease killed him at 63.
</P>
<P>
   At least times changed enough for my dad to reap some benefit
from women's liberation. My sister's youngest daughter came along
after Title IX and the relaxation of gender lines. A photo of her,
at age 5, watching intently as my dad shows how to bait a fishhook,
never fails to bring tears to my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Dad and I ever came to pal-ing around was when I was
a senior at Purdue and his business had him on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Every few weeks he'd come up to West Lafayette and take me out
for dinner at a place called Sarge Biltz's. I'd order a Manhattan,
he'd get a beer and we'd both have filet mignon.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember a single conversation we shared during those
meals, but when I see us in my head, we're having a hell of a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   A man friend once hazarded an observation that he meant as a
compliment but wasn't sure I'd take as such: ``You give off a lot
of male energy.''
</P>
<P>
   I like to think that quality is the subtler companion to my face
_ evidence that I am my father's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Feminist though I've been since age 19, I have always felt at
ease in the company of men. I like drinking with them and trading
stories, laughing and making them laugh.
</P>
<P>
   More times than I can remember, I've looked up in the middle of
a delightful social occasion and realized I was the only woman at
the table. Partly this is because I spent about a decade covering
sports for a living. But I believe that it is also partly my dad's
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow _ maybe by modeling masculinity in such a healthy,
approachable way _ he imparted the joy of being ``one of the boys''
to me, his elder daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Dad also managed to pass along some of his ferocious work ethic
and his unflagging curiosity about the world and its current
events.
</P>
<P>
   From him I learned how to shine my shoes properly, wash a car
and whistle whole songs, not just a bar or two. Because he taught
me better, I never leave the garden hose pulled out and lying in
the yard, and I don't let the gas tank of my car get down to where
``it's running on fumes.''
</P>
<P>
   When I was little and my dad was young, I never doubted that he
loved me. But, times being what they were and he being a fairly
typical American male, he wasn't all that verbal about it.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, has changed with the years. Now when we talk, after
exchanging headlines and offering our solutions to international
and domestic crises, my dad always signs off the same way: ``I love
you.''
</P>
<P>
   I can see his face every time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
