<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUE-CHINA-ART-HNS &LR;      06-21 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-CHINA-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE WILLOW WARE STEEPED IN TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database; Web address is CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Blue willow ware employs a chinoiserie design in
the decoration of ceramics, by transfer printing in a blue
underglaze. English potter Thomas Minton is the reputed inventor of
the blue and white willow porcelain dating to around 1780.
</P>
<P>
   It's believed to be the oldest blue and white pattern made, was
copied from early Chinese patterns, and is probably the most famous
blue and white pattern made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the blue denim of its day,'' said Shelia Chefetz, owner
of the Country Dining Room Antiques in Great Barrington, Mass. ``It
was heavily copied. Just about every factory in England made a
version of blue willow. One factory alone made more than 40
variations. In the 1930s and 1940s it was in almost every Chinese
restaurant around the world. You could even get willow-ware dishes
in soap boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not uncommon to mix and match pieces from different
factories. But the essential components are a stylized willow tree,
a Chinese temple, a bridge with three figures on it, a little
house, a boat, a distant island and two turtle doves.
</P>
<P>
   Several fanciful stories have been associated with the pattern
to explain its significance.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Antiquing for Dummies,'' by antiques specialists
and dealers Ron Zoglin and Deborah Shouse (IDG Books 1999), the
pattern is based on an ancient Chinese legend and there are some
200 variations.
</P>
<P>
   The most common is about a Mandarin's daughter who falls deeply
in love and runs away with her lover.
</P>
<P>
   In their escape, the couple runs across the bridge to hide in a
small house until they can escape by a small boat to a distant
island the next day.
</P>
<P>
   After several years the Mandarin finally catches up with the
couple, and just as they are about to be beaten to death, they turn
into a pair of turtle doves to live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   During the Victorian era, you could also find willow ware in
black, yellow and green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willow ware is relatively well priced because so much of it
was made,'' Chefetz said. ``You can pick willow ware up at good
prices, getting you more value for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   A 16- to 18-inch willow-ware platter costs approximately $365 to
$395. As with any antique, the price depends on age, condition and
rarity.
</P>
<P>
   To find out more about willow ware, visit the Web site
http://www.willowcollectors.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
