<SLUG> BC-DANCE-CAMP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE LINEUP FEATURES A WORLD OF DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRESCA WEINSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ At the end of the millennium, Jacob's Pillow
director Ella Baff has programmed a season of dance that shows just
how small the world has become.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers from the United States, Cuba, Brazil, Peru, Tibet,
China, Russia, Angola, Puerto Rico and Bosnia-Herzegovina will be
converging on the Pillow's bucolic grounds in Becket, Mass., this
summer. As they share the diversity of their cultures and
traditions through performances, workshops, lectures and
demonstrations they will also be celebrating the universality of
the creative force.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention is to bring a very wide view of dance to the
public,'' said Baff, who replaced former director Sali Ann
Kriegsman in the spring of 1998. ``For the people who come here and
for the artists themselves, it creates an atmosphere of cultural
exchange that's very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pillow's 67th season opens at 8 p.m. Wednesday with the
Brazilian dance/theater troupe Grupo Corpo. The Doris Duke Studio
Theatre opens its season on July 1 with Pepatian, presenting a new
work, ``Pasaporte,'' set to live salsa music.
</P>
<P>
   This year's schedule also includes works by modern American
masters Paul Taylor, Mark Morris and David Parsons, as well as
appearances by new sensations like dancer, juggler and illusionist
Michael Moschen and Irish-American choreographer Sean Curran. This
season the Pillow also emphasizes dance for families and children.
</P>
<P>
   The Pillow will present a number of pieces that Baff specially
commissioned for the festival. ``It's very exciting and very
anxiety-producing to commission new works,'' she said. ``You don't
know exactly what's going to happen. Sometimes collaborations that
look like marriages made in heaven fall apart. That's the roller
coaster part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   World premieres of commissioned work include Trisha Brown's
first dance that's set to a jazz score by composer and trumpeter
Dave Douglas; Doug Varone's ``Democracy,'' which draws inspiration
from Bauhaus art; and Ronald K. Brown's ``Water,'' a series of
contemporary rituals created in collaboration with a poet and
visual artist.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest tickets of the season is an exclusive,
Pillow-produced performance by prima ballerina Nina Ananiashvili
and principal dancers of the Bolshoi Ballet. ``This will not happen
anyplace else in the world,'' Baff said.
</P>
<P>
   Three works on the schedule a new evening-length work by Martha
Clarke, a new dance/theater piece by 33 Fainting Spells, and Jane
Comfort and Company's Bessie Award-winning ``Underground River''
were begun during residencies at the Pillow. ``Many things we end
up presenting had their very conception here,'' Baff said. ``It's
satisfying to see things grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Child-friendly companies appearing this summer include Teatro
Hugo and Ines, combining mime, dance and puppetry, and the
Harlem-based children's troupe Batoto Yetu, which creates dances
based on traditional African movement, song, and folktales. To
encourage more families to attend performances, the Pillow now has
2 p.m. matinees on both Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also trying to present more live music with dance,''
Baff said. ``The experience of live music with dance is so much
richer, and there's so much more to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of the performances on the schedule will be
accompanied by live music _ including the Cuban troupe Los
Munequitos De Matanzas and Indonesian-influenced compositions for
Empty Tradition/City of Peonies, which is inspired by Chinese dance
and Tai Chi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baff said 57,000 people visited Jacob's Pillow last season for
performances as well as free lectures, art and photography
exhibits, demonstrations, workshops, and Inside/Out performances on
the Pillow's outdoor stage. The Pillow's outreach also includes
year-round education programs at schools and a Web site,
www.jacobspillow.org, which will begin showing live dance clips
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite record-breaking ticket sales last year, the Pillow, like
most dance venues and dance companies, balances on a precarious
economic structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Pillow is healthy _ we have no debt and a small cash
reserve _ we are in great need,'' Baff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching the dance world since the Ford Foundation
started supporting dance in the 1960s, and dance still struggles.
For some people, it's a completely alien form. The effort the
Pillow makes to be informative and to provide a knowledge base in a
welcoming environment helps encourage people to enter into the
world of dance and come back for more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
