<HEADLINE>
CRANK IT UP: A RADIO FOR THE NEW MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No battery, no electricity? No problem, at least not if you've
got the Freeplay radio. The device, seemingly designed to appeal to
Y2K phobics and boaters, operates without the need for external AC
power or a disposable battery.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it runs on solar energy or via wind-up power. Turn the
crank on the back for 45 seconds and the AM/FM radio will run for
up to an hour; exposure to sunlight automatically switches the
power source from crank to solar. Equipped with jacks for an AC
adapter and headphone, the Freeplay comes in an impact-resistant
and splash-proof plastic case, in colors including black,
translucent blue and clear. It costs $100.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGING: Our favorite recent book, the one we keep on our desk
and on the back of the toilet for snippet reading, is ``What's In
an Age? Who Did What When, From Age 1 to 100,'' written by Andrew
Postman and illustrated by Nick Galifianakis.
</P>
<P>
   The author says not to use the book to bum yourself out by
comparing others' accomplishments with yours at particular ages.
Don't fret, for example, that the Steves (Jobs and Wozniak) were 21
when they introduced their first Apple computer or, as bitter
humorist Tom Lehrer noted, at age 37, ``When Mozart was my age, he
had been dead for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, simply read for fascination. Alfred Hitchcock was 60
when he made ``Psycho.'' Lee Harvey Oswald 24 when he assassinated
JFK. Leopold Stokowski signed a six-year conducting contract at age
94. And so on. Find the volume, for $10, in bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   CANDELABRA-CADABRA: A trio of wacky guys in Los Angeles (Matt
Mogol and the brothers Duffy and Seamus Culligan) have created
Aromapharmacy, or candles with names like popular drugs that are
packaged in amber glass jars resembling prescription-pill
containers.
</P>
<P>
   While there's no scientific evidence for the claims of magical
results, the makers say their candles will ``help remedy specific
conditions or set a desired mood.'' The four flavors are: Niagara,
``sexually charged (with) ylang-ylang and patchouli (and) ... an
aphrodisiac''; Valiumello, to ``soothe and relax ... using vanilla
and sandalwood''; Lozac, an ``antidepressant (with) sage and
geranium''; and Ritalert, alleged to ``help the mind stay alert and
focused'' with grapefruit and cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   The candles, which cost $15 each, can be ordered by visiting
http://www.aromapharmacy.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
