r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-ACTORS-LADN     06-21 2223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-ACTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER-GENERATED CHARACTERS MOVING TO FOREFRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Note use of italics in grafs 2 and 3) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; A lithe young Jack Nicholson cartwheels across
the screen, tucks into a somersault then explodes into an
eye-popping kung fu kick that catches a muscled-up Humphrey Bogart
across the chin, sending him sprawling over a table where three
gungans chat about the next ``Star Wars'' episode with a geriatric
Helen Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL START)This(ITAL END) is as good as it gets?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. But it (ITAL START)is(ITAL END) where movies
are heading in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Special-effects wizards have been using computers for some years
to create increasingly realistic images of creatures, places and
events that never existed in real life.
</P>
<P>
   But they really haven't had the digital tools that would allow
them to create compellingly lifelike, computer-generated characters
that are central to a film and can interact convincingly with live
actors and their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change _ and with it, the very fabric of acting
and movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is doing here is hinting at the immediacy of it and
the creativity of it,'' said Andre Bustanoby, visual effects
supervisor for Digital Domain, at a recent seminar on
motion-capture and related techniques at the American Film
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, a series of companies were showing off the powerful,
increasingly inexpensive tools they've created to capture human
motions and map them flawlessly to a computer-generated creature on
a screen and from there to a film.
</P>
<P>
   And they're far from the only ones out there trying to create
the new tools.
</P>
<P>
   Special effects pioneer Douglas Trumbull of ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' fame has been tinkering in his home studio in
Massachusetts' Berkshire Mountains with systems that will allow him
to plunk a live actor into a computer-generated set and costumes in
real time. Instead of ``blue-screening,'' where actors emote in
front of a blue or green background that is later replaced in
costly post-production, it all will be tied together at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtual set technology, to allow you to insert live
actors in real time,'' Trumbull said in a recent Los Angeles
appearance. ``It's not like laborious blue screening. All you need
to do is edit (the tape you generate).''
</P>
<P>
   What counts as a digital special effect and what is real already
are impossible to differentiate in many films, such as ``The Truman
Show,'' which was part of the annual Academy Awards nominations
``bake-off'' contest between special effects movies, said Tom
Atkin, executive director of the Visual Effects Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't even tell where the effects left off, they were
so seamless in that movie,'' Atkin said. ``And there will be more
and more work where, especially if it's not a science-fiction film,
you're not going to be able to tell. You'll see more and more
movies where you're not going to be able to spot huge effects work,
unless it's because of the plot.''
</P>
<P>
   In both ``The Mummy'' and ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' digital characters were strongly integrated in the films,
impossible to differentiate from live actors, and to some extent
judged just as harshly for their acting as were the humans.
</P>
<P>
   And soon enough, the powerful new tools being created by
Trumbull, companies at the AFI seminar and others will be available
to low-budget enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with other cheap digital technology and the
distribution power of the Internet, those newcomers will be able to
create and show a wide variety of new works, said Bustanoby, who
has worked on films such as ``Titanic'' and ``The Fifth Element.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's stuff on these desktops that a couple of years ago
cost 10 to 20 times as much,'' said Bustanoby. ``A lot more people
at home are going to be taking this technology and kicking (the
results) out on the Internet, where you've got a worldwide
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   And decreasing equipment costs, coupled with increasingly
powerful hardware and software, mean that digital special-effects
work is creeping into all kinds of areas where it previously hadn't
been because of cost, time and other considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two areas where I think there's great potential are the games
business and the Internet,'' said Atkin. ``I think over time, some
of our folks will get involved in the games business and see how we
can take our technology to those platforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The gaming business is exploding, with sales this year expected
to rival those of the movie business's domestic box office.
</P>
<P>
   And the machines that run the latest and greatest games, from
high-end PCs and Power Macs to next-generation gaming consoles from
Sega, Sony and Nintendo expected to hit U.S. stores in the next 18
months, are providing the kind of processing power that can rival a
DVD player's crisp and gorgeous graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Between the massive market and the amazing machines, game
developers are increasingly mixing digital creations and effects
together to liven up their interactive offerings.
</P>
<P>
   And you can expect to see more eye candy of all sorts on the
Internet, particularly as broadband technologies such as cable
modems and DSL give Joe and Jane Sixpack high-speed digital
connections that will support video quality close to that of
television.
</P>
<P>
   Combine those kinds of media with increasingly powerful computer
systems and software, creative writers, animators and directors and
new kinds of performers, and here's the kinds of fascinating new
cinematic techniques and experiences you can expect:
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL MAKEUP. Computers are being used to transform the way
performers look, making them appear older or younger or putting
them through digital transformations (such as turning into a
werewolf or alien) that otherwise might require excruciating hours
in the makeup chair each morning.
</P>
<P>
   With such digital techniques, it's pretty easy to make Helen
Hunt go from spritely to unsightly. And if the face of Jack has
gone slack, a digital tuck can have him looking better than any
Brazilian or Brentwood scalpel slinger could ever manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to create hyper-realistic kinds of characters,
digital actresses with close-ups where you can't tell it's
digital,'' said Mark Sager, vice president of research and
development at Pacific Title/Mirage, an effects house in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   His company had originally created technology designed to help
doctors in virtual surgery, Sager said. But the technology's
ability to virtually age or revivify someone on screen soon found
other applications in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sager said, about 80 percent of the people who watch scenes
generated by their software can't tell if the performer is digital.
In the future, the digital character will be indistinguishable from
a real person on screen.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER STUNTS, EVEN FOR OLD GUYS. Jackie Chan's mid-40s martial
arts pyrotechnics aside, most aging action stars will appreciate
the assist they'll soon routinely get in performing eye-popping
stunts, even if they're past their physical _ but not box-office _
prime. Think ``The Matrix'' on, believe it or not, steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a good actor, a good performance, you can leverage
that,'' said Bustanoby. ``Say someone is not as physical as they
were in their 20s _ they can still do stunts. At that point, the
palette is so much wider. I have new stories I want to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL CHARACTERS. ``The Phantom Menace'' and ``The Mummy'' are
two films that prominently feature a new kind of performer, the
digital actor.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, a human actor provided a living armature upon
which computer gurus constructed the digital character. Other new
technologies don't even require someone on screen, instead using an
off-screen performer's body movements to animate a digital
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like real camera-based media, but all the cameras are
virtual,'' said Dave Blackburn, president of Virtual Ventures, a
Manhattan Beach company that provides packages of computer hardware
and software to studios wanting to create those digital performers.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, an actor with 10 sensors attached to his main joints
makes various movements that are exactly mimicked by an animated
cactus in a pot on a nearby computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get it in real time and on the fly,'' Blackburn said.
``You can see if you get it the way you wanted it, and if you do it
wrong, it's easy to do it over.''
</P>
<P>
   The motion-capture computer systems he sells cost around $85,000
these days, a 10th or 20th of what they used to cost, and now it
comes with the software to do what was just being demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's a first blossoming of this kind of software,''
which will make it much easier for more companies to use the
technology, Blackburn said. In the past, they had to write their
own programs, a laborious process with no guarantee of success.
</P>
<P>
   The new power of these tools also means that digital performers
will increasingly have central roles in film, as opposed to the
peripheral roles of the digi-dinos in ``Jurassic Park'' or the
doomed crowds of ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Phantom Menace,'' for instance, director George Lucas has
created a computer-generated character named Jar Jar Binks. Jar Jar
may have annoyed the heck out of many critics and adult fans, but
the key is that people accept the digital construct as just another
performer, a peer of sorts with Liam Neeson and Ewan MacGregor.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``The Mummy,'' the mummy is completely digital for big
chunks of the film, said Seth Rosenthal, who worked on ``Phantom
Menace'' and ``The Mummy'' as a motion-capture supervisor for
Industrial Light &AMP; Magic, the George Lucas-owned special-effects
house in San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   Though both digital characters have limitations _ requiring in
the mummy's case some real-world workarounds _ that won't be the
case soon, Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short to medium term _ some people would debatably say
now _ it will be possible to make believable characters on film,''
Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   BRINGING BACK THE DEAD. At the Virtual Humans III conference
held last summer in Universal City, participants showed off digital
Dietrichs and W.C. Fieldses.
</P>
<P>
   Just as with the AFI demos, the Fields impersonator is strapped
to special sensors connected with a computer. As the impersonator
talks and moves, the sensors key actions by the digital Fields'
representation in real time, allowing the character to answer
questions and react to an audience.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the start, some say, as they excitedly talk
about a future where the computer skins they've created are
inhabited more fully by a virtual personality distilled from a
performer's movements, actions, beliefs and words into an
artificial intelligence that guides the on-screen performance.
Think Max Headroom for the formerly living.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's hard is characters that autonomously generate
performances,'' said Rosenthal. ``A lot of the hype is pushing the
notion that we're going to have these characters and they'll just
act.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't count on AI actors happening soon, or even more
problematically, having them work well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a much harder problem and, to my mind, a much less
interesting problem,'' Rosenthal said. ``There's something about
performance that you just can't expect. You're going to have to
bring (Dietrich) back in a way that surprises you. Otherwise, it's
not going to work. Does (the digital performer) ever really
surprise you with its performances?''
</P>
<P>
   Some actors have expressed fears that virtual performers will
supplant them, with notables such as Screen Actors Guild president
Richard Masur declaring that it can never happen. Something gets
lost in translation, notably the serendipity that can enliven a
living person's performances.
</P>
<P>
   But enthusiasts for the new world say that, if anything, the
digital possibilities of the future will create new opportunities
and possibilities, extending what actors can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we're not replacing anything,'' said Paul Charette, a
vice president of research and development at Pacific Title/Mirage.
``We're opening up a lot of possibilities. We're giving the
animator more tools.''
</P>
<P>
   And it will change the very definition of what an actor is _ and
who gets paid for what, as the talents of computer animators,
puppeteers and actors are merged in ways never before possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, who authors that digital performance?''
Bustanoby asked.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the actor whose face is digitally scanned and pasted onto
the on-screen body, the performer whose body is used for real-time
motion capture, or the animator who merges it all together and
makes it work in a film?
</P>
<P>
   Charette's company's new digital-character software has been in
testing with producers of several upcoming movies, including a
remake of ``The Incredible Mr. Limpet,'' starring Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actors we talk with about this technology, it doesn't
leave anyone indifferent,'' Charette said. ``Some people think it
will cost them work. Big-name actors see it as a way to extend
their careers. Jim Carrey's reaction was, `You mean, I can just
stay home and you guys can do all the work for me?' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
