<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-DIAMOND-CREEK-HN     06-21 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-DIAMOND-CREEK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL VINEYARD EMPHASIZES QUALITY OVER QUANTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Brounstein built Standard Drug Distributors from
scratch. He founded the Los Angeles-based pharmaceutical company in
1951 by borrowing $300, taking a used car and hitting the road.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a decade he had a $1 million business with
a warehouse and 15 employees. What he didn't have was peace of
mind, or a labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   Brounstein would find both in a small corner of California's
wilderness, at the northern end of Napa Valley near Calistoga. In
1966, at age 46, he bought an 80-acre mountain plot and mostly by
himself cleared 20 acres of hillside in order to pursue his dream
with a passion _ to create a vineyard of superior quality.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades and three years later, Brounstein is the proud
owner of one of the most highly regarded wineries in the world,
Diamond Creek.
</P>
<P>
   His is a riches-to-rags-to-riches story that Brounstein, a
balding, white-haired man whose wry humor is affected not at all by
a dozen years of Parkinson's disease, shared recently in Manhattan
at an invitation-only wine tasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost money with the winery for the first 15 years,'' he
recalled. ``It's called negative cash-flow, and that doesn't sound
as bad as losing money, so I called it that.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't drop out of the business world without knowing a
little bit about what he was getting into. While he ran the
successful pharmaceutical company, Brounstein took night classes at
the University of California at Los Angeles. He studied French, and
then took a course in wine tasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the course, when I'd learned about Lafite and
Latour and other tremendous French wines, I said to my instructor,
`Gee, I'd like to have my own vineyard. Just raise grapes and pay
the taxes. Have a nice, quiet, easy life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Don't do it. You'll never make any money.' For a
long time I thought I probably should have listened to him, because
it took us quite a few years to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard of Diamond Creek, don't worry: You're not
alone. Although the winery has received rave reviews in the Wine
Spectator and other publications, it is hardly high-profile. It's
open to visitors only four days a year, by invitation from the
winery's mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Creek produces such a tiny amount (3,000 cases a year,
compared with the 160,000 cases so-called small wineries turn out)
that it is indeed rare to spot one of Diamond Creek's four Cabernet
Sauvignon labels in a store.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the wine is sold directly to individuals who are avid
collectors of Diamond Creek, to appointed distributors, and to
restaurants. And all of the recipients are folks with deep pockets,
because these intense, purpley cabernets retail for between $100
and $300 per bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Brounstein's cabernet-sauvignon-only winery _ which
at age 79 he continues to supervise, with six employees doing the
farm work and four in the office doing book work _ is the grapes.
</P>
<P>
   He told the 200 or so at the wine-tasting in New York about how
he was able to circumvent U.S. Customs by smuggling in first-growth
cuttings from a prestigious vineyard in the Bordeaux region of
France, a winery whose identity he has vowed to keep secret. It was
1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised that I would never reveal who I got the cuttings
from,'' he said. ``Then everybody and his brother would be out
asking for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brounstein flew the cuttings into Tijuana, Mexico, and from
there picked them up personally in his own private plane. His
girlfriend at the time accompanied him during the illegal pickup.
She was thrilled by the risk Brounstein was taking, bringing in a
product the U.S. Department of Agriculture would consider
contraband.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought it was so much fun that we should try it again,
this time with marijuana,'' Brounstein recalled. ``That was when
she stopped being my girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   He was at that time a widower. He later remarried, and his wife,
Adele (her friends know her as ``Boots''), helps him run Diamond
Creek. He also employs a wine maker, Phil Steinschriber, a
California native who was working for a winery in the Golan Heights
in Israel when he met Brounstein, who was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The original French budwood was taken to nurseries, where for
two years it flourished and developed a sound root system before
being transplanted to Diamond Creek. It took another four years to
raise the vines to a respectable level where the grapes produced a
salable wine. The first 15 cases, from 1971, were used to top off
the 1972 wines, the first vintage Brounstein would put on the
market. It didn't become available until 1974.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasizes quality, not quantity. He thins his crop at least
one more time every season than most other growers, he said,
ensuring that the grapes that remain will get as ripe as they
possibly can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel if we make a real quality product people will be
willing to pay for it,'' he explained. ``They don't get this kind
of wine from every Tom, Dick and Harry. Most wineries have their
interest in other varieties besides the one that interests us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Creek does grow a small amount of both merlot and
Cabernet Franc, which are blended in, in small portions, during the
production of the winery's Cabernet Sauvignons. A typical Diamond
Creek wine contains 88 percent Cabernet Sauvignon, 8 percent merlot
and 4 percent Cabernet Franc.
</P>
<P>
   Brounstein uses a trusted panel of tasters during the
preparation of Volcanic Hill, Red Rock Terrace, Gravelly Meadow,
and Lake, the four distinct soil types his grapes grow on at
Diamond Creek and the names of the four Cabernets he produces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in on all of the tastings,'' he insisted. ``We have
capable people, but I still overrule them. If I feel it's a great
wine or not a great wine, I'll make the call.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to argue with Brounstein's palate. During an
international competition in France two years ago, only four U.S.
wineries, including Diamond Creek, were invited to participate
among the 100 most prestigious wines of the world. Diamond Creek
received seventh place, the best among U.S. wines. (Top prize went
to La Romanee-Conti.) Not surprisingly, Brounstein has fielded
numerous offers to sell his winery. He has resisted with a
determination that does not bode well for the big guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10 years ago, I had a guy phone me up from Mitsubishi
who said he was willing to pay $20 million for a prestigious
winery, and I said, `What would I do with the money that would give
me more pleasure than I'm getting now?' I told him to call me back
in 300 years' time. I might be interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kendall-Jackson tried to buy us, my wife, Boots, said,
`Call us in 100 years' time.' But then, she's more generous than I
am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
