<SLUG> BC-FORENSIC-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORENSIC SCIENTISTS FACE MAJOR TEST IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Forensic science has always had a ghoulish
glamour, epitomized by the television programs ``Quincy'' and
``Picket Fences,'' as well as Thomas Noguchi, the Los Angeles
coroner who performed autopsies on Marilyn Monroe, Janis Joplin and
Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the world's forensic scientists are uniting to investigate
the grizzly crime scene in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   These scientists are accustomed to the human wreckage of urban
crime. But the war-torn province of Yugoslavia will present a vast
tableau on which to deploy their forensic skills and tools.
</P>
<P>
   They will use satellites that spot mass graves and gadgets that
sniff for buried bodies in an attempt to unearth hundreds of
corpses, and then identify them. And, with luck, to find the
killers.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Reid, a spokesman for the British Embassy in Washington,
said the mission of the more than 300 forensic scientists expected
to go to Kosovo is bring to justice ``these vile guys'' who
slaughtered ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. The team members will come
from some of the most prestigious law enforcement agencies,
including the FBI, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and Scotland
Yard in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Using science to capture killers in politically troubled
countries around the world has been a chief goal of Physicians for
Human Rights, a Boston-based group that helped pioneer forensic
human rights in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us are a little idealistic and hope that this will say
to the people who perpetrate these kinds of things: `You can't get
away with this _ so don't do it again,''' said one researcher long
associated with the group, archaeologist Douglas Scott of the
Midwest Archaeological Center at the National Park Service in
Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo marks the first time such a large-scale forensic
investigation has been ordered by several governments acting on
behalf of a global authority, the international war crimes tribunal
at The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports indicate that Serbians, who were the brunt of
the police and military in Yugoslavia, frantically tried to destroy
evidence of the killings before fleeing as NATO troops rolled into
occupy Kosovo. But evidence tampering is tougher now with the
advanced skills of forensic scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to get rid of a body. Bones and teeth and hair
_ they last almost forever,'' said Clea Koff, a Stanford
University-educated anthropologist who has participated in numerous
forensic investigations of human rights crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the killers toss a body onto a funeral pyre and soak it
with lighter fluid, she said, often some tooth will still survive,
and the characteristic grooves or fillings of the tooth might
reveal the person's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic scientists investigate mass graves in the same way
archaeologists unearth ruins: very slowly and carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Artifacts ranging from bullets to buttons, and their precise
position when unearthed, can prove crucial in uncovering evidence.
Besides being a painstaking process, it can be trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dead bodies don't affect me. Mass graves don't affect
me,'' said University of Chicago pathologist Robert Kirschner, a
veteran investigator of human rights crimes. ``What is disturbing
to me is talking to survivors _ listening to survivors' and
witness' stories. I don't think anybody can be unmoved by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirschner, the former deputy chief medical examiner for Cook
County, Ill., warned Kosovo-bound forensic investigators to
remember that ``the scale of this thing is so enormous that it's
just going take many more people, and much more time, than you
think. ... You need to use people who have a lot of street
experience dealing with homicides and crime investigations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
