<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-NEXT-BIG-THING-NY     06-21 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-NEXT-BIG-THING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE NEXT BIG THING?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 By LISA LOCKWOOD, ANNE D'INNOCENZIO, ROSEMARY FEITELBERG and MILES
SOCHA 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leave all the predictions about computer
consciousness, interplanetary colonization and 200-year-old people
to Kreskin and his cronies. The following is a spot-check of those
operating in the here and now _ advertising, marketing and industry
executives _ on what's the next big thing in media.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; David Pecker, president and chief executive officer of American
Media: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next big thing is convergence, where the Web, cable and the
PC all converge in one set box in your office or home. The most
important part of it will be content. Here's where magazine
publishers will be able to go into the millennium as big content
providers for all the new media. Major publishers with megabrand
titles will be the biggest producers of the content. The other
element will be e-commerce, and there are big opportunities for
smart publishers. Magazines will sell products from the pages, and
smart publishers will take a portion of the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Janine Lopiano-Misdom, partner in Sputnik Inc., a trend
forecaster: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next big thing in media is already happening today:
interactive Web sites. What we mean by interactive is online,
real-time, soon-to-be-video-streamlined ``gatherings'' on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will marketers be competing with the hundreds of TV
stations already on cable, but with the millions of Web sites and
interactive sites that will exist. The winners will those who
deliver the engaging, entertaining, interactive and informative
experience that immerses consumers. Web sites will no longer be
digital catalogs or e-commerce vehicles; they will become the next
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sam Shahid, owner of Shahid &AMP; Co. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone will surprise us, but it might not be a magazine; people
are reading less and less. It'll be the Internet. Instead of
carrying pocketbook novels, it'll be a new Walkman that's
battery-operated, where you can see and read everything you want in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ingrid Sischy, editor in chief of Interview: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think the idea of psychographics will be more important than
demographics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dan Brewster, president and ceo of American Express Publishing
Co. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fully integrated media and marketing programs. Companies will
put together packages that include a magazine element, TV element,
trade element, in-store events and a data base.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peter Arnell, chairman of The Arnell Group: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing that will be really big is specific-frequency AM
broadcasting. The big usage will be on billboards, so when you're
passing a billboard and see the station, you turn on that
particular radio station and it'll talk to you. In a retail
environment, you walk into a Macy's and you have something in your
ear, and then you can hear a broadcast from Macy's radio station
about sales and what's going on in the store.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rebecca Shafer, creative director of Tse: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next big thing will be the Internet, without a doubt, along
with interactive media like live billboards. Also, more niche
marketing to the young, like young luxury. The connection will have
to be immediate from the brand to the consumer. You can't take five
years to develop and hit your target. Also, there will be more
magazines like Talk that can be targeted to the young as well as
older.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Steven LaGuardia, creative director of Louis Boston: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magazines are moving to be more lifestyle and attitude-based,
rather than gender-based. Look at Wallpaper, Surface and I-D. It's
not so much segregating men from women. We're seeing that kind of
media becoming much more important.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stefani Greenfield, co-owner of Scoop: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I definitely think that in the millennium, communication is
going to be driven by the Internet. From a fashion standpoint,
shopping online is the way of the future. It's not enough to have a
store now. You have to have a Web site. Now you have an opportunity
to reach the public at large, and it's a lot more cost-effective
than opening up a store. You're going to see the Internet as the
new focus group. We're going to take what's happening in fashion
globally and see it at our fingertips and communicate on that
level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Irma Zandl, president of The Zandl Group, market researcher: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think it's going to be totally about customized media and
magazines will deliver these things via the Internet. People who
feel like they've been inundated will want to filter things out. I
see this as being more of a guy thing because guys are more
focused, whereas girls have more of a gathering mentality. This has
a lot of applications. For example, a Playboy kind of person who is
into blondes only. He'll say, ``Don't send me any of those
redheads.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marc Balet, principal of Balet &AMP; Albert Advertising: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I believe that the next big thing in media will be back to
basics: storytelling to groups of six or 12. Someone brings the
marshmallows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Madonna Badger, president and creative director of Badger Worldwide
Advertising: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will definitely be the Internet. Right now, it's estimated
the Internet will capture 50 million users in just five years. It
took TV 13 years and radio 38 years. The Internet demographic is
really a marketer's dream. They're young, they're smart, they're
educated and they have a decent household income. This is quite
simply a great way to increase brand awareness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charles DeCaro, partner at Laspata/DeCaro: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mini fashion magazines on the Web. They will offer a lot of
snippets. They will be the Cliff Notes of magazines. People have so
little time to read lengthy articles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Richard Martin, curator of the Costume Institute at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think the next thing will be HDTV (high-definition
television). People really want to see runway shows as vividly as
they would by being there. Once they see high-resolution TV, it
will be like it was between 1951-54, where everyone had to go out
and buy a TV set.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lisa Lockwood, Anne D'Innocenzio, Rosemary Feitelberg and
Miles Socha are reporters for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
