   ``So many (companies) are involved with featuring musicians,''
Klein said. ``And we had to figure out, how does it apply to us? I
like to take a risk early on, like what we did with Marky Mark _
what he represented, his music and his ability to write his own
music. It goes back to that moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted musicians and young actors who are not necessarily
that well known, and they all have their own look,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a bit more on the edge, not ones who are played on the
radio all around America. They're not so mass. They're all
acclaimed by critics and other musicians and most of them are the
cool ones,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's lineup includes musicians Foxy Brown, Liz Phair, Shirley
Manson of Garbage, Kim Gordon of Sonic Youth, Melissa Auf Der Maur
of Hole, Moa (a 25-year-old singer from Iceland), Jon Spencer,
Butch of Marvelous 3 and Ryan Shuck of Orgy.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also includes Julia Stiles, a young actress who
stars in ``Ten Things I Hate About You,'' as well as actors Vincent
Kartheiser, who appeared in ``The Other Side of Paradise,'' and
Justin Chambers, who's featured in the Contradiction ads and has a
new film coming out, ``Liberty Heights,'' with Carolyn Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are some famous progeny such as actor Ben
Taylor, son of James Taylor and Carly Simon; actor Scott Caan, son
of James Caan, as well as musician Leona Naess, the stepdaughter of
Diana Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Where did Klein come up with this list?
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter,'' the designer revealed, referring to Marcy
Klein, who's a producer at ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the spreads shows a horizontal shot of Foxy Brown in her
CK Jeans, while another shows a heavily tattooed Butch of Marvelous
3 wearing CK jeans. Vincent Kartheiser is photographed in his CK
Jeans licking a spoonful of peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   The print ads carry the musician or actor's name and what
they're wearing, such as ``Deconstruction Denim,'' ``Pewter Denim''
or ``The Original Calvin.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads were photographed by Steven Klein at Silvercup Studios
in Long Island City, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The designer, who attended the three-day shoot, said he worked
with Steven Klein to determine who the artists would be and that
they'd do portraits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also spent a great deal of time with my daughter discussing
who the talent would be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his criteria, Klein said, ``A few of the artists have
albums coming out this summer. Some of them are all over MTV and
are hot now, and this is their moment. Others are cool and edgy and
not so new, but something's happening at this moment or is going to
happen real soon,'' said Klein, who's created more than a few stars
in his day.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said he asked the musicians and actors to choose their own
CK clothes to wear in the shoot, and Jon Spencer, who ``only wears
black,'' had no problem finding an outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were incredible,'' said the designer, about the assembled
group. A few were big fans of some of the others, he added. ``They
were so happy to do this. I was shocked. Ben Taylor was singing
while we were doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   The fall campaign encompasses the junior, women's, kids' and
men's CK Jeans lines (owned by Warnaco), as well as CK Calvin Klein
women's and men's collections (owned by Calvin Klein Inc.).
</P>
<P>
   And while Klein might feel right at home in the studio, he
acknowledged that media planning has become a lot more difficult
these days, with so many choices of magazines, cable and network TV
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Klein recalled how he was the first to run multiple-page
portfolios in magazines in the late '70s, but doesn't want to go
that route anymore. Instead, he said, he prefers to run spreads in
a greater number of publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the story is multiple pages in a magazine. The
magazines may not be thrilled to hear this. But the spreads say
what I want to say. I'd rather say it through different photographs
of different people in unexpected places. I don't think the story
is multiples pages in a book. When I look at those, it's not
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the core fashion and lifestyle magazines, Klein
has also selected some ``edgier'' publications such as Nylon,
Raygun, Contents, Notorious, Alternative Press and Trace. The ads
will run in the United States, Asia, Europe and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many new magazines. I have a stack of them. I
chose many of the new ones. They're small audiences and you can
target them. I like the idea of supporting them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as the media business becomes increasingly complex
and there's so much discussion about the Internet, Klein's excited
about placing his ads on an old format, radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try radio in a strong way. I want to hear what they (the
musicians and young actors) have to say. It's more about saying
something,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm clearly going after a young audience, and music is a
primary thing in their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who's no stranger to controversial ad campaigns, said he
doesn't think he'll run into any trouble this time, even though
some of the artists' lyrics may be questionable. And now that he's
associating his name with many artists, he's hopeful none of them
will do anything to embarrass the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the risk. We were careful, with the way everyone tends
to scrutinize what we do. Some of the lyrics are edgy. I'm not sure
everything they sing is going to be agreeable, but there's nothing
offensive. They're not killing people or advocating murder,'' Klein
said. ``In the end you have to take certain risks. Not everyone
will love what you're doing. In all the work, there's nothing
anyone would find offensive. Some people won't even get it, and
others will say, `Who are these people?''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lisa Lockwood is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
