<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAS IT WRONG TO PLAY IT SAFE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a woman, 81, married and in good health. During the last
10 years or so I've received cash gifts, which I have saved, so I
was able to purchase three T-bills in the amounts of $95,000,
$17,000, and $10,000. Recently I received an inheritance of
$75,000, with which I opened a money market account at our local
bank. I have avoided the stock market completely, because while
growing up ``stock market'' were bad words in our family _ my
mother and some of her friends suffered in the 1929 crash. For
peace of mind I decided to make less interest and invest in sure
things. Am I correct in having gone this route? Now I can say no,
but 10 years ago or more, who could foretell the future? I'm
heavily criticized by friends, but I'm happy enough with what I
have. The interest has helped with living expenses and in helping
members of the family, although it really hasn't been all that
great. I could have used it in the early years raising a large
family _ more then than now. I'm very grateful today and it's
appreciated more because everything we have was hard to come by. I
would appreciate your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   A. B., Panorama City, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To be perfectly honest, my first thought upon finishing your
letter was: God bless you _ both for your generosity of spirit as
well as your solid decision to value peace of mind over the
prospect of monetary gains.
</P>
<P>
   My parents, too, lived through the 1929 crash and the Great
Depression, and while it didn't entirely scare them off the stock
market, it certainly gave them a vivid awareness that Wall Street
runs two ways.
</P>
<P>
   You are doing just fine, and you'll continue to do well by
leaving the stock market to people who have the inclination to risk
their money there.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there's not a change which will benefit you
and improve your income stream. Keeping that inheritance in a
bank's money market fund is a big mistake. Banks typically pay only
about half of the interest on money market accounts that mutual
fund companies do in their money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   They're not identical, of course. The money on deposit in a
bank's money market account is insured just as other savings and
bank deposits are. Money in a mutual fund money market is not
insured _ but it is invested extremely cautiously, typically in
government securities, overnight loans to banks, and short-term
corporate loans called ``commercial paper.''
</P>
<P>
   When you buy shares in a money market fund, the net asset value
is always calculated at $1 per share, and the daily interest rate
changes to reflect changes in the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically such a fund could lose money on an investment and
be compelled to ``break the buck,'' which is to say, to report a
net asset value of less than $1.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long history of money market funds, no fund offered
to the public has ever done so; in the few cases in which managers
have invested in bad assets, the parent company decided the loans
were imprudent, and voluntarily made good their manager's losses.
</P>
<P>
   It's not entirely altruism: If a fund were to break the buck, it
would generate reams of bad publicity, which would redound to the
sponsoring company as well as the fund itself.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the yields on money market funds runs 4 to 4.6
percent. And you can get check-writing privileges with most money
market funds, so your funds will be just as liquid as at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 82 and my wife is 75. I am retired from the Postal
Service and have dabbled in stocks for the past 15 years _ and I
have lost in most of them, with the exception of the Vanguard Index
500 fund. However, I sold that holding to make home improvements,
selling at $86 per share. It is now about $123. I got out of the
market for safety's sake and put what I had in CDs, since I was
using my retirement money. A month ago a friend of mine came over
and was telling me about how great Dell Computers were, and I
bought 147 shares at $47.50. In the past month they have dropped to
about $34 per share. Did I buy a dead horse? I am worried and
concerned. Should I get out and take the loss?
</P>
<P>
   E.S., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You certainly would have done better had you stuck with the
CDs or the Standard &AMP; Poor's Index fund. But Dell Computer is a
very solid company with a terrific position in its market and
well-esteemed products.
</P>
<P>
   What you've done is demonstrated two things _ first how buying a
single stock can be a lot more dangerous than owning shares in a
mutual fund with a diversified portfolio, and second how the sexy
sectors of the market carry a higher degree of risk than the market
at large.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is now trading at only 60 percent of its 52-week high, but
also at a similar premium to its 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tumble, I would hang on. I think the long-term
picture for Dell is very solid, and if you're willing to be patient
with the stock it will eventually reward you.
</P>
<P>
   I think the old saw about IBM _ nobody ever got fired from their
corporation by buying IBM _ has now become true of Dell, which not
only sells solid machines but has an envied record of supporting
its customers.
</P>
<P>
   So yours is the old tale, of the speculator who stayed in to
become a long-term investor. But after this, I suggest you leave
your retirement money in more stable vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Over the years since 1985 I have held a goodly sum of
Franklin California Tax-Free fund, Class A shares. Since my
purchase I have made no additions and the balance has appreciated,
but the dividend has not. It seems like each year they cut the
dividend enough to make an impact on my income. For instance, from
1994 to the present it has fallen from .037 per share to .029. The
question is that none of my other tax-free funds have cut their
dividends, so why has Franklin? Is there a reason?
</P>
<P>
   H.N., Oceanside, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you look at the total returns from the various tax-free
funds you own, I think you'll see that Franklin California Tax-Free
fund has been holding up very nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, in a period of declining interest rates _ which is
certainly a fair characterization of the 1994 to 1999 period _
managers for fixed-income funds such as this have only a few
options when it comes to arranging their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   They can, as the managers of the Franklin fund have done,
maintain their portfolios in a consistent manner, seeking to
maintain a stable net asset value and letting the yield simply
represent the realities of the interest rate climate.
</P>
<P>
   Or a manager can pay premium prices for older, higher-yielding
bonds, which would serve to prop up the yield, but, reflecting the
premium paid for the holdings, would eventually eat into the
principal value.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a manager can stretch further in terms of risk, holding
somewhat riskier securities that will command a higher yield.
</P>
<P>
   The net result of all these moves can be found in the total
return, which not only reflects the yield but also changes in the
net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, Franklin California Tax-Free fund
fares a little above average in this measure, with a five-year
total return of 39.05 percent compared with a 38.32 percent average
for its peer funds, according to the May 31 report from Lipper
Analytical Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That result ranked your fund 32d among 67 peer funds with
results for that period. Using shorter-term measures the same
pattern holds: Over a year Franklin's 4.60 percent total return
compared with a peer average 3.81 percent; over three years its
total return of 23.06 percent compared with a 22.77 percent average
for its peers.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back further, its 10-year total return of 100.88 percent
compared with a peer average of 98.45 percent, according to
Lipper's figures.
</P>
<P>
   If you want further confirmation of the strength of the fund,
consider the summary from Morningstar Mutual Funds, which accords
to the fund its highest five-star rating: ``California muni
investors will be hard-pressed to find a better all-around
option.'' In short, what you're seeing is the general effect of
declining interest rates and not an underperformance on the part of
your fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
