<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-CELLPHONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELL-PHONE PLAN: BILL THE CALLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, Robin Richards signed up for a wireless phone,
but within months got rid of it because she got sick of paying huge
bills for incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   Now federal regulators are moving toward a revolutionary change
in the way US cell phone calls are billed _ charging incoming calls
to the person calling _ that could lead to a boom in the ranks of
cell phone users, now estimated to exceed 70 million. Once they do,
Richards plans to get another phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have a portable phone now, but I can't afford
it,'' said Richards, 26, who works for the Discover Boston trolley
tour line. ``Every time someone calls, you wind up paying for that
call, and what good is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Federal Communications Commission board
unanimously approved a proposed rule dubbed ``calling party pays''
under which the price of all incoming calls to cell phones would be
charged to the caller, not the person who owns the phone. Most
European, Latin American, and Asian telephone systems use this
billing method.
</P>
<P>
   FCC chairman William Kennard has said he hopes to make the rule
final by late this year or early in 2000, after public hearings.
Kennard predicts cell phone use ``would increase dramatically'' and
overall calling prices could drop.
</P>
<P>
   Under the most likely scenario being considered by the FCC,
someone dialing a wireless phone would hear a recording warning
that he must pay extra to complete the call, and the caller would
then hit the pound key to complete it. (A possible option is that
wireless phone owners could designate a handful of numbers, such as
those of parents or children, for which they would pay incoming
fees.)
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of delay, hassle, and as-yet unknown extra costs
for completing such calls concerns some consumer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entire proposal has tremendous potential to create a
great deal of confusion for the consumer,'' said David Butler, a
spokesman for Consumers Union in Washington, the group that
publishes Consumer Reports magazine. He sees FCC approval getting
bogged down by controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Facilitating wireless use could also bring other downsides,
analysts note, such as more proliferation of eyesore antenna towers
to serve them and more public disturbance from chirping telephones
and people chatting.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule change has strong support from the wireless
industry. And Adam Zawel, a wireless industry analyst with the
Yankee Group in Boston, said he thinks local phone companies would
move quickly to add a calling plan under which calls to wireless
phones would automatically be connected for a flat fee of, say, 10
cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Zawel's reasoning is that companies that are frequently calling
sales representatives or employees who have cell phones, as well as
residential customers whose family members or friends carry one,
would hate hearing the recording every time they called and would
happily pay a premium to skip over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think certain customers would demand it,'' Zawel said,
adding that he shares the perception that it would greatly increase
the market. ``It would bring wireless one step closer to being your
only phone.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lacey, a spokesman for Cellular One in Massachusetts, an
SBC Corp. unit, said his company ``does not oppose'' the plan but
wants to be sure the FCC adopts uniform notification and billing
procedures to make it work smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   A survey conducted by the Yankee Group in Boston last month
found that 70 percent of US cellular phone owners agree that
per-minute charges (including incoming call fees) limit their
overall usage of the phone, and 60 percent would be somewhat or
very willing to tell more people their wireless number if callers
paid for calling them.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, only 64 percent of people said they know their wireless
phone number, indicating a large minority are using it only for
outgoing calls.
</P>
<P>
   A good example is Buster Bradway, 49, a personal assistant to a
high-tech executive whose business card has his beeper number _ but
a blank space for him to write in the cell phone number, which he
has to copy from a card he carries in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only put it on for the people I want calling me,'' said
Bradway, a bass drummer in the Boston Crusaders drum and bugle
corps who is often coordinating gatherings and performances by the
South Boston-based group.
</P>
<P>
   Bradway said if callers had to pay the price for reaching him on
his cell phone, he would be inclined to give more people his
number, but he admits: ``I don't want everyone to know my cell
phone number, if you know what I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as average calling prices have dropped by 60 percent since
1994, wireless telephoning has boomed to $32 billion-a-year
business in the United States, counting 68 million subscribers at
the end of 1998 and an estimated 70 million today.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Kennard told an industry convention that he thinks
``it's time for us to find a way to implement a `calling party
pays' system in this country,'' noting that only 5 percent of all
calls are now made on mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate at which local competition has been established in
this country has been too slow,'' said Kennard.
</P>
<P>
   Some cell companies are offering calling party pays as a local
option, but no more than 10 percent of subscribers use it,
estimates Thomas Wheeler of the Cellular Telecommunications
Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   One example is a Bell Atlantic Mobile subsidiary that operates
systems using the Cellular One brand name in Albuquerque, Phoenix,
and Tucson, and began offering calling party pays 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, up to 50 percent of subscribers took advantage of it,
said Greg Klinek, president of the subsidiary, Soutwesco Wireless
L.P. But in 1995, Klinek said, problems with an elaborate scheme
that used an out-of-state ``dial-back'' number for people to cheat
on the cost of local calls led his company to limit it to ``local
calling party pays.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, about 20 percent of subscribers use the system, even
though they have to pay for incoming calls from out-of-state
callers. Klinek thinks usage would jump back up to its original 50
percent or higher if the FCC adopts the new plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
