<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HALL-2TAKES-ART-BO     06-21 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HALL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY MICHAEL HALL AND THE GEEK MYSTIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a moment of deja vu, you might glimpse him on the street, a
blur of fair skin, reddish-brown hair, eyes of steel. And you might
wonder ``Who is that guy?'' as strains of a bittersweet 1980s pop
song swell in the back of your mind. ``Don't you . . . forget about
me . . .'' And before long your memory, that quicksand of celebrity
has-beens and will-bes and woulda-coulda-shoulda-beens, will
convulse and explode and, finally, give it up: He's Anthony Michael
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Once the rail-thin jester of the 1980s Brat Pack, once the geek
icon who brought his wiry energy to ``The Breakfast Club'' and
``Sixteen Candles,'' Anthony Michael Hall is now a vaguely familiar
face on a city street. His features thickened, his jacket more
Brooks Brothers than ``Miami Vice,'' he is 15 long, strange years
away from his reign as the hottest teen actor on all of planet
Hollywood. Unlike fellow Brat Packer Demi Moore, who overcame drug
and alcohol abuse to enjoy a boffo career in the '90s, Hall has
struggled through many seasons of bad press and bad movies. But
unlike tragic child stars such as the late Dana Plato, he has
survived the trials of a youth lived in the glare of the public
eye, the psychological twists of too much fame, too much money, and
way too much candy.
</P>
<P>
   Now a calmer 31, Hall is in Boston as part of a promotional tour
for a cable-TV movie that he hopes will usher his career into a
better future. Called ``The Pirates of Silicon Valley,'' it's a
dramatized chronicle of the race between Apple Computer and
Microsoft, with Noah Wyle of ``ER'' as Steve Jobs, and Hall doing
the geek thing all over again as Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very excited about this project because it allows me an
opportunity to start again as an adult,'' he says. ``It's really
kind of funny how that works out. I'm 31 right now. Most actors
don't get started until they're in their 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, in the name of starting over, Hall is wearing a pressed
blue suit, a white shirt, and a contained, businesslike manner that
would probably win him the respect of even the stiffest of Silicon
bazillionaires. There's not a hint of brattiness in sight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Brat Pack lives
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before you can understand the history of Anthony Michael Hall,
you have to understand the Brat Pack, the grouping of young actors
associated with mid-'80s hits by writer-director John Hughes and
the movie ``St. Elmo's Fire.'' After the label was used by reporter
David Blum in a 1985 New York magazine article, it stuck to them
like Krazy Glue, winding up in every review and celebrity profile,
and it's now destined to appear in their obituaries. These actors _
including Rob Lowe, Ally Sheedy, Emilio Estevez, Judd Nelson, Molly
Ringwald, and Andrew McCarthy _ were linked not only by their
ability to portray teen alienation and early 20-something angst,
but by tales of their romantic and alcoholic misbehavior behind the
scenes. Hall and Ringwald were five years younger than the others,
but that didn't appear to stop them from keeping up.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the '80s, most of the Brat Pack careers had
derailed, thanks to the passing of trends, the strains of substance
abuse, and the blinding light of the always troublesome ego. But
the buzz about the Pack didn't die with the Bush administration,
when a grungier gang of young actors took over the limelight. Brat
Pack movies have become beloved cult objects in the '90s for those
who were raised on them, and recent references include an April
People magazine cover and a ``Breakfast Club'' goof on last week's
MTV movie awards. In an homage to Hughes's teen movies, Kevin
Smith, the director of ``Chasing Amy,'' has even based his new
film, ``Dogma,'' on a quest for the fictional Chicago suburb where
many of Hughes's classics were set. Just as children of the 1950s
harbor affection for ``Rebel Without a Cause,'' and just as today's
youth will look back at ``Dawson's Creek,'' Generation X will
always be curious about the Brats.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that the Brat Pack lives greeted Hall during his visit to
Boston, the city where he was born in 1968. Amid the clatter of the
Hard Rock Cafe, he lunched with 10 women culled from a KISS radio
contest, one of whom actually asked him to sign her underwear. ``I
asked her what her husband's name was, and I wrote `Sorry, Jim' on
the underwear,'' Hall says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes corporation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does Hall resent his Brat Pack notoriety? ``I don't really
obsess about it,'' he says, following the comment with an
inscrutable half-laugh that recurs many times during our interview.
``To be mentioned as a part of a period of young actors emerging or
working together, that's fine. . . . It's a gift to have been able
to contribute to some funny movies that people still refer to. As
an artist, that's what you want to do, you want to contribute and
be remembered. So it was a great place to start. It put me on the
map and changed the course of my young life. It gave me a career.''
</P>
<P>
   He lavishes praise on Hughes, with whom he had his three biggest
hits _ ``Sixteen Candles,'' ``The Breakfast Club,'' and ``Weird
Science.'' Hughes paved the way for the current popularity of teen
movies, as he grabbed '80s teen audiences by the throat with his
heartfelt insights and his shrewd use of pop music. ``During the
time we made those films, the focus was just to enjoy ourselves,''
Hall says. ``He was empowering as a writer and director because he
was very much a collaborator. He empowered the actors to make
choices and to take chances with him, and to come to him with
suggestions, to embellish scenes. He was very inspired to that
extent. It was a work in progress. It was never: `The door is
shut.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What Hall brought to the table with Hughes was his own wacky
personality, the kind of unstoppable clowning that had him doing
shows for his family as a kid. ``It was exciting to know that I was
his protege, and that he was very much looking to me for humor and
for ideas as well,'' he says. But once Hall graduated from Hughes
High School, he had to work with directors who had other ideas
about his performances, and his life changed. ``It's like after I
did the John Hughes films is when I had to become an actor,'' he
says. ``It was at that point it got hard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was then
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall fell into a post-Hughes rut of mediocre movies (with the
exception of small parts in ``Edward Scissorhands'' and ``Six
Degrees of Separation'') that he is still trying to climb out of.
He was Hughes's protege, but their fruitful relationship
deteriorated in the years after 1985's ``Weird Science.'' Hall says
he's been leaving phone messages for Hughes, but that Hughes hasn't
responded. Why not? ``He's become a Hollywood mogul,'' Hall says,
``and ironically he has kind of a Howard Hughes streak in him.''
But in 1992, Hall was more open about his falling out with Hughes:
``I can't call him up anymore,'' he told the Baltimore Sun.
``There's a lot of pain in that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
