<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HUSBAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING UP WILDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attending a West End theater production of Oscar Wilde's ``An
Ideal Husband'' in London a few years ago, Oliver Parker listened
intently to Wilde's wonderful, witty prose. Parker, a filmmaker,
had an immediate reaction to the audience's enthusiastic response
to this comic concerto of blackmail, friendship, and romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a very bad idea, actually, for a film,''
Parker said. ``It seemed so theatrical, I had no idea how we would
get it off the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet by the end of the play, Parker found himself ``sort of going
into a corner and scribbling out a few ideas.'' Within a few weeks
he had written a quick first draft, which would evolve into his
screen adaptation of ``An Ideal Husband,'' opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really came away from it thinking, `Well, I don't think we
should do it,' '' said Parker, during a recent publicity stop in
Boston. ``But there were so many curious elements to it that hooked
me
</P>
<P>
   somewhere, more subconsciously than I was aware.''
</P>
<P>
   Set during the Victorian era, the film stars Jeremy Northam as
Sir Robert Chiltern, whose white-hot political career and marriage
to Lady Gertrude (Cate Blanchett) are jeopardized when a mysterious
schemer, Mrs. Cheveley (Julianne Moore), tries to blackmail him by
threatening to expose a past indiscretion. Attempting to help
Robert is Arthur (Rupert Everett), a charming rogue who may prove
to be a better friend to Robert than a potential husband to Mabel
(Minnie Driver), Robert's lovesick sister.
</P>
<P>
   While Parker liked the story, at first he wasn't sure how it
would transfer from stage to screen. But he knew what he didn't
want _ a static, claustrophobic play on film. The only way it would
work, he believed, was to expand the play beyond the confines of
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Parker began ``a process which could make it much more
cinematic. It was like detective work going through the play and
finding all the references which related to things happening
outside the arena of the stage,'' he said. ``Then I became
intrigued by the challenge of delivering something which, apart
from its relevance, had something compassionate to say about our
nature. The relevance of many of the themes seemed so glaring that
my mind kept running over it like a tongue over a sore tooth.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A familiar scenario &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The relevance to which Parker referred concerns the play's basic
premise _ a promising politician whose professional and personal
life may unravel because of a selfish, stupid act concealed from
his wife and closest friends. (Sound familiar?) Although the play
is set in 1895, it's a story Parker believes contemporary audiences
can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   An actor before making his directorial debut with a 1995 screen
adaptation of William Shakespeare's ``Othello,'' Parker, who lives
in London, was familiar with Wilde's plays. He performed in ``The
Importance of Being Earnest,'' and learning Wilde's words gave him
a better appreciation of the man who is often reduced to a series
of witty observations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I acted in his plays, I thought of him as a bit of a
smart aleck, always with something clever to say about something.
And I thought it all seemed a little brittle, harsh and cynical,''
Parker said. ``It seemed Wilde was very happy to sacrifice a
reasonable plot line for a better gag line. And this is one of the
things which made me believe (Wilde's play) would be so difficult
to put on-screen because there needs to be more of a satisfying
narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Parker believes, Wilde's plays have not
received the recent popular attention Hollywood has lavished on
novels by Jane Austen and Edith Wharton, and all things
Shakespearean. Some have been straightforward adaptations, but
others have been updated. Austen's ``Emma'' was transformed into
``Clueless,'' and ``Romeo and Juliet'' has inspired everything from
``West Side Story'' to Baz Luhrmann's 1996 music-pumped urban drama
starring Leonardo DiCaprio and Claire Danes. But it's a safe bet
that Hollywood isn't planning a Wilde film adaptation called
``Bein' Earnest'' with James Van Der Beek as Jack, Freddie Prinze
Jr. as Algernon, and Katie Holmes as Gwendolen _ although Parker
briefly considered modernizing ``An Ideal Husband.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting idea, but I think you have to be very
aware of why you're updating a piece,'' he said. ``For me, this
story was all the more alluring because locating it in its original
time allowed perspective. The modern parallels, in terms of the
political scandals, if you actually made them specific and modern,
you would just go, `So what?' Part of the joy for me is showing
this happened 100 years ago, and it works almost on a metaphorical
level.''
</P>
<P>
   While keeping much of Wilde's original play, Parker did not shy
from injecting his own touches. One is an ode to the playwright,
showing several characters attending a performance of ``The
Importance of Being Earnest,'' with an appearance by Wilde (Michael
Culkin) for a curtain call. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Disservice to Wilde'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to offend somebody, but I think you do a
disservice to Wilde if you didn't do alterations, because he wasn't
writing for the screen,'' Parker said. ``I wanted to give Oscar as
much rein as possible, even if that meant tinkering with the lines.
He had some very specific agendas in his time. Some remain, some
are no longer as valid. For me it was about capturing the spirit,
and whatever it took, that's what you should be prepared to do. If
you don't do that, you can deliver something flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge was the language, which, while lovely to the
ear, sounds like nothing in contemporary culture. Parker said he
needed to reduce the ``linguistic complexity'' of the sentences
that were built like ``pyramids, with all these clauses which are
beautifully structured, but you can only get away with so many of
those.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language is perfect, so perfect it's almost at times
unpalatable for an actor to say on-screen. My intention was to
nudge it toward naturalism, without being obsessed with it,''
Parker said. ``I was keen to find a way to deliver the language
which became spontaneous, and I worked with the performers to make
sure we had a house style. The challenge was to sustain the
language without being throttled by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, much has been said and written about the
Irish-born Wilde, considered by some to be the first true
celebrity. Last year, two New York plays, Moises Kaufman's ``Gross
Indecency: The Three Trials of Oscar Wilde,'' and David Hare's
``The Judas Kiss,'' dealt with Wilde's downfall after he was
convicted of ``gross indeceny'' for his then-scandalous affair with
a young nobleman, Lord Alfred Douglas. Wilde died at age 46 in
1900, a few years after completing a two-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   With this adaptation of ``An Ideal Husband,'' Parker hopes to
turn the attention from Wilde the martyr back to Wilde the
playwright and novelist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was inherently modern, a great satirist, and a rousing
rebel. He was turning convention on its head. He was on the bridge
between the end of one century and the beginning of the next, and
he was pointing the direction like a signpost,'' Parker said. ``He
was hugely compassionate, and there's a general plea for tolerance
in everything he does. He dares you to accept the inconsistencies
of life, and its complexities and ambiguity. He challenges you not
to see the world in black and white. That's something people always
kind of need reminding of, and it's hardly been better expressed
than in Oscar's works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
