<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 1/2 pages of stories on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The agreement reached early
Monday to disband the Kosovo Liberation Army included, at the
insistence of its commanders, a pledge by the NATO allies to
consider letting the rebels form a provisional army for Kosovo
modeled on the U.S. National Guard. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Dateline to be determined) _ Status/future of
KLA; interview with top rebel commander Ceku. By Carlotta Gall.
Eds: tentative, may hold.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WOMEN-ASSAULT (Zrze, Yugoslavia) _ In interviews over the
last two weeks, dozens of women and men in Kosovo and in refugee
camps in Albania told stories that suggest that sexual assault and
intimidation, if not rape, were widespread, common and used by
Serbian forces to strike at the heart of a society in which the
virginity and fidelity of Muslim women is central. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Grace, Yugoslavia) _ NATO tries to control
Albanians who are looting and burning Serbian homes. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Ljubljana, Slovenia) _ President Clinton praises
Slovenia for being first Yugo republic to break with Milosevic;
also says he would like to be the U.N. czar of Kosovo. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is also working on the following (which may become
separates or be incorporated in one of the stories above):
developments on Serbs returning to Kosovo; developments in
Belgrade, including an anti-Milosevic demonstration being broken up
and the leader taken away; the difficulty in identifying individual
Serbian paramilitaries who may have committed atrocities, since
many wore masks; the frustration in Macedonia over various
accusations, including that it tried to make money off the refugee
crisis; developments at the Pentagon.
</P>
