<SLUG> BC-MUSLIMS-SECULAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S MUSLIMS PAVE NEW PATHS IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A crescent moon is rising over the world's
largest Muslim nation, a country that long has prided itself on
being a staunchly secular state. As results trickle in from its
first democratic elections since 1955, a stealth winner has
emerged: Muslim power.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of the 48 parties that contested the
historic June 7 elections are Muslim-based, a dramatic flowering
after decades of official suppression of Islam in politics. Several
of the parties are doing better than expected in partial returns.
Since neither of the leading secular parties will win a majority in
parliament, Muslim parties could be instrumental in deciding the
next president of the world's fourth-most-populous country.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-eight percent of Indonesia's 210 million citizens are
Muslim, yet for decades religion was excluded from politics and the
majority was sidelined in the corridors of military and economic
power, where Christians and ethnic Chinese long have held key
posts. That has been slowly changing this decade, but only in the
past year have grass-roots Islamic parties emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The rising tide of Muslim political power, and morality, could
challenge the foundations of this inclusive and tolerant nation, a
place where minidresses are more often seen on the capital's
streets than Muslim headscarves, where many Muslims drink and smoke
freely, and where a woman is the front-running presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A new breed of Indonesian politicians is invoking Muslim values
as an antidote to dirty politics, and Islamic unity as the means to
claim a larger piece of the pie for a long-disadvantaged majority.
They want more Muslims in top government posts, affirmative action
for Muslim businesses, more social safety nets, and tough
anticorruption laws. It remains to be seen whether any of the new
parties would want to impose a stricter view of religion or Islamic
law on the diverse population, or whether the largely liberal
public would accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muslim people in Indonesia need to be a united power, not
separated,'' said Djauhuri, 38, a Koran teacher who like many
Indonesians uses only one name. As his female students at Jakarta's
Al-Azhar mosque sang Koranic verses, Djauhuri reflected on the fact
that ``some people fear the power of Muslims, but they shouldn't.
True Muslims are for the interests of all people.''
</P>
<P>
   He also added that although he voted for a Muslim party, he _
like dozens of others interviewed _ does not want an Islamic state.
``Let there be no compulsion in religion,'' he said, quoting the
Koran.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of Islamic parties ``is a backlash'' against
the sidelining of Muslims in Indonesia, ``but a backlash should not
be in the form of another discrimination,'' said Abdurrahman Wahid,
a cleric and former head of perhaps the world's largest Muslim
organization, the 35-million-strong Nahdlatul Ulama, or Awakening
of the Learned.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid is now the presidential candidate for the most popular new
Muslim-based party, the National Awakening Party, which was running
second with 19 percent of the vote in the official tally Sunday. He
also leads Indonesia's ``traditionalist'' strand of Islam, which is
inclusive, tolerant, and secular in its political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that a few groups that have surfaced in the past
year _ such as the militant youth group Preparing for Islamic
Martyrdom _ might try to reverse Indonesia's secular traditions if
given the chance. ``They're everywhere in the Islamic world,'' he
said of the new zealots. ``But they don't have the votes here'' in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Alwi Shihab, deputy chairman of Wahid's party and a visiting
professor at Harvard Divinity School who is on leave to run for
parliament, said his party ``would like to see Islam as a cultural
and moral force, not as a political force. . . . Political Islam
could lead you to radicalism, to establishing an Islamic state, and
that is contradictory to our national ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the birth of new Muslim parties cannot help but reshape
Indonesian politics. On one side are nationalists and secularists,
led by the reformist party of Megawati Sukarnoputri, daughter of
the country's founding president Sukarno, and Wahid's Muslim-based
but inclusive party. On the other side is Golkar, the secular party
of Suharto, the ousted autocratic president. In recent years,
Muslim-trained leaders have taken the helm of the party, and in
this campaign Golkar tried to court the Muslim vote.
</P>
<P>
   Most Muslim parties espouse a reformist agenda, which would ally
them with Megawati and Wahid. But many conservatives oppose a woman
president and fear her party for its prominent Christian
leadership, even though Megawati is Muslim. In late May, eight
Muslim parties announced a deal to share votes to boost their
parliamentary seats. And the week before the election, two Muslim
associations ordered followers to vote for Muslim parties only,
while some clerics issued ``fatwahs,'' or religious edicts against
voting for secularists.
</P>
<P>
   The fatwahs seem to have had little effect, however. Megawati's
and Wahid's parties led in the official count Saturday, with a
combined 56 percent of the vote. (In an unofficial faster count,
the two parties had garnered just 47 percent of the vote as of
Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   But since the National Assembly, not the public, will choose the
next president, the Islamic bloc in parliament conceivably could
thwart the country's most popular politician from getting the top
job.
</P>
<P>
   It is a striking change of fortune for Islam in a country whose
national ideology all but forbade a single-religion state, and
where for decades, Muslim political groups were banned and
religious leaders muzzled. Initially, they were seen as a menace to
unity in the diverse, multireligious nation; later, they were a
threat to the unquestioned leadership of its autocratic president.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants make up 6 percent of the population, Catholics 3
percent, Hindus 2 percent, and Buddhists 1 percent, according to
government figures.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, himself a Muslim, cultivated a Christian leadership in
the armed forces and bestowed valuable deals on ethnic Chinese
businessmen-friends, feeding a divide-and-conquer culture that
spared him strong Muslim rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The Suharto era ended amid violent protests last year, and the
last 13 months have seen a renaissance of Muslim social and
political groups, underlining what many here say is a widespread
hunger for morality in government after decades of corruption,
cronyism, and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts worry that the rise of Islam in politics could
exacerbate Christian-Muslim violence that has claimed hundreds of
lives this year.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, the battle for dominance may not be among
different religions, but within Islam itself. With an array of
leaders, the lines have been drawn between three camps: a liberal,
inclusive philosophy espoused by Wahid, a ``modernist'' Muslim
movement that is more conservative and rising in popularity, and
fringe groups that have yet to define their agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Islam never has been a firebrand in Indonesia. It came
peacefully to the archipelago with Arab traders 1,000 years ago,
and over the centuries, it blended with Hinduism and indigenous
faiths. Sufi clerics preached a mystical and eclectic form of
worship, and unlike in the Arab world, Turkey, and India, there
were no wars to convert the masses.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the new, missionary-oriented parties?
</P>
<P>
   Indra Gunawan, 25, is a leader of the Justice Party, and he and
his missionary colleagues observe stricter codes for everyday
behavior than most here: They greet women with a prayer-like salute
rather than a handshake, they don't drink alcohol, and they don't
smoke. But Gunawan says his party does not want to establish an
Islamic state or impose rules that would, for example, force women
to wear jilbabs, or Islamic headscarves, which were illegal in
schools and government offices until around 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the values of Islam, which are universal,'' he said.
``We want something between a secular and relgious state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Sukatmajaya, secretary general of the Gerakan Pemuda
Islam, or Islamic Youth Movement, agrees that ``of course we don't
want Pakistan or Iran.'' The rise of Islamic politics, he says, is
to counter decades of ineffectual leadership by Islamic
``yes-men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Indonesians to follow the values of Islam, but
whatever we do must be in the context of our culture,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
