<SLUG> BC-SNORE-UNREST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT HELPS SNORERS SNOOZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Once or twice a week, Robert D'Amore recalls, the woman in his
life would wake him up in the middle of the night, complain about
his snoring, and ask him to sleep somewhere else. Anywhere else,
just as long as it was out of earshot. Despite this, D'Amore says,
he didn't fully appreciate how loud and obnoxious his snoring
really was. Then, one night, she left a tape recorder running and
played it back to him the next day.
</P>
<P>
   That did the trick. ``It was horrible,'' the 31-year-old man
acknowledges. ``I don't know how I was able to sleep through that
racket.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that about 40 million Americans are afflicted
with habitual snoring, it's a wonder that so many of us manage to
maintain relationships and get a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   According to medical studies, snoring affects about 20 percent
of the general population, and about 60 percent of men over 40.
While 57 percent of men in one study reported that their wives
snored, 85 percent of women polled said that their husbands did.
``Impaired social relationships'' is among the major problems
associated with loud snoring, according to the American Sleep
Disorders Association.
</P>
<P>
   In its extreme form, snoring can threaten the most solid of
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Linda Greenblatt, for instance, have been married for
33 years, peacefully sharing a bedroom for most of them. But a few
years ago, Martin Greenblatt's snoring escalated from a relatively
subdued hum to a rasping, annoying buzz.
</P>
<P>
   This is a fairly common later-in-life male development, but one
that can seriously affect spousal relations. ``When your partner
can't sleep because you're sawing wood,'' says Martin, 59, a Boston
lawyer, ``she can build up a pretty good head of resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a candidate for sainthood nor a silent sufferer,''
says Linda Greenblatt. ``He was so loud I could hear him through
earplugs, and I'd wake up and walk to another bedroom. I was
walking around like a zombie and really angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brody's wife, Susan, wasn't happy about his snoring,
either. Brody, 45, has had a serious snoring problem since his
mid-20s. ``I broke my nose four times when I was a kid,'' he says,
``and again when I was in the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in recent years, the Andover man reports, his snoring
got so bad his wife resorted to extreme measures. ``I was banished
from the bedchamber and had to sleep in a bunk bed in my son's
room,'' says Brody. ``It was the room farthest from the master
bedroom, but she says she could still hear me.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, problem snorers such as D'Amore, Greenblatt, and
Brody had only a few treatment options, all involving considerable
pain or discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Snoring results from a narrowing of the airway at the back of
the throat because of muscle relaxation during sleep. As air is
forced through the narrow passageway it causes excess soft palate
tissue to vibrate, producing sounds ranging from a series of low
snorts to what can resemble a high-powered chain saw badly in need
of oiling.
</P>
<P>
   Laser surgery to the palate can be effective in reducing
habitual snoring but causes swelling and lingering post-operative
pain. It has mostly been used to treat extreme cases of obstructive
sleep apnea syndrome, a potentially life-threatening condition in
which breathing is repeatedly interrupted for 10 seconds or more
during sleep. Nonsurgical options include nasal dilators, such as
adhesive tape that widens the nostrils to improve airflow, and oral
appliances that adjust the position of the jaw or tongue to prevent
closing of the airway.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering how awful his snoring was, D'Amore says, he
went to his primary care physician and asked to be fitted with a
jaw retainer. However, the doctor suggested instead that he look
into Somnoplasty, an effective and relatively painless new snoring
treatment that uses radio-frequency energy to shrink soft palate
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Past procedures involved shortening or cutting into the
palate, but Somnoplasty, or radio frequency palate ablation, is
about as minimal as a surgical procedure can be and it doesn't
really hurt,'' says Dr. Gregory Randolph of the Massachusetts Eye
and Ear Infirmary, the first surgeon to perform the procedure in
the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by Somnus Medical Technologies, a California company
specializing in treatments for upper airway disorders, Somnoplasty
involves inserting a needle into the palate and delivering
controlled thermal energy to targeted areas with a hand-held
instrument, reducing tissue volume, and stiffening soft tissue.
``Somnoplasty causes scarring that makes the tissue tighter and
less inclined to vibrate,'' Randolph says.
</P>
<P>
   An outpatient procedure, Somnoplasty requires only a local
anesthetic and a treatment takes about a half-hour. ``There's a
little swelling in the throat for a day or so,'' says Dr. Randolph,
``but no pain.''
</P>
<P>
   It typically takes three to five Somnoplasty treatments to
eliminate snoring, or reduce it to a minimum, he says, and most
patients are willing to stay the course. ``The other procedures
were so painful that it was very hard to get patients to submit to
such serial treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Somnoplasty doesn't come cheap. Randolph and the other members
of his surgical team, Dr. Nicholas Busaba and Dr. Richard Fabian,
charge $1,800 for the first treatment. Subsequent treatments are
$250 each.
</P>
<P>
   Because Somnoplasty is a new procedure, approved by the US Food
and Drug Administration less than two years ago, it is not covered
by most insurance plans. However, a pretreatment examination to
determine that snoring is the problem and not a symptom of some
other condition, such as obstricted sleep apnea, usually is covered
by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amore considers himself one lucky snorer. After his first
treatment, the volume of his snoring dropped significantly. ``I was
allowed back in the bedroom,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A second treatment he had recently, D'Amore says, has probably
cured him. ``I still snore a little bit, but I think it's going to
go away,'' he says. Although D'Amore didn't realize it at the time,
his loud snoring was affecting the quality of his own sleep almost
as much as that of his friend. ``Now I wake up feeling refreshed,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Brody and Greenblatt, who have also been treated by Randolph,
each report noticeable improvements. But neither is cured yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in the bottom bunk in my son's room,'' says Brody,
``but he tells me I sound a lot better.'' He thinks it will
probably take three or more treatments to bring his snoring to
acceptable levels. ``My wife is very encouraging,'' Brody says.
``She wants this to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Greenblatt has had two treatments. ``It's an incremental
thing,'' he says, ``and the second treatment definitely moved the
ball down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He isn't cured,'' says Linda Greenblatt. ``He still snores and
I'm still wearing earplugs, but now I'm not sleeping in another
room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marriage has lasted 33 years and it will probably survive
a little bit longer,'' says Martin Greenblatt, who plans to have
another treatment. ``But laugh and the world laughs with you. Snore
and you sleep alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
