<HEADLINE>
GRUDEN OF THE OAKLAND RAIDERS FLEXES HIS CLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The group of NFL coach/emperors is a small
one, and a well-aged one at that. After all, the twin skills of
wisdom and leverage take time to nurture and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes you wonder how Jon Gruden did it so quickly,
especially where he does it, and for whom.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden just finished his fifth or sixth or seventh minicamp
(hey, who counts?) as the head coach of the Oakland Raiders this
past weekend, and while minicamps are by and large exercises in
glamorless living, they also provide occasional clues to a team's
direction, even if, in some cases, the direction is only circular.
</P>
<P>
   In Gruden's case, there were two relatively little noted but
interesting decisions, and they both involved players who didn't
fit into the grand plan.
</P>
<P>
   On successive days, he released backup quarterback Heath Shuler,
who had been signed in the offseason as an intriguing additive to
Rich Gannon, and Harvey Williams, the running back turned tight end
turned running back turned . . . well, the Raiders really never
knew what to do with him now, did they?
</P>
<P>
   These seem like such small things (except, of course, to the
freshly unemployed), but when you add them to the release of Jeff
George and the signing of Darrien Gordon (ergo, the release of
Desmond Howard), you get the unmistakable feeling that Gruden is
truly the master of his own destiny, and at a staggeringly young
age, too.
</P>
<P>
   Before you get your spines up about what seems like another
swipe at Gruden's birth certificate, we mention it only to point
out how quickly he has come to his present position, and how
quickly he convinced Al Davis to let him get there.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden is 36, which you know. He has been a salaried, real
assistant or head coach in the NFL for only six years. His first
Raider team started 6-2 and ended 8-8. He is not, therefore,
overburdened by resume.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this to the other nine NFL coaches who also have their
owners' ears and wallets. St. Louis' Dick Vermeil is 62, and has 15
years' NFL experience. New Orleans' Mike Ditka is 59, with 26 years
on the job. Carolina's George Seifert is 59, with 18 years. Bill
Parcells of the New York Jets is 58, with 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Jimmy Johnson is 56, with eight years. Dan Reeves of
Atlanta is 55, but with 29 years on the job. Seattle's Mike
Holmgren is 51, with 14 years. Dennis Green of Minnesota is 50,
with 11 years. Mike Shanahan of Denver is 47, but with 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Six of those nine (Ditka, Seifert, Parcells, Johnson, Holmgren
and Shanahan) have Super Bowl rings as a head coach. Two others
(Vermeil and Reeves) have been to the big show. Against all that,
Gruden seems as shiny and new as the day he was hired.
</P>
<P>
   But power is power, no matter when you get it, and in the
context of football in the hierarchy-sensitive NFL, power is good.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden's power is, of course, conditional, which is less than
can be said for most of the other men on the list. He could not,
for example, sign Billy Crystal to play strong safety without
having an extraordinarily good explanation for The Al, unlike
Parcells, Vermeil, Holmgren or Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Gruden has to have a good explanation, the fact is
that he has dismissed the two biggest signings the Raiders have
made since returning to Oakland, and we know they are the biggest
because Al His Own Self was there at the press conference for
George and signed Howard himself.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing Shuler didn't have the same impact, but it was an
indication that Gruden can call mulligans on himself, which almost
no other coach on any level dares do. And Williams' dismissal was
an admission that Gruden had no more idea how to utilize him than
Joe Bugel did, or Mike White before him. Indeed, Gruden used
Williams less than either of his predecessors because, at least in
his own estimation, Williams wasn't a good enough running back or
tight end for Gruden's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Power of this sort can be transitory, but it usually isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Green, for example, ripped his owners in a book after years of
underachievement and off-field rumors and charges, and held his job
long enough for Randy Moss and Randall Cunningham to cure
everyone's ills. Vermeil was gripped by the angst of his Rams'
horrors, but was talked off the retirement ledge. Parcells had a
heart problem, but no such problem getting his ventricles cleared
for another job.
</P>
<P>
   In short, once you get this kind of hammer, you have to do an
awful lot to lose it. At least in most cases, anyway. It is always
dangerous to underestimate the length of Al Davis' reach.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, it is equally dangerous to underestimate the
length of Jon Gruden's sleeve. The last Raider coach to win even
this much control was John Madden. You'll have to do the rest of
the math yourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
