<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-21 1889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ELDERS ON THE ROAD, THE BEST ADVICE IS `BE PREPARED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Margaret Treseler was only a day into her long-planned vacation
on Spain's Costa del Sol last March when she began feeling muscle
aches all over her body. An experienced traveler, the 73-year-old
Boston woman knew it was something beyond jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   A hotel doctor gave her a salve. But the achiness didn't
subside, and three hours later, another physician who answered her
distress call suggested a shot of cortisone for the pain. At that
point, Treseler decided to go to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the language barrier, I waited two hours in the
emergency room,'' she said. ``But once they saw me, they started
paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Treseler was having a heart attack _ her second one.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing 12 days were a nightmare for Treseler and her eight
children back home. ``It was terrifically frightening,'' she says.
``I would ask the cardiologist `What is it? How bad is it?' and he
would just point to his chest and shake his head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until my brother and sister got over there, we didn't know how
bad off she was,'' adds John Treseler, a son who tried to
coordinate the situation from his home in Baltimore. ``That was our
biggest frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Treseler's ordeal had a happy ending: she had
open-heart surgery back in Boston that has put her well on the road
to recovery. But it serves as a warning to the growing number of
adventurous elders embarking on far-flung trips they have long
dreamt of and saved for. ``These days you find a lot of people in
their 80s and beyond out there doing whatever they have to do to
see the sights,'' says Walter Sanders, a retired TV newsman and
frequent globe-trotter who is president of the Massachusetts
chapter of the American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Elders travel more often and stay away longer than their
under-50 counterparts, according to a 1995 survey by the magazine
Modern Maturity. Two-thirds classify themselves as ``adventurous''
or ``experimental'' tourists who frequently scout out new
destinations. A quarter-million will sign up this year for one of
the 12,300 Elderhostel educational programs held all over the
planet, on everything from Maori culture and Elizabethan theater to
Viking shipbuilders and choral singing. Travel agencies that
specialize in seniors are thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more older travelers, and they're going on more
extensive trips,'' reports Alicia Gallagher, who coordinates a
travel clinic, which focuses on infectious diseases, at Lahey
Clinic in Burlington, Mass. ``Older people are healthier now, and
that makes them more adventuresome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the ability we now have to extend life with specific
medications, people are able to be more active,'' agrees Dr. Paul
Mendis, medical director for Harvard Pilgrim's First Seniority HMO,
which serves about 70,000 seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``And with families scattered all across the country, there's
more incentive for elders to travel to see their grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, travel is arduous for anyone, full of unaccustomed
stress and temptations to overdo things. Elders are likely to have
chronic diseases, both recognized and undiagnosed, that can flare
up under the travails of travel. Even ordinary tourist curses, such
as jet lag and travelers' diarrhea, can escalate into serious
problems for elders.
</P>
<P>
   Little attention has been paid so far to the particular problems
of older travelers. There is little systematic advice to tap into,
virtually no studies on the issues facing older travelers, and few
organizations or Internet sites targeted specifically to them. One
exception is a useful website run by the US State Department at
http://travel.state.gov/olderamericans.html, which is accessible
through many libraries for those without home computers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the general paucity of information, with a little
foresight, planning, and common sense, older travelers can lower
their risk of vacation-spoiling (or life-threatening) health
problems and increase their chances of coping successfully if a
medical crisis does arise far from home.
</P>
<P>
   The to-do list should lead off with a review of health insurance
coverage and limits. Regular Medicare, the coverage on which most
Americans over 65 rely, is good throughout the United States. But
don't count on it to cover anything beyond these borders. Some
``medigap'' or Medicare supplement policies, such as Medex Gold or
Bronz through Massachusetts Blue Cross-Blue Shield, will cover
limited medical expenses in foreign countries; check your policy's
fine print, call the insurer before departure if anything is
unclear, and be prepared to pay for care and medications yourself
and save receipts to get reimbursed later.
</P>
<P>
   Many Medicare beneficiaries should seriously consider buying a
time-limited health insurance policy for the duration of their
trip, say health and travel professionals. The cost will vary by
insurer, coverage limits, and the length of the trip, but it should
be within $100 to $300 for most trips. That could turn out to be a
bargain if a serious problem arises.
</P>
<P>
   But beware: Don't buy a policy with ``preexisting condition''
exclusions, and do seek out a reputable insurer with an established
track record. Depending on your destination, health risk, finances,
and how risk-averse you are, you might consider buying insurance to
cover medical evacuation to a specialized hospital or one back
home. There's also trip-interruption insurance, which refunds the
unused portion of tours cut short by illness.
</P>
<P>
   Elders in Medicare HMOs, such as Secure Horizons, First
Seniority, Fallon's Senior Plan, and HMO Blue, are covered for
emergency or urgent health care in the States or abroad, but not
normally for medical evacuation costs.
</P>
<P>
   In Treseler's case, Tufts Health Plan's Secure Horizons covered
her entire hospital stay in Spain (and an agent persuaded the
hospital by telephone to refund a $2,000 credit card charge it
extracted from Treseler's son). A separate trip insurance policy
paid for Business Class passage home for Treseler and her daughter,
a nurse who had flown to Spain to help her mother.
</P>
<P>
   For domestic travelers, new federal rules make it easier for
``snowbirds'' who spend part of the winter in warmer climes.
Medicare HMOs must now cover emergency and urgent care for up to 12
months' out-of-area stays. Plan managers say they often bend the
rules to include necessary non-urgent care for certain things, such
as monitoring high blood pressure and blood-clotting tendencies _
but they ask subscribers to get prior authorization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very committed to seeing that patients are covered when
they're out of the area and we just don't quibble about it,'' says
Dr. Allen Smith, medical director of Secure Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs can present a travel problem. The best
strategy is to take an ample supply of all medications to cover the
trip's duration _ in their original containers. But if pills get
lost or run out, it should be possible for your primary care
physician to call in a prescription in another state (except for
narcotic painkillers). It's a different story abroad; you will
probably need a list of the generic names (not the US brand names)
of the drugs you're taking. Carry an explanation from your doctor,
on the physician's letterhead, about why you need the medications.
In some cases, this may be sufficient to get a prescription, but in
others, you'll need to contact a local doctor.
</P>
<P>
   If you have insurance coverage for prescription drugs, be
prepared to pay the local pharmacist and get reimbursed later, so
keep receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Need to carry narcotic painkillers or needles and syringes for
diabetes care? Get a doctor's verifying letter to deal with zealous
officials concerned about illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the pre-departure list: allow four to six weeks to get
vaccinations for destinations where certain diseases are prevalent
_ such as yellow fever in sub-Sarahan Africa, diphtheria in Eastern
Europe, and typhoid fever in many off-the-beaten-track locales in
Latin America, Africa, and India. There's no vaccine against
malaria, but if you're traveling to areas where this mosquito-borne
disease is common, you may want to take anti-malarial drugs, along
with supplies of DEET-containing insect repellent and mosquito
netting.
</P>
<P>
   Those headed for less exotic destinations still should pack a
kit with basic first-aid supplies, analgesics, and sunscreen. And
don't forget anti-diarrhea medications _ Pepto-Bismol (except for
those who shouldn't take aspirin), Kaopectate, and Lomotil or
Immodium AD.
</P>
<P>
   Traveler's diarrhea is the bane of all ages, but for elders a
bout of diarrhea can grow beyond nuisance proportions because of
fluid loss and depletion of blood chemicals called electrolytes,
which are vital for proper nerve conduction and normal heart
rhythm. ``Traveler's diarrhea is one of the biggest risks for
elders,'' says Dr. Winnie Ooi, director of Lahey Clinic's travel
clinic. ``Often patients are on diuretics for blood pressure
problems and they will need to stop the medication for a day or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Elders for whom dehydration may be particularly dangerous _ or
anyone worried about it _ should pack an oral rehydration powder
that can be mixed with (bottled) water to replenish electrolytes
and sugar. It's available from pharmacies as WHO Oral Rehydration
Salt, Pedialyte, Rehydralyte, Ricelyte, and similar forms.
</P>
<P>
   Much traveler's diarrhea can be prevented with simple
precautions (see chart), but many people who know better still get
sick _ often toward the end of a trip. ``We have a theory about
that,'' says Lahey's Alicia Gallagher. ``They feel well, and they
get a little cavalier about precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   When diarrhea strikes, doctors advise staying away from milk and
milk products because of temporary deficiency of the enzyme
lactose, which is necessary to digest milk.
</P>
<P>
   If diarrhea persists beyond 24 hours, despite over-the-counter
medicine, Ooi and Gallagher advise starting an antibiotic, such as
ciprofloxacin, which they often prescribe in advance of a trip.
</P>
<P>
   So you're as prepared as you can be and departure day is
approaching. How can you minimize jet lag, which can hit elders
particularly hard? The Lahey travel experts advise eastbound jet
travelers to go to bed and get up an hour earlier than usual three
days before the flight; then they should set the sleep-wake
schedule back another hour for each of the next two days.
(Westbound travelers do the opposite, retiring an hour later for
three days and rising later.)
</P>
<P>
   On flight day, eat light, avoid caffeine and alcohol, and adjust
your medication schedule with your physician's advice. Take it easy
when you land, and get some bright light exposure and exercise in
the mornings (if you've flown east) or the late afternoon (if
you've flown west).
</P>
<P>
   And if this all sounds so intimidating that you're tempted to
stay at home, take heart from Margaret Treseler's response when
asked if her traveling days are over: ``I hope not,'' she said. ``I
brought up a big family, and these are my fun days!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox's e-mail address is knox(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
