<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXTINCT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF TIGER'S RETURN GREATLY EXAGGERATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does extinction really have to be forever?
</P>
<P>
   The news flash several weeks ago was tantalizing: Australian
Museum director Michael Archer announced that the thylacine, or
Tasmanian tiger _ an exquisite creature presumed extinct for 50
years _ could be ``kick started'' back to life. Archer claimed that
cloning techniques could be applied to newly discovered baby tiger
specimens that had been pickled in alcohol rather than a
formaldehyde solution, which damages genetic material.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Archer, who has a specimen that dates back to 1866,
boasted recently in an interview with the BBC that within 50 years
it will be possible to walk out of a pet store with a Tasmanian
tiger on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites at ABC, CBS, and CNN hyped the news to the hilt. ``I
call this the Jurassic Park syndrome,'' says Michael Hutchins,
director of conservation and science for the American Zoo and
Aquarium Association. The movie, which brought velociraptors and a
brontosaurus back to life on screen, seems to have inspired a
number of assertions that extinct animals really can be cloned
including the woolly mammoth, the giant sloth, and the quagga, a
partially-striped variety of zebra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of any cases in which the cloning process has
brought a species back from the dead,'' Hutchins says.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchins, who helps mastermind endangered species breeding
programs in North American zoos, and happens to be a fan of the
thylacine, understands the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The thylacine was an animal like no other: It was the largest
marsupial carnivore of modern times and a creature that looked
something like a wolf crossed with a tiger crossed with a kangaroo.
In fact, it is also called the Tasmanian wolf. The muscular animal
had the head of a wolf and its massive jaws could open at a
startling 120 degrees and then close with ferocious force. A fully
grown male would measure 6 feet from nose to tail tip, and weigh as
much as 77 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Thylacines were ruddy brown in coat color with a set of 15 to 20
dark stripes extending from mid-section to tail. The tail was less
like a wolf or tiger's and more like that of a kangaroo. And in
true marsupial fashion, this fearsome hunter had a pouch to carry
its young. Like the Tasmanian devil, another marsupial carnivore,
the pouch of the thylacine faced backwards, presumably to protect
the young while the animal trotted through heavy brush.
</P>
<P>
   Though capable of relentlessly pursuing prey, such as the
kangaroo-like wallaby, the thylacine was driven to extinction
thousands of years ago on mainland Australia with the introduction
of the social dingo dog. But without competition for food from the
dingo on the nearby heart-shaped island state of Tasmania, the shy,
secretive animal held out well into this centry. But a campaign of
slaughter, probably aided by an outbreak of a disease with
distemper-like symptoms, obliterated the population in the early
1900s. The last known living Tasmanian tiger, named Benjamin, died
at the Hobart Zoo in Tasmania in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to become enchanted with the ghost of this elegant
animal, and though there has never been any hard evidence that
Tasmanian tigers survive today, there are about 10 sightings each
year reported to the Tasmanian National Parks and Wildlife Service,
according to research officer Nick Mooney.
</P>
<P>
   It seems everyone wants to believe that the Tasmanian tiger
still lives, or will live in the future. So who wouldn't pounce on
Archer's notion? Well, most people who have looked at the science.
Mooney of the Tasmanian wildlife service says cloning a Tasmanian
tiger will not happen ``in the foreseeable future.'' He also thinks
all of the ``fascination with how technologically clever we are,''
is ``very distracting from grassroots conservation'' efforts in
Tasmania.
</P>
<P>
   And he feels that the wild Tasmanian habitat might be so
degraded by the time the lab work is finished that ``the poor clone
would be condemned to being a captive curiosity, no doubt in the
`Mike Archer wing' of the Syndey Museum or suchlike.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Archer's colleagues from the department of zoology at
the University of Tasmania are more bemused than intrigued.
Professor Craig Johnson, the head of the department, said, ``To be
blunt, with present technology and even within the reasonable
horizons of future developments in molecular techniques, producing
thylacines (or any other extinct species) from tissue preserved in
alcohol is unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   And the university's marsupial expert, Dr. Randy Rose, concurs.
``Mike Archer's claims are a bit far-fetched,'' Rose says, though
he clearly gets a kick out of Archer's showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is conceptually feasible,'' says Eric Overstrom, the man
from Tufts University School of Veterinary Medicine, who brought
the world its first cloned transgenic goats. ``But there are three
large hurdles.''
</P>
<P>
   The first one is DNA. Overstrom says it is ``unlikely'' that the
DNA samples they could retrieve from these specimens (there are at
least seven in museums around the world) would be ``adequately
intact.'' In fact, like Hutchins, Overstrom says as far as he
knows, no dead animal, no matter how it was preserved, has ever
been cloned.
</P>
<P>
   In cloning, scientists place the nucleus of a cell of one animal
into the egg of another whose genetic material has been removed.
The implanted nucleus, which carries the cell's genetic
information, acts as a blueprint, and the egg divides and grows,
eventually becoming an identical twin of the animal whose cell
nucleus was used to create it.
</P>
<P>
   The second big hurdle involves a host animal. If you scoop out
some nice, intact thylacine genetic material, who will carry the
egg and the fetus to fruition? All of the cloning breakthroughs
have involved domestic, not extinct or rare, animals. Scientists
can harvest sheep or goat eggs for implantation in the wombs of
sheep or goats, but whose egg would be compatible with that of the
thylacine?
</P>
<P>
   Although of very different appearance, the closest species is
the Tasmanian devil, the animal who has inherited the title of
``largest marsupial carnivore.'' The stumpy little spaniel- size
creatures are basically jaws on wheels with a bite estimated to be
three times as strong as that of a pit bull, allowing a ``tassie''
to devour carrion, including cows, from stem to stern.
</P>
<P>
   But would doctored deviled eggs do the trick?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Betsy Dresser of the Audubon Institute and the Audubon Park
and Zoo in New Orleans, doesn't think so. She is no stranger to
cross-species work in assisted reproduction (though not cloning).
She successfully implanted an embryo of the largest forest
antelope, the bongo, into the womb of a much more common species,
the eland in the early 1980s. (She also was responsible for the
world's first test-tube gorilla in 1995.) Dresser's work over the
years has proven how tricky it is to harvest mature, useable eggs
from various species. She suspects that the Tasmanian devil is a
species too different for easy egg transfer. But there may be an
animal out there whose eggs would work for both implantation and
gestation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are probably a long, long way from doing this,'' Dresser
says, ``but I will never say never.''
</P>
<P>
   Overstrom says the part of the cloning work that involves egg
compatibility and then the implantation into the host is not well
understood. Crossing species lines in the cloning process further
muddies the amniotic waters and going from doctored egg to womb to
newborn may, in fact, turn out to be ``species-specific.'' He says,
``We just don't understand the details of that process, going
across species.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to do this work with two related species _ buffalo and
cattle _ have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Third on the list of Overstrom's concerns: money and material.
It takes millions of dollars to fund a cloning project. And it
takes hundreds if not thousands of eggs to get one success.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, everyone, including the scientists, would like to
say that cloning a thylacine is possible. The Tasmanian tiger was a
unique creature that was, unfortunately, trapped and shot by humans
until it disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can acknowledge that, by our own ineptitude, a species was
wiped out,'' Overstrom says. ``And the humanistic part of us is
justified in wanting to correct that mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
