<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HALL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-ART     06-21 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HALL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... in that.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In fact, during our interview Hall downplays most of the horror
stories that have trailed him, vignettes that make him a prime
candidate for an ``E! Hollywood True Story'' pathography. In his
effort to escape the oblivion of projects like ``The Killing
Grounds'' and ``Into the Sun,'' he seems to be revising the canon
of negative media images: Hall as the 17-year-old party boy
``drinking vodka by the quart every day,'' as he told People in
1992; Hall as a terror on the movie set of 1986's ``Out of
Bounds,'' where crew members referred to him as ``Anthony Michael
Moron'' or simply ``The Brat''; Hall as the misguided careerist who
turned down roles in ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off'' and ``Pretty in
Pink'' and gave up the lead in Stanley Kubrick's ``Full Metal
Jacket'' because of ``scheduling and business,'' as he told the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fun, you know what I mean?'' he says now. ``It was never
disruptive. . . . Honestly. I didn't have the Sean Penn experience.
I didn't grow up in Malibu, I haven't punched people out, I haven't
done any of that. I think a lot of it is unfair.'' But there was a
punching incident reported in the Los Angeles Times in 1988, with
Hall quoted as saying, ``I slugged a guy in a club a few months
ago. My mother was singing there and some guy made a comment, so I
hit him. Of course, the press reported it, but I don't regret doing
it.'' Today, reminded of the incident, he says, ``I don't remember
punching anyone when I've worked. I have an Irish temperament, but
I am a professional.'' When pressed, he says, ``That's an old
thing. That was years ago. Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Hall doesn't embark on a confessional about his
ill-fated year on ``Saturday Night Live'' in 1985, when at 17 he
became the youngest-ever Not for Prime Time Player. ``I was rude to
a lot of people,'' he said in 1988. ``I was drinking on the set.''
Today, he says simply, ``It didn't take me long to realize I wasn't
a stand-up comic. It was difficult insofar as they didn't know how
to work with me. They didn't know what to write for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But who wants to push Hall back into the mire of publicity
mistakes past? He has a sincere desire to move forward to a day
when articles won't need to elaborate on his difficult years. ``A
lot of that was an unfair rap, honestly,'' he says. ``It wasn't
like I was lashing out at people. I feel like I'm going around with
this Lee Marvin image or something. . . . I have dedicated my life
to my work, and the challenging times have been 10 years since. . .
. The best publicity is to work and keep working. There's other
tragedies like Dana Plato that are very sad. I feel fortunate that
I kept my head on and persevered. A lot of people have been less
fortunate with more success.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with the 1990s has come an enlightened awareness of the
pitfalls of growing up on-screen. We have a better understanding of
the traumas of someone like Macaulay Culkin, who was similarly
squired into fame by John Hughes. ``I sacrificed, but I wouldn't
say that I suffered,'' Hall says. ``Suffering is Kosovo. But I feel
there were sacrifices involved _ being away from my family for
extended periods of time, forfeiting time in the school
environment. It was interesting to grow up in the industry where I
was subject and object. I look at it as a 15-year film school
education.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is now
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall says he passionately wanted to play Bill Gates, bad hair
and all, when he auditioned with ``Pirates of Silicon Valley''
director Martyn Burke. ``I told him that it mattered to me and that
I wanted to be involved. Oftentimes you leave meetings not having
said something like that, and connecting on some small level.''
</P>
<P>
   To create an impression of the real Gates, he watched
documentary footage and visited the Microsoft Web site. But he did
not have the chance to meet Gates, since Burke and TNT decided not
to tell an authorized story of either Microsoft or Apple. ``We
deconstructed Gates,'' Hall says. ``We didn't want to approach
parody, but I definitely wanted to get his tone. We did everything
from cutting up cotton balls or tampons on the set and, in some
scenes, stuffing them in my nose to get that nasal tone that he
has. Also his body language is interesting. We deciphered that at a
certain point he kind of left his body behind, it was all cerebral
energy. He kind of has this old man's gait to his walk.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance, like his smaller role in ``Six Degrees of
Separation'' in 1993, is a hint of what his acting future may
bring, if he can continue to land good parts. Meanwhile, he
recently produced an album of his own songs called ``Hall of
Mirrors,'' on which he sings and plays guitar, bass, and drums.
It's on sale through his Web site. He's also hoping to star in a
biopic about Robert Kennedy, either his own project or one
currently planned by TNT. To cultivate his career, he lives in
Marina del Rey, Calif., but he says he misses the street life of
New York City, where he spent much of his youth. ``I realized I had
to be out there. As they say, even Spielberg lives there.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes to return to Boston a few times a year. His
mother, Mercedes Hall, and her family are from West Roxbury.
``That's where I lived for the first couple of years of my life.
Then we moved. I have such a huge family. My mother is one of 13,
and so it's a classic Boston family. . . . I was like the 14th
child, because I was the first grandkid.'' He credits his mother,
his family, and his Northeast temperament for his ``survivor
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more relaxed and comfortable with myself now,'' he says.
``For a while, there was a lot to learn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
