<HEADLINE>
FILMS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!!! ``Buena Vista Social Club'' Musician Ry Cooder and
filmmaker Wim Wenders went to Cuba to capture on film a handful of
Cuban jazz giants whose careers have been in limbo during the
Castro era. Finding them alive and vital, this documentary provides
them with a chance to restart their careers, which ignite
irresistibly in a pair of concerts. (G) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The General's Daughter'' Bold, slick juggernaut of a
military murder mystery. The crude selling of a brutal sex crime on
a swampy army base undercuts potent performances by John Travolta
as an Army investigator who won't be swerved into a whitewash and
Madeleine Stowe as his sexy, savvy rape-counselor colleague. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Red Violin'' Handsome film about the journey of a
priceless 17th-century Cremonese violin whose owners don't have
much luck with it. Visually, it's a stunner; dramatically, it's not
_ it never stays with a character long enough or more than
superficially enough for us to attach to anyone. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Tarzan'' This lively take on the ape man as a sensitive
superstar athlete should reinvigorate the lagging Disney animation
franchise. It allows Tarzan to do things no live version could, and
finds the animators confidently working in the tradiitonal Disney
house style, abetted by computers. Tony Goldwyn voices Tarzan,
Minnie Driver voices Jane, and Glenn Close is another vocal plus as
Tarzan's adoptive gorilla mom. (G) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
