<HEADLINE>
EX-SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR CONSIDERS RUNNING AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Former Mayor Frank Jordan has taken preliminary
steps toward a campaign against the man who unseated him four years
ago, Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who served as mayor of San Francisco from January 1992
to January 1996, has filed a ``declaration of intent'' with the
Department of Elections, a move that allows him to solicit or
accept campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   He has until Aug. 6 to decide for certain whether he will run.
Meanwhile, campaign strategist David Looman, who is working with
Jordan, said they would use the next two months as an exploratory
period to raise money and test public reaction to the prospect of a
Jordan comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose job approval rating has steadily dipped in the
polls since he took office, defeated Jordan in the December 1995
run-off election, tallying 57 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, also a former police chief, has been hinting for months
that he was considering a rematch. The election is Nov. 2. Unless a
candidate wins a majority, there will be a runoff in December.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has kept a relatively low profile since he left office,
although he hasn't been shy about criticizing Brown over his
development plans for Treasure Island and for boosting city
spending by $1 billion. He said in a recent interview with that
Brown had been too cozy with special interest groups and with
helping his friends, rather than focusing on quality-of-life
issues.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Johnston, a spokesman for Brown's re-election campaign,
said his team welcomed Jordan into the campaign. ``Ultimately, it
will be the voters who will decide whether they want to keep the
city moving forward under Mayor Brown or whether they want to look
back to the Jordan years.''
</P>
<P>
   The voters, he said, spoke clearly in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem like it was a fairly decisive victory last time
around,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is one of 20 challengers who have filed declarations of
intent with the Department of Elections. Among them is Clint
Reilly, a businessman who, as a former campaign consultant, ran
Jordan's unsuccessful re-election race in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and Jordan, both considered law-and-order moderates who
relish the chance to take on waste in government spending, have
their strongest base in the West of Twin Peaks neighborhoods, which
are often San Francisco's most conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Several other high-profile politicos haven't ruled out
campaigns. Topping the list are Board of Supervisors President Tom
Ammiano; Supervisor Leland Yee, an Ammiano ally who chairs the
board's powerful Finance and Labor Committee; and Supervisor Gavin
Newsom, who was appointed by Brown but has been showing a growing
independence.
</P>
<P>
   David Binder, a San Francisco pollster who currently isn't
working for any mayoral candidate, said Jordan would most likely
face an uphill battle in trying to retake the mayor's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a lot of potential for Frank Jordan's campaign,''
Binder said. A poll he conducted in spring for another campaign
unrelated to the mayor's race found Jordan's negative ratings with
voters were higher than his positives.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed weren't ``adverse to Frank Jordan, the man,'' he
said. ``They think he's generally a good guy, well intended. But
there are many people who don't like his politics. They think he's
too conservative for San Francisco, and they don't think he was a
strong leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Bruzzone, an activist in Republican politics, suggested
that Jordan should be given a second chance, simply because he
faced circumstances _ such as a much less robust economy _ beyond
his control as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economy and city budget deficits, Jordan ran the
city without imposing significant tax increases or laying off
employees Bruzzone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably no one else in this city who deserves a
chance again to be mayor,'' Bruzzone said.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor, Jordan faced vigorous opposition from a more liberal
Board of Supervisors, which blocked many of his initiatives.
Advocates for the poor, particularly homeless activists, held
regular protests inside and outside the mayor's office after he
cracked down on nuisance crimes and welfare cheats. City employee
unions also took him on.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the shower.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of the mayor's race, Jordan, in a whimsical,
spontaneous campaign stunt, jumped into a shower _ naked _ with two
male disc jockeys from Los Angeles. A San Francisco Examiner
reporter and freelance photographer were on hand to capture the
moment (a photograph exposed Jordan from the waste up), landing the
story on the front page and provoking national attention.
</P>
<P>
   While the incident didn't decide Jordan's re-election chances,
it spawned countless jokes and has become part of his legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
