<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HYNDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISSIE HYNDE RETURNS WITH `VIVA L'AMORE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visiting Manhattan to promote her new album, Chrissie Hynde of
the Pretenders has just come from a photo shoot that threatened to
get testy. The photographer had brought along clothes for Hynde to
wear _ a common gesture in today's fashion-conscious photo spreads
_ but Hynde set her straight quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to use my own clothes,'' Hynde says she told the
photographer, ``and I won't say who made the clothes, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The photographer looked stunned, then asked, ``Have you always
dressed yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon Hynde burst out laughing and said, ``Look, if you had
tried to tell us how to dress in 1981, we would have cracked you in
the jaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hynde, a godmother of the punk scene, is still a total
individualist. This is a woman who wore a T-shirt with the words
``Have a nice death'' during her first tour with the Pretenders.
Today, after spending time as a single mom raising two children,
then marrying a Colombian sculptor (Lucho Brieva), she retains an
uncompromising spirit.
</P>
<P>
   That spirit flowers again on the Pretenders' new album, ``Viva
L'Amore,'' which comes out Tuesday. It doesn't rock as hard as
early Pretenders discs, but then what does? And the rock that does
adorn it is still bracingly vital, as heard in the guitar-stoked
``Legalize Me,'' ``Dragway 42,'' and the razor-edged ``Baby's
Breath,'' with Hynde reviving her caustic side: ``Why did you send
me roses? / Save them for someone's death,'' she sings. ``There was
a time when you thought I was in love with you / Well, think
again!''
</P>
<P>
   These songs are counterbalanced by some pretty, more positive,
sometimes gloppy love ballads and by the reflective thoughts in the
tune ``Human'': ``I crash, I burn, and maybe someday I'll learn /
I'm only human on the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Hynde even adds a song in Spanish, ``Rabo de Nube,'' about
finding hope; and, as if to demonstrate the versatility that
defines her adult-rock era, she features a wide array of album
guests, including guitar god Jeff Beck, lounge lizard David
Johansen, songwriter Jules Shear, and reggae-pop singer Ali
Campbell of UB40.
</P>
<P>
   She and the rest of the Pretenders _ Martin Chambers on drums,
Adam Seymour on guitar, and Andy Hobson on bass _ are also due to
play a bunch of Lilith Fair dates this summer, including an Aug. 3
date at the Tweeter Center in Mansfield with Sarah McLachlan,
Sheryl Crow, and several other strong-minded, female-fronted acts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she thinks of Lilith during our phone interview,
Hynde has a ready answer. ``It's show business, isn't it? Having
all women is kind of a gimmick. It's entertainment. I don't know if
it's supposed to be anything else, but for me, that's what it is. .
. . But it sounds like fun, like joining the circus for a couple of
weeks. And, surely, what self-respecting kid didn't want to do
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Taken overall, the Pretenders' new album marks an energetic
return for Hynde, 47, who grew up in Akron, Ohio, before moving to
London in the mid-'70s and sparking that city's blossoming new
wave-punk movement. She and the Pretenders went on to record such
hits as ``Precious,'' ``Brass in Pocket,'' ``Stop Your Sobbin' ''
(written by the Kinks' Ray Davies, who is the father of one of her
children), ``Back in the Chain Gang,'' ``Talk of the Town,''
``Don't Get Me Wrong,'' and ``I'll Stand by You.''
</P>
<P>
   Hynde's restored energy is also seen in the new album's cover _
a portrait of herself with fists in the air, taken by Linda
McCartney. ``It's got a revolutionary kind of vibe, which fits
nicely into my album title, which is `Viva L'Amore.' It's supposed
to sound like a revolutionary slogan,'' says Hynde.
</P>
<P>
   There are no firebrand politics on it, however, but the
controversial opening track, ``Popstar,'' has been interpreted as
Hynde's ranting about the record industry. On that cut, which has a
Lou Reed-like toughness, Hynde sings about the phony nature of some
of today's young teen stars who feel they have to resort to breast
implants to have a more videogenic image. ``After a couple of hits,
she'll be getting a new pair of (breasts),'' Hynde wails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds like I'm railing against the industry and
talking about the new breed of singers,'' says Hynde. ``But,
really, it's more about talking to an ex-boyfriend who is going out
with a young pop star.'' The climactic verse, directed to the
ex-boyfriend: ``They don't make 'em like they used to / You should
have stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hynde has made many personal changes in recent years _ besides
marrying, she gave up her longtime marijuana habit, partly to
please her nonsmoking husband. ``I had always mixed (pot) with
tobacco in the English style, so I quit the whole thing in one
go.''
</P>
<P>
   But something she doesn't see changing is the greed-driven
record industry. She's always been an outsider to it, and that
still holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you went back to the '50s, '60s, '70s, or any time, you
could always see a lot of evil doings in the industry,'' Hynde
says. ``As Otis Redding said, `Everything changes, but it still
remains the same.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hynde, that means she's still going her own way, is still
ruffling the industry, and is still making some of the best rock
'n' roll around, regardless of age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
