 Monday, June 21, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the
following stories for Tuesday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SLOVENIA (Ljubljana, Slovenia) _ President Clinton
visits Slovenia, the former Yugoslav republic that rejected
President Slobodan Milosevic and embraced independence, democracy
and the West. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court upholds the
death sentence of a Texas killer, dismissing his complaint that
jurors in his case were so confused by the judge's instructions
that they mistakenly opted to sentence him to death. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SEARCHES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
police generally do not need a warrant to search a car that they
believe is carrying illegal drugs. The court says a search warrant
is not required even if the police had plenty of time to get one
after receiving a tip that a car would be carrying drugs. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PLAYBOY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to hear a
Clinton administration appeal aimed at reviving a federal law
intended to shield children from sex-oriented cable TV networks. A
lower court judge struck down the law, saying it violates the
free-speech rights of channels such as Playboy Television. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN _ The House, unable to agree on a real solution to
the real problem of school violence, passed the buck to God by
granting states the right to permit the posting of the Ten
Commandments in schools and government buildings. Religion has its
place in life but it is not in the classroom. In any case the Ten
Commandments won't deter a single kid with a grudge and a gun. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
