<HEADLINE>
`NED DEVINE' BRILLIANT; `SWEETHEARTS' NOT FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Waking Ned Devine'' _ Casting is crucial in the
movie industry, and star David Kelly is perfect in the leading role
in writer-director Kirk Jones's brilliantly funny story of
deception, impersonation, and affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweethearts'' _ The cast includes star Janeane Garofalo and
supporting players Bobcat Goldthwait and Margaret Cho. So why isn't
this story of dating a lot funnier? Not smart enough to be this
serious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PICKFORD PICKS: Mary Pickford, the woman many consider to be the
first superstar, was also a very bright businesswoman. One of the
founders of United Artists _ along with Charlie Chaplin, D. W.
Griffith, and her husband, Douglas Fairbanks _ Pickford
revolutionized the way actors were handled by the studios. Billed
as ``America's Sweetheart,'' she was tough as nails. Five of
Pickford's films, all remastered and retinted, are now available
for $29.95 from Milestone Film &AMP; Video _ ``Stella Maris'' (1918),
``Amarilly of Clothes-line Alley'' (1918), ``Daddy Long-Legs''
(1919), ``Tess of the Storm Country'' (1922), and ``My Best Girl''
(1927).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
