<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS BLOOD IN VEINS ACTUALLY BLUE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is the blood in veins actually blue, turning red when it
mixes with oxygen in the lungs?
</P>
<P>
   B.M.N., Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Only if you live on Beacon Hill,'' replies Dr. Chris
Stowell, head of the blood bank at Massachusetts General Hospital.
In fact, not even in the truest blue-blooded Brahmin does blood run
anything other than red. But it does come in different shades of
red.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more oxygen it's carrying the redder it is,'' Dr. Stowell
explains. As blood comes out of the lungs with a fresh load of
oxygen, it's as bright as it gets. As it travels through the body,
releasing some of that oxygen, it darkens. By the time the blood is
on it's way back to the lungs, though it's still carrying 80
percent of it's oxygen capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Look inside your forearms. If you see any blood vessels that
look blue, it doesn't mean you're a Cabot or a Lowell. The veins
are carrying burgundy blood but they look blue to us because of the
way our skin and blood vessel walls transmit light. (Technically
speaking, there is less red light reflected from the shallow area
between the surface and the vessel than blue light because blue
light scatters more widely. The tissue around the vein reflects
back more red. This doesn't mean the vessel is really blue, only
that it looks blue.)
</P>
<P>
   And why is blood red in the first place? Red blood cells, which
look like a mini version of a jelly doughnut after somebody pushed
their thumb down on the middle, contain a special molecule called
hemoglobin, which has four iron atoms. The iron is the magnet that
grabs and holds the oxygen as the blood travels through the lungs,
then lets it go as it passes through the body. Each iron atom is
surrounded by a little ring of amino acids called porphyrin. The
combination of the porphyrin ring and iron atoms creates the red
color of our blood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the greatest earthquake that could occur on this
planet?
</P>
<P>
   S.B., Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The experts agree that it'll be tough to top the 9.5
magnitude quake 50 miles off the coast of Chile in 1960. That
massive event involved a huge section of ocean bottom being pushed
under the land mass of South America. It killed 5,700 people. It's
power was enough to raise sections of the Andes mountains 20 feet,
and the seismic waves it generated caused the earth to vibrate and
ring like a bell (though we couldn't hear it) for more than a
month.
</P>
<P>
   MIT Professor of Geophysics Nafi Toksoz says such a quake would
have the energy equivalent of 10 to the 25th power ergs _ a unit of
energy measurement equivalent to about 10 BTUs. That's one tenth of
the total amount of energy consumed by the United States in a year.
It is one hundred thousand times the amount of energy released by
the nuclear explosion over Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Why couldn't we get a bigger quake than that? Toksoz explains
that earthquakes occur along faults, places in the topmost layer of
the earth known as the crust or lithosphere of the earth, which is
roughly 60 miles deep, where sections of rock are sliding along one
another, pushing against one another, or pulling away from each
other. No evidence has ever been found of a fault zone being any
longer than the 680 miles-long fault that produced the Chilean
quake. The famous San Andreas fault in Southern California is 375
miles long.
</P>
<P>
   We usually hear about earthquake magnitude as measured by the
Richter scale, named for Charles Richter, a crusty seismologist
from the California Institute of Technology. It turns out Richter's
scale isn't precise for many quakes, especially big ones. But it's
not really his fault
</P>
<P>
   We've learned a lot about earthquakes since he set up his famous
scale in 1935. We now know they generate different kinds of waves.
Some shake the ground up and down, one full wave, once a minute.
Some create only one wave per hour. New England quakes create
several ground waves per second. There's a scale for each wave.
</P>
<P>
   We've also learned about different kinds of faults. Put your
hands together, pointed forward, and rub them sideways against each
other. That's called a ``strike-slip'' fault. That's how the San
Andreas moves. Now, hands together, slide one down compared with
the other. That's called a ``normal'' fault. Hands together again,
raise one up compare to the other. That's a ``thrust'' fault. We
get a lot of those in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Toksoz says geologists now favor the Moment Magnitude scale,
which simply measures how long the fault is, and how far the rock
on one side moved, or slipped compared to the other. Toksoz says
Chile showed 8.5 on the Richter scale, but a Moment Magnitude 9.5.
But Moment Magnitude isn't as precise for smaller quakes. So
several scales, including Richter's, will probably remain in use
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
