<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOOST FOR DISABLED WHO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Senator Edward Kennedy rose on the Senate floor on June 14,
he was confronting (not for the first time) one of those bizarre
realities that is only possible in an American legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, there was this overwhelmingly popular, very
carefully assembled proposal that will be transforming in its
impact on the better part of 8 million people plus their families _
the disabled who can work _ which on its merits had managed to
assemble no less than 78 co-sponsors by the moment Kennedy stood
up. It was what you would expect for an initiative that taps into
an almost desperate yearning to work and empowers it by making
health care affordable for those now dependent on federal income
maintenance payments.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, fronting for the Senate's hard-core
conservatives, there was one man _ Phil Gramm, the Texas Republican
_ blocking any scheduling of the measure on the floor. It was
staying blocked because of reflexive fears that anything remotely
resembling a new entitlement is necessarily dangerous. The proposal
had overwhelming, bipartisan support, including the strong backing
of all the relevant big shots, and yet it had to that moment
received no date for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason why we should be denied further opportunity
to consider this legislation,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Until there's a date from the fellow who presides
over this largely dysfunctional body, Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the Work Incentives Improvement Act will be an
amendment to whatever else happens to be on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he knew full well (from rich experience) that ``it
is a rather unusual process and procedure. I know the Senate has
its repsonsibilities, but there is also a responsibility to the
millions of Americans with disabilities. They have been waiting for
some period of time as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the possibility that Kennedy might act had already moved
Lott off his backside, leading to chats about scheduling the bill.
But by literally standing up for people who can't stand up on their
own, Kennedy sliced through the blockage like a knife through
butter. When he arose, the bill on the Senate floor was a spending
measure; that meant Budget Committee chairman Pete Domenici,
Republican of New Mexico, would now be going to Phil Gramm to
wonder why his ``hold'' on the disability bill was messing up his
own legislation; and that meant the same would happen for all the
other items lucky enough to be on Lott's desultory agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, within three days of Kennedy's maneuver, time
for floor consideration had been hastily arranged, Gramm's concerns
swept aside. The measure passed by the razor-thin margin of 99-0.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the margin involved far more than just the fact
it had the support of the four senators with relevant expertise and
power: Labor Committee chairman Jim Jeffords, Republican of
Vermont, and ranking Democrat Kennedy; and Finance Committee
chairman Bill Roth, Republican of Delaware, and ranking Democrat
Pat Moynihan of New York.
</P>
<P>
   It also involved substance and logic. Oversimplified, the bill
will keep care and health insurance affordable for disabled people
who require expensive treatments or expensive medicine in order to
work. Currently, there are millions of people who would have a job
literally tomorrow if it didn't rob them of the care that makes
work possible.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, states could offer the disabled a chance to
maintain comphrehensive coverage under Medicaid, with cost-sharing
on a sliding scale with income. They could also cover people with
Social Security disability insurance under Medicare after they
start working.
</P>
<P>
   And, to greatly improve the opportunities for the disabled to
work, the bill would create a new payment system for employment
services, authorizing government funds to rehabilitation or
training providers based on a portion of the cash benefits that are
no longer necessary after somebody starts working.
</P>
<P>
   No one is really sure that any of this will cost a dime over
time, given the explosion in job opportunities _ and therefore
income tax revenue _ that it is certain to produce.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that it took a good old-fashioned use of political
muscle by Kennedy to make this happen. Unlike most pols, however,
Kennedy played hardball on behalf of the disabled instead of some
big-bucks campaign contributor seeking a tax break. He's done it
all his life, and he will do it again this year on behalf of a
higher minimum wage and greater rights for health care consumers
known as patients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For anyone who has trouble grasping that Kennedy's ties to the
voters are based on far more than mystique and money, there was one
perfect example in the Senate last week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
