<HEADER>
A3818 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-     06-21 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-FELICITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SENSE OF `FELICITY': BEHIND THE SCENES ON TELEVISION'S FAVORITE
NEW DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Keri Russell, Scott Speedman and Scott
Foley in a scene from ``Felicity.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, ``Felicity'' was being hailed by critics as
1998/99's only can't-miss new show _ and also suffering the
customary bashing that comes with front-runner status.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone had an opinion about ``Felicity,'' including plenty of
people who'd never seen a second of it.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the WB drama about a pert California teen (Keri
Russell) who moves to New York to attend college _ and pursue her
handsome high-school classmate, Ben (Scott Speedman) _ has
established itself as a solid hit, not to mention making stars of
Russell, Speedman and Scott Foley, who plays the third leg of their
triangle, the thoroughly decent Noel.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Felicity,'' Russell's biggest credit was a gig on ``The
New Mickey Mouse Club.'' Speedman had virtually no acting
experience, having been cast purely on the basis of a killer
audition tape.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Russell says, getting used to the show has been much
like the adjustments their characters have gone through as
first-year college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a parallel there,'' she says. ``None of us
knew what to expect when this all started. This show was a lot
different from anything I had ever worked on before, and it took
some adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when I first signed onto the show, I was so
excited, but I was also so scared,'' she recalls. ``It was
completely overwhelming. Now I feel like I know what's going on,
and I know how to handle all the publicity and craziness. I have a
better sense of awareness, and I know how to pace myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedman says he never felt overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody kept telling me what a crazy year it was going to
be,'' he says, ``but it wasn't. I mean, it was crazy at times, but
that was mostly because of the workload and long hours. It was
pretty weird, but not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As the title character, Russell naturally got a more
concentrated version of the hype. She's become used to seeing her
character dissected as a role model _ and faring better than such
past victims as Murphy Brown or Ally McBeal _ and says she's been
delighted by the show's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get tons of letters,'' she says, ``and everyone is just
completely cool. It's the same thing with the way people respond in
public _ they're pretty laid back: They don't come up screaming,
`There's Felicity!' They usually just come up and say, `We think
your show is so cool.'
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to be a little calmer, I guess, compared to fans
of other shows,'' she adds. ``But those are the type of people the
show attracts. Our viewers are really intelligent. They're not
screaming, unless it's a pack of 12-year-old boys or something.
They always have positive things to say about the show, so for the
most part it's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedman adds that the difference is more noticeable when they
get away from Los Angeles, which he says prides itself on letting
celebrities alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many actors down there, they can't tell one from
the next,'' he says. ``It's when you go to a small town that it
gets kind of strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans seem to be really polite,'' he says. ``They're not
overwhelming. We've got a small, really hardcore audience. Those
people who've come up to me are just really polite.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the fans do get excited about, however, is Felicity's
vacillating between her longstanding crush on the often-arrogant
Ben and her new interest in the lower-key Noel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the neighborhood I live in, there's an all-girl school,''
Russell says. ``I would be riding my bike to the post office or
whatever, and these girls would always come up to me and ask who I
liked better, Ben or Noel. Then they would chant, `Noel! Noel!
You've got to choose Noel!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the occasional few of them liked Ben,'' she says with a
joking sneer at Speedman. ``But I really liked the idea that girls
like Noel best, because he's definitely more of a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a period for about a month last season where Ben
just got hit with one thing after another,'' Speedman says
defensively. ``He had a gambling problem, and so on. There was no
good news for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the writers make Noel a really pleasant guy, so there's
not much comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   The series began as a star turn for Russell, but seems to be
evolving into an ensemble show _ a development which she says suits
her just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea that we've become an ensemble cast,'' the
actress says. ``And it did make things a bit easier on me. I'm
still working a lot, but it's a lot easier than those first few
episodes, when I was in almost every scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also some really talented people in our cast,''
Speedman adds. ``They deserve their chance, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity'' fans rave about the show's music, which offers a
much wider range than most teen shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely love the music on our show,'' Russell says,
beaming. ``Our music supervisor, Amanda Demme, is fabulous. Look at
our soundtrack album that was just released _ it has people like
Kate Bush, Peter Gabriel, Aretha Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just teenybopper little songs,'' she says. ``It's the
same kind of music that I like listening to.''
</P>
<P>
   The series seems likely to continue indefinitely, but Speedman
doubts that it will rack up anything like the nine-year run of
``Beverly Hills, 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all, like, 40 years old now,'' he groans. ``That show
is like a factory, just pushing out product. I'd leave the show if
we ever got like that _ which isn't likely to happen. Our show is
so different. We have great writers, and the quality control is
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as much as either is willing to say about the future.
Nothing closer-range _ such as how they'll resolve last season's
teaser ending, which left Felicity torn between going to Europe
with Noel or driving home to California with Ben.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to know what happens,'' Russell says, laughing.
``So many people have been asking me that question. And they're
just writing the new season right now, so it's still up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of know what's going to happen,'' she says teasingly,
``but I have to keep quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
