<SLUG> BC-KEVIN-KLINE-IN-WILD-WILD-WEST-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEST'-WARD HO! KEVIN KLINE GOES WILD WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kevin Kline with Will Smith in a scene
from ``Wild Wild West.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``How many actors does it take to screw in a light bulb?'' Kevin
Kline asks.
 &HT;    The Oscar-winning actor pauses, then offers the punch line.
 &HT;    ``It takes 15 actors,'' he says. ``One to actually screw the
light bulb in and 14 to debate if they could have done it better if
given the role.''
 &HT;    It's a strange joke to hear from an actor, but then Kline is not
a typical actor. He thinks of himself as a character actor, but has
the dashing good looks of a leading man. He's a workaholic, but he
spends a long time waiting for good roles to come along.
 &HT;    He loves the written word, but you'll rarely find him poring
through scripts for those elusive roles.
 &HT;    ``I hate reading scripts,'' Kline explains. ``It's like looking
at a blueprint for someone's house you probably have no intention
of visiting.''
 &HT;    Kline's latest role is a fine example of his ambiguous status in
Hollywood. It's a part that seems ideal for him, with plenty of
opportunities for the off-center comedy which is perhaps his
greatest skill _ but it came his way only after another actor
passed on it. It was originally intended for George Clooney, a
television star whose resume features only a fraction as many
movies as Kline's, not to mention one fewer Oscar.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, when ``Wild Wild West'' opens on June 30, the
megabudget summer blockbuster will find Kline co-starring with Will
Smith as two heroes in post-Civil War America, trying to thwart the
evil plans of mad scientist Arliss Loveless (Kenneth Branagh).
 &HT;    It can be a bad career move to pick up a role that another actor
has already spurned, but Kline says he had no hesitation in
accepting the part of Artemus Gordon, the master-of-disguise
gadgetmeister who's partnered with Secret Service agent James West
(Smith).
 &HT;    ``I loved the script because it was unlike anything I'd ever
read,'' the actor says. ``It was just filled with incidents and
action sequences and one event after another _ it was
irresistible.''
 &HT;    Besides, he adds, the chance to do comedy appealed to him.
 &HT;    ``It was the perfect anecdote to `Ivanhoe,' which is what I was
doing on stage last year,'' Kline says. ``A lot of times I choose
things according to what I'm doing now _ I always want to do
something very, very different.''
 &HT;    Certainly, Gordon is an unusual character, one that Kline found
intriguing.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to make him nonviolent. He is actually someone who
abhors violence,'' Kline says. ``I also wanted to make him more
cerebral than instinctive. He needs his wits in order to survive.''
 &HT;    He didn't check out Ross Martin's approach to the role in the
original 1960s television series, he adds.
 &HT;    ``I have never seen the show in my life,'' Kline says. ``What if
I didn't like it?''
 &HT;    Besides, he adds, ``I never base a performance on another's
performance.''
 &HT;    It's been a busy year for Kline, who early this spring was seen
as the megalomaniacal aspiring actor Bottom in ``William
Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' Puncturing Bottom's
pretensions was catnip for Kline.
 &HT;    ``I admit I have a very low threshold for pompous people,'' the
actor says. ``In high school, I had such a problem with authority.
I found it so absurd and overdone.''
 &HT;    Kline grew up in St. Louis, the son of a Jewish father and a
Catholic mother _ which may account for his troubles in a Catholic
high school ran by Benedictine monks.
 &HT;    ``I was the class wit,'' he says. ``I couldn't not talk back. I
was the smartass.
 &HT;    ``I went to a school where there was corporal punishment, so I
was beaten on my hands,'' Kline says. ``But even though my hands
hurt so much I couldn't make a fist, I would still act up.
 &HT;    ``There was one teacher _ we really had it in for each other,''
he recalls. ``I remember he'd come in and I'd actually throw myself
out of class. Why wait for him to do it?''
 &HT;    At the time he had no plans to become an actor, but gradually he
was drawn in that direction by early inspirations ranging from
Laurence Olivier, Paul Newman and Marlon Brando to Jerry Lewis,
W.C. Fields and the Marx Brothers.
 &HT;    ``I never had one dramatic moment where I said, `I have to be an
actor,''' he says. ``I think just watching certain actors do
certain roles over a period of time influenced me.''
 &HT;    After studying at New York's prestigious Juilliard School, Kline
found work with touring theater companies almost immediately. It's
a source of pride to him that he's always earned his living by
acting.
 &HT;    ``I never had to work as a waiter,'' Kline says. ``I would have
been terrible. I'm sure I would have told the truth about which
specials sucked.''
 &HT;    A role on the daytime soap opera ``Search for Tomorrow''
(1976-77) took Kline back to New York, where he subsequently became
a stage favorite, winning Tony awards for ``On the Twentieth
Century'' (1978) and ``The Pirates of Penzance'' (1980) and
starring in two critically acclaimed productions of ``Hamlet.''
 &HT;    His screen debut came opposite Meryl Streep in 1982's ``Sophie's
Choice.'' A variety of film roles followed, ranging from wild
comedy _ his Oscar-winning turn as a dimwitted hit man in ``A Fish
Called Wanda'' (1988) and his double performance in ``Dave'' (1993)
_ to such heavy dramas as ``Grand Canyon'' (1991) and ``The Ice
Storm'' (1997).
 &HT;    All of which doesn't change the fact that right now Kline is
looking for work.
 &HT;    ``That's the horrible thing about acting,'' he says. ``When
you're not working, you're in essence unemployed.''
 &HT;    Not that he minds the chance to spend time in New York with
actress Phoebe Cates, his wife of 10 years, and their children. But
he admits that he's getting itchy, and is thinking about a return
to the stage, possibly in Shakespeare.
 &HT;    On the film front, he adds, things are less encouraging.
 &HT;    ``I take my agent's word for it if I should read something,'' he
says with a grimace. ``Most of the film scripts are just awful. I
assume you've been to the movies lately, so you know what I mean.
 &HT;    ``It's hard for an actor,'' he adds, ``because today's scripts
are works in process. You'll hear, `It's the 13th draft, and we
have a new writer coming in.' I'm like, `Why don't you just send it
to me when you're finished?'
 &HT;    ``I'll hear, `We are finished _ except we've got a new middle, a
new beginning and we'll probably redo the ending.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, he says, his passion for acting remains undimmed.
 &HT;    ``I think the best aspect of an artist is his desire to probe
and communicate a notion larger than himself,'' Kline says. ``You
can also use acting to shed light on your particular existence.''
 &HT;    Long active in programs to encourage and support rising young
actors, Kline says that their talent, passion and commitment helps
keep him dedicated to his own work.
 &HT;    ``The highest compliment I can give them is, `I envy you. I
wanted to play that part.'''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
