<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JULIANNE-MOORE-IN-AN-     06-21 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULIANNE-MOORE-IN-AN-IDEAL-HUSBAND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIANNE MOORE'S WALK ON THE WILDE SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Julianne Moore in a scene from ``An
Ideal Husband.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    We've seen Julianne Moore doing an extended monologue naked from
the waist down. We've seen her fleeing for her life from rampaging
dinosaurs. We've seen her having sex with a spectacularly
well-endowed porn star.
 &HT;    But this is something new.
 &HT;    ``An Ideal Husband,'' being released throughout the United
States in June and July, takes Moore into Helena Bonham Carter
territory. Based on Oscar Wilde's play, the film is set in 1890s
England, with all the elaborate costumes, sumptuous scenery and
painstakingly perfect manners which that implies.
 &HT;    And her co-stars are period-piece veterans, one and all: Rupert
Everett plays a shameless womanizer, Jeremy Northam an honest
politician with a dark secret and Cate Blanchett as his adoring
wife.
 &HT;    Moore? Well, she plays Mrs. Cheveley, a deceptively pleasant
woman who's learned Northam's secret, and whose flawless demeanour
masks a ruthless determination to play it for all it's worth.
 &HT;    In short, she plays arguably the film's most complicated
character _ which means we're on Julianne Moore turf after all.
 &HT;    There may not have been many corsets or brittle epigrams in a
filmography that includes memorable, naturalistic performances in
such films as ``The Hand that Rocks the Cradle'' (1992), ``Short
Cuts'' (1993), ``Safe'' (1995), ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park''
(1997), ``Boogie Nights'' (1997) and ``Cookie's Fortune'' (1999),
but Moore says she didn't have many qualms in tackling
writer/director Oliver Parker's film.
 &HT;    ``I'd done plenty of period work and acted in the classics when
I went to acting school,'' the Boston University graduate says.
``It's just that I hadn't done those things on screen. Doing this
didn't feel alien to me. A lot of my film roles have been very
contemporary, so it may be new for the audience, but it wasn't
particularly new to me.
 &HT;    ``The dialogue was a bigger challenge,'' Moore says by
telephone, speaking from the streets of New York as she walks
hurriedly across town for a doctor's appointment. ``Anytime you're
dealing with a specific style of dialogue, it's challenging.
Wilde's language is inherently theatrical, which is part of the
beauty of it, but you can't do too much of that in a film, because
it just doesn't work.
 &HT;    ``For all of us, especially Oliver Parker, the goal was to make
it somewhat naturalistic and more accessible,'' she says. ``I hope
we pulled that part of it off.''
 &HT;    Most difficult of all, the actress says, was to balance her
performance so that the audience wouldn't be entirely put off by
Mrs. Cheveley and her underhanded machinations.
 &HT;    ``That was tough,'' she says, then breaks off to chastise
someone for zipping through a yellow light.
 &HT;    ``I sometimes think I could have gone further with the
villainy,'' she resumes. ``When I look at the film, I think, `Oh,
what the hell! She is the villainess.'
 &HT;    ``It was hard, because you need to keep people interested, but
you don't want people thinking, `Oh, just get that horrible woman
out of here!'
 &HT;    ``The way I tried to approach it was that she's an incredibly
self-directed person,'' Moore says. ``She's not necessarily evil,
but she just really, really knows what she wants, and is more than
willing to do what she has to do to get it.
 &HT;    ``And, as she's doing everything she does, she's really enjoying
herself,'' the actress concludes. ``I loved that part of playing
her.''
 &HT;    Moore admits that she was wary of her status as the only
American on the set, but adds that it didn't turn out to be a
problem.
 &HT;    ``Being around so many Brits made me more and more American,
strangely enough,'' she says. ``When I was younger and was around
Brits, I'd try to be more British or at least squelch my
American-ness. On this job, for some reason, I got to be enormously
American _ it became my one defining characteristic.
 &HT;    ``I don't think anyone else on the set cared or even noticed.''
 &HT;    Moore's resume includes hits and flops alike, independent
features, modest studio productions and blockbusters in turn. The
actress admits, with a giggle, that there isn't any one
consideration behind her decision-making process.
 &HT;    ``It's often the script,'' she says. ``It's often the character
and it's often the director. Sometimes it's the other actors.
 &HT;    ``I really love to work, so if something in a film interests me
I'll probably do it,'' she concludes. ``Of course, I'd like for as
many elements at once to be there, but's that not always the
case.''
 &HT;    And, oh yes, there's the money. Unlike some other actors, Moore
readily admits that there are some movies she does simply for the
paycheck.
 &HT;    ``I do a movie like `Safe' and I lose money,'' she says.
``People will say, `Why did you do such and such?' and it's like,
`Look, I'm a person. I have a family _ I need to pay my mortgage
and I need to feed my child.'
 &HT;    ``It's not like we all stand around, do parts and people throw
money at us,'' she says with a laugh. ``On some movies we make a
really good living, and on some jobs we make nothing.
 &HT;    ``There are always financial considerations to think about.''
 &HT;    Her next couple of movies, however, definitely are ones she has
her heart in. She reteams with Paul Thomas Anderson, director of
``Boogie Nights,'' for the ensemble drama ``Magnolia,'' and then
co-stars with Sigourney Weaver in ``The Map of the World,'' a
somber piece about a woman (Moore) whose daughter accidentally
drowns while playing in the yard of a neighbor (Weaver).
 &HT;    Then there's ``The End of the Affair,'' based on the Graham
Greene novel. Directed by Neil Jordan, it teams Moore with Ralph
Fiennes and Stephen Rea.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, it's got the most beautiful story in the world,''
Moore says enthusiastically. ``I hadn't read the novel when I read
the script, so I came to it completely cold. I just couldn't
believe it when I finished the script.
 &HT;    ``It's about a writer (Fiennes) who, during World War II, has an
affair with a woman (Moore) who's married to a government employee
(Rea),'' she says. ``It's about what happens to these people's
lives as a result of the affair. It's just a really poetic,
wonderfully moving story about love and grief and human nature.''
 &HT;    Nowadays stories about the fundamental issues of life resonate
with Moore, who in the last couple of years has had her own view of
the world redefined. While shooting ``The Myth of Fingerprints''
(1997), she fell in love with the film's director, Bart Freundlich.
They quickly had a child, Caleb, now 18 months old.
 &HT;    Becoming a mother, Moore says, changed her sense of herself, her
life and the entire world.
 &HT;    ``I don't mean to sound too deep, but it just connects you to
the chain of human events in a really, really wonderful way,''
Moore says. ``That's what was completely unexpected about it for
me.
 &HT;    ``Everybody talks about that and writes about that, but you
don't really understand it until you experience it for yourself,
until you move from being the child to being the parent,'' she
says. ``It's given me a lot of perspective, and that alters how I
approach my life and my work.''
 &HT;    With a mom who's an actress and a dad who directs, the boy seems
all but predestined to be an actor.
 &HT;    ``I think so,'' Moore says with obvious pride. ``Caleb's
wonderfully expressive. Actually, he loves to dance, so we might
have a dancer before we have an actor.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``An Ideal Husband,'' consult
the Miramax Films Website at www.miramax.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
