<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-BOGOSIAN-BOS &LR;      06-21 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BOGOSIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERIC BOGOSIAN HAS NOTHING BUT QUESTIONS ON HIS MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Listening to Eric Bogosian talk is a bit like watching
a one-man intellectual Ping-Pong match: He's been having a heated
debate with himself, on and off the stage, since he began writing
and performing solo shows 20 years ago. Should he sell his soul to
Hollywood or should he devote himself to art? Is he simply ``the
guy in the Steven Seagal movie'' (``Under Siege 2: Dark
Territory'') or is he a philosopher/playwright? Is he a brooding
cynic, deliberately detached from the main, or is he just another
middle-class mensch with a wife, two kids, and a picket fence? Is
he arrogant and self-centered, or is he terrified of ``losing his
chops''? Is he a ``dangerous bad guy'' or a ``boring middle-aged
putz''?
</P>
<P>
   The answers depend on the situation and the time of day _ that
is, if you can get any answer at all. ``I'm a question guy, not an
answer guy,'' he says, admitting that he is full of clashing
convictions. The endless introspection, fraught with nervous
energy, finds its way into his art. ``There are days when I'm
feeling sharp and smart, and then there are days when I'm feeling
insecure,'' he says. ``I mine all those thoughts for the dark days,
and I put all the pettiness and selfishness into my characters. I
make work about all the petty, stupid stuff, but at the same time,
I hear that other voice about a higher plane of values.'' A pause.
``Oh, God, this is so full of. . . .'' Inner contradictions, if you
will.
</P>
<P>
   Life for Bogosian is a never-ending point-counterpoint. Voices
bounce around in his head, and those contrary thoughts find their
way into his latest work, ``Wake Up and Smell the Coffee,'' which
opens a weeklong engagement Tuesday at the American Repertory
Theatre in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   In such celebrated early works as ``Sex, Drugs, Rock &AMP; Roll''
and ``Drinking in America,'' the chameleonlike performer presented
a gallery of characters, folks like the fatuous producer, the
vacuous pill popper, and the unctuous preacher. He paraded these
sharply etched portraits onstage one after the other, but in the
new show, he mixes them up for the first time, interrupting his own
monologues with competing characters. He connects all these voices
with a leitmotif about a plane crash. ``The whole mind-set of the
piece is about ambition and crashing in America today,'' he says.
``What happens in airports is a lot of waiting and running. Just
waiting in line seems to be the contemporary condition.''
</P>
<P>
   And you know what happens when you wait in line. You think. You
question. You obsess. That seems to be the Bogosian condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a point in my life where I'm looking over my shoulder
and saying, `Who am I, and what have I been doing for the last 20
years?' '' says Bogosian, 46. ``Because I talk so much about
issues, I really have to ask myself, `Yeah, so? You have all these
smartass things to say, and what good does it do, really?' That's
an honest question I ask myself, and it comes up in the
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, so?
</P>
<P>
   ``I beg the question,'' he says. ``Maybe the answer is felt by
the audience. The more we try to explain it, the more we're missing
the point. It's like when you study Shakespeare, all you talk about
is the plot lines and the ideas and the themes and the history of
whether there really was a Hamlet. But when people went and saw
those plays originally, they didn't think about any of that stuff.
If you overintellectualize this stuff, you kill it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Explaining himself
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, he says he hates trying to explain himself
publicly, but on the other hand, he isn't afraid to call a reporter
and ask for an interview. ``The work should speak for itself, but
you gotta be on the drive-time show at 7 a.m. and have some DJ go,
`All right, we got Eric Bogosian here, and he's really wild.' What
I would really prefer to be is J. D. Salinger and say, `Here's the
work. Goodbye.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Bogosian also allows that he's flirted with celebrity over
the years, appearing in more than a dozen films, including the
Seagal action picture. He starred in the film adaptation of his
play ``Talk Radio,'' which was directed by Oliver Stone. His play
``subUrbia'' was also made into a film. Today he says he lives in
``a kind of twilight zone of semi-celebrity,'' hardly J. D.
Salinger. But now that he's well into his 40s _ ``I'm so old; I
look terrible'' _ he isn't as conflicted as he once was about
alternating the film work and the stage work. He also isn't
interested in projecting the image of the angry young man he
cultivated when he left his native Woburn for the New York
performance art scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of Woburn, coming out of the '60s, coming out of
the downtown New York punk scene, I carried all this attitude,'' he
says. ``I think shedding that attitude is part of my journey. Maybe
it's OK to admit at the end of the day that I'm nothing more than a
sort of bookish, wimpy guy. I get into my feelings, but then I
really can't stand doing that in the end, so I have to diss that as
well. It really is like living in an echo chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought leads to another stream of assertions and
contradictions. He is delving into spirituality, reading ancient
texts, but then again, he hates evangelical hypocrisy, and he
skewers it in his show. He has gotten over his irrational fears,
but then again, he's terrified of cable cars and roller coasters
and any vehicle that goes clank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Angst making art
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It goes on and on, this endless self-scrutiny. ``I guess I'm a
little crazy, but I wouldn't be able to make work if I wasn't,'' he
says. ``As long as it isn't hurting me or making me feel bad _
well, it sort of makes me feel bad at times _ but that's who I am,
and that's always been the case. It's not the bogeyman that it was
when I was a kid, and today, I actually feel blessed that that's
the way my head works.''
</P>
<P>
   Those blessed contradictions infuse ``Wake Up and Smell the
Coffee,'' which is directed by Bogosian's wife, Jo Bonney. Bogosian
uses his nervous energy and angst to create a cacophony of voices
that mirrors his own chaotic thought process _ and, by extension,
reflects the overwhelming and competing forms of communication of
the information age.
</P>
<P>
   Bogosian has been honing the piece for four years; it has
changed since he performed it at Trinity Repertory Company in
Providence in 1995. He says there's nothing he loves more than
working on his plays, and there's nothing more terrifying than the
fear of losing his writer's touch. (Except maybe cable cars.) He
despaired in 1997 when his then-new play, ``Griller,'' performed at
the Goodman Theatre in Chicago, was poorly received. ``I didn't
solve the play, and when I really applied myself, I still couldn't
figure it out,'' he confesses. ``I think I'm afraid of losing my
chops or not being as smart as I want to be. That's really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's now free to labor on his plays; the occasional
Hollywood gigs provide financial security and support his art. ``I
make money so I can write plays, whether anyone wants me to or
not,'' he says. ``That's the sort of scary existential situation
that I've been passing through over the last five or six years.
I've had more and more freedom to do whatever the hell I want.''
But even that raises a final question. ``Then you say, `So what is
that? So do it already. Shut up.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
