<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, June 22:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The agreement reached early
Monday to disband the Kosovo Liberation Army included, at the
insistence of its commanders, a pledge by the NATO allies to
consider letting the rebels form a provisional army for Kosovo
modeled on the U.S. National Guard. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Dateline to be determined) _ Status/future of
KLA; interview with top rebel commander Ceku. By Carlotta Gall.
Eds: Tentative, may hold.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WOMEN-ASSAULT (Zrze, Yugoslavia) _ In interviews over the
last two weeks, dozens of women and men in Kosovo and in refugee
camps in Albania told stories that suggest that sexual assault and
intimidation, if not rape, were widespread, common and used by
Serbian forces to strike at the heart of a society in which the
virginity and fidelity of Muslim women is central. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Grace, Yugoslavia) _ NATO tries to control
Albanians who are looting and burning Serbian homes. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Ljubljana, Slovenia) _ President Clinton praises
Slovenia for being first Yugo republic to break with Milosevic;
also says he would like to be the U.N. czar of Kosovo. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION-ASSESS (Jakarta) _ Indonesians have remained
remarkably patient as they wait out the slow, confused counting of
the parliamentary votes they cast two weeks ago. But it seems that
whatever the outcome, the will of the people may in large part be
denied. By Seth Mydans. Eds: May hold.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-TALKS (Beijing) _ North Korean officials failed to turn up
for high-level talks with their South Korean counterparts here
Monday, complaining that the South had failed to meet a Sunday
deadline to deliver 22,000 tons of fertilizer to North Korea, South
Korean officials here said. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   TOGO-EYADEMA (Lome, Togo) _ A year after winning re-election in
voting that was widely considered tainted, President Gnassingbe
Eyadema has continued to tighten his three-decade hold on his
nation's politics, preserving his status as sub-Saharan Africa's
longest-ruling head of state. Eds: May hold.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-EVANGELIST (Funabashi, Japan) _ Former Japanese gangster
starts a church, saying he has found Jesus, and takes his mission
to the streets to recruit Japanese outcasts. By Stephanie Strom.
Eds: May hold.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ Lede on whether states can impose
professional license fees on federal judges. Supreme Court says
fees are allowed, as long as they apply to state judges, too. Other
cases including regulating obscene material on cable television. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ First case interpreting new
federal death penalty law, upholding a death sentence, and agreeing
with prosecution on jury directions, and other details. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ White House memo on the president,
military action, other issues, and public opinion. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ATTORNEYS-GENERAL (Washington) _ The GOP kicks off a big
effort to elect Republicans in more states as attorney general,
pointing out that high-profile issues, from guns to tobacco, will
be decided by those state officials. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON (Naval Weapons Base Concord, Calif.) _
During World War II, an explosion on a segregated naval base here
killed 320 men. After the accident, black sailors were ordered to
resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty of them refused, were
court-martialed by an all-white panel, found guilty of mutiny and
imprisoned. Now, in an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for one
black veteran have filed for a presidential pardon arguing that the
black sailors failed to follow orders out of legitimate fear and
had no intent to mutiny. The petition pits the racial symbolism of
a celebrated case against the military's view that servicemen
cannot choose which orders to obey. By William Glaberson. Eds: May
hold.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and a map.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-DENTAL (Manchester, N.H.) _ Even though the vast
majority of the poorest Americans, particularly children, are
covered by Medicaid for dental care, they are not getting it. Why
not? Several reasons, experts say. Most dentists tend to be loath
to take Medicaid patients because the program scrimps on payments
and involves pencil-breaking bureaucracy; also, Medicaid patients,
often with transport and day care problems, are likelier to miss
appointments. By Carey Goldberg. Eds: May hold.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-POLITICS (Baton Rouge) _ After a few years of relative
political quiet, Louisiana is reverting to traditional chaotic
form. A look at several events, focusing on the recently disclosed
alliance between the governor and David Duke, via the payment for
the list of supporters. The GOP split over an effort to distance
itself from the Christian Coalition. One senior official was locked
out of his office. And several unusual bills in the Legislature,
including one requiring students to address teachers with ``Sir''
or ``Miss.'' By David Firestone. Eds: May hold.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENTAL-PATIENTS (Undated) _ Chronically ill patients with
limited or no health insurance are increasingly filling a demand
for experimental drug study participants as drug companies rush
record numbers of new medications through the testing process. For
these people, experiments have become treatments; clinical
investigators are their specialists. But the benefit can be
fleeting or nonexistent. Chronically ill patients with no other
options can be treated with an experimental medication that does
not work or that even worsens their condition. Or they can end up
with a placebo rather than the medication itself. And once the
study is over, usually in a matter of weeks, they are left to their
own devices. By Gina Kolata and Kurt Eichenwald. Eds: May hold.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-QUOTAS (Washington) _ Looking ahead to expected Senate
vote Tuesday on steel import quota bill. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MERGERS-SHIPLEY (Undated) _ In an industry that has seen many
careers and companies derailed by bungled mergers, Walter Shipley
has quietly pulled off two of the biggest banking mergers in
history, folding Manufacturers Hanover, Chemical and Chase
Manhattan together to create a leader in the rapidly changing
financial services business. And Shipley, who retired as Chase's
chief executive on June 1 but will remain chairman, has advice for
dealmeisters hoping to ride America's merger wave: Slash-and-burn
takeovers will come back to haunt you. ``Our philosophy is that the
best is when both sides feel they've come out winners,'' he said.
By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-COKE (Undated) _ Developments: Coca-Cola meets with
Belgian officials over lifting a ban on Coke, Fanta and Sprite and
takes out full-page ads in French newspapers to reassure consumers.
The European Union has asked Belgium and France to investigate
further why more than 200 people got sick after drinking Coca-Cola.
By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   SURVEY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The next phase of a major
multi-year communications effort to promote the importance of
advertising is getting under way _ and not a moment too soon,
judging by the results of a national survey of top executives. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Dateline to be determined) _ Commentary by Anthony
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Dateline to be determined) _ ``Foreign
Affairs'' by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
