POP 
Produced and directed by: Joel Meyerowitz 
Date: Tuesday, 9 p.m. 
On: PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well known and respected for his color photography, Joel
Meyerowitz has now made a film, his first, called ``Pop.'' Produced
for ``Frontline,'' it's a highly personal account of a road trip
Meyerowitz took with his elderly father, who was suffering with
Alzheimer's disease, from the older man's adopted home in Florida
to the block in the Bronx where the family lived when Joel was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerowitz's acclaimed still photography is so finely attuned to
his sense of geometric form and the brilliance of light, it was
hard to imagine him being comfortable with moving images. Would he
be able to relax his control enough to give the family chronicle
air and life? Wouldn't he helplessly overwhelm the human themes
with obsessive attention to painterly images?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is simple, and gladdening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop'' is a filial love poem driven naturally by the dynamic of
Hy Meyerowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, son Joel can't suppress his formal artistry, so the
hourlong film offers some striking images _ of stringent Atlantic
seascapes, fine low skies filmed through the car windshield,
elegant-looking human shadows cast on the side of a stucco
building.
</P>
<P>
   But the foreground of this memorable nonfiction film is, as it
should be, filled by the irrepressible 87-year-old Meyerowitz. He's
a failing but somehow indestructible and enormously likable little
man: onetime Golden Gloves lightweight boxing champ, expressively
loving father of three sons he doesn't clearly remember, and a kind
of poet in spite of, or perhaps because of, his loosening grasp on
normal language.
</P>
<P>
   There is some wistfulness in this father-son journey (which also
included Joel's son Sasha), a sense of things past and passing.
``What do I do, Pop?'' Joel asks his dad en route, trying to
exercise the older man's blurring memory. ``You're a doll. Number
One,'' Hy pipes up from the rear seat. Does it bother him that he
can't clearly remember his sons' jobs and lives, Joel asks next.
``Well, I tell you, yeah. I see them. Hello . . . goodbye.'' In a
heart-wrenching riff shadowed with grief, apropos of nothing much,
Hy says, ``Everybody, I'm sure, is sorry they have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But almost everything that should seem sad or perhaps angle down
a dark pathway, paradoxically, doesn't. Despite occasional
unfounded worries that his 86-year-old wife is cheating on him, Hy
is a repository of love, and the film is charged with his vesuvial
affections. No matter what else he is losing, has lost, Hy's love
for people and life itself seems undiminished. It's as though
perhaps we're seeing his very core, all the more visible for his
loss of various past powers and defenses. His heart seems like a
furnace, warming waitresses, theme-park patrons, random folks he
buttonholes on streets in Southern backwaters or his blighted old
Bronx neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Where many filmmakers doing a film about a loved one end up
really telling a story about themselves, Joel Myerowitz doesn't.
He's very present, of course, but never in the way, and,
mercifully, he never steps on Hy's wonderful lines. Hy says so much
that is memorably rich with emotion, nothing more so than: ``My
life _ it wasn't much, but it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to some wonderfully edited and deployed clips from family
home movies, we see that life in tender bloom. The athletic young
father balancing one of his sons on an outstretched hand; the
competent young adult Hy when he was considered arbiter of
neighborhood disputes and known as ``the mayor''; and Hy larking
with wife Sally, both of them moving in the stately slo-mo that
imparts a dreamy quality to the footage from the past.
</P>
<P>
   One peculiarity about ``Pop'' throws it slightly off balance.
That is the presence of Sasha, who interacts only briefly, although
endearingly, with his grandfather and very little with his own dad,
the filmmaker. It appears that Sasha may be on board mainly to help
with the filmmaking. But his role isn't properly explained, leaving
us with nagging questions about this rather elusive youngest
Meyerowitz, and the sense that ``Pop'' might have been, but for
some reason isn't, more about the interconnectedness of three
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Hy, though, was certainly meant to be the focus of this
celebratory portrait. In many ways, he seems the very soul of
optimism. With good reasons to complain, he rarely does. On the
contrary, as he says on the phone one day to his wife back in
Florida, ``To my limit, I'm having what I like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
