<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-JUNETEENT     06-21 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-JUNETEENTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIMMED-DOWN `JUNETEENTH' LEAVES UNANSWERED QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Random House publication of Ralph Ellison's ``Juneteenth''
is Ellison's vision according to John Callahan, an Ellison scholar,
his literary executor and friend.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan has carefully pared Ellison's unfinished 1,500-page
manuscript into a trim, neatly structured 354-page novel. And he
chose the title.
</P>
<P>
   As with any vision based on someone's other than the visionary,
there must be departures. Here, Callahan imposed a structure on an
unwieldy narrative that he said spiraled out of control. Ellison,
Callahan has explained, was determined to fold everything from his
experience in hometown Oklahoma into an American epic that pulled
together the country's disparate cultural threads.
</P>
<P>
   Though Callahan's editing was limited mostly to creating a ready
structure for readers, it's a severe edit that in the end leaves
the reader wondering what Ellison's vision might have been had he
finished it. But just as we read the Gospel according to the
disciples wondering which rendition best captures the time, we
should read ``Juneteenth'' as, if nothing else, a guide to better
understanding Ellison's literary aim and the obstacles that
obscured a finish.
</P>
<P>
   We can't say for sure that the famed author of the 1952 classic,
``Invisible Man,'' would have succeeded in fitting the pieces of
his manuscript together. He had been struggling with the work for
the last 40 years of his life, which ended at the age of 80 in
1994. So it might be safe to say there was no solution. It didn't
help that writer's block plagued Ellison after a 1967 fire in his
Massachusetts farmhouse destroyed extensive revisions of the
manuscript, revisions that presumably had brought him closer to
completion of his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Ellison's vision came out of the premise that black
culture has marked all of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize no American culture which is not the partial
creation of black people,'' Ellison told author James Alan
McPherson in a 1969 interview. ``I recognize no American style in
literature, in dance, in music, even in assembly-line processes,
which does not bear the mark of the American Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   We see Ellison's position clearly in ``Invisible Man'' as the
protagonist learns from work in a paint factory that the whitest
white is made with a drop of black.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bold statement in a country that for generations has held
that American culture is white. In an essay from ``Thirteen Ways of
Looking at a Black Man,'' Henry Louis Gates Jr. states that Ellison
and close friend Albert Murray held tight to the assertion that the
truest Americans were black. For Ellison and Murray, said Gates,
being American does not mean being white. It means, in large part,
being inextricably linked to blackness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, literary critics and historians continually deny American
culture's link and indebtedness to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In her extended essay, ``Playing in the Dark: Whiteness and the
Literary Imagination,'' Toni Morrison says this denial maintains
that the canon of American literature is ``free of, uninformed and
unshaped by the four-hundred-year-old presence of, first Africans
and then African-Americans in the United States. It assumes that
this presence _ which shaped the body politic, the Constitution and
the entire history of the culture _ has had no significant place or
consequence in the origin and development of that culture's
literature.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Juneteenth,'' white America's denial of its
African-American heritage is personified in Sen. Adam Sunraider, a
light-skinned man of indefinite race who shuns his rearing in rural
Georgia as a black boy named Bliss. Sunraider reinvents himself,
severing ties with the only family he knew: the Rev. Alonzo
Hickman, who raised Bliss as his own, and Hickman's congregation.
</P>
<P>
   In his reinvention, Sunraider becomes a flimflam movie man and
later a politician, turning the very oratorical skills that Hickman
taught him into weapons against blacks.
</P>
<P>
   When Hickman gets word that Sunraider's life is in danger, he
and his congregation go to the senator's office to warn him. The
secretary promptly turns them away. But Hickman is persistent.
</P>
<P>
   While he and the congregation sit in the Senate gallery hoping
to ward off threats, the assassin, a man named Severen, raises his
gun and shoots the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Alive when he reaches the hospital, Sunraider calls for the man
he knew as Daddy Hickman. It is here that the narrative launches
into a journey of betrayal and reconciliation, exploring what it
was that made Bliss leave and disown part of himself, and how
willing he is to return.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to be admired in ``Juneteenth.'' Ellison's
lyricism, spun in antiphonal and jazz motifs, highlights his
elegant use of language. Sometimes he pays homage to William
Faulkner, turning phrases in a mishmash of varying time frames.
</P>
<P>
   As Sunraider goes in and out of consciousness, we're led through
both dream and memory. The senator remembers an encounter in one of
the many small towns he and his movie/confidence-men visit. He
meets a young black woman, skin the color of peaches, who pines to
be in moving pictures. His own longings and loneliness penetrate
like the fog. The more he reins in his desires for her, the closer
he comes to splitting himself in two.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he leaves his soul behind.
</P>
<P>
   But because ``Juneteenth'' is an unfinished work, it presents
problems. The narrative begs for other voices and perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   What had Sunraider done that angered Severen that he wanted to
kill him? How far had Sunraider gone to destroy the people who
loved and cared for him? One is left wondering if the answer is in
the larger manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman's voice is strong and vital to the narrative, but at
times he takes over, drowning out Bliss and the dilemma that drives
the young man. In the end, through the power of redemption, Hickman
emerges the hero _ not only saving Bliss but preserving humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juneteenth'' is both gift and torment. Experiencing Ellison
all over again whets the appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan vows he will publish a scholar's version of Ellison's
manuscript _ one that will allow readers and Ellison enthusiasts to
decide for themselves what should have and might have been.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard truth is no one will ever know for sure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
