<P>
   SCI-HISMANAL-WITHDRAWAL (Washington) _ After multiple reports of
serious adverse reactions, Janssen Pharmaceutica is withdrawing its
prescription antihistamine Hismanal from the U.S. market, the Food
and Drug Administration said Monday. The drug has been the subject
of a series of warnings and label changes since it was approved in
1988. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-IMPLANTS (Washington) _ A federal advisory panel
formally issues its report on silicone breast implants saying they
do not cause life-threatening illnesses. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOW-WE-NAVIGATE (Undated) _ Scientists have taken a keen
interest in how humans and other species navigate _ or fail to. The
study of what they call spatial cognition, or way-finding, is
attracting a growing cadre of researchers from all sectors of the
academic map, including psychology, neuroscience, computer science,
zoology, anthropology, linguistics and geography. By Natalie
Angier.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEUTRINO-DETECTORS (Undated) _ Scientists operating huge
underground detectors in Japan and Canada are racing to obtain
independent proofs that the elusive neutrino _ a ghostly particle
whose vast family may constitute a large fraction of the mass of
the universe _ changes form as it flies through matter or space. By
Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOMEN-IN-ENGINEERING (Undated) _ Dr. Eleanor Baum,
electrical engineer, dean of engineering at Cooper Union in New
York and the first woman to head an engineering college anywhere,
is running a one-woman affirmative action campaign that is
transforming engineering.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INFECTION-THE-GAME (Undated) _ Infection, sort of a cross
between Monopoly and Trivial Pursuit, is a new board game of
questionable taste, but unquestionable imagination. It pits from
two to nine people against one another on a playing field run
rampant with disease, from the fiercest (like malaria) to the
simply annoying (say, athlete's foot). By Eric Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHIMPS-HABITS (Undated) _ More on the cultural habits of
chimps. By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Americans, famous for wanting their
cake and eating it too, were delighted to learn that even though
French foods seem to be rich in fat, much of it artery-clogging
saturated animal fat, the French are not nearly as likely to be cut
down in midlife by heart attacks. This intriguing phenomenon is
called the French Paradox, and it has drawn comment, criticism and
speculation for much of this decade. What is helping protect their
hearts? By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENETIC-CODE (Undated) _ Researchers at Mount Sinai School
of Medicine in New York have developed a technique for conducting
espionage on a molecular level, by hiding a message in human DNA.
Using the technique, a sender would create a unique strand of DNA
that only an intended recipient could isolate and ``read'' from
millions of similar strands. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SICKLE-CELL (Undated) _ Two companies are conducting human
tests with several new types of agents that may result in the first
drugs to attack the basic mechanisms of sickle cell disease itself
and interrupt attacks once they have started. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLIND-MELATONIN (Undated) _ For the blind, the body's clock,
normally harnessed to the 24-hour cycle of daylight and darkness,
often goes into free run, disrupting sleep patterns. Now,
researchers may have help, using the hormone melatonin, for the
estimated 200,000 Americans who are totally blind and suffer from
sleep disorders. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEMALE-ATHLETE-TRIAD (Undated) _ Educators, coaches,
researchers, physicians and parents are expressing increasing
concern about the female athlete triad, a syndrome experts have
defined as three distinct but related problems: disordered eating,
suspended menstrual cycle and premature bone loss. By Linda
Villarosa.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Your science questions answered: How do
seashells grow?.
