<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONASTERY-0622     06-21 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONASTERY-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONASTERY A REFUGE FOR IN THE TROUBLED BALKANS
 &HT;    550&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECANI, Yugoslavia _ Offering a tranquil campus behind a massive
stone gatehouse, the Serbian Orthodox Visoki Decani monastery is a
refuge in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Monks here measure time in centuries, so as they
completed the first Sunday mass since NATO troops moved in to
Kosovo, they had little hope for a quick peace in the burned and
bloodied towns around them.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the monastery gate, monks brought tea to the Italian
NATO troops standing guard next to a tank. Inside, birds chirped
and a monk tended to his bee hives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nearby town of Decani is in almost complete ruin
and mass graves of Albanians foul the air in several spots along
this stretch of road.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, the monastery was refuge to about 150
ethnic Albanians fleeing the terror and murder of Yugoslav forces
and Serb police. Most of their fellows Kosovars had fled Kosovo to
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Serb troops completed their withdrawal from the war-torn
province, 15 Serb civilians were in the monastery for safety. They
fear a return to their homes could leave them vulnerable to ethnic
Albanian revenge. About 20 Gypsies also had taken shelter in the
Monastery; in the past Gypsies often have cooperated with the
ruling Serbs here.
</P>
<P>
   One of 20 monks in residence, Abbot Theodosie -- he would not
give his family name -- commented to journalists on the many
calamities that have befallen the region since the monastery was
built 665 years ago: from the Turkish conquest and 500-year
occupation to the mass emigration of the Austro-Hungarian wars to
the Italian occupation of World War II and Communism.
</P>
<P>
   He gestured to the stately domed church, handsome in soft
horizontal stripes of cream and rose marble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This church remembers a lot of things,'' he said. ``Today we
have a similar situation as many times before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have been done without any reason. (There has been)
conflict that has not been good for anyone,'' he said. ``First we
were witness to the exodus of the Albanian people. Now we are
witness to the exodus of the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   A 64-year-old Serb man approached visitors with a letter signed
by three Albanians attesting that he was not a looter or murderer.
But, he is afraid to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Patriarch Pavle, the head of the Serbian Orthodox
Church, took the unprecedented step of calling for the resignation
of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, who led the Serb
onslaught in Kosovo. He also urged ethnic Serbs to stay in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For inspiration, Pavle moved the seat of the church from
Belgrade to Pec, a city in Kosovo which has been the home of the
church several times since the 14th Century.
</P>
<P>
   The church complex in Pec is sheltering more than 100 Serbs.
But, Albanians do not see the church in Pec, at times the
instrument of Serb nationalism, as benevolent.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sunday, a nun who spotted two Albanians accompanying
foreign journalists was far from welcoming. ``Look at the Albanians
trying to come here, acting like foreigners,'' she hissed within
earshot.
</P>
<P>
   Ekram Ceku, Pec commander of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army,
said last week that church officials apologized to him for the Serb
carnage. The apology rang hollow to him, coming now from the
vanquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a declaration and doing something is two different
things,'' Ceku said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But, the monastery here at Decani has a reputation for kindness
worthy of its quiet splendor.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church are brilliant, original frescos. The face of
Jesus looks down from the dome high above heavy marble pillars as
if it is afloat. One fresco shows a scale balance, with an angel on
the left, the devil on the right and a naked human in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, people have gone away from God and in this sense
they have gone away from each other,'' Abbot Theodosie said of the
recent carnage.
</P>
<P>
   He said he sees no end to the cycle of violence between Serbs
and Albanians. ``But, God can see it,'' he said, ``And we pray for
him to bring reason to peoples' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
