<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3951 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      06-21 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Missouri wanted to test the
theory that the way to make better, shorter business meetings was
to take the chairs away. And sure enough, comparing outcomes for
111 meetings, they found that those conducted while the
participants were seated lasted longer than meetings in which the
participants remained standing. However, the quality of
decision-making was the same for both formats.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which appears in the current issue of The Journal of
Applied Psychology, looked at 56 standing meetings and 55 sitting
meetings for five-member groups of students ages 19 to 44.
</P>
<P>
   The groups took part in an exercise called Lost on the Moon. In
it, each group was told that their space shuttle had crashed on the
moon and was given a list of the items that survived the crash. The
participants were asked to rank the supplies collectively in the
order of their importance to the group's survival. The
participants' rankings were compared to a ``best answer'' provided
by NASA experts. The students also filled out questionnaires before
and after their meetings to assess their commitment to the
decisions and satisfaction with the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that seated meetings lasted 34 percent
longer than the standing meetings and that the standing students
reported greater satisfaction with their meetings. Sitting and
standing participants also reported equal commitment to their
groups' decisions, and researchers said that there was no
significant difference in the quality of the decisions produced in
either format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone hates meetings in organizations,'' said Dr. Allen C.
Bluedorn, professor of management at the University of Missouri's
College of Business and Public Administration and lead author of
the study. ``They're usually poorly done. We expected the quality
of the decision making to suffer when the meetings were conducted
standing up. But there was no significant difference.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another surprise for the researchers. ``As the
sitting-down meetings took longer,'' Bluedorn said, ``we thought
they would lead to more creativity and more synergy. That didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary Waller, a professor who specializes in organizational
behavior at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champagne, who was
not involved with the study, added: ``I think it's a pretty
important finding. If I was consulting with an organization, I
would probably suggest that they combine sit-down and standing-up
meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   _ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Spanish explorers in the 16th century first recorded the fact
that dead rattlesnakes can bite, but that word has apparently not
gotten around: Two toxicologists in Phoenix found that 15 percent
of the rattlesnake bites they treated in a 10-month period came
from snakes that had been decapitated, shot or whomped until dead.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey R. Suchard of the Good Samaritan Regional Medical
Center said that he and a colleague, Dr. Frank LoVecchio, conducted
the study after a man came in for treatment in 1997 after he had
been bitten while picking up the corpse of a snake he had
bludgeoned with a shovel. ``We thought it was pretty weird, and
decided to keep track,'' Suchard said. Their study was published as
a letter in the current issue of The New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Their expectation was that such after-death encounters would
prove to be very uncommon. But five of the 34 rattlesnake bite
victims they treated fit the bill. The first of the five had beaten
a rattlesnake on the head with a stick until it was motionless,
then was bitten on the index finger when he picked it up. Two
others had shot the snakes in the head and picked them up after
waiting a few minutes. And two had decapitated the snakes with
bullets and were bitten when they picked up the severed heads; one
patient had to have a finger amputated.
</P>
<P>
   Suchard said that earlier studies have found that overall,
people who are bitten by rattlesnake tend to be ``intoxicated young
men.'' Only one of the five patients bitten by a dead snake in his
study was drunk, but none displayed what he considered to be good
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic message people should know is to leave snakes
alone,'' he said. ``If you are so foolhardy as to try and kill one,
then don't think it's OK to pick it up just because it's dead.''
</P>
<P>
   There is only one right thing to do when a rattlesnake is
encountered, he added: ``Call animal control.''
</P>
<P>
   _JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Can riding a bicycle lead to erectile dysfunction or
impotence? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It is well established that cycling can cause penile numbness,
erectile dysfunction and impotency. At Boston University, several
studies have shown a significant correlation between cycling and
these conditions. In one study, 4 percent of young, healthy male
cyclists in their 20s and 30s reported erectile dysfunction
compared with only 1 percent of runners of the same age, fitness
level, and health status. Although this is a small percentage, the
data suggest a statistically significant increase in problems
compared to runners.
</P>
<P>
   The design of the bike seat is the major problem. The back of
the traditional hard, narrow bike seat is not wide enough to
support the ``sit'' bones, so the cyclist moves forward, putting
weight on the soft tissue of the perineum _ the area between the
genitals and anus. Compressing the artery and nerve in this area
may cause irreversible impotency.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclists should choose a wide, soft saddle and should stop
riding if they feel any pain or numbness in the genital area.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Dr. IRWIN GOLDSTEIN, Professor of Urology, Boston University
School of Medicine &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of riding a bike far outweigh any risk of impotency
or sexual dysfunction for the general population. I have seen many
people with sexual dysfunction and impotency, many of whom rode
bikes, but riding was never found to be the cause of their problem.
</P>
<P>
   While some studies have shown a link between cycling and
decreased blood flow to the genitals, numbness and impotency, the
data are far from definitive and more studies are needed before
anyone recommends not riding a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, cycling for improved health and fitness is one way to
help prevent impotency and enhance sexual performance.
</P>
<P>
   The main risks for impotency include heart disease,
hypertension, diabetes and smoking. When cyclists become more fit,
they reduce their risk of developing heart disease and high blood
pressure. And few cyclists smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In general, people who are fit and feel good about their bodies
are less likely to suffer psychogenic-related erectile problems.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; DR. IRA SHARLIP, Medical director, Pan Pacific Urology, San
Francisco &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
