<HEADER>
A3961 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-     06-21 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-GENERAL-HOSPITAL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GENERAL' DYNAMICS: BEHIND THE SCENES AT `GENERAL HOSPITAL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of John Ingle, Stuart Damon, Leslie
Charleson and Amber Tamblyn in a scene from ``General Hospital.'') 
 By MICHAEL LOGAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the men of General Hospital are good, they're very, very
good _ but when they're bad they're better. And soap fans will find
out just how much better on July 11 when heartthrobs Maurice Benard
(Sonny), Steve Burton (Jason), Billy Warlock (A.J.) and Wally Kurth
(Ned) appear in a rare, no-holds-barred question-and-answer session
at the Canada's Wonderland theme park in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Benard and Burton play mobsters, while Warlock is seen as the
alcoholic black sheep of the show's ritzy Quartermaine clan.
Kurth's character is the only ``good guy'' in the pack, though even
Ned's been known to reveal a naughty side on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the guys are married: Benard is wed to his longtime
sweetheart Paula Smith (they have two children), Burton recently
said ``I Do'' with Sheree Gustin, a former GH production intern,
and Kurth is the husband of actress Rena Sofer (formerly GH's
Lois), who will star this fall in the new ABC sitcom ``Oh, Grow
Up!''
</P>
<P>
   Warlock and ``Port Charles'' sensation Julie Pinson (Eve)
recently became engaged and plan to wed in the spring of 2000. TV
Guide caught up with this quartet of popular actors to grill them
about fame, fans and the future.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: Your work schedules are insane. You have very full personal
lives. Why make time for this fan appearance?
</P>
<P>
   BENARD: The money! No, just kidding. The fans are great. I wish
I could do more weekend appearances, but it's the traveling that
breaks my butt. I only get out, maybe, once a month.
</P>
<P>
   WARLOCK: I want the feedback of the fans, I need it as an actor.
Besides, the fans dictate everything. The producers and writers are
very influenced by what the fans want.
</P>
<P>
   KURTH: I love the fans. They are so committed. A lot of them
tell me they still watch GH because they grew up watching the show
with their mothers or grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: Why is it so rare to see a Wally Kurth interview?
</P>
<P>
   KURTH: I've been doing soaps for 13 years. I've stopped doing
interviews in the last few years, because I feel there's just
nothing more anyone could possibly want to know about me _ or that
I want to tell them. I think we could all use a little more mystery
_ the actors and the shows.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: The clean-cut heroes used to be the most popular characters
on soaps. Now, more and more fans seem to be sparking to the dark,
complex, dysfunctional, antihero characters, such as Sonny and
Jason.
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: It all goes back to that James Dean thing. You know, the
tortured, brooding, vulnerable guy who can't help but be a little
bad. The fans like bad boys, which is why I was freaking out during
my first few years on GH because Jason used to be as wholesome as a
Boy Scout. Thank God Jason hit his head on a rock and joined the
mob.
</P>
<P>
   BENARD: It's more interesting to play someone with demons. The
dark side excites me. And a lot of the fans think they can help
you, that they can set you straight. They think, ``I could be the
one to change him.'' The clean-cut hero doesn't have all that much
to change.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: You guys aren't just bad, you're in the Mafia! Isn't the
adoration women feel for you rather, well, twisted?
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: GH is just a fantasy. The fans know it's just a soap
opera playground. Audiences love the Mafia _ from ``The Godfather''
movies to ``The Sopranos.'' We're intrigued with that world. We're
fascinated to see that you can be in organized crime and still be
real people with real problems and romances and families. The fans
can enjoy the bad things we do because they know Maurice and Steve
don't really do them.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: Does it help that GH has always kept Sonny's and Jason's
mob activities sort of vague? What exactly do they traffic in?
We've been watching for years and have no clue!
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: Basically they try to, uh, I don't know, control the
unions? It's so funny that we don't really deal in anything
illegal. No drugs. No black-market babies. We just sorta strong-arm
people.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: Billy, prior to GH, you played a hero _ and won an Emmy _
as Frankie on ``Days of Our Lives.'' What's your preference?
</P>
<P>
   WARLOCK: It's always more interesting to play someone with
emotional problems, though there was a time when A.J. was so bad
even I couldn't justify it as an actor. We definitely went
overboard, but that's all in the writing.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: Wally, you've played back-to-back clean-cut heroes (before
GH, he was Justin Kiriakis on Days). Do you envy the bad guys?
</P>
<P>
   KURTH: I do prefer the times my character has an edge. Ned is
very similar to Justin, which is why actors have to get off soaps
after a while _ we need to prove there's more to us than what we're
allowed to play.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: So are you thinking about leaving GH?
</P>
<P>
   KURTH: I'll definitely consider it when my contract is up. At
that point, hopefully, I'll feel financially comfortable enough to
take the chance, because Rena's sitcom is very funny, and I think
it'll be a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to get back to the theater (Kurth starred on Broadway
in ``The Pirates of Penzance''). After years of never-ending soap
stories, I want to do movies where there's a beginning, middle and
end. In fact, I just finished writing a screenplay, which I will
produce next summer. It'll be shot in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: Maurice, you left GH to pursue greener pastures. Then you
returned last November, but only signed a one-year contract. Does
this suggest you'll leave again?
</P>
<P>
   BENARD: I won't leave GH again unless I have something great to
go to. I'm glad I came back. I did roles in three little
independent films while I was off the show, but it wasn't much to
brag about. The only thing that frustrates me is that I feel I
deserve a shot at something big, and I just haven't had that shot.
I'm honest and realistic, but I also feel I can hold my own with
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   TVG: And the rumors of your departure, Steve?
</P>
<P>
   BURTON: My contract is up in December and, for the first time,
certain networks have been coming to me to discuss stuff. But I
love GH. I know I can work elsewhere, but it's the quality of the
work I'm worried about. I'm not planning to be the next Tom Cruise
or Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   If an offer won't improve my career, if it's not a better role
than Jason, then what's the point? GH is home for me.
 &UR; (Michael Logan is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``General Hospital,'' consult
the official Website at www.abc.go.com/soaps/generalhospital. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
