<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SLOVENIA-HNS &LR;      06-21 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SLOVENIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES YUGOSLAVIA TO FOLLOW SLOVENIA'S EXAMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ President Clinton challenged the Serbs in
nearby Yugoslavia Monday to sack Slobodan Milosevic so they will be
eligible for the multi-billion dollar reconstruction package being
assembled by the United States and the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also emphasized the prosperity that could await
Yugoslavia as he paid a celebratory visit to Slovenia _ the first
former Yugoslav republic to reject Milosevic and embrace
independence, ethnic tolerance and the West.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in rain-swept Congress Square, Clinton urged the Serbs
to join ``a Europe undivided, democratic and at peace for the first
time in history.'' The president also praised Slovenia as a top
candidate for future admission to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   By visiting a former Yugoslav republic and meeting here with the
president of the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, Milo Djukanovic,
Clinton appeared to symbolically tighten the diplomatic isolation
around Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked to meet Djukanovic to underscore allied support
for ``democratic efforts in Montenegro and our willingness to work
with them,'' said White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also planned to meet leaders of Macedonia and Albania
during a visit to Macedonia on Tuesday _ a schedule that will bring
him face-to-face with three leaders who govern territory adjacent
to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world admires Slovenia's success in building freedom
and prosperity _ and now we look to you to play a crucial role as
we build a better future for all of Europe,'' Clinton told
thousands of Slovenes who waited more than three hours in the rain
to hear the first American president to visit their eight-year-old
nation, population of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Serbia to be part of the new Europe,'' Clinton
continued. ``But Serbia must reject the murderous rule of Mr.
Milosevic and choose the path that Slovenia has chosen, where
people reach across the old divides and find strength in their
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek called Clinton's visit
``confirmation'' of Slovenia's ``partnership'' with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came here following a summit in Bonn with German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder where the American president and the
current president of the 15-nation European Union agreed to map a
multi-billion dollar reconstruction program for Kosovo and the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked Slovenia for allowing allied warplanes to use
its airspace to reach Yugoslavia during the 78-day bombing campaign
by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization that forced Milosevic to
halt his troops' murderous campaign against ethnic Albanian Muslims
in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo. He also praised Slovenia for
providing help to thousands of Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all you have done, I am very, very grateful,'' Clinton
said, adding: ``You have been a good partner and you are an
excellent candidate for NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO admitted Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary earlier
this year, leaving Slovenia disappointed that it would have to wait
at least until 2002 to be considered for membership in the
19-nation alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remark offered no firm commitment of U.S support. But
his words were greeted with enthusiastic cheers by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia is one of eight nations seeking NATO admission. A
crossroads between Europe and the Balkans, Slovenia is a member of
NATO's consultative Partnership for Peace which readies aspiring
member nations for membership.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the audience, Peter Judez, 29, an electrician from
Novo Mesto, said he is willing to be patient for his small nation
to join the western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be good for us to join,'' Judez said. ``We would feel
safer then.''
</P>
<P>
   Judez praised Clinton's visit: ``It is a good job, Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the crowd, Peter Stegnar, 16, a high school
student, said membership in NATO will be ``difficult to obtain
because so many other nations want to join, too.'' Stegnar added:
``We are a small country and alone. We can't move ahead without
joining the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Judez and Stegnar said Clinton's visit helped soothe their
nation's sense of disappointment about having to wait for
admission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia also is scheduled to join the 15-nation European Union
in 2006. Slovenia's per capita income of $11,000 is comparable to
Portugal and Greece, both members of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenes expressed zero tolerance for Milosevic, a Serbian
dictator who has ordered wars against Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and
now Kosovo since the breakup of Yugoslavia began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is a terrorist,'' declared Stegnar. ``It is not
right for people to be killed in Kosovo because they want to speak
their language, practice their religion and preserve their customs.
Milosevic must go on trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Stegnar expressed confidence that the Balkans can overcome their
ethnic and religious diversity and rivalries, saying: ``You do it
with friendly ways. The Serbs have been a very aggressive people.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosovic and four lieutenants have been indicted for war crimes
by an international war crimes tribunal based in the Netherlands.
Clinton conceded last week in Paris that the allies have little
chance of capturing Milosevic for trial, if he remains inside of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton was taken by the enthusiastic
reception, that included crowds along the motorcade route from the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This in many ways will be very memorable for the president
because of the sight of so many tens of thousands of people out
there in the rain, who had waited out there for many hours,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia, a predominantly Roman Catholic Slavic nation governed
for centuries by the Austo-Hungarian Empire, has long been a
step-child of Europe. Leaders of the victorious nations in World
War I redrew the map of post-war Europe to lump tiny Slovenia
together with the Slav principalities of the Balkans to create the
Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes _ renamed Yugoslavia in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
