<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INFECTION-THE-GAME-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING HEALTH AT RISK JUST FOR THE FUN OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My wife and I had barely settled down across from each another
when she got the bad news: She had smallpox. An inauspicious start,
I thought, trying to tamp down any sense of satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   This became easier to do once I got my own diagnosis: spotted
fever. Things weren't looking so hot for me, either.
</P>
<P>
   But my spirits were buoyed anew when my wife found out she had
contracted woolsorters' disease _ better known as anthrax. And my
next diagnosis, however embarrassing, did not diminish my
hopefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dandruff!'' my wife snickered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty funny for somebody with two fatal diseases,'' I replied
icily.
</P>
<P>
   This exchange set the tone for the 45 minutes or so that
followed, in which we played a new board game of questionable
taste, but unquestionable imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Infection, sort of a cross between Monopoly and Trivial Pursuit,
is a game that pits from two to nine people against one another on
a playing field run rampant with disease, from the fiercest (like
malaria) to the simply annoying (say, athlete's foot).
</P>
<P>
   The goal is survival. The first player who is completely cured _
or, in a less hopeful scenario, is the only one left alive _ wins.
</P>
<P>
   While the game, which costs $30, allows players to get rid of
diseases by giving them to other players (or casting them off at
places like a public pool), its creator, Dan Sullivan of Milpitas,
Calif., says, ``The game is really about getting healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, 34, a chemist who works for a large computer parts
company, created the game as an independent venture. He sees his
audience as the ``hypochondriac in all of us.'' To date, he has
sold 800 in stores or through his Web site (www.earwig.net).
</P>
<P>
   Players begin with five diseases, which are contained on cards
bearing the name of the malady, its description and its treatment.
Then they try to buy cures from specialists or even a voodoo
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said much research went into the game, and it shows.
Still, there will always be quibblers. My wife, told that she had a
collapsed lung, peevishly noted that the condition is not
infectious. ``So, `Infection' is really a misnomer,'' she said.
``You could just call it `Disease.''' (Yeah _ or you could also
just avoid playing against copy editors.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she was just sensing her impending defeat. Soon, I cured
myself of my last disease, leaving her with heartburn, athlete's
foot _ and that collapsed lung.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
