<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMERSONGS-1000(2Tak     06-21 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERSONGS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES A HIT RADIO SONG IN THE SUMMER?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-SUMMERSONGS-LIST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer 1965, El Paso: I'm nearly 6 years old, riding in the
family car _ a Ford Fairlane, as I recall _ with one of my older
sisters. It's hellishly hot, and the car isn't air-conditioned.
We're listening to KELP, El Paso's top AM station, and this Rolling
Stones song comes on, with this incredible, buzzing guitar riff
followed by Mick Jagger purring, ``I can't get no ...
sat-is-fac-tion ...''
</P>
<P>
   I'm too young to have any idea what Jagger is singing about, but
that guitar sure sounds good, as do the parts where all the other
instruments drop out and it's just the drums and then Jagger sings,
``Hey hey hey, that's what I say ...''
</P>
<P>
   It would take me till November 1974, when I rediscovered
``Satisfaction,'' to figure out what Jagger was singing about.
Didn't matter _ for me, the most famous guitar intro in rock is a
time machine, one that takes me back to my last free summer before
entering first grade.
</P>
<P>
   For me, and probably for a lot of people, ``Satisfaction'' is
the epitome of a single of the summer. This is not to be confused
with a summer song, which is merely a song ABOUT summer; a single
of the summer DEFINES a summer. When you hear it, it brings you
back to where you were and who you were with that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think that it comes down to a really personal
thing,'' says Pat McMahon, program director for Dallas R&AMP;B oldies
station KTXQ/102.1 FM. ``It comes from youth, summer, long days,
girlfriends, boyfriends, days at the beach or at the park.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, one person's single of the summer could be
another person's shoulder-shrug. But some songs transcend this, and
take on a more generational aura. Martha and the Vandellas'
``Dancing in the Streets'' (1964) is one of 'em; so is
``Satisfaction.'' But then, so is the Police's 1983 hit ``Every
Breath You Take.'' ``Summer in the City,'' from 1967; ``Summer
Nights,'' from 1978; ``Love Shack,'' from 1989; and last year's
``The Way'' are all evocative summer songs for their eras.
</P>
<P>
   These examples are a diverse lot, ranging from ebullient calls
to party to anthems of rebellion, to a moody ode to sexual
obsession. So it's hard to get a handle on just what makes a song a
single of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The curt answer is, its release date,'' says Thomas Ryan,
author of ``American Hit Radio,'' in which Ryan discusses his picks
for the best Top 40 singles from 1955 to 1994. ``Sometimes, I think
that that's the way this works out.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not that simple. If a release date were all it took, a
kitsch classic such as Paper Lace's ``The Night Chicago Died'' _
which actually hit No. 1 in 1974 _ could be a contender for that
summer's representative single. Even a good song that's a huge hit,
such as Boyz II Men's 1992 blockbuster ``End of the Road,'' can
find the single-of-the-summer honor elusive. That song was No. 1
forever, but something about it is too elegiac to evoke that summer
feeling. ``Every Breath You Take'' aside, it's rare to hear a slow
summer song.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something with a lot of energy,'' says Dave Morales,
music director for Dallas Top 40 station KHKS/106.1 FM (a k a
KISS). ``You almost see somebody driving with the top down,
cruising the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan agrees, but adds that there's even more to the sound,
something almost ethereal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best songs of summer definitely convey an atmosphere,''
Ryan says. ``A perfect example is that Seal song from a few years
back, `Crazy.' The opening riff just floated on the air. It was
like it was coming from space, or from a p.a., or coming around the
mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Atmosphere is certainly part of it, in more ways than one. Ryan
points out that a single of the summer is ubiquitous; it's the type
of song you hear everywhere you go, even without trying (for this
reason, Ryan picks the Captain &AMP; Tennille's ``Love Will Keep Us
Together'' as the single of the summer for 1975, even though he
doesn't like it). Because more people are outside in the summer,
it's easier to hear incidental music wafting over from someone
else's sound system. Even geography can fit into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, music is a very public thing,'' says Robert
Christgau, pop music critic for The Village Voice. ``It's songs you
hear in open-air situations. Up north, I think that means more than
it does down south, because our summer season is shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason you hear about singles of the summer while
you don't hear about, say, singles of the fall. Radio programmers
say that because school is out in the summer, the days are longer
and TV is in reruns, radio listening increases. But not all summers
have representative singles; sometimes, the music's just not strong
enough or right enough. Then again, some summers have more than one
flagship single. A good example is the summer of 1978, when the
Rolling Stones' ``disco'' move ``Miss You'' hit at the same time
that John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John were singing about
``Summer Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Once again, this may be a personal thing. When ``Miss You'' came
out, I had just moved to Los Angeles, leaving behind a crush that
was never reciprocated. As a generational song, ``Summer Nights''
probably gets the edge, because not only was it a big summer hit,
it was ABOUT summer. But just because a song sounds summery doesn't
mean it was released in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of (the Beach Boys') `Good Vibrations' as a
summer song, because I remember, quite distinctly, listening to
that record in November in my car,'' Christgau says. ``The reason
`Good Vibrations' registers as a summer song is supposedly
everything the Beach Boys do is about summer. It's really about
California, where it's summer for eight months a year.''
</P>
<P>
   You can write a song about summer and release it in the summer,
but that won't make it a single of the summer. First Class' ``Beach
Baby'' fits the criteria, but who even really remembers what year
it came out? (Answer: 1974.) You can't force a single of the
summer; it has to happen by itself. A single of the summer can't be
self-conscious; the most evocative ones (such as ``Every Breath You
Take,'' which lingered at No. 1 for eight weeks in 1983) probably
didn't even feel like singles of the summer when they were first
released. But hearing them later always takes you back to that
certain time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that stops record companies from trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of their biggest hypes when they're pushing songs is,
`It's a great summertime record,' '' Morales says. ``But if the
listeners don't go for it, it's not going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations have also tried forcing the matter. Recently,
stations have tried to give the honor to songs as unsummery as
Collective Soul's ``December,'' which was released in summer 1995
but was a self-pitying ditty about a wintry breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, one of the radio stations here kept calling this
song `Hooch' the single of the summer,'' says McMahon, the KTXQ
program director. ``I don't think a radio station has the power to
do that.'' Sure enough, it's hard to remember who even sang
``Hooch'' (answer: Everything), while the 1998 single-of-the-summer
honors probably go to Barenaked Ladies' inescapable ``One Week'' or
Fastball's ``The Way'' (a perfect summer song for road-trippers).
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's theory of ubiquity fits in here; ``One Week'' and ``The
Way'' received airplay all over. But he believes that the
fragmentation of radio formats has made it more difficult for a
summer to have a representative song. In 1965, ``Satisfaction'' was
played on the same stations that played ``I Got You Babe,'' ``The
Same Old Song'' and ``Papa's Got a Brand New Bag.'' Today, it would
be unusual to hear a rock song, a folk song, an R&AMP;B song and a funk
song on the same contemporary radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, other people's radios often keep the phenomenon
alive. Some R&AMP;B hits, such as Coolio's ``Fantastic Voyage'' and
TLC's ``Waterfalls,'' cross over to Top 40 radio, but that doesn't
mean that fans of ``alternative'' rock, country or hard rock are
going to hear these songs _ unless they're channel-surfers, or they
hear someone else playing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think that the rise of the boom box and the moving
sound system has a lot to do with this,'' Christgau says. ``That's
been a really important change in just putting music out on the
street in a way it didn't use to be. Up here, at least one (single
of the summer) is gonna be a hip-hop song. Because hip-hop
dominates street culture. ... I'm talking about what people listen
to on the streets, even in white neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the single of the summer for 1999?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's Ricky Martin's `Livin' La Vida Loca,' '' says
Morales, the KISS music director. ``We're banging the hell out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, to show you how subjective this is, Christgau disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's peaking a little early to be a summer song, I think,'' he
says. ``It was No. 1 for five weeks and it's on the way down.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be too early to tell whether this summer has a song;
TLC's ``No Scrubs'' is hanging around, and Will Smith's ``Wild Wild
West'' seems likely to peak on the charts about the same time the
``West'' movie comes out, on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Martin's ``La Vida Loca'' is pretty much everywhere.
You don't even have to be outside to hear it; if you're in a
restaurant, a clothing store or coffee shop that's tuned in to KISS
or one of its rivals, you're likely to hear Martin's hit. As
Christgau says, it's the music that's in the air.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
