<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3988 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FEMALE-ATHLETE-TR     06-21 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FEMALE-ATHLETE-TRIAD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRI-FOLD AILMENT STALKS FEMALE ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nancy Thies Marshall, director of the U.S.A. Gymnastics Athlete
Wellness Program, is one of a growing number of educators, coaches,
researchers, physicians and parents who are concerned about the
female athlete triad, a syndrome experts have defined as three
distinct but related problems: disordered eating, suspended
menstrual cycle and premature bone loss.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall understands the syndrome, which can lead to
permanent damage, better than many. She lived it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Ms. Marshall was the youngest member of the U.S.
women's Olympic gymnastics team, which finished fourth in Munich.
The next year, at age 15, she left her hometown of Urbana, Ill., to
train with her coach in Eugene, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a group house with eight other gymnasts, Ms. Marshall
spent most of her time in the gym, practicing six hours a day
almost every day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult time for me,'' said Ms. Marshall, now 42
and living in Salem, Ore. ``When I hit puberty, I didn't have the
guiding influence of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   As the months passed, Ms. Marshall began to lose her
preadolescent body shape, so valued in gymnastics. After gaining 10
pounds, she started a series of fad diets.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while I tried a no-carbohydrates diet,'' Ms. Marshall
said, ``then for three weeks I had only onion soup and Fresca. My
weight went up and down. I wasn't anorexic, but I had definite
disordered eating and no energy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall's erratic eating pattern and rigorous exercise led
to amenorrhea, generally defined as the cessation of the menstrual
period for at least three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have my period for a year,'' Ms. Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of injuries, and worried about the long-term
health of her bones and cessation of menstruation, Ms. Marshall and
her parents decided that she should return home. The experience
convinced her that she should suspend the high-level training
needed to gain a spot on the 1976 Olympic team, and limit herself
to gymnastics competition at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened to me,'' Ms. Marshall said, ``it became a
passion to do something about the female athlete triad.''
</P>
<P>
   Through her wellness program, Ms. Marshall strives to help
athletes and parents and to educate coaches in a number of health
areas, including the triad.
</P>
<P>
   The female athlete triad is now widely discussed in
sportsmedicine and coaching circles, and a number of medical
journals _ including the New England Journal of Medicine _ have
reported on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the National Institutes of Health and
American Academy of Orthopedic Surgery held a joint workshop to
discuss the triad, and the American College of Sports Medicine and
the U.S. Olympic Committee held a half-day seminar on the subject.
The latter two groups convened a panel of experts to create a
consensus statement about the triad. The statement is to be
released in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The female athlete triad is not new. The term was coined in
1992, when a group of concerned female doctors and sports
scientists became alarmed after seeing more and more female
athletes who were not eating well, not menstruating and suffering
stress fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Aurelia Nattiv, an assistant professor of family medicine
and orthopedic surgery at the University of California at Los
Angeles and a team physician in the university's Department of
Intercollegiate Athletics, was one of the first physicians to
notice the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all seemed to have the same story,'' Dr. Nattiv said. ``It
wasn't just a coincidence that these three things were occurring
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Eating disorders in female athletes gained widespread attention
in 1994 with the death of Christy Henrich, a world-class gymnast
who suffered from anorexia nervosa and bulimia. At the time of her
death at age 22, the 4-foot, 11-inch Ms. Henrich weighed less than
60 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No studies have pinpointed exactly how prevalent disordered
eating is among female athletes, mainly because of disagreement
about how to define the disorder. But informal surveys suggest that
15 percent to 62 percent of female athletes are affected by
disordered eating behavior that ranges from a preoccupation with
losing weight to anorexia or bulimia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many athletes do not necessarily meet the strict psychiatric
criteria for an eating disorder,'' said Dr. Elizabeth Joy, an
assistant professor in the Department of Family and Preventive
Medicine and a team physician at the University of Utah in Salt
Lake City. ``But if an athlete demonstrates restricted eating
behavior that does result in amenorrhea, I don't care what you call
it, it's clearly not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Amenorrhea occurs in many women who practice disordered eating
and rigorous athletic training. Deprived of fuel and exercising at
a high level, the body can move into a state of energy imbalance, a
kind of starvation mode. When this occurs, the body may respond by
shutting off systems that are not essential, like the reproductive
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In women who are training intensely, as many as 40 or 50
percent may be amenorrheic,'' said Dr. Anne B. Loucks, a professor
in the Department of Biological Sciences at Ohio University. ``It
may be even higher for cross-country runners and ballet dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the general population, amenorrhea affects 2 percent to 5
percent of women who would be expected to have menstrual periods,
Loucks said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts worry that many female athletes _ and a fair number of
doctors _ hold the belief that amenorrhea is a natural side effect
of high-level exercise. But, Loucks cautioned, ``This should not be
considered a healthy part of training. It is a serious medical
condition that requires treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The third component of the triad, loss of bone tissue, is
quietly dangerous. When a young woman's body falls into a
low-estrogen state, similar to a postmenopausal woman, she may
experience decreased bone density, an early stage of osteoporosis.
In runners especially, this may show up as a stress fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it's never too late to work on bone health,'' said
Nattiv, who is also director of the Osteoporosis Center at UCLA,
``bone loss may be irreversible. As these women get older and more
frail they are going to be set up for a more serious problem like a
hip fracture because of their low bone density.''
</P>
<P>
   Although experts stress that any female athlete is at risk for
the female athlete triad, those in certain sports are more likely
to experience the problem. For example, women who compete in
endurance sports like distance running _ in which low body weight
can improve performance _ may be at high risk for the syndrome.
Sports that are judged subjectively, like figure skating, diving,
gymnastics, those with body-hugging uniforms, like swimming and
gymnastics, and sports with weight categories, like martial arts,
may also produce a disproportionate share of athletes with the
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   But some doctors and coaches believe that gymnasts may be at
particular risk. In that sport, the best performers are often
preadolescents _ or those with a preadolescent body type. Gymnasts
who gain weight or those with larger body frames may try
desperately to lose weight, which can spiral into the female
athlete triad.
</P>
<P>
   Psychological reasons may also explain the prevalence of the
triad among female gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sport attracts athletes who are also at risk for
developing eating disorders,'' Ms. Marshall said. ``Age is also a
factor: Gymnasts are often adolescent women, which is also the
primary population for eating disorders. And those the sport
attracts are highly motivated, very driven, detail oriented people,
personality traits common in those with eating disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   Nattiv added, ``The same characteristics that make her your best
athlete, also put her at greatest risk for the triad.''
</P>
<P>
   For parents and coaches and for athletes who are concerned about
any of the female athlete triad disorders in themselves or
teammates, the first step should be to consult a health care
professional who is familiar with the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to do something,'' said Audrius Barzdukas,
associate director of coaching for the U.S. Olympic Committee. ``If
something doesn't seem right, it's better to err on the side of
caution than to ignore a potentially life-threatening problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the female athlete triad is serious, Ms. Marshall said,
it should not drive women away from exercise or competitive sport.
``Sports is a good thing. The question is: If the majority of women
are coming out of sports with character strengthening and life
skills, how we can we help the segment that gets out of balance?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
