<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `REEL' MOMENTS OF FATHERHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TO STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now I was in one heck of a mess, I figured, and
it meant big trouble. Big Trouble with Dad.
</P>
<P>
   I was 11 years old, back when I thought I could think a fish on
the hook, and we were fishing in a small boat in the shallows of
Monterey Bay, just off Capitola. It was a warm, blue-sky day, with
scarcely a breeze and just a light roll to the calm, briny blue. We
had anchored along some shallow kelp beds, then dropped our baits
to the bottom, just 40 or 50 feet deep, and started catching small
rockfish and maybe a rock crab now and then.
</P>
<P>
   We were fishing in a wood dory that had a mid-boat engine well,
and when my dad wasn't looking, I began pointing my rod inside that
engine well. I started to think it would be fun to catch a fish
right through the engine well, as if I had caught a fish inside the
boat. But after I cut a small piece of bait, I suddenly noticed
that my fishing rod had somehow disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   First, I accused my brother, Bob Jr., of stealing it. When he
professed convincing innocence, I figured a pelican had flown off
with it when I wasn't looking. But then I noticed that I still had
my bait in one hand, hook in the other, and started tracing the
line. I followed it across the boat, and there it went, right
through that engine well and into the ocean below; somehow I had
dropped my fishing rod right through the engine well in the boat:
The rod was on the bottom of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, Dad, I've got a little problem with my line,'' I
explained.
</P>
<P>
   He traced the line with his eyes into the sea, and after a
shocked, ``What will you do next?'' he started pulling on my line.
In time, to my amazement, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got something coming up now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough. In a few minutes, by hand-lining the fishing line,
he was eventually able to pull the rod in right off the bottom of
the ocean. It popped through the engine well, and in minutes, I was
fishing again, though with the requisite, ``How did you manage to
do that!'' from brother Bob. After all, brothers keep track of
screw-ups.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of moments that boys, brothers and parents
remembered Sunday, Father's Day. Sure, dad usually feels it's his
job to provide his family with a home, food, safety and security.
But that's not what kids remember. They remember the moments when
they were in trouble, a mess from which there appears no possible
extrication, and somehow dad bails them out. That is what Father's
Day is really about.
</P>
<P>
   Well, last week was a special time for my own two kids, Kris, 8,
and Jeremy, 11. Like so many youngsters across America, they got
out of school for summer, but a special reward came when I was able
to get permission from Brian Riley of Red Bank Quail to take the
boys out on the 15,000 acres of property he manages and fish a few
of the farm ponds there.
</P>
<P>
   As we drove to Red Bluff, there were visions of so many bass and
bluegill that we'd have to fight them off with the oars. To make
the trip work, I bought each of the boys a raft, so they could
paddle around the ponds and fish, and I'd be nearby in a float
tube.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm evening, clear sky, with a light ripple on the
pond from a breeze out of the north. As we arrived in my old pickup
truck, we watched a fish rising on the surface in the corner of a
pond, leaving little swirls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that,'' Jeremy said in a nervous whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it, too,'' Kris answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go get him,'' I answered.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy jumped out of the truck, grabbed his rod and snuck up on
that fish from shore. His first cast landed with a plop, sending
out miniature rings on the surface, and the lure sat motionless,
floating quietly, until the rings disappeared. Then Jeremy twitched
that lure, and in the next instant, a fish smashed into it and
practically came flying out of the water, and then came the shout,
``I got him!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was a friendly tussle, and it turned out be a bluegill,
a strong little fellow, and I showed Jeremy how to grab the hook
with pliers and release the fish back to the lake without harming
it.
</P>
<P>
   In minutes, we plunked our rafts in the lake, strapped on our
life vests, then starting floating around, casting about with our
lures, catching fish, letting them go amid shouts that echoed
across the water ... ``I got one'' ... ``Look at this one!'' ...
``This one's huge!''
</P>
<P>
   As dusk arrived, the bullfrogs were croaking away in the tules
along the shore, and sometimes when we approached, they would jump
a foot or two, startling us for moment. When it was time to leave,
we'd caught too many fish to count. At one point, Jeremy was in
what he called ``Bluegill Central,'' a fish a cast. At another,
Kris announced he was going to catch one at a certain spot, then
did.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, this is what being a dad is all about, and I announced it
was time to head out, but across the pond, Jeremy was lost in
concentration, working on a knot or something in his little raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working on a line problem,'' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, he was still out there, floating about, not
fishing, but working at something. It was nearly dark now.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with a giant grin he rowed in. As he neared shore, I
could see that in his raft was this giant mess, the fishing line,
billowing in a huge tangle in a two-foot mound, all of it, with no
line left on his reel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he grinned. Later, he confided: ``I was changing lures
and I noticed my rod was gone,'' he explained. ``I didn't know
where it was for a second, then I followed the line and it went
right out of the boat and into the pond, and that's when I figured
out it was on the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added: ``So I started pulling the line in, all of it,
until the rod came back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kris grinned, a triumphant moment for his brother to get in a
mess. After all, he noted, ``I'm usually the one getting in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Jeremy added, ``You might not understand how a thing like
this can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, actually, I know exactly how these things can happen,''
remembering when I had done the same exact thing on that day out in
Capitola.
</P>
<P>
   It's knowing about how ``these things can happen'' and making
them OK that makes being a dad special.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
