<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMERSONGS-LIST-TEX     06-21 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERSONGS-LIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMERTIME BLUES AND RED-HOT SINGLES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies SUMMER SONGS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Singles of the summer don't have to be about the summer, but it
helps. The only criterion for this subjective and highly personal
list of singles of the summer is that the songs actually were hits
in the summers of their respective years. Not every year has a
single of the summer; some years have more than one. Here are some
choices from the past 35 years. Feel free to argue with them.
</P>
<P>
   1964: ``Dancing in the Street,'' Martha and the Vandellas _ The
group that gave us ``Heat Wave'' in the summer of '63 peaked at No.
2 with this anthem, a call to party in a nation still jolted by the
Kennedy assassination and starting to become divided over Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   1965: ``(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction,'' the Rolling Stones _
Arguably the most famous riff in rock history announces a song
about youthful disaffection, lust and rebellion, sung by Mick
Jagger in a voice that moves from a purr to a yowl.
</P>
<P>
   1966: ``Summer in the City,'' The Lovin' Spoonful _ A crashing
organ introduces one of the best summer songs of all time, painting
a picture of sidewalks hotter than a matchstick and joyous
nighttime meetings on rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   1967: (four-way tie) ``Groovin','' the Little Rascals; ``Light
My Fire,'' the Doors; ``All You Need Is Love,'' the Beatles; ``Ode
to Billie Joe,'' Bobbie Gentry _ If any summer proved that it could
hold more than one single, it was the Summer of Love. A celebration
of a lazy Sunday afternoon; a dark, lusty anthem driven by a trashy
Farfisa organ; a Fab Four plea for unity; and a countryish
melodrama about a mysterious death _ all ruled the airwaves that
year.
</P>
<P>
   1969: ``Hot Fun in the Summertime,'' Sly &AMP; the Family Stone _
Sly's good-time song, which sounds like it was made to be played at
a picnic, would be one of the last times he evinced a vibe this
positive.
</P>
<P>
   1970: ``In the Summertime,'' Mungo Jerry _ Easily the goofiest
song on this list, this skiffle-group hit was anachronistic even
when it peaked at No. 3 in July 1970 _ and yet it's completely
infectious.
</P>
<P>
   1975: ``Love Will Keep Us Together,'' the Captain and Tennille _
Hey, we didn't say we LIKED all these songs. But in the summer of
'75, you couldn't get away from this perky concoction, which stayed
No. 1 for four weeks. Maybe it was this, and not disco, that led to
the fragmentation of radio formats.
</P>
<P>
   1978: (tie) ``Miss You,'' the Rolling Stones _ The Stones'
``disco'' move _ really not a very good dance song _ got them
airplay on stations that had given up on them, making the song
unavoidable during the summer of '78. ``Summer Nights,'' John
Travolta and Olivia Newton-John _ Just as faux retro as ``Miss
You'' was faux disco, this was completely manufactured nostalgia
(and poorly produced, too _ the background singers all but drown
out the weaker-voiced leads). But it was about summer nights (and
days), so we all said, ``Tell me more, tell me more.''
</P>
<P>
   1979: ``Funkytown,'' Lipps Inc. _ Yeah, so maybe it wasn't THE
single of the summer, but it's one of the best disco songs, with a
driving groove and a buoyant chorus. It was also the epitome of an
open-air song, because even those of us who were anti-disco in '79
couldn't get away from the blasted thing. Not that all of us wanted
to.
</P>
<P>
   1983: ``Every Breath You Take,'' the Police _ Sting's lyric,
about stalker-level obsession, was so misinterpreted as a love song
that Sting wrote ``If You Love Somebody Set Them Free'' as an
answer to it a couple of years later. But this stayed at No. 1 for
eight weeks, entering the chart in June and staying on the radio
the remainder of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   1984: ``When Doves Cry,'' Prince _ Man, what a day the first
Tuesday in June was this year, as Prince's ``Purple Rain'' and
Bruce Springsteen's ``Born in the U.S.A.'' albums were both
released. But ``Rain's'' flagship single, about the wounds created
by a turbulent relationship, stayed at No. 1 for five weeks and
sounded far more summery than any of the Springsteen singles (note
to wise guys: ``Glory Days'' was released the next summer).
</P>
<P>
   1989: ``Love Shack,'' the B-52's _ Believe it or not, this
didn't debut on the Top 40 till September, but it bubbled under so
long on then-new ``alternative rock'' formats that it felt like a
single of the summer, especially with its lines about laughin' and
a-dancin', kissin' and a-huggin'. To think that we ever thought of
such ebullience as ``alternative'' ...
</P>
<P>
   1994: ``Fantastic Voyage,'' Coolio _ Yes, we know, we skipped
some years, and during one of 'em Boyz II Men's ``End of the Road''
ruled the summer charts. The Boyz had an even bigger hit in summer
'94 with ``I'll Make Love to You.'' But c'mon, what makes you think
more of trips to the beach, the Boyz's too-cool harmonies or
Coolio's bouncin' hip-hop anthem that beckons you to slide, slide,
slippity-slide?
</P>
<P>
   1998: ``The Way,'' Fastball _ Yeah, Barenaked Ladies' ``One
Week'' was all over the place, but this song had it beat for summer
feeling; it starts like it's on an old transistor radio, it has a
keyboard riff AND a chorus you swear you've heard before, and it's
about a couple of folks who simply decide to aimlessly hit the
highway. Perfect road-trip music.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
