<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4000 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      06-21 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Metal in the Microwave
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1 in the modern kitchen: never put metal in the
microwave. Aluminum foil and metal containers reflect, rather than
absorb, microwave radiation, and can cause overheating, arcing,
even fire.
</P>
<P>
   But now materials scientists at Pennsylvania State University
have developed a process that allows metal to be microwaved. Rather
than popcorn, their ovens produce precision machine parts.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers adapted a technique known as sintering, in which
powdered metals are cold-pressed into a desired shape and heated
below the melting point until the powders fuse. Most sintering
processes use a conventional furnace, although some microwave
sintering of ceramics and semimetals (containing carbide) has been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The Penn State team, which described its research in the journal
Nature, used mixtures of powdered iron, copper, tungsten and other
metals in microwave ovens of up to 6,000 watts. The researchers
found that rather than reflecting microwaves, the powdered metals
absorbed them.
</P>
<P>
   The cold-pressed parts, toothed gears and other components up to
about two inches wide, were placed in a ceramic tube in the oven.
The tube, a key to the process, allows microwaves in but will not
let the resulting heat out, helping to maintain the high
temperatures (typically 2,000 degrees) needed for sintering. The
researchers found that in many cases, microwaved parts were denser
and harder than similar parts sintered in a conventional furnace.
</P>
<P>
   Secrets of the Mayans
</P>
<P>
   The materials scientists among the ancient peoples that once
dominated Central America did not have high technology at their
disposal, but their results were equally astonishing. Among other
things, the Mayans and other civilizations made natural latex into
rubber, producing strips for attaching ax heads to handles, hollow
figurines, and balls for the ritual ball game that played such a
huge role in their societies.
</P>
<P>
   Rubber was made in Central America as early as 1600 B.C.,
predating modern vulcanization processes by a cool 3,500 years. And
the secret formula has been out for a long time: Spanish invaders
in the 16th century described how the Indians mixed latex sap with
juice from a type of morning glory vine to make the rubber. What
has been lacking has been an understanding of how the process
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology have
now filled in some of the gaps. Ancient samples were too heavily
oxidized and otherwise degraded for analysis, so the researchers
found the next best thing: rubber produced by the same traditional
process by people in the Chiapas region of southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The MIT team compared unprocessed latex, which becomes brittle
when dried, to the rubber. They found that proteins and other
compounds in unprocessed latex disrupt interactions among the
polymer chains. The vine liquid separates these compounds, allowing
the polymer chains to become entangled. Other compounds in the vine
liquid itself increase the cross-linking between the polymers. Both
phenomena help account for the rubbery qualities of the finished
product.
</P>
<P>
   Origin of a Comet
</P>
<P>
   In studying how an icy comet has evolved, one clue can be found
in the amount of carbon monoxide it gives off as it nears the Sun.
Relatively less carbon monoxide would mean that the comet formed in
the warmer confines of the ancient disk of gas and dust that
swirled around and eventually formed the planets. More carbon
monoxide would mean the comet was born in the colder gas cloud that
preceded the disk.
</P>
<P>
   But astronomers had never had the chance to get detailed
information about cometary carbon monoxide until Hale-Bopp appeared
in 1997. Now, researchers from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and several American universities report that carbon
monoxide emissions from Hale-Bopp are consistent with its having
been formed in the protoplanetary disk, in an area between Jupiter
and Neptune.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in Nature, also report that Hale-Bopp's
carbon monoxide comes from two sources, evenly split: ice in the
nucleus, and the coma, where more complex molecules may be being
broken down by the Sun's warmth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
