<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seashells
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do seashells grow?
</P>
<P>
   A. Seashells, and indeed all shells of the mollusk group,
whether they live in salt water, in fresh water or on land, do not
grow by adding cells of living tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they gradually increase in size at one edge, called the
growing edge, as crystals of mineral salts are secreted by a large,
thin, enveloping flap of tissue called the mantle and laid down in
a framework of a hornlike substance called conchiolin.
</P>
<P>
   Seashells are chiefly calcium carbonate, extracted from the
water, according to The Illustrated Encyclopedia of the Animal
Kingdom (Danbury Press). In the mantle, tiny tubes excrete the
almost invisible specks of mineral salt that cement to the
conchiolin.
</P>
<P>
   Most shells have three layers: first, a protective outer skin of
organic matter that may be smooth or rough; second, a layer of
crystals arranged at right angles to the surface of the shell, and
finally, an inner layer composed of overlapping crystals. In some
mollusks, like oysters, this layer is pearly and iridescent.
</P>
<P>
   Shells increase in size as material is added to the growing edge
and in thickness as overlapping layers are added to the inner
surface.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an injury to the shell or if a foreign body is
inserted between the mantle and shell, secretions from the mantle
quickly repair the damage or encase the foreign object.
</P>
<P>
   _C. CLAIBORNE RAY
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to:
Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
