<HEADER>
A4006 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-POP-TEX     06-21 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALZHEIMER'S DOESN'T BLUR PHOTOGRAPHER'S LOVING PORTRAIT OF `POP'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we meet him, Hy Meyerowitz is 87 years old. He's an affable
sort who loves his wife, Sally, has a kind word and a handshake for
everyone he meets, fondly recalls boxing in the Golden Gloves in
the '20s _ and can remember neither the names of his three sons nor
what he did yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Hy Meyerowitz has Alzheimer's, which is slowly robbing him of
his life experiences _ but which somehow, to judge by his son
Joel's documentary, ``Pop,'' never manages to steal his humanity.
</P>
<P>
   And it is portraying this dichotomy that makes ``Pop,'' which
airs Tuesday night on PBS, such a moving, uplifting hour of
television _ a perfect Father's Day present, two days late.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Meyerowitz is an acclaimed photographer whose work has
appeared in more than 120 exhibitions in museums and galleries
around the world, including the Museum of Modern Art in New York
and the Museum of Modern Art in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   His premise for ``Pop'' was simplicity itself: The two of them,
plus Joel's son Sasha, would go on a two-week road trip to Florida
and back, with Joel goosing Hy's memories as they drive and hit
various tourist spots.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like a truly bad idea: Let's stick the old guy
with the degenerative brain disease in a car, take him to
unfamiliar surroundings, and ask him a lot of questions. What good
could possibly come of this?
</P>
<P>
   What emerges, however, is a portrait of a man caught between
wholeness and nothingness. And what comes of that, and Hy's
interaction with Joel, is a glimpse of the universal truth of the
bond between all fathers and sons that cannot be broken, that is
unique in the human family.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost sure to be imperfect, and tested in a thousand
ways, but it remains, no matter what changes swirl around it. Even
if the son becomes, in many ways, the protector.
</P>
<P>
   Hy's moments of lucidity _ and there are many _ include poignant
memories, touches of whimsical humor, a genuine love for other
people (friend and stranger, black and white) and a deep insight
into himself. With all his defenses gone, we see the real man,
without pretense. We see him as still in love with his wife, proud
of his kids, and still living life on life's terms.
</P>
<P>
   It is, moreover, hard to believe that this is Joel Meyerowitz's
first film. He deftly intersperses periods in which Hy simply talks
among those moments in which he is gently questioned, and mixes
footage of the journey with photos and film of Hy and his family
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The film has a sweet, easy feel _ in the hands of a lesser
artist this journey could have turned horribly maudlin, but
Meyerowitz never lets that happen.
</P>
<P>
   We feel for Hy, and we gain more insight into just how baffling
the disease's effects are, but we are never asked to view him as
just a victim, as just an old man with a nice life behind him and a
horrible void awaiting.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping the tone just right _ through memories, through
subtly placed music, through showing Hy as a fully formed man,
warts and all _ we feel more for him, and for the relationship
between Hy and Joel.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it wasn't much, but it was great, I was having a great
time all the time,'' he says at one point, and it's a totally
revealing moment. We see that Hy realized he was one among many,
that he always felt he had a responsibility to his friends and
neighbors to do his best, and that that love of simply being alive
could not be killed.
</P>
<P>
   Hy Meyerowitz did his best. His was not an extraordinary life,
but it was one lived extraordinarily well _ even at the end.
Meyerowitz has given us the universal through the specific. ``Pop''
captures both the idea that your dad is the greatest, strongest,
most powerful man in the world, and the realization that he is
simply flesh and blood. And that's pretty wonderful, too.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
