<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: REAL DOGS DON'T BEEP
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, June 21)  
(nk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for the millennium (no, not a doomsday comet; we
should be so lucky), comes Aibo, the $2,500 robot dog from Sony
that looks and acts just like a real dog assuming your idea of a
real dog is something with titanium skin and what appears to be a
CB antenna sticking out of its butt.
</P>
<P>
   Aibo, which is short for Artificial Intelligence roBOt, is, in
the lyrical prose of Sony's engineers, ``an autonomous robot that
is capable of not only functioning in response to external
stimulation and its own judgment, but also of expressing various
emotions, growing through learning and communicating with human
beings to provide an entirely new form of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's true, you could use similar words to describe Al Gore,
but in this case we are not talking about a presidential candidate
but rather a 3 1/2-pound, 11-inch-long assemblage of circuit boards
and transistors that looks somewhat like a cross between Snoopy and
a Big Bertha driver.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sony geek-speak, ``Aibo has a head and legs with 3
degrees of freedom (up and down, forward and back, left and right)
each, a tail with 2 degrees of freedom (up and down, sideways) and
a mouth with one degree of freedom (open or closed), and is capable
of four-legged locomotion. It incorporates various sensors and
autonomous programs that allow it to behave just like a living
creature, reacting to external stimuli and acting in accordance
with its own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated, that means (I think) that Aibo can walk, sit and
beg, lie down, wag its tail, yawn, chase a ball and even dance.
And, just like a real dog, when it runs out of power, you simply
plug Aibo into its own personal battery charger and four hours
later, its ready for more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding, kids! Real dogs don't come with their own battery
charger! And even if they did, the first thing they'd do is bury it
in the yard or drool over it so much that the circuits would short
out and the whole thing would be way too disgusting to touch.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the obvious question of how a robot dog like Aibo
would stack up against a real dog. For testing purposes, the
closest thing I could come to a real dog was our pug, Buster. Don't
worry: Buster was not harmed in any way during this exercise. In
fact, exercise is probably the wrong word to use since he slept the
whole time.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here is a trait-by-trait comparison:
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Aibo: 3.5 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Buster: 25 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Details: Thanks to a diet of scrambled eggs and popcorn, Buster
is an ounce of two over his ideal weight and is currently on a
strict diet (absolutely no sour cream on his baked potato). The
drawback is that when he falls asleep on your lap, your legs go
numb. But unlike Aibo, he makes an excellent doorstop on windy
days.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Buster
</P>
<P>
   DISGUSTING PERSONAL HABITS
</P>
<P>
   Aibo: None
</P>
<P>
   Buster: Too many to list.
</P>
<P>
   Details: You don't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Aibo
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HE WILL DO IN AN ELECTRICAL STORM
</P>
<P>
   Aibo: Attract lightning
</P>
<P>
   Buster: Hide under bed
</P>
<P>
   Details: Buster is usually found under 13-year-old's bed, as
there is a better selection of food there. If lightning strikes
while Aibo is recharging, your house may become the set for the
upcoming Godzilla sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Buster
</P>
<P>
   NUMBER OF STATIONS PICKED UP BY TAIL
</P>
<P>
   Aibo: Dozens, but all in Japanese
</P>
<P>
   Buster: None
</P>
<P>
   Details: When you grow tired of him, Aibo would make a great
$2,500 shish kebab skewer. When you grow tired of Buster, he will
still want more shish kebab.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Tie
</P>
<P>
   REACTION TO TV DOORBELLS
</P>
<P>
   Aibo: Whirling of gears, flashing of lights
</P>
<P>
   Buster: BARKBARKBARKBARKBARK!
</P>
<P>
   Details: Thanks to Buster's vigilance, we have never had our
home broken into by Homer Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Buster
</P>
<P>
   Well, folks, you can't argue with unbiased scientific research
and you can't argue with whatever this thing was, either. Real dogs
are, for now at least, superior to robot dogs, which is not to say
that Buster's intelligence wouldn't be enhanced by a 100MHz, 64-bit
RISC processor with 16 MB of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he didn't slobber on it or bury it in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
