<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-GUIDEBOOKS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE TO BLANKET NATION WITH GUIDEBOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ariz., Fla., Ohio, Ore., Wash., Mass.)  (nk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following a trial run in five states, the federal
Medicare agency is planning nationwide distribution of a new
consumer guide it held back last year due to fears it would foster
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The handbook, set to go in the mail this fall as part of a $133
million public education campaign, will provide 39 million
beneficiaries with general information about Medicare as well as
available managed care options. The handbook will direct recipients
to a toll-free number and Internet site for more details and
in-depth comparisons of HMO benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials said their experience in five test states _
Arizona, Florida, Ohio, Oregon and Washington _ provided them with
important insight into how to craft the handbook to make it most
useful to the recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a special effort over the past year to really listen
to beneficiaries,'' said Nancy-Ann DeParle, head of the Health Care
Financing Administration, which oversees Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the Medicare &AMP; You handbook was to be distributed
nationally last year as part of a congressional effort to slow
spending on Medicare by encouraging more older Americans to join
health maintenance organizations and other managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers, Clinton administration officials and senior
advocates became worried that beneficiaries _ most of whom have
little or no experience with managed care _ would be overwhelmed
and frightened by the imposing 45-page handbook, a concern
supported by surveys and focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the national initiative was scrapped and the
five-state pilot program was undertaken instead. In addition, the
Medicare agency conducted in-depth studies of beneficiary response
in five communities in the trial states _- Sarasota, Fla.; Dayton,
Ohio; Eugene, Ore.; Olympia, Wash., and Tucson, Ariz. _ as well as
Springfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   One of the findings made by the researchers, according to the
health care agency, was that the handbook did not provoke the
predicted anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't happen,'' said Carol Cronin, director of the
health agency's Center for Beneficiary Services.
</P>
<P>
   What the agency did discover was that most beneficiaries glance
through the handbook but hold on to it to refer to the information
when the need arises. The researchers recommended several changes
to make it more digestible, including a quick summary at the front.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, senior advocates and others anticipate the handbook
will spark some puzzlement when it goes out in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inevitable,'' said Tricia Smith, a top lobbyist for the
American Association of Retired Persons. ``You have 39 million
beneficiaries. You have more complex information than they have
confronted before coming into their homes. The fact is this is an
extraordinarily complicated program.''
</P>
<P>
   One source of trouble may be the current upheaval among Medicare
HMOs, with plans withdrawing from counties and scaling back benefit
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to cover whole states and other large geographic areas,
the handbooks will list available HMOs. But all those plans will
not serve all communities receiving the literature.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, beneficiaries who call the hotline or check the Web
site will get brochures describing what plans, if any, serve their
particular ZIP code, raising the possibility of disappointment if
the coverage they wanted is not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be about more choice but then they find
out they don't have much choice,'' said Smith. She said, though,
the opportunity for a second, more detailed mailing for those who
call the hot line should reduce confusion. ``I think that is
actually a very good step.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some insurance carriers are predicting more turmoil in
the Medicare HMO community in the coming months, DeParle, the
Medicare administrator, is optimistic the disruption will be
minimal. ``I am not anticipating quite what we saw law year,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency intends to print 34 million of the books,
distributing one per household after some couples complained the
agency was wasting money by sending them two. Officials were
enthusiastic about the way the Medicare hotline functioned and
expect callers to get answers with no waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare managed care companies are underwriting the cost of the
education program through a special assessment, a fee the industry
believes is unfair since Medicare HMOs are already struggling
financially and the handbook information goes far beyond managed
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Medicare beneficiaries in fee-for-service amount to 85
percent of all beneficiaries and managed care plans take care of
only 15 percent, they imposed on managed care plans 100 percent of
the costs,'' said Stephen J. deMontmollin, an executive with AvMed
Health Plan in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But Medicare officials say the assessment is justified because
the handbook will serve as a marketing tool for managed care plans
trying to gain Medicare customers.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
