<HEADER>
A4017 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SAYLES-LIMBO-TEX     06-21 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SAYLES-LIMBO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIMBO' BENDS OVER BACKWARD TO TAKE RISKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director John Sayles has a reputation as an
independent-film pioneer. But chatting with Sayles and Maggie
Renzi, his longtime companion and frequent film producer, feels
less like talking about movies than it feels like listening to the
adventures of a world-traveling couple.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles' movies have taken the pair all over, from the Harlem of
1984's ``The Brother From Another Planet'' to the Irish shores of
1994's ``The Secret of Roan Inish'' to the Mexican jungles of last
year's ``Men With Guns.'' Last year, the couple spent the summer in
and around Juneau, Alaska, working on Sayles' 12th directorial
effort, ``Limbo,'' which opened last week. Although they don't make
the job sound a whole lot like work, they give you the sense that
they weren't accidental tourists. They lived the local life, made
friends in the community and came to understand what makes Alaska
unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part of Alaska we were shooting in, until probably the
last 10 years, was mostly men,'' says the tall, affable Sayles.
``Women were very, very scarce. Traditionally, it's a place where
men went to risk their lives to make a living, to make a fortune.
And women were more like camp followers. I'd say in the last 10 to
20 years, really, more and more women have come up there just
because they wanted to come up there _ and they've stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   This knowledge helps inform ``Limbo,'' a complex _ some would
say problematic _ movie that starts, like many of Sayles' films, as
an examination of a culture before switching gears to settle on
three characters. But ``Limbo's'' male lead, Joe Gastineau (David
Strathairn), isn't a risk taker _ he's been reserved and haunted
since a fishing-boat accident 25 years ago. He begins to come alive
again through his burgeoning relationship with feisty singer Donna
De Angelo (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, in a career-defining
performance) and her sullen daughter Noelle (Dallas native Vanessa
Martinez).
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't already know that Sayles and Renzi were a couple,
it would take you seconds to figure it out. They have that way of
picking up on each other's sentences, of pushing the conversation
ahead by filling in each other's gaps. As easy as it is to talk to
them, though, ``Limbo'' is a tough movie to discuss without
spoiling a few things. Sayles continually pulls the rug out from
under his audience, changing the movie's focus and giving it an
abrupt, ambiguous ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a phrase early in the movie where a guy says, `What do
you get when you get on a roller coaster? Not risk, but the
illusion of risk,''' Sayles says. ``Most movies are meant to be
roller-coaster rides. If you think of `Mad Max' or `Raiders of the
Lost Ark,' it's a great roller-coaster ride. There's a lot of
twists and turns, but finally you know that Mel Gibson and Harrison
Ford aren't going to get killed. There's that seat belt, that this
is a `movie' movie. It's the illusion of risk. In this movie, what
I'm asking of the audience is to take that seat belt off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has been comfortable removing it. Although
``Limbo'' recently earned Sayles the best director award at the
Seattle Film Festival and has received many positive reviews, its
ending has caused a certain amount of outrage among audiences and
critics. Boos were reported at some screenings, and the movie
inspired one California entertainment journalist to write an entire
column about how movies should have endings. Curiously, many of the
reviewers who have taken issue with the movie's unpredictability
are the same ones who object to the connect-the-dots structure of
movies like ``Instinct'' _ and who have forgotten that many
influential movies had ambiguous undertones.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's getting scary,'' Renzi says. ``Either people
have forgotten about the movies they saw before 1980, or they never
saw them. John talks about the ending of `The Graduate,' which as
you remember is not a freeze-frame with the bride and the boy
running away. It is, in fact, the two of them sitting in the back
of the bus riding into the rest of their lives with a big question
mark about what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayles, who says he hasn't read a review since eight movies ago
(a period that would include ``City of Hope'' and ``Lone Star,''
two of Sayles' best efforts), believes that ``Limbo's'' themes are
getting lost in the uproar about the ending. But then, the movie's
various meditations on ``limbo'' aren't easy to address, although
they're more secular than spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, in the movie, limbo kind of represents those
situations that everybody kind of gets into or lives in, where
you're not drowning but you're not going anywhere,'' Sayles says,
citing an example: ``You're in a job you hate, but you know, `I've
got rent to pay, I've got kids to feed, I don't have another job
lined up, it's not a good time to quit. ... Ah, I can stand it.'
... The only way out of those, truly, is either incredible luck _
and that rarely happens _ or taking a risk. And when you take a
risk _ not the illusion of risk, but real risk _ you don't know how
it's going to turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayles' movies have sometimes been criticized for being too
scriptbound, for their sense of concentrating too much on the words
and not the pictures. ``Limbo'' hasn't escaped these complaints,
but the movie's not likely to let down Sayles' admirers, who often
come to his films not for the stories but for the characters and
dialogue. No filmmaker has a stronger sense of place, the result of
his and Renzi's extensive research, their living on location and
their use of local talent wherever they film. And Sayles is rare in
the way that he can provide a story line for even the smallest
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say to the actors in our movies, no matter how small
the part is, the camera should be able to follow you, and we should
feel like you have a totally interesting story to tell,'' Sayles
says. ``This movie could be about you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
