<SLUG> BC-SHANIA-TWAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP STAR TO SELL ESTATE AFTER ZONING CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT REGIS FALLS, N.Y. _ Country-pop music superstar Shania
Twain and her husband-producer Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange have
vacated their vast estate in upstate New York after an
environmental controversy and put the property up for sale for $7.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the largest and most expensive private properties
currently on the market in the six-million acre Adirondack Park.
</P>
<P>
   Twain and Lange have not been seen around their 3,039-acre
Adirondack getaway for months after paying $45,000 in fines,
agreeing to remove soil used to fill protected wetlands and to
address other environmental violations in a settlement with the
Adirondack Park Agency, which oversees zoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've pretty much abandoned the Adirondacks,'' said
Mike Dikun, manager of the Adirondack Regional Airport in Saranac
Lake. There haven't been any sightings since last fall of the
couple, who had flown into the airport frequently in a chartered
private jet and were whisked away in a GMC sport utility vehicle
with a TWAIN vanity plate.
</P>
<P>
   Twain was not available for an interview, her publicist, Jim
Flammia, said. He added that the demands of Twain's tour schedule _
a West Coast swing begins with a concert June 24 in Portland, Ore.
_ likely would not permit her to stop in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``Twain Zone'' by the singer for its remoteness, the
property includes the entire 300-acre Dexter Lake and is located
near Saint Regis Falls, on the northern border of the Adirondack
Park.
</P>
<P>
   The estate features a 26,628-square foot, state-of-the-art
recording studio and apartments designed in the shape of a castle,
with turrets and a glass wall offering panoramic views. Twain and
her husband began building the complex four years ago after tearing
down a historic lakeside mansion. The estate includes a boathouse,
tennis court, horse stables and corrals. The hideaway is accessible
by a mile-long private dirt road through forest land.
</P>
<P>
   On June 15, at the gated entrance along Blue Mountain Road, a
guard shack was empty and the only sound was a brisk wind hissing
through pine trees. Orange no trespassing signs were posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're long gone,'' said Wayne Hart, a neighbor on Blue
Mountain Road. ``Even when they were here, they were very quiet and
kept to themselves. I'd see them riding their horses once in a
while, but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain's plans to build a 12,000-square foot lakeside mansion
that she once described as ``Mediterranean-meets-Adirondack Great
Camp'' apparently have been shelved, despite being approved by the
Adirondack Park Agency just last month. That approval would
transfer to a new buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a zoning problem,'' Twain said in the June 14 issue
of People magazine. ``My husband wanted to do a lot of landscaping.
And that landscaping wasn't permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain told the magazine that she and her husband spend most of
their time in Tour-de-Peilz, Switzerland, at a 19th-century manor
house overlooking Lake Geneva that they bought in December.
</P>
<P>
   Lange scored platinum album successes with such artists as
Michael Bolton, Bryan Addams and Foreigner before discovering Twain
in a video in 1993 and marrying her later that year. Twain's career
soared with the help of Lange's work on her Grammy-winning 1995
country album, ``The Woman in Me,'' which has sold more than 10
million copies and became the biggest-selling album by a female
artist in country music history.
</P>
<P>
   Their Adirondack estate is in decidedly non-celebrity environs,
surrounded by unpaved roads, mobile homes, sagging bungalows and
junk cars in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   The isolated setting _ 25 miles south of the Canadian border _
fits when one considers that the Canadian-born Twain, 33, grew up
in a poor mining town 500 miles north of Toronto and Lange, 50, who
is from South Africa, is known for a reclusive streak. Lange
recently bought the rights to nearly every photograph ever taken of
him, according to People.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These violations were cited in the November 1998 settlement with
the Adirondack Park Agency:
</P>
<P>
   _ A half-dozen areas where newly built structures, including a
retaining wall and a gazebo, were not set back at least 100 feet
from the lake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Five wetlands areas filled without proper permits, including a
one-acre section at the base of a slope into which the recording
studio was built.
</P>
<P>
   _ Installation of a septic system in a wetlands without proper
permits.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Curran, director of regulatory programs for the agency said
the wetlands fill is currently being removed. The septic system was
relocated to a new site away from the wetlands. Also, movable
structures such as the gazebo were transported beyond the 100-foot
lake setback zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The applicant (Lange) and his representatives really rolled
their sleeves up and did everything they could to correct the
situation,'' Curran said. ``They were very cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Politi, owner of the Lake Placid real estate company
listing the couple's estate, defended Lange and Twain. ``It was an
error in construction,'' Politi said. ``There's a lot worse going
on up here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
