<SLUG> BC-X-GAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL COMPETITION IN X GAMES ISN'T ATHLETIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Generation X circus will roll into town
later this week _ a three-ring affair spanning the Embarcadero, the
Great Highway and Treasure Island and leaving the city awash in
skateboards, in-line skates, a man-made pile of snow, pierced body
parts, free-flowing locks, tattoos and an overriding sense of the
extreme and the rebellious.
</P>
<P>
   Here come the X Games, fashioned by ESPN, the all-sports network
that spawned the idea in 1993 to create an Olympics-modeled
competition for alternative sports and then gave birth to the event
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath all of the anti-establishment aura emitted by the X
Games lies a traditional reality: money. In actually creating its
own event, as opposed to the more traditional role of buying rights
to a sporting extravaganza (see: Super Bowl, NCAA Final Four, World
Series, NBA Finals), ESPN devised an avenue to reach an audience
coveted by sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One word: demographics,'' said Barry Frank, a senior group
vice president at the mega-marketing company IMG. ``It's very hard
to capture those teen-age viewers under any circumstances,
particularly young males.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that, ESPN set out to find a way to reach consumers ages
12 to 34, to sell potential sponsors on the idea that their
advertising actually would be seen by young people.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a market that actually does have money to spend, and
that companies would like nothing more than to latch onto now in
hopes that younger people will remain loyal to their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X Generation is more independent at an earlier age and
with a higher discretionary income than any other generation in the
history of mankind,'' said Dean Bonham, whose business, The Bonham
Group, advises companies on sponsorship of sporting events. ``And
by the way, the income that is not discretionary is in their
parents' pockets, which they have influence over.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC saw the benefits of this type of event so clearly that it
recently announced its creation of the Gravity Games _ a carbon
copy of the X Games that will include some of the same sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it's significant that people recognize that the X
Games and the Gravity Games are both made-for-television events,''
Bonham said. ``And I think that will be more prominent in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hagle is ESPN's vice president in charge of integrated sales
and marketing. In other words, he's the top gun charged with
hunting down companies to attach their names _ and considerable
financial support _ to the X Games. More and more, Hagle has become
the hunted as well as the hunter.
</P>
<P>
   While the event had just six sponsors in 1995, it now has 16,
and the list includes the likes of Visa, AT&AMP;T, Taco Bell, the U.S.
Marine Corps, Snickers and Adidas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always the desire of ESPN, to try to create an event
that is of significant interest to both viewers and sponsors,''
Hagle said. ``It's not like this is necessarily new. ABC had the
Superstars years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of made-for-TV events, but the idea of
creating events based on what is the perceived marketplace demand,
I think that's a little bit of a new wrinkle.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wrinkle that has brought the programming and marketing
departments much closer together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, it was programmers program it and sellers sell
it,'' Hagle said. ``Now there's a tremendous amount of interaction
between the two groups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
