<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATING-CHECK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MAKES IT EASIER TO CHECK OUT MR. RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men and women ring the bar at a local Razzoo's, swilling goblets
of wine and bottles of beer under a haze of white cigarette smoke.
There is a din of constant chatter in the background.
</P>
<P>
   At the front of the bar, Eric Edwards and Billie Jo Donath are
in a tight embrace, smiling as they gaze into each other's eyes
like lovers do.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the man of Donath's dreams, or are they just
friends?
</P>
<P>
   More important, how much does she really know about him? Has she
done her homework?
</P>
<P>
   Though Donath said she would never go to such extremes, private
investigators said that a growing number of women are relying on
the Internet and more conventional means to do background checks on
prospective suitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking for a technological means to find Mr.
Right,'' said Ed Pankau, a Houston investigator who co-wrote ``How
to Investigate by Computer.'' ``In comes the Internet and the means
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the investment of a few minutes online, women can verify
their love interest's name, determine whether he is single or
married, and learn whether he has been named in any lawsuits, has a
criminal record or has a lien against property he owns, said
Pankau, a former investigator for the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women today are dating virtual strangers _ men they've met via
the Internet, personals, or in nightclubs and bars,'' said Joseph
Ryan, author of a recently published manual called ``Check Him Out!
The American Woman's Guide to Background Investigations.'' ``Often
these men are much different in reality from the knights in shining
armor they make themselves out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   While the potential for fraud has always been real, Ryan said
the ``deceit factor'' in dating is probably 100 times higher on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a worldwide phenomenon,'' Ryan said. ``The catch is
you don't know anything about a person except what they tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all women are willing to hire an investigator or use the
Internet to verify that their man is who he says he is. They prefer
to rely on information from friends or use their intuition.
</P>
<P>
   Donath, for example, is a 25-year-old teacher in the Fort Worth,
Texas, public school system. She said she would buy a book like
``Check Him Out,'' and read it for her own information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be valuable to have, but I would never use
it,'' she said. ``I'd never check someone out. I'd get to know them
on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Donath and Eric Edwards said they are just
friends. He appreciates her way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, if you don't trust a person to tell you the
truth, you shouldn't even be wasting your time,'' Edwards said.
``Why would you date someone you'd even have to think about doing a
background check on?''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeanne, who identified herself as a 21-year-old waitress
from Arlington, Texas, has a different view. She considers meeting
men via the Internet unsafe, but said that she'd probably go online
to check out a man she's interested in dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was that into him, I would definitely do it,'' she said.
``You can't be too sure about anything these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from a small town, and everyone I ever dated I knew
something about them,'' Jeanne said. ``Now I'm in a big city, and I
know nothing about the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne would want to know, among other things, Does he have a
girlfriend? Does he have a job or is he freeloading on his mother?
</P>
<P>
   Pankau, who receives about 60 requests a month for background
checks, said women ask for a variety of facts, such as employment
and credit history, educational background, and sexual practices.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you ask, background checks using agencies can
cost from $150 to $500. On the Internet, it's free.
</P>
<P>
   At Brown and Associates in Orlando, Fla., owner C.R. ``Bob''
Brown said his firm can do a complete background check for $150.
``That would include what we call a marriage tree, driving history
to help tell us if the person has a disregard for the law, criminal
history, and also a list of the vehicles registered to that person
and who's living in his home,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get children checking on Mom's guy or Mom doing the
checking herself. But usually it's a single woman who wants
surveillance more so than a background check.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier times, women dated men from their neighborhood, not
from the World Wide Web. They relied on their mother's opinion,
even if they didn't always agree.
</P>
<P>
   But today, checking out a man's background may be a necessary
evil.
</P>
<P>
   A 38-year-old secretary, who asked not to be identified,
remembered a man she met on the Internet who for nearly a year led
her to believe he was single.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after she attended an out-of-town conference with
him that she learned he was married with two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will lie,'' she said. ``You'd better check them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who said she would never hire a private investigator,
said that she had learned through experience to do her own
snooping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I married my husband, I asked him to show me his
divorce decree,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He complied. They have been married for five years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ .MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
