<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-CO     06-21 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Memories of a red dirt hill
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Linda Sinclair
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   From the time I was 3 years old I visited my grandparents in a
small town in Alabama, and that place was more familiar to me than
any of the many towns where my parents and I lived during those
years.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I was there in the fall to help my granddaddy dig
potatoes, and sometimes we were there at Christmas or Thanksgiving
with some or all of the families of my three aunts and two uncles.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly I remember summer.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, I don't remember it being the terrible,
down-South hot that I know it must have been.
</P>
<P>
   I only remember the freedom and safety of being able to play in
wonderful places like the barn, where a rope swing hung from the
highest rafter, or up the chinaberry trees laden with ammunition
for cousin fights.
</P>
<P>
   I would play jacks or marbles under the shade of the pecan trees
in the front yard or escape beyond the garden and the chicken yard
to the top of a red dirt hill.
</P>
<P>
   My cousins and I took turns zipping down that hill in two Red
Flyer wagons. Then we would hide in the trees at the bottom, so
completely covered by kudzu vine that they became shadowy caves.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally in the afternoons we were allowed to walk the six
blocks to town to visit the ``handy'' store, a sagging, gray wood
building set on stilts over a little stream.
</P>
<P>
   There were jars of penny sweets, rows and rows of candy bars and
suckers on sticks sprouting from holes in a wooden block.
</P>
<P>
   In the evenings after supper everyone sat on the big front
porch. If I was lucky I got a place in the swing, where I rocked
and listened to stories of our family's past.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a great while a car would pass, and my grandfather could
almost always identify the people for us.
</P>
<P>
   Finally one of the grownups would notice the lateness of the
hour, and we were sent or carried off to bed.
</P>
<P>
   The house, the garden and the red dirt hill are gone now, or
changed beyond recognition, and cars whiz by constantly at the
place where pecan trees used to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The little town isn't such a little town anymore. It started
growing up about the same time I did.
</P>
<P>
   But in my mind it will always stay the same as it was when I was
a child visiting in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Sinclair lives in Hendersonville, N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, particularly if it ties in with
the upcoming Fourth of July holiday, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit htt://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
