<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV27-NY     06-21 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES `RELIGIOUS' SUDDENLY NEED A SYNONYM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 27)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Government should welcome the help of  &UR; faith-based &LR; 
institutions,'' Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said in 1996. In April
of this year, a spokesman for his brother, Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida, told The News and Record of Greensboro, N.C., ``The
governor supports  &UR; faith-based &LR;  initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long,'' said Vice President Al Gore to the Salvation
Army in Atlanta last month, `` &UR; faith-based &LR;  organizations have
wrought miracles on a shoestring.'' He welcomed ``the voices of
 &UR; faith-based &LR;  organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   In covering Gore's speech, John Harwood of The Wall Street
Journal noted ``both political parties' growing acceptance of
 &UR; faith-based &LR;  solutions since Republicans began promoting the idea
several years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Sack of The New York Times, though reporting Gore's
usage in direct quotation, did not use the suddenly popular phrase
in his own writing; instead, he used the more traditional noun in
discussing ``government financing of  &UR; religion-based &LR; 
welfare-to-work initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Faith-based &LR;  is hot enough to be enshrined in the official
canon. In Wisconsin, the Joint Legislative Council established the
Special Committee on  &UR; Faith-Based &LR;  Approaches to Crime Prevention
and Justice. Assembly Speaker Scott Jensen's legal counsel defines
those approaches as ``the acknowledgment of and faith in a higher
power,'' the belief that social pathologies include ``conditions of
the soul'' and that treatment involves ``a fundamental
transformation of character.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest use of this modifier now so in vogue was in
criticism, not affirmation, of religion in public life. In 1981,
Clarence Martin, a lobbyist for the Association for the Advancement
of Psychology, wrote that scholars of the social sciences, heirs to
Darwin, Marx and Freud, ``are the empirical left who may challenge
the views, or more importantly reject the  &UR; faith-based &LR;  values, of
the creationists, the moral majority, the laissez-faire
industrialists, the economic determinists, the sexists, the
militarists, the coalition who put Reagan in office.''
</P>
<P>
   The linguistic mystery: Why are political figures all using
 &UR; faith-based &LR;  rather than  &UR; religion-based &LR;  or, more simply than
that adjectival compound, the old-fashioned adjective  &UR; religious &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Religion &LR;  (probably from the Latin  &UR; religare &LR; , ``to restrain'')
is a set of beliefs;  &UR; faith &LR;  (from  &UR; fidere &LR; , ``to trust'') is the
unquestioning trust in the truth of those beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   American political tradition, following its metaphor of ``a wall
of separation between church and state,'' shies away from
``religion in politics'' but not away from religious values in
public life.
</P>
<P>
   By substituting  &UR; faith &LR;  (trust in the truths) for  &UR; religion &LR; 
(the organized set of beliefs), the new compound adjective gets
around the traditional objection. The Rev. Bill Callahan of the
Quixote Center in Hyattsville, Md., says, ``The language of
 &UR; faith-based &LR;  signals to people our motivation while separating us
from the institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -Based &LR;  is a hot formative suffix. Though  &UR; broad-based &LR;  is two
centuries old,  &UR; zero-based &LR;  took off around 1970 and missile lingo
gave us  &UR; land-based &LR; ,  &UR; sea-based &LR;  and  &UR; space-based &LR; . A discussion
of this particular parasynthetic derivative is  &UR; based-based &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   DISMILITARIZE?
</P>
<P>
   Few people are for unilateral  &UR; disarmament &LR; . Most Koreans and
Americans are familiar, after four decades, with a  &UR; demilitarized &LR; 
zone, or DMZ. Now, from the war that brought us  &UR; nonpermissive
environment &LR; , we have a distinction drawn between  &UR; disarm &LR;  and
 &UR; demilitarize &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs, Gen. Henry Shelton, said on
ABC's ``This Week'': ``We never said that we were going to
` &UR; disarm &LR; ' the KLA. We used the term ` &UR; demilitarize &LR; .''' The Wall
Street Journal editorialized on its meaning to the Kosovo
Liberation Army: ``This distinction apparently means they can keep
their hunting rifles, relying on a U.N.-supervised force to protect
them from Serbian tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The distinction, more finely put, is this:  &UR; Disarm &LR;  means ``to
divest of weapons; to deprive of the means of attack.''
 &UR; Demilitarize &LR;  means ``to close a military organization; to remove
the military power or potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we're into the trickiest kind of semantics. How  &UR; disarmed &LR; 
do you have to be to call yourself  &UR; demilitarized &LR; ? I think it
depends, first, on the power of the weaponry: If you carry a rifle
or a pistol, you are armed but not necessarily militarized; if you
are in an armored personnel carrier or in a choppering gunship,
You're in the Army Now.
</P>
<P>
   But how about an automatic rifle, a small mortar or a light
machine gun? If that's not  &UR; militarized &LR; , what about a little
howitzer or a heavy machine gun or shoulder-mounted missile? This
has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the meaning of  &UR; demilitarized &LR;  deals with
organization. Can a  &UR; demilitarized &LR;  group call itself an army? (The
Salvation Army would say yes.) Are a buncha guys hanging around in
civvies and calling one another ``Mister''  &UR; demilitarized &LR;  if they
practice maneuvers and draw a table of organization in the sand?
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman, Ken Bacon, informs me: `` &UR; Disarm &LR;  means
to take weapons away from an army.  &UR; Demilitarize &LR;  means to disband
the army.'' As I get it, the KLA will be disbanded but not
 &UR; disarmed &LR; , which suggest its members can keep all their arms as
individuals but may not assemble or otherwise get organized.
</P>
<P>
   The current meaning will be worked out at the negotiating tables
and on the field, then passed to lexicographers. Meanwhile, we are
in a very gray area. I asked a top soldier-diplomat if he would
like to set me straight on the latest specific meaning of
 &UR; demilitarize &LR; . I am not sure if he replied, ``No, thanks'' or ``No
tanks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
