<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-BOOK-REVIEW     06-21 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-BOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE AT FIRST LIGHT': THE HUNTER RETURNS, WEARY BUT STILL MACHO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Africa was a fine subject, and he had written about it well and
truly in the past, but the old days were gone now, and he was old
and weary and ailing, and what he wrote this time was not good and
it was not true. The writer was a proud man and he took pride in
his writing, and when the writing of the Africa book did not go
well, he put it away. Long ago, he said that there was nothing
worse for a writer than for his writing ``which has been rewritten
and altered to be published without permission as his own,'' and he
believed this as he believed few things. Later, when he was gone,
others would forget his pride and his love of words, and they would
publish his Africa book and other books he had put aside. They
would publish the books because the writer was a famous writer and
he had many readers, but they would do damage to his name.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Hemingway: Although his instantly recognizable style helped
remake the writing of English prose in the first half of this
century, it would grow mannered and flaccid in the latter part of
his career, and it would make him an easy mark for feckless
imitators and hostile critics. His public persona, which initially
brought him fame and wealth, would become a kind of prison, and in
the years after his death, it would also make him an object of
derision among feminists and multiculturalists intent on judging
him by contemporary mores as a bigoted, sexist pig.
</P>
<P>
   No one has given such critics more ammunition than his estate
and publishers, who have brought out a succession of posthumously
published books consisting of writing that Hemingway himself chose
not to publish _ books that show Hemingway in the worst of all
possible lights, his prose a near-parody of his earlier style; his
self-portraits exercises in self-aggrandizing bravado. The latest
of these volumes is ``True at First Light,'' a so-called
``fictional memoir,'' laboriously extracted by Hemingway's son
Patrick from a 200,000-word, untitled manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which is roughly half the length of the original
manuscript, purports to chronicle a safari trip in Kenya that
Hemingway took with his fourth wife, Mary, in 1953. It recounts the
story of Mary's efforts to kill a lion that she has been tracking
for six months, and the narrator's involvement with a young woman
from the Wakamba tribe who is referred to as his ``fiancee'' or
``extra wife.'' Although ``First Light'' is not as embarrassing a
performance as ``Garden of Eden'' (published in 1986) or ``The
Dangerous Summer'' (published in 1985), it is decidedly mediocre
Hemingway, a pallid, perfunctory echo of ``Green Hills of Africa,''
a 1935 nonfiction work that itself holds up poorly next to his two
classic African stories, ``The Snows of Kilimanjaro'' and ``The
Short Happy Life of Francis Macomber.''
</P>
<P>
   As Edmund Wilson has observed, Hemingway was able to externalize
and objectify the conflicting elements of his own personality in
his fiction. This capacity for self-criticism, however, tended to
fade away when he wrote in the first person, and it disappeared
entirely as Hemingway became increasingly concerned with living up
to his public persona and mythologizing his own life _ problems
pointed up all too clearly in ``First Light.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this book seems completely intent on creating a portrait
of the author as the white alpha male, an Uebermensch fought over
by women and looked up to by Africans. He protectively watches over
his wife, making sure she is not hurt while she is hunting, and he
takes it upon himself to help the local villagers rid themselves of
the scourge of marauding lions and leopards. He presumably embodies
Hemingway's belief that blood sports are a test of manhood and
honor, and he adheres to the hunter's code of ethics _ that is,
always kill cleanly and never leave an animal wounded.
</P>
<P>
   He looks at a picture of a man strangling two lions and is
``deeply moved.'' He declares that ``love is a terrible thing that
you would not wish on your neighbor.'' And he thinks to himself
``how nice it was that there was no African word for I'm sorry.''
He seems to think of himself as brave and honorable, when in fact
he comes across as patronizing, paternalistic and self-deluding. He
makes a lot of snide remarks about the Masai, describing them as
``a syphilis-ridden, anthropological, cattle-worshiping
curiosity,'' and petulantly knocks such literary rivals as Henry
James, John O'Hara and F. Scott Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Although Patrick Hemingway argues in his introduction that
``First Light'' is not a journal but a work of fiction, the book
hews closely to accounts of Hemingway's 1953 safari set down by
biographers, who have pointed out that the author did become
involved with an African woman and did ``go native,'' shaving his
head and hunting with a spear. The main difference between these
biographical accounts and ``First Light'' concerns Hemingway's _ or
``the narrator's'' _ prowess as a hunter and all that that implies
in the author's macho esthetic. While the biographies stress the
writer's humiliating difficulties with his marksmanship on this
trip, ``First Light'' focuses on Mary's disappointing encounter
with a lion: an encounter in which the Hemingway character must
come to her aid, kill the lion and then try to cheer her up.
</P>
<P>
   As in so much of Hemingway's later work, all this spinning of
his own legend is reflected in the deterioration of his prose. What
was special _ and at the time, galvanic _ about his early writing
was its precision and concision: Hemingway not only knew what to
leave out, but he also succeeded in turning that austerity into a
moral outlook, a way of looking at a world shattered and remade by
World War I. His early work had a clean, hard objectivity: It did
not engage in meaningless abstractions; it tried to show, not tell.
</P>
<P>
   In ``First Light,'' however, his angular language has turned
maudlin and flabby. The narrator is given to tendentious comments
like ``revelation stands in the same relation to human reason as
heavenly water does to the earthly water.'' Or ``Who knows what the
carrot feels, or the small young radish, or the used electric light
bulb, or the worn phonograph disk, or the apple tree in winter.''
The other characters are just as bad. ``Nobody knows the night,''
says one of his African crew. ``Not me. Not you. Nobody.'' As for
Mary, she is made to utter such absurdities as: ``I am a warrior.
I'm your wife and your love and your small warrior brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The famous rhythms of Hemingway's prose have similarly devolved
in these pages into empty mannerism and nervous tics. Of one
character, he writes: ``He coughed his cough at once so there would
be no doubt of it and it was a legitimate cough.'' And of his
narrator's drinking: ``Whisky can be as right as it can be wrong
and it said I was not a stranger and I knew it was correct at this
time of night.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Patrick Hemingway makes no great claims for
this book, saying he has licked the manuscript ``into what I hope
is not the worst of all possible shapes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Hemingway himself could have licked his unfinished draft
into the Ursus horribilis it might have been,'' he adds. ``What I
offer in `True at First Light' is a child's teddy bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Hemingway has done a more coherent job of editing this
book than his predecessors did with ``The Garden of Eden'' and
``The Dangerous Summer'': In comparison with those volumes, ``First
Light'' at least possesses a certain narrative tension and drive.
That, however, is beside the point. This book, which Hemingway
worked on while recovering from terrible injuries sustained in two
plane crashes (including a fractured skull, two cracked disks, and
a ruptured liver, kidney and spleen), was consigned to a bank vault
by its author, who did not regard it as fit to print.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Light'' never should have seen the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `TRUE AT FIRST LIGHT: A Fictional Memoir'
</P>
<P>
   By Ernest Hemingway
</P>
<P>
   Edited with an introduction by Patrick Hemingway. 319 pages.
Scribner. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MONTECRISTO-REVIEW     06-21 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MONTECRISTO-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVO REVEALS A LESS THAN FULL `MONTE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The English know their way around the classics, and now the
French step up with a ravishing version of ``The Count of Monte
Cristo.''
</P>
<P>
   And the star of the miniseries, which will be shown Monday,
Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday on the Bravo cable channel, is that
lovable lug of French cinema, Gerard Depardieu, in his first TV
project.
</P>
<P>
   But a few cautions are required. One, it's in French with
English subtitles. Two, it's eight hours over four nights. Three,
the source material is a hoary specimen of ``classic'' literature.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance was never a specialty of Alexandre Dumas. Nor character
insight. He liked plot. He liked action. He liked love.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Count of Monte Cristo'' provides all that, in stark
melodrama, along with false imprisonment, fabulous wealth,
dastardly betrayal, multiple disguises, poison potions, sleeping
potions and, above all, vengeance served as chilled as vichyssoise.
</P>
<P>
   You get an early glimpse of Depardieu's son, Guillaume
Depardieu, as the young naval officer Edmond Dantes, who is in
Marseille and about to celebrate his engagement to a well-appointed
Mercedes (Naike Rivelli).
</P>
<P>
   But instead he's arrested by the prosecutor Villefort (Pierre
Arditi) and thrown into the prison fortress Chateau d'If, because
he was innocently carrying a letter from the exiled Emperor
Napoleon to a key supporter in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Dantes is still rotting in prison 18 years later (he's now
played by the elder Depardieu) when an unexpected encounter with
another inmate leads to his freedom and to a fortune in gems and
gold concealed on the rocky island of Monte Cristo.
</P>
<P>
   Dantes creates the identity of the mysterious count of Monte
Cristo and returns to the mainland to avenge himself. He's rough,
he's tough and, reminded that it's a shame to be consumed with
vengeance, he replies, ``What matter when vengeance is allied with
justice?''
</P>
<P>
   His targets are the corrupt innkeeper Caderousse (Roland
Blanche), who could have saved the young Dantes and didn't; his
anonymous accusers Danglars (Michel Aumont), now a Paris banker,
and Fernand de Morcerf (Jean Rochefort), now a Paris nobleman; and
the prosecutor, Villefort.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter Didier Decoin and director Josee Dayan dwell on
several romances along the way, the better to relieve the
one-dimensional tedium of Dantes' obsession. One involves
Villefort's daughter, Valentine, played by yet another Depardieu
family member, Gerard's daughter Julie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Count of Monte Cristo'' has its grand moments, one of
which is a protracted scene where Morcerf is humiliated in the
upper house of the French parliament. But time has given this tale
a bad case of the dodders, and the crutches that hold the plot
aloft are too conspicuous.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also reasons to watch. The $20 million production
is gorgeously filmed, for one thing, on Malta and at a series of
French locales. The miniseries is a lavish, big-scale event.
</P>
<P>
   And there's Depardieu. The character of Dantes is really as
wooden as a mallet, but Depardieu shows why he's made himself an
international film star.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, he's an actor of disparate elements _ barrel torso,
short legs, clownish nose, thick jaw, sad eyes and blond hair that
somehow ought to be dark. And rather attractive in spite of flawed
parts, or possibly because of them.
</P>
<P>
   There's a gentleness beneath the burly exterior, and this
miniseries stretches Dumas to take advantage of it. Yes, Dantes is
bent on vengeance. But he's also a sort of blend of Santa Claus and
Robin Hood, spreading his largesse as he homes in on his targets.
</P>
<P>
   The miniseries is a lot of Depardieu in four sittings, and he's
a rare performer who can carry the burden. You can tire of the
miniseries, but not of its star.
</P>
<P>
   As for the subtitles, they shouldn't be an obstacle. I watched
on a small screen without problem. And as background noise goes,
the French language is easier to take than the cacophony of
American television.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
