<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      06-21 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, June 22. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The agreement reached early
Monday to disband the Kosovo Liberation Army included, at the
insistence of its commanders, a pledge by the NATO allies to
consider letting the rebels form a provisional army for Kosovo
modeled on the National Guard in the United States. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WOMEN-ASSAULT (Zrze, Yugoslavia) _ In interviews over the
last two weeks, dozens of women and men in Kosovo and in refugee
camps in Albania told stories that suggest that sexual assault and
intimidation, if not rape, were widespread, common and used by
Serbian forces to strike at the heart of a society in which the
virginity and fidelity of Muslim women is central. By Elisabeth
Bumiller. 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIMENTAL-PATIENTS (Undated) _ Chronically ill patients with
limited or no health insurance are increasingly filling a demand
for experimental drug study participants as drug companies rush
record numbers of new medications through the testing process. For
these people, experiments have become treatments; clinical
investigators are their specialists. But the benefit can be
fleeting or nonexistent. Chronically ill patients with no other
options can be treated with an experimental medication that does
not work or that even worsens their condition. Or they can end up
with a placebo rather than the medication itself. And once the
study is over, usually in a matter of weeks, they are left to their
own devices. By Gina Kolata and Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report; 2,700 words. An abridged version will also be
sent.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ATTORNEYS-GENERAL (Washington) _ At a time when a number
of state attorneys general have embraced a new activism against
industries like tobacco and high technology, the Republican
National Committee is for the first time helping create a
Republican Attorneys General Association as a fund-raising
organization and think tank devoted to electing more Republicans to
positions as chief law enforcement officers and to promote
Republican ideas. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON (Naval Weapons Base Concord, Calif.) _
During World War II, an explosion on a segregated naval base here
killed 320 men. After the accident, black sailors were ordered to
resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty of them refused, were
court-martialed by an all-white panel, found guilty of mutiny and
imprisoned. Now, in an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for one
black veteran have filed for a presidential pardon arguing that the
black sailors failed to follow orders out of legitimate fear and
had no intent to mutiny. The petition pits the racial symbolism of
a celebrated case against the military's view that servicemen
cannot choose which orders to obey. By William Glaberson. 2,100
words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and a map.
</P>
</TEXT>
