</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYDNEY-PROFILE-COX     06-21 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sydney considers image as it gears up for 2000 Olympics
 &HT;    (Eds: For release Saturday, June 26. Moving in international (i)
and sports (s) categories. With 3-column map of Sydney showing
venues.)
 &HT;    By John Reetz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Forget the fact they're cute. Sydney 2000
backers would prefer you don't fixate on the 'roos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but most people don't know there are 27 varieties of
kangaroos, that they're not mammals but marsupials, that they all
have a pouch. And that there's one type of kangaroo that lives in a
tree,'' the Australian mining executive explained to a visitor as
the 15-hour flight from Los Angeles approached Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``And koalas, mate? They're not bears, you know. Marsupials. Not
bears, mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the tale of his provincial-sounding countryman, Peter
Christopher buries his head in his hands and talks to the table:
``We like 'roos, but there's so much more.''
</P>
<P>
   He is correct, and the setting in which he speaks makes the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher, the Olympics coordinator for the Fairfax newspaper
group, sits at Nick's, a harborside restaurant in the Darling
Harbour area of downtown Sydney. In the turning basin ahead, Sydney
water ferries maneuver. To the left are shops, restaurants and the
massive hall where wrestling, judo and a host of other Olympic
sports will be played. To the right sits the historic Pyrmont
Bridge, now a pedestrian span. A quiet monorail, carrying the
advertising of an Olympic sponsor, glides over the bridge to a
station in a waterside shopping mall on the far side of the basin.
</P>
<P>
   This has the look, the feel and the amenities of one of THE
gathering spots during the Sydney Olympics, which start Sept. 15,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Atlanta in 1996, Sydney's is already there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the nice things: We've got this great gathering
spot that is already in place, waiting for the Olympics,'' said
Christopher, guiding a visitor through the city.
</P>
<P>
   With less than 470 days to go, Sydney is starting to tie up the
loose ends.
</P>
<P>
   By no means is the city finished and ready for the Olympic
crush, but the venue construction is in excellent shape, and work
proceeds along on redoing the airport, city streets, shopping
plazas, transit areas and other public sites.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Atlanta four years ago would have seen a similar
construction build-up as the city spruced up on schedule for its
Olympic visitors. But a criticism of the Atlanta experience was
that downtown was not entirely visitor-friendly outside the newly
built Centennial Olympic Park, and temporary street vendors brought
an unfortunate tackiness to the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, with its famed and striking Opera House, its magnificent
harbor and its lively downtown and culture that already include
tasteful street vendors, newsstands and flower stands, looks like a
city that will keep the Olympic crowds happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have to do a lot to bugger it up, `` said Milton
Cockburn, General Manager, Media, for the Sydney Organising
Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG).
</P>
<P>
   But there's always that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Still looming in the background is the continuing controversy
over the International Olympic Committee's city selection process.
If new problems arise, Sydney could suffer, and there's always the
fear that sponsors would back out.
</P>
<P>
   Hedging its bets, Sydney has started chopping its budget,
seeking ways to save as insurance against a shortfall later. The
latest cuts included about $50 million in funds for a variety of
programs, including a salary freeze, reduced staffing levels during
the Games, a short-term hiring freeze and some savings on Olympic
family services, such as free tickets and pool vehicles instead of
dedicated cars for some IOC family members.
</P>
<P>
   SOCOG's budget is now at $1.69 billion, about the same as
Atlanta's in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly keen to get the IOC to behave as much as
possible like ordinary citizens of Sydney,'' said Michael Knight,
SOCOG president. ``There are some bits that the IOC will be more
relaxed about than others, but in the end I think it's fair to say
that the IOC's negotiating position in the current climate is not
particularly strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the cuts, there were signs of strain between the IOC
and SOCOG. IOC Vice President Richard Pound said Sydney has escaped
the scrutiny given to the Salt Lake bid, kept secret the cool
temperatures there during September and failed to disclose problems
with the city's transport system.
</P>
<P>
   ``A touch of malice,'' one local paper said about Pound.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that mix the debate over Olympic official Phil Coles, who
was embroiled in the IOC controversy. Coles has resigned his post
with SOCOG and the Australian Olympic Committe but remains an IOC
member.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other local controversies, too. Bondi Beach
residents didn't want beach volleyball in their neighborhood, but
it made such a great TV setting that Sydney didn't want to back off
despite protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``NIMBYs, that's what I call 'em,'' one irate taxi driver said
of those who use the not-in-my-back-yard argument. ``Who are they
to tell us we can't have beach volleyball there? They ran off
'Baywatch,' too.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, another beach community did that.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seems settled, at this stage, with concessions being
made to make life more palatable for Bondi Beach residents during
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the usual concerns that rise from people who
actually live in a host city: steep ticket prices, congestion in
general, how to get to work during the Games, concern about how
their city and country will be portrayed internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is at the point many Olympic cities find themselves in
the year before the Games: lots of time spent on citizens'
complaints, construction issues, funding debates _ and not much
public discussion of the sports and the Games.
</P>
<P>
   As Sydney heads toward Opening Ceremonies, Cockburn said, SOCOG
has employed 40 to 50 people who worked with the Atlanta Committee
for the Olympic Games, a move that initially bothered some because
locals felt they didn't need any guidance from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But those feelings have for the most part disappeared, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something reassuring when you're in a room and
discussing how to handle issues and hearing those American
accents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They have taken note of some of the issues from the Atlanta
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had (ACOG chief operating officer) A.D. Frazier down here a
while back,'' said Cockburn, ``and one of the things that he said
he'd look at differently if he had it to do over again would be
dealing with the press. Not the broadcasters because they aren't
going to go on TV and trash you after they've paid so much to
televise the Games. But the press. He said he still has scratch
marks on his back from that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney organizers certainly understand how quickly the
international press can turn on an Olympic city, and they're doing
what they can to make sure that doesn't hapen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going through ways to cut the budget,'' Cockburn told editors
from across Australia and New Zealand recently, ``we looked at the
three bars we have in the Olympics area for journalists. We
considered eliminating those to save money, but decided that
wouldn't be a good thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Sydney's Olympic construction is proceeding
without a hitch, with nearly all venues completed on time and
within budget. Still to be finished are the Superdome (for
basketball and gymnastics), Tennis Centre, Shooting Centre,
Velodrome and, early next year, the second water polo venue.
</P>
<P>
   The center of activity is the Olympic stadium (Stadium
Australia), a striking structure that has already seen action,
hosting several sporting events, including one filled to its
110,000-person capacity.
</P>
<P>
   One reviewer calls it ``a display of structural virtuosity.''
Others say it looks like a Pringle potato chip.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium is the centerpiece of the Homebush Bay Olympic
facility. On the outskirts of Sydney, it's the central spot for
Olympic activities and home for track and field, swimming, water
polo, baseball, field hockey and other events. It's a huge sports
complex, made even more photogenic by the burying of major
electrical transmission lines to make the site attractive for the
television audience.
</P>
<P>
   One Homebush Bay stadium _ the woodchop pavilion _ won't see any
Olympic action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually quite a sport ... very strenuous and exciting,''
Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   Like American pro wrestling?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, this is the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sydney was struggling with the Bondi Beach controversy,
there was even one proposal that sand be carted to the woodchop
pavilion so it could be used for beach volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   For those who view Sydney's beaches as some of the finest in the
world, that was the last straw in the balancing act between Olympic
needs and local desires.
</P>
<P>
   In a countdown report, the Sydney Morning Herald noted the
timeline, and the local apprehension, and asked: 500 days ``to what
precisely? The greatest event on earth or the greatest
imposition?''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are strange and confounding times for a Sydneysider
attempting to make sense of an event bewildering in its magnitude,
though many of us are yet to come to terms with the scope of the
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
