<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring starts service for business Internet users
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having already established itself as one of the top
Internet service providers for consumers, MindSpring Enterprises is
turning its attention to small business customers. Monday, the
company officially launched a new division dedicated specifically
to business Internet customers, called MindSpring Biz.
</P>
<P>
   The service will be a separate division of the company, focused
on small businesses. The debut of MindSpring Biz is part of the
company's plans to grow its Web hosting and businesses services.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring Biz offers special Internet software for businesses,
including dedicated Internet access, Web hosting and design
services.
</P>
<P>
   The company estimates only 20 percent of businesses have an
online presence. The new unit will build upon offerings from Netcom
On-Line Communication Services Inc., which focused on business
customers and was purchased by MindSpring in February for $245
million.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring Biz has its own staff of 280 dedicated employees,
with 100 based in Atlanta and the others primarily centered in San
Jose's Netcom headquarters. Other MindSpring Biz employees will be
based MindSpring's call centers in Dallas, and Harrisburg, Penn.
MindSpring Biz hired a new director of marketing, Tim Sesmones, who
will be based in Atlanta. The others are existing employees.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring said about 20 percent of its 1.2 million subscribers
are small businesses. Business customers typically provide higher
profits because they pay more for premium services, said Ed
Douglas, a vice president with the new unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They require a lot more hand-holding,'' Douglas said. ``That's
one of the things that's been missing out there in the
small-business arena.''
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring hopes to attract small businesses to the Web by
making speed the cornerstone of its small business offerings.
Through an arrangement with Covad Communications' networks, the
largest provider of high speed phone service in the country,
MindSpring will be able to provide its business customers with
symmetrical digital subscriber lines. The service will offer
business users a high speed ``always on'' connection. The
high-speed connections will be available this fall in Atlanta,
Dallas, San Francisco and Los Angeles. More cities are slated to be
added in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``MindSpring sDSL is a low-cost, high speed alternative to a T1
line or ISDN service,'' said Greg Stromberg, executive vice
president of MindSpring Biz.
</P>
<P>
   Services are bundled in packages with prices starting at about
$100. Depending on the Internet speed and services selected,
pricing can vary.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
