<SLUG> BC-COURT-SEARCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS WARRANTLESS SEARCH OF CARS IN DRUG CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police do not have to obtain a warrant to search a
car suspected of carrying illegal drugs, even in cases where they
had plenty of time to get one, the Supreme Court said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In an unsigned opinion, the court noted that it has said in the
past that the Fourth Amendment, which generally requires police to
get a warrant from a judge before conducting a search, does not
apply to cars because they are mobile. Now, the court said, the
so-called ``automobile exception'' is valid even when time is not
an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision stemmed from a Maryland case that began at
11 a.m. July 2, 1996. At that time St. Mary's County Sheriff Deputy
Lyle Long received a tip from a reliable source that Kevin Dyson, a
known drug dealer in the area, had gone to New York that morning to
buy drugs and would be returning to Maryland in a rented red Toyota
later that day with a large amount of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Long called the rental car company to corroborate the
information given him. After the facts checked out, the sheriff's
staff decided to pick up Dyson's car when it entered St. Mary's
County.
</P>
<P>
   At 1 a.m. July 3, other deputies stopped Dyson's car, searched
it for drugs and found 23 grams of crack cocaine in a duffel bag
the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson was convicted in a county court of conspiracy to possess
cocaine with intent to distribute it. He appealed, arguing that the
warrantless search violated his Fourth Amendment rights because the
sheriff's deputies had sufficient time after the informant's tip to
obtain a warrant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Court of Special Appeals of Maryland reversed the
county court's decision. It ruled that for the automobile exception
to the warrant requirement to apply, there must be not only
probable cause to believe that evidence of a crime is contained in
the car but also that police do not have time to get a warrant. The
state's highest court declined to review that decision, and the
Maryland attorney general appealed
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's decision the Supreme Court reversed the special
appeals court ruling and reinstated the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holding of the Court of Special Appeals that the
`automobile exception' requires a separate finding of exigency in
addition to a finding of probable cause is squarely contrary to our
previous holdings,'' the high court said.
</P>
<P>
   All nine justices agreed that the sheriff's deputies did not
need a warrant in Dyson's case. But Justice Stephen Breyer
dissented from the result, saying the high court should not reverse
the state court without hearing arguments that Dyson was not
properly represented because his lawyer did not file a response to
the attorney general's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
