<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Truth more awful than believed in Kosovo
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a chilling report from Kosovo, a team of Time reporters
discovers evidence of Serbian atrocities more horrible than
imagined. In the town of Pec, a rich, urban center, Serbian forces
swept through the city three times in an attempt to crush the
Kosovo Liberation Army and to destroy the Albanian intellectual and
political culture. The tales of death and brutality are troubling
enough, but the photograph of a young Albanian boy carrying a
one-legged doll and a bowl of crumbs is absolutely haunting.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek ($3.50), meanwhile, sent reporters and photographers
into Suva Reka, where victims and killers were often on a
first-name basis and Serbs settled old scores with ethnic Albanian
neighbors over business competition. Twenty-one members of the
prominent Berisha family were killed, apparently in retaliation
over a dispute with Serbian businessman Misko Nisavic. ``This was a
massacre with a personal history,'' says correspondent Rod
Nordland.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remembering Papa: Cigar Aficionado pays tribute to Ernest
Hemingway on the 100th anniversary of his birth and examines the
mystique that has spawned a cottage industry for scholars and
Hemingway heirs. Hemingway's sons, John, Patrick and Gregory,
formed Hemingway Ltd. in 1992 to license the use of the patriarch's
name and image. The authorized items included a Hemingway shotgun
(which caused a storm of protest since the writer used a shotgun to
kill himself) and a $600 limited-edition Mont Blanc fountain pen. A
nice gift, but Hemingway wrote the first drafts of his books in
pencil. So what is Hemingway's connection to cigars? Well, the
Tabacalera A. Fuente y Cia. produces a line of stogies in different
sizes _ Short Story, Best Seller and Masterpiece. Papa would have
been proud.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eye-opener: Nicole Kidman reveals almost all in the July 8
double issue of Rolling Stone ($4.95). Devastated by the death of
Stanley Kubrick, Kidman talks about working with the director of
``Eyes Wide Shut'' and her marriage to co-star Tom Cruise. ``The
shock for Tom and me is that nobody knew us the way Stanley did.
Not even my mom and dad.'' And while the film is being touted as
the summer's sexiest movie, Kidman denies that it's going to be a
sex romp. ``The sex is such a small part of the story. ... Tom and
I aren't exhibitionists.'' Other articles of note: Johnny Depp
writes about the night he met poet Allen Ginsburg, and ``South
Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone take on Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Not listless: Magazine editors apparently love lists, even if
they're meaningless. Entertainment Weekly's ($3.50) latest ranking
is the ``It List'' of the 100 ``most creative people in
entertainment.'' Among those profiled are Nicole Kidman, Heather
Graham, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Rupert Everett and Ricky Martin, as
well as behind-the-scenes artists including ``Titanic'' costume
designer Deborah Scott. Other trendsetters include creators at the
Cartoon Network and choreographers for the swinging Gap
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Essence ($2.75) explores reactions to the
long-held taboo of black women dating _ and marrying _ white men.
Research shows that the trend includes working-class women as well
as upwardly mobile professional females. ... What will marriage be
like in the next millennium? According to John Gray and other
experts quizzed by Bride's ($4.99) magazine, couples will get
married later in life and most couples won't start families until
their mid-30s. Gray sees more breakthroughs such as Viagra that
will keep the marital fires blazing. ... In addition to the typical
cover story on how to have great abs, the August Men's Health
($3.50) has a thirst-quenching article on beverages to beat
fatigue, anxiety and hangovers. According to one nutritionist, club
soda with lime will boost your energy, nonalcoholic beer will calm
you, and V-8 vegetable juice or tomato juice will help you recover
from too much alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
