<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 22, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 4 p.m. Monday, the temperature at Washington, D.C., was just
67 degrees, or about 20 degrees below normal. The laden overcast
that has covered the Middle Atlantic States the past few days will
slowly erode Tuesday, allowing temperatures to rebound closer to
seasonal levels. A few locations in eastern Virginia, however, will
stay cloudy and cool as damp winds from the Atlantic persist.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy fog near the Northeast Seaboard will dissipate yielding
sunny skies by early afternoon as high pressure builds across
upstate New York. Abundant sunshine and warm conditions will cover
the interior Northeast. Farther south, scattered thunderstorms will
again plague Florida, especially just inland from the coast where
developing sea-breeze fronts undercut and lift sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   A steady stream of humid air from the Gulf of Mexico will fuel
showers and thunderstorms over Texas and the southeast Plains. Some
flooding is expected. A cluster of showers and storms will also
affect the Middle West as an approaching jet stream disturbance
augments the ascent of humid air covering the region.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated potent storms will erupt over eastern Wyoming the
central high Plains ahead of a cold front crossing the region. Some
of the storms will contain large hail and damaging winds.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore breezes will direct cool air with spotty showers into
the western Washington. The Southwest deserts and interior
California will broil beneath abundant sun. Local thundershowers
will develop near the higher mountain ranges of the Rockies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Mountain Clouds
</P>
<P>
   Like clockwork each afternoon during the past several days,
billowy clouds have boiled up along the crests of the central and
southern Rockies, muddling the mostly clear skies that have
dominated hours near dawn. At the top of a mountain, air in contact
with the warming ground quickly becomes warmer and less dense than
the free-floating air that surrounds the summit. Like a hot-air
balloon, bubbles of heated air rise, sometimes leading to cumulus
clouds. When the sun sets, air in contact with the mountainside
cools rapidly and the rising air currents that sustain the clouds
cease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
