<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0622-C     06-21 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO VISIT REFUGEES, TROOPS; LAUDS SLOVENES ON DEMOCRACY,
CHIDES SERBS ON MILOSEVIC
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0622.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ President Clinton travels Tuesday to
Macedonia, where he will meet with refugees just miles from the
border of war-shattered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to go from there to Aviano Air Base in Italy, where
he'll thank U.S. pilots and air crews for their participation in
NATO's 78-day air war against Yugoslavia, wrapping up the final leg
of a week-long victory lap through Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Journeying Monday to the flashpoint that set off a decade of
Balkans bloodshed, Clinton praised Slovenia's fledgling democracy
as a beacon of hope for the wounded region and a model for the
future of southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He received a rock star's welcome from several thousand Slovenes
who braved a summer downpour to jam into the central square in this
ancient crossroads along Europe's southern underbelly. They waved
small rain-soaked American flags and applauded his vision of Balkan
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must build a Europe with no frontline states, a Europe
undivided, democratic and at peace for the first time in history,''
Clinton said, as cheers welled up from beneath a kaleidoscopic sea
of umbrellas. ``Slovenia can lead the way -- and America will
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Bonn, Germany, Clinton said he and his European
counterparts are planning a summit later this summer -- perhaps in
the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo -- to discuss a
multi-billion-dollar mini-Marshall Plan to help rebuild the Balkans
and set the region on an ambitious course of integration with the
rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that money, Clinton said, would go toward providing
emergency food and medicine to Serbia, and to restoring essential
heating services and electrical power there, even if it remains
under the control of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it is important that if the Serbs want to keep Mr.
Milosevic, and don't want to be part of Southeastern Europe's
future, that at least they not freeze to death this winter and that
their hospitals not be forced to close,'' Clinton said. ``Babies
will be born, people will get sick, and people shouldn't be cold in
the winter if we can help that.''
</P>
<P>
   He rejected, however, the rebuilding of dozens of road and rail
bridges NATO bombs destroyed across Serbia, saying those do not
qualify as humanitarian needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of rebuilding the bridges so people can go to work, I
don' t buy that,'' Clinton said during a news conference following
a meeting with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and European
Commission President Jacques Santer in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of their economic reconstruction,'' said Clinton,
``and I don't think we should help -- not a bit, not a penny,''
unless Milosevic first leaves office in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia must reject the murderous rule of Mr. Milosevic and
choose the path that Slovenia has chosen,'' Clinton said here in
Ljubljana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racial and religious hatred has not a place in a civilized
society,'' Clinton said. ``That is why free nations stood against
Mr. Milosevic's ethnic cleansing and killing in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke in English, a group of several hundred young
Slovenes enthusiastically applauded, even before an interpreter
translated his words into Slovenian.
</P>
<P>
   Among his admirers was a young biology student, who said she was
glad Clinton had come to show the world that Slovenia is a Balkan
nation dedicated to democracy, peace and progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they will know who we are -- the whole world,'' said Tina
Sedmak, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others in this region, she said she harbors
complicated feelings about the air campaign waged by NATO
warplanes, which roared within earshot of this placid riverside
city on their nightly raids.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, she said there was no other way to combat
Serb repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't right,'' she said of the air campaign. ``But was the
only way.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia was the first republic to break away from the former
Yugoslavia, opting for independence in 1991, just as the former
Eastern Bloc country was beginning to crumble under Milosevic's
emerging policies.
</P>
<P>
   In a bloody prelude of the broader tragedy to follow, Yugoslavia
sent troops to fight Slovenia's secession in a 10-day war that left
66 dead. The forces withdrew three months later, leaving the tiny
Alpine republic to go its own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago, Mr. Milosevic triggered a military assault on
your nation,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you resisted. You secured your freedom. And you
proclaimed, 'It will never be the same again,''' Clinton said to
rousing applause. ``Now all the people of every part of Europe must
be able to say the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In some sense, Slovenia's secession helped touch off the powder
keg that was Yugoslavia in the waning days of the Cold War
structure in central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The former Yugoslav republics of Bosnia, Croatia and Macedonia
soon followed in declaring independence, eventually leaving only
Serbia and Montenegro to form the rump Yugoslavia, but not before
several hundred thousand people were killed and more than 3 million
others were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent chapter in the Balkan nightmare unfolded in
Kosovo, a province of Serbia, where Serb repression of ethnic
Albanians has resulted in an estimated 10,000 deaths and forced
more than 1 million people to flee their homes, thousands of which
were later destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been indicted on four counts of war crimes by the
United Nations tribunal investigating the atrocities in Kosovo. If
apprehended, tried and convicted, he could face life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton followed his speech here Monday with a state dinner
hosted by Slovenia's president, Milan Kucan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to wrap-up a week-long Europe tour late Tuesday
at Aviano, fly back to the United States aboard Air Force One and
return to the White House early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
