<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The day after the final
Serb troop pullout from Kosovo province, the dangers/concerns of
that will plague NATO in the future began to rear their ugly head.
An explosion in a school outside Pristina killed four people,
including two Gurkha soldiers in the British peacekeeping force. A
fifth person was injured, the first casualties since the allied
peacekeepers entered Kosovo on June 12. DEVELOPING.
(Kunstel/Kaplow, Cox New Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/CLINTON-KOSOVO _ LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ President Clinton today
firmly rejected spending U.S. dollars to help Yugoslavia rebuild
bridges and roads damaged during the NATO air campaign. ``I don't
think we should help, not a bit, not a penny,'' Clinton said.
``That basically is where I draw the line.'' The attacks destroyed
dozens of bridges and rail links across the country, disrupting
major transport routes and connections between the northern
food-producing regions and large cities further south. DEVELOPING.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/KOSOVO-MONASTERY _ DECANI, Kosovo _ Offering a tranquil campus
</P>
<P>
   behind a massive stone gatehouse, the Serbian Orthodox Visoki
Decani monastery is a refuge in Kosovo. But, the Monks here measure
time in centuries, so as they completed the first Sunday mass since
NATO troops moved in to Kosovo, they had little hope for a quick
peace in the burned and bloodied towns around them. A couple weeks
ago, the monastery was refuge to about 150 ethnic Albanians fleeing
the terror and murder of Serb troops. Now, as Serb troops completed
their withdrawal from the province, 15 Serb civilians were in the
monastery for safety. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BELGIUM _ BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas
Ivester, who met privately over the weekend with top company
executives to assess the company's crisis in Europe, met Monday
with Belgian govenment officials to try to get all of the company's
products back on store shelves in the aftermath of the health scare
involving its beverages. Plus other developments in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   (Roughton, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS _ WASHINGTON _ Linda Jones, the onetime mistress of
former Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros, told
a pretrial hearing Monday that she felt betrayed by Cisneros and
made phone tapes to prove he had offered her money. Cisneros faces
a federal trial on charges of lying to the FBI about the payments.
(Malone, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-GOP _ WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders Tuesday
will introduce their alternative to President Clinton's Elementary
and Secondary Education Act. This isn't the argument over how much
to spend on education; it's the argument over who will control how
the funds are spent over the next five years. Clinton's bill would
increase regulations for states, but the GOP bill would let states
opt out of hundreds of existing federal restrictions and let them
give their governor more say over decisions usually made by a
state's chief school officer. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The final witness in the federal
antitrust trial of Microsoft Corp. took the stand Monday. The
company sought to show that consumers suffered no harm from the
monoply practices the goverment accuses it of.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   VETOED-BILLS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush and his staff
worked into the wee hours Monday to finish up work on the 1,600
bills the Legislature passed this year. He cut $51 million in
spending from the state budget, vetoed 29 bills, let several become
law without his signature and signed hundreds more. Among the
casualties: a bill allowing county commissions to appoint legal
counsel for indigent defendants. Among the successes: a law that
could take some of the sting out of the Hopwood court ruling. It
allows Texas universities to match scholarships offered by other
states, including those awarded on the basis of race. (Brooks,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BARR-FORBES _ ATLANTA _ Rep. Bob Barr announces that he is
endorsing Steve Forbes for president. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH_SOUTHCAROLINA _ GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush
makes his second presidential campaign trip this week, with several
stops Monday in South Carolina. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   LAURABUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Much has been made about whether
Gov. George W. Bush got what he wanted from the 1999 Legislature.
But few people even knew First Lady Laura Bush also had a
legislative agenda. But while the spotlight was on her husband,
Laura Bush quietly worked for passage of a bill creating special
Head Start programs for reading. Are these the beginnings of her
own White House career? (Brooks, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BISON-TURNER _ Ted turner is merging the marketing arm of his
bison operations with that of a national industry coop in the
Dakotas. He is not leaving the business and will continue to raise
bison. His herd now numbers 15,000 head. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-SMOKE _ Closing arguments in the Florida class action
lawsuit against the tobacco industry may come this week. The
marathon trial began last summer, with Miami attorney Stanley
Rosenblatt trying to stick the industry with billions in payments
to every sick smoker who has ever lived in Florida. Rosenblatt won
a partial victory last year in a precedent-setting second-hand
smoke trial in which airline flight attendants argued that
smoke-filled planes made them sick. This trial has the potential
for billions in damages, and is being closely watched. (Williams,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TWISTER-CHASERS _ The boiling black and gray clouds have a
sinister spin as they slide east, hanging low over the lonesome
west Texas outback. Surface winds from the south feed the storm,
kicking up dust as they rush to the dark belly. A khaki-colored
column of dust rises toward the cloud, slowly at first, then with a
great rush as if being sucked up with a celestial Shop-Vac. ``This
is it,'' shouts an excited Matt Crowther. ``This is it. A tornado
is imminent.'' Each May, Crowther and his wife take time off from
their jobs as meorologists at the metro Atlanta-based Weather
Channel to chase storms. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
35. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
