<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 27)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giant Western Murals: Tall in the Saddle
</P>
<P>
   When the bucking broncos leap from their stalls at the Fourth of
July Rodeo in Toppenish, Wash., the spirit of the event will be
echoed by the mounted cowhand in the 16-by-20-foot mural on the
other side of town. In this town of 7,500 in the Yakima Valley, two
and half hours east of Seattle, nearly 60 huge murals on the sides
of buildings record the history of the rodeo and the West.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roger McCarthy, a local artist, had the idea for the murals in
1989 as a revitalization project after a number of agricultural
businesses closed. Along with Joseph C. Murphy, a lawyer and
friend, he raised nearly half a million dollars from local citizens
to commission various Western artists, including Fred Oldfield and
Mavis Willson, to paint murals based on local events. Each summer
several new murals are added to the town's collection, which totals
57. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The viewer can view the murals in a horse-drawn wagon or stroll
around town to savor details, like the snap of the crisp white
tablecloth in the wind in Ju-hong Chen's ``Old Lillie Mansion'' or
the eye of a lead steer in Don Gray's ``Cattle Drive.'' The town's
latest mural _ as yet unnamed, and completed in one day this month
by a team of 12 artists _ depicts an early service station. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rodeo runs all day and all evening from Thursday to Sunday.
Tickets are $10, $5 for ages 5 to 12, under 4 free. Information:
(800) 569-3982. Call the Toppenish Mural Society, (800) 569-3982,
for information on the wagon tours, which cost $10, seniors $8,
children $3.
</P>
<P>
   Two Airlines Seek Timelier Passengers
</P>
<P>
   Passengers on United Airlines and US Airways flights who are
running late to the airport will have to run a bit faster to make
their flights under new policies designed to have more planes
arrive at their destinations on time. Both airlines are trying to
close plane doors five minutes before the scheduled departure
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to improve on-time performance and also to reduce
the hassle in the boarding process,'' said Joe Hopkins, a United
spokesman. ``If you get the plane out on time, it is going to
arrive on time, which all our market research says is very
important to customers. And why penalize the 179 people already on
for one person?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under United's Time to Go policy, all ticketed passengers should
be seated 10 minutes before the scheduled departure time, giving
gate agents five minutes to board standby passengers and handle
standby upgrades to first class. Each airline sets its own rules on
when passengers with reservations can lose their seats. At United,
reservations are subject to cancellation 20 minutes before
departure, Hopkins said. The US Airways deadline is 10 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   US Airways adopted the new rules on June 15, copying a policy
United Airlines began in April.
</P>
<P>
   A Eurailpass Gift For the Big Four-O
</P>
<P>
   Users of Eurailpasses who turn 40 in 1999, the 40th anniversary
of the first Eurailpass, will receive a 40 percent discount on
train fares. The passes are offered by the national rail systems in
17 European countries, and are good for travel in all 17. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The basic Eurailpass is good for unlimited first-class travel
for periods ranging from 15 consecutive days to 3 months. Other
versions of the Eurailpass, including Eurail Flexipass, Eurail
Saverpass and Eurail Saver Flexipass, also qualify for the
40th-anniversary discount. They have varying time periods and
conditions. The Europass, a more restricted type of Eurailpass,
allows unlimited travel in five countries _ France, Germany, Italy,
Spain and Switzerland _ to which up to four other countries may be
added. The 40-percent anniversary discount does not apply to the
Europass, however.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Users of both Eurailpasses and Europasses will once again have a
grace period of up to six months _ not three months, as was the
case earlier this year _ before having to start their first trip.
Americans intending to use Eurailpasses or Europasses are expected
to buy them in the United States before going abroad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eurailpass fares range from $554 for 15 days to $1,558 for 3
months. Europass fares range from $348 for 5 days in 2 months to
$828 for 15 days in 2 months, with two extra countries in both
cases. Contact Rail Europe, (888) 382-7245 or www.raileurope.com.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Nightly: Elvis in Wax
</P>
<P>
   An animatronic Elvis _ dressed in a jewel-studded jumpsuit and
crooning his greatest hits _ will be one of 100 wax figures at
Madame Tussaud's Las Vegas, opening in Las Vegas on July 8. The
attraction is the first Madame Tussaud's in the United States _
there are others in Amsterdam and Australia, and a New York version
is scheduled for late 2000 in Times Square.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Madame Tussaud's was established by Marie Gresholtz Tussaud, a
Swiss woman who made death masks of aristocrats executed during the
French Revolution, including Marie Antoinette and Louis XVI. In
1835 she established a permanent home for her works in London,
where yearly attendance is now close to 3 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wax crowd at the 30,000-square-foot Madame Tussaud's Las
Vegas will include Louis Armstrong, Cher and Muhammad Ali, as well
as some Las Vegas fixtures like Liberace and Siegfried &AMP; Roy. A wax
Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward, who were married in a Las Vegas
hotel, welcome guests to a wedding chapel furnished with
memorabilia and photographs of celebrities who have tied the knot
in Vegas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Madame Tussaud's Las Vegas is in the new Venetian Resort Hotel,
3355 Las Vegas Boulevard South. Admission is $12.50. Information:
(702) 367-1847.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
