<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORCORAN-GEHRY-NYT &LR;      06-21 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORCORAN-GEHRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT FAR FROM THE ROSE GARDEN, ANOTHER MUSEUM FOR GEHRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Corcoran Gallery of Art has selected Frank O. Gehry as the
winner of a competition to design a new wing for its historic
Beaux-Arts building one block west of the White House. The addition
would nearly double the space that houses the museum and the
Corcoran School of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran Gallery officials expect the expansion to cost about
$40 million, half of which already has been raised. David Levy, the
president and director of the privately financed museum, hopes
construction will begin by spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry, who received this year's American Institute of Architects
Gold Medal, was chosen by the Corcoran from among two other
finalists, the architects Daniel Libeskind of Berlin and Santiago
Calatrava, a Spaniard. Gehry's design for the 140,000-square-foot
expansion, which includes renovation of the older building, will
not be published.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry was reached by cellular telephone in Prague, Czech
Republic, on the roof of the office tower he designed there,
popularly known as the Fred and Ginger Building. Of the design he
plans for the Corcoran, he said, ``I hope to take it to the moon,
try something else, go somewhere new.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy said it was Gehry's way of thinking rather than a
particular design that won him the commission. ``Frank's design is
responsive first of all to a very subtle, intelligent understanding
of the needs of the institution,'' he said. ``And then the exterior
of his addition is a logical extension of that thinking, not just a
piece of sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Corcoran's selection process differed from other
high-profile competitions, like the one completed in December 1997
by the Museum of Modern Art, because the selection committee's goal
was to choose an architect rather than a design.
</P>
<P>
   At 130, the Corcoran is the oldest art museum in the capital,
and its current building was designed in 1897 by Ernest Flagg, with
an addition by Charles Platt in 1928. Its collection of 19th- and
early 20th-century American art includes works by Albert Bierstadt,
Frederic E. Church and John Singer Sargent. An earlier plan to
defray operating and exhibition costs by developing an office
building on part of the Corcoran Gallery's site was derailed in
1990 because it was seen as too commercial. The approach was
similar to the Museum of Modern Art's selling its air rights for
construction of the Museum Tower condominium next door.
</P>
<P>
   Levy has been president since 1991. Over the last decade he has
bolstered the museum's reputation, which was battered by its
cancellation in 1989 of an exhibition of controversial photographs
by Robert Mapplethorpe in response to pressure from conservative
members of Congress. Since then he has increased the endowment to
$29 million from $8 million and broadened the museum's appeal with
exhibitions like a 1997 show of photographs by Gordon Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Levy has envisioned a building that would include new spaces for
the College of Art, new administrative offices, restored and
expanded galleries and a new conservation laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting an architect was not simple. Gehry is still taking
bows for his design of the titanium-clad Guggenheim Museum in
Bilbao, Spain, with its explosive sculptural forms. He might easily
be considered the most famous museum designer today. Yet the
Corcoran chose the architect, who is based in Los Angeles, only
after a methodical process lasting more than a year. Initially more
than 200 architects were considered, a number whittled down to 60
who were invited to submit their qualifications. In October that
list was reduced to 10.
</P>
<P>
   In January, three finalists were asked to compete: Libeskind,
whose Jewish Museum in Berlin has become something of an
architectural pilgrimage; Calatrava, who is completing his first
American commission, the Milwaukee Art Museum, and Gehry, who no
longer enters competitions, according to his office manager, except
when intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists' designs were intended only as the starting point
to a collaboration with the Corcoran's staff members and advisers.
Levy said he decided to publish neither the contenders' nor the
winner's submissions to avoid giving an impression that the
institution was committed to a specific plan.
</P>
<P>
   The decision may have disappointed those curious to see whether
Washington would be getting its own Bilbao on the Potomac. (Or
rather Bilbao off the Rose Garden; Levy's office is on axis with
the garden.) Submissions circulated within the Corcoran showed that
Gehry's plan incorporated wavy strips of metal seeming to flap with
sculptural gusto, akin to his design in Bilbao.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the confines of the triangular lot and the museum's
needs, the addition is both taller and deeper than the original
structure, with four levels of underground parking and a large
rooftop terrace for the donors' dining doom and a children's
museum. Neither garage nor rooftop additions will be visible from
the classically placid facade, which Frank Lloyd Wright said was
one of his favorites in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Considered among the most significant architects of the
late-20th century, Gehry, at 70, can be selective about the
projects he pursues. The work in his office includes a concert band
shell and pedestrian bridge for Millennium Park in Chicago, two
rehabilitation centers for hospitals in Britain and a complex for
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry said of the Corcoran design competition, ``I've been
through this a few times, and it was tough, certainly no
cakewalk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
