<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DYLAN-SIMON-REVIEW-LA     06-21 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYLAN-SIMON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYLAN, SIMON AREN'T FINISHED YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Watching Bob Dylan bound around the stage at the
Anaheim Pond on Sunday brings to mind a black-and-white picture of
him in ``Rolling Stone: Images of Rock &AMP; Roll.'' It shows a
youthful Dylan flying through the air. Dressed in jeans and a
short-sleeve pullover shirt, the legendary singer/songwriter has a
wispy beard and relatively short hair. His arms are spread wide,
his feet bare. His legs are bent, and only the sky and treetops are
visible in the background.
</P>
<P>
   As he was on Sunday, he is completely in the moment. So there we
have it, a record of the man once called ``the voice of his
generation'' defying gravity, free of expectations and free of the
weighty seriousness that many of his fans and critics have hung on
him during his nearly four-decade odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book's notes, the picture was taken in
Woodstock, N.Y., around 1970 by Elliot Landy, a friend who had been
invited over to help Dylan put together a trampoline, and Dylan,
like most of us would, enjoyed playing on it.
</P>
<P>
   The image brings to mind the words of a song: ``There is a girl
in New York City who calls herself the human trampoline. And
sometimes when I'm falling, flying or tumbling in turmoil, I say,
`Oh, so this is what she means. She means we're bouncing into
Graceland.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was not written by Dylan, of course, but by his current tour
mate, Paul Simon, another icon from the '60s. It is an apt
description of the pair's careers, which in their own ways have
been bouncing erratically toward Graceland, if, in this case, you
think of Elvis' former residence as some sort of pop-culture
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that the pair keeps popping up in
disconcerting ways (Dylan with his Grammy-winning ``Time Out of
Mind'' album last year, Simon with his Broadway failure,
``Capeman''). They are as much in the present as they are in the
past So unlike, say, Presley or Frank Sinatra _ neither of whom
were songwriters and whose artistic careers were limited to mostly
to being pop icons, and so essentially they were always seen
through that prism _ fixing Dylan and Simon's positions in the
entertainment firmament becomes tricky.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear watching them Sunday that neither of them is going
to make it easy. Before a crowd that ranged from those in their 20s
to graying middle-agers, a relaxed, playful Dylan performed a set
that was both crowd pleasing and, at times, unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a four-piece band, Dylan opened with a rousing
bluegrass piece and then moved to one of his best-known numbers,
``Mr. Tambourine Man.'' Like many of his most-famous tunes he
played Sunday night _ ``It's All Over Now, Baby Blue,'' ``Masters
of War'' _ Dylan had transformed the song so it was hardly
recognizable at first, but after a while this new ``Tambourine
Man'' had a life of its own. It was as if Dylan was saying, ``I'm
not yet finished with these songs.''
</P>
<P>
   By revising them, he has done what he has done throughout his
career _ challenge his audience's expectations. But more
surprising, he has added an element of showmanship and fun to his
performance. The man on stage Sunday mugged for the audience as he
played lead guitar and prowled the stage. His voice may be little
more than a growl at times, but he was a much more animated and
affable Dylan than the one who played last year at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   If Dylan is saying there is still something new to be found in
his songs, he is also saying it about himself. Dylan rocked out
with his final three numbers _ ``Highway 61,'' ``Like a Rolling
Stone'' and, perhaps most telling, a raucous version of the Buddy
Holly classic ``Not Fade Away.'' Holly had been an idol, so when
Dylan went electric, he wasn't abandoning folk music but following
a dream. Unlike Holly, though, Dylan didn't die young nor has he
faded away. He's just still following his dream, as if being older
has given him the freedom to do so. Ironically, it has given him a
youthful appearance, and, as one young member of the audience
remarked, ``He's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a marked contrast in styles when Dylan brought out
Simon _ and not just in the clothing. (Dylan was dressed in a
Holly-style black suit with a stripe down the side, and Simon was
in a workmanlike gray T-shirt, jeans and Yankees baseball cap.)
While Dylan has mined the folk, blues, rock and country genres,
Simon has expanded into world music, with Latin and African
influences. So they chose four songs in the folk-rock-country vein
to sing together _ ``The Sounds of Silence,'' ``I Walk the Line''
(a nod to Johnny Cash), ``Blue Moon of Kentucky'' (a nod to Elvis)
and ``Knockin' on Heaven's Door.'' Though even the most tone-deaf
couldn't mistake Dylan's voice for that of Simon's former partner,
Art Garfunkel, the duo did a fairly moving version of ``Silence.''
Dylan was much more comfortable on the other numbers.
</P>
<P>
   When Simon returned after an intermission, he launched into a
spacey, jazzy rendition of ``Bridge Over Troubled Waters.'' Backed
by a band that at times numbered 11, including three drummers,
Simon then did ``Can't Run But,'' the first of four songs from his
1990 ``Rhythm of the Saints'' album, which was seen as somewhat
disappointing after ``Graceland.'' It was interesting that Simon
chose to do them, as well as a song from ``Capeman,'' which Simon
made a point of saying was ``really good.'' He certainly has plenty
of hits to pick from, but he clearly wanted to keep pushing to more
difficult, less familiar songs because that's what he's interested
in. More importantly, songs such as ``The Coast,'' ``Further to
Fly'' and ``Cool, Cool River'' sounded vibrant, especially with
Simon's stellar backup band, which included drummer Steve Gadd.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Dylan, Simon was animated and playing to the audience,
enjoying himself as he waved his arms, acting out his songs on such
up-tempo tunes as ``Me and Julio Down by the Schoolyard,'' ``The
Boy in the Bubble,'' ``Diamonds on the Soles of Her Shoes'' and
``You Can Call Me Al.''
</P>
<P>
   But Simon saved his most telling song for the end of his first
encore _ ``Still Crazy After All These Years,'' which he sang sans
guitar as he exhorted the audience to join in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy''? ``Not Fade Away''? If Dylan and Simon are
making a statement about themselves, they are also offering some
advice to their middle-age fans. They're showing they can change
and not rest on their laurels, going from icons to entertainers
without sacrificing who they are.
</P>
<P>
   There is some weird irony that the two poet-songwriters who
captured and helped propel the changes of the '60s in their music
are heading later this week to perform at the MGM Grand in Las
Vegas, a place where Elvis and Frank would feel at home. Few back
then, though, could have conceived of Dylan and Simon in the
playground of the Rat Pack.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one lesson to be learned from them, it's that
expectations are to be defied. As Dylan said, ``I was so much older
then, I'm younger than that now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
