<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MOVIE-STUDIO-ART-2     06-21 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOVIE-STUDIO-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES AND DOUBTS GREET PLAN FOR SOUND STAGES AT BROOKLYN NAVY
YARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To skeptics it is too big, too far, too speculative
and, coming at a time when sound stages are sitting empty across
Los Angeles, altogether too much: the kind of boom-era bubble
likely to pop as soon as it hits the first sharp object or
dissonant breeze.
</P>
<P>
   But like a particularly tangled Hollywood potboiler, the
proposal to build a mammoth movie-making complex at the Brooklyn
Navy Yard continues to lurch along, navigating a wall of worry
while it is propelled by a big-name steamroller.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not entirely clear whether the proposal backed by
Robert De Niro's TriBeCa Productions and Harvey Weinstein's Miramax
Films will go forward, and what it would mean for the other
sound-stage projects being proposed in New York. Potential lenders
are still studying the Navy Yard proposal, which was announced in
May and has commitments for less than half the $150 million in
financing it needs to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question that there has never been more interest
in building movie studios in New York since the industry left for
California at the beginning of the century, and that the outsize
aspirations of the Navy Yard project parallel the growth of the
film business in the city over the last decade. Less clear is
whether that growth will continue and whether there is enough
business for the proposed projects.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, skeptics wonder if there would be enough
filmmaking for the 12 sound stages envisioned for the Navy Yard, if
people would travel to Brooklyn and if the current glut in Los
Angeles should be a warning for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 20 years, there have been a lot of projects
announced, and most of them never happened, so until someone puts a
shovel in the ground, you can't be sure of anything,'' said Pat
Scott, commissioner of the city Office of Film, Theater and
Broadcasting. ``But we keep losing work because we can't supply the
facilities, and it's absurd to have the talent and the creativity
here and not have the right facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is some logic in developing some sort of studio project at
the Navy Yard, which was founded in 1801, saw employment peak at
71,000 in World War II and was shut down in 1966. The city
purchased the site between the Manhattan and Williamsburg Bridges
across from Manhattan's Lower East Side in 1970, and since then
employment _ in industries that include offices, ship repair and
manufacturing of products that range from housing to Sweet 'n Low
to shrouds _ has bounced around at a few thousand jobs. The number
has been creeping up in recent years, and the city has approved $40
million to upgrade the waterfront, buildings and electrical and
water systems on the site's 169 acres.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing in the hodgepodge of warehouses, offices and
industrial sites bears any resemblance to the ambitious plan to
build a movie-making complex on 15 acres that now stand largely
empty except for three hulking structures once used to store and
manufacture parts for World War II battleships and aircraft
carriers. The project, with a dozen sound stages and 700,000 square
feet overall, would be the largest by far in the city, and would be
expected to spawn spinoff businesses to create a permanent
filmmaking infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The best argument for the site is the current boom in film
activity in New York. City figures indicate that a record 221 films
were shot in New York last year, generating $2.57 billion in
economic activity. It was the fifth straight record-breaking year.
The number of days films were shot in New York increased by 50
percent over the past five years, and direct expenditures on
filmmaking have risen 78 percent. Over the last year alone, the
number of prime-time television series filmed in New York climbed
to 10 from six.
</P>
<P>
   But New York has only 600,000 square feet of sound stages for
major productions, Ms. Scott said, while Los Angeles has about 3.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   People in government and the industry agree that there is
enormous demand for the kind of stages being contemplated, and that
having people like De Niro, Weinstein and the developer Steven
Roth, chairman of Vornado Realty Trust, behind the project gives it
a credibility earlier projects did not have.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have people involved who can generate their own
production and co-production like Tribeca and Miramax, you're just
immediately on another level,'' Ms. Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers tend to come to New York to shoot on location and
then do indoor and post-production work in Los Angeles or
increasingly in Canada, where costs are lower than in New York or
Los Angeles. But if better space were available, it is likely that
more would be willing to do that work in New York as well,
filmmakers say. They say it makes enormous sense to do both in one
place, so if, for example, bad weather scuttles outdoor shooting, a
production can move indoors for the day. Working in one place also
cuts down on having two production offices and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   And the Navy Yard, in many ways, is a tantalizing option. It has
the kind of vast expanses and room for support and satellite
businesses almost impossible to find in New York or Los Angeles.
Existing buildings at the Navy Yard have already been used for
filming. Because of the investment approved by the city, the
proposed complex would have the kind of advanced fiber optic and
telecommuncations equipment needed. And as a municipally owned site
it has an owner desperate to make the site work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I sound like a Pollyanna, but this is going to
happen,'' said Marc H. Rosenbaum, president of the Brooklyn Navy
Yard Development Corp., which was established by the city to run
the Navy Yard, as his van skirted potholes and puddles at the site,
which is as glamorous as a sewer pipe but nonetheless employs 3,000
people in 200 businesses that would coexist with the movie complex.
``All it takes is a little vision.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still, vision can be a little clouded for New York's film
industry. After all, the local film business boomed in the 1970s
and early '80s, collapsed in the face of disputes with unions in
the late '80s and early '90s and has come roaring back in recent
years. Similar deals with less high-powered backing have regularly
collapsed over the past 15 years. And some wonder if the digital
era will lessen the need for huge sound stages.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The most recent mega-plan, by an independent film production
company, the Shooting Gallery, called for building 15 sound stages
for $75 million in an old industrial park in Harrison, N.J. That
was scrapped for a much more modest project in lower Manhattan.
Similarly, the original proposal for the Navy Yard by two young
promoters, Louis Madigan and Cory Dean Hart, foundered, and without
the Miramax and De Niro names it seems unlikely that investors for
the project would have been found.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even producers who would like to see the additional space say
sound stages have little appeal to lenders, who would rather build
an office or apartment building than a sound stage with no
guarantee that it can withstand cyclical ups and down of the movie
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be great if it happened,'' said Ilene
Landress, producer of the television series ``The Sopranos,'' which
is filmed at Silvercup Studios, at a former bread bakery in Long
Island City, Queens. ``But I might be retired by the time it does,
and I'm not old. The problem is you need to find someone with a lot
of money for a project like this, and there are so many other
businesses that make more sense than building black boxes for sound
stages.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons to be wary. Filmmakers consistently
express a preference for Manhattan, and an aversion to fighting
bridge and tunnel traffic to Brooklyn. Even the two existing sound
stage complexes in Queens, Silvercup and Kaufman Astoria Studios,
have far better access to public transportation than the Navy Yard
does.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the city's efforts to spruce it up, the site is widely
viewed as an eyesore, and is sometimes referred to as Dodge City
because of the need to dodge trucks, cranes and heavy equipment.
And many people are skeptical about the project's scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by the notion of building 12 sound stages,'' said
Phil Dixson, managing director of Televest, which produces soap
operas for Procter &AMP; Gamble. ``It sounds awfully ambitious to me. I
could see three or four being booked up rather quickly. But I'm not
sure how they came up with the number they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the uncertainties are expansion plans at other
studios that could include five new studios at Silvercup, five at
the proposed Hudson River Studios at Houston Street and one at
Kaufman Astoria. Only Silvercup has begun construction.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the larger issues buffeting the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, studio space in Los Angeles is going begging, it's
empty,'' said Tom Pollock, former head of Universal Pictures and
currently the chairman of the American Film Institute. ``And sound
stages are not a way to make a lot of money. It's a rental business
of small margins and fixed costs. You don't make money by owning
the lot. You make it by owning the successful software, the
successful movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in question is the need for big sound stages at a time when
production can increasingly be done on computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The parties to the Brooklyn proposal are declining comment while
the major potential financer, Union Labor Life Insurance Co., a
union-supported pension fund, studies a potential $80 million
investment in the deal. Absent that commitment, the deal remains
nowhere near the financing needed to go forward. And for all their
nominal support, neither Miramax nor Tribeca has made any binding
commitments to use the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their announcement was the biggest non-announcement
announcement I've ever seen,'' said one person in the film
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to securing the rest of the money and the role of
all the principals, the project must deal with Madigan and Hart,
the promoters, who say they still hope to be a major part of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The plan has a lot of constituencies. The New York film industry
sees it as a catalyst for expansion. City officials see it as an
economic development plum. De Niro and Miramax see it as a project
that would make it easier for them to make movies in New York. And
Union Labor Life Insurance Co. would get both construction jobs and
the possibility of future union jobs, though company officials take
pains to say the project has to make economic sense on its own.
</P>
<P>
   And the proposal may benefit from coming at precisely the right
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing on this couldn't be better,'' said Dan Levinson, a
producer and director who moved to Los Angeles from New York in
1987 and returned two years ago. ``New York is hot. People really
want to come here again. If the unions are smart and make some real
concessions, I think New York can steal a lot of the business back
from L.A. Will it happen? I don't know. But I wouldn't bet against
Harvey Weinstein and Robert De Niro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-21 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING PERSONS BUREAU TAKE NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Where was Scotland Yard when that little old tennis
tournament called Wimbledon was in need, with a missing persons
case? Not, however, in need of persons to fill the seats and every
available space on the grassy hillside facing a gigantic TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's never a problem at the Big W, where 36,471
communicants _ a record opening-day throng _ squeezed into the
premises Monday to eat a lot of strawberries &UR;  &LR; and &UR;  &LR; cream and help
start the 113th edition of the world's elder among such
celebrations. Many of them had camped overnight Sunday on sidewalks
outside the green walls to be early in the lines that stretched as
far as a half-mile from the black iron gates.
</P>
<P>
   English people care.
</P>
<P>
   But where were two of the people they care much about, Serena
Williams and Katharine Windsor? Missing. That's for certain; that's
the mystery. It made you want to ring 999 (the British version of
911) and request a posse of detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever she was, Williams is, as you may know, the younger of
the Sisters Sledgehammer, ranked No. 10 on earth. The other is No.
5 Venus, who trotted out onto Centre Court, following Pete Sampras,
to dismember Miriam Oremans, 6-1, 7-5, with a variety of stinging
shots including the second-fastest female serve ever launched on
these lawns: 123 m.p.h. The record is 125 _ set by herself a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unseen Windsor, as you also probably know, is the Duchess of
Kent. One of the few stars of the local dysfunctional royal family,
she is a stylish pillar of Wimbledon, customarily decorating the
front row of the Royal Box.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sampras, the champ, appeared on Centre along with
victim Scotty Draper to signal the beginning of another Wimbledon,
and turned to bend at waist in the ceremonial bow to whatever royal
birds roosted in their aviary just above and behind the court _ the
best seats in the house _ he looked puzzled for an instant. No
Duchess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed her,'' said Sampras after a sharp first act in his
quest for a sixth title, a 6-3, 6-4, 6-4 decision sprinkled with
crisp volleys and forehands. Instead of the Duchess's sparkling
smile, the champ had to settle for her roommate, the Duke of Kent,
and Prince Michael. Chopped liver lined up against the prime rib.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the show went on. The Duke, who doesn't talk to
persons such as I, wouldn't reveal whether he'd ordered Katharine
to stay home and do windows, or whether she'd been abducted by a
sheikh of Araby.
</P>
<P>
   She hadn't called in sick as Serena did last Thursday, thus
withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena has the blue flu,'' said her mother, Oracene Williams,
with a Mona Lisa smile, not caring to define colorations of
influenza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the flu,'' said Venus. ``I miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Williamses, the royal family of Palm Beach Gardens,
Fla., function very well _ though sometimes in secretive and
baffling ways _ there are some who believe Serena is an on-purpose
missing person, avoiding an entanglement with her big sister.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is nine-time champion Martina Navratilova, now a TV
babbler for HBO, who strongly challenges the disappearance: ``I
just wish they would tell the truth, because flu is not the truth.
She may be a little sick, but not that sick. You don't withdraw on
a Thursday when you may not have to play until Tuesday or
Wednesday. Either Serena has another injury or she didn't want to
play against her sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Aha.
</P>
<P>
   Serena did behave curiously in that respect last year. Facing a
lesser foe, Virginia Ruano Pascual, in the third round, seemingly
sure to collide with Venus in the fourth, Serena played
desultorily. She quit when behind, 7-5, 4-1, claiming a leg injury.
Yet she reappeared afresh to win the mixed doubles with Max Mirnyi.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, when the pairings were announced Wednesday, Venus
and Serena looked headed for a fourth-round head-on. Did papa
Richard Williams, who has plotted his kids' courses cleverly, feel
he knew best by withholding his 17-year-old to keep the progress of
his 19-year-old uncomplicated emotionally?
</P>
<P>
   Not even Scotland Yard, Sherlock Holmes, or Miss Marple could
solve that one.
</P>
<P>
   Papa did say after Venus beat Serena for the Lipton title in
April that the match strained the entire family.
</P>
<P>
   Bart McGuire, boss of the Women's Tennis Association, offers the
expected, and, you hope, correct opinion: ``I can't believe Serena
would give up Wimbledon if she's not sick.''
</P>
<P>
   A missing person in 1998, one-time top 10 inhabitant Anke Huber
has turned up again, not only here, but in the life of her
rebounding boyfriend, Andrei Medvedev. Medvedev, who has risen from
No. 100 to No. 31 by attaining the French final and almost beating
Andre Agassi, credits his rejuvenation to Huber.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently they were scheduled for back-to-back engagements.
He beat up on her German countryman, Bernd Karbacher, 7-6 (7-1),
7-6 (7-3), 6-4, then settled in for a long vigil as Huber went
against another found-again type, Jennifer Capriati. Not even a
sharp north wind that cooled the place to the 50s could discourage
these two battlers into the gloaming.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:05, after both had suffered numerous knockdowns on the
dewy, treacherous turf, referee Alan Mills interceded and stopped
the fight, sending them home all tied up in the third. From the
standpoint of Capriati, who trailed, 0-3, in the second, the score
is 5-7, 6-3, 5-5, with more to come today.
</P>
<P>
   Romantics surely must believe that Andrei will have fixed Anke a
nice, comforting cup of tea. Also that the Duchess will materialize
once more in her front row seat. And that Serena will recover in
time for the US Open, so we won't have to call 999 after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
