<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINEHURST NO. 2, STEWART BOTH ON TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ There were two winners in the 99th US Open at
Pinehurst's cherished No. 2 course.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the course. ``I would very much like to see the
Open come back to Pinehurst,'' said Phil Mickelson, the runner-up
by a stroke. ``I felt this was the first Open course I played that
tested every area of the player's game from the driver all the way
to the short game.''
</P>
<P>
   The other winner, of course, was Payne Stewart. A few years ago,
he stood outside the clubhouse at Augusta National during the
Masters and talked dejectedly about his future in the game, citing
a loss of enthusiasm. That was light-years away from the emotion he
showed Sunday when he won his second US Open with a 15-foot par
putt on the 72d hole.
</P>
<P>
   He prevailed heroically over Mickelson, Tiger Woods, and Vijay
Singh in an enthralling finish to a tournament that tore apart some
of the game's best players with pin positions that many considered
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   What it ultimately came down to on this Father's Day was that
Stewart had to lay up out of damp rough and sink that 15-footer.
When he made it _ after Mickelson missed a putt that could have
forced an 18-hole playoff Monday _ Stewart went into an emotional
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe I accomplished another dream of mine,''
said Stewart, who also sank a 25-foot putt on the 16th to save par
and hit a 6-iron to 3 feet on 17 to set up a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   After losing by one shot last year at San Francisco's Olympic
Club, Stewart didn't want to return home to Orlando to confront the
same questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said, `Oh, man what a great try,' '' said Stewart.
``I didn't want to hear that when I got back to Orlando and all my
friends came up and said, `Boy, you sure tried. It was a great
effort. You're a great competitor, but bad luck.' I didn't want to
hear that, and it motivated me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mickelson, ``I think it was very exciting towards the end
with four players having a very good opportunity to win the golf
tournament. I felt with three holes to go I was in control of the
tournament because I was leading and it's a very difficult course
to make birdies on. Even until the last putt, I felt there was
still a very good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson had a future Father's Day in mind as wife Amy was due
with their first child; he had every intention of leaving on the
spot if she went into labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a disappointing day for me,'' said Mickelson, ``but
the fact that our first child is expected to come here in the next
week or so is awfully exciting. It will be a bigger change of my
life than had I won today.''
</P>
<P>
   As he played out the drama, Stewart was stone-faced and laconic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept playing,'' he said. ``I kept plugging. I didn't hit the
great shots at certain times and then I did hit the great shots.
Then I'd hit the great putts and poor chips. But I got the job
done, and that means a lot to me. I told you last night that if I
won again that I'm going to enjoy it a lot more, and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the saga of Woods, who left long putts woefully
short and missed one from inside 3 feet on the 17th to stymie his
charge for a second major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' said Woods. ``It's pretty intense, and you've
got to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
