u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-UPDAT     06-21 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (nk) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 1/2 pages of stories on Kosovo for
Tuesday, June 22.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The agreement reached early
Monday to disband the Kosovo Liberation Army included, at the
insistence of its commanders, a pledge by the NATO allies to
consider letting the rebels form a provisional army for Kosovo
modeled on the National Guard in the United States. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Interview with top rebel
commander, Gen. Agim Ceku, who already has the formation of a
future army for Kosovo planned out, even as he is preparing to
disarm and demobilize his guerrilla force. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WOMEN-ASSAULT (Zrze, Yugoslavia) _ In interviews over the
last two weeks, dozens of women and men in Kosovo and in refugee
camps in Albania told stories that suggest that sexual assault and
intimidation, if not rape, were widespread, common and used by
Serbian forces to strike at the heart of a society in which the
virginity and fidelity of Muslim women is central. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With a map and photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ For the third consecutive
day, several dozen Serbs in civilian dress who call themselves
``warrior citizens'' prevented ethnic Albanians from entering the
predominantly Serbian sector of this northern Kosovo industrial
town Monday, jeering and threatening any Albanian who dared to
enter. In a direct challenge to NATO authority, the Serbs are
declaring their neighborhood, about a third of the city, and the
predominantly Serbian towns to the north a ``Serb zone,'' which
they say stretches from here to the border with Serbia. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Ljubljana, Slovenia) _ This tiny and new nation
perched on the Adriatic was held up Monday by President Clinton as
a shining example of what was possible if a people decided to stand
up to the ethnic terror of Slobodan Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A small group of
Yugoslav opposition parties said Monday that it would call
demonstrations this weekend to demand early elections and
democratic change. But Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is
considered highly unlikely to call early elections, senior
government officials said Monday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Pec, Yugoslavia) _ Three battle helicopters
hovered overhead, and there were nearly as many military vehicles
as plain cars. But that is what NATO decided it would take to bring
70 Serbs back to this destroyed city Monday, in a high-minded
attempt to enable Kosovo Serbs and Albanians to live together even
in the ruins. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Undated) _ It is hard to say which accusation
rankled the most: that Macedonia was trying to make money off the
Kosovo refugee crisis; that the Macedonian people as a whole
refused to treat the Kosovar Albanian refugees with the respect
they deserved; or that Macedonia was exaggerating the damage it
suffered from the conflict over Kosovo. But Macedonians from all
political points of view resented being portrayed as would-be
profiteers or even collaborating with the Serbs in the latest
chapter of eight years of Balkan wars that have brought them little
but an extremely tenuous independence. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
