<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVEN HELP US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives, unable to agree on
any realistic remedy for the very real problem of school violence,
has passed the political buck to God, allowing states to permit the
display of the Ten Commandments in public classrooms or government
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds harmless, right? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an affirmation of the value of religious principles.
It is an alarming example of congressional fantasizing. It is a
sneaky attempt to force the language of one religion into the minds
of youngsters who may not yet have chosen their faith. And it will
not keep a single crazy kid with a grudge and a gun from hurting
others.
</P>
<P>
   The Ten Commandments are good words to live by, but they are
just words. They didn't prevent murders and hatreds and evil deeds
in Biblical times and won't do it now.
</P>
<P>
   Kids can hang the Ten Commandments in their rooms if they want;
parents can hang them over the sofa or the kitchen table. But
displaying them in locations like schools and courtrooms where
states exercise authority over individuals puts an unacceptable
official stamp of approval on them.
</P>
<P>
   What the new House measure means is that our elected nitwits
have chosen to hide behind pseudo-religion rather than fulfill
their proper duty, which is the hard work of dealing sensibly with
national issues in a huge nation of competing interests and needs.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, religious zealots have promoted the spread of
Christian symbols and prayers in public places as the way to
strengthen the American character. Their political sympathizers
prefer to try to legislate morality than come up with practical
secular ideas that might cost taxpayers money or irritate powerful
lobbyists _ but actually do some good.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the right moment to do the wrong thing came during the
tumultuous, emotional debate over gun control and juvenile justice
last week. In its confused, panicky response to the shootings at
Columbine High School in Colorado, Congress was at its very worst,
which can be really terrible.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of the worst was the House majority whip, Rep. Tom
DeLay of Texas, who blamed the gun violence in schools on day care,
abortion, the teaching of evolution, the absence of prayer in
schools, too many civil rights for children, irresponsible parents
_ everything but the kitchen sink, and nut cases who have easy
access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, considered the most powerful Republican in the House
these days, thundered ``the issue is God, not guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny. We thought DeLay was elected to participate in running a
government, not to anoint himself commander of our souls.
</P>
<P>
   And just when did God become a political issue? Religion,
according to most surveys, is doing very well. Americans still go
in large numbers to church, which is where God in any form belongs.
True faith should be a private matter, not a partisan plaything.
</P>
<P>
   The last we heard, God doesn't pick sides in elections. God has
nothing to do with the manufacture and sale of semi-automatics and
other weapons by which students are killing rival students. If He
disapproves of day care, He has overlooked the millions of tots who
benefit from such early attention and turn out great.
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay sold the House on the concept of ``returning God to
the schools'' with the Ten Commandments. This is almost surely
unconstitutional, although the House tried to get around the
traditional separation of church and state by merely specifying
that states could ``allow'' displays of the Ten Commandments rather
than mandating the change.
</P>
<P>
   And the direct impact of the Ten Commandments upon the moral
behavior of schoolchildren seems dubious at best.
</P>
<P>
   Since religion is very personal, I am going to rely on my own
family Bible, which is a 1904 St. James translation. In this
version, the First Commandment is ``thou shalt have no other gods
before me.'' That's pretty dictatorial about who's the religious
boss but lacking in persuasive content.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not make unto thee any graven image ... Thou shalt
not bow down thyself to them, nor serve them.'' Again, it's
dictatorial but lacks persuasive content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not take the name of the Lord thy God in vain.''
OK, no swearing would be an improvement. But over the decades human
ingenuity has expanded crude verbal opportunities beyond the
Bible's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the sabbath day, to keep it holy ... Thou shalt not
do any work, nor thy son.'' This one lost its meaning long ago in
most families, where church may fill mornings but the rest of the
day is occupied by jobs, studies, shopping, and other secular
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honor thy father and thy mother.'' This is generally a good
idea, but the Bible didn't know about deadbeat dads and parents who
beat up on their children and each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not kill.'' This is a timeless goodie, but hard to
explain if your parents favor capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not commit adultery.'' Also timeless, but there
doesn't seem any relevance here for schoolchildren not yet old
enough for adult temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not steal.'' Also a goody, unless you want to go to
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not bear false witness against thy neighbor.''
Assuming ``neighbor'' includes wives and mistresses, too bad
President Clinton didn't read this one. But this could be useful if
your kid tends to lie about stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not covet thy neighbor's house, nor his wife ...
nor anything that is thy neighbor's.'' This could be useful to warn
off kids who want to steal their buddies' hot shoes or jackets. But
it doesn't cover lust for a gun that can be bought firsthand at the
local gun show.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
