<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMERTIME AND THE NET HOAXES FLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ahh, summer. Time for sun, swimming and, sadly,
Internet hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the recent furor over real Internet threats, such as
the Melissa virus and the Worm.Explore.Zip trojan horse virus, many
e-mail users have been hit with a flurry of hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them are old, returning for an encore. Some are new, or
relatively new. But all share a common thread: They are untrue and
serve no purpose other than to scare people and clog the Internet
with junk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   An old one that's making the rounds again involves a claim that
Congress wants to pass legislation giving the government power to
impose a 5-cent surcharge on all e-mail delivered anywhere in the
country. This is a hoax!
</P>
<P>
   The ``Washingtonian,'' an actual publication quoted in the hoax
e-mail, says it never wrote about such a surcharge and that the
congressmen quoted in the hoax e-mail don't exist. You can read the
entire disclaimer at www.washingtonian.com/about/emailhoax.html.
</P>
<P>
   A new hoax _ at least one that I'd never run across before _
involves a story of how Stanford University began.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tale of how two ragtag people in threadbare clothing show
up at Harvard University one day, asking if they could donate a
building to the campus in memory of their son who was
``accidentally killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's president ``rolls his eyes'' and dismisses the two,
who end up going to California and building an entire university.
</P>
<P>
   The couple turns out to be wealthy railroad baron Leland
Stanford and his wife, Jane.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University archivist Margaret Kimball said she's been
trying to kill this story for more than a year. Kimball says the
e-mail is entertaining but untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Stanford Jr. died of typhoid fever, not by accidentally
being killed, she said. And after their child's death, the
Stanfords decided to found an institution that would ``serve the
children of California,'' where the elder Stanford had served as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanfords apparently visited Harvard, Cornell, MIT and Johns
Hopkins while trying to decide whether to build a university,
museum or technical school as a monument to their son.
</P>
<P>
   But, she says, the Stanfords were quite wealthy and certainly
did not show up in threadbare clothing. In addition, Kimball said,
it's hard to imagine that the Stanfords were treated with anything
but respect by Harvard University's president.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanfords ended up building a university and museum near
Palo Alto, Calif. The site apparently is near a tree where the
younger Stanford once ate his lunch.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other e-mail hoaxes that have made the rounds.
They include Good Times, AOL4FREE, the Internet Cleanup Day, the
Bill Gates hoax and one called It Takes Guts to Say Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do if you get an e-mail that makes some wild
claims? First off, try to verify the information before you
duplicate it and send it off to all your friends. Clogging the
Internet with unnecessary e-mails is one of the worst impacts of
online hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   There are many Web sites that can help you verify whether an
e-mail claim is true or a hoax. One is operated by the U.S.
Department of Energy's Computer Incident Advisory Capability. You
can find it at ciac.llnl.gov/ciac/CIACHoaxes.html. This site is
also good for getting reliable information on viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites with information about Internet hoaxes include
www.datafellows.com/news/hoax.htm (a very good site),
www.symantec.com/avcenter/hoax.html and www.4urbanlegends.com.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, and remember: Don't believe everything you read in
e-mail! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nullsoft gets new parent
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regular readers of this column have read about Nullsoft Inc.
(www.nullsoft.com) before. It's the Sedona, Ariz., company that
produces WinAmp, the most popular software player for MP3 music
files.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I mentioned Nullsoft, the company was being sued
by PlayMedia Systems Inc. (www.playmediasystems.com) for alleged
copyright infringement. PlayMedia claimed that its playback
software was used in WinAmp, a charge Nullsoft denied.
</P>
<P>
   This time I mention Nullsoft because the company has been
acquired by none other than America Online. The purchase, which
also included San Francisco-based Spinner Networks Inc., was
announced this month.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never heard of Spinner, you should check out its Web
site (www.spinner.com). The company delivers virtually any kind of
music to your desktop. Download and install the Spinner player, and
you can have background music all day. About 1.5 million people use
it monthly.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said the purchase of Nullsoft and Spinner will ``enable
consumers to play all leading formats of Internet music.''
</P>
<P>
   The sad part for Arizonans is that the deal means Nullsoft will
be moving its headquarters from Sedona to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Nullsoft's president and founder, Justin Frankel, sounded happy
about the multimillion-dollar deal: ``Working with America Online's
tremendous resources and infrastructure will let us focus our
efforts on what's really important: Making cool software.''
</P>
<P>
   Way to go, Nullsoft! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Web sites of the week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
- Are you in Scouting? There are a couple Web sites that claim to
specialize in finding information just for Scouts, whether they are
boys or girls (or adult leaders, for that matter). One is called
the Scouting Spider. It's at spider.scout.net. The other is the
Girl Scout Only Search Engine, at girlscout.jalyn.net/search.html.
(A tip of the hat to reader James W. for letting us know about
these two sites!)
</P>
<P>
   - Tired of paying $1.30 or more per gallon of gasoline? A group
of Phoenix residents wants to help. They've created a Web site
called Azgasprices.com, where you can check a long list of the
cheapest places in town to buy gas. It's updated frequently, and
relies on input from everybody who uses the site. A recent check of
the list showed several stations selling gas at $1.07 per gallon or
less. Find the site at www.azgasprices.com. (Thanks to reader Becky
B. for telling us about the site.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     06-21 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMIND BOSS IT'S A JOB, NOT AN ENCOUNTER GROUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: I've been working at a small company for
about five years, and I haven't had any real complaints. We just
hired our first human resources director. Through the rumor mill, I
heard that she suggested to the owner that the employees meet in
small groups to criticize each other and bring all our faults into
the open. The boss thought this was a terrific idea. How do I
convince the boss that this would be the beginning of the end? S.G.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Assuming that your company's rumor mill is grinding out
accurate information, it sounds like your new human resources
director has a less-than-resourceful idea. Unless your boss is
interested in a program that will generate dissatisfaction,
distress and disharmony, you should consider making some
suggestions on your own.
</P>
<P>
   In the broadest sense, the idea of a new HR director conducting
some group sessions to learn about employee attitudes is a good
one. However, these discussions should focus on attitudes toward
such issues as productivity, teamwork, job design, rewards, and the
work atmosphere and culture.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell your boss that in sessions where employees are
encouraged to unleash negative feelings toward each other, such
feelings are not put back into a sealed bottle when the session
ends. Rather, many of the participants will feel hurt, attacked,
betrayed and defensive, and they will take these feelings right
back to their jobs. When a project calls for cooperation with
someone who slammed them in the group session, the outcome is not
going to be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Let your boss see the costs of the new director's approach, and
the benefits of sessions that focus on performance rather than
personality. This may be the beginning of the end ... of a
questionable idea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am the manager of a department at a large company. There is
another manager who has a history of angry outbursts, mistreatment
of assistants and verbal abuse of co-workers, regardless of
warnings from upper management. He claims that people are yelling
at him, so he yells at us. His behavior is abusive and against all
company policies and harassment laws. I need some advice. J.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hopefully your company has some form of employer practices
liability insurance, because it sounds like it is just a matter of
time before someone gets litigious.
</P>
<P>
   In a company where yelling, screaming and abusive treatment are
found at the highest levels of management, it is not surprising to
find this type of behavior oozing down to lower levels of
management as well. In fact, many managers learn how to manage or
mismanage from their superiors. In addition, when such outrageous
behavior is practiced at the highest levels, the real message is
that such behavior is entirely acceptable, company policies and
laws notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   You should approach senior management, provide specific examples
of questionable managerial behaviors, and advise the topsiders of
the significant costs and risks associated with abuse, harassment
and bullying. The idea of risk management should not be entirely
foreign to the company leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Any possible improvement in your situation must come from the
top. If the company leadership does not make a move on the issues,
then perhaps you should make a move.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of my good friends at work is sort of a goof-off and a
clown. The other day, my manager came down very hard on me and said
that he has seen us fooling around too much and he wants it to
stop. I don't spend that much time with him, and I'm not sure how
to handle what the manager said. R.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: When you hang out with the office clown, people can think
that you are part of the act. According to what your manager has
seen, the two of you are together too much and working too little.
Whether this is an accurate perception or not, it is reality for
him. The best step is to cut back on the clown-time.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than getting into a debate with your manager over the
amount of time that you may or may not have spent with your friend,
it will be more helpful for you to focus on your productivity. You
should tell your buddy that you both are under the corporate
spotlight and need to make sure that your performance levels are
first rate.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that you can no longer be friends, nor does
it mean that there can be no more humor at work. It just means that
you both need to remember the real meaning of performance on the
job. After all, humor at work is very important. However, when
carried to an excess, it can cause both of you to be carried to an
exit.
</P>
</TEXT>
