<SLUG> BC-EPIDEMIC-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV REVIEW: WHEN A QUICK FIX BECOMES A LONGER-TERM PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Kan., Ga.)  (Production notes at end of review) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most parents and many doctors, antibiotics are a quick fix
for the colds, fevers and assorted ailments of childhood. As the
contributors to ``Epidemic,'' Tuesday night's ``Fred Friendly
Seminar,'' caution, worried parents and busy doctors are
co-conspirators in the development of drug-resistant bacteria that
threaten health around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert C. Moellering, an infectious-diseases specialist at
Harvard Medical School and the Beth Israel Medical Center, tells
how formerly ``first-line drugs'' like penicillin and ampicillin,
have lost effectiveness and some diseases are resistant to any drug
at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation that pops around from affluent America to
disease-stricken East Africa, where as one doctor says, ``hospitals
are running on Band-Aids,'' public health experts agree on the need
for a comprehensive approach to the appearance of frightening
symptoms like those connected with the Ebola virus.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Arthur R. Miller of the Harvard
University Law School, who tends to get a touch cute about dire
matters (a reporter is named Manfred Muckraker), the panelists get
into the problems of keeping reporters and politicians from
spreading pandemonium while researchers try to figure out what is
happening. Dr. Joshua Lederberg, an expert on bacterial genetics,
has compliments for the way journalists generally handle the
subject of antibiotic resistance, but warns that under deadline
pressures they have trouble dealing with potentially catastrophic
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the panelists have much of interest to contribute. Nancy
Kassebaum Baker, former senator of Kansas, comes out in favor of
bigger appropriations for health, and Dr. John D. Siegfried, who is
affiliated with the pharmaceutical industry, puts in a plug for
``an active and functioning pharmaceutical industry working in
conjunction with the federal government and academic researchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Moellering acknowledges the drug successes but expresses concern
over the financial incentive to bring new drugs onto the market:
``They have to cover their costs.'' (The program is sponsored by
Bristol-Myers Squibb.)
</P>
<P>
   The hour ends with a brisk exchange about the pressures on
public health specialists to deal with potential epidemics without
adding to panic among parents and elected officials, who, as Bill
Campbell, the mayor of Atlanta, notes, have to worry about legal
challenges no matter what they do, especially when children are at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. David A. Kessler, former commissioner of the Food and
Drug Administration, warns that ``the riskiest thing we can do'' is
not to take any risks at all.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   EPIDEMIC: A Fred Friendly Seminar
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 8 p.m. ET, PBS
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kilberg, executive producer; Andy Halper, producer; Joan
I. Greco, senior writer; Arthur R. Miller, host and moderator. For
``Fred Friendly Seminars'': Ruth W. Friendly, senior editorial
advisor; Barbara E. Margolis, executive director; Kilberg,
president. A production of ``Fred Friendly Seminars'' and the
American Museum of Natural History in association with WNET, New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
