<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBO-FAIRYTALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING FAIRY TALES A FEMINIST TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In HBO's latest fracturing of fairy tales, ``The Three Little
Pigs'' as reinterpreted by Tama Janowitz will be set in a girls'
camp where ``You can never be too fat or too dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   The stars are three very chubby and very muddy little girl
piglets, whose voices are those of three notably unchubby (and
presumably unmuddy) young women: the actresses Courteney Cox and
Sandra Oh and the supermodel Tyra Banks. With Loretta Lynn in a
Dolly Parton-esque role as Deli Pork Chop, the camp leader, and
Sinbad as the Big Bad Wolf, Tuesday night's presentation of ``The
Three Little Pigs'' is the first of 13 new tales in a monthly
series called ``Happily Ever After: Fairy Tales for Every Child.''
It began in 1995 as an effort to add other races to the white
European stereotypes of fairy-tale lore, but this season's stories
have also been given a feminist twist.
</P>
<P>
   To get attention, HBO and the co-creators, Donna Brown-Guillaume
and Meryl Marshall, went all out with celebrity solicitations. For
writers they attracted Erica Jong, Linda Fairstein, Anna Quindlen
and Roy Blount Jr. (his ``Frog Princess'' is one of three stories
by men). The voice-over actors range from Eartha Kitt to Angie
Dickinson, from Andre Braugher to Doug E. Doug.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Henny Penny,'' the story of Chicken Little as rewritten by
the tart-tongued political columnist Molly Ivins, a sky-is-falling
election debate in the barnyard features the voices of Sharon
Stone, Johnnie Cochran, Alan Dershowitz, the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
Henry Kissinger and, as Merle and Earle, Geraldine Ferraro and
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York. Naturally, HBO has scheduled
that one for November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharon Stone actually called and asked to do a voice,'' said
Ms. Brown-Guillaume, adding that the series' first two seasons gave
it a certain cachet among entertainers. Calista Flockhart, star of
``Ally McBeal,'' for example, plays Vanna, Rip Van Winkle's wife,
while Tom Arnold gives a resounding male-chauvinist spin to old
Rip.
</P>
<P>
   And if something seems askew in having a woman who earns
world-class paychecks by being slim and beautiful play a fat and
sloppy piglet, Ms. Banks does not see it that way. ``In my world,
you can never be too thin,'' she said disapprovingly, adding that
when she was seriously ill and lost 30 pounds, she was horrified at
the number of people who told her she had never looked better. ``I
kept calling HBO to make sure that this story was consistent:
skinny was ugly, and fat was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   For others looking for doctrinaire feminist interpretations,
Carole Rosen, the HBO executive in charge of this series, has
another message: Lighten up. ``These words may sound familiar:
militant, humorless, taking themselves too seriously,'' she said.
``These labels have been applied to feminists. Yet this series is
marked by tremendous humor and satire.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blount, who wrote ``The Frog Princess,'' sounded earnest and
serious when he said writing a feminist tale was more complicated
than, say, replacing a white Cinderella with an Asian one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just flip-flop the roles,'' he said. In traditional
tales, the prince goes on a quest to win a princess, he said, ``And
you don't want your female characters going off on a quest for no
other reason than to find a prince. So you need to find a whole new
kind of story to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this means letting girls have the adventures
or be the leaders or the rescuers. For example, Ms. Fairstein, head
of the Manhattan district attorney's sex crimes unit and a mystery
writer (for adults) in her spare time, said she had fun writing
``Aesop's Fables: A Whodunit Musical'' and making sure that ``a
smart female detective solves the mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Janowitz's ``Three Little Pigs'' (written, she said, with
her own lively 3-year-old daughter in mind) starts the series
Tuesday night at 8 p.m. (ET). Most episodes will be at 8, although
Ms. Quindlen's ``Ali Baba and the 40 Thieves'' (Ali is a girl, of
course), next Tuesday, is scheduled for 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more famous fairy tales that would seem ripe for a
feminist reworking _ ``Sleeping Beauty,'' ``Snow White,''
``Cinderella'' _ were used in the earlier two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind, said Ann Richards, the former governor of Texas,
who lends her voice as a wise old woman of the mountain (``It was
just typecasting,'' she said) in Ms. Jong's version of ``Rip Van
Winkle.'' Feminist infusions are still needed in children's
stories, she said, including modern ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took three of my grandkids to see that new `Star Wars'
movie, `The Phantom Menace,'' she said. ``Here we are in 1999,
moving into the new millennium. What does the central female
character do in this movie? She changes clothes, and she fixes her
hair in a different, very elaborate style in every scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what do the boys do? They drive fast cars, they win the
race, they sit with the guy who is the biggest hero of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message still is that women get dressed up and look nice,
and boys do brave, constructive, wonderful things. So you cannot
think that kids aren't still getting stereotypical messages these
days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
