<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Who's the Dummy?'' is the provocative title of an
exhibition that explores the evolution of mannequins from
dressmakers' forms to store-window displays to live runway models.
The show, opening Tuesday in the Museum at the Fashion Institute of
Technology, combines serious scholarship with humor. It grew out of
a yearlong seminar on exhibition planning for graduate students,
two dozen of whom worked on the displays.
</P>
<P>
   One room contains vintage mannequin heads, videos of how
mannequins are made and of live models in fashion shows, and photos
that demonstrate the use of mannequins by Salvador Dali and Giorgio
de Chirico (who called the mannequin ``a sad and monstrous
reality'').
</P>
<P>
   It's a thought-provoking exhibition that encourages viewers to
consider how mannequins stand in for the human body and in the case
of fashion forms, actually define each age's standard of beauty.
Contemporary fashion mannequins made by Pucci, probably the
best-known manufacturer today, demonstrate the current emphasis on
diversity, with a slender high-fashion type, a voluptuous model
inspired by Dianne Brill, Asian and black versions, and a size 18.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the crash dummies and medical mannequins that
can make you squirm (especially one with surgical scars and an
attached catheter).
</P>
<P>
   Dolled-Up Paper
</P>
<P>
   Another exhibition in the museum is a pure delight. Titled
``Papiers a la Mode,'' it consists of 25 paper dresses that are
nothing like the throwaway paper dresses of the 1960's. These are
painstakingly hand-painted, pleated, frilled, tasseled and braided
dresses tracing fashion from a panniered Venetian court dress circa
1745 in red and gold to a 1930's Fortuny pleated dress and jacket.
</P>
<P>
   A Belgian artist, Isabelle de Borchgrave, painted, dyed and
stenciled the paper to resemble silk, linen and lace, which Rita
Brown, a Canadian costume designer and restorer, then assembled
into dresses. Ms. de Borchgrave also decorated the museum's walls,
painting trompe l'oeil curtains and even a little dog that sits by
a mannequin in an early 20th-century ``linen'' suit. &QL; 
Pancaldi Updated
</P>
<P>
   Pancaldi was once a leading purveyor of fashionably classic
women's shoes at stores like Bergdorf Goodman. But as styles became
more extreme, Pancaldi found its star fading. In the last year,
Pancaldi has updated its styling and is taking steps to become a
worldwide brand.
</P>
<P>
   The company now makes the currently popular square-toed shoes
and boots on molded soles as well as sexy metallic sandals and
shoes with Lucite heels that look like Lalique. Neiman Marcus has
sold 2,000 pairs of a $220 Pancaldi mule. Saks Fifth Avenue and
Bloomingdale's also carry the shoes and, this summer, so will three
Pancaldi stores in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market in Russia is picking up,'' Stefano Pancaldi, the
president of the family-owned Italian company, said on a visit to
New York last week. ``There are plenty of wealthy people in
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year there will be a Pancaldi store in New
York at 775 Madison Ave. And 12 more stores are due to open in the
next two years in Italy and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stores will be showcases,'' Pancaldi said, ``both to grow
the business and to show the potential customer the full line of
what we make, including accessories.''
</P>
<P>
   Pancaldi produces its own lasts, heels and components in
company-owned factories, he explained, just as it has since its
founding in 1888.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
