A4217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-EVANGELIST-ART-     06-21 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-EVANGELIST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER JAPANESE GANGSTER TURNED MINISTER TAKES MESSAGE TO THE
STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUNABASHI, Japan _ Elaborate tattoos of a carp and mythic
characters of great strength work their way from his pectoral
muscles, over his shoulders, down his arms and across his upper
back.
</P>
<P>
   The tips of his pinkie fingers are conspicuously missing. And
his teeth, capped to perfection, provide more evidence of Hiroyuki
Suzuki's organized-crime credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But while his flesh brands him a member of the yakuza, Japan's
storied underworld, he now says his allegiance is to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, 43, formerly a member of the Sakaume gumi, a small
independent crime family best known for its role in gambling, is
the founder of Mission Barabbas, an evangelical Christian church in
this Tokyo suburb here, and a minister in the church.
</P>
<P>
   Mission Barabbas features the brand of tongue-speaking,
faith-healing, arm-waving Christianity popular in parts of America
but a distinct oddity in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Christianity in Japan has prevailed only among a
small number of highly educated people, never really reaching the
masses the way it has taken root in other countries. Masaru Hayami,
the governor of the Bank of Japan, is probably the most prominent
Japanese Christian at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 1.1 million Christians, including foreigners, in
Japan, according to The Christian News, a Tokyo weekly; that is
less than 1 percent of the population. Christians here typically
maintain a low profile, perhaps a carryover from the days of the
Tokugawa shogunate, when Christians were persecuted and the
religion was all but stamped out. Since then, Christianity has
spread largely through private schools and universities like Sophia
University.
</P>
<P>
   Mission Barabbas, on the other hand, takes its message to the
streets, a practice reflected in its membership, which is divided
between people who are handicapped, unemployed and otherwise
outcast from Japanese society and people who would disappear in the
crowd at an average train station.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this church, because I used to take drugs and commit
crimes, people who have problems but can't talk about them anywhere
else come here,'' he said. ``It's split about 50-50 between those
who change their lives and those who just drift on.''
</P>
<P>
   The church, which was started four years ago, has some 60
members, and its tiny, one-room sanctuary tucked away in a typical
neighborhood is packed for Sunday services. ``On average in Japan,
one church collects about 30 or 40 followers over a 20-year
period,'' Suzuki said. ``So we're pretty pleased with our
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki and his handful of fellow yakuza converts use a mobile
ministry, song and fiery preaching to win converts. They spent six
months lugging a cross from Okinawa to Hokkaido, a march they have
repeated on a tighter schedule in South Korea and Hawaii. ``Rather
than waiting for people to come in and find us, we decided we'd go
out to the people and talk to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has gained enough attention to earn a speaking engagement at
the president's Prayer Breakfast at the White House last year,
along with President Clinton and the Rev. Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Suzuki's conversion from gangster to minister is as
much a love story as a tale of an epiphany. As a young yakuza
member, he fell in love with a hostess in a bar in Osaka, a young
woman from South Korea who called herself Mariko but was born Han
Kumja.
</P>
<P>
   The two separated many times but always found themselves
reunited. They were a sad pair. Suzuki was struggling under a pile
of debt accumulated in heavy gambling binges, and Mariko was deeply
disappointed with her life in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   She began going to a Korean church, having sought solace in
Buddhism and fortunetelling but to no avail. She liked the people
she met at church, Suzuki said, and found that she felt buoyed,
although she could not explain exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   Some time later, Mariko broke her kneecap. The minister and
members of her church fasted and prayed for healing, Suzuki said,
and when Mariko went to church the next Sunday, the minister put
his hands on her broken knee and pronounced it healed.
</P>
<P>
   She walked away from church that day, and although Suzuki
regarded her religion as a silly waste of time, the recovery of her
knee fascinated him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In gambling,'' he said, ``you use dice. Dice are made from
bone, and if God could heal her bone, I figured he could probably
assist my dice and make me the best dice thrower in all of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of prayer, Suzuki's gambling skills did improve,
enabling him to pay off his debts.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly lapsed back to his old ways, abandoning Mariko,
who had become his wife, shortly after she gave birth to their son.
``At that time, I was like a stone rolling down the hill into the
mud,'' Suzuki said.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, his debts mounted, and he drank and took drugs. He
fled Osaka and his young family, returning to Tokyo with his
favorite bar hostess in tow. He had his girlfriend call his wife
and taunt her and eventually demanded a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months later, he became ill. ``I thought my wife was
trying to kill me with a curse from God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring God had cured his wife's leg, he sought out a church
wedged between a brothel and a gambling parlor in a seedy section
of Shinjuku ward in Tokyo. Once there, he says, he collapsed in
front of the cross, where he stayed for three days, praying and
calling out to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carpet was soaked with my tears,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the minister finally approached him, Suzuki screamed out
that he was beyond redemption. ``I was shouting because I was
hurt,'' Suzuki said. ``I had severed two of my fingers by myself,
undergone the pain of tattooing, spent two years in jail and
deserted my wife and child.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister persisted, however, and Suzuki calmed down. He
returned to Osaka to confront his wife, and her immediate
acceptance of him despite his misdeeds clinched his faith, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that I could start over again, which I had thought was
impossible,'' he said. He was officially expelled from his gang
when he entered the seminary in 1990, but he doesn't fear reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``God is protecting me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
