<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4220 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     06-21 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CHILDREN TO EXOTIC PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 27) 
(jt) 
 By MARTHA STEVENSON OLSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before I was married, in 1991, I traveled as much as I could in
what was then called the Third World. My husband, Jinx, shared my
fondness for these regions. We were determined that having children
wouldn't slow us down, so after our first daughter, Allie, was born
in 1992, we took a trial vacation to the Baja peninsula for a
couple of weeks, albeit with a rented house as our base. When Allie
was 18 months old, we departed for six months in Central America.
Our second child, Katherine, was an infant when we took off for
three years of combined work and vacation in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives were worried: What would we do in a health
emergency? Would they get enough nutritious food? Don't children
need stability and a bed they can call their own? We had questions,
too.
</P>
<P>
   I read and reread Lonely Planet's ``Travel With Children,'' now
in its third edition, by Maureen Wheeler, co-founder of the
guidebook series with her husband, Tony. It answered many of my
questions and offered crucial reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   These days, there is the Internet. Some Web sites I've found
recently include www.havechildrenwilltravel.com, a newsletter
available for $29 a year (four issues). It focuses primarily on
travel in the United States and Europe, but occasionally covers
destinations in the developing world. About.com, formerly
miningco.com, has forums and chat rooms that focus on traveling
with children at www.travelwithkids.about.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting Web site, www.familytravelforum.com, has
forums as well as links to child-friendly destinations and books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We found that keeping the children happy was key. We didn't try
to do major jungle treks or long expeditions to ruined cities. We
went to the beach, a playground or pool. We ate outdoors when we
could. One excursion a day was enough, usually in the morning. When
we found a comfortable place, we stayed a while.
</P>
<P>
   For peace of mind medically, we joined the International
Association for Medical Assistance to Travelers, or I.a.m.A.T., a
nonprofit organization that publishes a directory of participating
doctors worldwide, all of whom speak English or French, have been
trained in a Western medical institution and pledge to charge a
fixed amount for a first visit; I used it a couple of times, with
gratifying results. The organization (membership is by donation)
also sells a freestanding mosquito net that I wish we'd had on our
trips.
</P>
<P>
   The SFO Medical Service, a joint project of the University of
California at San Francisco, San Francisco General Hospital and San
Francisco International Airport, has a Web site that covers some of
the basics of travel with children: itsa.ucsf.edu/sfomed. (Click on
``Travel Medicine.'') It also operates a clinic at the airport that
provides health care and advice.
</P>
<P>
   We continued to pay our Blue Cross premiums, to get catastrophic
coverage for expenses beyond $2,000 each. From previous travels in
Asia, I knew that doctors there are pretty good at treating local
maladies, if sometimes overly reliant on antibiotics, and that care
is inexpensive by American standards.
</P>
<P>
   If anything major were to arise, we'd fly back to the United
States, or head to Singapore, which has the region's best hospitals
and doctors. Before leaving, we had the usual vaccination updates,
as well as gamma globulin, an infectious-hepatitis prophylactic,
before our trip to Central America, and its recent successor, the
hepatitis A vaccine, before leaving for Asia. We declined the
rabies vaccine, though one doctor recommended it.
</P>
<P>
   Malaria prophylactics are a subject of some controversy; each
family should decide what's right for them with their own doctors.
Most urban and tourist centers in Asia are fairly safe from
malaria, and doctors there tend to know how to deal with it if
presented with an early enough case. To protect against mosquito
bites, we covered as much of the body as possible between dusk and
dawn, sleeping under mosquito netting and applying repellents,
first a commercial one formulated for children then a
one-to-three-parts mixture of citronella and coconut oils that we
mixed ourselves and seemed to work just as well.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of our stay Jinx did get dengue fever, a serious
disease carried by day-biting mosquitos; it cannot be prevented by
vaccination or treated except symptomatically. Jinx got his dengue
bite on a remote Thai island, but dengue fever is also on the rise
in many cities. (He was very ill for about five days and got good
care at a hospital in Chiang Mai, in northern Thailand.)
</P>
<P>
   Sanitation was a prime concern, as most travelers' ailments in
developing countries tend to be gastrointestinal. Breastfeeding an
infant, if possible, is the easiest and healthiest way to feed a
child. Well-known formula brands are easily bought _ but the
headache of washing and sterilizing the bottles along with the
questionable purity of even some of the bottled water makes it more
chancy than breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
   When my girls used bottles and cups, I washed them with tap
water and soap, rinsed them with bottled water and, when possible,
let them dry in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Asian toilets tend to be ceramic trough set in concrete, with
foot treads on either side of the hole. A basin or tank of water
nearby, with a little bucket, is used to flush. The basin water is
used only for this purpose, and you avoid touching the bucket,
except for the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Disposable diapers are widely available, although larger sizes
can be hard to find. Quality varied; we'd save good ones we'd
imported or bought in cities for nights or long bus trips, use
cheap brands for short-term duty, and, if possible (at the beach,
for instance), go without, as many Asian families did, keeping a
close eye on the toddler and cleaning up when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Diaper rash was a constant concern in the tropics; any skin
lesion is an entry point for germs. A good diaper cream is
essential, but even more so is antibacterial ointment. I applied it
to any skin lesion, on adult or child, until healed.
</P>
<P>
   When the children had a stomach upset, we followed the same
regime as for ourselves: bananas, plain rice with traces of ketchup
or soy sauce and plenty of clear fluids. (We drank bottled water;
if we ran out, in a pinch I would boil tap water.) We had come
prepared with packages of hydrating solution, a powder of
nutrients, salts and sugars that dissolves in water, but the
children refused it _ too yucky.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting a small island in southern Thailand that had a
water shortage, the girls came down with diarrhea and fever, Allie
so seriously that we were ready to take her to a hospital when the
illness subsided. During that one awful night I was tortured with
guilt; then I remembered that children in the United States get
ill, too.
</P>
<P>
   Another bit of hard-earned wisdom: Carry much less. On our first
trip with Allie, to Central America, we took an enormous backpack
stuffed with diapers, as well as a stroller, a portable crib and
other paraphernalia. On our second trip, to Asia, we abandoned the
crib, tried to get rooms with four beds and made little bunkers
with pillows and bits of luggage that managed to contain a sleeping
child fairly well. A good stroller, on the other hand, was crucial.
It allowed us to take an occasional daylong expedition that might
include a napping child and served as a high chair. I could loop
bags over its handle, and the canopy blocked the tropical sun.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy children's clothing as you go _ it's very
inexpensive, often well made and suited to the climate.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding the girls turned out to be less a problem than we'd
feared. Packages of corn crisps, rice cakes and other munchies can
be bought at every corner store and travel hub. At mealtime, our
children tended to stick with favorites available on the travelers'
circuit: pancakes, omelets, grilled cheese sandwiches and spaghetti
with tomato sauce. They shunned vegetables, but familiar fruits _
bananas, peeled apples, oranges _ helped balance their diets.
</P>
<P>
   The International Association for Medical Assistance to
Travelers is at 417 Center St., Lewiston, N.Y. 14092; (716)
754-4883; on the Internet www.sentex.net/iamat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
