<SLUG> BC-NYC-VA-TRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CITY COLUMN: THIS HAZARD FOR VIRGINIA IS UNREPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Second of two John Tierney columns on Virginia and New York
City trash.) 
(jt) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Va. _ Under cover of darkness, the trucks rumble
out from an industrial complex hidden in a wooded ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Flouting the law, they speed along Virginia's roads,
distributing the environmental burden that is their cargo: bales of
newsprint amounting to 120,000 tons of solid waste per year. While
local communities struggle to pay the consequences, the profits
flow to an out-of-state corporation, The Washington Post Co.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, little attention has been paid to the perils involved
in delivering the 400,000 copies of The Washington Post printed
here each night. Virginians have been concentrating on another
out-of-state menace: the trucks delivering garbage from New York
City. The state recently put limits on the imports, in no small
part because of The Post's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper detailed the dangers of out-of-state trash last
November in a series of three front-page articles totaling more
than 12,000 words. The first article began with a grim scene of
trucks lumbering out of the Bronx, and went on to describe the
``terrifying'' and ``frightening'' hazards posed by speeding trucks
with bad safety records. It described one fatal accident on
Interstate 95 and included complaints about the incessant parade of
trash trucks, which were said to make 100,000 trips annually into
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   That statistic works out to about 275 trucks per day, which
seems less than frightening when compared with the total traffic in
the southbound lanes of Interstate 95 here: 133,000 vehicles daily,
including about 2,400 trucks not carrying trash. It doesn't even
loom large by comparison with the 1,500 trucks, vans and cars
delivering The Washington Post each day in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   How safe is the Post fleet? A New York Times investigation _
which consisted of my tailing 10 trucks leaving the plant here with
Friday's papers _ found that 90 percent of the trucks exceeded the
speed limit by at least 10 miles per hour. While those safety
violations posed little obvious danger _ the trucks were keeping
pace with other vehicles flouting the law _ records show that
trucks delivering The Post have injured people.
</P>
<P>
   My investigation did not impress Leonard Downie Jr., the
executive editor of The Post. ``It sounds silly,'' he said. ``Our
article reported serious safety problems with some trucks and
drivers, and they travel much larger distances than trucks in
Virginia making local deliveries of The Washington Post _ or The
New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, why focus on a few bad drivers hauling trash when many
others carry more hazardous cargo? In December, a tractor-trailer
ran off the road in central Virginia while carrying a bleaching
agent to the Bear Island Paper Company, a newsprint mill that
supplies The Washington Post. The chemical spilled and ignited,
forcing nearby residents to stay inside for hours to avoid toxic
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The trash industry ships generally innocuous cargo, consisting
chiefly of cardboard and paper, to be buried in new double-lined
landfills, surrounded by buffer zones of woods and fields, in rural
communities that willingly bear the environmental costs in exchange
for the economic benefits. For some reason, though, a lot of city
dwellers _ journalists, environmentalists, politicians _ are
convinced the countryside is being ruined. ``If we don't stop it
now,'' one Norfolk politician told The Post, ``we won't have any
space left but one big dump.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the big new Virginia garbage pits together amount to
only three square miles. That leaves more than 40,000 square miles
in the rest of the state, including 243 occupied by the timberland
that supplies the newsprint mill at Bear Island.
</P>
<P>
   That newsprint eventually turns into solid waste that must be
collected for either recycling or disposal. Based on the average
cost of collecting and processing solid waste, Virginia taxpayers
are spending at least $5 million annually to get rid of old copies
of The Post, and tens of millions of dollars to handle all the
other newspapers that ran articles about Virginians being exploited
by trash-exporting New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that New Yorkers last year sent more than $50
million to Virginia along with their trash, you might wonder who's
exploiting whom. If Virginians really care about their fiscal
health and their roads and their environment, maybe they shouldn't
worry so much about out-of-state trash.
</P>
<P>
   It's an awkward question to ask in these pages, but is it time
for them to limit out-of-state newspapers?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
