<HEADER>
A4226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JANUS-MARKETPLACE-NYT     06-21 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANUS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE 2 FACES OF JANUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In April, Janus 20 sat atop the mutual fund world. It was the
best performer of any large stock fund, having doubled investors'
money since the start of 1998. And it had taken in so much money so
fast _ nearly $7 billion in four months _ that Janus said it would
close the fund to ``deliver superior performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the fund has once more earned a prominent place on the
performance charts _ this time, at the bottom. In fact, through
Thursday, it ranked as the 15th worst-performing general equity
fund of 4,008 funds in the second quarter, according to Lipper, the
Summit, N.J., mutual fund data company.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's concentration in 20 to 30 stocks _ mostly big growth
companies like America Online, Dell Computer, Microsoft and a
handful of pharmaceutical companies _ carried it to lofty heights
the last two years. But some of those same holdings proved a drag
on performance this spring, when the strengthening global economy
prompted investors to shift to shares of cyclical companies and
other value stocks that had lagged behind the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   So far this quarter, Janus 20 is down 4.4 percent, compared with
a 5.2 percent gain in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and an
10.9 percent gain in the Dow Jones industrial average. That was in
spite of a bounce the last week that lifted the fund's return from
a loss of 13.2 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The decline shows the pitfalls of buying funds that have
concentrated bets in one sector, especially in a volatile area like
technology. It also demonstrates what so often happens to investors
who rush into a fund before it closes: They regret it. In fact,
investors often pick exactly the wrong time to throw their money
in.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, new money had been accumulating at Janus 20, which
is managed by Janus Capital Corp., a unit of Kansas City Southern
Industries, at an average of nearly $500 million a week before the
fund was closed. According to AMG Data Services, an Arcata, Calif.,
fund-tracking company, the inflow peaked the week ended April 14 _
the height of IRA season _ with investors pouring in $654.6 million
just as the fund's performance began to slide.
</P>
<P>
   Fund investors ``tend to be very poor buyers in terms of timing,
and the more volatile the area, the worse their timing decisions
usually are,'' said Scott Cooley, an analyst at Morningstar Inc.,
the Chicago fund tracker. ``There is a lot of risk in having all of
your money pretty much in a specific style that is fairly volatile,
and Janus has a lot of shareholders who have come to it recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoelzel, the fund's manager, said Monday that he is not
altering his strategy. The portfolio is invested largely as it was
at the start of the year, though Schoelzel said he has trimmed
holdings in drug companies like Pfizer and Eli Lilly. ``I should
have recognized we were going to go into a period of time when the
news flow from the pharmaceuticals was going to be less than
upbeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To complement the fund's biggest names, like America Online and
Dell, Schoelzel said, he has been aggressively buying a few other
large-capitalization growth stocks. He's also sitting on about 15
percent cash, though he says that's not a reflection of any
bearishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, I kind of expected there would be a period of
time where the fund would have trouble,'' he said. ``For the most
part we didn't get shaken out of anything, but I've got to tell
you, I have a lot more gray hair than I had in March.''
</P>
<P>
   The average stock in the fund is trading at close to 50 times
earnings, according to Morningstar, high by almost any measure.
Schoelzel's justification: Old valuation yardsticks don't mean much
anymore. The market, he said, ``is going to vacillate from being
expensive to really expensive for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   He also doesn't buy the argument that investors ought to shift
to stocks with lower valuations and cyclical stocks that rise with
a strengthening economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me how panicky the market gets,'' he said,
``to think we can change the direction of a $7 trillion economy
with a 25-basis-point'' increase in short-term interest rates. His
reference was to the quarter-percentage point rise that the Federal
Reserve is expected to make at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Like Janus 20, many of the funds in the Janus group have their
biggest positions in large-cap growth stocks, with a strong
technology bent. The other funds have not taken such a beating, but
as Janus 20 goes, so may they.
</P>
<P>
   Janus has a deep stable of analysts and more stockpicking talent
than most firms, Cooley of Morningstar said. ``But it's still very
dangerous from a firm-wide perspective to have so many eggs in one
basket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
