<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC SEEN AS EASILY WITHSTANDING PROTESTS AND CALLS FOR
CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A small group of Yugoslav opposition
parties said Monday that it would call demonstrations this weekend
to demand early elections and democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is considered highly
unlikely to call early elections, senior government officials said
Monday. The term of the federal parliament does not expire until
2001 and the Serbian parliament until 2002, while Milosevic's own
single term runs through the spring of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic's political position is considered to be weaker
now, after the defeat by NATO in Kosovo, rumors of his removal
appear highly exaggerated, even opposition figures here admit.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Orthodox Church has called for his resignation,
there is unfocused unhappiness in the army, which considers itself
undefeated in Kosovo, and Serbian refugees from that province held
another small protest Monday in Belgrade, easily broken up by the
police.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic appears to retain a bedrock of popular support, 20
percent in recent opinion surveys, and there is no other political
figure who comes close to him. The most popular alternative is an
unpredictable former democratic opposition leader, Vuk Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic has moved into the government and outside of it,
and his political image is considered muddied, said Srbobran
Brankovic, a pollster and political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has turned his back on the idea of a transitional
Serbian government to be led by Draskovic, the officials say, and
appears to be planning to tough out the protests. The NATO air
campaign caused perhaps $40 billion worth of destruction, American
officials estimate, and did considerable damage to electrical power
stations, roads, bridges and factories.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials also say they can offer Yugoslav
opposition figures little more than advice, moral support, and
relatively small amounts of aid to independent media outlets,
presuming that diplomatic relations are soon restored.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, a senior Clinton administration diplomat, Robert
S. Gelbard, met Yugoslav opposition figures _ minus Draskovic _ in
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking the opposition to be an opposition and to aspire
to be a government, and to take steps within the constitutional
framework to do that,'' another senior Clinton administration
official said by telephone Monday. ``But the help we can provide is
limited. It's partly moral support and partly advice,'' as well as
a continuing isolation of Yugoslavia so long as Milosevic, an
indicted war criminal, continues to lead it.
</P>
<P>
   The call for protest rallies comes from one of the smallest of
Yugoslavia's opposition groups, the Alliance for Change, which gets
only about 2 percent of the vote. Still, it follows Draskovic's
call on Sunday for a new interim government, early elections,
democratic reforms and a free press to try to reintegrate
Yugoslavia into Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That call brought a quick attack on Draskovic by the state
television and other media as a corrupt opportunist who would do
anything to curry favor with the West.
</P>
<P>
   In general, said Brankovic, the political scientist, democratic
opposition leaders face the problem of calling for exactly the sort
of change publicly advocated by the Western alliance that has just
been bombing the country and its army and that has occupied Kosovo,
the historical heartland of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Change said demonstrations would start in
central Serbian towns where the opposition is already strong and
where there were protests against the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday we'll gather in Cacak and Kraljevo to demand early
elections on all levels and freedom of media,'' said Vladan Batic,
the group's coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Another official of the Alliance for Change, Milan Protic, said,
``This is the last minute to reverse the present political course
in Serbia and to demand the responsibility of those who have had
unlimited power in the decision-making process over the last 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   But senior Yugoslav officials did not seem concerned about such
protests Monday. ``Milosevic is not going anywhere,'' one said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bratislav Grubacic, an independent analyst here, said Milosevic
was weaker in important institutions like the church, the Serbian
Academy of Sciences and even the army. But he said the opposition
was also divided and was afraid to shed blood, while being
convinced that Milosevic would do whatever is necessary to remain
in power.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1996-97, Milosevic waited out huge
demonstrations against him led by Draskovic and Zoran Djindjic of
the Democratic Party. But the two opposition leaders split and are
now sharp rivals. Milosevic has thus far successfully played off
Draskovic against the ultranationalist leader of the Radical Party,
Vojislav Seselj, who has agreed not to vote against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs from Kosovo staged a small protest in central Belgrade
Monday for the second day in a row, but there were more journalists
than protesters. After about half an hour, the police rather
politely led off the organizer, Svetozar Fisic, a Democratic Party
official from Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   The group called on Milosevic and the United Nations to protect
the Serbs of Kosovo, to stop violence by the Kosovo Liberation Army
and its supporters there and to treat the refugees with full
rights. They said they would be willing to return to Kosovo
eventually, as Belgrade urges, but only if their security can be
guaranteed.
</P>
</TEXT>
