<HEADER>
A4235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      06-21 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOLDS UP SLOVENIA AS A MODEL FOR REFORM-MINDED YUGOSLAVS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ This tiny new nation perched on the
Adriatic was held up Monday by President Clinton as a shining
example of what was possible if a people decided to stand up to the
ethnic terror of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   He came here, Clinton said, to draw attention to the fact that
Southeastern Europe, now the favored name for the Balkans, could
produce a country that is free and prosperous. Slovenia, Clinton
added, had shown that it was possible to reject ``the murderous
rule'' of Milosevic, the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia has to ``choose the path that Slovenia has chosen, where
people reach across the old divides and find strength in their
differences and their common humanity,'' Clinton said to a crowd of
several thousand in the city square who had waited for hours in the
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip to Europe has centered on finding ways to rescue
the debris caused by the conflict in Kosovo, patching together
plans for aid packages to Kosovo and the rest of the region and
mending the relationship with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing the little known country of Slovenia, Clinton was
trying to stress the positive. In June 1991, Slovenia declared
independence from Yugoslavia, and when Milosevic sent in the
Yugoslav army, the Slovenians stood firm under the leadership of
Milan Kucan, who is now president and whom Clinton met Monday.
After what became known as a largely bloodless 10-day war, Slovenia
declared independence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton congratulated the Slovenes, saying: ``Eight years ago,
Mr. Milosevic triggered a military assault on your nation. But you
resisted. You secured your freedom. And you proclaimed it will
never be the same again.''
</P>
<P>
   But in singling out Slovenia, Clinton dwelled on a place with
unusual characteristics in the former Yugoslavia. Slovenia, a
country of two million people, is almost ethnically and religiously
unified. About 2 percent of the population are Serbs, and the
country is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic. The Slovenes are proud of
their own language, which is Slavic, written in the Roman script
and dates from the 12th century.
</P>
<P>
   Since separating from Yugoslavia, Slovenia's economy has bounded
ahead. The European Union granted Slovenia associate status, and
the country is trying to meet targets that would allow it to join
the European Union early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Clinton's trip was a reward for a large
disappointment. Slovenia had banked on joining NATO, and its
rejection for membership, along with Romania, several years ago,
was a severe blow. Clinton tried to assuage the blow by saying
Monday that Slovenia was ``an excellent candidate for NATO.'' But
he promised no more.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO will formally decide to expand further, after
accepting Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic as members this
year, remains an open question.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived from Bonn, Germany, where he attended a meeting
of the United States and the European Union on trade and other
issues. Near the top of the agenda again was organizing the
reconstruction of Kosovo and the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In Bonn, Clinton said he was in favor of German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder's idea of bringing leaders together in Sarajevo,
perhaps as early as next month, to plan for the Balkans' future.
Clinton said the gathering should be modeled after the development
of the Marshall Plan, when the benefactors met with the devastated
countries in Europe after World War II and fashioned a far-reaching
rebuilding program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a separate donors conference would be organized to
finance the immediate reconstruction projects. Such projects would
focus on Kosovo. An additional conference would be planned for the
fall to gather the financing for long-term needs, Clinton said.
Clinton repeated that the United States opposed financing
reconstruction in Serbia while Milosevic remained in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it be a good thing if Serbia had a democratic leader who
didn't do things like what we've seen in Bosnia and in Kosovo?''
Clinton asked at a news conference in Bonn. ``Of course, it would.
And I can't wait for the day when that happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
