<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WILL NEED MORE THAN EXPECTATIONS TO CONTINUE CAMPAIGN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Although the law of gravity often catches up with
high-flying White House campaigns, there was no way Texas Gov.
George W. Bush was going to let anything _ or anyone _ spoil his
first for-real campaign tour.
</P>
<P>
   Not questions about his ``young and irresponsible'' past. Not
questions about abortion. Not challenges of his ``compassionate
conservatism.'' Not even the million and one logistical details of
handling the largest traveling army of reporters and camera crews
ever to accompany a presidential candidate on his first trips to
Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign had recruited scores of volunteers with
invaluable experience at handling presidential trips and national
campaigns to ensure that hotel rooms were ready, buses were on time
and stages for well-staged campaign events were properly set.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the technical machinery of the four-day foray
performed very well. So did the candidate, as most of America
probably knows by now.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to suggest that Bush can start writing his inaugural
address or planning his Cabinet. Although he is clearly the
candidate to beat for the Republican nomination, no one _ not even
popular, well-funded sons of former presidents _ can be considered
unbeatable this early in a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has left the friendly Governor's Mansion in Austin
to meet other contenders head-to-head in key nominating states,
Bush will be forced to more precisely define himself on taxes,
foreign policy, Social Security and other important issues _ and
his huge lead in voter preference polls will tighten.
</P>
<P>
   In most respects, Bush continued to enjoy something of a
honeymoon on his first out-of-state trip. In his first extended
news conference with the national media, he faced some pointed
questions on abortion, taxes and his own past, but he survived
them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his events were well-organized, well-managed media
affairs or fund-raisers for Republican congressmen, not the type of
personal, retail politicking that voters in Iowa and New Hampshire
have come to expect of would-be presidents.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to be up-close and personal when three bus loads
of reporters and media technicians are following a candidate
around, but Bush promised a greater degree of intimacy on
subsequent trips, when his press contingent will likely be smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Even on his first campaign swing, the Texan had several
occasions to work the crowd, and he did it well, obviously enjoying
the opportunities and even _ sorry, governor _ inspiring some
national media comparisons to Bill Clinton's masterful command of a
rope line.
</P>
<P>
   Bush kissed babies, shook countless hands, signed almost as many
autographs and posed for hundreds of snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   In a packed reception for his New Hampshire supporters at a
small college in Goffstown, it took Bush a full hour to make his
way from the podium after his speech, through the crowd and out to
a waiting bus.
</P>
<P>
   Grinning all the way, he paused at one point to thump a Texas
reporter on the stomach and exclaim, ``It's wild!'' Or something
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Bush even managed to handle what little dissent he encountered
along his well-scripted route.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief question-and-answer session with real people at a
fire station in Bow, N.H., a heckler standing on the back of a
camera platform tried to challenge the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the flag amendment?'' the man asked, referring to a
proposed constitutional amendment to outlaw desecration of the
American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for it,'' Bush replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the First Amendment and freedom of speech?'' the
questioner persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're exercising it,'' Bush shot back, to the delight of the
rest of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But when the heckler tried to ask a third question, the governor
cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not exercising free speech anymore,'' Bush cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not a spellbinding orator. But he delivered his stump
speech, an expanded version of what he has been saying in Texas for
a long time now, well enough. He misspoke a couple of times but
committed no serious gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in control and obviously enjoyed the excursion _
``sky high'' was how he described himself after his first day in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appropriately dubbed his first campaign plane, ``Great
Expectations,'' because great expectations _ his own and those of
many other Republicans _ have gotten him this far.
</P>
<P>
   He will need more than expectations, though, to carry him the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Clay Robison is chief of the Houston Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
