<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-COSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLPHONE COSTS DOWN 38 PERCENT SINCE 1996 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wireless telephone costs have dropped by 38 percent since 1996
in North America, but cellular phones continue to be considerably
more expensive in the United States than in many European and
Canadian cities, according to a new study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As of the first quarter of this year, Boston-area wireless phone
owners were paying an average of 36 cents a minute, factoring in
monthly access fees and taxes, according to a study by The Yankee
Group, a Boston telecommunications analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers _ particularly heavy users spending 30 minutes a day
or more on the cell phone _ have benefited from ``an aggressive
pace'' of cost reductions, the report said, but they are still
paying much higher rates than residents of two dozen other cities
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's 36-cent average compared to 32 cents in Chicago, 33 in
Los Angeles and 40 in New York. In some developed countries,
however, rates were far lower: 8 cents in Toronto, 12 cents in
Seoul, 15 cents in Tel Aviv, and 20 cents in Hong Kong and
Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those cities have lower rates in part because of fierce
competition and because they use a system known as ``calling party
pays,'' where incoming calls are charged to the person making the
call, not the cell phone owner. US authorities are proposing to
adopt calling party pays rules by next year.
</P>
<P>
   For people using a wireless phone 60 minutes a month, Boston was
the fourth most expensive city of the 31 studied, exceeded only by
Paris, Tokyo and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Expressed another way, the average Boston cell phone user would
pay 1.5 percent of his salary for 100 minutes of cell phone calling
per month. That compares to under 1 percent in Toronto, and just
over 1 percent in Helsinki, Hong Kong, Tel Aviv and Rome, but 3 to
5 percent in some Asian and Latin American cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simplification along with reduction of wireless tariffs is a
key factor to increase wireless usage,'' said Christiane Mahler,
principal author of the report. Globally, Mahler said, wireless
costs will drop by another 33 percent by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   In US cities and Toronto, the greatest cost declines have been
enjoyed by heavy users, those racking up 500 minutes a month or
more, whose costs dropped by 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While relatively high compared to rates in other developed
countries, compared to land-line calling, US wireless charges have
dropped below the threshhold at which many analysts believe a
significant number of consumers will begin to switch over to using
a wireless phone full-time.
</P>
<P>
   In North American cities, heavy users spending more than about
35 minutes a day on their wireless phone, or 1,000 minutes a month,
paid 106 percent more per minute than they would have for land-line
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe the premium was 185 percent, while in much of the rest
of the world wireless calls continue to cost 5 times more than
land-line.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Yankee research found that US wireless users estimate
they have used wireless phones to replace 12 percent of their
land-line calling, and expect to increase that share to 17 percent
by 2001. ``Dramatic rate reductions are making wireless an
affordable alternative'', said Mark Lowenstein, senior vice
president of the Yankee Group's global wireless practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
