<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-PLAYBOY-HNS &LR;      06-21 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PLAYBOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT AGREES TO REVIEW ANTI-SMUT LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether a
federal law designed to protect children from sexually-explicit
cable channels violates the free-speech rights of cable TV networks
such as Playboy Television.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said they will review a Clinton administration
appeal aimed at reviving the 1996 law, which was struck down last
year by a three-judge U.S. District Court in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   That court said the law went too far in trying to keep children
from seeing sex-oriented programs on networks that are only partly
scrambled for non-subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The law required cable operators that don't fully scramble, or
block, sex-oriented networks for non-subscribers to show those
channels' ``indecent'' programs _ even to paying subscribers _ only
between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, cable operators have several types of technology for
scrambling and unscrambling TV signals, but the effectiveness
varies depending on the weather, the quality of the equipment, its
installation and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The government's appeal of the three-judge panel's ruling said
society has an interest ``in seeing to it that children are not
exposed to sexually explicit materials.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-smut law was enacted as part of the 1996 Communications
Decency Act after complaints arose that even though sex-oriented
channels are scrambled for non-subscribers, the picture and sound
sometimes get through in what cable operators call ``signal
bleed.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's appeal cited testimony from a Cape Coral, Fla.,
woman who said she found her seven-year-old daughter and
eight-year-old son and a playmate ``transfixed'' one afternoon at 4
p.m. as they were watching scenes on the Spice channel of a couple
seemingly having sex.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy had challenged the law in 1996, saying it violated the
Constitution's First Amendment, which protects freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy's lawyers said that under the law, cable operators
already give subscribers, free of charge, the ability to completely
block any channel once they request such action.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge court agreed with Playboy, saying that giving
customers adequate notice of their ability to block any channel for
free would be a less-restrictive alternative to barring all daytime
adult-oriented programming.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Justice Department argued in a brief that relying
on individual households to request the blocking of sex-oriented
channels failed to guarantee that children would not have access to
this material.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would certainly be parents _ perhaps a large number of
parents _ who out of inertia, indifference or distraction, simply
would take no action to block signal bleed, even if fully informed
of the problem and even if offered a relatively easy solution,''
Solicitor General Seth Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   The invalidated law ``imposes a very limited restriction on
speech and is a very effective approach to the substantial evil it
addresses,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy's lawyers disagreed, saying it was ``far from obvious''
that adult-oriented channels were more harmful than other premium
channels that show movies with profane content. They said a film
called ``Another 48 Hours,'' shown on HBO, averaged one profanity
every 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After the high court's decision to hear the case was announced,
Playboy Television lawyer Robert Corn-Revere said that the law was
``unnecessary overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the law requires ``turning off Playboy Television for
two thirds of the day'' even though two thirds of American
households don't have children. Many televisions these days have
technology allowing the owner to block a particular channel, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voluntary solutions are far more effective to block unwanted
programming,'' Corn-Revere said.
</P>
<P>
   The court, nearing the end of its 1998-99 term, planned to
announce more decisions Tuesday, and the justices could release all
remaining decisions and begin their summer recess later this week.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
