<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0622-COX     06-21 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEACEFUL ERA FOR KOSOVO OPENS WITH TWO NATO, TWO CIVILIAN
DEATHS; KLA REBELS BEGIN HANDING OVER WEAPONS
 &HT;    With CLINTON-KOSOVO-0622; KOSOVO-MONASTERY-0622.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Warring ended here Monday and the hard
job of nurturing peace paradoxically began with the deaths of two
NATO peacekeepers and two Kosovo civilians blown up in an ordnance
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   On the day NATO declared its air assaults finished and
Yugoslavia's government moved to end its state of war, the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army also began to carry out terms of a new
demilitarization agreement. KLA guerrillas turned over maps of
minefields and, in some cases, their guns and grenades, giving the
movement toward peaceful renewal a tap forward.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers killed, members of Great Britain's 69th Gurkha
Field Squadron, were Nepalese ordnance experts who hold among the
most dicey jobs in the military. And on Monday they were carrying
out one of the most important tasks necessary for reconstruction of
war-torn Kosovo even to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The troops were clearing explosives found near a school in the
village of Negrovce, about 20 miles west of Pristina, when the
munitions exploded at 1:25 p.m. (local time) and killed the two
soldiers and two civilians, according to NATO spokesman Lt. Col.
Nick Clissett. Another injured civilian was in stable condition at
a military field hospital here.
</P>
<P>
   The ordnance at first was said to be a mine, but later reports
raised the possibility that what exploded was bomblets from a NATO
cluster bomb or other left-overs from the allied air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was in the former Yugoslav republic of
Slovenia Monday, telephoned British Prime Minister Tony Blair to
offer his condolences, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   British NATO peacekeepers said they were investigating the cause
of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   The Gurkhas, compact, brown-skinned men from the rugged
mountains of southwest Asia, did not let the fatal accident impede
their work. A few hours later on a road just south of the
explosion, soldiers from the bomb squad were surveying roadside
properties, talking with landowners, and putting up new warning
markers with red-and-white striped roping to keep people out of
minefields.
</P>
<P>
   Mines and unexploded bombs are perhaps the most deadly legacy of
the Serb ethnic cleansing campaign that pushed an estimated 1.3
million Kosovar Albanians out of their homes. Military experts have
estimated hundreds of thousands of mines were laid throughout
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian agencies are running an information campaign,
putting up posters everywhere showing types of mines people might
encounter. The group Doctors Without Borders also is briefing
villagers on mine dangers at every mobile clinic stop, when a nurse
gives graphic descriptions of how unsuspecting Kosovars have been
killed or had their feet and legs mangled.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was a grim way to usher in the new stage of peace
in Kosovo. On Sunday Serb military and police forces completed
withdrawal under terms of a military technical agreement negotiated
with NATO, and in the early morning hours Monday NATO completed a
pact for the demilitarization of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Those two events released NATO to declare an end to the air war
against Yugoslavia that began March 24, and led the Yugoslav
government to request that its parliament revoke the state of war.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the KLA pact achieved after protracted negotiations,
NATO commander Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson said he hoped the world will
``look back and see it as a turning point in every way.''
</P>
<P>
   Very soon, KFOR will be the only military security presence
here, Jackson said, referring to the NATO-led Kosovo Force of
peacekeepers. ``That is how it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   But with returning Albanians forced to confront the grisly
evidence of months of Serb atrocities, ``It's going to take a lot
of leadership and a lot of self-discipline for those who have come
home not to retaliate,'' said President Clinton in Bonn, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke to the
issue in a brief phone call Sunday night to KLA leader Hashim Thaci
and expressed their appreciation and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should not do it. They should not do it,'' Clinton said
of Albanian retaliation against Serbs. ``In the end, it will not
satisfy anyone, and it will only compound the horror.''
</P>
<P>
   Thaci, appearing at a news conference here Monday with U.S.
State Department spokesman James Rubin, hailed the demilitirization
pact as marking ``a new epoch beginning for the people of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Thaci said, ``We ask all Serbs that have fled from
Kosovo and haven't done any crimes here to come back and live in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to disarm the KLA and get it out of power positions have
been aimed not only at securing peace, but also at convincing
ethnic Serbs to continue living in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement that gives the KLA 30 days to turn over heavy
weapons and 90 days to give up automatic firearms also mandates
that guerrilla fighters not carry weapons within two kilometers
(1.2 miles) of main towns or borders.
</P>
<P>
   It was having some impact already on Monday, when KLA officers
handed over to German peacekeepers in the southern city of Prizren
some maps of minefields primarily located in the border area with
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   KLA troops also began heading home.
</P>
<P>
   One truckload of at least two dozen fighters was standing
outside a post of Italian peacekeepers in Djakovica Monday
afternoon, after the NATO troops extracted a cache of weapons from
them. Inside the post, a range of rather old looking rifles and
automatic guns, machine guns and hand grenades, was laid out on the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Italian troops had surrounded the truck with arms at the ready,
even though the KLA men had readily given up their weapons and
seemed pretty relaxed as they waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to disarm,'' said Emin Tuqi, the 27-year-old
commander of the squad. ``Our mission was to get out the Serbs and
now they are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The men, mostly young fighters who smoked and talked easily with
the few journalists there, said they had just come down from a
mountain posting near the Albanian border and were anxious to get
home to find out how their own families fared.
</P>
<P>
   At other places around the province -- in Pristina and Pec and
Klina and along the roads between -- KLA soldiers were plentiful
but not obviously armed in public.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas who fought for Kosovo's independence had become a
potential barrier to waging peace in this Yugoslav province, taking
over villages, setting up road checkpoints and swaggering around
cities heavily armed. They also engaged in several kidnappings and
are accused of vengeance killings of Kosovar Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs were not much convinced, although 70 of them came back
across the border Monday under NATO escort from Montenegro to their
home city of Pec. They did not immediately go to their houses, but
stayed at a NATO post.
</P>
<P>
   At Patriarchate of Pec monastery, where 300 Serbs have taken
refuge, there was no sense the KLA agreement gave comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is the same as yesterday. There is no difference,'' said
Metropolitan Ameilohije Radnic.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Bonn, questioned about fears of retaliation against
Serbs by returning Albanians and KLA forces inside Kosovo,
President Clinton shifted the focus to the mounting evidence of
anti-Albanian atrocities inside the war-ravaged province.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair, the real story coming out of there is still the
staggering number of civilians that have been murdered,'' said
Clinton, who plans to visit refugee camps in Macedonia on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
