<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-GOP22-COX     06-21 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-GOP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE GOP TO UNVEIL 'STRAIGHT A's' EDUCATION PLAN
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans offer the states more
control over federal funds in their alternative to President
Clinton's plan for assisting elementary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's five-year bill, to be introduced Tuesday, places more
stress on flexibility for the states, and less on making sure that
the grants are used for reforms mandated by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   A law passed earlier this year gave all states the right to
mingle funds from six federal programs that distribute about $10
billion in education grants annually. Clinton's bill places a few
new restrictions on that procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican ``Straight A's'' bill, the Academic Achievement
for All Act, loosens existing restrictions and widens the pool to
include about $3 billion annually from another 12 education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic president's insistence on lots of ``rules and
regulations'' continues programs that have shown ``little or no
academic results,'' said Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of
the House Education and Workforce Committee. But Clinton says
schools that take federal aid should have to meet federal standards
such as reduced class sizes or testing new teachers on their
mastery of subject matter and skills.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side has been able to recruit congressional sponsors
from the opposite party for its bill.
</P>
<P>
   The new GOP bill is supported by such prominent Republicans as
House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois and Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi, as well as a few Republican governors.
</P>
<P>
   But most governors would prefer a bipartisan compromise. For
that reason, the Republican Governors Association _ like the
National Governors Association and the Democratic Governors
Association _ has yet to take sides.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., chairman of the Senate education
committee, said he will try to draft a bipartisan bill, but not
until later this year, after he has held more hearings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the final struggle to avoid a damaging stalemate is
likely to take place next year amid the political pressures and
partisan posturing of election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill gives states the right to mingle funds from
18 of the 20 largest education programs. To do that, states would
have to sign contracts with the federal government spelling out
their goals for improving the academic achievement of all students,
low-income students and students who have fallen behind.
</P>
<P>
   States that met their goals would get extra federal money, and
those that missed their goals several years in a row would risk
losing their right to mingle the funds from the different programs.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the president nor the Republicans would tamper with two
existing programs _ special education aid and impact aid, which
helps school districts that include large amounts of non-taxable
federal land.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 billion that states can already mingle includes $7.7
billion in Title I aid for disadvantaged students and $2.3 billion
from five other programs: Perkins vocational education grants,
teacher training, safe and drug free schools, immigrants and
innovative education.
</P>
<P>
   About $3 billion a year is spent on the 12 programs that the
House Republicans would add to the pot. They range in size from the
president's $1.2 billion plan to reduce class size by subsidizing
the hiring of new teachers for grades one through three, down to
$24 million to prepare facilities to be used by public-school
specialists who provide services to low-achieving children in
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
