<SLUG> BC-MURDERED-NANNY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY OF MURDERED NANNY UNRESOLVED AFTER THREE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- She could have been a nurse or a skydiver. A pianist
or a gardener. A mother, and even a great-grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   But to anyone who followed the investigation into her murder,
and even those who knew her, Karina Holmer will forever remain 20
years old. And she will always be an au pair.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after friends last saw the Swedish au pair wandering
outside a night club in the early morning hours, police Monday said
a murder in Florida last month _ an eerily similar case that seemed
to hold the most promising lead in finding Holmer's killer _ was
unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   ``After speaking with the police in Florida about both cases,
there doesn't appear to be any connection whatsoever,'' said Boston
Police Sgt. Det. Daniel Coleman, referring to the murder of Delia
Lorna Mendez, a 34-year-old prostitute whose body was found severed
and dumped in a pet store trash bin in Hollywood, Fla., on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Her slaying marked the first time a body had been mutilated that
way since Holmer's torso was found in a trash receptacle in Boston
in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The au pair had been in Boston only three months when she was
murdered. The crime stunned the city, and hinted at the
helplessness of parents who lodge young female foreigners thirsting
for downtown excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez' murder sparked conjecture that her killer and Holmer's
were the same. Not only were both women discarded in trash bins
after being cut in half, but both seemed to have been severed with
some kind of power instrument.
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman Monday said the differences in the circumstances
which led Holmer and Mendez to become victims _ and the details of
both crimes _ had all but eliminated a connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dealt with what we know about our case, and what they know
about their case, and the two incidents did not have a lot of
similarities,'' said Coleman, one of three homicide investigators
currently assigned to find Holmer's killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a young girl in a nightclub district who was reported
to have been drinking, and she was alone,'' he said. ``Their case
was very different from that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Mendez was about 14 years older than Holmer. Mendez
was beaten to death, while Holmer was strangled. And while police
recovered both halfs of Mendez' body, Holmer's legs and lower torso
were never found.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the Mendez murder, Boston police said
detectives in Hollywood had received three anonymous calls alluding
to the Holmer case. Coleman said those were general calls pointing
out similarities to the Holmer case, ``but there was nothing
specific connecting the incident in Florida to what happened in
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how investigators reacted upon learning the cases
are not connected, Coleman said, ``As investigators, we try to be
methodical and analyze whatever we've got. But we don't really get
hopeful unless the investigation leads us down that road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't go into this saying, `This is it,' because often
times it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman said the case remains open, and that each
possibility that is ruled out is at least some progress in finding
the killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, everybody remains committed to this case,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
