<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW UNEASY SERBS RETURN TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ Three attack helicopters hovered overhead, and
there were nearly as many military vehicles as plain cars. But that
is what NATO decided it would take to bring 70 Serbs back to this
destroyed city Monday, in a high-minded attempt to enable Kosovo
Serbs and Albanians to live together even in the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties were clear just from the amount of military
hardware. ``It's to send a message,'' said Col. Vincent Diaz de
Villegas, the NATO officer who oversaw the operation Monday. ``We
will use all necessary means to accomplish our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   That mission, he said, is to let any Serb return to Kosovo
without being harassed _ or worse _ by Kosovo Albanians in reaction
to the killing, burning and looting during a year of ethnic purging
at the hands of Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Many Albanians here said they were in no mood to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they won't be safe here,'' said Gazmend Amati, 21, a
Kosovo Albanian who lives here. ``You can't live anymore with
Serbs, not after all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pec, in western Kosovo, is one of the cities most damaged by
Serbian forces in the last two months, and it remains one of the
most tense. On Saturday three Serbs in civilian clothes were shot
to death in a nearby village, in what military officials say
appeared to be the work of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the Albanian
separatist rebel force.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days more than 18,000 Serbs have fled into the
neighboring Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, which is nearby, the
U.N. High Commission for Refugees reported. The agency said a total
of 50,000 to 60,000 Serbs have fled Kosovo in that time.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 Serbs have expressed the wish to return to the area
around Pec, and the operation Monday was aimed at accomplishing
that. But by Monday many seemed to be having second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz de Villegas said 50 cars had signed up for an escort from
the border with Montenegro Monday, but only 27 had showed up. A
group of Serbs also arrived at the border for a second convoy, but
in such small numbers that the Italians who control the sector said
they would not run a second convoy until more Serbs came, perhaps
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs in the convoy were decidedly polite. Many of them
flashed the victory sign used by Albanians returning to their homes
in the last weeks. Only one boy made the Serbian victory sign _ an
extended thumb, index and middle finger _ used by so many Serbs on
their way out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They did not go immediately to their houses, but to a car parts
factory occupied by NATO troops to wait while soldiers make sure
that it is safe for them to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Yugoslav president and Serbian leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, made a plea for Serbs from Kosovo to stay put or to move
back to their homes. Kosovo is the southern province of Serbia,
which is the larger of the two republics that make up Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It was not possible to interview the Serbs who returned Monday,
so it is hard to know whether Milosevic's statement played any part
in their decision to return.
</P>
<P>
   But Zlatko Arsovic, 41, a Serbian businessman who fled Pec in
fear two days ago, said he would never again listen to anything
Milosevic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't remind me of him,'' Arsovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Arsovic drove to the border between Montenegro and Kosovo Monday
afternoon to speak with Italian soldiers about how safe it was to
return to Pec, where he owns a mini-market and has plans to open a
small brewery. He said he still had not decided whether to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll be safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz de Villegas said the Serbs would be safe and would feel
secure enough to return in greater numbers in convoys in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we will be able to do it with more Serbs and less
forces,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
