A4292 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-PRINCIPALS-BOS &LR;      06-21 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PRINCIPALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEARTH OF PRINCIPALS SENDS SCHOOL OFFICIALS SCRAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As Massachusetts public school officials scramble to
find enough classroom teachers, they're discovering an even more
critical shortage in the school office: principals.
</P>
<P>
   Low pay, long hours and eroding authority in recent years has
meant scores of principal vacancies in schools next year. Boston
will have about 18 openings for principals in the coming school
year out of 129 schools.
</P>
<P>
   And the picture is repeated across the country as an estimated
30 to 35 percent of school administrators are expected to retire or
resign _ particularly in urban districts where job stress is high
and the pay can be only nominally better than a veteran teacher's
salary.
</P>
<P>
   The search for qualified applicants may go on for as long as
eight months as officials search for the perfect fit for a school.
Meanwhile, assistant principals pinch hit, retiring principals are
asked to stay or former principals in other jobs are asked to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out three times just to make sure I had quality,
quantity and the applicants were culturally diverse,'' said
Cambridge School Superintendent Bobbie D'Alessandro.
</P>
<P>
   It took her six months to attract 52 qualified applicants before
finally hiring Paul Evans from the Annenberg Institute at Brown
University to head the Cambridge Rindge and Latin High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go to the Internet, the New York Times,''
D'Alessandro said. ``There is significant accountability now with
principals. It's tough to get people to take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, under the 1993 education reform act, principals are now
not only responsible for the usual tasks of running the building
and dealing with parents, but they also must hire and fire staff,
redesign curriculum _ and even make sure the new state MCAS test is
boxed properly for scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal has to accept all the responsiblity and they
will be on the line again for underperforming schools,'' said Linda
Davin, an eighth-grade English teacher in Malden who got her
principal certification in 1990, but has never been a principal.
</P>
<P>
   She would love to run a school, Davin says _ if she could also
teach a class. She knows that's all but impossible.
</P>
<P>
   And as the state begins to grade schools based on MCAS scores,
many principals say they will ultimately be held accountable for
their students' scores. Principals, unlike teachers, do not have
strong unions so they can be hired and fired more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Many principals also say despite the added responsibilities,
their authority is eroded by school site councils and faculty votes
that sometimes override their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job has changed tremendously,'' said Robert Salamone,
retiring principal of the Emerson School, who has been in the
Boston Public School system for 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people involved in the decision-making is now a very wide
base,'' he said. ``Everybody wants to be involved in the
formulation of policy but the ultimately responsiblity rests in the
hands of the principals. There is a contradiction in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although reform efforts differ in other states, shortages are
just as pronounced, national educators say. A survey conducted last
year by the National Association of Elementary School Principals
and their secondary school counterpart found that half of 403
school districts had shortages for K-12 principals. Some national
statistics say school districts will see an additional 10 to 20
percent need for school administrators through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear more about this problem even more than teacher
shortages,'' said Michael Casserly, head of the Council of Great
City Schools, a national organization of urban school districts.
``Other than recruiting folks from inside the district, there isn't
a lot districts can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Public School Superintendent Thomas Payzant has tried to
lure principals and headmaster by raising their salaries _ some
$10,000 for high school chiefs. Still, the raise is merely
competitive with suburban districts where the job is often
perceived by candidates to be easier and less stressful.
</P>
<P>
   Since Payzant began his job four years ago, almost half of all
principals have resigned, retired or moved to other jobs. So he
also has embarked on an agressive ``grow your own'' policy of
training teachers for management positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real sanguine about being able to attract people to
relocate from other parts of the country,'' Payzant said. Unlike
other professions, schools usually do not pay moving costs and
salaries aren't competitive enough to entice someone to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll focus on growing our own and regional recruitment,''
Payzant said.
</P>
<P>
   The true competition, however, remains the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the classroom there are more rewards for teaching. You see
the light go on in a child's eye,'' Davin said. ``Often, these
days, I don't think principals see that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
