<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEW-BUFFY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUFFY' FINALE IS A REAL BLAST, DESPITE BEING POSTPONED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Spoilers of the finale of ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' are revealed in this story. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the season finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'':
</P>
<P>
   -- Faith lies mortally wounded in the Sunnydale hospital, having
been stabbed in the stomach by Buffy, then jumping from a building
onto a moving truck.
</P>
<P>
   -- Angel ``necks'' with Buffy so that he can survive a
potentially deadly wound of his own (and go on to star in his own
series this fall).
</P>
<P>
   -- Angel sucks so much of Buffy's blood that Buffy nearly dies.
</P>
<P>
   -- As the mayor addresses the graduating class of Sunnydale
High, he transforms into a serpent at least 60 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   -- Buffy, Angel, Xander, Cordelia, Willow and Oz lead the rest
of the Class of '99 in battle against the serpent and his vampire
bodyguards. Flame throwers, harpoons, arrows and axes are the
weapons of choice.
</P>
<P>
   -- Per usual, Buffy and her cohorts make prodigious use of the
show's signature fighting technique: fierce, acrobatic,
hand-to-hand, foot-to-head combat.
</P>
<P>
   -- The serpent, which appears to be all head and long neck,
literally devours one student and a recurring character.
</P>
<P>
   -- Several vampires get staked to death.
</P>
<P>
   -- In a quick but frightening scene, the serpent chases Buffy
through the school, the serpent's size causing considerable
destruction to the school, particularly doorways.
</P>
<P>
   -- Buffy leads the serpent to a room stocked with explosives.
The resulting kaboom destroys much of the school.
</P>
<P>
   That's entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   For this reviewer, yes, absolutely. In fact, I am such a fan of
this well-written, well-acted, well-produced show, it's my Emmy
pick for best drama series of the year. It is certainly the most
original broadcast network series on TV today.
</P>
<P>
   For other viewers, especially the uninitiated, the acts listed
above could suffice for Examples 1-10 of media violence run amok.
This, you might ask, is what our teen-agers are watching? Then no
wonder kids are shooting kids at school.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the folks at the WB were worried you might think that,
too, which is why they postponed the finale, moving it from May 25
to July 13. (An earlier episode that was also pulled has yet to be
rescheduled.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision to delay the air date had to do with many issues,
the foremost of which was being sensitive and respectful to the
communities and individuals devastated by recent acts of violence
in their local high schools,'' said WB CEO Jamie Kellner. ``The
timing of the finale also coincided with over 35,000 junior high,
high school and college graduation ceremonies being conducted
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   However, from this vantage point, Kellner and the WB made a
mistake with that decision. By pulling the episode, they
acknowledged, however slightly or inadvertently, that there might
be a relationship between their show and the school tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a show were a fantasy, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' is.
Buffy, after all, is a series about vampires, demons, slayers and
werewolves. There is violence, sure, but it's fantasy violence,
usually conducted using stakes, crosses and well-placed body blows.
Guns seldom, if ever, appear.
</P>
<P>
   With government looking at the media with an intensity not felt
in years, networks are backing down on shows they feel might be
sending a wrong, violent message. CBS in May rejected a pilot about
a New York mob family for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   The mob is real. ``Buffy'' is not. The mob uses guns. ``Buffy''
does not. The mob is about greed and corruption. ``Buffy'' is about
the fight between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   (``Buffy'' might qualify for censorship, but not for violence.
The show sometimes crosses the line where sex and language _
especially the double entendre _ is involved.)
</P>
<P>
   Kellner acknowledges that the move to postpone the show was
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received both praise and criticism for our decision,''
he said. ``If we erred, it was on the side of caution.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
