<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EU-COX     06-21 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspection question points to problems of authority
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The European Union's ``suggestion'' that a new round
of inspections be conducted on two Coca-Cola plants is the latest
sign of bureaucratic wrangling as member states lurch toward
uniform food safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian and French health officials will team up with commission
representatives to conduct the inspections of the plants in
Dunkirk, France, and Antwerp, Belgium. Coca-Cola said the plants
are the sources of soft drink contamination that have left some
Europeans ill.
</P>
<P>
   Commission spokesman Pietro Petrucci said the inspections will
begin in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a proposal, a suggestion,'' Ella Krucoff, spokeswoman
for the European Commission's delegation in Washington, said after
the inspections were announced at EC headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission would still lack authority to order an
embargo of Coke products following the inspections, but could
propose such a step to the European Union Council of Ministers. The
council, the supreme decision-making body made up of top-level
representatives from the 15 member states, would have authority to
order such an embargo, which would be enforced by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The council took such a step in 1996 when cattle in Britain were
found to have Mad Cow disease, Krucoff noted.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development in Coke's soft drink scare is another
indication of the overlapping and sometimes confusing authority
over food safety enforcement in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   C. Fred Bergsten, director of the Washington-based Institute for
International Economics, said the turn of events is understandable,
given the politically touchy nature of food safety and continuing
moves to impose uniform standards.
</P>
<P>
   Since its 1992 ``single market'' initiative, the EU has sought
to gain members' agreement a host of issues, health and safety
among them. Given that the 15 nations had formed a tariff-free
trading zone, the idea was to create a single market that would be
``the economic equivalent of the United States,'' Bergsten said.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been uneven. There is no European equivalent of
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, though the recent series of
food safety scares could prompt establishment of such an agency.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission currently has authority to set broad
policies and has done so through directives that have dealt with
everything from limits on antibiotic residues in milk to the color
of paint on slaughterhouse walls.
</P>
<P>
   But it's up to member states to enforce the directives, and
countries have done so with varying degrees of rigor.
</P>
<P>
   The commission Monday launched legal proceedings against Belgium
for violating EU rules by waiting a month before warning the agency
about food contaminated with cancer-causing dioxin. That scandal
brought down Belgium's government last week.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Mad Cow controversy, the European Commission
in 1997 established a separate agency to deal with ``consumer
policy and consumer health protection.'' The agency, known as
Directorate 24, seeks to ``develop a consumer policy and contribute
to consumer health protection and food safety at the level of the
European Union.'' Authority over food safety was previously
invested in the agriculture directorate-general, one of 30
executive departments.
</P>
<P>
   It is Directorate 24 that that made the initial recommendation
Friday that led to the inspections of Coke's plants announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
