<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HDEPOT-VILLAGER-COX     06-21 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-VILLAGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot's smaller creation focuses on goods for the home
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. _ If it's any consolation to hardware store
owners, they aren't the only ones in the cross hairs of Home
Depot's newest retail weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Villager's Hardware, opening here this week, makes a much
broader assault. In space about the size of a medium-sized grocery
store, Villager's Hardware takes a swipe at Wal-Mart, Target,
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. and any other retailer that sells home-related
goods.
</P>
<P>
   From toilet seats to tableware, Villager's Hardware has pulled
together everything Atlanta-based Home Depot thinks a consumer
would need for a small repair or home decor project. The new store,
the first of four test sites, attempts to fill in where Home Depot
left off with its warehouse stores and upscale Expo Design Centers,
said Bob Wittman, senior vice president of business development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot is home improvement, Expo is home design and
Villager's Hardware is home enhancement,'' Wittman said Monday
during a tour of the store. Villager's Hardware is going after a
$50 billion market that's currently served by hardware chains, mass
merchandisers and home centers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Home Depot announced the Villager's Hardware concept last
year, analysts and industry observers expected a format that would
compete directly with hardware chains such as True Value, Ace
Hardware and Sears Hardware. (Home Depot's Wittman is the former
chief operating officer of Orchard Supply Hardware, a large
California chain acquired by Sears in 1996.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Villager's Hardware seems to be going for the jugular in
some categories. Take fasteners, for example. Consumers can browse
6,152 types of fasteners with a computerized touch screen that
plays a video on the use and installation of each. There are more
than 600 light switchplates to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the 10 main departments, the idea behind the
merchandising was to go deep on so-called convenience items that
shoppers wouldn't want to shop for in a huge Home Depot warehouse
store. ``When people think of a convenience store, it usually means
a little bit of everything. The difference here is that we'll
dominate in selected areas,'' said Wittman, as he pointed to
several dozen hand clippers and pruners.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the 37,000 products at Villager's Hardware overlap
with Home Depot products, including tools, paint, window treatments
and lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are differences. Villager's Hardware carries fewer
power tools but more accessories. It sells shower heads and faucets
but no shower stalls or countertops. The product mix includes
cookware and even candleholders, and instead of the generic
fast-foot corner found in some Home Depot warehouse stores,
Villagers takes a softer approach with an in-store cafe that serves
muffins and bagels.
</P>
<P>
   While the traditional Home Depot orange is nowhere in sight,
expect Villager's to incorporate a good deal of the Home Depot
philosophy. About 10 percent of the new store's employees were
recruited from Home Depot stores, including the manager, Christine
Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   The second Villager's Hardware site will open later this year,
in Garwood, N.J. Two stores more stores will open next year in New
Jersey. If consumers like the new stores, they'll eventually come
to Atlanta, although there is no timetable.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to tell what impact Villager's Hardware could
have on other retailers. Home Depot was tight-lipped about the
store format and merchandise mix during the development phase, and
many industry observers weren't sure what to expect. Some analysts
are waiting to check out customers' reactions before giving their
verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   TruServ Corp., which counts itself the nation's biggest player
in hardware, is using Villager's Hardware as a motivational tool.
``We feel if Home Depot is moving into this marketplace, that means
there's a market to move into. This is a reinforcement that there's
a market out there for our business,'' said Don Hoye, president and
chief operating officer of TruServ, a Chicago-based cooperative of
more than 10,000 independent retailers.
</P>
<P>
   TruServ was formed two years ago when True Value Hardware,
ServiStar Hardware and Coast to Coast Hardware merged to better
compete with Home Depot and Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse.
(Ironically, Villager's Hardware takes the former site of Rickel
Home Centers, which closed in 1996 in part due to competition from
Home Depot.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the onslaught of the big boxes, local hardware stores
are plugging along. The number of hardware stores has dropped by
only 12 percent since Home Depot first opened in the late 1970s,
according to the National Retail Hardware Association. Nearly all
of the 21,400 hardware stores in the country are still
family-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the stores are still in business because they joined
co-ops such as TruServ or Ace Hardware Corp., which has more than
5,000 member stores. As part of the TruServ or Ace family, member
stores save money on merchandise because the co-op buys it in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   While there are still mom-and-pop hardware stores that look like
they're out of the 1950s and 1960s, most stores have expanded their
formats to compete with mass merchandisers, Hoye said. TruServ
wants its members to relocate or update stores every three to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older stores only fill the market for the most convenient
items,'' said Hoye, who noted that it's nearly impossible to make a
living by selling screws and masking tape. ``Those stores are in
their last decade of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
