<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-21 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAUDS SLOVENIA'S BREAK WITH MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ Visiting this former Yugoslav Republic
that was the first to break from President Slobodan Milosevic,
President Clinton called on Serbs Monday to follow this nation's
lead by rejecting the Serb leader's ``murderous rule'' and becoming
part of the ``new Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   While promising help to Serbia should it break from Milosevic,
he vowed not to spend ``a penny'' reconstructing its bridges that
were damaged during NATO's 78-bombing campaign, as long as the Serb
leader remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, peacekeepers clearing land mines, booby traps and
unexploded ordnance from a school in Kosovo set off an explosion
Monday that killed two Nepalese soldiers and two civilians _ the
first allied fatalities since the NATO-led force entered Kosovo on
June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from the 69th Gurkha Field Squadron _ riflemen from the
South Asian nation attached to the British peacekeeping force _
were helping clear ammunition in the village of Negrovce, 20 miles
west of Pristina, when a mine or booby trap went off, NATO said.
Two civilians also died and a third was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for the first time Monday, said he did not consider
repairing bridges part of the humanitarian aid that NATO has
promised to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of rebuilding the bridges so people can go to work, I
don't buy that,'' Clinton told reporters in Bonn, Germany after
attending a summit of the United States and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of their economic reconstruction, and I don't
think we should help _ not a bit, not a penny,'' he said. ``I think
their hospitals ought to be able to function...and people shouldn't
be cold in the winter if we can help that. That's basically where I
draw the line.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton began preparing Americans for the price of peace,
saying that reconstruction of the Balkan region will ``probably
cost more than most people think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I promise you, it will be a lot cheaper than a
continuation of the war would have been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the United States bore most of the cost of the bombing
campaign, Clinton said he believes that European nations should
provide most of the peacekeeping force and pay for most of the
reconstruction in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects European leaders to keep their word to do so
but warned that ``in the next few days, all of you will hear
various things about how much the immediate reconstruction of
Kosovo will cost, what we're looking at in terms of long-term
development. Then you will see both Europeans and Americans say we
will or won't pay this or that amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said representatives of the
European Union and World Bank were currently in Kosovo gathering
estimates on the ground of humanitarian and economic costs, a
process the official said was likely to take a few weeks to
complete. Some initial projections put the figure at $1.5
billion-$3 billion to reconstruct Kosovo and southeasern Europe,
but that has been bumped up to a range of $3 billion-$5 billion a
year, the official said,
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said a ``donor's conference'' would be
held next month, possibly in Bulgaria, to examine the region's
short-term needs. A second conference that would bring together
Clinton, other world leaders and those from the front-line states
in Yugsoslavia may take place possibly as soon as next month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he expects ``some difficulty'' in getting Congress
to approve humanitarian and economic aid for Kosovo and other
Balkans areas, but that he had begun to lay the groundwork to try
to convince them. ``I think that if we can make the case, that they
will be willing to support it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who will visit a refugee camp in Macedonia and
then troops involved in NATO's bombing campaign at the air force
base in Aviano, Italy, said he was troubled by reports of returning
Kosovar Albanians attacking Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was critical to get all of NATO's peacekeepers into
Kosovo to prevent such conflicts. ``I hope there will not be any
retaliation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair, the real story coming out of there is still the
staggering number of civilians that have been murdered,'' he
continued. ``It's going to take a lot of leadership and lot of
self-discipline for those who have come home not to retaliate.''
Early Monday, just hours after the last Serb soldiers left Kosovo,
negotiators from the NATO-led peacekeeping force reached a
settlement with the Kosovo Liberation Army that called on the
rebels to turn over their heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The document calls for a 90-day demilitarization program in
which the KLA forces will place all heavy weaponry -- including
machine guns and anti-aircraft weapons -- in designated ``storage
sites'' that were agreed upon by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Pistols and shotguns are not covered by the agreement. They also
agreed not to use explosives, and to clear minefields and
booby-traps within seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The six-page document also spelled out parameters of the KLA's
future role in participating in the governing Kosovo. It recognized
the KLA's ``aspiration'' to form an organized security force that
would be similar to the American National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   However, the agreement makes clear that for now KFOR will be
responsible for all security in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The text also addressed the KLA's hopes to transform itself from
a military force to a political organization.
</P>
<P>
   After signing the agreement, one of the KLA's top officials and
a prime minister of a shadow government in Kosovo, Hashim Thaci
spoke by telephone to President Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will now start the new battle in Kosovo for the return of
the refugees to Kosovo and to speed up the process for democratic
elections in Kosovo,'' Thaci said.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference at the KFOR press center in Pristina,
commander Lt. Col Mike Jackson said that the agreement and the
final withdrawal of the 40,000 Yugoslavia Army forces from Kosovo
marked a ``turning point'' in KFOR's mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now get on with the next task of maintaining peace and
security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, meanwhile, was trying to defuse the potentially
destabilizing problem of Serb civilians fleeing from Kosovo,
convinced the NATO-led troops wouldn't protect them from revenge
attacks by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   His government has given little attention to their plight in the
official news media, prevented them from setting up camps in
Serbian cities and tried to force them back in convoys led by
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   A convoy of 150 people headed back from the Serbian city of
Kragujevac and 50 vehicles left from Krusevac, Belgrade news media
reported Monday. After confiscating their guns and grenades at the
border, Italian peacekeepers escorted a 50-car column of Serbs from
Montenegro to Pec.
</P>
<P>
   But refugees continued to flee Kosovo, and the UN refugee agency
said the situation of the 50,000 or so Serbs there was ``a very
grim one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer Charlie Sennott contributed to this report from
Pristina. Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
