<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-FRENETTE-COX     06-21 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-FRENETTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firm sends trusted fix-it man to restore faith
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles S. Frenette, who virtually grew up in the
Coca-Cola family, is now charged with one of the biggest company
assignments in recent times _ the rehabilitation of the Coke name
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While a whole team is at work, headed by Chairman M. Douglas
Ivester, it is Frenette's responsibility to guide the message to
millions of European consumers that the company apologizes for
breakdowns in product quality and can be counted upon to work hard
to regain public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette, the grandson and son of Coca-Cola bottlers in upstate
New York, is now senior vice president and chief of marketing for
the huge soft drink company. It is his job to put the health scare
behind the company.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Frenette is singularly qualified for his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a passionate leader, a good strategist and a very
effective executive,'' said Carl Ware, president of the Coca-Cola
African Division. Frenette reported to Ware for two years when
Frenette successfully rejuvenated the southern Africa business
between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Like no other executive, Frenette's experience over the last 25
years has been broad, embodying operations jobs, such as his
management of the fountain business in the 1980s, later management
of Coca-Cola USA operations and southern Africa and most recently
as manager of marketing on a global basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frenette has the ability to understand completely the internal
operations of the company and develop a feel for the consumers,''
Ware said.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette's fine hand was seen in a noteworthy 12-paragraph open
letter ``to all the Belgian people,'' published in 15 newspapers
today . The letter, from Chairman Ivester, apologizes for the
product difficulties and for the tardiness of the apology.
</P>
<P>
   But it then goes on to capitalize on the strength and power of
the precious Coca-Cola brand by saying Belgians and consumers
around the world partake of Coke's ``moment of pleasure'' a billion
times a day, engendering trust.
</P>
<P>
   And that foundation of trust is the bond between the company and
the public, which was put at risk by the health scare, and which
the company pledges to restore.
</P>
<P>
   In the formulation of the message, analysts say, the company
opens the door to restored communications, a healing process that
frequently takes place quickly between leading brands and their
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette's assignment is one in a series of big assignments
passed along by his boss, Doug Ivester. For instance, he was called
on to straighten out problems in South Africa and environs, the
biggest market on the continent with more than 75 percent of the
local market share, and emerged with bottlers and consumers more
comfortable with Coca-Cola operations.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, when legendary marketer Sergio Zyman left the
company, Ivester tapped Frenette to fill the slot, quieting fears
and anxious feelings from Wall Street to Coke operations around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Ivester said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie's long experience as an operator, in both the
bottle/can and fountain arenas and domestically and
internationally, makes him the right person to lead marketing into
this new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Frenette's stock has been high for some time, and his name and
fortunes have been a source of hot speculation ever since debate
began over the succession of Roberto Goizueta, when the late
chairman moved past retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   His success at age 46 in the present crisis, which blew up as
rapidly as a summer storm, can do nothing but enhance his stature _
especially if the troubles grow calm in relatively short order.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
