<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERGERS-SHIPLEY-ART-2     06-21 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGERS-SHIPLEY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE'S SHIPLEY: A NICE GUY WHO FINISHED FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early one morning about 10 years ago, Jack Welch,
chief executive of General Electric Co., waited for an elevator in
the hallway outside his apartment in the Waldorf Towers in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Welch was feeling at the top of his game, bursting with
confidence. Then the elevator doors opened. Deflated, he stood face
to face with Walter Shipley, then head of Chemical Banking Corp.,
who at 6 feet 8 inches loomed a foot above him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of stuck my thumb in my mouth and said, `Gee, Walter,
thank you for adding to all of my insecurities,''' Welch recalled
in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although few might have agreed at the time, given Chemical's
financial woes, Welch accurately took Shipley's measure. Since that
encounter, Shipley has quietly pulled off two of the biggest
banking mergers in history, no mean feat in an industry that has
seen many careers and companies derailed by bungled mergers.
Chemical eventually became Chase Manhattan Corp. and is now one of
a handful of clear leaders in the rapidly changing financial
services business.
</P>
<P>
   And Shipley, who retired as Chase's chief executive on June 1
but will remain chairman for an undetermined time, now has some
advice for dealmeisters hoping to ride America's merger wave:
Slash-and-burn takeovers will come back to haunt you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people's philosophy is I win, you lose,'' he said. ``Our
philosophy is that the best is when both sides feel they've come
out winners.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Shipley, 63, is the least likely poster boy for
the merger boom that has reshaped financial services and other
major industries over the last decade. Deliberate in his speech,
modest and self-effacing to a fault and willing to share power,
Shipley has not enjoyed the renown of chief executives like
Citigroup's John Reed or Bank of America's Hugh McColl. But within
banking circles, and in the broader reaches of corporate America,
Shipley is widely admired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter has been able to do the deals he has because he has a
very contained ego,'' said Lawrence Bossidy, chairman of Allied
Signal Inc. ``But he's also been able to get people to work very
hard for him and get results. I don't think many other people in
his seat could have accomplished what he's accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, said executives who have worked closely
with Shipley, is that he is anything but Machiavellian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who is quietly capable, bright, sensitive, and a
very good guy right down to his toes,'' Welch said. ``I haven't had
a dealing with him in which he wasn't completely straight up.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, despite Shipley's achievements, not all of Chase's
holes have been plugged during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   William Harrison, Shipley's successor as chief executive,
inherits a bank that is not big enough or profitable enough to be
competitive in some key consumer businesses. On the corporate side,
Chase still needs to buy an equity underwriting business at some
point, though the bank said it feels no pressure to rush into a
deal. And some community activists have criticized Chase's lending
record in low-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shipley leaves a formidable legacy. In 1990, the stock
market collectively valued the three banks that now make up Chase _
Chemical, Chase and Manufacturers Hanover Corp. _ at about $4
billion. Today, the market values the company at more than $60
billion, testimony enough to how the bank's fortunes have changed
since the dog days of the late 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   During those years, Chemical was often derided as ``Comical.''
The bank, along with many of its competitors, suffered through a
nightmare era of shoddy lending that called into question the
survival of some of the country's largest banks, including Chemical
_ and reaffirmed the popular image of bankers as slow-moving
fumblers.
</P>
<P>
   Bad overseas loans, many of them arranged when Shipley oversaw
Chemical's international division, were not the bank's only
problem. Deals that Shipley cut as Chemical's chief executive in
the 1980s failed to meet expectations. Chemical's acquisition of
Texas Commerce Bancshares Inc. in 1987 was seen as too pricey at
the time and was undertaken shortly before Texas' high-flying oil
and real estate markets collapsed. Smaller deals, like Chemical's
takeover of Horizon Bancorp, a New Jersey bank, also misfired.
</P>
<P>
   But as the economy began to surge in the early 1990s, and as the
Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan, adjusted interest rates
to help banks recover, Shipley had the foresight and ability to
place Chemical in the forefront of the merger boom. Much of his
approach toward mergers was learned the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Wall Street investment banker who regularly
surrounded his wife and four children with visitors from overseas,
Shipley attended Williams College to study economics and political
science. Although he shot hoops well enough to be named captain of
the basketball team, off the court he was slipping. Bad grades
forced him to leave Williams in 1956, during his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a family that put tight controls on kids, and so
when I went away to school it was kaboom, I'm free,'' Shipley said.
``I'd gotten through high school with ease, without ever having to
really apply myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipley referred to his departure from Williams as a ``wake-up
call'' that made him determined to prove to his family and friends
that ``I was better than I had demonstrated up until that time.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined New York Trust Co. in 1956 and later earned his
undergraduate degree from New York University. In 1959, New York
Trust was bought by Chemical, and many of Shipley's colleagues were
shunted aside because they did not come from Chemical _ a
disturbing episode he vowed not to repeat if he ever orchestrated a
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely influential in my thinking about how to do a
merger,'' said Shipley, who rose through the ranks to become
Chemical's chief executive. ``If you simply work to create an
environment based on meritocracy as opposed to one based on what
your pedigree is, you create an environment where no one is
unintentionally demotivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Shipley believed, mergers should be as friendly as
possible. So when Chemical hitched up with Manufacturers Hanover in
1991, the deal that raised the curtain on the 1990s merger boom,
Shipley agreed to take a back seat at first as president, letting
John McGillicuddy of Manufacturers be chief executive. But he also
insisted that the best people from each bank be given other top
slots.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley succeeded McGillicuddy in 1994 and a year later effected
his second blockbuster deal, the $10 billion union with Chase,
which secured the new bank's place in the top tier.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chemical clearly took over Chase, Shipley adopted the
Chase name and went out of his way to make a place for Chase's
chief executive, Thomas Labrecque. He ultimately asserted that he
and Labrecque should be considered equals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create a new and better culture for a new and
better bank,'' Shipley said. ``Our idea is to create an environment
where no one feels self-conscious about themselves or where they
came from. I want them to feel self-conscious if their performance
is not up to standard.''
</P>
<P>
   For those employees further down the totem pole, thousands of
painful layoffs made the merger of Chase and Chemical far rockier.
But the union was marked by an effort to make the job losses as
humane as possible. The bank said that since the merger with Chase
was completed in 1996, enough new jobs have been added so that the
staff size has remained steady at about 72,000. Although plenty of
higher-paying jobs were undoubtedly replaced by lower-paying ones,
Chase also awarded stock options to remaining employees, options
now worth tens of thousands of dollars to many of them.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, for all the drawbacks to the merger, Chase has been
spared much of the prolonged turmoil of other banking mergers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. bought First Interstate
Corp. in 1996 in a hostile takeover, service disruptions and
declining morale ate into the combined bank's profits. That forced
Wells into a merger last year with Norwest Corp., ending Paul
Hazen's tenure as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, First Union Corp., despite having a reputation as one
of the most astute acquirers in banking and being led by a
well-regarded chief executive, Edward Cutchfield Jr., badly botched
its acquisition of Corestates Financial Corp. Profits have been
hurt, employee morale is low, and First Union is now regarded as a
potential takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, while posting impressive earnings recently, is still
trying to overcome the divisive turf disputes it has encountered
since Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc. merged last year. Other
banks that have simply sat out the merger boom, including venerated
titans like J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., now run the risk of being
marginalized because they are not large enough to compete.
</P>
<P>
   But Shipley has re-created Chase as a true financial powerhouse
with a global reach, particularly in areas like trading and
corporate finance. Despite lingering skepticism among some analysts
and investors about Chase's ability to maintain its robust
profitability and avoid financial pitfalls _ skepticism heightened
by the bank's role last year in the near-collapse of the Long-Term
Capital Management hedge fund and its heavy reliance on volatile
trading revenue _ the bank has repeatedly proved its mettle in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter understands people very well, and he has built a very
strong staff at that bank,'' said H. Rodgin Cohen, a lawyer
specializing in mergers and acquisitions with Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell.
``There's a very eclectic mix of people at Chase because Walter
looks at people in terms of their talent, not what bank they came
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, addressing hundreds of employees at an awards
ceremony at Chase's New York headquarters, Shipley realized it
would be the last time he appeared before the group as chief
executive. As he digressed and told the throng how proud he was to
have led them, he grew flustered. At that moment, the employees
rose and gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in the company feel good, and it wasn't always
that way,'' Shipley said, recalling the incident. ``I think people
in Chase today feel proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
