<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-REVIEW-SUMIJO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMI JO ENLIVENS RECITAL WITH FLAIR AND FINESSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reasons some likely singers haven't appeared in a Houston
Grand Opera production can be myriad and mysterious _ as
complicated as scheduling, or as simple as not fitting in with the
program of general director David Gockley.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Korean soprano Sumi Jo, who made her Houston
debut Sunday in a recital co-sponsored by HGO and the
Korean-American Association of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Jo, a graduate of the Saint Cecilia Academy in Rome, sang a
program of art songs, opera arias and Korean folk songs at the
Wortham Theater Center in downtown Houston. She is a singer of high
artistic sensitivity and skill who engrossed almost everyone
present.
</P>
<P>
   From the first notes of the opening song, Rossini's ``La
promessa'' (``The Promise''), Jo prompted me to muse on what makes
some singers so magnetic in performance _ and also, what pre-empts
them from having a greater career.
</P>
<P>
   Jo is a specialist in coloratura and bel canto repertoire, music
from Mozart through Bellini and Donizetti that invites an almost
promiscuous display of technical virtuosity in runs, leaps and high
notes.
</P>
<P>
   In her two announced arias, ``Una voce poco fa'' from Rossini's
``The Barber of Seville'' (normally a mezzo-soprano's forte) and
``Ah, fors' lui,'' the miniscene that ends Act 1 of Verdi's ``La
Traviata,'' Jo scurried every which way with the nonchalance of a
virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially for her success, she backed up display with
storytelling and emotion of exceptional depth and substance. The
audience indicated clearly that it sensed the skill in Jo's
performance of numerous folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the recital, William Vendice played the folk songs'
almost rococo piano accompaniments with exceptional grace and
beauty. He and Jo had the good fortune of using probably the best
piano heard publicly in the city, the Hamburg Steinway that the
chamber music society, Da Camera, keeps at the Cullen Theater.
</P>
<P>
   At least Sunday, Jo's voice had a tight though not pronounced
quiver. Yet, rather than distracting, that quality was part of the
distinctiveness of her voice. Jo was a master of subtly coloring
her sound to emphasize details of texts, while keeping the tone
consistently clear and focused.
</P>
<P>
   Those three elements _ technical virtuosity, interpretation and
vocal color _ were at the heart of Jo's allure as a recitalist.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there was a matter that is crucial in defining
the scope of a career: reliability. Rather consistently, Jo did not
land squarely in the center of the pitch of high notes that count _
the tops of phrases, the last two notes of the final cadence, and
so on.
</P>
<P>
   It is the singer who persuades the listener that there will be
no flaws, no questions about the voice at such moments, who will
have the stellar career and the most fiercely loyal fans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
