A4310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HBOC-FIRINGS-COX     06-21 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBOC-FIRINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HBOC: Troubled McKesson dismisses chairman
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ McKesson HBOC on Monday put the blame for its
accounting problems squarely on former executives of Atlanta-based
HBO &AMP; Co., firing Chairman Charlie McCall, who built HBO &AMP; Co. into
the U.S. leader in health care software.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson also fired four other executives of its health care
information technology unit _ the former HBO &AMP; Co., which was
acquired by McKesson earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the San Francisco-based company said that two McKesson
officers would resign. They are Mark Pulido, 46, chief executive
officer and president, and Chief Financial Officer Richard Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   The management shake-up won't affect the company's Alpharetta,
Ga.-based operations, said John Hammergren. He and David Mahoney
will be co-chief executive officers of McKesson HBOC.
</P>
<P>
   The purge came after a 14-hour board meeting Friday. It follows
a year-end audit in April that found $42 million in sales were
improperly recorded by HBO &AMP; Co. That news drove McKesson shares
down 50 percent in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The company said a month later that it would restate earnings,
and warned that HBO &AMP; Co. results may have to be restated for at
least two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson is conducting an audit of the accounting problems. But
the company revealed new details about those irregularities Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson spokesman Larry Kurtz said the HBO &AMP; Co. accounting
improprieties ``were outside of normal business practices, were
secretive and appeared to be intentionally kept from (McKesson's)
due-diligence team during the acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the four former HBO &AMP; Co. individuals were fired
``for cause,'' Kurtz said. The four are Albert Bergonzi, who was
president and chief executive of the information technology unit;
David Held, who was CFO and controller; Jay Lapine, who was general
counsel; and Michael Smeraski, who was head of enterprise sales.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's firing occurred because the problems ``happened on his
watch,'' Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting problems, Kurtz said, related to the practice of
contingency sales. Software contracts were signed for HBO &AMP; Co.
products, but the salesman and a hospital customer also would
create a ``side letter'' that stated a contingency for that sale,
such as a hospital board's approval, Kurtz said. Revenues were
nevertheless recorded at that point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kurtz said that sales can't be recognized until all
contingencies are satisfied. The side letters were kept secret even
from HBO &AMP; Co.'s auditors, Arthur Andersen, Kurtz added. The
improprieties date back at least one year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz would not comment on whether the accounting problems were
known by Jay Gilbertson, a former chief financial officer at HBO &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson joined Atlanta-based Internet company WebMD in
November. That company said last week that he was resigning.
Gilbertson denied the disclosure was related to the financial
problems at HBO &AMP; Co. From the start, the merger of McKesson, a $30
billion pharmaceutical distribution company, and HBO &AMP; Co. raised
questions about a lack of strategic fit. But McKesson officials
asserted the business combination would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we've changed is senior management,'' said Graham King,
who will be president of the information technology unit. ``We're
not changing strategy. McKesson HBOC remains absolutely committed
to the Atlanta market.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall, 55, could not be reached for comment Monday at his
Alpharetta office. Nor could the other four former HBO &AMP; Co.
executives be reached.
</P>
<P>
   McCall came to HBO &AMP; Co. from IBM in 1991. At the time, the
software and services company had high debt and a stock price stuck
in the single digits.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996 and 1997, HBO &AMP; Co. led all other Georgia public
companies in financial performance, as measured by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   McCall got much of the credit for the company's spurt. He owns
about 1.7 million shares of McKesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCall did a great job; he's a great leader,'' said Sheldon
Dorenfest of Sheldon Dorenfest and Associates, which analyzes the
health care information technology business. ``Everybody has their
strengths and weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet analyst Mike Krensavage of Brown Brothers Harriman noted,
``It's not every day that a company's board fires its chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Krensavage pointed out that in contrast to the firings, Pulido
and Hawkins, the McKesson holdovers, were allowed to resign. Both
McKesson and the former HBO &AMP; Co. remain the market leaders in
their niches, noted David Risinger of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
McKesson, he said, ``is clearing the slate to move the company
forward.'' McKesson shares fell $2.37 1/2 to close at $33.68 3/4 in
New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
