<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4311 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS &LR;      06-21 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MISTRESS ADMITS `BITTERNESS' IN CISNEROS AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Linda Medlar told a hushed courtroom Monday that
she secretly taped telephone talks with former Housing Secretary
Henry Cisneros out of fear he would end his financial support
following disclosure of their extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was jealously, it was bitterness,'' said Medlar, 50. ``He
was going to Washington. I wasn't doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And she admitted in the federal court hearing to altering the
tapes to remove self-incriminating threats to ``tell the press, the
president, anyone who would listen'' about Cisneros' arrangement
that funneled $250,000 into her bank accounts before and after his
nomination to head the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar, also known by her married name Linda Jones, was poised
in her retelling of the publicity that swirled through San Antonio
in 1988 when Cisneros made their affair public. And she recounted
the pain of later being rejected by him.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was not at Monday's hearing, but his lawyers are trying
to keep the tapes from being admitted as evidence when he goes on
trial on conspiracy charges after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the government has advised the court
already ... they were tampered with. End of story,'' Cisneros'
lawyer, Barry Simon, said of the recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The defense will have its turn with Medlar today during
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes form the crux of Independent Counsel David Barrett's
conspiracy case against Cisneros, who is charged with lying to the
FBI about the payments to Medlar to protect his Cabinet-level
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin rejected the defense's
motion to close the hearing, saying, ``My courtroom is open.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sporkin complained about the ``blizzard'' of last-minute
filings made on Cisneros' behalf to quash testimony and potential
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin, who has set a Sept. 7 trial date, is expected to rule
on a portion of the motions this week. The proceedings are expected
to last through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackowski, a prosecutor with Barrett's office, brought
Medlar to the stand to open the hearing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   She told the court she edited the tapes with a ``boom box'' to
erase embarrassing sexual material, conversations about third
parties and to remove threats she made to Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar said she edited the tapes shortly before she filed a
breach-of-contract lawsuit in 1994 accusing Cisneros of failing to
live up to a verbal agreement that gave her $4,000 per month in
support.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was later settled out of court for an undisclosed
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar said her lawyers in the civil lawsuit, Bruce Magness and
Floyd Holder of Lubbock, Texas, instructed her to erase the threats
``because it looks like extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she used the ``stop'' and ``pause'' buttons to edit the
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no scientific method to it,'' she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar appeared as part of an agreement to reduce the 3-1/2-year
sentence she received after pleading guilty to 28 counts of money
laundering, bank fraud and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Those charges also resulted from Barrett's $7 million
investigation into allegations that Cisneros lied to the FBI and
Internal Revenue Service about the $250,000 in ``hush money'' paid
to Medlar to protect his nomination to serve in President Clinton's
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged are John Rosales and Sylvia Arce-Garcia, aides who
moved from San Antonio to Washington to work for Cisneros at HUD.
Cisneros is a former mayor of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The three have pleaded not guilty and did not attend Monday's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar was brought here from Carswell Federal Medical Center in
Fort Worth to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers are asking for a psychological examination of
Medlar, who admitted Monday that she was hospitalized for an
overdose of sleeping pills when her affair with Cisneros was made
public.
</P>
<P>
   Medlar testified that when Cisneros moved to Washington for the
Cabinet post in 1992, advisers to President-elect Clinton warned
that the payments ``looked like hush money, blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just very insecure about everything,'' Medlar said. ``I
knew at that point in time Henry could care less about me. He was
focused on getting to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was HUD secretary from 1993 to 1996. He is now the
president of the Spanish-language, television network Univision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
