<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4314 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ALL IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Jewish Jerusalem used to just be divided between
secular and religious. Today the divide is so much more profound.
This city is now part Tehran, part Palo Alto. It has one foot in
cyberspace and the other in the Second Temple. Part of Jerusalem's
youth have Bill Gates as their role model and another part the
fiddler on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem's Har Hotzvim district, Israeli companies are
designing the next generation of the Internet. Indeed, outside of
Silicon Valley, Israel's Silicon Wadi is now the most dynamic
producer of Internet technologies _ notably Internet security
systems _ in the world. Yet a mile away from Har Hotzvim, in
Jerusalem's ultra-Orthodox Mea Shearim neighborhood, wall posters
now regularly appear warning residents not to have Internet-linked
computers in their homes because of the worlds it might open. These
ultra-Orthodox don't like windows or Windows.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the recent Israeli election was actually two revolts
at once. The first was a revolt by the secular fundamentalists _
the high priests of high tech, who are powering the dynamic,
computer side of the Israeli economy. They voted in droves for
ultra-secular parties, as a way of saying to the no-tech, religious
fundamentalists that the secularists were no longer going to let
their tax dollars, generated from 21st-century innovations, be used
to fund 18th-century ghetto schools, where kids are given no math,
science or computing skills that might prepare them for the future.
(Israel has no core curriculum, so you can teach whatever you want,
even in state-financed schools.)
</P>
<P>
   The counter-revolt was by the ultra-Orthodox and traditional
Sephardic Jews, who rallied in droves to the Shas party, making it
the third-largest in Israel, just behind Likud. Their message was:
``Once again we are being left behind. We have been here for three
generations, but new Russian immigrants, many of them not really
Jews, have come in with their education and skills and leapfrogged
over us. So we're voting Shas to express our rejection of the
yuppified, Internet-obsessed, secularizing elites, who want to keep
us down and assimilate Israel into global mush.''
</P>
<P>
   How Ehud Barak manages these twin revolts will be the domestic
drama in Israel. It will be worth watching because how modern,
liberal democracies deal with such fundamentalist social-protest
movements is now a worldwide challenge. We've seen three
strategies: The first was used by Bibi Netanyahu (and his Labor
predecessors), which was to try to buy off Shas by plying it with
state funds in return for political support. But that resulted in
Shas sending thousands of kids to their own schools, where they
learned virtually no skills and became wards of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The second is the Algerian model: Simply crush the
fundamentalists. The third model was tried (and failed) in Turkey:
Bring the fundamentalists into power, but set some real limits on
them to force them toward modernity. This is the model that Barak
will attempt by bringing Shas into his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   There is one reason for hope. Shas now has an internal
contradiction: It has been so successful at attracting non-Orthodox
Sephardic youth (Shas won 13 percent of the army vote!) that it
will have to be increasingly sensitive to their demands _ and these
non-Orthodox Sephardim want better schools and skills, so they can
compete with the Russians. So Shas itself needs to find a road to
modernity without losing its identity.
</P>
<P>
   The state has to help them do that. It should begin by changing
the law that says anyone who shuns army service for religious
reasons can't hold a job and must stay in yeshiva. Israel needs to
let those Shas youth, who for religious reasons don't want to serve
in the army, be able to work if they so choose. ``There is nothing
that says Orthodox people can't work with computers,'' says Shlomo
Kalish, the Orthodox founder of Jerusalem Global, one of
Jerusalem's most dynamic high-tech venture capital companies. ``In
fact, yeshiva graduates can make great programmers. They are used
to sitting for long hours working on logic problems. But the
government has to set them free to work, even if they choose not to
serve in the army.''
</P>
<P>
   My hope is that Barak's motto will be: ``Draft Shas into the
21st century, not the army.'' Nothing would do more to begin
healing Israel's internal divide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
