<HEADER>
A4317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARR-FORBES-COX     06-21 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR-FORBES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Barr throws support behind Forbes campaign
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Sherman
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) is supporting Steve Forbes's
presidential campaign, joining the magazine publisher's effort to
attract social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said Monday that he is endorsing Forbes because he is an
articulate conservative who ``addresses the
</P>
<P>
   issues _ he doesn't evade them.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said would take an active role in Forbes's campaign, to the
extent that his own congressional re-election campaign permits. He
cited Forbes's stance against gun control and his detailed proposal
to reform the Social Security system as reasons for his
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement is the first from an elected Republican in
Georgia, and reflects the view of some social conservatives that
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has been vague or too moderate on a
range of social issues.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of House Republicans and many Georgia elected
officials have lined up behind Bush. Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) is
a leader of the congressional contingent backing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, however, said of Bush, ``I don't know an awful lot about
him. I know more about Forbes because he actually addresses
issues....He has not seemed to go out of his way to avoid
addressing issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign hopes Barr's support will give the candidate
a boost in the contest to emerge as the conservative alternative to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Barr has been outspoken in his condemnation of gay marriages,
his efforts to impeach President Clinton and his staunch support
for gun rights, among other issues that galvanize the right wing of
the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we have to do is energize those folks who don't
believe the pace of reform and pace of change is going fast enough
and are concerned that George W. Bush is not the person who can do
that. Barr can help us do that,'' said Rusty Paul, Forbes's
Southern political director and former Georgia GOP chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Paul also dismissed the notion that Barr, as a lightning rod for
controversy in his 4 1/2 years in Congress, will turn off potential
supporters of the wealthy candidate, who spent more than $30
million of his own money on his 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is win-win for us. We've got resources. We need to make
this a two-man race,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   They make, in some respects, an unlikely pair. Barr, a
Midwesterner of modest means, often drops the final ``g'' from
words to sound more Southern. Forbes lives in New Jersey's
high-priced horse country and travels in his private jet.
</P>
<P>
   But each praised the other's forthright stands, regardless of
their popularity. In a statement, Forbes called Barr ``a principled
conservative.'' Barr returned the compliment, saying Forbes ``is
not afraid to tackle the tough issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is expected to announce the support of other prominent
Georgians next month.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, along with most other Georgians in Congress, backed Sen.
Phil Gramm of Texas for president in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nick Smith (R-Mich.) is the only other House member to have
announced his support for Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
