A4319 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIPPIES-COURT-KAN &LR;      06-21 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPPIES-COURT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TELLS FOREST SERVICE NOT TO CAST SHADOW OVER RAINBOW FAMILY
GATHERINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A federal judge in Springfield has decided
that America's hippies deserve a little less attention from the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In a 26-page ruling this month, Senior U.S. District Judge
Russell Clark barred the U.S. Forest Service from using checkpoints
and roadblocks to discourage illegal activity at the annual
gatherings of the Rainbow Family on public land.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Family is a large but loose collection of
counterculture enthusiasts who gather every summer at a national
forest.
</P>
<P>
   Their events draw people from throughout the country who pursue
spiritual rejuvenation, eat from rustic communal kitchens and shed
mainstream taboos about public nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Clark noted that a system of Forest Service checkpoints and
roadblocks at the Rainbow Family's 1996 gathering near Thomasville,
Mo. _ which drew 15,000 _ uncovered only four felony drug cases
worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Targeting a group _ any group _ and setting up a checkpoint in
close proximity to the site of their gathering in order to ferret
out a few lawbreakers cannot be done at the expense of trammeling
the rights of law-abiding citizens,'' Clark wrote. ``Basically
subjecting Rainbow Family members to a `shakedown' to achieve
ignominious results should strike fear into any citizen who values
their personal liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling stemmed from a lawsuit filed by Tracie Park, who
attended the 1996 gathering and contended that the Forest Service
had violated her Fourth Amendment protections against unreasonable
search and seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who now lives in Canada, could not be reached for comment.
Her lawyer in Kansas City, Fred Slough, said Clark's ruling was an
important addition to the law governing how police can use
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Supreme Court has allowed the use of roadblocks for
narrow purposes, such as to catch drunken drivers or illegal
aliens, it has not approved them for discouraging crime in general,
Slough said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement has taken this idea of using roadblocks to an
extreme,'' Slough said. ``This is a little finger in the dike
saying, `Hey, the courts have authorized roadblocks, but not
anytime you want them.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Steve Duncan of the Peace Conspiracy in Springfield
attended the 1996 gathering and was elated with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we wanted to hear!'' Duncan said Monday. Clark
``is a very insightful judge who upheld the Constitution and our
forefathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Davis, a Forest Service spokeswoman, deferred comment on
the ruling to the U.S. attorney's office in Kansas City, which
represented the agency. Davis noted, however, that the service was
not using checkpoints at this year's Rainbow Family gathering, now
getting under way at Little Bear Creek in Pennsylvania's Allegheny
National Forest. The service will depend on police patrols to
enforce traffic laws and federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Stephen Hill was traveling Monday and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
