<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-NYT &LR;      06-21 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ONE WEEKEND OF PLAY: WOMEN'S WORLD CUP WILL NOT BE A U.S.
CORONATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It is apparent after the opening weekend that the
Women's World Cup will be something more than a three-week
coronation for the United States, which must now face a Nigerian
team that has Patience and Mercy in its lineup but not in its
temperament.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds were record breaking, and the talent was impressively
deep and widespread in four weekend doubleheaders. The U.S.-Denmark
match drew 78,972 at Giants Stadium, the largest audience for a
women's sporting event in the United States. A doubleheader in San
Jose, Calif., drew 23,289 in a 26,000-seat stadium. Although
matches in Foxboro, Mass., (14,873) and Pasadena, Calif., (17,102)
drew fewer than 20,000 fans, the weekend total of 134,236 surpassed
the 112,000 for the entire 1995 Women's World Cup in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales have passed 500,000 _ including more than 60,000
for Thursday's United States-Nigeria match here at Soldier Field _
and organizers are hoping that the total might reach 600,000. That
would shatter the world record for a sporting event held for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm incredibly pleased,'' Marla Messing, president of the
tournament's organizing committee, said Monday from Los Angeles.
``Our mandate was to sell out, or have near sellouts, for the U.S.
games and to have respectable crowds at the other games. Having
14,000 at Foxboro for Ghana-Australia and Norway-Russia is
excellent. No one ever expected us to get out of single digits.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one game _ Brazil's 7-1 blowout of Mexico _ was not
competitive. There were no 0-0 ties, which non-soccer fans use as
an excuse to bash the sport. And, unlike the inaugural Women's
World Cup in 1991, the gap between the best and worst teams has
shrunk. Ghana is a 1,000-to-1 shot to win the tournament, but it
still managed a 1-1 tie with Australia, despite being down one
player for 65 minutes when Barikisu Tettey-Quao drew the
championship's first red card. Ghana's delighted fans responded by
handing the players $10 bills and $20 bills for good luck.
</P>
<P>
   The women's game has become increasingly sophisticated in terms
of goalkeeping, tactics and gamesmanship, such as melting the clock
and drawing fouls, which Italy smartly did to earn a 1-1 tie with
Germany, the 1995 runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping the field wouldn't be as good as it is,'' said
Tony DiCicco, the American coach.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea, a team in the Americans' group, remains as unknown
after the first weekend as it was before the tournament began. Its
star, Kim Kum Sil, was yanked early in Sunday's match against
Nigeria and proceeded to sit in front of the team bench, not
speaking a word to her coach or teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if her coach was mad at her or what,'' said
Lauren Gregg, the American assistant coach who scouted the match.
</P>
<P>
   While Kim sat and sulked, Nigeria won, 2-1, with a style that
resembled a videotape set on fast-forward. There is only one gear
for this engaging team: pedal to the metal. The Super Falcons, as
they are known, beat China, 4-3, in a World Cup tuneup on three
goals by Patience Avre and are flying with extreme confidence.
Mercy Akide showed no mercy against North Korea, rocketing home a
goal and collecting an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if we meet the Brazilian men's team, I believe in
attacking football,'' said Ismaila Mabo, Nigeria's coach.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said that he might make a lineup change to counter
Nigeria's speed, mentioning that Sara Whalen, Christie Pearce or
Shannon MacMillan may be called on to pass the baton in what could
be a 90-minute relay race. To keep the Nigerian fast break in
neutral, the Americans say they must extend their own possession of
the ball. They also expect to exploit the gaps created when the
Super Falcons swoop forward in a swarming but risky attack.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, which received hat tricks from Pretinha and Sissi, looms
for a mesmerizing samba in the quarterfinals or semifinals. Norway,
the defending champion, dominated Russia, 2-1, as forward Marianne
Pettersen deftly pulled balls out of the air and fired them on
goal. China, the Olympic silver medalist, struggled to win, 2-1,
over Sweden and will need its top scorer, Sun Wen, who shoots
precisely from distance, to recover fully from a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Most important for this World Cup to succeed in the public
imagination, the identifiable American star, Mia Hamm, brilliantly
calmed a nervous team with a goal and an assist, dismantling
Denmark and her reputation of not always playing big in big
tournaments. ``Her unique finesse and her instinct for the game
separate her from the crowd,'' said Leo Cuellar, the Mexican coach.
``Her quickness off the ball, her passing, dribbling, cutting, are
up to the level of high-class men in the world.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
