<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEEL-QUOTAS-575&AMP;ADD-     06-21 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEEL-QUOTAS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION HOPES TO AVOID SHOWDOWN ON STEEL QUOTAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Mont.)  (lh) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Senate poised to act Tuesday on a bill
that would sharply restrict the amount of imported steel in the
United States, the Clinton administration took a series of actions
Monday to convince Congress that it could protect the jobs of
American steelworkers with far less drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   The actions, announced by Commerce Secretary William Daley,
appeared intended to stem the number of Democrats in the Senate
planning to vote for the steel quota bill, which would roll exports
back to 1997 levels and has been pressed by steelworkers and steel
manufacturers. The bill, which the administration denounces as
protectionist, has already sailed through the House by a vote of
289-141.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest in a series of confrontations over trade policy
with his own party, President Clinton has promised to veto the
measure if it reaches his desk. But the White House desperately
wants to avoid that step because it would cause create enormous
political problems for Vice President Al Gore, who is trying to
court the votes of the United Steelworkers of America, the AFL-CIO
and voters in steelmaking states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is agony for Gore,'' one senior administration official
said, ``because it puts him in the position of angering supporters
who he needs very much. And the Republicans know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House argues _ and many trade experts agree _ that the
bill's import quotas would violate global trade treaties. There is
little doubt it would be struck down if challenged before the World
Trade Organization _ though the legal arguments could drag on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding a violation of America's trade commitments, however,
carried little sway with the House in March. And those arguments
may not overcome tremendous political pressure in the Senate.
Hundreds of steelworkers plan to raise the level of pressure on
Tuesday morning with a noisy arrival outside the Senate on a fleet
of Harley-Davidson motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a convergence of agendas here,'' said Gary Hubbard,
the spokesman for the United Steelworkers. ``This is an emergency
restraint measure to save high-wage jobs. And there are Republicans
who want to see Vice President Gore associated with the White House
position against this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley, in the midst of a day of lobbying against the bill on
Capitol Hill, announced Monday that as an alternative he was
beginning an investigation into whether steel from Japan, China,
Russia, Brazil, Indonesia, Thailand and other nations was being
``dumped'' in the United States at unfairly low prices. Four of
those nations received financial bailouts led by the United States
over the last two years and have been exporting aggressively _ in
part on the advice of the International Monetary Fund _ to get back
on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   But that export strategy has already begun to cost a relatively
modest number of jobs in smaller steelmaking factories nationwide.
Daley argued Monday that there were ways of dealing with that job
loss short of sending a message that the United States is closing
its doors to imports _ and opening the way to retaliation against
American goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of message would we send if we _ as the world's
leading economic power, riding the wave of an historic sustained
expansion and the one bright spot during the long months of
economic turmoil elsewhere in the world _ now send the message that
we intend to close our borders and violate international trading
rules?'' Daley asked Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As in many trade arguments, the White House has lost more
Democrats than Republicans. Chief among them is Sen. Jay
Rockefeller of West Virginia, whose state includes Weirton Steel
and other large steel manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing very well putting the votes together,''
Rockefeller said Monday afternoon. ``The White House is clearly
scared about how far this has come, because this has everything to
do with Gore's future.''
</P>
<P>
   But another Democratic senator, Max Baucus of Montana, said in
an interview that he had decided to vote against the measure
because ``it would encourage other countries to retaliate against
us, in agriculture and other areas.'' Baucus' state is a leading
exporter of farm goods, an easy target for retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has stayed silent on the issue, and his office declined
Monday to say what he thinks about the bill. But in private he is
trying to weave a line between the steel unions and the White
House, hoping to avoid a vote altogether.
</P>
<P>
   That was the strategy in announcing new dumping investigations
Monday, involving cold-rolled steel, which is used to make cars,
bicycles and household appliances. But it will take months before
the Commerce Department issues a final ruling on whether dumping is
taking place. In the far more lucrative area of hot-rolled steel,
the Commerce Department and the International Trade Commission just
approved punitive tariffs against Japan, South Korea and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The administration argues that its administrative actions have
worked and that steel imports are subsiding. But the unions and
steelmakers interpret the data very differently, and they have
demanded protection.
</P>
<P>
   It could turn out to be expensive protection. A study published
by the Institute for International Economics earlier this month
estimates that restricting steel imports will send prices up
significantly for cars, construction materials and other steel
products. The report, prepared by Gary Hufbauer and Erika Wada,
estimated that the bill would preserve the jobs of 1,700 workers at
an annual cost to consumers of $800,000 a worker.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would not ban all steel imports, but rather they would
limit them to 1997 levels. The administration argues that steel
imports are falling back to that level anyway. ``If that is the
case,'' said Rockefeller, ``then the penalties won't go into effect
and they have nothing to worry about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4342 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT22-2NDLEDE-C     06-21 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT22-2NDLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE: MICROSOFT'S INTENT HOLDS KEY TO VERDICT
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects ``indented'' to ``intended `` in lede.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the last witness in the Microsoft antitrust
trial took the stand Monday, the presiding judge said the verdict
could well turn on whether Microsoft intended to turn Windows into
a predatory monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's intended behavior would prove crucial in deciding
the landmark case, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
suggested to Richard Schmalensee, dean of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology business school and Microsoft's final
witness in the 21-week-long trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that's what courts do every day,'' Jackson told
Schmalensee, who had just testified that, when it comes to
measuring pricing policies, economists typically cannot
successfully measure corporate intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see for the court's purposes that intent might be
relevant,'' Jackson said, engaging Schmalensee in an unusually
spirited and prolonged dialogue over the basic issues in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we call a smoking gun,'' Jackson declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's rare, of course,'' Schmalensee shot back.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange took place during a courtroom discussion of
``predatory'' behavior that turned on whether Microsoft had crossed
the line between aggressive business tactics that are legal and
anticompetitive actions that are not.
</P>
<P>
   However Jackson should rule, his findings of fact and law will
serve as the basis of an expected appeal that's likely to be
ultimately decided by the U.S. Supreme Court. As a consequence,
both sides have sought to wind up the testimony phase of the trial
by presenting theirs strongest possible arguments.
</P>
<P>
   For Schmalensee, that meant showing Microsoft's business
practices had benefited consumers or, the very least, had caused
them no harm.
</P>
<P>
   Where Schmalensee saw Microsoft's decision to embed Internet
browser technology in the widely used Windows operating system as
the natural and normal flow continually seeking to improve the
product, David Boies, the Justice Department's lead lawyer, saw
matters quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking outside the courtroom, Boies said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did they intentionally set out to lose money? Did they make
these hundreds and hundreds of millions of dollars _ a billion
dollars perhaps _ (in designing the Internet Explorer browser) with
any business plan that they would very recover it other than
through the price of Windows?
</P>
<P>
   ``This witness,'' Boies concluded, ``came very, very close today
to saying that the only way they were going to recoup was through
the price of Windows. That's exactly what the government's theory
is. They can get their money back by maintaining their Windows
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies plans to cross-examine Schmalensee on this key issue
Wednesday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states contend that Microsoft
abused its Windows monopoly power for personal computers, thereby
stunting innovation and keeping prices high. Microsoft claims it
has done no wrong in a dynamic industry where vigorous competition
remains the watchword.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Microsoft lawyer Michael Lacovara noted that the judge
wanted to know whether it was correct to also view computer makers
as consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, it's not appropriate,'' Schmalensee said. The
economist said the hardware vendors are in reality distributors who
resell Windows, ``close to the way a Chevrolet dealer resells
Chevrolets.''
</P>
<P>
   Should a Cadillac dealer alter the engine or Cadillac name on
the cars it sells, it might well serve that particular dealer's
interest by making the outlet stand out from the pack. But,
Schmalensee added, ``it would weaken the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   So, as Schmalensee saw it, Microsoft was had every right to
impose strict conditions on the ``look and feel'' of the
Windows-loaded machines when they were shipped from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   `consequence, both sides have sought to wind up the testimony
phase of the trial by presenting theirs strongest possible
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   For Schmalensee, that meant showing Microsoft's business
practices had benefited consumers or, the very least, had caused
them no harm.
</P>
<P>
   Where Schmalensee saw Microsoft's decision to embed Internet
browser technology in the widely used Windows operating system as
the natural and normal flow continually seeking to improve the
product, David Boies, the Justice Department's lead lawyer, saw
matters quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking outside the courtroom, Boies said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did they intentionally set out to lose money? Did they make
these hundreds and hundreds of millions of dollars _ a billion
dollars perhaps _ (in designing the Internet Explorer browser) with
any business plan that they would very recover it other than
through the price of Windows?
</P>
<P>
   ``This witness,'' Boies concluded, ``came very, very close today
to saying that the only way they were going to recoup was through
the price of Windows. That's exactly what the government's theory
is. They can get their money back by maintaining their Windows
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies plans to cross-examine Schmalensee on this key issue
Wednesday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states contend that Microsoft
abused its Windows monopoly power for personal computers, thereby
stunting innovation and keeping prices high. Microsoft claims it
has done no wrong in a dynamic industry where vigorous competition
remains the watchword.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Microsoft lawyer Michael Lacovara noted that the judge
wanted to know whether it was correct to also view computer makers
as consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, it's not appropriate,'' Schmalensee said. The
economist said the hardware vendors are in reality distributors who
resell Windows, ``close to the way a Chevrolet dealer resells
Chevrolets.''
</P>
<P>
   Should a Cadillac dealer alter the engine or Cadillac name on
the cars it sells, it might well serve that particular dealer's
interest by making the outlet stand out from the pack. But,
Schmalensee added, ``it would weaken the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   So, as Schmalensee saw it, Microsoft was had every right to
impose strict conditions on the ``look and feel'' of the
Windows-loaded machines when they were shipped from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
