<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPLANTS-CANCER-BOS &LR;      06-21 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPLANTS-CANCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL CONCLUDES BREAST IMPLANTS DON'T CAUSE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KRISTIN VAUGHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silicone breast implants do not cause women to develop cancer,
immunologic disease or neurological problems, according to a report
released by a committee of the Institute of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   While the report did not find life-threatening illnesses related
to silicone breast inplants, it did find that implants can cause
``serious problems,'' including pain and disfigurement that require
surgery. It also reported that many women said they had not
received adequate information about possible problems with the
implants before receiving them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee heard directly and indirectly from many women
who suffer severe systemic illnesses that they firmly believe are
due to their silicone breast implants. Many of these women are
seriously ill, and the committee was moved by their suffering.
However, the committee is convinced that in most instances the
silicone breast implants are not causally related to these
illnesses since such illnesses appear to occur at about the same
frequency in women with silicone breast implants and in women
without implants,'' according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's findings are in line with several other studies
that also found no scientific evidence to substantiate a link
between the implants and the systemic disease claims made by women.
The institute, an arm of the National Academy of Sciences, also
found no evidence that breast-feeding women with implants pass
silicone to infants.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of whether implants make mammogram tests for
beast cancer more difficult, the report acknowledged the problem
but said that with special procedures radiologists can still
``ensure accurate readings.''
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning, once the largest manufacturer of the implants,
called the new report ``good news for women with implants.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is half-owned by Dow Chemical and half by
Corning and was forced into bankruptcy by the implant litigation,
does not have plans to alter its $3.2 billion settlement with women
who say the implants made them sick.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, claimants would be able to get $5,000 for
implant removal surgery and $20,000 for ruptured implants. The
leaking and rupturing of implants led to many of the complaints of
pain and disfigurement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached an agreement, we are committed and we would like to
resolve this once and for all and put it behind us,'' Doug
Schoettinger, a Dow Corning lawyer, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Schoettinger said women can opt out of the
settlement and pursue their own litigation. However, Schoettinger
said, ``fewer will probably pursue their own litigation as the
result of this'' report.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will go before bankruptcy court next week.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1.5 million and 1.8 million US women had silicone breast
implants by 1997, according to the report. The implants are now
banned except for experimental use.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of those women received implants for cosmetic
reasons, while 30 percent received them for breast reconstruction
after surgery for cancer, fibrocystic disease or other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Keithley Johnston of the Toxic Discovery Network, a
grass-roots consumer-protection group, called the report ``a step
backward.'' Johnston is a nurse who had silicone breast implants in
1984 and has been diagnosed with several medical problems,
including lupus and connective tissue ailments. Several friends who
had implants also have lupus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a sick person and you were a healthy person
before and the only common denominator is the implants,'' Johnston
said, ``then it is obvious that we can validate these women's
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marcia Angell, executive editor of the New England Journal
of Medicine, called the report ``thorough and . . . unequivocably
consistent with the findings of other panels.''
</P>
<P>
   Angell, who wrote ``Science on Trial'' about silicone breast
implants, was one of the first to state that there was no
scientific evidence to link implants to systemic illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientifically, we know everything that we have to know about
whether it causes disease. There has not been one credible study
that has found a connection, so maybe it will finally be put to
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Angell called the Dow Corning settlement an example of the
``legal system run amuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Knowles, a plaintiffs' attorney in Atlanta whose firm has
represented more than 900 silicone implant clients, said that he
does not consider the new report to be the ``last word'' about
implant safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that there is causation'' for disease, Knowles
said. ``Obviously every instance has not been caused by implants,
but at the end of the day, once we get over the manufacturers' hype
and their studies, then everyone will say it was real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
