<SLUG> BC-KOREA-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREANS FAIL TO SHOW UP FOR TALKS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ North Korean officials failed to turn up for
high-level talks with their South Korean counterparts here on
Monday, complaining that the South had failed to meet a Sunday
deadline to deliver 22,000 tons of fertilizer to North Korea, South
Korean officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were the first government-to-government discussions in
more than a year. The countries planned to discuss food aid to the
North, which has had severe food shortages for the last five years,
and the re-unification of families separated by the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans said they would start the talks after the
fertilizer arrives, the South Korean officials said, though no time
has been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The ship carrying the fertilizer was delayed by rain and was
expected to reach the North Korean port of Nampo at 2 a.m. on
Tuesday. North Korean officials were previously informed of the
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very regrettable that they are using the fertilizer aid
to delay the talks,'' Yang Young-shik, the South Korean vice
minister of unification, said at a news conference here Monday
afternoon. The 22,000 tons of fertilizer were the last installment
of 100,000 tons the South pledged to send to the North.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean delegation said it plans to stay in Beijing.
``We eagerly hope that talks can start tomorrow,'' said Wi
Keyei-chul, a spokesman for the South Korean Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The delay was not unexpected. Relations between the countries,
which are never simple, have worsened in the last week after a
skirmish in the Yellow Sea last Tuesday resulted in the sinking of
a North Korean torpedo boat and the death of at least 20 North
Korean sailors.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean delegation to the talks, which is already in
Beijing, did not comment on the postponement. But the North Korean
Embassy here called a news conference to berate South Korea for its
``reckless provocation'' in sending warships into what is said were
the North's territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
   The North does not recognize the ``northern limit line'' in the
Yellow Sea, which separates the two countries. Each side accused
the other of firing first last week after North Korean vessels
repeatedly crossed the line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
