<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DETAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURIST DETAINED IN NORTH KOREA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ North Korea has detained a young South Korean tourist,
South Korean officials said on Monday. They said that the tourist,
34-year-old Min Yung-mi, was detained on Sunday while hiking with a
group in the mountains in the North. South Korean officials said
they hoped Ms. Min would be released on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The detention is likely to add to the mistrust between the two
sides at a time when relations have suddenly taken a turn for the
worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the environment of mutual hostility, the tour groups to the
North had been a rare example of cooperation. Begun late last year,
they have brought more than 50,000 South Koreans to the scenic
Mount Kumgang region in the North.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Corp., South Korea's largest conglomerate, operates the
tour groups, and it said on Monday that it was also talking in
Beijing with its North Korean business partners about the
detention.
</P>
<P>
   The tours have been a centerpiece of the ``sunshine'' policy of
engagement vigorously pursued by President Kim Dae-jung of South
Korea. In return for the right to operate the tours, Hyundai has
paid $125 million in cash to North Korea this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Min, whose 6-year-old son was with her on the tour, was
detained by North Korean authorities after she struck up a
conversation with one of the officials she met on the tour. Lee
Bo-yong, a spokesman at South Korea's Unification Ministry, said
that Ms. Min had told a North Korean tour monitor that South Korean
television programs described the comfortable life style of North
Korean defectors to the south. North Korean officials then detained
her, accusing Ms. Min of trying to persuade North Koreans to
defect.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean government delayed the departure of a cruise
ship that was to leave on Monday for North Korea. Moreover, the
vessel that Ms. Min traveled on did not return on Monday to South
Korea as scheduled, mainly on the hope that Ms. Min might be
released on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai's tours leave South Korea virtually every day. In the
six months that the tours have been operating, this is the first
time a South Korean tourist has been detained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
