<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDER OF KLA PLANS FOR FUTURE ARMY EVEN AS HE DISARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The chief of general staff of the Kosovo
Liberation Army already has the formation of a future army for
Kosovo planned out, even as he is preparing to disarm and
demobilize his guerrilla force.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel official, Gen. Agim Ceku, arrived on Monday in
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, dressed in his military fatigues, the
red and yellow rebel insignia on his cap and sleeve, to mark the
signing of the agreement to demilitarize.
</P>
<P>
   Ceku, 38, has emerged in the last three months as the leading
military figure of the Albanian separatist force in Kosovo. He is
the man who negotiated the bulk of the agreement on
demilitarization, and who will be responsible for carrying it out
with Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, the commander of the Kosovo
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, he said he had no doubt that Kosovo
would need its own army for its future defense, and he mapped out
his vision for such a force in detail.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would seek to form ``a defensive army from a small
number of soldiers, respecting our economic resources, the level of
danger we face and the demographics of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that under his plan, a Kosovo army would have a small
active core of professional soldiers and a larger component of
reserves. He said he also envisioned an ``intervention unit,''
similar to the National Guard in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sees it, such a fighting force would be formed within the
contours of collective security in Europe, since Kosovo would want
to take part in Western European alliances, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will respect all the standards of NATO, at the same time
staying loyal to our national and historical traditions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ceku, a Kosovo Albanian, got his military training in the
Yugoslav army under the former communist government. In 1991, as
several of the republics that had been part of Yugoslavia declared
their independence, he joined the Croatian army and was rapidly
promoted to the rank of general. He resigned his commission there
to return, in March, to fight against Serbian forces with the
Kosovo rebels. He was appointed their chief-of-staff in April.
</P>
<P>
   The general said the decision to demilitarize had been a very
hard one for the rebels. He said that ``one of the biggest
victories of the war was that for the first time'' Kosovo Albanians
had their own fighting force, adding: ``And every decision that is
made to lower the standing of the army is really hard. But all the
soldiers of the KLA and the people of Kosovo, we all want to be
part of the democratic world, and every decision of the
international community is an obligation for us too, even when it
is not in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   The commanders and their men would comply with the agreement to
disarm, he said, because the international community had guaranteed
to take into consideration the rebels' experience and role in the
conflict when recruiting people for the new institutions being
established in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim Thaci, the rebels' political leader, who signed the
demilitarization agreement, said on Monday that the general was
``respected by all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His association with the KLA was from the very start of its
organization in the early 1990s, and he was instrumental in
structuring the KLA into a more professional force,'' Thaci said in
a separate interview on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A Western official who had seen Ceku in his mountain
headquarters said rebel commanders had appeared deferential to the
general.
</P>
<P>
   The general defended his headquarters over the last three months
from a major Serbian offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci appeared confident that the order to demilitarize would be
obeyed. ``A soldier did not get his weapon to keep in his hand or
in his house,'' he said. ``He got it to fight to liberate Kosovo
from Serbia. That objective is realized, and our objective now is
to restructure and integrate ourselves into society.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceku said the rebel force had swelled to 20,000 during the last
month of the conflict. Until March, when the NATO bombing began, he
said, the force had consisted of 12,000 fighters and 4,000 to 5,000
unarmed volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 rebels were killed and 4,000 wounded during the 15
months the rebels fought Yugoslav troops, he said. About 100 are
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The general contended that the Serbian offensive had
strengthened the rebel group. ``It drew more people to our ranks,
and it gave us new military experience,'' he said, ``and by
surviving the offensive we gained the faith of the people. Without
the bombing, the Albanian people would have suffered much more.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia had planned an ethnic purge of Kosovo Albanians whether
NATO had begun its bombing campaign or not.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would move down to Pristina from his mountain
hideout. A headquarters has already been selected in the wealthy
suburb of Kojlovica, the gate guarded by uniformed soldiers bearing
no weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
