<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA GAINS IN ALL-STAR BALLOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With a week to go before the polls close, Red Sox
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra closed the gap again on Derek Jeter of
the Yankees in the latest balloting for the American League
All-Star team. But apparently for the fans in Cleveland, in a
perfect world every AL starter would be an Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Four Cleveland players lead in the voting for their positions:
first baseman Jim Thome, second baseman Roberto Alomar, and
outfielders Manny Ramirez and Kenny Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Indians rank no lower than runner-up at their
positions, including ex-Sox outfielder Wilfredo Cordero, who is
second in the voting for DH despite being on the 60-day disabled
list with a fractured wrist. Sandy Alomar is second at catcher,
Travis Fryman is second at third base, and David Justice is fourth
among the outfielders, trailing the three starters.
</P>
<P>
   Indians shortstop Omar Vizquel, meanwhile, is third at his
position, trailing Jeter of the Yankees by just over 55,000 votes.
Garciaparra, who last week was nearly 15,000 votes behind Jeter, is
now 7,344 votes behind Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland showing can be attributed to several factors. The
Indians have drawn nearly 1.6 million fans, most in the majors.
They have the best record in baseball (45-21, .682), and their
lineup is stocked with former All-Stars at every position. Finally,
their fans are encouraged to vote early and often.
</P>
</TEXT>
