<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISON-TURNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner rounds up the herd
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ted Turner is merging the Atlanta-based marketing arm
of his bison-raising operations into a national industry
cooperative based in North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal, which will fold Turner's U.S. Bison Co. into
the North American Bison Cooperative, were not disclosed.
Specifically, U.S. Bison will merge into North American
Provisioner, the newly formed marketing arm of the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the North American Bison Cooperative established North
American Provisioner, we realized the best thing for both companies
was to create a strong, unified alliance,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The merger doesn't mark Turner's exit from the bison business.
He will continue raising bison on his many ranches across the West
and selling them to the cooperative. The cooperative will then
handle the slaughtering, marketing and sale of the bison.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Turner's bison operations continue to grow. He has more
than 15,000 head of bison now, making him one of the largest single
bison ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   But Turner's son, Teddy Jr., is leaving the business. He had
been chairman of U.S. Bison, but it will no longer exist as a
separate company. The younger Turner will remain involved with his
other companies, which include e.TV Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. Bison will no longer exist as a separate company, its
name will live on in the Southeast. North American Bison will
continue to market its meat under the U.S. Bison brand name.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, North American Bison will retain U.S. Bison's
current president, Hansell Roddenbery, as its sales representative
in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Roddenbery has been on a roll recently. In a significant coup,
he announced that Publix supermarkets would carry bison hamburger
and hot dogs at its 64 locations in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public demand for bison has been steadily growing,'' says
Roddenbery.
</P>
<P>
   He has also signed deals with various restaurants in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
