<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARTSFIELD-SAFE-COX     06-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARTSFIELD-SAFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hartsfield airport sees rise in theft
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world's busiest passenger airport is trying to fix
a larceny problem.
</P>
<P>
   With 73.5 million passengers coming and going in a year's time,
it may have been inevitable that Hartsfield International Airport
would run into a bad patch of thievery. Larceny at the airport is
up 26 percent for the first four months of this year, compared to
1998, according to Atlanta police.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Ben DeCosta said he has taken steps to fight the
thefts. More police now patrol the terminal, and a special unit of
16 bicycle-mounted customer service representatives routinely scour
the parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves are particularly fond of luggage, cell phones and laptop
computers left unattended on the concourses or on car seats in
parking lots. They also move through restrooms and make off with
jewelry and other valuables lying on counters, Atlanta police
spokesman John Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta is awaiting figures from later in the year that he
expects will show a slowing of the crime increase. ``The police are
doing a fine job at the airport, and they should know it's
appreciated,'' the airport chief said.
</P>
<P>
   But stopping crime has to start with attentive passengers and
visitors, he cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are leaving valuables in plain view,'' DeCosta said.
``These are crimes of opportunity. If we can change (people's)
behavior, then we can get a handle on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Larceny and auto theft accounted for all but seven of 529
incidents reported to police during the first four months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Violent crime _ homicides, rape and robbery _ is rare at the
airport. No homicides have been reported in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Total crime numbers rose 45 percent from 1997 to 1998. The
biggest leap was in car thefts, which doubled from 107 to 215 in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta has requested a further analysis of the reports to
determine whether a theft ring has developed or if other factors
are at work. For example, he said, thieves may be targeting rental
car agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the volume of passengers _ and not counting 43,000
employees and untold thousands of non-passengers going through the
airport _ the chances of becoming a crime statistic at Hartsfield
are small, airport officials conclude.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when 73.5 million passengers made Hartsfield the
busiest passenger airport in the world, the statistics work out to
one crime for every 47,700 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DeCosta said the surge in larceny needs attention and is
a customer service problem. He attributes the problem in part to
the soaring volume of people passing through: Hartsfield had 9
percent more passengers this year.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other suspects, the airport's general manager
said. The rise in theft comes from several sources drawn by the
same circumstance _ they have plenty of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Arrest records indicate professional criminals and some homeless
people who camp out at Hartsfield know they can find unattended
valuables in the terminal and concourses, DeCosta said.
</P>
<P>
   Sting operations _ where airport police have left decoy items
unattended _ have shown that employees at the airport make up a
significant percentage of the thieves, DeCosta said. Six of the 10
arrested in the sting were employees, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Police are increasing their presence throughout the airport,
including four officers on bicycles who can be seen in the
terminal. The 150 police officers at Hartsfield have been working
longer shifts on overtime to increase their visibility. Undercover
police also are at work, said DeCosta.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Chicago O'Hare International Airport said an
increase in the number of police kiosks there have contributed to
an 11 percent drop in property crimes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare, which handled 72.5 million passengers last year,
experienced a drop in auto thefts from 125 in 1997 to 80 in 1998,
said Monique Bond of Chicago's Department of Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   The exception to the good news at O'Hare is a wave of crimes
taking place in restrooms, where theft is up 99 percent over the
two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be a crime trend,'' said Bond. ``Thieves understand
that it's a vulnerable point. You can't put a police officer in
every washroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with crime is not new for Hartsfield's DeCosta. He was
previously the head of Newark International Airport where, he
recalled, criminals were more resourceful than in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Newark had a problem with thieves going into women's rest rooms,
reaching over stall doors and yanking pocketbooks from the hooks
inside the doors. The thieves moved fast, so they just reached over
any closed door and gambled that they'd luck onto a purse.
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta said the problem was solved by the airport installing a
little cover over the top of the hook.Gary Hendricks writes for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. John McCosh contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
