u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-RDP-400(2TAKES     06-21 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-400(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGES LOSE BATTLE AGAINST A COUNTY TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For more than 10 years, two U.S. district judges in
Birmingham, Ala., have fought against paying an occupational
license tax imposed by Jefferson County on the earnings of all
public officials and many other people who work in the county.
</P>
<P>
   The two judges might have expected to find a sympathetic ear at
the Supreme Court. But Monday, by a vote of 7-2, the court ruled
for the county and held that because the tax did not single out
federal employees for discriminatory treatment, it was permissible.
</P>
<P>
   The judges, William M. Acker Jr. and U.W. Clemon, had invoked a
doctrine known as intergovernmental tax immunity to argue that the
tax could not lawfully be applied to them. The 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals, in Atlanta, agreed in a decision last year,
holding that Jefferson County was improperly trying to impose a tax
on the privilege of performing the federal judicial function.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing that decision Monday in an opinion by Justice Ruth
Bader Ginsburg, the court said the tax was just an income tax under
a different name. Congress in 1939, under the Public Salary Tax
Act, made federal employees subject to ordinary, nondiscriminatory
state and local income taxes. Lacking authority from the Alabama
Legislature to impose an income tax, Jefferson County in 1987
enacted the occupational license tax instead, levied at the rate of
0.5 percent of a person's gross earnings within the county. For the
judges, who earn $136,700 a year, the tax amounts to about $700
annually.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion Monday, Jefferson County vs. Acker, No. 98-10,
Ginsburg said the important aspect of the challenged tax was not
its form, but its function. While it looked like an effort to
license or regulate the judges, she said, ``in practice, Jefferson
County's license tax serves a revenue-raising, not a regulatory,
purpose.'' She said the county ``neither issues licenses to
taxpayers, nor in any way regulates them in the performance of
their duties.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Stephen G. Breyer said, ``The
language, structure, and purpose of the ordinance indicate that it
imposes a fee upon the performance or work, not a tax upon
income.'' His opinion was joined by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor,
while Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices John Paul
Stevens, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, and
Clarence Thomas voted to uphold the tax.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the court pressed to finish its term by the end of the week,
there were these other developments Monday.
</P>
<P>
   INDECENCY ON CABLE: Returning to an issue it has struggled with
in the past, the court agreed to decide whether the latest federal
effort to regulate sexually explicit programming on cable
television was constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The case, an appeal by the Clinton administration, concerns a
technological problem that permits viewers who have not paid for a
premium cable channel to nonetheless receive a portion of the
channel's video or audio signal through what is known as ``signal
bleed.'' Signal bleed is the result of an effort that is only
partly successful at scrambling a station's signal. As sexually
explicit premium or pay-per-view cable channels proliferated in the
early 1990s, Congress received complaints that some of the
programming was available to children in homes that did not want to
receive it.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a section of the Telecommunications Act of 1996
requiring sexually explicit channels to provide fully effective
blocking or, if they could not do so, to limit their programming to
the late evening so children would not be exposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling last year in a lawsuit brought by the Playboy
Entertainment Group, which operates the Playboy Television and
AdulTVision networks, a special three-judge U.S. District Court
panel in Wilmington, Del., declared the provision unconstitutional.
The court said that because of the free speech interests involved,
Congress was obliged to choose the ``least restrictive
alternative'' to deal with the problem, such as requiring cable
system operators to make blocking devices available on request.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal, U.S. vs. Playboy Entertainment, No. 98-1682, the
administration told that Supreme Court that the district court's
analysis was ``deeply flawed'' and that its proposed solution,
depending on parental action, would not be effective in protecting
children. The case raises the deeper question of what type of First
Amendment analysis applies to cable television, a question the
court has yet to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   KIRYAS JOEL RETURNS: The court granted a stay of the latest
ruling in the long-running case of the Kiryas Joel School District
in Orange County, N.Y., effectively enabling the district to
continue in operation while the justices consider the case further.
</P>
<P>
   New York's highest court ruled last month that the state
Legislature's most recent attempt to overcome the constitutional
problems involved in creating a special school district for the
benefit of Kiryas Joel's Satmar Hasidim had failed. As in earlier
versions _ the Supreme Court struck one down in 1994 _ the district
still amounted to ``preferring one religion over others,'' the New
York Court of Appeals said. The school district serves the
religious enclave's disabled children; the other Satmar children
are educated in private religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The action Monday, sought by Gov. George Pataki as well as by
the state's Board of Regents, the Kiryas Joel school board, and the
school board of the surrounding Monroe-Woodbury Central School
District, allows the school district to operate at least until the
fall, when the court will decide whether to hear the appeal, Pataki
vs. Grumet, No. 98-1932. If the justices do agree to hear the case,
then the stay will last until they decide it, perhaps a year from
now.
</P>
<P>
   BARGAIN, NOT BRIBE: Without comment, the court let stand a
ruling that offering witnesses leniency in exchange for their
testimony at a criminal trial does not violate the federal bribery
law.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a federal appeals court panel's decision that such
everyday deal-making was the equivalent of an illegal bribe sent
shockwaves through the criminal justice system. The 10th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in Denver, quickly vacated its panel's
opinion and took the case up before the entire court, ruling 9-3 in
January that the panel had been wrong. The appeal before the court
Monday was Singleton vs. U.S., No. 98-8758.
</P>
<P>
   CAR SEARCH: Ruling summarily, without hearing arguments in the
case, the court overturned a ruling by a Maryland appeals court
that state law enforcement officials should have obtained a warrant
before searching a car that they believed was transporting drugs
from New York. Fourteen hours elapsed between the time the
officials received a credible tip about the car and its mission and
the time when they spotted it in St. Mary's County, Md. The
warrantless search revealed cocaine in a duffel bag in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland Court of Special Appeals ruled that the search was
invalid because the police had not demonstrated that exigent
circumstances precluded getting a warrant. In an unsigned opinion
Monday, the Supreme Court said that the general exception from the
warrant requirement that the court's precedents have given
automobile searches does not require such a separate finding,
because of the ready mobility of cars. Because there was probable
cause to search the car, the search was valid even without a
warrant, the unsigned opinion said.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer and Stevens, while agreeing with the legal analysis of
the case, Maryland vs. Dyson, No. 98-1062, said the court should
not have decided the case without finding a lawyer to represent the
defendant, Kevin D. Dyson. His lawyer had declined to file a brief
in response to Maryland's appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
