<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIZENS-UST-BOS &LR;      06-21 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIZENS-UST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS FINANCIAL-UST CORP. SET $1.4B ACQUISITION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Citizens Financial Group Inc. agreed Monday to acquire
UST Corp. for $1.4 billion in cash, the latest merger to reshape
New England banking's rapidly changing landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction comes only three months after the region's
largest banks, Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp.,
announced their powerhouse combination.
</P>
<P>
   In buying one of the last local banks available, Citizens, the
number three player in the area, is staking ground in an industry
where consolidation is creating new competitors and dismantling old
ones.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, the birthplace of banking more than two
centuries ago, the winnowing has broadly left one giant institution
and scores of savings and loans. Medium-sized companies such as
Citizens, which will be the area's second largest bank after Fleet
and BankBoston merge, are increasingly rare, and may become portals
for big national players seeking to expand into one of banking's
most lucrative markets.
</P>
<P>
   But by acquiring UST only one month after snapping up State
Street Corp.'s commercial lending business, Providence-based
Citizens has almost instantly transformed itself from an
old-fashioned savings bank into a full-fledged financial
institution that aims to compete with players big and small.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transaction firmly establishes Citizens as the second
largest bank in New England,'' said Lawrence K. Fish, Citizens'
chief executive, at a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A self-styled ``super community'' institution with $22.1 billion
in assets, Citizens has grown this decade by acquiring hometown
institutions throughout New England and touting personalized
service.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based UST, with $5.9 billion in assets, has carved out
its own niche, providing loans to smaller businesses in eastern
Massachusetts and cut-price retail banking to ordinary depositers.
</P>
<P>
   With USTrust, as UST's bank is known, Citizens will have $28
billion in assets. (By contrast, the combined Fleet-BankBoston,
which will be the nation's eighth largest bank, will have over $160
billion). The next largest bank after Citizens is People's Heritage
Financial Group Inc. of Maine, with $14.5 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   In the increasingly competitive world of financial services,
Monday's deal has several important implications.
</P>
<P>
   It raises questions over how so-called community-style banks can
maintain the personalized service they pride themselves on while
growing bigger. It leaves observers wondering whether the new
Citizens will not seek to grow through further acquisitions. And it
leaves some industry analysts thinking a heftier Citizens will
become a takeover target for bigger banks outside the region.
</P>
<P>
   With UST, Citizens adds 300,000 new customers to its 1.2
million, and boosts its branches by nearly one-third, to 370. The
company operates as Citizens Bank in Massachusetts, Rhode Island,
Connecticut, and New Hampshire,
</P>
<P>
   More important, Citizens pumps up its nascent loan portfolio by
$4.4 billion, to $16.9 billion. The increase could give the bank
more leverage if it decides to make a play for some of
Fleet-BankBoston's cast-off assets, which are now being sold and
for which regulators want a strong lender as owner.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Citizens and UST said the $16 billion
Fleet-BankBoston combination _ and the ready-made competitor it
will create as it spins off assets to meet antitrust rules _ served
as catalysts for their own merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fleet-BankBoston transaction caused us to rethink our
strategy,'' said UST Corp.'s president and chief executive, Neal F.
Finnegan, under whose six-year tenure UST's market capitalization
swelled more than tenfold. ``We looked at all the options, and it
became very clear that making a deal with another company made the
most sense.'' Fish approached Finnegan six weeks ago, two months
after Fleet and BankBoston announced their deal.
</P>
<P>
   There are other implications.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Rosenblatt, a mergers and acquisitions attorney at
Nutter, McClennan &AMP; Fish LLC in Boston, said the new Citizens
provided ``a critical mass for regional banking.'' Fleet and
BankBoston have national and international, rather than regional,
focuses in their commercial lending unit, leaving banking
regulators worried about who will serve New England's smaller
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A combined Citizens-UST, Rosenblatt said, would provide ``a new
vibrancy'' to the region's banking needs.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators overseeing the Fleet-BankBoston divestiture _ the
largest in banking history _ are keen to have a single large bidder
acquire most, if not all, of the assets, which include $12.5
billion in deposits and nearly $2 billion in loans.
</P>
<P>
   With its acquisition of UST, the new Citizens may have a
stronger hand in making a play for the assets, which have attracted
an avalanche of bidders from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to wait and see'' if Citizens joins in the
bidding, Fish said.
</P>
<P>
   Fish, 54, will run the new company, which will be the nation's
33rd largest bank, while Finnegan will serve as nonexecutive
chairman of Citizens Bank of Massachusetts. Under the deal, which
still needs regulatory approval and is expected to close in
January, Finnegan, 61, is widely viewed to be easing into
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Privately owned Citizens, whose owner, The Royal Bank of
Scotland PLC, is bankrolling most of the acquisition, is paying $32
per UST share, a 32 percent premium to the company's closing price
on Friday. Shares in UST soared 6 on the Nasdaq market to end at 30
1/4. The Royal fell 2 pence to close at 1424 pence on the London
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts welcomed the deal, in which Citizens is paying
a relatively low 2.6 times book value.
</P>
<P>
   But The Royal may have more in mind for Citizens, which accounts
for one-quarter of its parent's profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Royal will eventually have an eye on the fact that it can
sell out Citizens to a larger bank,'' said Stephen Kirk, an
industry analyst at Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown in London.
</P>
<P>
   Fish said the combined bank, which has about 7,800 employees,
has identified 800 positions to be cut but that actual layoffs
would be lower due to attrition and new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens, which also gains investment management and insurance
brokerage units in the deal, aims to eke out $80 million a year in
savings by 2001, or cut costs by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fish declined to be drawn on just how large he wants Citizens to
grow, saying only that he is reevaluating his previous estimates
that Citizens needs to have $25 billion to $30 billion in assets to
do well _ a range it is now firmly in.
</P>
<P>
   But Fish admitted that the bank could not resist change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I get a little bit bigger I worry about our ability
to serve,'' he said. ``I don't want to get too big. I just want to
make sure this company is big enough to compete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
