<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HISMANAL-WITHDRAW     06-21 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HISMANAL-WITHDRAWAL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER PRESSURE FROM FDA, MANUFACTURER WITHDRAWS ANTIHISTAMINE FROM
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hismanal, an antihistamine that has fallen out of
favor with consumers in the wake of warnings about its safety and
the emergence of less dangerous alternatives, is being withdrawn
from the market, the Food and Drug Administration announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer of the drug, Janssen Pharmaceutica of
Titusville, N.J., described the withdrawal as a voluntary business
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But FDA officials, who last year warned that Hismanal could
cause fatal heart rhythm disturbances in high doses or in
combination with certain other drugs, said they asked for the
withdrawal for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly indicated that we were very concerned about the
product,'' said Dr. John Jenkins, director of one of the agency's
drug evaluation offices, ``and that we would find it most
beneficial to patients if they would withdraw the marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said the decision was not prompted by any new reports of
patient deaths or injuries. Rather, he said, the agency had
concluded in recent months that with safer alternatives available,
the risks of Hismanal now outweighed the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, which has been on the market for 11 years, will not
disappear from pharmacy shelves immediately, but will become
difficult to obtain over the coming weeks. Greg Panico, a spokesman
for Janssen Pharmaceutica, which is owned by Johnson &AMP; Johnson,
said the that company had discontinued production of the drug and
that the withdrawal was effective worldwide. Patients who suffer
from seasonal allergies should ask their doctors for alternatives,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Panico had no estimate of how many patients might be affected,
but at least one allergist said in an interview on Monday that
Hismanal would not be missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a patient on it in years,'' said the allergist,
Dr. Harold Nelson, a senior staff physician at the National Jewish
Medical and Research Center in Denver. ``It isn't a very good
drug.''
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal marks the second time in two years that an
allergy medication has been taken off the market for safety
reasons. Seldane, which could cause fatal heart rhythm disturbances
in combination with other drugs, was ordered removed from pharmacy
shelves by the FDA at the end of 1997, when its manufacturer
received approval to market Allegra, a similar drug that lacked
Seldane's dangerous side effects. But Janssen had no substitute for
Hismanal, so the FDA permitted the company to keep it on the
market, a decision that has drawn complaints from the agency's
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long classified Hismanal as a `do not use drug'
because of its life-threatening interactions,'' said Dr. Sidney M.
Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's Health Research Group, an
advocacy organization in Washington that publishes ``Worst Pills,
Best Pills,'' a consumer guide to medication. ``The evidence was
very strong several years ago for taking it off the market.''
</P>
<P>
   But Panico, the Janssen spokesman, said Monday's decision had as
much to do with the competitive $7 billion antihistamine market as
with safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to voluntarily discontinue Hismanal recognizes
that the allergy marketplace is crowded with a number of other
drugs,'' he said. ``It was a business decision.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hismanal, known by the generic name astemizole, first received
approval from the Food and Drug Administration in 1988. Four years
later, the agency issued a warning about ``rare cases of serious
cardiovascular events, including death'' that occurred when
patients exceeded recommended doses. In February 1998, the agency
repeated that warning and added some new ones to Hismanal's label:
The drug, it said, could be dangerous in combination with some
antibiotics; the protease inhibitors that are used to treat AIDS
patients; certain antidepressants, including Prozac, and even
grapefruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   Following those warnings, industry analysts said, international
sales of Hismanal dropped sharply, to $90 million last year from
$180 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, worldwide sales for Claritin, an antihistamine that
has been marketed since 1993 by Schering-Plough Corp., totaled
nearly $2.3 billion last year, said Sergio Traversa, an analyst
with Mehta Partners in New York City, which tracks the drug
industry. Claritin has been the subject of heavy television and
magazine advertising, and it lacks Hismanal's dangerous
cardiovascular side effects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
