<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BELGIUM22-COX     06-21 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BELGIUM22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EU inspects Coke plants
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (i) International and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr. in Brussels
 &HT;    and Henry Unger in Atlanta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   European health officials today are scheduled to inspect
Coca-Cola plants in Belgium and France to determine whether it is
safe to drink Coke products.
</P>
<P>
   The inspections, which might last for the next few days, were
requested Monday by the European Union, which ensures the quality
of food products distributed among the body's 15-member nations.
</P>
<P>
   The entry of the EU is a clear signal the Coca-Cola controversy
is rising on the agenda of European leaders as the health scare
entered its second week.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian officials also are expected to decide today whether to
continue restrictions on the sale of canned and bottled Coca-Cola,
Coke Light (the European version of Diet Coke), Fanta and Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, meanwhile, is beginning a mea culpa advertising
campaign to try to win back the confidence of European consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The company is publishing a letter from Chairman M. Douglas
Ivester in 15 Belgian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have spoken with you earlier, and I apologize for
that,'' Ivester says to Belgian consumers. ``For decades, we worked
very hard to establish ourselves as leaders in providing
consistently high quality consumer goods on a global basis. But
over the past several days in Belgium, we allowed . . . breakdowns
to occur in fulfilling the promise of Coca-Cola. . . . To all the
Belgian people, I want to say that I'm personally very sorry for
any discomfort or inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 people in Belgium and France reported nausea,
dizziness and vomiting after consuming Coke products from plants at
Antwerp, Belgium, and at Dunkirk, France. The plants are operated
by the company's largest bottler, Atlanta-based Coca-Cola
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton Jr. and Henry Unger write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0374 </DOCNO>
