<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS22-COX     06-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CISNEROS'S EX-LOVER TELLS OF SECRET PAYMENTS, TAPES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking the witness stand against her ex-lover,
Linda Jones testified Monday that former Housing and Urban
Development Secretary Henry Cisneros secretly funneled more than
$250,000 to her.
</P>
<P>
   In a pretrial hearing, federal prosecutors are seeking to use 33
tape recordings that Jones made of phone conversations to show that
Cisneros lied to the FBI about the extent of the payments when he
was under consideration for President Clinton's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is facing trial in September for conspiracy to defraud
in a case directed by independent counsel David Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's tapes could be crucial, since they provide vivid
exchanges in which Cisneros urges Jones to go along with hiding the
true size of the payments.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Cisneros vigorously objected to use of the
recordings, which are duplicates of originals that Jones destroyed
in 1994. Moreover, Jones admitted in court to altering five of the
tapes to delete conversations that would be embarrassing or
incriminating to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has advised the court that the tapes were
tampered with. End of story,'' Barry S. Simon, a Cisneros attorney,
told the court. Moreover, Simon held that the tapes should not be
admitted because they were made with the intention of extorting
money from Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin responded, ``There's a
fairness problem. I'm sensitive to that.'' Even so, he allowed the
prosecutors present their case for admitting the recordings by
bringing in Jones, who has been serving a 3-1/2 year sentence at
the Federal Medical Center at Carswell, Texas, where she has been
treated for depression and dependence on the drug Ativan.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her plea bargain, Jones agreed to assist the
prosecution of Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black suit with long skirt and looking much younger
than her 50 years, the striking blonde spent more than three hours
relating the saga of her affair with Cisneros, which began in 1987
when he was mayor of San Antonio and she was a fund-raiser for his
political committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating,'' Jones said of her ordeal when the affair
was made public in 1988 in a blaring headline in the San Antonio
Express-News. She said that her political clients abandoned her
consulting business and her husband filed for divorce, leaving her
without a guaranteed financial support.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Cisneros alternated between promises to marry her
and giving interviews with the news media promising to reunite with
his wife, Mary Alice, which eventually he did.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutor Mark Jackwoski sought to show that Jones had
made the secret tapes of Cisneros not for extortion purposes but
out of her fears and financial insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   She repeatedly testified that she had taped Cisneros only when
she felt their relationship was rocky. However, she said she also
made threats to Cisneros, telling him that if he made no agreement
to support her, ``I (would) go to the press, the president, whoever
would talk to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Jones made good on her threats by filing a lawsuit
against Cisneros in her home town of Lubbock, Texas, and by taking
her story to the TV program ``Inside Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   Those actions set in motion the investigation that landed her in
prison and led to charges against Cisneros and two of his former
aides, Sylvia Arce-Garcia and John Rosales, who are accused of
assisting in the cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who resigned from the cabinet in 1997 and is now
president of a Univision, a Spanish-language TV network, was not
present for the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
