<HEADLINE>
SAYING GOODBYE TO CHARLES PIERCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Ken Maley &LR; , who was among the San Franciscans at Saturday's
memorial service for  &LR; self-described ``male actress''  &UR; Charles &LR; 
 &UR; Pierce &LR;  at the Church of the Hills in Forest Lawn cemetery in Los
Angeles, says the day was hot and the place was packed.
</P>
<P>
   Master of ceremonies  &UR; Michael Kearns  &LR; noted that the service had
been ``written, produced and directed'' by Pierce, whose ashes were
placed, as he'd planned, in a columbarium near the graves of
 &UR; Bette Davis &LR;  and  &UR; Lucille Ball &LR; , whom he'd often played.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's final farewell, written by him to be read aloud to the
mourners, said, ``It's not true that my ashes are going to be put
with glitter in a Smirnoff bottle and tossed from the Golden Gate
Bridge. A bit too splashy, don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIVIC AFFAIRS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A merchants' association in Pittsburgh has placed 30 rocking
chairs around its Market Square, each paid for by a contribution
from a local merchant. The chairs are fully occupied almost every
day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bernie Lynch &LR; , the association's executive director, told the
New York Times that people laughed at her idea at first. ``The
retailers are still teasing me. But when they see that they're
packed and that people are fighting for them at lunch, maybe they
realize I'm not as crazy as they thought.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At Strawberry Village in Mill Valley, Calif.,  &UR; Anne Anderson &LR; 
asked an elderly shopkeeper, ``What is the best way to go to
Berkeley from here?'' His reply: ``If I were going to Berkeley, I
wouldn't start from here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RADICAL ART? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Last week's arrest of former SLA associate  &UR; Kathleen Ann &LR; 
 &UR; Soliah  &LR; has prompted an East Bay woman to report on seeing  &UR; Wendy &LR; 
 &UR; Yoshimura &LR;  _ who was arrested with  &UR; Patty Hearst &LR;  _ in her studio
as part of the recent East Bay Open Studios tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``She paints watercolor portraits of fruits and vegetables,''
writes the art lover. ``If she still sees folks as pawns in a white
male-dominated, capitalist pig-driven society run by plutocrats,
her prices certainly don't reflect that view. Most pieces went for
$750 to $1,000. ... Her work is exquisite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
