<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-ATTORNEYS-GENE     06-21 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ATTORNEYS-GENERAL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 NEW REPUBLICAN GROUP SEEKS TO REIN IN ATTORNEYS GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a time of new activism among state attorneys
general, Republicans are creating a party attorneys general
association to promote government restraint and raise money to
elect more Republicans as states' chief law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the Republican National Committee in conjunction
with several Republican attorneys general comes as many of the
states chief law enforcement officers have aggressively expanded
their roles by bringing lawsuits against tobacco companies or
joining the Justice Department in bringing antitrust charges
against Microsoft. In the 43 states that elect attorneys general,
Republicans hold only 12 of the positions. Thirty-one states have
Republican governors.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Condon, the attorney general of South Carolina and the
chairman of the new group, said it would serve as both a think tank
and a campaign vehicle and he raised questions about the new
activism by many of the states chief legal officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot speak for all the attorneys general,'' Condon said.
But pointing to the national battle over smoking as an example, he
said, ``I think everyone has his role and in terms of limited
government the idea of what should and shouldn't be done through
the legislature rather than through the judicial branch raises some
serious questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Attorneys General Association held its first
fund-raiser Monday night at the Capitol Hill Club, a bastion of
Republican fund-raising events, and was seeking donations of at
least $1,000 per person for an RNC fund that is used for party
activities that indirectly assist an array of state-level
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans declined to say how much money they were seeking to
raise for the fledgling organization and it was not clear who else
was attending the event. But one official said that donors would be
able to choose whether they supported the Republicans' view of
limited government or the Democrats legal activism.
</P>
<P>
   The money was to go to one of the party's so-called soft-money
accounts which are free to accept unlimited donations from
individuals or corporations. Tobacco companies have long been heavy
Republican donors and Republicans recently have been trying to
court the high-tech industry as well.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the group was being modeled on the Republican
Governors Association, which was founded in 1963 and has become a
force for promoting the party's governors and their ideas. Party
officials said that they also considered it important to increase
the ranks of Republicans in attorney general positions because such
officials later become candidates for governor or senator.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the move has prompted sharp debate, particularly with the
fund-raiser coming just a week before the annual summer meeting in
Tennessee of the bipartisan National Attorneys General Association.
In a letter pointedly addressed to ``Dear Republican Attorney
General,'' Mark Pryor, the Democratic attorney general of Arkansas
predicted that formation of the partisan association would prove
``disastrous and extremely divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The office of Attorney General is unique,'' he wrote. ``We are
the attorneys for our respective states, not hacks for our
political parties. We have ethical obligations to best represent
our clients that do not apply to governors and legislators. The
primary nature of the office we hold is legal, not political.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the law enforcement officers had made significant
strides in consumer, anti-trust areas and in the tobacco settlement
by working together. ``To put it bluntly,'' he wrote, ``how can we
expect our colleagues to work with us in the courtroom if we are
determined to work against them at the polls?'' Pryor also sent
copies of his letter to ``all non-Republican attorneys general.''
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives have a different view of the recent activism
by these state officials and some Republicans said that the states'
chief legal officers from their own party have felt that their
views are getting short shrift from Democratic colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Federalist Society, a conservative jurists
group, and the Manhattan Institute and the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce's Institute for Legal Reform, have scheduled a conference
on state attorneys general and on the lawsuits against gun
manufacturers being brought by many of the nation's cities. The
conference, featuring some of the same people serving as hosts of
Monday night's fund-raiser, was to explore whether such suits
represent ``a useful balance in our political system or an abuse of
power?''
</P>
<P>
   Condon dismissed Democrats' complaints about the new group,
pointing to some of the controversy surrounding President Clinton's
own fund raising for the Democratic Party in 1996. ``Weren't they
raising soft money from the Chinese?'' he asked. He noted that most
attorneys general run for office. ``Now that we're raising some
money it's, `oh my gosh, attorney general, isn't this outrageous,''
he said., ``I think when they run their races, I tend to notice
they are a little bit political aren't they.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But he also acknowledged that ``phone lines and fax machines
have been burning up'' over the new group. And he said there was a
``developing consensus'' that the group not get involved in races
against Democratic incumbents but only in the case of open seats.
</P>
<P>
   Only three attorneys general are up for election in 1999,
including Michael Moore of Misssiippi, the Democrat who was a
driving force behind the tobacco suits and who is the head of the
National Attorneys General Association. Condon said his group might
not get involved in that race. A spokeswoman for Moore did not
return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   But in the original announcement of the new Republican
association earlier this month, Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the
Republican National Committee, did not draw any distinction between
incumbents and open contests. He said in a news release that the
new association would have a ``tremendous opportunity'' to increase
the number of Republicans in the ranks of the states' chief law
enforcement officers because 12 of the 13 attorneys general seats
up for election in 1999 and 2000 are held by Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4382 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FORENSIC-BOS &LR;      06-21 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FORENSIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORENSIC SPECIALISTS TO SIFT KOSOVO KILLING GROUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VELIKA KRUSA, Yugoslavia _ It is what investigators are calling
the world's largest active crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a dirt road here, inside a burned stone shed,
blue-and-white police tape marks the beginning of a massive
forensic undertaking to investigate the killing of at least 10,000
ethnic Albanians in a methodical campaign of ethnic cleansing by
Serb forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The first of an international team of forensic experts has begun
the grim task of gathering evidence at seven key massacre sites in
Kosovo to support the indictment of the war crimes tribunal in the
Hague against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and four of his
top aides.
</P>
<P>
   The small stone structure here is the first.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators at the scene said Monday there are remains of 40
people, including the bones of what appear to be two small
children, who were shot at close range and then incinerated.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre took place March 26, witnesses said, two days after
the NATO bombing of Serb forces began in Kosovo. The town, a key
crossing point for fighters of the Kosovo Liberation Army coming
from the Albanian border, appeared to be a target of Serb
paramilitary units.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first site we are focusing on,'' said Scotland
Yard Detective Sgt. Ron Turnbull as he emerged from the site of the
burned bodies, shed a white suit and bathed in chemical
decontaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbull is the crime scene coordinator for what will eventually
be a team of 350 investigators with varying expertise in gathering
and analyzing forensic and ballistic evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A 60-member FBI forensic team, the same task force that
investigated the bombing of the US Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, last
summer, arrived Sunday and is expected to begin working Tuesday
with Turnbull's team from Scotland Yard.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbull, who in 1996 led an investigation that unearthed mass
graves in Bosnia's horrific ethnic cleansing, said the
investigation in Kosovo was an ``actual crime scene'' in which
detectives have access to the bodies as they were.
</P>
<P>
   In this phase, investigators are gathering ``surface evidence''
before removing the bodies from the massacre scenes and exhuming
those bodies they believe are buried in at least 90 mass graves
throughout Kosovo. This is different he said from Bosnia, where
investigators were left to unearth the remains of much larger mass
graves for attrocities that had been carried out years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique opportunity for us,'' he said. ``We did not
have fresh crime scenes like this in Bosnia. And we hope this will
mean we can build a stronger forensic case of the atrocities and
prosecute those who carried them out.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the initial findings at this site are that more than 40
people appeared to have been herded into the one-story stone shed
and killed with AK-47 automatic rifles at close range using
.762-caliber bullets. The victims were kneeling, he said, judging
by the ``low shots'' against the stone foundation. Their bodies
were then covered with tractor tires and hay and set on fire with
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of clothing he said are all civilian and the
charred footwear are sneakers and shoes. They are also gathering
personal effects amid the remains, such as watches and mens'
wedding rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sign that these were military casualties. These
appear to be civilians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Risley, spokesman for the International Criminal Tribunal
for the Former Yugoslavia, said: ``This is the first time in
history for war crimes investigators to act in real time. And now
there is a very short window of opportunity for us to gather the
forensic evidence that we will need to indict those responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Risley said the seven massacre sites listed in the indictment of
Milosevic were the focus of investigators now. Milosevic, the first
sitting head of state to be indicted for war crimes, has been
accused of war crimes for years. The indictment is largely
symbolic, making Milosevic more of an international pariah than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   It is still considered a remote possibility that he will
actually be taken into custody in handcuffs and face trial in the
Hague. Instead, analysts believe, he will be left as a wanted man
in every nation of the United Nations. His homeland will be his
bunker unless he is overthrown _ as Western powers openly say they
hope he will be.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the seven massacre sites that are listed in his
indictment, Risley said investigators would also be fanning out
over 100 other ``priority sites'' in which there is evidence of
more massacres and systematic rape of ethnic Albanian women by Serb
forces.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most haunting of the ``priority sites'' is a silver
and lead mine north of the Kosovo capital Pristina where KLA
commanders and witnesses say they believe as many as 700 bodies of
ethnic Albanian victims were burned in deep shafts. Risley said the
allegations were credible enough that forensic investigators would
examine the site, which is now ringed by approximately 50 NATO
troops.
</P>
<P>
   It is known as the Trepca Mine, and it was the setting of
powerful Albanian-led labor strikes in the late 1980s that were
seen as galvanizing Albanian resistance to Serb domination.
</P>
<P>
   Regional KLA commanders and witnesses who live nearby said Serb
forces and paramilitary units operated there during the
nearly-three-month war. They claimed that scores of ethnic Albanian
men were taken there and have not been seen since. They also said
covered trucks, which they allege were loaded with the bodies of
massacre victims, were seen entering the mine. They said
smokestacks at the site, which had not operated for years, were
seen billowing with white smoke throughout the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   But Risley said the investigators will need to do more than
simply gather evidence of killing to successfully build a case for
prosecution of the leaders of Serb forces, a web of military and
paramilitary units that carried out most of the war's atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to find individuals who talk and then aim for the
very highest officials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That will be a difficult, perhaps impossible task, given that
most of the Serb forces fled into Serbia after the military
agreement for Yugoslavian troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tribunal investigators must act in the same manner as a
modern domestic law enforcement agency might going after the mafia
or a drug cartel,'' he added. ``It will take time and diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Risley said, the investigators will be relying on
corroborating accounts of the atrocities from individuals who
witnessed them.
</P>
<P>
   One witness critical to building the case in the massacre in the
shed in Velika Krusa is Avdi Duraku, 41, who lives in an apartment
adjacent to the building where the 40 bodies were found. War crimes
investigators from the Hague, Duraku said, had spent hours taking
down his account in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   With the smell of death in the air Monday, he recounted what he
saw on the afternoon of March 26.
</P>
<P>
   He watched from a crack between the curtain and a window as a
Mercedes three-ton truck rumbled down the dirt road flanked by
several cars carrying men dressed in the distinctive blue military
uniforms of the ``MUPs,'' or Serb special police.
</P>
<P>
   Over the sound of the truck idling, he could only hear faint
voices of men barking orders in Serbian. After several minutes, he
heard what sounded to him like three separate machine guns spraying
bursts of gunfire for at least two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then he could see thick acrid smoke and hear the crackling of a
fire.
</P>
<P>
   What appeared to be a commander with a hand-held radio shouted,
``Let's go. Let's go. We're done.''
</P>
<P>
   Duraku said he hid in his home for a half hour after the men
left and then ran out and saw the bodies engulfed in flames. He
tried to pull two bodies close to the entrance out but could see
that both were dead. He tried futiley to douse the flames with a
blanket and buckets of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare. I couldn't believe the killing. I couldn't
believe anyone could do this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Velika Krusa was a central focus of the fury of Serb
forces and in bombed out homes throughout the rolling hills there
are small clusters of human skeletons. In one home, the skeletal
remains of Ramadan Duraku and his 16-year-old son were sprawled on
the floor. A tray with two cups and a tea pot was still sitting on
a kitchen table in the partially burned-out home. A skull of one of
the bodies lay in a nearby field, dragged there, neighbors said, by
a wild dog.
</P>
<P>
   The man and his son were from the same extended family as Avdi
Duraku.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they killed so many here,'' he said Monday,
watching the investigators work next to his home. ``The KLA were
way in the hills. These were just people. These were not fighters,
they were fathers and sons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
