<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-PRUDENTIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. APPROVES AETNA'S PURCHASE OF PRUDENTIAL, BUT ORDERS
DIVESTITURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the objections of doctors' groups and consumer
advocates, the federal government on Monday approved the $1 billion
acquisition of Prudential Health Care by Aetna Inc., which will
create the nation's biggest managed-care company.
</P>
<P>
   Following a six-month review, lawyers at the Justice
Department's antitrust division approved the deal on the condition
that Aetna sell its NYLCare Health Maintenance Organization in the
Dallas-Fort Worth and Houston markets. That divestiture _ the
centerpiece of a consent decree that settles a civil suit filed by
the federal government and Texas _ will result in the loss of about
425,000 subscribers. Even so, Aetna will provide benefits to more
than 21 million individuals, or about 1 in 11 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition had been criticized by physicians' groups and
consumer organizations, which were concerned about the power of the
newly merged entity. When the deal closes, Aetna will control
between 30 percent and 60 percent of the HMO markets in some major
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas markets where Aetna must divest, the acquisition
would have given the company control of 63 percent of the Houston
market and 42 percent of the market in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna first announced in December that it would buy Prudential
Health Care from the Prudential Insurance Co. of America for $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Critics had petitioned the government to impose far more
conditions on the deal, saying it would vastly increase Aetna's
ability to negotiate fees and working rules for doctors and
hospitals, squeezing the medical profession for greater cost
savings while possibly raising premiums and controlling practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately for the patients and doctors around the nation,
this means the industry leviathan has control of the whole pond,''
said Jamie Court, director of Consumers for Quality Care, a
consumer group based in Santa Monica, Calif. ``We will likely see
doctors with more complaints and patients with fewer services.''
Court called the decision ``a black eye for the Clinton
administration in terms of patient protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Dickey, president of the American Medical Association,
said the divestitures required by the Justice Department were ``an
important first step'' but ``not the end of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This will still leave Aetna with a tremendous piece of the
market,'' Dr. Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Monday that the government decided not to
challenge Aetna's presence in a number of other markets because it
was already so large and the proposed merger would not appreciably
alter that. Moreover, they said, federal law only gives them the
authority to examine the effects of the proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement demonstrates the department's commitment to
preserve competition in all sectors of the health care industry,''
said Joel Klein, assistant attorney general in charge of the
Justice Department's antitrust division. ``The required
divestitures will have two important effects. First they will
preserve competition and protect consumers from higher prices for
HMO and HMO-based point-of-service plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, the divestitures will deny Aetna the ability to
unduly depress physician reimbursement rates and thereby impair the
quantity and quality of physician services provided to patients.''
</P>
<P>
   In their complaint filed in U.S. District Court in Dallas on
Monday, the federal government and Texas said that Aetna's
acquisition of Prudential would have eliminated the competition in
Houston and Dallas, ``allowing the merged entity to increase the
prices and to reduce the quality'' of services.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint also challenged the deal in Texas on the grounds
that it would give Aetna too much control over many physicians,
leaving them highly vulnerable in the event they became embroiled
in a dispute with the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna executives said they had decided only reluctantly to part
with some of the HMOs in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we do not agree with the Justice Department's
concerns about the effect of the acquisition, a divestiture was the
most expeditious way to bring closure to the comprehensive DOJ
review process,'' Richard Huber, the chairman and chief executive
of Aetna, said.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives said that even after the sale, the company
would remain the leader in the Texas market, with about 2.5 million
health clients, including 1 million HMO subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives said that they plan to close the deal this
summer, though the regulatory process will likely continue through
at least the fall. Officials in six states _ California, Florida,
Georgia, New Jersey, New York and Texas _ are still reviewing the
acquisition, and could order further modifications.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dickey, of the AMA, said that state chapters of the group
would continue to press state regulators to scrutinize the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Aetna executives said they have no further plans to sell any
other parts of the company. ``It's not what we believe will
happen,'' said Patricia Seif, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
