<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OPEN AT PINEHURST: DRAMA OF TONY QUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Instead of facing Phil Mickelson in an 18-hole
playoff Monday, Payne Stewart enjoyed being U.S. Open champion for
the second time.
</P>
<P>
   With one precious putt, Stewart captured one of the most
dramatic national championships ever, draining a 15-footer on No.
18 to defeat Mickelson by one stroke. It was the kind of major that
people dream about _ big names on the leader board, a great golf
course that featured danger on every hole and a dramatic finish
with a Hollywood-type conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart reaped many rewards, winning his second U.S. Open and
his third major championship, and clinching a spot on this year's
U.S. Ryder Cup team. But golf was a winner, as well. Not only will
people remember the 1999 U.S. Open for generations, but the world
became more familiar with Pinehurst Resort and Country Club's No. 2
course, which had never been host to an Open.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the U.S. Golf Association brings the Open
back to Pinehurst in the not-too-distant future. You didn't have to
win at Pinehurst to love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this golf course proved that it's a championship
course,'' said Tiger Woods, who finished tied for third place with
Vijay Singh, two strokes behind Stewart. ``It deserves another U.S.
Open because it's a golf course that tests every facet of your
game. Most U.S. Opens don't. It was great to see.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Stewart, it was a great victory. At age 42, Stewart has
won three majors _ the 1989 PGA championship, the 1991 U.S. Open
and Sunday's triumph _ and that puts him in elite company. Consider
that Stewart has won more majors than a host of other fine golfers
of his generation, like Greg Norman, who has won two; Mark O'Meara,
who has two; Curtis Strange, two; Fred Couples, one; Tom Lehman,
one; Hal Sutton, one, and Corey Pavin, one.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart began Sunday's final round with a one-stroke lead, but
many thought he might be overtaken by Mickelson, Woods, Singh or
David Duval. Instead, Stewart saved his best for the final three
holes, when he salvaged a par at No. 16 with a 25-foot putt,
birdied No. 17 to take the lead for good, then won at No. 18 with
his memorable putt.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart proved something not only to others, but to himself.
Last year's U.S. Open was a bitter experience for him, when he took
a four-stroke lead into Sunday's final round, but lost to Lee
Janzen by one stroke. Stewart vowed that he would give himself
another chance to win the Open, and he returned this year more
confident, more determined and better prepared to handle the
pressure. Stewart is at peace with his life and with his game. And
it showed on Sunday's back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to give thanks to the Lord for giving me the ability
to believe in myself,'' Stewart said. ``I wasn't thinking about
Phil, or Tiger or David or anybody. I was thinking about getting
the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mickelson and Woods were left with other things to
think about. For Woods, most of those thoughts were good. Though he
did not win, the third-place tie was his best finish at a U.S.
Open. And if not for missing key putts at No. 11 (2 and a half
feet) and No. 17 (8 feet), Woods might have won. At age 23, Woods
has won the Masters and finished third at the U.S. and British
Opens. And Woods left Pinehurst even more confident despite the
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This golf tournament has been one I've always wanted to win,
because I've won three U.S. Juniors, and three U.S. Amateurs and it
would be nice to win three U.S. Opens,'' said Woods, who has
finished first, first and third in his last three starts. ``I know
I can win a Masters. I know I can win a British Open. This makes me
feel like I can definitely win a U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also the best finish at a major for Mickelson, whose
wife, Amy, is expecting the couple's first child at the end of
June.
</P>
<P>
   When Stewart's final putt fell in, Mickelson knew he had lost to
a deserving player. It took something special to make that putt in
that situation. And Stewart had what it took.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the last putt, I felt there was a very good chance,''
Mickelson said. ``Payne Stewart made two exceptional putts, on No.
16 and No. 18. Those putts showed a lot of character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
