<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSTODYBATTLE-SUICIDE     06-21 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTODYBATTLE-SUICIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pain of custody battle likely lead to suicide, notes reveal
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In letters she left behind, Gena Roach wrote
about the strain of a custody battle over care of her adult son.
</P>
<P>
   Her death Sunday was ruled a suicide. Her son, Rodney Roach, 32,
severely impaired from a previous auto accident, was fighting for
his life Monday with a bullet wound in his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Roach was found Sunday in his mother's Jeep Cherokee at
the Englewood Reserve MetroPark. His mother, also shot in the
chest, sat next to him. A pipe ran exhaust from the tailpipe into
the cab.
</P>
<P>
   While police are not certain that Mrs. Roach shot her son and
herself, ``it's pointing in that direction,'' said MetroParks
Rangers' Detective Monnie Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are awaiting ballistics tests, Bush said. But
rangers found ``several notes addressed to several people,'' Bush
said, in which Gena discussed the pain of the custody battle with
Rodney's wife Janet.
</P>
<P>
   A ranger found the two Sunday afternoon, after he noticed the
Jeep parked just off the main roadway. Mrs. Roach, 58, was in the
driver's seat. Her son was in the passenger seat. A gun was found.
</P>
<P>
   A couple passing by told rangers they had noticed Mrs. Roach
slumped over. Rodney was holding a teddy bear, the couple told
rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney was in critical condition Monday at Miami Valley
Hospital. He had required constant care, following a January 1998
traffic accident which ``left him pretty much unable to take care
of himself,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney was driving a sport utility vehicle when he hit a bit of
frost or black ice on the road, said Sgt. Carl Plummer of the
Butler Twp. Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost it right in the curve,'' Plummer said. ``It was a
freak accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney drove into a tree, which hit the passenger side, Plummer
said. Because Rodney wasn't wearing a seat belt, his head smashed
into the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   His mother and brother, Russell, fought often with his wife over
his care, Bush said. Each side accused the other of not taking
adequate care of Rodney, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ongoing battle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janet was unavailable for comment. A man who parked a pickup
truck at Mrs. Roach's home in Dayton declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Janet and Gena had sought to be Rodney's legal guardian,
but Probate Judge George J. Gounaris appointed attorney Christopher
Cowan on June 7, Cowan said. He met with Rodney, Gena and Janet for
the first time Friday, Cowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowan said he could not offer many details about the parties'
``bickering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just getting started,'' Cowan said. ``I get on it, meet
my client. Two days later, he's shot, his mom's dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney was in a wheelchair and could not speak, Cowan said. He
could point to an alphabet chart or signal yes or no by moving his
left thumb, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Hollencamp, attorney for Gena and Russell Roach, said
Rodney had been removed from his wife's custody in April. During
Friday's conference, the attorneys discussed Cowan's proposal to
offer alternating weeks' visitation for Rodney's wife and mother,
Hollencamp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the weekend dictating an objection to it, which was
never filed because it's now moot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Russell will be applying to become Rodney's legal
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Donald Hawkins, who represents Janet Roach, declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Grieco writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio. Mara
Lee contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
