<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS OK AETNA'S PRUDENTIAL PURCHASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
and MARY SIT-DuVALL 
 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal and Texas regulators have approved Aetna's
planned $1 billion purchase of Prudential HealthCare, provided
Aetna sells its NylCare health maintenance organization business in
Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   In a consent decree filed in U.S. District Court in Dallas
Monday, Aetna agreed to sell the NylCare operations in Houston and
Dallas-Fort Worth by the end of the year to a buyer to be named
later.
</P>
<P>
   About 260,000 HMO patients in Greater Houston and another
167,000 clients in the Dallas-Fort Worth area will be affected by
the government-ordered divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna's acquisition of the health-care
business of Prudential Insurance Co. of America is expected to
close early in the third quarter. It will create the nation's
largest health-benefits provider, with 21 million members,
including 18 million enrolled in its managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's announcement last December of its intent to purchase
Prudential HealthCare, coming just six months after Aetna's
acquisition of NylCare, raised concerns at the U.S. Justice
Department and the Texas attorney general's office that it would
stifle competition for managed care in the Houston and Dallas-Fort
Worth areas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger, regulators said, would have given Aetna
control of 63 percent of the HMO and related HMO-based
point-of-service business in Houston, and 42 percent of the market
in Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna will be able to keep the rest of its NylCare business in
Texas. Following the divestitures, Aetna will remain the
managed-care leader in Texas with 2.5 million members, including 1
million HMO members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement protects the consumer by preserving
competition,'' Texas Attorney General John Cornyn said in a written
statement Monday. ``Patients will benefit both from the lower
health-plan prices that competition ensures and the preservation of
quality health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Klein, the assistant U.S. attorney general in charge of the
antitrust division, said regulators feared that, without the
divestitures, Aetna would have been able to unduly depress the
reimbursement rates physicians receive, ``and thereby impair the
quantity and quality of physician services provided to patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aetna that results from this agreement will be smaller, with
strong competitors that will have to behave and perform better than
the combined company, said Dr. Paul Handel, immediate past
president of the Harris County Medical Society in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna Chief Executive Officer Richard L. Huber said that while
company officials did not agree with regulators' concerns, ``a
divestiture was the most expeditious way to bring closure to the
comprehensive ... review process.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling off the NylCare business, Huber said, will be easier
than trying to carve out the Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth portions
of the Prudential business.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Bernica, executive vice president of the Harris County
Medical Society, hailed the divestiture order as good for
consumers, businesses and physicians.
</P>
<P>
   The county medical society, which represents about 8,000 doctors
in the Houston area, estimates that a combined Aetna-Prudential
will still control about a third of the commercial HMO market in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Inlander, president of the People's Medical Society, a
nonprofit patient advocacy group based in Allentown, Pa., argued
that regulators have to be cautious about approving mergers too
quickly in this industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to watch them, and we have to be careful,'' Inlander
said. ``We have to be careful they're not expanding too fast, and
are able to absorb the needs of the patient and the needs of the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted L. Goldberg, a consultant for the Deloitte &AMP; Touche
Consulting Group, said the Aetna-Prudential merger poses ``a big
challenge'' for the companies involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very, very complex organizations,'' Goldberg said.
``And to quickly bring them together in one entity _ given the
differences in systems, processes and people _ will be a tremendous
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
