<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS CONTINUE UP; BLUE CHIPS CLOSE LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Optimism that second-quarter earnings will be strong
pushed technology stock prices up for the fifth straight session
Monday. But a rise in interest rates hurt cyclical stocks, and the
blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average closed lower.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by gains in well known names like Microsoft, Cisco
Systems, Amazon.com and Yahoo, the NASDAQ composite index soared
66.84 points, or 2.6 percent. That, after the 4.7 percent gain the
index recorded last week, put the NASDAQ up just under 20 percent
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation is that this earnings season will reflect a
very strong economy in the first half, and the bargain hunters are
going to technology stocks because they have the best prospects,''
said Richard Cripps, chief market strategist at Legg Mason in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But upbeat talk about earnings did not lead to a surge in
business on the floor of the exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange remained fairly
light, with only 680 million shares changing hands. On the NASDAQ,
895 million shares were traded.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism about second-quarter earnings also helped lift
brokerage stocks. A number of companies, including Goldman, Sachs;
Lehman Brothers, and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, are expected to
report their second-quarter results this week.
</P>
<P>
   Among brokerage stocks, Charles Schwab soared 8 1/4, to 98 1/4.
Goldman Sachs was up 4 11/16, to 69 1/2. Lehman Brothers gained 4
1/4, to 60 5/16. And Morgan Stanley Dean Witter rose 4, to 99 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   However, the rise in interest rates, which pushed long-term bond
yields back above 6 percent, depressed cyclical stocks. Led by
Alcoa, Chevron, General Electric and Exxon, which each fell by more
than two points, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 39.58
points, or 0.4 percent, to 10,815.98.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 6.16, or five-tenths
of a percent, to 1,349, bolstered by gains in technology stocks,
including America Online and Lucent Technologies, and finance
company shares, including Chase Manhattan. America Online gained 3
3/8, to 115 3/8, and Lucent rose 2 7/16, to 65 3/8. Chase added 3
3/8, to 83 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Small company stocks also had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small company shares rose 4.39 points,
or 1 percent, to 449.44. And theStreet.com's Internet stock index
soared 30.17 points, or 5.4 percent, to 594.51.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates have been the dominant concern of stock traders
for the past few weeks. But anxiety about rising rates eased last
week after the release of reassuring news about inflation and a
comparatively straightforward talk by Federal Reserve Board
chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the overwhelming sense is that the Fed will tighten
at the end of the month, and at worst once more sometime after
that,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor
Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to have a better tone to the bond market.
If that happens, then we could have an explosive move to the upside
in stocks, and move to new highs.''
</P>
<P>
   Among big technology stocks, Microsoft gained 3 15/16, to 88
15/16. Cisco Systems gained 3 3/4, to 123 3/16. Sun Microsystems
rose 4 1/2, to 68 9/16 .
</P>
<P>
   Of the Dow stocks, technology stocks were the biggest winners.
</P>
<P>
   IBM gained 3 7/8, to 124 3/4. And Hewlett Packard rose 2 1/16,
to 94.
</P>
<P>
   A drop in crude oil and gasoline futures prices hit oil and oil
service stocks. Chevron, a Dow component, fell 2 5/8, to 90 9/16,
Exxon fell 2 1/8, to 78 1/4. Halliburton slid 2 1/16, to 43 13/16.
And Schlumberger fell 1 1/2, to 63.
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet stocks, Yahoo! shot up 14 7/16, to 158 7/8 on a
report it would raise investment in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Weyerhaeuser, the big forestry company, slid 2 9/16
to 67 3/16 after saying it had agreed to buy MacMillan Bloedel Ltd.
of Canada for $2.45 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing fell 1 5/8 to 43 after the top sales executive of rival
Airbus Industrie said the company risked reviving a price war.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, plagued by continued worries and official sales bans
in several European countries after reports of illness last week,
saw its stock slip again Monday. At the close, Coke shares were
down 1 7/8, to 61 9/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
