<SLUG> BC-R-TOGO-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOGO'S PRESIDENT DECREES A NEW GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; also budgeted as TOGO-EYADEMA)  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOME, Togo _ A year after winning re-election in voting that was
widely considered tainted, President Gnassingbe Eyadema has
continued to tighten his three-decade hold on his nation's
politics, preserving his status as sub-Saharan Africa's
longest-ruling head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has announced, by presidential decree, the formation of a
new government made up of his longtime loyalists. The announcement
came three months after his party swept parliamentary elections
boycotted by all opposition parties and a month after Amnesty
International released a report describing widespread human rights
abuses in Togo.
</P>
<P>
   Togo is a sliver of a country just east of Ghana with about 5
million people. But despite its size, Eyadema's career has been
watched closely in West Africa for its particular role in the
region's history.
</P>
<P>
   As a 26-year-old sergeant, Eyadema staged post-colonial Africa's
first military coup, in 1963, eventually seizing the presidency for
himself in 1967. When Mobutu Sese Seko was toppled from power two
years ago in the former Zaire, Eyadema became the continent's
longest-serving ruler.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when West African nations began holding
multiparty elections and Eyadema's grip on power seemed shaky, Togo
experienced a political liberalization with a dilution of
presidential power. But Eyadema succeeded in clinging to power by
pitting opponents against one another and heading one of the
largest armies, per capita, in Africa, foreign officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, after presidential elections were held and returns
showed Eyadema trailing, one of his generals took over the ballot
counting. Since then, the West has withheld foreign aid that Togo
desperately needs, and relations between the government and
opposition parties have worsened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government line is brotherhood, reconciliation, peace,
love, make nice to everybody,'' said a foreign official here who
observed the March elections. ``But the March elections just
complicated matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the opposition declared that it would boycott the
elections, Eyadema's party, Assembly of the Togolese People, went
ahead with the voting. The party claimed a 66 percent turnout and
victory in 77 out of 79 seats, with the other two going to
independent allies of the president. Foreign observers described
the turnout as less than half that figure and the voting as
tainted.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that a new government has been formed even as
Eyadema is supposed to hold talks next month with opposition
parties. The opposition parties held seats in the former
parliament, though Eyadema's party held the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can the government be considered legitimate when all the
members are from one party?'' said Emmanuel Akitani Bob, vice
president of the Union of the Forces for Change, the main
opposition party. Standing inside the party's headquarters, which
was ransacked and set on fire by soldiers last August, he added,
``We are pessimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob's organization is led by Gilchrist Olympio, considered by
most to have been the real winner of last June's presidential
elections and now living in exile in London. Olympio is the son of
Sylvanius Olympio, a wealthy businessman who was Togo's president
when he was assassinated in 1963 in the coup led by Eyadema.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Eyadema did not respond to requests for an interview.
In the past, however, the government has denied that the two
elections were rigged.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the government has also attacked Amnesty
International's charges of abuse and political repression. Late
last month, the government barred Amnesty International's secretary
general, Pierre Sane, from entering the country. After the group
accused the Togolese government of detaining and torturing one of
its Nigerian investigators for nine days, the government said the
Nigerian had been held as a suspected drug trafficker.
</P>
<P>
   Although events in the last year amounted to a setback for the
political liberalization in the early 1990s, even political
opponents acknowledge that the Togolese enjoy more freedom than in
the past. The government daily newspaper, Togo Presse, still
consists of photographs of the president and detailed descriptions
of his daily activities, but the cult of personality has died down
compared with the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there was the naming of two of the capital's most
famous hotels. In January 1974, the president incurred minor
injuries as his plane landed in the northern town of Sarakawa; on
his triumphal drive back to the southern coast, he announced on
February 2 that Togo's main commodity, phosphate, would be
nationalized. The hotels were named Hotel Sarakawa and Hotel 2
Fevrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that a decade ago, I would have never talked openly
about politics with a journalist,'' said Artheme Ahoomey-Zunu, the
secretary of the Togolese Union for Democracy, an opposition party.
``But to have Africa's longest ruling head of state, it's
shameful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
