<SLUG> BC-ABBOTT-ALZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT LABS TO ACQUIRE ALZA FOR $7.3 BILLION IN STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abbott Laboratories, one of the world's top sellers of
antibiotics, announced Monday that it would acquire Alza Corp. for
$7.3 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will not only become a formidable maker of
cancer and incontinence medicines _ some of the pharmaceutical
industry's most competitive categories _ but it will be the
nation's leading maker of sustained-released drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praised the acquisition, noting that it marked a strong
debut for Abbott's chairman and chief executive, Miles White. When
White became Abbott's chief executive in January and chairman in
April, he told Wall Street analysts he wanted to expand the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``White has done exactly what he said he'd do,'' said Sergio
Traversa, an analyst with Mehta Partners, a biopharmacology
research company in New York. ``The two companies are a perfect
fit. Alza has excellent drug delivery programs and good
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Abbott will trade 1.2 of its shares
for every Alza share, or $53.025 each, based on Abbott's closing
price of $44.1875 on Monday. Alza's shareholders will receive a
14.6 percent premium, on top of two weeks of healthy gains. Lifted
by rumors of a pending acquisition, Alza's shares have increased
29.6 percent since June 1. The deal was announced after financial
markets had closed Monday. Shares of Abbott closed down 50 cents,
to $44.1875, while Alza rose 25 cents, to $46.25.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Monday that the Alza acquisition would give Abbott
some badly needed momentum. While the company is one of the drug's
industry's most consistent earnings performers, its marks are far
from stellar. Abbott's earnings increased 12 percent last year,
compared with 16 percent for the industry. Warner-Lambert, by
contrast, raised its earnings by more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Abbott, which is based in Abbott Park, Ill., has
become successful at diversification _ the company also sells
hospital, nutritional and agricultural products _ these businesses
are usually not as profitable as pharmaceuticals. Analysts said
Monday that the Alza acquisition should increase Abbott's profits
quickly because Alza made most of the delivery systems for its own
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Alza, based in Palo Alto, Calif., has long been rumored as a
takeover target, but its deals with other pharmaceutical companies
made any acquisition tricky. Among the products that Alza has
developed and licensed to other companies are the Nicoderm CQ
Patch, sold by SmithKline Beecham, and Pfizer's heart drug
Procardia XL.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott has no trouble with licensing or acquisition agreements,
having recently made more than 40. The company recently bought
Medisense, a glucose monitoring company, for $876 million, and Novo
Nordisk's plant-protection business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies shied away from buying Alza because of its
agreements,'' said Neil Sweig, a pharmaceutical analyst with
Southeast Research Partners. ``But the company started to develop
its own drugs, and that has made it more attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   While analysts noted that Abbott's research pipeline was thin
compared with those of some of its competitors _ the company should
release a new compound for congestive heart failure later this year
_ its existing portfolio of drugs is relatively strong.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Biaxin, its antibiotic, are expected to top $1.3
billion this year, a modest 5 percent increase. Yet sales of
Depakote, for manic depression, are projected to grow 20 percent
this year, to $780 million.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott executives are cautious of their need to bolster their
profits. The company said Monday that the Alza purchase would
dilute earnings by about 3 cents a share next year but should add
to the company's bottom line in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
