<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-STRATEGY-COX     06-21 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STRATEGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multifront effort seeks to restore confidence
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr. in Brussels
 &HT;    and Henry Unger in Atlanta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola is running on at least three tracks at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the European health scare, the company is trying to
persuade politicians and scientists that all of its soft drinks are
safe and should be allowed back on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company also is going after the hearts and
minds of European consumers with advertising campaigns in several
nations, including Belgium, France, Italy, Greece and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Internally, Coca-Cola is trying to make sure its own troops
maintain high morale in the face of the public relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, company Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer M. Douglas Ivester met Monday with Belgian Prime Minister
Jean-Luc Dehaene to discuss ending the government's partial ban on
Coca-Cola products.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Randal Donaldson said it was a brief meeting
in which Ivester expressed his apology for the problems Coca-Cola
has caused the Belgian government. The government already had been
dealing with a health scare over meat and dairy products
contaminated with cancer-causing dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dehaene resigned this month after his party was
swept from power in national elections, he is considered one of
Belgium's most influential figures. He has been mentioned as a
likely successor to NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
   Dehaene also is a good friend of Luc Van den Bossche, the
country's tough-minded health minister, who has been critical of
Coca-Cola's reaction to the crisis and skeptical of the soft drink
giant's explanation for what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Bossche met with his staff on the Coca-Cola issue
Monday, but he didn't decide to remove the sales restrictions on
the company's major brands, including Coca-Cola, Coca-Cola Light
and Sprite. The government is expected to make a statement today.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola officials provided the Belgian government with copies
of studies commissioned by the company to determine whether the
contaminants it described posed a health risk. The scientists
determined that the substances were present in amounts too small to
pose any risk.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested that the symptoms reported by consumers were
perhaps psychosomatic reactions to the foul smell caused by the
substances.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, the European Union's executive body, the
European Commission, instructed Belgian and French authorities to
inspect the two bottling plants at the center of the crisis, said
Paola Testori, an EU spokesman. The organization was prompted to
move because it did not have satisfactory information on what
caused the illnesses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the EU is supposed to do in a situation such as
this when there is a food crisis,'' Testori said. The inspections
are expected to be completed in a few days, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The EU action could slow the process of getting Coca-Cola back
on the shelves because it may make officials in Belgium and France
reluctant to act before all the inspections take place.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Coca-Cola said it would welcome the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to facilitate them as soon as possible,'' said
Paul Pendergrass, the company's European spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has said bottles were infused with defective and
foul-smelling carbon dioxide gas at the Antwerp, Belgium, plant,
while cans from Dunkirk, France, were contaminated with a fungicide
administered to wooden pallets used in shipping products from that
plant to Belgium. The plants are operated by Atlanta-based
Coca-Cola Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 people in both nations reported illnesses, mainly
nausea, vomiting and stomachaches, after drinking Coca-Cola
products. As a result, Belgium has instituted the partial ban on
Coca-Cola products. French officials have banned canned Coke
products made at the Dunkirk plant, while officials in Holland,
Germany and Spain have banned Coca-Cola products from plants in
Antwerp and Dunkirk.
</P>
<P>
   The public relations battle
</P>
<P>
   Eager to shore up its credibility with consumers, Coca-Cola ran
full-page ads Monday in major newspapers in France, Spain and
Italy. The ads said analyses by Coca-Cola and by independent teams
show that ``the drink is not in question ... Its quality is
irreproachable.'' The ads also display a toll-free consumer
hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Full page ads are running today in 15 Belgian newspapers
featuring a personal apology letter from Ivester to the country's
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the company's marketing chief, Charles Frenette,
has been holding strategy sessions to plan the company's
advertising, marketing and public relations campaigns in the wake
of this unprecedented crisis. Industry analysts predict a very
aggressive, multimedia approach.
</P>
<P>
   Employee morale
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ivester and CCE President Henry Schimberg are
trying to shore up employee morale. Both met Monday with all of the
Coke system's employees in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Both sent memos to employees to reassure them that everything
possible is being done to handle the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we had any quality issue ... is intolerable,''
Ivester said in an e-mail to employees around the globe. ``What I
can tell you, with absolute certainty, is that we will learn from
this mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company will do everything in our power to enforce our
high standards and consistently strive to raise those standards to
even higher levels.''
</P>
<P>
   In his memo, Schimberg thanked CCE's European employees for
working around the clock to try to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply grateful for their remarkable commitment to our
business,'' he wrote. ``The formidable task remains for us to
rebuild consumer confidence in the integrity of our brands, and we
are working with the Coca-Cola Co. on the development and
implementation of a strong marketing-public relations plan.''
</P>
<P>
   CCE, the world's largest soft-drink bottler, has about 9,000
employees in Western Europe and 57,000 in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton Jr. and Henry Unger write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
