<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BADUM-SLAYING     06-21 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BADUM-SLAYING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OUTSIZED LIFE AND DEATH FOR A SEVENTH AVENUE INSIDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like many people who come to New York from somewhere
else, who have a heightened attraction to the city's openness, Todd
Oldham had an ideal, and it was John Badum. To Oldham, the
Texas-born fashion designer who made his name in the early 1990s,
Badum was a catalyst, a ringleader, someone who was not only openly
gay but who was also constantly at the center of everything.
</P>
<P>
   He was those things, too, to the photographer David LaChapelle.
And to Simon Doonan, the creative director of Barneys New York, who
met his future employers, the Pressman family, through Badum. And
to Beverly Mace, a friend, who said in the days following Badum's
brutal murder on Memorial Day weekend in upstate New York, that it
seemed to her as if everyone she knew in the city had started off
at Badum's East Village apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``John lived, lived for sure,'' Oldham said last week. ``He was
our own Auntie Mame. God, he was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the early hours of Sunday, May 30, in Batavia, 40 miles
east of Buffalo, Badum, 46, a former fashion industry executive,
was repeatedly stabbed by a person whom his friends knew slightly,
and whom it now appears Badum didn't know well enough.
</P>
<P>
   That person, Hamid Ouhda, a 23-year-old Moroccan immigrant, was
Badum's companion. He was also the husband of Badum's sister
Theresa, a teacher in Batavia, who admitted in an interview that
she had married Ouhda in Morocco last January to get him an
American visa.
</P>
<P>
   Although Batavia police investigators said they believed Ouhda
had intended to kill both Badum and his sister when he broke into
Ms. Badum's one-bedroom apartment, Ms. Badum, 40, escaped with
minor stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ouhda, too, died that night. At 4:55 a.m., an hour after fleeing
on foot, the man the police say killed Badum was himself killed by
a mini-van traveling on Route 33, about a mile east of Batavia.
Chuck Dudek, one of four Batavia detectives on the case, said that
Ouhda appeared to have thrown himself into the vehicle's path. His
death was ruled a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   While the events of May 30 are clear in the minds of the
detectives, what is not clear to them is what drove Ouhda to stab
Badum 31 times. The mystery has also consumed many people on
Seventh Avenue, where Badum once helped build a $30 million
business and where he knew, as LaChapelle said, ``the `411' on
everyone in the fashion industry.''
</P>
<P>
   No less confounding to Badum's friends, about 200 of whom
gathered last week for a memorial service, is how a man so
supremely good at connecting people could have made so fatal a
misconnection with Ouhda. The two had met while Badum was traveling
in southern Morocco in 1996, his sister said.
</P>
<P>
   To the victim's friends, Ouhda was little more than a handsome
stranger. He was 6 feet 2 inches tall, weighed 220 pounds and was
described by those who had met him as pleasant but immature. He
spoke little English and conversed with Badum in poor French.
Ouhda's family lives in Ouarzazate, a farming village 125 miles
south of Marrakesh, where the Sahara begins. Last week, an
English-speaking friend of Ouhda's father, who is a civil servant
with the Moroccan Ministry of Agriculture, said by phone that the
family was itself trying to comprehend what had happened. ``They're
just completely shocked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the opinion of several of Badum's friends that he ``died
for love,'' in Ms. Mace's words. Such an assertion, if true,
suggests that Badum was a rash and foolish person. But friends say
this was not the case. ``I've known John for 14 years, and I've
never seen indiscretion like this,'' said Jerry Hirsch, whose
company, L'Zinger, produced Go Silk, the washable silk sportswear
line that Badum, who was national sales director, helped turn into
one of the hottest labels of the 1980s and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial, which drew a downtown contingent as well as
designers like Oldham and Thierry Mugler, Hirsch, who said he had
spoken to Badum three days before his death, was surprised by some
of the tributes. ``I heard people say that John was Auntie Mame and
a queen,'' Hirsch said, ``but they are. He was really more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   From a business point of view, which is really the only one on
Seventh Avenue, Go Silk was a tremendous success. Hirsch had
founded L'Zinger in the 1970s with a partner, Mitsu Aoki, and in
the early '80s, at the request of a retail client, Henry Lehr, they
produced some washable silk separates based on Lehr's designs. It
was a lark. But within a week, Lehr had sold all the clothes, and
in its first full season Go Silk sold 3,000 units, a number that
eventually reached 450,000 units annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just about every major retailer coming through our
door,'' Hirsch said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
