<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPE-ABDUCTION-VERDIC     06-21 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-ABDUCTION-VERDICT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury reaches verdict in rape-abduction case
 &HT;    (Attention: Ohio, Tennessee eds.)
 &HT;    By Rob Modic
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ After seven hours of deliberations over two days,
a jury Monday convicted Kevin Joseph Caes in a month-long
rape-abduction of a Nashville woman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Caes, who had missed part of the trial because he yelled at the
victim as she testified, remained quiet and fixed his gaze ahead as
Judge Dennis J. Langer of Montgomery County Common Pleas Court read
each verdict of guilty for 28 felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Caes and his attorneys, Dana Martino and D.K. Wehner, had sought
to win verdicts of not guilty by reason of insanity based on
evaluations of two psychiatrists and a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the jury didn't buy into the insanity defense, which
absolutely was inappropriate in this case,'' said assistant county
prosecutor David Franceschelli.
</P>
<P>
   Four psychologists testified for the prosecution that they not
only failed to detect signs of insanity, they concluded he was
faking a serious mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Caes, 35, was convicted of 22 counts of rape, one count of
kidnapping, three counts of felonious assault on a police officer,
one count of failure to comply with a signal by a police officer
and one count of possession of a dangerous ordnance. Franceschelli
withdrew one count of rape during trial after the victim failed to
testify about it.
</P>
<P>
   All of the charges stemmed from a week-long period that ended
Aug. 20, 1997, when a 21-year-old woman severed an alarm wire in
the Harrison Twp. home of Caes' parents. When Montgomery County
sheriff's deputies showed up, the woman told them Caes had been
holding her gagged, handcuffed and shackled to a bed in the
basement. She said she was a prostitute in Nashville and Caes had
abducted her with a stun gun a month earlier after he had solicited
her for sex in his car.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, whose street name is ``Susan,'' testified Caes first
held her in a small trailer in the driveway of what turned out to
be the home of Caes' brother, who lives near Clinton, Ind. After
convincing Caes she had been seen inside the trailer where he had
concealed her, she said Caes drove her to the Harrison Twp. home
after his parents had left for a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   When Caes returned to the home Aug. 20 and spotted deputies
swarming over the street, he drove his car over front lawns and led
deputies on a chase through Harrison Twp. before he crashed his
car.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Langer said he will schedule sentencing and a hearing to
determine Caes' sexual offender classification sometime in July.
Franceschelli said Caes could face hundreds of years in prison and
one charge carries a mandatory, indefinite life prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Caes was offered a plea agreement in January 1998 that would
have required him to serve 10 years in prison. But he refused the
offer and the following day tried to cut his wrists with a safety
razor. The fit led to a ruling that he was not competent to be
tried. Six months later, Langer ruled Caes had faked the earlier
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Modic writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
