<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BADUM-SLAYING     06-21 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BADUM-SLAYING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Hirsch said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part of the draw was Badum, who had joined the company two years
before the start of Go Silk. A big man with an equally big gift for
gab, Badum, who grew up in Hagerstown, Md., had a ready grasp of
books, films and current events, all of which enhanced his
popularity _ and the label's _ with editors and stores like Neiman
Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Doonan of Barneys said: ``Sixty percent of the motivation for
going up to Go Silk was to see John. The rest was to buy the
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch agreed that Badum's personality was critical to the
line's success. ``John was a very entertaining person,'' he said.
``He knew the best restaurants, the best shows, and he could always
get someone a reservation. He really became a driving force behind
the collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Badum had no equity in the company, Hirsch said, he was
well compensated, enough so that in 1995, as Go Silk's luster was
fading, Badum resigned, telling friends he would travel for a year.
But a year turned into several years as he wandered from England to
North Africa _ ``wafting around the world in a djellaba,'' as
Doonan put it _ and relied on a network of friends. From India, he
wrote that he was staying with a prince, and, Hirsch recalled,
``Thierry Mugler took care of him in the summertime in the Greek
islands.''
</P>
<P>
   If Badum thought he was losing ground professionally or was
jealous of the success of friends like Oldham, he didn't show it.
Recently he had spoken of starting a home furnishings catalog based
on things he had found abroad.
</P>
<P>
   A number of friends, including Beverly Mace's husband, Alan,
said they detected a pattern in Badum's romantic relationships, and
it involved younger, often foreign-born men of little or no means.
And, Mace said, Badum believed that because he was a large, portly
man ``it would be easier to find someone from another culture to
accept him physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Mace said he had advised his friend against an involvement with
Ouhda, because of the age and cultural differences. And, indeed,
Badum may have underestimated how Ouhda's traditional upbringing
might affect him when he arrived in New York in March and settled
into Ms. Badum's apartment in Batavia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Badum said the marriage had been her idea. ``I really felt
that this was a person for my brother,'' she said. She said she
continued to think so through March, as Ouhda and her brother, who
also stayed at the apartment sometimes, talked about buying a house
near Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   But by late April, Ms. Badum said, she began to see emotional
stress in Ouhda. On May 6, she recalled, he stormed out of the
apartment, saying: ``You don't own me. I'm free.'' He went to live
on a nearby farm, where he earned money, Ms. Badum said, milking
cows.
</P>
<P>
   Badum told Hirsch and others of the deterioration of the
relationship in the days before the murder. His shame about
misjudging Ouhda and his fear of putting his sister in legal
jeopardy seemed to weigh heavily on him, Hirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of May 29, Ouhda left Batavia and traveled by bus
to New York, where, Detective Dudek said, he waited for nine hours
outside Badum's apartment. Based on statements Ouhda had made to an
acquaintance in Batavia, the detectives concluded that he was
planning to kill Badum and then himself. But Badum was not in New
York: he had gone to Batavia to be with his sister. Around 5 p.m.,
she said, Ouhda telephoned her brother on his cell phone. He
sounded frantic, and from what Ms. Badum overheard, ``it seemed to
me that he wanted to go back to Morocco.'' She said her brother
tried to calm him, telling him to go to a hostel and that he would
see him in New York the next day. Badum then booked an airline
reservation on the Internet for Ouhda to return to Morocco on
Sunday, his sister said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the police said, Ouhda boarded a Trailways bus for
Batavia, arriving at 2:20 a.m. An hour and a half later, as a
police dispatcher was responding to a ``911'' call from the
apartment, Ouhda heaved a brick through a sliding glass door and
entered the kitchen. There, the police said, he turned on a light
and picked up two knives. He proceeded toward the bedroom,
shattering a plywood door into four pieces. Detective Dudek said,
``He went through this door like it wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial service two weeks later, Ms. Badum told the
gathering that her brother had saved her life. And it was true, the
police said: Badum had absorbed the brunt of Ouhda's fury. But this
is not what Badum's friends dwelled on _ how he was killed. Rather,
it was the way that Badum, unknown to the larger world, was one of
those behind-the-scenes figures in fashion who knew how to connect
the dots, make introductions and be present at the start of so many
careers. The way he was so much a part of their New York.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
