<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYWIDE-REPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOST IN COUNTRYWIDE'S EARNINGS ANTICIPATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ Countrywide Credit Industries Inc., the
nation's largest independent home mortgage lender, is expected
Tuesday to report a quarterly earnings increase of nearly 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus of 14 analysts surveyed by First Call put the
Calabasas-based company's earning at 88 cents a share vs. 78 cents
in the 1998 first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They also rate the company in northwestern L.A. County a strong
buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analysts are pretty positive on this one,'' said Chuck
Hill, First Call's research director.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly results will reflect the impact of Countrywide's
expansion of operations beyond its core home loan business.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the company branched out into the consumer
insurance business, offering a full range of products that include
home, life and auto coverage. The company does not underwrite the
policies but acts as an agent for major providers.
</P>
<P>
   But during this quarter, Countrywide said it would buy
Irvine-based Balboa Life and Casualty Insurance, which has 600
employees and wrote $234 million in policies during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Then in February, Countrywide and Woolwich PLC announced they
would form a European mortgage banking joint venture. Countrywide
will provide sophisticated technology and expertise to service the
portfolio held by Woolwich, which has operations throughout the
United Kingdom and in France and Italy. The joint venture will
market its services to other lenders. Woolwich's mortgage servicing
portfolio is worth $40 billion, with annual funding of about $10
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Houck, an analyst at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. said
Countrywide has a good interim growth strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been executed over a long period of time,'' he said of
the growth plan. ``And you've got a growing earnings stream with
limited downside.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people might be concerned that as the refinancing boom
winds down the company's earnings could take a hit. But Houck
expects this will be more than offset by profits from Countrywide's
huge loan servicing portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the earnings will drop off as the refinancing
boom tapers off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the February fourth quarter, Countrywide earned $102 million,
or 86 cents per share, on revenue of $532 million. That was up from
net income of $85.1 million, or 74 cents a share, on revenue of
$410 million in the 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   Countrywide shares closed at $45.25 on Monday, up $1.25, on
694,100 shares traded. That's about 50percent higher volume than
its 30-day average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
