<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATION-     06-21 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-DESEGREGATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS' SUIT SEEKS END TO RACE-BASED SCHOOL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Twenty-five years to the day a federal judge ordered
Boston to desegregate its public schools _ leading to one of the
most tumultuous and ugly chapters in the city's history _ a group
of parents asked a federal court Monday to abandon the last
remnants of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Saying four white students were unconstitutionally denied
entrance to schools because of their race, the lawsuit asks the
court to throw out a decade-old policy that assigns students to
schools based on choice and race.
</P>
<P>
   The suit comes as similar ones are filed around the country
asking federal courts to throw out any public student assignment
policy that uses race. The courts have largely been sympathetic to
such cases _ and in many cases have ordered entire desegregation
orders lifted in school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfair for my son to be denied anything because of his
race,'' said Rose O'Toole, one of the five plaintiffs and a mother
of a 4-year-old she says was denied entrance to his choice of
preschool because he was white. Boston's Children First, a
pro-neighborhood school group, spearheaded the lawsuit and also is
as a plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   The School Department and Mayor Thomas M. Menino's office
declined to comment on the 18-page lawsuit, saying it was received
too late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes after a three-year losing effort by Boston
public schools to defend race-based admission policies at their top
exam school. School officials argued that the educational value to
a diverse student body is so great, a race-based policy is needed
to ensure it.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court, however, ruled in December that the
city could not use race in assigning students to Boston Latin
School. Soon after, the School Committee abandoned a pledge to take
the case to the US Supreme Court, fearing it would lose the
precedent-setting case and jeopardize desegregation efforts around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   But how federal courts ultimately decide the latest Boston case
_ and the underlying question about the value of a diverse student
body _ could have implications for desegregation efforts
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The US Supreme Court has yet to rule on race-based admissions
policies in public school cases, although several cases are in the
pipeline and could eventually be chosen. The nation's highest court
already has ruled against using race in college-based admissions
and in awards for government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, courts were ruling much differently.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, 1974, federal Judge Arthur Garrity Jr. ruled the
Boston School Committee and the state Board of Education violated
the rights of black children under the 14th Amendment and ordered
desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was never the same. Racial tensions exploded in September
1974 when the first phase of busing began between Roxbury and South
Boston. Violent protests were commonplace, and Boston gained an
infamous entry in the nation's history books as a symbol of
desegration woes. Trouble continued through the years, and racial
tension occasionally flared, particularly in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1987, a federal appeals court said Boston schools were as
desegregated as possible. The school department was allowed to come
up with a new student assignment plan _ as long as it did not
return the city to segregated schools. The current plan, called
controlled choice, began in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, one of the designers of that plan, Michael Alves, said
controlled choice was intended in part to prevent discrimination,
not encourage it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenge the notion that this is intentionally designed to
discriminate against white students,'' said Alves, a national
desegregation specialist. ``It is also miscasting controlled
choice. It is not race-based. It is choice-based, and race is
factored in to ensure racial fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the city spends an estimated $17 million a year busing
students for racial balancing, out of a total busing budget of
about $48 million. The city does not break out the number of
students assigned to school based solely on race, using instead a
combination of choice and race.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's lawsuit against the city was filed by Boston lawyer
Chester Darling, who used the 1st Amendment to persuade the Supreme
Court to uphold the rights of organizers of the St. Patrick's Day
in South Boston to exclude a gay and lesbian group.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the lawsuit aims at returning the city to
neighborhood schools; its plaintiffs say parents and students will
feel more invested in the district if they attend schools closer to
home. The group says 25 years of desegregation efforts in Boston
have gotten rid of inequalities between schools _ but to the
detriment of all schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents the possibilities for the future,'' said Ann
Walsh, head of Boston's Children First. ``This is the beginning of
reform of a system in chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Menino recently endorsed the concept of neighborhood
schools and said he would build five more. The question left
unanswered: Will race be abandoned in assigning students to
schools?
</P>
<P>
   But those who argue for busing say it is not segregation by race
they fear anymore _ it is segregation by class. With neighborhood
schools, richer areas like West Roxbury could end up with better
schools than poorer areas such as Mattapan, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A drawback of not busing is that you will have a group of
children in nicer neighborhoods with parents that are involved in
the schools,'' said parent Terina Davulis of Dorchester. ``Students
in poorer neighborhoods where the schools are not as good will get
shortchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents remain split on whether busing should stay. ``I like the
idea of busing because your child can get exposed to different
children from different backgrounds,'' Davulis said.
</P>
<P>
   But Carl Askins, a parent from Jamaica Plain, believes busing
has destroyed ``the fabric of the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   And once new neighborhoods schools that can provide equal
resources are built, busing should end, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you would go to school in your
neighborhood, where everyone knew everyone's child and the
neighborhood would keep you in line,'' Askins said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Kayce Ataiyero contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
