<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNG-CANCER-SPI &LR;      06-21 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNG-CANCER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH, TOBACCO FIRMS LINK IN SEARCH OF LUNG CANCER THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A Seattle biotechnology company, Corixa Corp., has
entered into a research partnership with one of the world's largest
cigarette makers, Japan Tobacco Inc., to develop a therapy for lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Corixa expects to receive more than $40 million from Japan
Tobacco in return for granting the company _ the third largest
cigarette manufacturer worldwide _ rights to the biotech company's
experimental immunologic treatments for lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lung cancer is the leading cause of cancer death of people
worldwide,'' said Mark McDade, president and chief operating
officer for Corixa. ``From a market standpoint, it's an obvious
target.''
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of anti-tobacco activists, however, the
partnership between a biomedical company and a tobacco merchant is
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obscene,'' said Dr. Michael Lippman, a Seattle family
practice physician and president of the anti-smoking advocacy group
Washington DOC. ``If Japan Tobacco wants to combat lung cancer,
they should just go out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Astrid Berg, executive director of the Washington state branch
of the American Lung Association, criticized Corixa for claiming to
be ``committed to saving lives and preventing diseases'' while
entering into partnership with one of the world's leading tobacco
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a little bit weird,'' Berg said. ``Here's a
company that purports to want to save lives and they strike a deal
with the agent that's responsible for creating the disease ... It's
a deal with the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Steven Gillis, chief executive officer at Corixa, and
McDade said they were surprised at the criticism, noting that
Corixa's partnership deal is only with the pharmaceutical division
of Japan Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Hironori Mizuguchi, a spokesman for Japan Tobacco in Tokyo, said
his company has diversified into numerous other fields and
products, some of which have nothing to do with tobacco
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the different divisions have their own business
missions,'' Mizuguchi said. He said Japan Tobacco, which calls
itself JT in its non-tobacco operations, decided to partner with
Corixa because of its interest in incorporating more biotechnology
into its pharmaceutical business.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Tobacco is becoming one of the bigger pharmaceutical
companies in Japan, McDade said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have top-notch researchers there ... We think it's going
to be a solid partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillis, who helped found Immunex prior to launching Corixa, said
it is simplistic to criticize Japan Tobacco for trying to shift its
business from tobacco into biomedical research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many pharmaceutical companies developed initially as producers
of chemicals, chemicals used to kill,'' he said. The chemical
weapon known as mustard gas, Gillis noted, eventually gave rise to
some of today's chemotherapy drugs. Japan Tobacco should be lauded
for supporting drug development, he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. tobacco manufacturers, though many have diversified into
food and other industries, so far do not appear to have invested
heavily in pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1994, Corixa focuses on using immune system therapies
to combat cancer and other diseases. Corixa researchers have been
exploring, among other things, experimental therapeutic
``vaccines'' aimed at treatment rather than prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In its research partnership with Japan Tobacco, Corixa
scientists have just started a program aimed at identifying how to
boost the immune system's response and therapeutic reaction to lung
cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Corixa's policy of finding financial partners
early in development to speed commercialization, the local biotech
company has given Japan Tobacco exclusive rights in North America
and Japan to market the lung cancer therapies Corixa hopes to
develop in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian firm, Zambon Group, has an agreement with Corixa to
market the same potential lung cancer therapies in Europe. In
China, Zambon and Japan Tobacco would share licensing rights.
</P>
<P>
   The goal at Corixa, McDade said, is to get the financial backing
needed to develop an effective lung cancer therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For big pharmaceutical companies, if they don't have an
exclusive right to sell the product they're not necessarily going
to give it a priority development and marketing effort,'' he said.
If Japan Tobacco or Zambon choose not to market the therapy, the
licensing rights revert to Corixa.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman and other critics said it's no surprise that a tobacco
maker might want to invest in a potential new treatment for lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make money causing the illness and then they get to make
more money selling a treatment for the illness,'' Lippman said.
``It's a great deal for Japan Tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the claims of diversification, Lippman quotes from Japan
Tobacco's web page describing tobacco as the company's ``core
business.'' On the page describing the company's interest in
pharmaceuticals, the company states that it ``encountered
pharmaceuticals through our studies toward acquiring a total
balance in human health.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan Tobacco's Mizuguchi said his company does not believe it's
been conclusively demonstrated that tobacco is the leading cause of
lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not proved that smoking is the sole cause of lung
cancer,'' Mizuguchi said. ``But we don't deny the possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association attributes almost nine out of 10
cases of lung cancer to smoking tobacco in the U.S. The World
Health Organization has reported that aggressive marketing of
tobacco in Asia has doubled consumption in the region since the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said it's clear the company intends to continue
aggressively marketing cigarettes and smoking even if it also
intends to become a player in the ``lung cancer market.''
</P>
<P>
   John Banzhaf, executive director of the Washington, D.C.-based
Action on Smoking and Health, said Japan Tobacco may have a real
interest in the pharmaceutical business but there are other
possible reasons a tobacco company might want to support research
into treatments for lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may think that they're going to soon have this vaccine
for lung cancer so, gee, I guess I can go ahead and smoke,''
Banzhaf said. ``At the very least, the industry can at least appear
to demonstrate that they're doing something about the health
risks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
