<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-SOUTHCAROLINA-CO     06-21 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SOUTHCAROLINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush calls for abstinence programs at latest campaign stopBy Ken
Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ He's conquered Texas politics and cakewalked
to the front of the presidential field. Now Gov. George W. Bush is
ready to go head-to-head with the influential forces of nature. He
has long supported sexual abstinence for unmarried couples, and on
Monday he announced that if he's elected president the federal
government would channel as much money into abstinence education as
it spends on sex education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The twin epidemics of teen pregnancy and sexually transmitted
disease are a major problem for the future of America,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants government spending on abstinence programs, now $62
million a year, to equal the amount spent on contraception
programs, now about $135 million a year. He also said the two
programs must be taught separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like to me the contraceptive message sends a
contradictory message,'' he said. ``It tends to undermine the
message of abstinence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments came after he sat in on a course, offered by
Heritage Community Services, that teaches teens the risks of sex.
Bush's battle plan against premarital sex also includes an end ``to
hostile regulations and bureaucratic rules'' that deter religious
groups from seeking federal grants for abstinence programs, and a
long-term study to measure the effectiveness of all abstinence
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes, he said, are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for the American dream to touch a life if you've
had a baby out of wedlock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Monday began a five-day tour that also will take him to
Virginia, Washington, Pennsylvania, Michigan and Florida. In
Washington today Bush will visit Capitol Hill and hold a
fund-raiser that's expected to bring in more than $1.5 million, a
record for a presidential fund-raiser in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina primary, scheduled for Feb. 19, will be the
fourth contest, and the first in the South, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has solid support here, including endorsements from Sen.
Strom Thurmond, Lt. Gov. Bob Peeler, House Speaker David Wilkins
and more than 50 state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, Bush will lose support from eight South Carolina
legislators he thought were on his side. The eight were among those
who signed a February letter urging Bush to run and calling him
``the best candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Those eight, with nine colleagues, today will endorse Arizona
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suddenly became clear to a lot of us that the Republican
nomination should be earned not inherited,'' said McCain backer
Terry Haskins, speaker pro tem of the South Carolina House. ``And
John McCain is the one whose life of service really stands out.''
</P>
<P>
   Haskins was not one of the lawmakers who signed the February
letter encouraging Bush to run.
</P>
<P>
   Another South Carolina lawmaker who signed the February letter
to Bush opted earlier this month to endorse Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler, co-chairman of the Bush campaign here, discounted the
importance of the lawmakers' shift to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's making a mountain of a molehill,'' he said, noting that
more than half of the state's GOP lawmakers are Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's South Carolina stops also highlighted a key Bush asset:
Through his political and family ties he knows people everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sunset Restaurant in Columbia, where Bush spent an hour
shaking hands, he chatted with Toddy Atwater, mother of the late
Lee Atwater, who was the political guru behind the elder George
Bush's successful 1988 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He learned under the best, under Lee,'' Mrs. Atwater said
after Bush talked with her. ``He has learned from his dad, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening, Bush showed another valuable asset: the ability
to raise money. He expected to raise about $175,000 at a reception
at the Spartanburg-Greenville Airport, one of 13 such events
scheduled this week.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Bush said he supported the gun-control measure that
died in a political crossfire in Congress last week. He also
defended his decision to sign into law a measure barring cities
from filing lawsuits against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (gun) manufacturers have manufactured a legal product. I
think the people who need to be held liable are the criminals who
misuse a legal product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said lawsuits filed against gun makers are different than
the suits _ including one filed by the state of Texas _ against
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies were deceptive about their product, and
their product _ while legally used _ caused disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
