<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS STALL BILL TO FORCE CONSIDERATION OF PATIENTS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, was forced to set aside an agricultural spending bill on
Monday after Democrats sought to attach to it a broad proposal for
changes in managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   While those maneuverings were highly technical, the implications
were not. Democrats were serving notice that new protections for
patients enrolled in health maintenance organizations were among
their uppermost priorities, and that they were willing to disrupt
other Senate business to compel consideration of the issue as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for their part, were confronted with another
roadblock in their intermittently hobbled efforts _ more so in the
House than in the Senate _ to make good on promises to shepherd
spending bills through Congress with dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals for federally mandated changes in managed health care
_ or for what has come to be known on Capitol Hill as a patient's
bill of rights _ have been simmering on a back burner for several
years now.
</P>
<P>
   But in the House as well as the Senate, Democrats are turning up
the heat, eager to be seen as the principal champions of a popular
issue as the 2000 elections draw ever nearer. In the House,
Democrats this week began putting their names on a petition to
force a patient's bill of rights to the floor in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was with the same goal that Senate Democrats staged their
maneuver, which they said Lott could expect again on other pieces
of legislation unrelated to health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be facing it on every bill that comes along,''
said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass. ``This legislation will come to
the floor, and it'll come either in an orderly fashion or a
disorderly fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican proposal on managed care was voted out of committee
three months ago. It would have created new ways for patients to
appeal the coverage decisions of insurers, but Democrats complained
that it did not go far enough. For example, it did not eliminate
the hurdles that prevent patients from suing HMOs for denials of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said on Monday that Democrats would get a chance on the
Senate floor to amend that bill, but not before they narrowed their
wish list to a limited number of amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go,'' Lott said on Monday, referring to himself
and other Senate Republicans. But, he added, ``there must be some
reasonable understanding, some reasonable agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader, said
that the kinds of constraints that Lott has suggested, like a limit
of five amendments for each party, are inappropriate for
legislation that would affect scores of millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle also said that Republicans were trying to truncate the
debate as a way of preventing any close examination of Republican
versus Democratic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symmetry with the gun legislation is really evident,''
Daschle said, still reveling in his party's victory in prolonging
that debate in the Senate and persuading several Republicans to
alter their initial views.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
