<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURDISH REBEL LEADER TO SPEAK WHEN TRIAL RESUMES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The trial of the Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan is scheduled to resume on Wednesday after a 15-day
break; he could be sentenced to death within days.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers are expected to sum up their case when the court
reconvenes at the prison island of Imrali. The defendant is then
expected to make a statement. A quick guilty verdict is widely
expected on the charge of treason, which carries an automatic death
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Until the trial began last month, almost every Turkish
commentator and politician predicted that the death sentence would
be carried out. Many still believe so, but after Ocalan's
surprising testimony on the opening day of his trial, there are
dissenting voices.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Ocalan said he regretted the violence his
rebels have used in their 15-year campaign against the Turkish
state. He said that if he is allowed to live he would work with the
authorities to bring his guerrillas down from the mountains and
work for a peaceful settlement of the Kurdish problem in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no official response from government or military
leaders, but some commentators have suggested that Ocalan's
sincerity should be put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's guerrilla group, the Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK,
has said it will pursue ``total war'' if he is hanged. But it
endorsed his call for a peaceful solution and suggested that it was
ready to turn itself into a political organization.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Turkey's legal Kurdish political party, People's
Democracy, also endorsed Ocalan's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``A historic opportunity was born on Imrali,'' the party said in
a statement. ``The proposals of a solution to build social peace
are proposals we have advocated from the beginning. These proposals
are the only way out of the dead-end in which the nation finds
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the head of the German secret service urged that
Ocalan not be hanged, and said he hoped that German diplomats in
Ankara would do whatever possible to prevent an execution. Several
million Turks live in Germany, including many of Kurdish descent,
and the German authorities, like those in other European countries,
fear outbursts of violence if Ocalan is hanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it is not likely that the PKK would turn to
immediate violence, the execution of Ocalan would strengthen the
PKK and lead it to step up its campaign,'' Peter Frisch, who heads
the Office for the Protection of the Constitution, told a Berlin
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Although the death penalty remains on the books in Turkey, the
last execution here was 15 years ago. To be carried out, all death
sentences must be ratified by Parliament and the president. Senior
military officers might be able to exercise decisive influence if
they wished.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that may be lurking in the back of some minds here is
the Istanbul summit meeting in November of the Conference for
Security and Cooperation in Europe. The meeting is expected to
attract leaders from throughout Europe, in addition to President
Clinton, and the authorities view it as a chance to project
Turkey's image. They are anxious that the climate in Istanbul be
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   In line with an action of Parliament on Friday, a civilian judge
who has been present at every session of Ocalan's trial will
replace the military judge when proceedings resume.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
