<SLUG> BC-FOREST-MERGER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEYERHAEUSER TO ACQUIRE MACMILLAN BLOEDEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN AND JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two of the oldest names in the Pacific Northwest's
forest products industry are combining to make one of North
America's biggest timber and paper companies even larger.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser Co. said Monday it will pay nearly $2.5 billion in
stock for MacMillan Bloedel Ltd., one of Canada's largest forest
products companies.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition by the Federal Way, Wash.-based forest products
multi-national giant raised concerns among Canada's
environmentalists and nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is significant not just for its size, or for the fact
that it means the end of the MacMillan Bloedel name as an
independent company (although it may survive on products or an
operating division of subsidiary).
</P>
<P>
   It also signals the hastening consolidation of the forest
products industry, a trend that analysts say could mean more
cross-border deals. And environmentalists are concerned it could
mean an end to the Canadian company's shift toward more
environmentally friendly practices.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser will pay .28 shares of its stock for each share of
MacMillan Bloedel's stock. The deal needs the approval of MacMillan
Bloedel shareholders and regulators in the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting company will have annual sales of about $13
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser, already the world's largest producer of softwood
lumber and market pulp and the second largest manufacturer of
oriented strand board (a panel made by glue together large wood
chips), will become one of the world's biggest makers of cardboard
boxes. Already a major player in Canada, Weyerhaeuser would likely
become the largest forest products company in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser chief executive Steven Rogel declined to say how
many layoffs might result from combining the two companies,
including their corporate offices in Vancouver. But he said cost
savings from layoffs were not a major consideration in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser does think it can save $150 million a year in other
ways. For example, by combining the mills and box plants of the two
companies, it can cut millions every year in transportation costs
of shipping linerboard and corrugating medium from mills to the
plants where they're assembled into cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the specific gains for Weyerhaeuser, the deal is being
driven by major trends reshaping the industry. ``We want to create
a company out of this that is a global leader,'' Rogel told a news
conference in Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of companies in the forest products industry have the same
thing in mind, which is why there's been a flurry of big deals,
including Jefferson Smurfit Corp. combining with Stone Container
Corp. and International Paper acquiring Union Camp Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Rogel said consolidation is driven in part by what he called
``big-box syndrome,'' the growth of such giant retailers as Home
Depot and Wal-Mart. Companies that hope to supply those retailers
with merchandise have to be big themselves, ``if not globally at
least North American.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also the result of an industry marked by wide cyclical
swings, too much capacity in certain product lines and poor returns
compared to other industries. ``It's an industry that's ripe for
consolidation,'' said Paul Latta, analyst with McAdams Wright Ragen
Inc. in Seattle. ``It's fairly fragmented and there's little price
control.''
</P>
<P>
   To cope, most companies have decided to ``be large in particular
product lines rather than everything,'' said Susan Ryan Goodman,
analyst with the bond rating agency Fitch IBCA. Companies have also
decided they'll achieve the necessary size by buying other
companies, which is much less expensive than building new mills
that aren't needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every company is focusing on fewer businesses in which
it can excel,'' Rogel said. Weyerhaeuser itself recently announced
a deal to sell operations making particleboard and medium density
fiberboard, deciding it would never be big enough in those products
to make it worth the management time and investment capital
required.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser's stock price declined $2.63 to $67.13 yesterday.
The stock price of an acquiring company typically declines
immediately following a merger, as investors worry about how well
the combination will be carried out. Analyst Terry Schumacher with
Black &AMP; Co. in Portland said investors may also be wary that the
deal moves Weyerhaeuser into Coastal British Columbia, meaning more
exposure to environmental battles and to the still-fragile Asian
market.
</P>
<P>
   While the two companies hope to complete their deal by fall, it
could run into turbulence on several fronts, starting with the
traditional discomfort over selling a company, particularly one
with MacMillan Bloedel's history, to foreign interests,
particularly American.
</P>
<P>
   As British Columbia's best-known forest products company,
Macmillan Bloedel has long been a symbol _ notably to Canadian
nationalists who want British Columbia trees cut down by a British
Columbia company.
</P>
<P>
   Former B.C. Premier Dave Barrett termed the company's
acquisition by Weyerhaeuser ``a terrible mistake. ... If we are
going to maintain a Canadian identity, core parts of our economy
should be owned by Canadians, particularly in our resources
industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a job loss, a loss of Canadian identity, and it makes
Weyerhaeuser too big a player in our own forest industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been non-Canadian firms in our forests,''
Barrett acknowledged. ``But what always follows acquisition is
consolidation of head offices, loss of significant skills through
job integration.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact MacMillan Bloedel has already been substantially
transformed by an American _ Tom Stephens, the company's president
and chief executive who was recruited by MacMillan Bloedel a year
and a half ago to turn around the financially struggling company.
Stephens sold off such pieces as MacMillan-Bloedel's pulp and paper
operations, and his downsizing helped return the company to
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential source of contention is environmental
disputes. MacMillan-Bloedel is the flagship name in British
Columbia's forest products industry, but as such has spent the
1990s under fire over the cutting of old growth forests in Canada's
Pacific province.
</P>
<P>
   While possessive toward Macmillan Bloedel, British Columbians
have not hesitated to protest against it. The company has been in
the vortex of three landmark environmental controversies. These
are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Carmanah: A small Vancouver Island coastal valley, marked for
logging by the company, was discovered to hold 300-foot-tall trees,
the tallest in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clayoquot Sound: Bearing Canadian flags, protesters set out
every morning during the summer of 1993 for the Kennedy River
bridge, the main logging access to valleys of Clayoquot Sound,
least-logged of Vancouver Island's great coastal fjords. The
government eventually accepting recommendations of a scientific
panel that there be no more clearcutting in Clayoquot Sound.
</P>
<P>
   _ Land Swap: MacMillan Bloedel has lost a considerable amount of
cutting rights with the provincial government's decisions to create
23 new provincial parks on Vancouver Island, and to preserve a few
unlogged valleys on British Columbia's lower mainland.The
provincial government has proposed to compensate the company by
giving it to 74,100-acres of public land. Environmentalists have
packed public meetings to protest the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also the first major British Columbia forest
products firm to make changes in response to threatened
international boycotts of B.C. forest products firms. Stephens,
last year announced it would phase out clearcut logging and seek
international certification of its operations as environmentally
sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens also took his company out of the B.C. Forest Alliance,
an industry-funded public relations group known for its use of
heavyhanded tactics against environmental protests and critical
press coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Stephens has de-fossilized the company. MacMillan Bloedel
has changed its way of doing business, and I hope this continues
under the new configuration,'' said George Smith of the Canadian
Parks and Wilderness Society.
</P>
<P>
   Asked repeatedly at the Vancouver news conference, Rogel refused
to say whether Weyerhaeuser would back up MacMillan Bloedel's
commitment to end clearcutting in coastal forests in five years,
saying only that Weyerhaeuser would study the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
