<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JUNE 22
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-BOMB-SUSPECTS-NYT (moved on Friday, May 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, May 21,
about the indictment of Ihab M. Ali as part of the investigation of
Osama bin Laden misstated the charge against Mr. Ali. It is civil
contempt, for refusal to testify before the grand jury, not
perjury. The case is being handled under a court order of secrecy,
and the new information was confirmed only yesterday. Later
developments are reported today on page B4.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-NYT (moved on Tuesday, April 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, April 20,
about the massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.,
referred incorrectly to a person who was quoted as having said in a
telephone call to a television station, `I just can't believe it is
happening at my school.'' The caller told the station that he was
Bob Sapin, a Columbine student, and he was so identified in the
article. But last week a spokeswoman for the Jefferson County
School District said that no one with that name had been enrolled
at Columbine High, and the identity of the caller remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-PLANE-CRASH-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 8,
about the crash of an American Airlines jet at Little Rock, Ark.,
misstated the workings of the system for automatic operation of the
wing devices that reduce lift after a plane touches down. The
system deploys the devices, called spoilers, after the wheels make
firm contact with the ground and begin spinning, not when the
wheels stop spinning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
