-- Fred Meeks at home, right, and in a photo taken during World War
II where he served with the Navy. During the war an explosion on a
segregated naval base killed 320 men. After the accident, black
sailors were ordered to resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty
of the sailors, Meeks among them, refused and were court-martialed
by an all-white panel after being found guilty of mutiny. Now, in
an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for Meeks have filed for a
presidential pardon arguing that the black sailors failed to follow
orders out of legitimate fear and had no intent to mutiny. (Monica
