<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-COKE-NYT &LR;      06-21 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-COKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA CHAIRMAN USES ADS TO APOLOGIZE TO BELGIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chairman of Coca-Cola Co. apologized to the people of
Belgium in extraordinarily contrite newspaper ads Tuesday over a
contamination scare that began there more than a week ago and
spread to other countries in Europe. But he stopped short of
conceding that Coca-Cola products made anyone sick, and a study
released by the company suggested something else had caused their
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those people who suffered, especially the children, my
colleagues and I want to express a very sincere apology,'' the
chairman, M. Douglas Ivester, said in the ads, printed in Flemish
and French. ``We strive to make sure that Coca-Cola always stands
for good feelings, and we regret that it instead resulted in
feelings of illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's statement was more penitent than his first apology
issued last Wednesday, after health authorities in four European
countries had already yanked Coca-Cola drinks from store shelves in
the biggest recall in the company's 113-year history. Ivester,
responding belatedly to a public outcry over how the company was
handling the mess, had said he was sorry for any problems and
promised an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that investigation was made public by the company Monday
in a toxicologist's report. It concluded that substances like
hydrogen sulfide were present in Coca-Cola soft drinks that people
drank before coming down with symptoms like nausea and headaches,
but that the amounts were too tiny to have caused illness.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's efforts to end its image crisis came as officials
from the European Union said they wanted to review all data on the
causes of the scare. That could prolong the ban on Coca-Cola
products, which entered its eighth day Monday in Belgium and began
last Tuesday in Luxembourg, the Netherlands and France.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, a total ban on Coke products remained in
Luxembourg; France and Belgium allowed the sale of some brands, but
not Coca-Cola, Fanta or Sprite _ the company's biggest sellers. In
the Netherlands, products shipped through Belgium remained
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola had a run-in with the European Union this year over
its $1.85 billion plan to acquire Cadbury Schweppes brands around
the world. After delays and bureaucratic hurdles, including some
presented by the European Union, Coca-Cola announced a
trimmed-back, $1.1 billion plan in which it would buy Cadbury
Schweppes brands almost everywhere except in the countries included
in the union.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola intensified its public relations effort in European
newspapers Monday, purchasing full-page ads published in France,
Italy and Spain. The French ads, which ran in Le Monde and
Liberation, among others, included a toll-free telephone number for
people with safety questions. The ads were signed by the president
of Coca-Cola France, Daniel Malcorps, and the president of
Coca-Cola Enterprises in France, Dominique Reiniche.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ivester said he met last week with James Burke,
the former Johnson &AMP; Johnson chairman who helped that company
weather a crisis caused by cyanide-laced Tylenol in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Coke is stepping up to the line and accepting
responsibility, which is an excellent way to preserve and enhance
credibility and trust among consumers,'' said John Sicher,
publisher of Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not stopped the slide in Coca-Cola's stock, which
fell almost 3 percent Monday, to $61.5625, partly on concern about
the ban's effects on sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, there is only a limited impact,'' said Marc
Cohen, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``But what is of concern
is that this isn't happening in the depths of winter. It's
happening in the peak sales period.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen reduced his per-share profit estimates for the current
quarter by 1 cent for Coca-Cola and 2 cents for Coca-Cola
Enterprises, the company's biggest bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst, Martin Romm of Credit Suisse First Boston, has
estimated that Coca-Cola Enterprises is losing $3.4 million in
revenue a day as a result of the ban. Coca-Cola is expected to
announce second-quarter volume estimates, an important earnings
indicator, early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who has been in Belgium off and on since Friday, sent a
lengthy companywide memo Monday in which he announced that he would
apologize. ``You need to know the context in which our issue is
unfolding,'' he wrote to the more than 28,000 Coca-Cola workers
around the world, calling the mood in Europe ``understandably
sensitive and cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller stores in affected countries have not removed all
of the banned products, shoppers said. One sign of the publicity
surrounding Coca-Cola's travails is on the Pont d'Iena in Paris,
where one resident reported that soft-drink vendors who normally
charge 15 francs for a cold Coke have now dropped the price _ to 5
francs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
