says. ``All it takes is a little vision.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1999 -- NY-MOVIE-STUDIO-1, 6-21 --
Despite endorsements from Robert De Niro and Harvey Weinstein, the
future remains uncertain for a plan to build sound stages at the
Brooklyn Navy Yard. Regardless, there is no question that there has
never been more interest in building movie studios in New York
since the industry left for California at the beginning of the
century. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- June 21, 1999 -- BLACK-SAILOR-PARDON, 6-21
-- Fred Meeks at home, right, and in a photo taken during World War
II where he served with the Navy. During the war an explosion on a
segregated naval base killed 320 men. After the accident, black
sailors were ordered to resume loading ammunition onto ships. Fifty
of the sailors, Meeks among them, refused and were court-martialed
by an all-white panel after being found guilty of mutiny. Now, in
an extraordinary legal battle, lawyers for Meeks have filed for a
presidential pardon arguing that the black sailors failed to follow
orders out of legitimate fear and had no intent to mutiny. (Monica
Almeida, right/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PEC, Yugoslavia -- June 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NATO-2, 6-21
-- A Serbian woman who returned to Kosovo from Montenegro speaks to
NATO soldiers inside a fenced security zone set up on the grounds
of an auto parts factory on Monday. About 70 Serbs returned to the
region from Montenegro on Monday. Returning refugees are being
protected by NATO forces against reprisals by local ethnic
Albanians. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times) (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PEC, Yugoslavia -- June 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NATO, 6-21 --
Ethnic Albanian children watch as a car full of Serbs drive past
under the protection of NATO forces on Monday. About 70 Serbs
returned to the region from Montenegro. Returning refugees are
being protected by NATO forces against reprisals by local ethnic
Albanians. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- June 21, 1999 -- SCI-WOMEN-IN-ENGINEERING-B&AMP;W,
6-21 --Dr. Eleanor Baum, dean of engineering at Cooper Union, has
not forgotten how ``very conspicuous, very alone'' she felt as an
engineering student. In a time when the words affirmative action
are unmentionable in some corners of academia, Dr. Baum, the first
woman to head an engineering college any where, is running a
one-woman affirmative action campaign that is transforming
engineering. (Rockefeller University/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- June 21, 1999 --SCI-INFECTION-THE-GAME, 6-21
-- Infection, a new board game which is sort of a cross between
Monopoly and Trivial Pursuit, pits from two to nine people against
one another on a playing field run rampant with disease. The first
player who is completely cured or, in a less hopeful scenario, is
the only one left alive -- wins. (Tony Cenicolla/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
