<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-OWNERS-MEETING-NY     06-21 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-OWNERS-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NHL GETS RID OF CREASE REPLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than two days after the Dallas Stars won the Stanley Cup in
the third overtime on a goal from inside the goalie's crease, the
National Hockey League eliminated the use of video replay Monday to
determine crease violations on goals, shifting the responsibility
to on-ice officials instead.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bettman, the NHL commissioner, said the rule change made by
the board of governors had nothing to do with Brett Hull's disputed
goal against Buffalo but was made from a desire to regain some of
the time and spontaneity lost to review. He said the delays caused
by the video system made fans unsure about whether to cheer an
apparent goal, a situation the league found disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To rely on replay too much isn't good,'' Bettman said. ``The
fact that so many people didn't understand the rule and how it was
applied in that situation _ and that you had controversy on a
correct call _ simply cemented the fact that there was a better way
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the replay rule was placed on the agenda of
Monday's board of governors meeting last week and that he had
discussed the change since February with Colin Campbell, the
league's director of hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule was fine,'' Bettman said. ``It doesn't have
inconsistencies and it deals with zero tolerance.'' But he added,
``It's not as good a rule as the alternative, and we needed to make
a change.''
</P>
<P>
   On-ice officials will now have complete discretion on
man-in-the-crease calls, which will create the leeway to wave away
incidental intrusions into the crease that do not interfere with
the goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're leaving the crease to a judgment call,'' Bettman said,
adding, ``This way is better for the game and better for the
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Confusion reigned after Hull's goal, at 14 minutes 51 seconds of
the third overtime, even as Dallas players celebrated their 2-1
victory on the Marine Midland Arena ice in the early hours of
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The referees did not seek a review from the video judge,
although NHL officials said that they reviewed the tape several
times. They subsequently told the incensed Buffalo Coach Lindy Ruff
that although Hull's left skate preceded the puck into the crease,
Hull had continuous possession and the goal was legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule was absolutely, correctly applied,'' Bettman said.
``It was a non-issue. Everyone understands it was the right call.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Ruff was still irate about the goal. He said his
players wanted the league to use the familiar procedure for
reviewing man-in-the-crease goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to hear the horn sound,'' Ruff said. ``They wanted
to hear the announcer say, `This goal is under review.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although the video judge will no longer rule on
man-in-the-crease violations, he will still determine whether the
puck crosses the goal line, whether it crosses the goal line before
the cage is dislodged and whether it crosses the goal line before
time expired. He will also decide if the puck is directed into the
net by a hand or a foot; whether the puck deflected into the net
off an official and whether the puck is directed into the net by a
high stick. Video review will also continue to be used to establish
the correct time on the game clock.
</P>
<P>
   Video review has been used by the NHL since the 1991-92 season,
at the request of the referees. It was originally instituted to
protect goaltenders from injury but often drew criticism because
many goals were disallowed by infractions that were incidental to
the play, such as a teammate's skate in the crease away from the
action.
</P>
<P>
   For this past season, the policy was expanded to let the video
judge determine whether there was a man in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   The board of governors made two other major changes, altering
scoring and manpower during regular-season overtime periods.
Starting next season, each team will be awarded a point for a tie
after regulation. In a move to promote more offensive
aggressiveness, an extra point will be awarded to the winner in the
five-minute overtime period. In addition, overtime will be played
with four skaters a side, which is designed to create a more open
offensive flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have teams now that just want to play for the tie,''
Bettman said. ``From a fans standpoint this is going to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   In a test of the format during the final 243 games of the
American Hockey League's 1998-99 season, 27 of the 44 overtime
games were played to a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The league also voted to increase the number of games officiated
under the two-referee system from 270 last season to 700.
</P>
<P>
   And the league approved the purchase of the Washington Capitals
by Ted Leonsis, Jon Ledecky and Richard Patrick from Abe Pollin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
