<P>
   (NYT18) CHICAGO -- June 21, 1999 -- CORCORAN-GEHRY, 6-21 -- The
Corcoran Gallery of Art has selected Frank Gehry, right, as the
winner of a competition to design a new wing for its historic
Beaux-Arts building one block west of the White House. The addition
would nearly double the space that houses the museum and the
Corcoran School of Art. Gehry looked over the Millennium Park
Project with Ed Uhlir, the projects manager, in late April. Gehry
was asked to design the new performance bandshell and a walkway at
the park which will be adjacent to the Chicago Art Insistitute.
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) GRACE, Yugoslavia -- June 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-2, 6-21
-- An ethnic Albanian carries a piece of electrical equipment near
a burning house on Monday in the village which was inhabited
predominantly by Serbs. NATO forces commander Lt. Gen. Michael
Jackson apologized on Monday for widespread looting and burning of
Serbian homes in the region. The looting occured in some instances
under the watch of NATO troops. Referring in particular to the
village of Grace, Jackson said, ``On that occasion we fell short of
what I would have wanted.'' (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- June 21, 1999 -- MERGERS-SHIPLEY, 6-21 --
Walter Shipley, who retired as Chase's chief executive on June 1
but will remain chairman for an undetermined time, has some advice
for deal meisters hoping to ride America's merger wave:
slash-and-burn takeovers will come back to haunt you. ``Some
people's philosophy is I win, you lose,'' he says. ``Our philosophy
is that the best is when both sides feel they've come out
winners.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP, 6-21
-- A rebel with the Kosovo Liberation Army walks past a restaurant
on Monday. The agreement reached early Monday to disband the KLA
included, at the insistence of its commanders, a pledge by the NATO
allies to consider letting the rebels form a provisional army for
Kosovo modeled on the National Guard in the United States. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
