<SLUG> BC-FINBUDGET-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, June 22, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FOR SF CHRONICLE PAGE ONE &QL;  &LR; 
ALZA _ &UR;  &LR;  In the latest and largest in a series of drug industry
buyouts of Bay Area firms, Illinois-based Abbott Laboratories said
yesterday it will acquire Palo Alto-based Alza Corp. for $7.3
billion in stock. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FOR BUSINESS &QL;  &LR; 
MCKESSON _ In a dramatic corporate housecleaning, McKesson HBOC
Inc. fired five top executives and forced two others to resign, as
the beleaguered drug wholesaler made its strongest move yet to
repair the damage caused by an accounting scandal that has cut its
stock value in half. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   BILLS &UR; _  &LR; Electronic billing and payment is moving to another
stage. Microsoft, through its alliance with TransPoint, is making
it possible for consumers to receive and pay their bills online. By
Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   MONEYBAG &UR;  &LR; _ Investment advice from columnist Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   RICOCHET _ Metricom, which makes a popular wireless modem called
Ricochet, got a $600 million boost today from MCI WorldCom and Paul
Allen's Vulcan Ventures. The two companies will provide Metricom,
the privately-held Los Gatos firm $300 million each to fund a
national rollout of its Ricochet 128 kbps mobile data service. By
Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   PHONES &UR;  &LR;  _ The never-ending quest by advertisers to pitch
products has taken a new turn. An Alameda company is unveiling a
technology tomorrow that lets retailers hawk their wares to
customers via their digital cell phones. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
