<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-EXPO-COX     06-21 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-EXPO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security tops lists of concerns as computer industry meets at
expo
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ U.S. companies and government agencies lose at least
$100 million a year because of hackers, viruses and even employees
who breach their computer security systems.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands more companies remain blithely unaware of the
threat to their databases.
</P>
<P>
   That's the word Internet security experts are spreading at PC
Expo, the annual trade show for the computer industry, being held
in New York through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is expected to be one of the dominant topics at
this year's expo.
</P>
<P>
   Also on participants' minds is the increasingly intense price
competition in the PC business that is starting to show on the
bottom lines of some companies. Round Rock, Texas-based Dell
Computer Corp.'s growth, for instance, has slipped below 50 percent
for two consecutive quarters. And Compaq Computer Corp., already
facing a bevy of other problems, recently warned it may lose $250
million in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Chairman Michael Dell has scheduled a briefing with
journalists today, when he is expected to talk about steps his
company is taking to respond to changes in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, however, talk was of security. Recent studies have shown
that concerns about prying eyes are keeping millions of consumers
and businesses from buying more over the Internet. And recent
reports of viruses that invade and damage databases add to those
worries, said Scott Schnell of Security Dynamics, a Boston-area
company that sells security systems.
</P>
<P>
   While the PC hardware companies are coping with lower pricing
with varying degrees of success, the security software business is
growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and government agencies spent $3.1 billion on security
software last year and will increase that to $4.2 billion in 1999
and to $7.4 billion by 2002, according to a recent International
Data Corp. study.
</P>
<P>
   Schnell said simple security systems that require only passwords
for employees or customers to log into a business's database have
numerous cracks that invite trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the weaknesses stem from human nature, such as the
tendency to forget passwords. In response to password
proliferation, employees often use the name of a spouse, child or
pet to gain access. Or they write the password on notes and affix
them to their desks or cubicle walls where they easily can be seen,
Schnell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rely on people to take a reasonable password and be
secure,'' Schnell said.
</P>
<P>
   More reliable security systems use small devices, tokens, that
generate a random sequence of numbers that, with the password, make
a two-step security system. Some companies are offering a third
option involving recognition of eye patterns or fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   Far more nefarious than forgetful employees are workers who hack
their employers' systems either to damage the database or steal
data for financial or other purposes. Such insider work is
especially difficult to stop because while many systems can track
when employees log in and how long they were on line, they don't
show what the employee did.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 computer fraud survey for the Computer Security
Institute and the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation, nearly 170
of 520 companies surveyed said they had suffered an attack on their
databases from employees. Two-thirds of the 520 admitted that their
security systems had been breached by hackers or viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Schnell said the burgeoning use of portable PCs is making life
more difficult for companies' security systems. For one thing,
portables are easily stolen, which gives would-be hackers plenty of
time to try to break into a database. They may even be taken only
long enough to install programs that reveal passwords that can be
readily called up on the screen. Schnell said such programs are
readily available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kid out there that wants to fool around with it can get
these tools and run with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the threats, an IDC survey of information technology
specialists found that half of them believe their employers'
systems will be more secure in the future. That stemmed from their
faith in their employers' willingness to spend more on continuing
technological improvements, such as those that will be shown at PC
Expo.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated $100 million in losses because of hackers, viruses
and dishonest employees probably is far lower than the actual
losses, said Derek Brink of Security Dynamics. The losses stem from
lost data, stolen computers, damage to data and lowered
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   But many companies don't report how bad they were hit because it
might worry customers, Brink said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're reluctant to report their losses, because they're
worried about trust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
