<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TIBET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S UNSAVORY RESETTLEMENT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World Bank is scheduled to vote Tuesday on funding for the
China Western Poverty Reduction Project, a resettling of 57,800
poor Chinese farmers to the Tibetan and Mongolian Autonomous
Prefecture on the high, arid Tibetan Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   This is a project the World Bank should not fund. It would place
the bank in the position of helping to finance Beijing's policy of
transferring Han Chinese onto traditional Tibetan lands, reducing
the Tibetans to a small minority in those lands, and gradually
effacing their unique culture, their national identity, and their
way of life.
</P>
<P>
   The project would double the Chinese population in Dulan County,
the destination for the new Chinese immigrants. The population
shift would reduce the Tibetan portion of the population in Dulan
from 22 to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the Chinese project is funded, 2,500 nomads will have their
land taken from them and will be forced onto farms. Such an
involuntary or forced resettlement of indigenous people violates
the World Bank's own policy guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter appealing for help from the outside world,
Tibetans in Dulan said: ``There have been many conflicts and many
killings over pasture lands. In view of this, the settlement is
designed to create a dangerous situation in the region. Many of us
will die in the conflicts, and even if we survive, where do we
go?''
</P>
<P>
   The resettlement project also raises vexing questions about
environmental damage. Another concern, voiced in a letter from
members of Congress to World Bank president James Wolfensohn, is
that Dulan County has the highest concentration of prison laborers
in China. As Barney Frank and three colleagues said in their letter
to Wolfensohn, this raises ``the troubling possibility that the
project could, even inadvertently, use forced labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has exerted great pressure on the 24 World Bank
directors who will vote on transferring Chinese farmers to the
Tibetan Plateau. For the sake of persecuted minorities everywhere
and the bank's own reputation, the directors should resist China's
pressure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
