<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-POLITICS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEALING WITH DAVID DUKE HAUNTS LOUISIANA GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ The tranquillity that descended over
Louisiana politics for the last four years had become positively
Midwestern, and that is not a compliment in the state that invented
Tabasco. It had been years since anyone in office was indicted,
marriage vows were staying intact, and leading officials of the two
parties respected each other so much that they had actually agreed
to a non-aggression pact.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't last, and to the everlasting gratitude of the
state's Democratic Party, it didn't. For the last month, the
familiar rain of scandal has once again fallen on the state
capital, and this time it has drenched the popular Republican
governor, Mike Foster. Suddenly, there is talk that this year's
governor's race might be worth watching, after all.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the change in weather, not surprisingly, is David
Duke, the former Ku Klux Klan wizard whose racist and anti-Semitic
beliefs have made him the bete blanc of state politics. Most
Republican politicians want nothing to do with him, so it came as a
surprise last month when Duke told a grand jury that during the
1995 governor's race Foster had secretly bought his list of
contributors and supporters.
</P>
<P>
   What was even more remarkable was the size of the payment Foster
had made to Duke: $150,000 for a list of 80,000 names, most of
which were available for just a few hundred dollars at the state
Ethics Board for anyone who wanted to find out who had contributed
to Duke's various unsuccessful campaigns. This amount so far
exceeded the standard rate for a mailing list that most people
assumed Foster had actually paid Duke to stay out of the 1995 race
and endorse him, which is one of the subjects the federal grand
jury appears to be investigating.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury could indict Duke for failing to report the
payment on his income tax _ a charge that Duke says he expects _
and the Ethics Board is looking into whether the governor violated
any campaign-finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Foster has denied making a payoff to Duke, insisting that he
simply bought a list of voters that he never used and now regrets
buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't real cool to put out there that you are buying
something from David Duke,'' he said after Duke's grand jury
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, his overture to Duke makes it clear how pervasive
``Duke-ism'' remains in an extremely conservative state, where no
black candidate has ever won statewide office since Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you say about Duke, remember that Foster would not
have won without his endorsement,'' said Jeff Crouere, who until
last year was the executive director of the state Republican Party
and who is now the host of a radio talk show in New Orleans, on
which he is sharply critical of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Duke ``has a core base of support that is very loyal, and after
he endorsed Foster in 1995, Foster went from 7 percent in the polls
to 17 percent,'' Crouere said. ``He can never win an election, but
he can determine who does, and that's why Foster paid 25 times what
that list was worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995, Foster, then a recent convert to the Republican
Party, was not quite as confident running in a traditionally
Democratic state as he is today. Though he did not publicly welcome
Duke's endorsement, he did not disdain it, either, and the boost
helped him make it into the runoff against Cleo Fields, a black
Democrat he easily defeated. Even today, Foster has spurned all
efforts to get him to denounce Duke _ a fact noted with pride by
Duke, who has regularly pointed out that Foster may be the
highest-ranking public official who has not repudiated him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Duke said this week that Foster's money had essentially
financed his autobiography, ``My Awakening,'' which promotes white
supremacist views. Foster, who declined to be interviewed, wrote a
letter published today in The Baton Rouge Advocate in which he said
that buying the list was a mistake and that he disagreed with Duke
``on racial and anti-Semitic issues.'' Nonetheless, Foster wrote,
he does not make a practice of condemning people.
</P>
<P>
   Though Duke has run for office as a Republican, he has relied
more on blue-collar Democratic voters. White-collar Republicans,
who have struggled to eliminate Duke's tarnish on their state
party, were annoyed at Foster for once again connecting them to
such a divisive character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed, absolutely, and I expressed it to him,''
said state Sen. John Dardenne, a Republican floor leader for
Foster. ``I regret that he saw fit to enrich David Duke in any
manner. And it's even more disappointing that after all the reform
we've had in the last four years, this incident raises a question
in people's minds. I just hope it doesn't set back the momentum
that we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Foster seems safe, but his base may be eroding a
bit. After the news of the Duke connection broke, the governor
commissioned a poll from a well-known Baton Rouge firm, Southern
Media and Opinion Research, which showed that his approval rating
had slipped only to 78 percent from 81 percent. Foster retains the
approval of 90 percent of whites _ an astonishingly high number _
while his black support has fallen to 50 percent from 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Jefferson, a Democrat who is Foster's leading
opponent in this fall's governor's race, has drawn some courage
from the approval figures as has the state Democratic Party, which
plans to make the Duke connection a major campaign issue.
Jefferson, who is black, would have a hard enough time running
statewide against a popular governor, but he is likely to be joined
by several other politicians who have sensed blood and are talking
about running.
</P>
<P>
   Foster is doing what he can to court the state's moderate
center. Earlier this week, his forces tried to depose Mike Francis,
the state Republican chairman, who is aligned with the religious
right, stripping away his power to hire, fire and write checks.
(Francis called the move illegal.) The governor also appears to
have backed away from his opposition to gambling, and is trying to
use money from the state's current prosperity and forthcoming
tobacco-settlement windfall to improve in health care and
education.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Foster may hope that voters will thank him for
finally improving the entertainment value of state politics, a
traditional Louisiana diversion. Lance Hill, executive director of
the Southern Institute for Education and Research, a race-relations
center at Tulane University, notes that Louisiana neither expects
nor desires its politicians to be consistent in their ideology or
base of support. In that sense, a moment of political betrayal
might be seen as humanizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a unique political culture here,'' Hill said, ``and
I guess you could say it's come out of remission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
