A4467 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-BEER-BOS &LR;      06-21 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BEER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same lobby that killed a proposal last year to standardize
blood alcohol levels for drunken driving is now trying to keep
underage drinking out of a youth education campaign sponsored by
the nation's drug czar, General Barry McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   The National Beer Wholesalers Association opposes the inclusion
of underage drinking in the $195 million media campaign, claiming
that alcohol is a legal substance and should not be lumped with
marijuana, cocaine, and other illegal drugs. But drinking under age
21 is illegal in every state, and alcohol abuse is far more common
than any other drug among young people.
</P>
<P>
   General McCaffrey himself has said alcohol is ``the biggest drug
abuse problem for adolescents.'' But his office has been strangely
circumspect about adding underage drinking to the campaign, saying
the drug czar's charter limits his mandate to fighting controlled
substances. This is why Congress should favor an amendment
sponsored by Representatives Frank Wolf of Virginia, a Republican,
and Lucille Roybal-Allard of California, a Democrat, that
authorizes McCaffrey to include underage drinking in the education
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The alcohol lobby is terrified of being regulated like that
other legal killer, cigarettes, with warning labels on beer cans
and limits on marketing to teenagers. It points to its voluntary
public service ads that urge responsible drinking. But the alcohol
industry spends nearly $3 billion a year on marketing and
promotion. Against that backdrop, ``responsibility'' needs all the
help it can get.
</P>
<P>
   The facts about underage drinking are sobering. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration reports 16,100
alcohol-related fatalities in 1997 _ one person killed every 32
minutes. Intoxication rates were highest for the youngest drivers.
Although the universal drinking age of 21 has helped reduce
fatalities, motor vehicle crashes remain the number one cause of
death for teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   June _ prom season _ is the month when most of these tragic
deaths occur. It would be a good month for Congress to do something
about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     06-21 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
MONEYBAG/ ARTHUR M. LOUIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't Expect Jackpot From Class-Action Stock Suit
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: How do I get included in a class-action lawsuit filed against a
company in which I own shares?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are eligible to participate in the lawsuit, the
lawyers who filed the suit should have contacted you by now. Their
normal procedure is to send a form on which you enumerate your
holdings in the company and the dates you purchased your shares.
You may also be required to submit documentary proof _ for example,
copies of the confirmation slips you received from your broker when
you bought the stock.
</P>
<P>
   If the lawyers did not send you any material, it may be that you
did not buy or own the shares during the period covered by the
lawsuit _ the period in which the alleged financial skulduggery
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your broker whether it has any leftover copies of the notice
the lawyers sent to shareholders _ or perhaps it can simply tell
you who the lawyers are. You also might be able to find this
information by checking various media databases. Try the public
library.
</P>
<P>
   As a fallback, you might want to check the Web site of Milberg
Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach, a San Diego law firm, which is
heavily involved in class-action suits. There is a strong chance
that they are one of the firms involved in yours  &LR; your suit The Web
address is  &LR; www.milberg.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect the lawsuit to make you rich. Individual
shareholders usually get only a pittance from any class-action
settlement. The lawyers, who deduct massive contingency fees from
the settlements, are usually the big winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Index Fund Concerns
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard that in a market panic, index funds would likely
fare worse than other mutual funds because typically there is
great, built-up, unrealized appreciation, and as investors cash
out, this would build like a tidal wave and potentially wipe out
those slow in exiting. While a panic might have a similar effect on
any fund, index funds typically have more unrealized capital gains.
Index funds seem like a good choice because they perform so much
better than most other funds, but I would like to know the risks.
</P>
<P>
   A: Investors in index funds could indeed have a special problem
in a market crash, but you have the theory slightly muddled.
</P>
<P>
   You have got it correct up to a point: In a crash, index funds _
which normally sell stock only rarely _ might have to liquidate a
lot of holdings in which they have large, unrealized capital gains.
They would have to do this if so many investors flee the funds that
there is not enough cash in the portfolio to redeem the fund
shares.
</P>
<P>
   If the fund manager sells stock at a capital gain, the amount of
the gain must be distributed to the remaining fund shareholders.
Those shareholders would then have to set aside money to pay taxes
on their capital gains. In tranquil markets, when index-fund
shareholders are not cashing in, capital-gains distributions are
minimal or nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Actively managed funds, by contrast, sell stock all the time.
For their shareholders, capital-gains distributions are business as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   So for index-fund shareholders it would be largely a matter of
sticker shock, or culture shock, or whatever you want to call it.
</P>
<P>
   As you indicate, index funds have been a strong investment year
after year. It is even possible that the bulk of their shareholders
will remain faithful in a market panic, and therefore the funds
will not be overwhelmed by redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   So don't let potential tax considerations weigh too heavily. If
you expect a market crash tomorrow, the rational thing would be to
sell your shares today, not sit and ruminate about taxes.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you can avoid the tax problem if you hold index-fund
shares in a 401(k) plan, an individual retirement account or any
other tax-deferred or tax-free vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Problems With Rollovers
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you please discuss rollovers of 403(b) and 457 funds into
individual retirement accounts. There are millions of folks who
work in the education and nonprofit sectors, which put them into
403(b) plans, or in local and state governments, which put them
into 457 plans. How do they roll these funds into IRAs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bad news for you government employees out there: 457 plans
cannot be rolled over, according to Internal Revenue Service
spokesman Jesse Weller. The reason: ``They're not the same as
qualified retirement plans _ they are deferred-compensation
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   As for 403(b) plans, in general you can roll them over to IRAs
if you leave your job, reach age 591/2 or become disabled. The
maximum amount you can roll over is the amount that would be
taxable if you withdrew the money without rolling it over.
</P>
<P>
   You may already know this, but as with any rollover, the money
must be moved from one account to the other within 60 days.
Furthermore, you will be subject to a 20 percent withholding tax if
the rollover is not done directly _ that is, from institution to
institution. If the money passes through your hands, the tax will
be withheld and you will not get it back until you file your return
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
