</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLS-BILLS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 The Check's on the Net  
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Computer-based bill paying is one of the most intriguing and least
noticed developments in consumer finance.
<P>
   Payment via the Internet has been widely available for a couple
of years, and for nearly two decades it has been possible to pay
your bills electronically with special software and direct modem
hookups to your bank.
</P>
<P>
   Online bill paying typically is available for a fee of $5 to $7
per month _ probably less than the amount you would save on &LR;   &LR; pay
in postage stamps and checks. If your bank or other institution
considers you a valued customer, you might get it for free.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ease and convenience, only about 3 percent of the
nation's 100 million U.S.  &LR; households have tried it.
</P>
<P>
   The service has been slow to catch on partly because it hasn't
been aggressively promoted, partly because most consumers are slow
to change, and partly because many people are afraid to transmit
confidential financial data over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is another large stumbling block as well: Online bill
paying is still in a rudimentary stage. While you can pay just
about any bill online, scarcely any bills are delivered online.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, consumers who opt for online payments still
receive the bulk of their bills as hard copy through the mail. They
must spend time keying the biller's name and address and the amount
of the payment into templates on whatever Web site they are using.
</P>
<P>
   But online bill paying may be on the brink of a major
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The computer world's proverbial 800-pound gorilla, Microsoft,
has created a joint venture with Citigroup and First Data that
plans to greatly expand the use of bill presentment _ the jargon
term for online delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado-based venture, called TransPoint, will act as a
billing agent _ an intermediary between billers and financial
institutions _ providing the software and technology support needed
to keep billing data flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Although billers must pay TransPoint to put their bills online,
the fees will amount to far less than the $1.25 to $1.50 average it
costs to prepare and mail a hard-copy bill. Ralph Young, executive
vice president of TransPoint, says billers will be charged ``less
than 35 cents per bill.''
</P>
<P>
   TransPoint moved out of the pilot development stage last month.
It now has five billers _ Consolidated Edison of New York, GTE, the
Orange County Register, PECO Energy and Xerox _ displaying bills
and receiving payments through their Web sites. Several dozen more
should emerge from pilot before long.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, TransPoint will connect billers with Web portals
and the Web sites of financial institutions, so consumers can get
their bills off the Web site of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's ``basically endless financial resources'' should
give online bill paying the much-needed marketing and advertising
that it has lacked until now, predicts Paul Hughes, an analyst with
the Yankee Group consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   TransPoint's principal rival, Georgia's CheckFree Holdings, has
been in the automated-payments business in one form or another for
18 years, and has a considerable head start.
</P>
<P>
   Its CheckFree E-Bill electronic billing program, launched in
March 1997, was the first Internet billing service. It is used by
51 billers _ among them Chase Mortgage, MCI WorldCom and the Small
Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bills from CheckFree's clients are being delivered
electronically to the Web sites of 20 banks and other financial
institutions _ including San Francisco's Charles Schwab brokerage
firm. Customers of those institutions can receive their bills and
pay them at the Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Solomon, a Schwab vice president, says the online bill
paying service is available to customers of the firm who open
special accounts for this purpose. (You can't make bill payments
out of the cash balances in your regular Schwab brokerage account.)
</P>
<P>
   The fee ranges from upwards of $6.95 per month for some
customers to nothing at all for those who maintain large account
balances or make a lot of securities trades through Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal world, consumers would be able to view and pay all
their bills electronically at a single Web site _ their bank,
broker or favorite Web portal (such as Yahoo or America Online),
for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommend seamlessness _ the ability to take care of
multiple needs in one place,'' says Robert Sterling, an analyst
with Jupiter Communications, a New York consulting firm. `'People
don't want to bounce all over the Internet to pay their bills. They
want one place, with one password.''
</P>
<P>
   Something approaching seamlessness could happen before the end
of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   However, getting all bills from all billers online at all
financial-institution Web sites might prove impractical, if only
because there are a lot of billers that may never find it
worthwhile to sign up for electronic billing.
</P>
<P>
   Americans receive an estimated 18 billion bills per year, and
that includes bills from the gardener, the piano teacher and the
local delicatessen. These small fry may never make it to
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the problem of technophobia. Almost daily, the
media chronicles the exploits of computer hackers who invade
private databases or who infect computer systems with data-munching
viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these systems have a lot of built-in security
technology,'' says Michael Killen, president of Killen &AMP;
Associates, a market-research firm in Palo Alto. ``I tend to think
that it is pretty good security.''
</P>
<P>
   Killen acknowledges that ``everything can be broken into,'' but
he adds: `'I don't see it as a big problem. I'm personally not
going to get upset if someone figures out how much I am paying
Pacific Bell. I don't know what economic benefit it is to someone
to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a consumer summons the interest and courage to try
electronic bill paying, he is apt to be hooked for good, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that they never go back to paper,'' remarks
Laurinda Wilson, a CheckFree spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Those who pay their bills online swear by it. ``I'd recommend it
for anybody,'' says Rosemary Bedene, a Los Molinos (Tehama County)
homemaker and Wells Fargo customer who for more than a year has
paid her 10 bills per month through the bank's Internet Web site.
``I hate paperwork, and this is just so much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
