<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTIMES-RICOCHET_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 MCI Gives Ricochet a Big Boost  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Metricom Inc., the Los Gatos company that makes the popular
Ricochet wireless modem, got a $600 million boost yesterday from
MCI WorldCom and billionaire investor Paul Allen.
<P>
   MCI WorldCom and Allen's firm, Vulcan Ventures, said they will
invest $300 million each to fund a nationwide rollout of Ricochet _
a wireless modem that allows consumers to access the Internet from
laptop computers and other mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
   Metricom currently  &LR; offers the Ricochet service to mobile
workers in the Bay Area, Washington, D.C. and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   With this funding, the company plans to launch its wireless
modem service in 46 cities by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The $600 million investment will also allow Metricom to increase
boost  &LR; the speed of Ricochet to 128 kilobits per second, which is
about as fast as a dedicated ISDN line. Right now, Ricochet
accesses the Internet at roughly 28 kbps _ about the same as an
ordinary dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   The faster Ricochet will also allow users to access the Internet
while traveling at speeds up to 70 miles an hour _ something that
will come in handy for commuters who use BART and other public
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area should get the faster Ricochet modem by the middle
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our target is the business professional and mobile
professionals who need to have their desktop information available
for them in other cities,'' said John Wernke, senior vice president
of marketing and sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metricom's technology is excellent ...but the one thing
they've missed to date is having a 50 city top metropolitan
statistical area footprint and this is what they will get with MCI
WorldCom,'' said Andrew Cole, head of the wireless practice at
Renaissance Worldwide, a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to investing in the company, MCI plans to resell a
co-branded wireless modem to its wide customer base under the
Ricochet and MCI names.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, MCI and Vulcan will buy 60 million new Metricom
convertible preferred shares, priced at $10 per share. Allen, a
longtime investor in Metricom, matched MCI's $300 million
investment so he could retain a 49 percent stake in the company,
Wernke said. MCI will own 38 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Metricom has been testing its faster wireless modem service and
expects to launch it in mid-2000 in the Bay Area, as well as in Los
Angeles, San Diego, New York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   However, the company does  &LR; still faces face some  &LR; challenges. In
order to offer service in any city, Metricom must sign agreements
with municipalities for access to rights-of-way so it can install
antennas for its system. That could take time, Wernke said, so the
company is not committed to a start-date for any city.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said Metricom must gain that access quickly because it will
face competition from other wireless Internet devices, such as cell
phones, which can surf the Web and are expected to hit the mass
market in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the barriers for Metricom is their getting
rights-of-way and access. That is the key thing and it's filled
with bureaucracy,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Wernke said the company is positive it can secure the agreements
it needs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
