<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS BRUSHES ASIDE THE FIRST-ROUND JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The defending champion was worried about
feeling like one, but only the grass was vulnerable on opening day
at Wimbledon. Pete Sampras' early round jitters proved fleeting,
and the rest of the seeded shoo-ins stomped and skidded their way
into the second round without any unmanageable slip-ups.
</P>
<P>
   All except for third-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the 1999
Australian Open champion, whose temporary ascension to the No. 1
ranking this spring in the middle of a six-event losing streak
seems to have left him of two minds about his prospects as a world
beater. The mercurial Russian surrendered the first and fourth sets
Monday and had to save a match point held by Sweden's Magnus
Larsson in the fifth set before their match was suspended by
darkness with nobody ahead, 6-7 (4-7), 7-5, 7-6 (8-6), 4-6, 5-5.
Kafelnikov had just broken Larsson when play was halted.
</P>
<P>
   The baseline slugfest on Center Court between Jennifer Capriati
and Anke Huber, whose 7-5, 3-0 lead became imperiled after she took
a second-set tumble, arrived at a cliffhanger similar to that
experienced by Kafelnikov and Larsson. The failing light and
increasingly slick conditions forced the suspension of their
spirited confrontation at 7-5, 3-6, 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   While revelers marked the summer solstice at Stonehenge, here at
the All England Club, where the tennis fanatics braved an autumnal
chill and slept overnight on the sidewalks to guarantee their spots
in the queue, Sampras, the seven-time champion Steffi Graf and the
host nation's twin terrors, Tim Henman and Greg Rusedski, marked
their return to the epicenter of the tennis cosmos with convincing
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras struck a dozen aces, faced no break-point threats and
made 26 winning forays to the net in decimating Scott Draper, 6-3,
6-4, 6-4. Though Draper, the 75th-ranked Australian, possessed
enough grass-court gumption to grab last year's title at Queen's
Club, Sampras won that tournament this year and Monday improved his
latest streak of grass-court invincibility to 13 matches. ``I got
the early round jitters, but once I got out there, I felt like I
was back home on that court,'' said Sampras, who ended things with
a minor miracle, a lunging backhand half-volley that spurted over
the net like a piece of popcorn and fell to earth just in time to
glance off the sideline. ``I can do that sometimes; it's not that
complicated,'' deadpanned Sampras, a stickler for on-court
simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   The grass was slippery from the start on Center Court, but
Sampras navigated the lawn with a familiarity that explained why he
has captured 5 of his 11 Grand Slam titles here. With six more
victories, he can win a third straight Wimbledon and move into a
tie with Roy Emerson for the career record in Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras wants to use this event as a turning point in a year
blemished by mediocrity. After passing up the Australian Open, he
succumbed in the second round at the French Open, the only Grand
Slam event he has yet to win, and until his triumph at Queen's Club
two weeks ago, Sampras had not reached a final or won a title since
October. Not good numbers for the man who longs to be known as the
greatest player of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to put things behind you, look at Wimbledon as my
next goal, come over to London early, play Queen's, and really try
to be positive and turn my year around here,'' he said. ``I did it
last year and hopefully I can do it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope springs evergreen, too, for Graf, who won the French Open
three weeks ago. She is wondering if she can reprise that trick on
grass and, at the creaky tennis age of 30, win her 23d Grand Slam
title at Wimbledon, the event she, like Sampras, sinks into like an
easy chair. Monday the second-seeded German disposed of the Slovak
Ludmila Cervanova, 6-1, 6-4. ``I still feel pretty good out there
for my age,'' Graf said.
</P>
<P>
   So does 19-year-old Venus Williams, who chastised herself for
overconfidence after her 6-1, 7-5 defeat of Miriam Oremans. ``At
least I don't have a problem to be underconfident,'' Williams said.
``I'm a little overconfident, which can be highly dangerous also.''
</P>
<P>
   Another teen-ager who has made a staple of confidence, the
18-year-old Anna Kournikova, moved ahead with a 7-6 (7-2), 4-6, 6-2
defeat of Barbara Schwartz, the Austrian qualifier who spoiled
Venus Williams' French Open and was originally scheduled to meet
Serena Williams in this round.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's hankering for its first home-grown champion (or in the
Canadian transplant Rusedski's case, its first adopted champion) in
63 years received a double boost. The sixth-seeded Henman ousted
Arnaud Di Pasquale, 6-4, 6-0, 3-6, 7-6 (7-1), and the ninth-seeded
Rusedski defeated the Australian Jason Stoltenberg, a semifinalist
three years ago, 6-1, 6-4, 6-2. Australia's seventh-seeded Mark
Philippoussis, who received a four-spot seeding upgrade, showed the
seeding committee its confidence in him was not misplaced: with 28
aces, he subdued Belgium's Xavier Malisse, 6-7 (4-7), 6-4, 6-3,
6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
