<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HUSSEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAMAL EDDIN HUSSEIN, 77, FIGURE IN COUP AGAINST FAROUK IN 1952 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kamal Eddin Hussein, a crusty Egyptian army officer who helped
to overthrow King Farouk of Egypt in 1952, became a vice president
of Egypt and then clashed with two presidents, died on Saturday. He
was 77.
</P>
<P>
   He had liver cancer, his family said, according to The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein was a leading member of the group Free Officers, headed
by Gamal Abdel Nasser, who led Egypt's revolution in 1952. In
addition to overthrowing Farouk, who went into exile, the
revolution put an end to Egypt's monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Nasser became president, with Hussein as a member of
his original Revolutionary Council. Hussein went on to hold
important Cabinet posts under Nasser besides serving as a vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   But he came to oppose many aspects of Nasser's leadership,
including his authoritarian mode of governing and what has been
called his favoritism, which Hussein said led Egypt to lose in the
1967 Middle East war. After falling out with Nasser in the 1960s,
he was put under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   He was released early in the presidency of Anwar el-Sadat, who
succeeded Nasser in 1970. After food riots in Egypt, in 1977, when
Hussein was an independent member of the Egyptian People's
Assembly, he publicly accused Sadat of ``punishing the Egyptian
people'' instead of ``punishing your government for dereliction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein made his accusation in a telegram to Egyptian
newspapers, also deploring as unconstitutional certain punitive
law-and-order measures that Sadat had announced in a television
address. Hussein called the measures and ``an insult to the
intelligence of the Egyptian people.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Assembly then expelled him, by a vote of 281 to 28,
for having voiced ``insulting'' views of Sadat. Hussein was the
first National Assembly member to be ousted since 1971, when a
number of members had been expelled for plotting to overthrow
Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein is survived by three sons and several grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
