<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERN PUTS NBA'S PROBLEMS ON THE TABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He discussed plummeting television ratings,
unprepared teen-agers continuing their migration to the National
Basketball Association and, finally, the dreadful quality of play
in this lockout-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Given the transitional state of the game, NBA Commissioner David
Stern played defense Monday as well as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, making his annual championship-series address, prompted
serious discussion about instituting a minimum-age requirement _
perhaps age 20, he said _ for players' draft eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Stern also said a special committee would convene Tuesday to
discuss possible rule changes designed to address stagnant offenses
and low-scoring games. Yet faced with a major ratings drop from
last season's finals between the Chicago Bulls and the Utah Jazz _
a drop of 39 percent for the first two games of the Knicks-Spurs
finals _ the commissioner did not sound overly concerned about the
future of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there is an absence of the world's most famous
person, no less that world's most famous athlete, Michael Jordan,''
said Stern, who appeared with the deputy commissioner Russ Granik
at a midtown Manhattan hotel. ``But I think we're seeing the
creation in front of our eyes of the kinds of teams'' that will
become known.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the state of the league is one that finds us very
optimistic about the future,'' Stern added.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA set new standards for modern offensive futility this
season, with teams averaging a paltry 91.6 points, down 4 points
from last season and the lowest average since the inception of the
shot clock in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   This season teams shot 43.7 percent from the field. Ten years
ago, teams shot nearly 48 percent from the field and averaged 109.2
points. Only one team this season, the Sacramento Kings, averaged
more than 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-member special committee, made up of coaches, former
players, team executives and owners, will spend all day Tuesday
discussing possible rule changes for next season. The four major
areas include:
</P>
<P>
   _Officiating. ``How the game is called and particularly whether
the players become too physical or not, and what can be done about
that in terms of officiating,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   _Dimensions of the key. The dimensions of the court will not
change, but proposals to widen the lane will be given
consideration. Previous proposals have been rejected twice in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   _Clocks. Saying the 24-second shot clock would probably not
change, Granik nonetheless said it would be discussed. ``All the
issues _ the 24-second clock, bringing the ball up court in 10
seconds and what to do with the ball when the clock goes out of
bounds, things like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _Defensive guidelines. Two sets of rule changes the past four
years involving hand-checking and illegal defenses have done little
to improve the game's offensive quality. Of all the issues
discussed, this one may elicit the most drastic change _ including
the possibility of allowing zone defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The board of governors will receive the committee's
recommendations and vote on possible rules changes in August for
use in the 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a serious mandate for moving ahead if we come up with
a sort of overwhelming sentiment out of this committee to just
let's get it done,'' Stern said. ``The board indicated to us that
they don't need a lot of debate, that if we are comfortable with
the results of the committee, then we should just go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern would not go so far as to attribute the lack of scoring
and skill level to the proliferation of young players entering the
league, but added, ``I am prepared to go forward and try to put
some rule in that would have the effect of raising the beginning
age at which players come into the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what age that would be, Stern replied, ``That is a
discussion. We can pick a number. I have shown around 20. I asked
Isiah Thomas how he was when he left Indiana after his second year.
He said it was his birthday almost; he was 20. I don't profess to
have any magic number, but that seems to be a fair enough issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said such a rule might affect 1 out of 100 potential
players in the league. ``The better view is we should have some
rule that keeps people sort of growing, maturing and developing
their skills for an additional period of time,'' Stern said. ``But
there is no great answer here.''
</P>
<P>
   The feasibility of an age requirement would hinge on several
other factors, including an agreement with the players association
and perhaps forming an NBA-subsidized minor league or entering into
a minor league agreement with the Continental Basketball
Association. Stern said league officials had discussed both
options.
</P>
<P>
   To appease college players who enter the draft early for
financial reasons, the league has proposed $20,000 loans or
subsidies for those players deemed of NBA caliber.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said the National Collegiate Athletic Association had yet
to get back to the league about the proposal, which he said was
made several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hope Stern professed, a concerned Spanish journalist
seemed to sum up the proceedings well Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very worried right now because I have seen in San
Antonio, especially the second game,'' the journalist said to Stern
in halting English. ``I think it is my particular opinion the worst
game that I have seen in the finals. It was boring for me. I am
worried about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about physical game, great defense, but I have
seen only a few highlight plays and a lot of mistakes. You can win
the NBA finals scoring 70, 75 points. This is only a few points.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a smiling veneer, Stern replied, ``Well, let me say, I
want you not to despair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2218EDT &QL; 
