<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOOGE-HONORED-ART-NY     06-21 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOOGE-HONORED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIANS LOBBY FOR A MURAL OF THEIR `NATIVE STOOGE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Lyla Budnick with photographs of two Stooges,
her brother, Louis Feinberg, and Moe Howard, is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Lyla Budnick remembers her brother Louis Feinberg
as a warm and caring family man, hardly the frizzy-haired,
wild-eyed rapscallion the world knew as Larry Fine, one of the most
famous of the Three Stooges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he wasn't working, he was a different man,'' said Mrs.
Budnick, 78. ``He was 18 years older than me, so when I was born,
he was already an adult. After my father died, when I was 5, Larry
and his wife, Mabel, raised me. He really was my father. Being a
Stooge was his persona. It really wasn't him.''
</P>
<P>
   As the least antic of the Stooges in their heyday, the 1930s and
1940s, Larry was often an easy target for head bops and eye pokes
from his partners, Curly Howard and Moe Howard, who were brothers.
But Larry was no less popular among millions of fans who grew up
``nyuk, nyuk, nyuking'' their way into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, who was born in a South Philadelphia row house in 1902,
died in 1975, five years after a stroke had ended his acting
career. He was buried in a simple grave near his Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Budnick, who still lives in South Philadelphia with her
husband, Nathan, 82, a sound man on Stooge movie sets, said it
always saddened her that Larry's hometown never honored him as a
native son, beyond a small plaque in Jon's Bar and Grill, which was
once a jewelry store the Feinbergs ran out of the first floor of
their house.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, she said, she had asked local officials to have
the building designated as an historic site, always to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   But all that could change soon. Early this year, Stooge-mania
hit Philadelphia like a custard pie, leading to the possibility
that a large mural of Larry might be painted on a wall overlooking
the row house. More than 1,800 murals decorate the city as part of
a municipally financed arts program to encourage neighborhood
pride.
</P>
<P>
   After The Philadelphia Daily News ran a picture of Frank Sinatra
on its front page on March 23, suggesting that the city paint a
mural to honor him, The Philadelphia Weekly newspaper protested,
inasmuch as Sinatra had been born in Hoboken, N.J. Under a parody
of The Daily News front page, with Larry's head replacing Frank's,
The Weekly pointed out: ``Frank Sinatra ain't from Philadelphia.
Why not create a mural for a true native son?''
</P>
<P>
   Little did Weekly editors know at the time that David McShane, a
local artist and Stooge fan who had painted murals for the city,
had been clamoring to do a likeness of Larry. Already adorning city
walls were murals honoring other Philadelphians, like Paul Robeson,
Mario Lanza, Patti LaBelle and Julius Erving. So why not a Stooge?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tim Whitaker's phones did not stop ringing. He is The
Weekly's editor, who said he had planned the Larry parody ``to poke
fun'' at The Daily News. Little did he know the joke would send
local Stooge fans into a Curly-spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'd say hello, and all I heard at the other end was,
`Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk,''' Whitaker said, reciting a line Curly used to
razz Larry and Moe. ``People loved the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Golden, director of the city's mural arts program, which
receives hundreds of requests for money each year, said that the
cost of a Larry mural could reach $25,000 but that the project
could get under way with $12,000. The city has agreed to finance
about 25 percent of the total expense, Ms. Golden said, but the
rest would have to come from private donations.
</P>
<P>
   The Weekly has led the drive, donating the first $1,000 and
arranging for a series of fund-raisers. The first was held Monday
night at The Inn Philadelphia, a Center City restaurant, where more
than 100 Stooge fans donated $10 each to meet Mrs. Budnick, who
still bears a striking resemblance to her brother, watch Three
Stooges movies, trade head bops and admire McShane's draft of Larry
looking as if Moe is about to gouge his eyes out.
</P>
<P>
   Frank E. Reighter, who stocks shelves at a local supermarket,
took up a corner of the restaurant to sell Stooge memorabilia,
including posters, ties, dolls and glossy photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' he said of the Larry mural.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to Larry's role as a punching bag for Curly and Moe, he
added: ``As a native, he is a perfect typical type of
Philadelphian, always fighting the next level of people above him.
Stocking shelves at night, I think about this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Budnick, who knew the other Stooges well and became
something of an expert on the six men who played Stooges, said
Curly's famous ``Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk'' came about as a mistake. ``He
could never remember his lines,'' she said. ``Whenever he forget
them, he made noises.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she never cared for Moe, calling him ``a miserable,
mean-spirited man.'' Curly, she said, was ``1,000 percent
different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Curly,'' Mrs. Budnick said, ``what you saw was what he
was. He was a goofball, but a great goofball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
