<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RATINGS-DIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-JORDAN RATINGS IN A PRIME-TIME TORPOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three weeks ago, NBC predicted that the absence of
Michael Jordan would cause ratings for the National Basketball
Association finals to slide by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Think again: they have tumbled 39 percent in Games 1 and 2. The
9.6 Nielsen rating for Game 2 is the second lowest in NBC's
nine-season NBA reign, the lowest being a 7.8 for Game 5 of 1994
Knicks-Houston finals when viewers were distracted by coverage on
other networks of O.J. Simpson's slow-speed Bronco ride through Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The new reality for NBC is that after a decade of Jordan as
high-rated prime-time entertainment, San Antonio versus New York is
boring America. The ratings would smell no better if they were
doused with Michael Jordan Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a MASH unit, with the Knicks' injuries to Patrick
Ewing and Larry Johnson, and it's been an uncompetitive series,''
said Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports. ``The 39 percent
drop is in line with people thinking it will be a four-game sweep.
I always think in terms of six-game series, although I'd agree that
it'll probably take a miracle to get to six.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a reality check for NBC and the NBA _ a ``building
year,'' Ebersol said. In six of the first eight years NBC carried
the NBA, the Chicago Bulls won six titles. Last year, the
Chicago-Utah finals, Jordan's finale, soared to a league-record
18.7.
</P>
<P>
   To Ebersol, a permanent reduction of 15 percent from last year's
peak would be the best that the league can expect in future
post-Jordan finals. That would mean satisfaction is attainable at
15.9; the two non-Jordan finals in the last eight years rated no
higher than a 13.9, for Houston-Orlando in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced NBA ratings may please Major League Baseball, which
saw World Series beaten three times in the ratings since 1993 by
the NBA finals, including last year (18.7 to 14.1). But no World
Series game has rated below an 11.3 during the same period that NBC
has carried the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   More new reality: what if San Antonio, the smallest-market team
to play for the title since Fort Wayne lost to Philadelphia in
1956, makes the finals for years to come? Would a more-familiar,
improving Spurs team lure viewers back?
</P>
<P>
   Well, NBC hopes that it got something out of this season, like
playoff exposure to Tim Duncan, Allen Iverson, Kevin Garnett and
Jason Williams, whose teams will be seen far more in the regular
season than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a powerhouse San Antonio team rolling annually into the
finals is only peachy if Duncan &AMP; Co. become nationally popular and
casual fans want to see the Twin Towers wreak havoc. A dandier
reality would have the Los Angeles Lakers awaken to the rewards of
unselfish basketball under Coach Phil Jackson and tame the Spurs
for Western Conference supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   And in that future, wouldn't it be nice if teams could shoot
better? Bob Costas, who is calling the finals for NBC, said he was
not bored by the low scoring, but added: ``I recognize that this
isn't as free-flowing as it could be. The league wouldn't have a
committee meeting on this tomorrow if it were an ideal
representative of the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
