<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ICEMAN-FUNDRAISER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS HOPE `ICEMAN' WILL COME WITH BIG MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When President Clinton and other politicians come to
New York City to raise campaign money _ which they do frequently _
they tend to favor fund-raisers at elegant restaurants like Le
Cirque 2000, or special performances of crowd-pleasing Broadway
shows like ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   But next week, in one of the more unusual fund-raisers in recent
years, the president will join Democratic congressional leaders at
a $1-million fund-raiser built around a performance of ``The Iceman
Cometh,'' the grim if engrossing play by Eugene O'Neill that runs
close to 270 minutes. Notwithstanding its strong reviews and
sellout run, ``Iceman'' is not quite the
leave-your-troubles-outside evening most political donors expect
when they pay a minimum of $1,000 for a pair of theater tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Harry's bar,'' Kevin Spacey, the star of the
production, said Monday afternoon as he led Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, the House Democratic leader, onto the stage in the dark
and empty theater. Gephardt, who was in town to do some advance
work on next week's event at the Brooks Atkinson Theater, and
Spacey settled into two rickety chairs. Behind them were half-empty
liquor bottles, not the usual backdrop favored by politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey, who described himself as an avid Democrat, suggested the
fund-raising event, which will help the party raise money for the
2000 congressional races. The special performance will begin at 3
p.m. on Monday, so as to end in time for a political dinner, which
will also include Clinton, at the Supper Club. Democrats said it
was not yet clear if Mrs. Clinton will come.
</P>
<P>
   All of which, though, begs the question: Is the notably
garrulous Clinton going to be able to sit through four and a half
hours of, well, other people talking?
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt straightened up in the president's defense. ``Look, no
one thought anybody would sit for four hours,'' Gephardt said. He
then amended his remarks. ``Over four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey took over. ``You know, there's a kind of perception, they
hear, `Oh, four hours,''' he said. ``But in fact, there isn't a
person that I've ever spoken to who didn't think this play went by
like that.'' Spacey snapped his fingers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
