<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KASHMIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DANGEROUS ESCALATION IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 22:
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have long engaged in cycles of confrontation
and rapprochement, with war and threats of war followed by pledges
of cooperation. Now the latest promises of peace have yielded to
the worst fighting in decades. The provocation is the presence of
well-armed Islamic militants holding mountainous positions on
Indian territory, seeking independence for Kashmir, India's only
Muslim-dominated state. India, which has tried bombing and shelling
to dislodge them, is rightly demanding that Pakistan help in
removing the guerrillas as the first step toward defusing the
current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since their
independence and partition in 1947, two on Kashmiri territory. Past
uprisings in Kashmir have drawn in hundreds of thousands of Indian
troops and cost thousands of lives. India says that Pakistan has
aided the insurgents. Pakistan says it has merely supplied ``moral
support'' to indigenous ``freedom fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, however, just as the heavy snows were melting, a
guerrilla force seized positions in the mountains. It appears that
they could not have done so without Pakistani help. Pakistani
shells are being fired on a crucial mountain road, closing it to
civilian trucks that normally supply the area to the east.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, India has been lamentably slow in recognizing
that it could not crush the Muslim rebellion in Kashmir by force
alone. But the intervention of militants this spring has been
widely condemned as a provocation by Pakistan. Some say that the
Pakistani army engineered this crisis because it was unhappy with
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's earlier decision to meet India's
prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, in Lahore. Even Indian
officials have wondered whether the operation was carried out by
the government or rogue elements of the army. Sharif thus faces a
major challenge in demonstrating that he, not the military, runs
the country.
</P>
<P>
   India has so far shown commendable restraint, but warns that
time is running out. If the militants are not removed, India says,
it fears being unable to get supplies to places that need them
before the next snowfall in August. Frustrated by its failure to
dislodge the militants, India might be tempted to send troops into
Pakistani territory. That would be a serious escalation, all the
more worrisome because both countries possess nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   No rapprochement can occur without some sort of a political
resolution of Kashmir's status. Any such solution would probably
have to be a creative mixture of self-government for the Kashmiris
with some kind of political association with both India and perhaps
Pakistan. But no solution can be achieved under the threat of
military action. The next step must come from Pakistan, which
should encourage or perhaps even force the militants from their
incursion into Indian territory. Then talks can commence on steps
to improve relations and eventually settle the status of Kashmir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
