<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-LOBBYISTS-NY     06-21 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LOBYISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS ARE A LODE FOR THE LEADING PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is running as a
Washington outsider, but that is not stopping a galaxy of
Washington insiders from contributing more than $1 million to his
presidential campaign at a fund-raiser here on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail earlier this month, Bush criticized the
capital's deeply divisive culture, saying that as president he
would try to ``change the tone of Washington, D.C.'' On another
occasion, he derided the ``zero-sum politics'' of the capital.
``It's an `I win, you lose'-type attitude,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Washington Hilton on Tuesday night, the Texas
governor, a nonlawyer who wore black ostrich-leather cowboy boots
while campaigning in Iowa, will be eagerly embraced by hundreds of
lawyers and lobbyists wearing Gucci loafers. The list of 425
co-chairmen and vice chairmen for the Bush reception reads like a
who's-who of Republican lobbyists from K Street, this city's
corridor of power and influence.
</P>
<P>
   While he is in the capital, Bush will also meet with more than
100 members of Congress who have endorsed him, some of whom are
also raising money for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has essentially given the signal to the establishment here:
You can come on board, but you are not going to shape this
candidacy,'' said Wayne Berman, a Republican fund-raiser and a
lobbyist with Park Strategies, whose clients include PaineWebber
and Philip Morris. ``Bush has said: `I'm shaping it from the
outside.' The establishment here doesn't necessarily like it,''
Berman said, ``but Bush has been able to persuade them.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Vice President Al Gore, the early front-runner for the
Democratic presidential nomination, Bush is relying on lobbyists
and lawyers here to help raise the vast sums of money needed to run
for president. But the vice president has much deeper ties to K
Street, having dealt with and raised money from Washington
lobbyists since his election to the Senate in 1984. Many of Gore's
former aides and campaign advisers are prominent lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance of lawyers and lobbyists is distinctly important
in this early stage of presidential fund-raising, when there is a
premium on collecting $1,000 contributions, the maximum that
individuals can give to a candidate. Lobbying groups and law firms
bundle contributions from their employees, and lawyers and
lobbyists often tap their roster of clients for donations. Most
major lobbying firms have hedged their bets by having partners
raise money for different candidates. That way, no matter who wins,
the firms will have helped the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore have raised far more money from lawyers and
lobbyists than from any other profession, according to a study by
the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan research group
here. Gore raised $1.4 million from lawyers in the first three
months of 1999 and Bush $750,000. The figures include contributions
from lawyers and lobbyists, their spouses and employees of their
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In building a national fund-raising network that is the envy of
the rest of the Republican field, Bush cultivated many top
Republican lobbyists from K Street, asking them to raise $100,000
each and to recruit others. Among the most influential lobbyists
who are helping Bush are Peter Terpeluk Jr., a managing partner at
the American Continental Group; former Rep. Thomas Loeffler, a
Texas Republican and lobbyist; and Haley Barbour, the former
Republican National Committee chairman who is now a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said he met Bush in 1987 when he worked on the
presidential campaign of Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to know him then, and I expect a whole lot of people got
to know him then or got to know him after he was elected
governor,'' Barbour said. ``He became their friend, and then he
earned their support for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is also assisted by a prominent Democrat, James Langdon
Jr., a partner at the law firm of Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP;
Feld. Langdon has been a close friend of Bush for years; he has
agreed to recruit 100 lawyers and lobbyists here to raise $25,000
each.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has another distinct advantage. Many contributors attending
Tuesday night's reception are former members of his father's
administration and the Reagan administration, including C. Boyden
Gray, the White House counsel for President George Bush; James
Miller III, the budget director under President Reagan; Nick Calio,
assistant to the president for legislative affairs in the Bush
administration, and Andrew Card Jr., the transportation secretary
in the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   After the reception, Bush will spend the remainder of the week
raising money in Pennsylvania, Michigan and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Far more than Bush, Gore is perceived by the public as someone
with very close ties to the Washington establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The influential Democratic lobbyists Peter Knight, Peter Kelly
and Daniel Dutko lead Gore's push for dollars. Already, Gore has
had at least 10 lobbyists raise at least $50,000 each for his
campaign. While helping Gore, Knight, for example, is lobbying on
behalf of Bell Atlantic and Lockheed Martin, though he has said he
will take a leave of absence from his firm later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are helping us throughout the country,'' said Roger
Salazar, a spokesman for the Gore campaign. ``The vice president
has many friends in Washington, too, and it is not unusual to have
people here who are helping him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic and Republican candidates are also being helped
by lawyers and lobbyists, including Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.;
Elizabeth Dole, a former president of the American Red Cross and a
Cabinet secretary in both the Reagan and Bush administrations;
Lamar Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee; Bill Bradley,
the former senator from New Jersey who is Gore's main rival for the
Democratic nomination, and former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has attracted the help of several lobbyists with clients
who have interests before the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee, which he leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not say lobbyists are the foundation of John McCain's
support,'' said Howard Opinsky, the spokesman for McCain's
campaign. Opinsky added that McCain had accepted contributions from
people on both sides of numerous issues before the committee, and
that the senator's votes were based solely on ``what is best for
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole has been assisted in her fund-raising efforts by her
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, and several other
influential lawyers and lobbyists, including Wayne Valis of Valis &AMP;
Associates and James Burnley IV, a partner in the Washington office
of Winson &AMP; Strawn, a law firm based in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
