<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURVEY-AD-COLUMN-550&AMP;     06-21 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVEY-AD-COLUMN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY FINDS CEO'S LUKEWARM ON ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next phase of a major multiyear communications effort to
promote the importance of advertising is getting under way _ and
not a moment too soon, judging by the results of a national survey
of top corporate executives.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, commissioned by the American Advertising Federation,
shows surprisingly lukewarm support for advertising as a tool to
help companies grow. Even as the executives acknowledged that they
considered advertising a valuable sales stimulus, only 43.1 percent
of the survey respondents said that advertising would gain
importance for them over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked whether they were satisfied with their companies'
advertising efforts, just 6.8 percent replied that they were very
satisfied _ a fraction of the 69.8 percent declaring themselves
generally satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at companies with big ad budgets were much more
favorably disposed to advertising than were those with less to
spend. And large majorities of the respondents said they agreed
that advertising was a worthwhile long-term investment and could
help lift a company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the implications of the survey are clear. If chief
executives, chief marketing officers and other top managers are
skeptical about the effectiveness of advertising, they are more
likely to cut ad budgets in bad times and not increase them
significantly in good times.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, three out of four survey respondents said they expected
their companies' ad budgets to grow over the next three years, but
only by a modest average of 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What all that tells me is that these executives are not
enthusiastic about advertising,'' said Wally Snyder, president and
chief executive of the advertising federation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an optimistic person,'' he added, ``I think the survey
leads us to a real opportunity for enhancing advertising's
positioning with top executives. There's an upside for us in
convincing them that advertising has much to offer strategically.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted in March by Erdos &AMP; Morgan among senior
managers at U.S. companies. The results were released last week at
the 1999 American Advertising Conference in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The results show that advertising decision makers at companies
``are not strongly in favor of advertising, but they're not
strongly against it, either,'' said David Park, president at DDB
Los Angeles, part of the DDB Worldwide Communications Group unit of
Omnicom Group, which took part in analyzing the survey results.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the lack of fervor for advertising among
respondents, Park said, was a frustration that while they were
defining advertising more broadly, they perceived that agencies
were still defining it in terms of traditional measures like
television commercials and print ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of advertising needs to be redefined as a strategic
partner, and broadened,'' Park said, to include measures like
direct marketing, Internet advertising, sales promotion and other
so-called integrated marketing communications.
</P>
<P>
   Only then, he added, can advertising ``assert its role at the
enterprise table, as it were, in terms of convincing executives of
the contributions it can make to business success.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Plans for the survey were announced at the federation's
conference last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason for the survey was our belief that too many CEOs
still think of advertising as something further down on the food
chain than it should be, an expense instead of an investment,''
said Lou Schultz, vice chairman at Campbell-Ewald in Warren, Mich.,
a unit of Interpublic Group of Cos., who made a presentation on the
survey at this year's conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually came out a little more positively than we had
anticipated,'' he added, referring to the survey results. ``Still,
there's a lot of work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the federation also announced plans to undertake a
campaign aimed at corporate executives to demonstrate the
importance of advertising. Now, as the survey results underscore
the need for such a campaign, the federation is selecting an agency
to handle the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, chosen by a steering committee after a review, is
Carmichael Lynch in Minneapolis, a creatively focused shop owned by
Interpublic that works for clients including Harley-Davidson,
Korbel champagne and Schwinn bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A campaign directed to CEOs would have a good chance, if it's
the right campaign, to elevate advertising in their minds as a
strategic discipline to help them,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gratified that the survey demonstrates that people are
pretty happy with advertising,'' he added, ``and we have high marks
generally. On the other hand, advertising is not getting mentioned
as much as it ought to in regard to sales and marketing goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder was referring to a survey question that asked the
executives to rank the strategic importance of various company
departments in meeting sales and marketing goals. Advertising
ranked sixth out of seven, ahead only of the legal department and
badly trailing operations like product development, strategic
planning and public relations.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael Lynch is providing its creative services for the
campaign pro bono. The federation will pay the production costs and
is asking magazines and newspapers to donate the equivalent of $12
million worth of space to run the advertisements, which will carry
the theme ``Advertising: A new brand of business.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Snyder said, publications including Adweek, Forbes, The
New York Times and The Wall Street Journal have agreed ``to run at
least some of the ads.''
</P>
<P>
   The federation, which represents advertisers, agencies, media
companies, local advertising associations and college students
studying advertising, is not alone in sponsoring efforts to beat
the drum for drum-beating advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Advertising Agencies, for example,
is conducting interviews with corporate leaders who are true
believers in the power of brand-building advertising. The
association, based in New York, plans to distribute tapes of the
interviews, with executives like Herbert D. Kelleher, the chairman,
president and chief executive of Southwest Airlines Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
