<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH APPEALS TO SOCIAL CONSERVATIVES IN SOUTH CAROLINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: Toddy Atwater is cq) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The battle for the linchpin South Carolina
Republican presidential primary opened Monday as Texas Gov. George
W. Bush promised social conservatives he will promote
sexual-abstinence education if he becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, GOP candidate John McCain, a U.S. senator from
Arizona, tried to chip away at the impression that Bush is the
inevitable Republican nominee. McCain released a list of South
Carolina supporters, including eight state legislators who he said
had defected from the Bush camp. The eight had signed a letter in
February urging Bush to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   The skirmishing signalled the importance of South Carolina, the
first major primary after Iowa and New Hampshire and a harbinger of
the critical Southern primaries a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has the backing of South Carolina's lieutenant
governor and House speaker, called the state ``friendly political
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know I've got to earn the support and earn the votes of
the folks of South Carolina,'' Bush said. ``It's impossible to get
the Republican nomination without carrying this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is on a five-day campaign and fund-raising swing that will
take him from South Carolina to Richmond, Va., Washington, D.C.,
Pennsylvania, Michigan and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's capital, Bush will hold a fund-raiser and will
meet privately with his supporters in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   There was no public announcement of the meeting, but word was
spread by personal letter from Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``will be joined by 20-plus senators who have endorsed his
candidacy and who are hosting a meeting,'' Coverdell wrote in a
letter sent to all GOP senators except rival White House contenders
McCain and Bob Smith, R-N.H.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has been pivotal in at least three recent
Republican presidential nominating contests.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush all but put the 1988 Republican nomination
out of reach of Sen. Bob Dole and evangelist Pat Robertson by
winning South Carolina. And Dole revived his struggling 1996
campaign with a victory here over Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   But former Texas Gov. John Connally had the endorsement of every
major Republican in the state except one in 1980, when Ronald
Reagan won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina, since 1980, has always decided who the nominee
is going to be because of the momentum the winner gets from here,''
said J. Sam Daniels, executive director of the South Carolina
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   In past elections, the greatest threat to establishment
Republican candidates in this state has come from candidates who
appeal to social and religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush appealed to those voters Monday by laying out a
three-point promise to promote abstinence education, one of the
first specific plans of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to provide as much federal funding for abstinence
education as is now spent on teen contraception programs, about
$135 million a year. He said he wants to guarantee that faith-based
organizations can obtain federal funds for abstinence training
without compromising their religious mission. He also wants the
General Accounting Office to study the effectiveness of federally
funded sex-education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must encourage our children to make the healthy choice of
abstinence,'' Bush said after attending an abstinence-training
program in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also fired back at Democrats who have tried to portray him
as soft on gun control. President Clinton this week said Bush did
not do enough to influence passage of federal gun control
legislation, and last week Vice President Al Gore criticized Bush
for signing a bill prohibiting most lawsuits against gun
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the bill would allow the Texas attorney general to sue
gun manufacturers if it was in the public interest. Bush said
Democrats want to turn public policy over to trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in subcontracting out public policy to trial
lawyers,'' Bush said. ``This (Clinton) administration ... does
subcontract out a lot of public policy to some of their biggest
financial backers, the trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a Vietnam combat veteran who spent five years as a
prisoner of war, is practically abandoning any campaign in Iowa for
more emphasis on South Carolina because of the state's large
military population. The state is home to the Citadel military
school.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his strategy is to become a viable alternative for the
Republican nomination if Bush's campaign should falter.
</P>
<P>
   McCain released a list of legislative supporters, which included
eight of the 58 who signed a letter urging Bush to run for
president. One of the 58 had earlier signed on to the Elizabeth
Dole campaign.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Pro Tem Terry Haskins said the endorsements showed
that McCain is gaining momentum on Bush in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suddenly became clear that the Republican nomination should
be earned, not inherited,'' Haskins said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker David Wilkins, a Bush backer, called the
defections ``much ado about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is the majority of people who signed on are still
with, strong with Gov. Bush, and that's more than all the other
candidates put together,'' Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across South Carolina, the average citizen likes him (Bush),
and they will like him even more when they get to know him
better,'' Lt. Gov. Bob Peeler added.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 enthusiastic Republicans turned out to see Bush at the
Sunset Restaurant in West Columbia, including the mother of late
Republican political consultant Lee Atwater. The younger Bush was
Atwater's assistant when Atwater ran George Bush's 1988
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got South Carolina,'' Toddy Atwater said of the Texas
governor. ``He learned under the best, under Lee. He learned a lot
from his dad, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the restaurant said they were inclined toward Bush
because they liked his father's presidency and because they like
what they have heard about his leadership in Texas. Several said
they also liked either Dole or McCain as second choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happens to him, Elizabeth would be the next best
choice,'' said Marian Rozier, 80, of Camden, S.C. ``She energizes
the women. Of course, he does too because of his looks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
