<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-VOUCHERS-COX     06-21 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-VOUCHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State officials expect early challenge to school voucher law
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush fulfilled his most important
campaign promise Monday, signing into law the nation's first
statewide program to offer private-school vouchers to parents of
children in public schools deemed failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the fun begins, when we roll up our sleeves and see that
children learn. And when they don't we're not going to blame them
anymore,'' Bush said at a ceremony at a Tallahassee middle school,
the same place he announced his ``A-plus'' education plan last
August.
</P>
<P>
   The first vouchers could be issued in a matter of weeks for some
800 children at two Pensacola elementary schools _ the only two
schools to have made the state's current ``critically
low-performing schools'' list two years running and, under the new
law, therefore eligible for vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the children is 5-year-old Jessica Merkman, who would have
started kindergarten at A.A. Dixon Elementary on July 1. ``I don't
want her there,'' said her mother, hotel clerk Dermita Merkman, 26,
who is glad for the voucher that will let her daughter attend a
Montessori school or one of three Catholic schools that have agreed
to accept the voucher _ worth about $3,500 _ as full payment of
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Merkman is one of 120 Pensacola parents so far who have
expressed interest in a voucher _ if the plan's opponents aren't
able to block it in court first.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's teachers unions, their traditional allies like the
Parent-Teacher Association and the American Civil Liberties Union
plan to file a lawsuit in Tallahassee this morning challenging the
constitutionality of allowing tax money to be spent at religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``A scheme to divert public money to religious institutions is
in blatant violation of the Florida Constitution,'' said Leon
Russell, president of the Florida NAACP and among 17 groups that
call themselves the Florida Coalition for Public Education.
</P>
<P>
   Lining up against them are Floridians for School Choice, the
group financed by corporate executives that helped Bush lobby for
the schools law, and the Washingtonbased Institute for Justice, a
non-profit group that helps defend voucher plans in courts all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, this program will not proceed unmolested,'' said Clint
Bolick, the group's litigation director. ``We expect to see a
challenge before the ink is dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, all children in grades three through 10 would
be tested annually, with schools receiving letter grades based on
the scores. Schools receiving an ``F'' grade in two of any four
years would have to offer vouchers to all parents of its students.
</P>
<P>
   The broad testing plan won't begin for two more years, but in
the interim, schools could be subject to those measures if they
fail the existing batteries of tests now given to fourth, eighth,
and tenth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   No Treasure Coast schools are eligible for vouchers this year.
In Martin County, no school has had more than one year of failing
scores and any St. Lucie schools that might have been on the
borderline saved themselves this year with adequate scores in
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he only wants schools to serve all their students,
including those traditionally written off, such as those in poor
inner cities or areas with large number of seasonal migrants. He
would prefer that schools meet ever-higher standards and therefore
never be eligible for vouchers, or, as he calls them, ``opportunity
scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is zero,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, though, that he plans to fight the lawsuit vigorously,
with his legal staff cooperating with lawyers in Attorney General
Bob Butterworth's office, as well as with those from outside groups
like the Institute for Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Stephanie Desmon and Dani Davies contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
