<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-NACCHIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QWEST'S NACCHIO ADDRESSES HIS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the takeover battle for U S West, the smallest of the
regional Bell telephone companies, and Frontier Corp., the
long-distance telephone concern, were theater, it would have all
the plot twists of an Italian opera.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day, it seems, a new rumor pops up regarding these
two companies and the upstarts that are vying to own them. Global
Crossing Ltd., the fledgling concern based in Bermuda, wants to
build a worldwide telecommunications network and recently announced
agreements to merge with both U S West and Frontier valued at $47
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Qwest Communications International last week made a $55
billion hostile offer for the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, people close to the talks said U S West's board
of directors was meeting to discuss Qwest's bid as early as Monday
night, and a statement regarding the offer was expected soon. Last
week, Frontier said its board was taking no action regarding the
proposed bid from Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   But while U S West weighs the Qwest offer, Joseph P. Nacchio,
Qwest's chief executive, took the opportunity to address his
critics Monday when the company announced a joint venture with the
consulting and accounting firm KPMG LLP to sell Internet-based
business services. He angered investors recently, who watched the
value of the company's stock drop more that 24 percent June 14.
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio told reporters in a conference call that he had sent
letters to both Frontier and U S West reaffirming his offers and
had filed documents with the Securities and Exchange Commission to
support the bids. Nacchio has been criticized for not supporting
both bids fully.
</P>
<P>
   In those documents, the company said that it was Philip
Anschutz, Qwest's board chairman and largest shareholder who placed
the call to U S West's chief executive, Solomon D. Trujillo, June
13 telling him a hostile bid was about to begin. Trujillo was also
informed, via letter, that he would be allowed to stay on as vice
chairman of Qwest's board and that up to four U S West board
members would be added to the combined company's board. What is
less clear is what would happen to Joseph P. Clayton, chief
executive of Frontier, who was not offered a position in senior
management, but was told that Frontier would get two board seats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drubbing he has taken lately, Nacchio was relaxed
and confident when he sat down in one-on-one interviews to explain
his company's rationale. He scoffed at the notion that the battle
for U S West and Frontier was in any way ``personal,'' noting that
Jack Grubman, an analyst who works for Salomon Smith Barney, which
is advising Global Crossing, had attended his son's graduation
party the day before the bids were started. Grubman helped Nacchio
get his job at Qwest, and despite Grubman's defense of Global,
Nacchio said, ``The punchline is we'll still be friends after this
is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio said he spent the Friday before Qwest began the offer in
meetings with executives at BellSouth, which recently took a 10
percent stake in Qwest, including its chief executive, F. Duane
Ackerman. ``We asked them to kick the tires and see if the
synergies were there,'' Nacchio explained.
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio said he has been willing to make personal concessions if
U S West agreed to be acquired by Qwest, even stepping down as the
head of a combined entity. ``If my board asked me to step down for
Sol, I'd be fine,'' he said, referring to Trujillo, U S West's
chief executive. ``This is not my company, but the shareholders'
company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
