u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-NOTES22-CO     06-21 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks join debate on low scoring
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lenny Wilkens and Steve Smith are in town today to
see if they can help save the NBA from itself. The Hawks coach and
the team's best player are members of a special committee that will
advise the league on how to reverse a disturbing trend toward ugly
play and low scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy commissioner Russ Granik said Monday that the league can
use the various summer leagues and then the exhibition season to
implement changes that would promote offense and a better flow to
the game.
</P>
<P>
   In nine years, the league has seen team scoring decline from 107
points to 91.6 points per game. Shooting has dropped from .476 to
.437. A number of elements are to blame, from a trend to younger
and less skilled players to tighter control by coaches, who want to
hold down scores, to excessive physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   (The NBA board of governors) indicated to us that they don't
need a lot of debate, that if we are comfortable with the results
of the committee, then we should just go with it,'' commissioner
David Stern said. ``Let's put it into effect in the summer . . .
and get teams ready to abide by those changes during the exhibition
season, so that nobody is surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, there appears to be a mandate to clean up the game,
ending more than a decade of brutish play that has seen hard
physical blows and holding used to compensate for lack of quickness
and skills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the foul lane could be widened at its base to open
up the middle, and there is some sentiment to shorten the time the
ball can be held in the backcourt, now 10 seconds. There is no
clear consensus on throwing out rules prohibiting zone defenses,
and the outer dimensions of the court will not be changed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Wilkens, the committee includes active coaches
Rudy Tomjanovich, Rick Pitino and Pat Riley and club executives
Kevin McHale, Billy King and Donnie Walsh. All are former players.
Antonio Davis of Indiana is the other active player on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Three NBA television anaylsts _ former coach Hubie Brown, former
player and coach Doug Collins and former player Isiah Thomas _ will
sit in. Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski is a volunteer. The owners
involved are Phoenix's Jerry Colangelo, an advocate of an up-tempo
game, and Cleveland's Gordon Sund, who fired coach Mike Fratello to
change his team's walk-up style.
</P>
<P>
   The teen problem
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Granik said they will continue to address ways to
limit the influx of underclassmen into the league.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said that 20 appears to be the right age to begin a new
wage scale that discourages players from coming out, and that the
players association is sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA also is interested in having a league _ either the CBA
or a new one _ in which young players under contract could play
rather than sit on an NBA bench with no chance of gaining
experience.
</P>
<P>
   L.J.'s tantrum
</P>
<P>
   The league acted swiftly Sunday to fine New York forward Larry
Johnson $25,000 and the Knicks $25,000 more for his conduct.
Johnson cursed the media and was verbally abusive toward two
members of the NBA's public-relations staff.
</P>
<P>
   The fine is Johnson's second of the playoffs. He was fined
$10,000 during the Eastern Conference finals for refusing to
participate in a media session.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
