<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORES-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAID TO GIVE ALBERTSON'S APPROVAL ON $8.3 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal officials have agreed that they will not
block Albertson's Inc. in its $8.3 billion purchase of American
Stores Co., now that Albertson has agreed to sell 144 stores in
three states, people involved in the review said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The divestiture, which is expected to be announced soon by the
federal government and the states where the stores are to be sold,
would be the largest ever ordered by the Federal Trade Commission
in the retailing industry. But it represents only a small part of
the proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would create a company with more than 2,300 stores in
37 states and nearly 200,000 employees. When the deal was
announced, executives expected the new company to have revenue of
about $36 billion, creating the nation's second-largest food and
drug retailer, behind Kroger Co. of Cincinnati, which has $43
billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is part of a wave of consolidation in the supermarket
business. Four weeks ago, Kroger became the largest supermarket
chain in the nation when it completed its acquisition of Fred Meyer
Inc. In that deal, regulators ordered the sale of eight stores.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the review of the Albertson acquisition would
not disclose the buyers for the stores that are being sold. But
they said that more than 100 of the stores were in California and
the rest in Nevada and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   American Stores, which is based in Salt Lake City, operates more
than 1,500 stores in 26 states, including 269 combination
food-and-drug stores and 539 supermarkets that operate under the
names Acme markets, Jewel Food Stores and Lucky Stores.
Albertson's, which is based in Boise, Idaho, operates 916 retail
stores in 23 states. Both chains' stores will retain their names,
and the company headquarters will be in Boise. Executives have been
planning to close the deal by the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
