<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST KING WILL ELEVATE MURRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings' Andy Murray just became a
better coach.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, too, considering Larry Robinson's successor
absorbed more shots in his first week on the job than Kings
goaltender Stephane Fiset did all year.
</P>
<P>
   Come the fall, no one will care that Murray has never coached a
game in the NHL. Not now that sniper Zigmund Palffy has his back.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is in the trenches. When a coach has a proven
scorer within easy tapping distance, it does wonders for his
strategies and stature.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wilson's image as a rink general was transformed almost
overnight when the Mighty Ducks acquired winger Teemu Selanne from
Winnipeg in February of 1996. The Ducks were 18-30-5 at the time
and Wilson was wilting from having to dodge so many slings and
arrows. With Selanne, the Ducks went 17-9-3 the rest of the way and
just like that, Wilson became an inspiration to his troops.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, a seventh-year veteran from Slovakia, has great
instincts, soft hands and superlative vision. He can make everybody
around him look better, including his coach. He is Luc Robitaille
without the crow's feet, Jozef Stumpel with a shooter's mentality.
He is L.A.'s answer to Teemu Selanne right down to his clipped
accent and mitigated joy at coming to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   When Selanne was traded, he felt as though his foundation had
been rocked. His wife was within weeks of delivering the couple's
first child and he had just been assured by management that he
wasn't going to be traded. It was the first time he had been dealt
and the sensation was not unlike a sucker punch.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with Palffy, whom the Islanders claimed in the second
round of the 1991 draft. He made his NHL debut in 1993-94. Starting
two seasons later, he strung together three consecutive 40-goal
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   His ardor for the Islanders' management cooled as a result of
acrimonious contract negotiations that kept the 5-foot-10 right
wing off the ice for the first two months of the 1998-99 season.
But his love for the area and its fans never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five years there, it's hard to deal with (being sent
away),'' Palffy said.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding matters is the fact that not long after he was
finally signed to a six-year, $33-million deal, Palffy bought a
home on Long Island. It was his baby, if you will, but as of Monday
it was back on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can find somebody who'll be interested in it, let me
know,'' Palffy quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The laugh that followed was as infectious as a virus.
</P>
<P>
   If L.A.'s not careful, it could catch hockey fever hanging
around Palffy, who should warm to Southern California as quickly as
did Selanne. The good news is Palffy seems immune to the Hollywood
bug that has sapped the productivity of many athletes once they've
been exposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do nothing but play hockey,'' he said in a
conference call with reporters. ``The Los Angeles Kings have
brought me here for a reason, for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. To become the first King since Robitaille in 1992-93
to score 50 goals, for one thing. And mainly to get his first taste
of playoff experience. Palffy has played 331 NHL games, none of
them in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange but true: Right wing Dan Bylsma has scored 162
fewer NHL goals than Palffy's 168 and appeared in two more NHL
playoff games. No one ever said hockey was fair. (isn't that right,
Buffalo?)
</P>
<P>
   From what Palffy's heard, it can be stirring, playing in May and
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real difficult not to be in the playoffs,'' he said.
``I'm trying my best all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy figures it's time his potential was plucked. He feels
ripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the right age right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, 27, is the same age as two other scorers of note,
Shaquille O'Neal and Mia Hamm. It cheers us to report that Palffy's
priorities are closer to the team-oriented Hamm than the
me-oriented O'Neal. So there'll be no need to do any last-minute
tinkering with the blueprint to make room for another oversized ego
in the new Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey is 20 guys playing like a team,'' Palffy said. ``The
Kings want me to create offense. I'm ready for that. I like to
create a lot of offense. Hockey right now is two ways, so I play
defense, too. I play any way coach wants me to play now.''
</P>
<P>
   The breeze that just rustled the pages of your newspaper was
Murray sighing in immense relief.
</P>
<P>
   For all the fans who clamored this past season for the Russian
Rocket, Pavel Bure, consider this: When a Palffy-for-Bure trade was
floated this past fall, no one shot it down as though it were a
bunch of hot air.
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor tried prying Palffy from the
Islanders during the Slovakia native's contract holdout. His
persistence paid off on Sunday. The feeling is that come May,
Palffy's persistence finally will be rewarded, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
