<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOLF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN OPEN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 22:
</P>
<P>
   Heroic is a word that rarely leaps to the lips when talk turns
to golf. But if Payne Stewart's one-shot victory at the U.S. Open
on Sunday was not heroic in the physical-bravery sense, it
certainly met the competitive definition of grace under pressure.
He had won the tournament before, and he had lost before too, after
going into the final round last year with a four-stroke lead that
vanished by late afternoon. Stewart returned to the Open this year
much as Juli Inkster did to the U.S. Women's Open earlier this
month _ determined to redeem a painful loss.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster won comfortably, but Stewart did not win until the final
putt on the final hole, an interminable 15-footer that became the
longest winning final putt in Open history. If Tiger Woods, who
finished third, had made three putts that together totaled less
than 15 feet, he would have won the tournament. But what made
Stewart's victory valiant was not just his remarkable long putts on
16 and 18. It was having seen his lead slip away and refusing to
let it slip away for good. When Phil Mickelson, Stewart's playing
partner in the final pairing, pulled even and then ahead, nearly
everyone in the audience thought of last year, when Stewart lost a
chance to tie on the final hole. But this year, on a notoriously
difficult golf course in Pinehurst, N.C., Stewart demonstrated that
the course is only as difficult as the state of mind you play it
in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
