<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TERRORISM-WITNESS-     06-21 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TERRORISM-WITNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WON'T FREE MAN WHO REFUSED TO TESTIFY IN TERRORISM CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan has refused to free an
Orlando, Fla., man who was jailed last month for refusing to
testify before a federal grand jury investigating Osama bin Laden
and his suspected role in worldwide terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Robert Patterson Jr., issued his order last
Wednesday, after the witness, Ihab Ali, reiterated in court that he
would not testify. Ali had earlier cited religious reasons as a
basis for his refusal and has been held in the Metropolitan
Correctional Center since May 19. The case had been handled under a
secrecy order until last week's hearing. A transcript was made
public Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The jailing of Ali is just one of the latest developments in the
federal investigation of Americans suspected of involvement with
bin Laden, who has been indicted in the bombings of U.S. embassies
last August in Kenya and Tanzania as well as other acts of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, the government revealed for the first
time that it was investigating ``co-conspirators'' of bin Laden in
Orlando, Fla., according to a newly released indictment.
Prosecutors have also been investigating people in Texas and in
California, records show.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, moreover, a number of Muslims from Texas, the
Washington area and California have been subpoenaed by the grand
jury or questioned by the FBI, according to some of their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see if there's a network here,'' said Lynne
Stewart, who represents Khader Ibrahim, a Texas man who testified
for several hours last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart said that Ibrahim, a friend of Wadih el-Hage, a
Texan who has been indicted and is in custody, had nothing to hide.
``He is a small businessman who befriended a fellow Muslim, and
that's where it begins and where it ends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Cohen, who represents Moataz Al-Hallak, the imam of the
Islamic Society of Arlington, Texas, where el-Hage was a member,
said his client considered refusing to testify. But Al-Hallak then
decided to answer the questions ``because he felt an imperative
that the grand jury get a view of his world,'' Cohen said, ``a view
that they were otherwise denied, that as a man, a Muslim, an imam,
a community leader, there's nothing to fear from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen added: ``He wouldn't know Osama bin Laden if he knocked at
the door and tried to sell him cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney
in Manhattan, had no comment on the criticism or the case.
</P>
<P>
   The five defendants who are in custody in New York are scheduled
to appear for arraignment Tuesday before Judge Leonard Sand of
federal District Court. Nine other defendants, including bin Laden,
remain at large, while another is fighting extradition from
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Ali's lawyer, Ashraf Nubani, said his client denied any
wrongdoing. He said that Ali refused to testify last May 19 for
religious reasons, based on his conviction that he should not
answer questions that could unjustly harm other Muslims. In court
last Wednesday, after Ali again refused to testify, Nubani renewed
his arguments to Judge Patterson, the transcript shows, adding that
Ali also feared for the safety of his family in Egypt and
mistrusted the government's motives.
</P>
<P>
   Nubani said that his client believed that the government was
using ``guilt by association'' to harass Muslims, the transcript
shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990621.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4641 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-STEWART-HNS &LR;      06-21 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Payne Stewart is a father, too. And a far more
knowledgeable one now than when he won his first U.S. Open in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of people pulling for Phil Mickelson to win his
first major championship Sunday at the Open at Pinehurst No. 2. It
would have made for a terrific tale, Mickelson breaking through on
Father's Day, then jetting home to Arizona to become one as his
wife will have their first child probably this week or next.
</P>
<P>
   But what was lost in the grand moment that was one of golf's
most riveting tournaments this decade was how much Stewart has
changed during the course of his career and particularly in the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
   When he won the Open in '91, he did everything he could to
capitalize on the moment. Stewart flew overseas for all the
appearance money he could grab and signed endorsement deals. He
sold his soul but was rewarded with more money than most people can
even dream about. It is similar to what Mark O'Meara is doing this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his third major championship coming at age 42 and with
his kids age 13 and 10, Stewart knows he will handle this U.S. Open
championship differently. And better. While O'Meara can be excused
for jumping at every financial opportunity because he had never won
a major until getting two last year, Stewart now can push away from
the feast rather than feel like he has to gorge himself while the
getting is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to enjoy this one a lot more,'' Stewart said.
``It's easier to understand now the obligations that come along
with being the United States Open champion. It will be easier to
understand that my family comes first, and then if I have time for
those obligations I'll take care of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a lot more prepared to deal with everything that
goes along with holding on to this trophy for a year. I don't plan
on changing my schedules. I plan on doing the same things that I've
been doing that got me in position to win this, which is working
out and spending a lot of time at home and playing at golf
tournaments I enjoy playing at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look forward to running after the elusive dollar,
because I've been invited to go play here and here and here and
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart can take this approach because he's more content now
than he was eight years ago. He also has learned the value of
values. His faith became a stronger part of his life in the past
two years, and with that he has found out how rewarding it is to be
a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so much fun being at home, being a father, taking my
kids to school, going to school athletics,'' he said. ``That's what
my life is right now. And I'm not going to do what I did in '91
along those lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in '91, Stewart could be forgiven for milking the
Open title for all it was worth. His kids were younger, and it was
a valuable time in his life for cementing his future.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, Stewart not only can revel in the fact that he can
be a family man who just happens to have won one of the most
memorable U.S. Opens in history.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it on a course designed by Scotsman Donald Ross on a
Sunday that felt more like some dank, misty course in Britain than
in the sand hills of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Before Stewart had started his round Sunday, he cut off the arms
of what was no doubt an expensive rain shirt. Just before dusk, he
clipped off any question as to whether he deserves to be mentioned
with the top players this year in terms of what he has accomplished
in the here and now.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart became the only person other than David Duval and Tiger
Woods to have more than one victory on the PGA Tour this year. He's
the O'Meara of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was O'Meara who experienced a revival of his
career at the grand old age of 41. Stewart is 17 days younger than
O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Stewart has changed since his early days on
the PGA Tour. He often was gruff with the media and earned a
reputation for his sarcasm and his sometimes-caustic personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've learned that you guys have jobs, too,'' he said
earlier this year after winning at Pebble Beach. ``It doesn't make
any sense to make your life harder when it doesn't really take any
effort on my part to do an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart hasn't lost his outspoken ways. He says what he
thinks. And that's why he's going to be a strong member of the
Ryder Cup team in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about that, and there's going to be a lot of new
faces on both sides,'' he said. ``David Duval has never been on a
Ryder Cup team, which is really hard to believe. And there will be
a lot of new faces on the European team. I think I can bring some
knowledge to guys like Duval, who are not going to be used to
hearing people cheer when he misses a putt. I'm a rah-rah person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
