<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-STERN-ADDRESS-HNS     06-21 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-ADDRESS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ With the basketball world gathered in the Big Apple for
the NBA Finals, the league today will use the opportunity to
address the state of the game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his annual address to the media Monday, NBA commissioner
David Stern spent part of the time discussing today's meeting of
the ``Special Committee.'' A total of 16 representatives from
different areas of NBA expertise will meet to recommend ways to
address the decline in scoring and shooting percentages over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other issues discussed were age limitations on players
entering the league and television ratings in the wake of the
lockout. But the main issue was the Special Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' Rudy Tomjanovich is one four NBA head coaches on
the committee, along with Boston's Rick Pitino, Miami's Pat Riley
and Atlanta's Lenny Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   There are also players (Indiana's Antonio Davis and Atlanta's
Steve Smith), front-office personnel (Denver's Dan Issel,
Philadelphia's Billy King, Minnesota's Kevin McHale and Indiana's
Donnie Walsh), owners (Phoenix's Jerry Colangelo and Cleveland's
Gordon Gund) and broadcasters (Turner Sports' Hubie Brown and NBC's
Doug Collins and Isiah Thomas). The only non-NBA representative is
Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming the commissioner and some of the other people in
the league consider this a fairly substantial problem and want to
try and get it resolved,'' Issel said of the NBA's offensive woes.
``With the exception of Sacramento's, everybody's offense looks the
same. You find your best post player, and you throw it in to him so
that there has to be a double team. Then you kick it out and try to
find an open shot someplace. I think some changes need to be
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee will break the game up into four separate areas of
discussion _ how the officials call the game, changing the court
dimensions, tinkering with timing rules (the 24-second shot clock,
the 10-second rule for advancing the ball past midcourt, etc.) and
guidelines for how players play defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is something else that anybody has on the committee
that doesn't fall within those four groups, we will talk about that
as well,'' said NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik. ``But we have
sort of outlined those four things as areas to put in front of the
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of age requirements is touchy, since some of the
league's better players, like Thomas and Magic Johnson, entered the
NBA at a relatively young age.
</P>
<P>
   But one problem with the league's four-year rookie scale (with
clubs holding a fifth-year option), which was implemented as part
of the new collective bargaining agreement with the players, is
that an increasing number of players might leave school early
simply to get their commitment over with sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The league is talking about a minimum age of 20, with the
possibility of extending the scale one year for every year before
that age a player enters the league. But it is subject to
discussion with the National Basketball Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``(There is) the issue of whether 17- and 18-year-olds are
subjected to too much pressure and the sort of difficulties of life
on the road,'' Stern said. ``There is some notion of players, once
they are drafted young and they don't make it that may end their
careers. But if they had somewhat better-developed skills (through
staying in college), their chances for a longer NBA career would be
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the flip side of the argument having to do with
allowing people who are gifted who don't want to attend college
having access to the place where they can earn a living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
