<HEADLINE>
FARM FARMLAND INDUSTRIES BREAKS GROUND ON HEADQUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Farmland Industries Inc. broke ground Monday
on the first building in a 122-acre headquarters campus near Kansas
City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The six-story building will house about 1,000 employees who now
work in seven buildings scattered throughout the Northland.
Farmland executives said the building should be completed by
February 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Cleberg, Farmland's president and chief executive, said
heavy equipment would begin preparing the land for development
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said the farmer-owned cooperative scheduled the
groundbreaking now to calm worries about Farmland's merger talks
with Cenex Harvest States of St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we are having discussions,'' Cleberg told about 50
guests, including Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes. ``Yes, those
discussions are progressing satisfactorily. We expect to have a
presence in Kansas City for as long as we can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to reassure you that you have our presence in Kansas
City and our major commitment to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The agriculture co-op proclaimed that commitment in December,
when it announced plans for its new headquarters near Interstates
29 and 435.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a Kansas City Council committee granted
zoning for the development.
</P>
<P>
   David Eaheart, Farmland spokesman, said the plan for the site
now included 1.2 million square feet of office space because zoning
changes caused the co-op to drop one building from the plan. The
original eight-building plan, announced at the end of 1998, called
for 1.3 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The first building to go up will have about 280,000 square feet
and include a cafeteria, credit union branch office, a product test
kitchen and an employee fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Eaheart said he didn't know the cost of putting up the first
building.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland attorney Charles Miller said the co-op planned to seek
development incentives for the campus. Miller said the plan could
be submitted to the City Council in 30 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-99 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
