<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-21 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4658 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONE-PHONE_SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-PHONE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Cell Phones to Beep Hot Deals to Owners  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
As if billboards, television and radio weren't enough, advertisers
have found a new way to reach out and touch consumers _ through
their cell phones.
<P>
   An Alameda company called Geoworks Corp. is launching a service
today  &LR; t &LR; hat will alert consumers about promotional deals at
various stores and eateries through their wireless phone or pager.
</P>
<P>
   Stores like Virgin Records, for example, will be able to send
customers a text message telling them that the ``Austin Powers'' CD
is on sale for a few hours only.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike direct mail or e-mail solicitations, which are
usually unsolicited, these pitches will only go to people who sign
up for the Discopro.com service. Discopro is short for discount
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to get the ads will choose which companies they
want to receive information from, as well as how often and what
time of day they want the promotions to reach their cell phone or
pager.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will then receive information about deals being
offered by the various companies that participate in Discopro.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers may get a message saying `Come into Noah's Bagels
and get three free bagels,''' said Dave Grannan, president and CEO
of Geoworks. ``If a customer is on their way to work, they can pull
right in and take advantage of the promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefit to the advertiser is that the customer will probably
buy something else while he or she is in the store and probably
return for another visit, Grannan said. Advertisers pay Geoworks an
undisclosed fee to participate in the service.
</P>
<P>
   Discopro.com is free for consumers and available to anyone with
an alphanumeric pager or a digital cell phone that has text
messaging.
</P>
<P>
   To sign up, customers must go to  &LR; www.discopro.com &LR;  and give
their name and mobile phone or pager number. They are alerted to
incoming advertisements by a beep or ring.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, about 20 companies have signed up to advertise with
Discopro.com, including Virgin Records, Noah's, Hollywood Video and
T.G.I Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Grannan said he expects to at least double the number of
advertisers soon. Companies pay Geoworks a fee to be included in
the Discopro.com database.
</P>
<P>
   While the service is the first of its kind, it is part of a
growing trend to match up advertisers and consumers via a mobile
device.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Vicinity Corp. of Palo Alto let customers find
the nearest Starbucks or Marriott Hotel simply by pushing a few
buttons on their cell phone. And customers who use the new Palm VII
from 3Com's Palm Computing can access retailers with the Palm's
wireless Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   But Discopro.com is the first service to send promotional
information to a cell phone, industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Grannan said Geoworks decided to launch the service after asking
customers what they wanted from their wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we think is compelling is that it's completely consumer
controlled. You decide what you want to receive, as well as when
and where you want to get the information,'' Grannan said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is targeting a wide range of consumers, including
professionals and teenagers, Grannan said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Grannan is bullish on the service's future, industry
watchers say it may not be an instant success.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Enderle, vice president of Giga Information Group in Santa
Clara, said the success of Discopro.com will depend on how the
information is presented to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how invasive the advertising is,'' Enderle said.
``If the right kind of companies use the service and the
advertising is more entertaining than obtrusive, then than  &LR; yes,
you can drive purchasing activity.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the types of advertising that will work with this
service are limited, Enderle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good for things people want instantaneously,'' he
said. ``Less reliable are ads for large capital purchases, like a
washing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
