r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCKESSON-MCKESSON-SFC     06-21 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKESSON-MCKESSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
McKessonHBOC Dumps Its Top Management &HT;    
 &HT;    By Tom Abate &HT;    c.1999 The San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the biggest corporate bloodbaths ever, McKessonHBOC
Inc. said yesterday that it fired five top executives and two
others resigned in the wake of an accounting scandal that has cut
its stock value by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkably blunt statement, McKesson said its board of
directors had ``removed'' Charles W. McCall as McKesson's chairman
and ``dismissed'' him as an employee _ without a severance package.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking over as McKesson's chairman in January, McCall had
been chief executive of HBO &AMP; Co., the Atlanta software firm that
drug-distribution company McKesson acquired in January for $13.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In April, McKesson announced that before the merger, HBOC had
improperly booked millions of dollars in revenues. The revelation
cut McKesson's share price in half in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   Four of McCall's HBOC lieutenants, who joined McKesson, were
also sacked yesterday. Albert Bergonzi, David Held, Jay Lapine and
Michael Smeraski were ``dismissed immediately for cause,'' McKesson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Seelenfreund, a McKesson director who took over as interim
chairman yesterday, said McKesson fired the five former HBO
executives because the board believed they intentionally hid
accounting irregularities before the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have identified the persons responsible and they have been
dismissed for cause,'' said Seelenfreund, a former McKesson
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McKesson Chief Executive Officer Mark Pulido and
Chief Financial Officer Richard Hawkins have resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Seelenfreund said the board thought Pulido and Hawkins were
blameless for the actions at HBO. ``But they were the company's
senior officers and this situation occurred on their watch,''
Seelenfreund said.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Valiquette, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read, said
Pulido had to accept responsibility for the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson has lost $8.8 billion in market value since the
problems at HBO surfaced and about $15.1 billion since the merger
plan was announced in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McKesson board was opposed to the acquisition of HBO but
Pulido was aggressive in wanting to pursue it,'' Valiquette told
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson said yesterday it has promoted two executive vice
presidents, John Hammergren and David Mahoney, to share the job of
chief executive officer. Seelenfreund said their appointment was
permanent. Hammergren will run the firm's day-to-day operations
while Mahoney will be responsible for strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of McKesson dropped $2.38 yesterday, or 6.6 percent, to
close at $33.69. Although analysts cheered the board's action, they
were leery of the continued uncertainties. McKesson said it
probably will miss the June 30 deadline for filing its 1998 10-K
statements with the Securities and Exchange Commission, since
auditors continue to probe HBO's books.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really positive move for the board to take such
decisive action to rebuild investor confidence,'' said Amy Brodsky,
an analyst with Vector Securities International in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate governance experts said the number of executives and
the wording of yesterday's terminations were highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is exceedingly rare when a company says an executive is
fired or fired for cause,'' said Judith Fischer, managing director
of Executive Compensation Advisory Services in Virginia.
``Corporations usually more or less pay executives to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1997, Walter Forbes of CUC International and
Henry Silverman of HFS brought their firms together in a $14
billion merger that created Cendant Corp. That merger erupted in
accusations of pre-merger accounting improprieties at CUC. Even so,
Forbes walked away with $47.5 million in severance.
</P>
<P>
   Seelenfreund said yesterday that McCall ``doesn't have a
severance package and isn't going to get one.'' He said the other
four fired executives would get no severence pay ``unless we're
contractually obligated.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall, Smeraski and Held could not be reached for comment.
Bergonzi and Lapine declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   As for Pulido and Hawkins, Seelenfreund said ``no special
provision'' has been made for severance. But he said both should be
entitled to severance ``in the course of normal policies.'' Those
packages will not be reported until McKesson files its year-end
statement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Mark Pulido earned $2.6 million in salary, bonus and
other nonoption pay. In addition, he was awarded new options which
the company valued at $5.7 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
